<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, June 26.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SNAKEHEADS (Fuzhou, China) _ Just days after British
authorities discovered the bodies of 58 illegal Chinese immigrants
who were being smuggled into England in the back of a tomato truck,
the grisly news was all the talk in the towns around Fuzhou, in
Fujian Province, home to some if not all of the dead. But most
people here regarded it with the same mix of sadness and
disengagement that frequent fliers have when they hear of a plane
crash. They may hesitate a moment, but they will go again. And that
despite a cost of up to $70,000 that must be paid to the smugglers
_ or ``snake heads'' _ who make the travel arrangements, and
despite the tortuous emigration sagas, which, at best, involve
flying through a series of countries with forged travel documents,
and, at worst, mean running across borders on foot or traversing
them packed in airless trucks, disguised as tomatoes. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT9) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-FIRE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ In the end, it was
a simple candle, knocked over by one of the squatters, that put an
end to the famous City Hotel, lighting up the nighttime sky in
Freetown the way its guests had long ago. The City Hotel, which
Graham Greene turned into one of Africa's enduring literary
landmarks in ``The Heart of the Matter,'' had survived the end of
the British empire, the postcolonial slide into squalor and decay
and in the last decade, rebel invasions that destroyed many other
buildings on the street. By Norimitsu Onishi
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-EDUC (Los Angeles) _ When it comes to public education,
California is more like another of its most famous landmarks: Death
Valley, the lowest spot in the United States. How a rich state that
helped lead the post-Sputnik push for public education in the 1960s
fell so far is a long and complex story. But it is one that a new
generation of state officials and union leaders find themselves
grappling with as they strive to return state spending to what
would seem a modest goal: the national average. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT12) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-COTTAGE _ A rare corner in the life of Abraham Lincoln
largely unplumbed by scholars _ the country cottage that he loved
to commute to in three-mile horseback rides from the White House _
is about to be designated by preservationists as the most
endangered historic site in the nation. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photos
[NYT5,6,7,14) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-LEAKS _ Officials at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory pressured employees to report that security at the
laboratory is better than they actually believe, a report by the
Energy Department's inspector general says. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REPUBS _ Republicans in the House have a busy week
planned, with a goal of passing legislation on health care, foreign
aid, and campaign finance reform before the Fourth of July recess.
The political question hanging over all this activity is this: Will
a flurry of roll calls persuade voters that this is not a
do-nothing Congress? By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   MOYNIHAN-PROFILE _ Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, and his effort
to restore Pennsylvania Avenue. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-PROSECUTORS _ A look at why Attorney General Janet Reno is
so reluctant to appoint special independent investigators. The
question arises as Reno gets another recommendation to look into Al
Gore's fund-raising activities in the 1996 campaign. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUDGE (Washington) _ The order to suspend restrictions
on Microsoft's business practices until appeals of its antitrust
case are complete held some good news for every party to the suit.
But the true winner was the trial judge. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCOM-NICHOLAS (Irvine, Calif.) _ Broadcom, whose engineers
design silicon chips that quickly send voice, data and video over
cable lines, has risen to the top of its game as the photographic
negative of a Silicon Valley company. And its leader is the
antithesis of the New Age, New Economy zenmaster. At Broadcom, the
company's founder makes clear, ``I run the show.'' By Laura M.
Holson.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-EARLYSHOW-MEDIA (Undated) _ CBS' flop, The Early Show, is
getting help from ``Survivor.'' But is CBS' news division
cooperating too closely with an entertainment program? By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   MAY-REPORT (Chicago) _ Ron May's online newsletter, ``The May
Report,'' is the publication that everyone in the Chicago high-tech
community hates _ but reads anyway. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PRICES (Washington) _ If rules to protect the environment
drive prices higher, there is always the consolation that at least
the extra money buys some benefit. But that consolation may be hard
to find in Chicago and Milwaukee, where gasoline prices have
recently topped $2 a gallon, and the industry says the reason is
partly a government requirement for additives called oxygenates.
Experts say these additives may be obsolete and irrelevant, and may
even cause environmental damage. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The decision by a stock analyst at
Prudential Securities to announce that he was gay in an e-mail to
clients stirred interest last week because Wall Street is a
conservative place where few senior managers or analysts are openly
gay. But would a similar decision on Madison Avenue generate a
similar response? By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ By the end of next month, Bell
Atlantic will almost surely announce that it has signed up 1
million long-distance customers in New York just since the
beginning of this year. That is something like a quarter-billion
dollars in annual revenue swiped from the likes of AT&AMP;T, WorldCom
and Sprint in seven months. But here is the strange part: This
trend is just getting started. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Everyone's for sale in e-commerce.
With the exception of perhaps a small handful of players, all of
the pure-plays in e-commerce are being shopped around by investors,
and even those who have gone public are looking for `alternative
financing.' By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly Patents column, this week on
mammal-cloning technology. By Sabra Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   TELEKOM-FREESERVE (London) _ Deutsche Telekom's Internet arm,
T-Online International, has withdrawn from negotiations to acquire
Britain's largest Internet service provider, Freeserve PLC, for
about $9 billion, according to executives close to the discussions.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SUIT (Undated) _ Icann, the international body that
administers the Internet's domain system. faces its first suit _
from a company seeking to register names. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-BOOKS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Is the comic book doomed? A new
company tries a new model.
</P>
<P>
