<SLUG> BC-OLY-DIVE-TRIALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ COMPLETES SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. _ To qualify for the Sydney Olympics, diver
Mark Ruiz leaped from tree branches, sneaked into hotel pools,
moved with his mother to the United States from Puerto Rico,
learned English, studied ballet and overcame a fear of heights.
</P>
<P>
   David Pichler traveled an even more arduous route. He spent a
year selling life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The two followed different paths but both will represent the
U.S. in men's platform diving. Having won the three-meter
springboard competition on Thursday, Ruiz won the 10-meter platform
Sunday in the final event of the U.S. Olympic Diving Trials at the
King County Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 Olympian, Pichler recovered from a disappointing
springboard performance and earned a return to the Olympics by
finishing second to Ruiz for the other platform berth.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz, 21, grew up in Puerto Rico, where he developed as a diver
by leaping from tree branches on the riverbank and sneaking into
hotel pools (``The lifeguards got to know me,'' he said). At his
encouragement, Ruiz's mother, Lydia Torres, moved him to Orlando to
improve his training. She gave up her job and left behind a son in
college and a daughter with a child of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what every mother has to do,'' Torres said while wearing
a T-shirt and buttons with her son's name printed on them. ``That
kid has made me so proud, so happy. I was making pennies at the
beginning but I never doubted it wouldn't be worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's given up everything for me,'' Ruiz said. ``She gave up
her job and family, everything we had, just to give me the
opportunity. I owe it all to her.''
</P>
<P>
   With Torres working full-time and more as a hairstylist, Ruiz
often bussed and occasionally bicycled the six or so miles to the
pool for his training sessions. He studied Greg Louganis' diving
tape and took ballet as Louganis did to improve his flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little booger,'' said Jay Lerew, Ruiz's coach and the
newly named U.S. team coach. ``He'd cut in front of people in line.
You couldn't get rid of him. People were getting mad at him because
he had no manners. He didn't speak much English. He was a little
tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Pichler has a somewhat different story. He's from Pennsylvania
and is 31, which is old by diving standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be in your prime until you're about 26, 27, but at 28,
you're body starts giving out,'' Lerew said. ``Dave is very much
the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Pichler dove on the 1996 Olympic team, then sold life insurance
for a year before quitting to return full-time to diving again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working was definitely interfering with my diving,'' he said.
``I said, `All right, I either need to retire from diving or put
more into diving.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, actuarial tables might have looked good to Pichler on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He led the springboard event throughout the competition before
botching his final dive and finishing fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it was a good thing for me,'' Pichler said. ``You
can't really say not succeeding is ever a good thing but it gave me
a better outlook. It made me realize that if I didn't make the
team, it was not the catastrophe I thought it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it also kept him focusing on his dives, rather than his
opponents' scores. Which moved uncomfortably close to his own in
the first rounds Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Ramirez received a 10 on consecutive dives to move to one
point shy of Pichler for second place after the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Pichler maintained he ``had no idea how close it was,'' and
while Ramirez faded, he finished strong to take second place and
earn his spot on the team.
</P>
<P>
   A top medal hopeful for Sydney, Ruiz nailed a near-perfect dive
in the final round on Thursday to win the springboard but led
throughout Sunday's final rounds of the platform, his best event
despite a fear of heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made it in the three-meter, it made me more relaxed for
the platform,'' Ruiz said. ``I wasn't thinking I just want to be in
the top two, I wanted to win. You start thinking I just want to
finish in the top two, that's when bad things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He pumped his fist after one dive and raised his arms in
celebration when the scoreboard displayed his final marks. This
qualifies as a significant display of emotion in diving, where the
national anthem before Sunday's final was performed by a man
playing a saw (this is not something you're likely to hear at the
Experience Music Project).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Diving) needs a little excitement. The more excitement, the
better it is for the sport,'' Ruiz said. ``But that's just me. I
can't help it. I just like to show emotion when I do a great dive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even show it when I don't have a good dive.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres promised Ruiz that if he won the three-meter, she would
reward him with a special vacation _ a couple days at the Dorado
Hyatt in Puerto Rico, so he could finally use the pool as an actual
guest.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz, however, said there will be no diving involved in his
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing golf,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
