<HEADLINE>
TWICE AS NICE: DE FERRAN WINS G.I. JOE'S 200 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Gil de Ferran's race strategy was tried and
true. Drive off to a big lead, make a quick pit stop and return to
the track with enough cushion for victory.
</P>
<P>
   What the plan lacked in innovation, it made up for in efficiency
as de Ferran became the first repeat winner of the season in
Sunday's Freightliner/G.I. Joe's 200 and only the third driver to
win back-to-back CART races on Portland International Raceway's
1.9-mile road course.
</P>
<P>
   Equally as significant, de Ferran's victory was the third in the
past four races for Marlboro Team Penske, which had gone nearly
three years without a victory until this season. Team Penske is the
all-time winningest organization in Indy car racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you, the faster I pushed the better the car
seemed to get,'' said de Ferran, who led by 21 seconds before
making his final pit stop on lap 89 of the 112-lap race. ``Roger
(Penske) just said `Go,' and I must say the car was fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   De Ferran's Honda-powered Reynard rejoined the race in fourth
place and assumed the lead for good with seven laps remaining as
the three front-runners _ including Penske teammate Helio
Castroneves _ peeled off for their final fuel stops.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Moreno finished 2.525 seconds behind de Ferran in the
Patrick Racing Ford and claimed the CART points lead for the first
time in his seven-year career. Newman-Haas driver Christian
Fittipaldi rallied from an early mistake to finish a season-best
third, giving Brazilian drivers their first podium sweep in CART
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good for our country,'' said Moreno, who matched the
best finish of his career and was visibly pleased with his own turn
of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-year absence from CART, Moreno returned on a limited
basis in 1996. He earned the nickname ``Super Sub'' last year by
successfully filling in for injured drivers on the PacWest and
Newman-Haas teams.
</P>
<P>
   This is Moreno's first full-time CART job since 1986, and he's
determined to make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been so many years of hard work and I'm so grateful
just to have the opportunity to drive again,'' said Moreno, who
leads de Ferran by a single point in the championship standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intended to be a super sub,'' he said. ``I always came
to these races during the past few years hoping someone would hire
me on a full-time basis. I just refused to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   That mindset proved true Sunday, although Moreno's bid to catch
de Ferran was thwarted by the lapped car of Patrick Carpentier, who
ran between the two leaders and refused to let Moreno get past him.
</P>
<P>
   Carpentier said he was confused about de Ferran's and Moreno's
positions and didn't realize they were racing for the lead.
Nonetheless, the young Canadian was fined $10,000 for failing to
yield the way.
</P>
<P>
   A multi-car accident on the first turn of the first lap brought
out the only caution flag and took many of the series' top drivers
out of the race, or at least out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tracy and Jimmy Vasser, who were first and second,
respectively, in the points standings, were involved in the mess.
Vasser didn't continue and finished 24th in the 25-car field,
dropping to fifth in the standings, 14 points behind Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy rejoined the race only to hit a retaining wall with 41
laps left. He finished 18th and fell to third in the standings,
nine points behind Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   With so many good cars _ including Tracy's Team KOOL Green
teammate Dario Franchitti and Team Rahal driver Max Papis _ out of
contention, polesitter Castroneves, Moreno and de Ferran set the
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Castroneves, who won last week in Detroit, led the most laps
(85) and held a four-tenths of a second advantage on the field
before having to stop for a splash of fuel with seven laps
remaining. He returned to the race fourth, but his Honda ran out of
gas on the final turn and he finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fuel consumption came up just a half gallon short,'' said
Castroneves, who jumped from 11th to ninth in points. ``But it's
great that the team can carry this momentum heading to Cleveland
(this week).''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Holly Cain can be reached at 206-448-8015
</P>
