<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS COMPLETE SWEEP OF RED SOX IN 13 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ There's a jagged rip in the ultimate safety net. With
Pedro Martinez hurting, the Red Sox are in free fall, a predicament
never more apparent than on their longest afternoon of the season,
when the arrival of newcomer Izzy Alcantara was not enough to save
them.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to claw for survival after an out-of-sorts Martinez
failed to hold a 5-2 lead under a barrage of Blue Jay home runs,
the Red Sox lasted 13 innings before succumbing to Toronto, 6-5,
Sunday on Tony Batista's two-out single. Batista's hit, which
followed a three-base error by Sox center fielder Carl Everett,
gave the Blue Jays a three-game sweep in SkyDome and a 2 1/2-game
advantage in the AL East over the third-place Sox, losers of eight
of their last 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who were 3 for 17 with runners in scoring position and
left two runners on in four of the last five innings, finally
cracked when Everett committed the team's fourth error of the day.
Everett missed Chris Woodward's two-out drive to deep left-center
field as he and left fielder Curtis Pride converged on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Human error may have been compounded by unusual circumstances.
Everett, who has played alongside the deaf Pride in only three
starts, appeared uncertain that Pride knew he was calling for the
ball, even though he was waving Pride off with one arm, and took a
shortened stride just before the ball cleared his glove untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't catch a ball I should have caught,'' Everett said,
dismissing any suggestion that Pride's condition came into play.
``There's no reason to go any deeper into the story than what I've
already said.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams wasn't as certain, and Pride said
afterward he thought Everett may have been spooked by his presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't played together,'' Williams said. ``We understand
the human element of what's going on. I don't know if (Everett)
took his eye off the ball for a fraction of a second. I do know he
went hard after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Batista, who earlier had hit one of Toronto's three home runs
off Martinez, lined Bryce Florie's next pitch cleanly into right
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough game for both clubs,'' said Florie, the sixth
Sox pitcher during a 4-hour-25-minute exercise in which Toronto
manager Jim Fregosi used seven pitchers, and a rookie, Matt DeWitt,
emerged with his first major league win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best center fielder in the league (Everett)
missing a ball and the biggest pull hitter in the league (Batista)
shooting a ball to right field, all in a matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of those crazy things. It won't happen to him again
this year, I guarantee you. But that's baseball. They're going good
and we're going bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored five runs early against Blue Jays starter Chris
Carpenter. Nomar Garciaparra hit a two-run double off the New
Hampshire native in the first, Scott Hatteberg hit a two-run double
in the third, and when Pride doubled and scored on Jeff Frye's
single with one out in the fourth, Carpenter was done and Martinez
had more runs to work with than he'd had in any of his previous
five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The ace almost had as many runs as the Sox had scored in his
previous five starts combined (8). But the league's most potent
collection of sluggers took full advantage of a hurting Martinez.
Shannon Stewart, the first batter Martinez faced, hit a home run,
then on his next at-bat was hit by the third of three straight
pitches that backed him off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pedro is very fortunate he pitches in the American
League,'' said Jays manager Jim Fregosi, whose general manager,
Gord Ash, was steaming in his private box after Stewart was
plunked. ``He pitches up and in. That's the way he always has been.
That's his trademark.''
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi turned sarcastic. ``It was just a coincidence that the
guy he hit was the same guy who led off the game with a homer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Blue Jays did not retaliate Charlie Nagy-style. They
struck back with their bats. After a two-out throwing error by
third baseman Wilton Veras, Brad Fullmer doubled home a run in the
third. Batista hit a two-out home run in the fifth. Then in the
seventh, Carlos Delgado, perhaps the league's MVP for the first
half of the season, crushed a full-count fastball from Martinez for
a two-run homer, the first home run Martinez has allowed with a
runner on since Sept. 24, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That tied the score, and the game turned into a war of
attrition, no more so than in the 10th, when Derek Lowe staged a
dramatic duel with Homer Bush with Blue Jays on second and third
with one out.
</P>
<P>
   With Everett summoned by manager Williams to play the infield
between shortstop Garciaparra and third baseman Veras, Bush fouled
off seven pitches before hitting a one-hopper to Veras, who fielded
the ball on the line and threw to Hatteberg at the plate to retire
Jose Cruz Jr. Stewart then lined to the track in left to end the
inning, but it was only a temporary reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, everybody was at their complete wit's end,''
Hatteberg said of the Lowe-Bush battle. ``You're so locked in and
intense, you're burned out after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jays' pen held the Sox scoreless over the last 9 2/3
innings. Two on, one out in the ninth, Garciaparra hit into a
double play. Two on, two out in the 10th, Pride whiffed. Two on,
two out in the 12th, pinch hitter Jason Varitek popped to short
left. Two on, two out in the 13th, Garciaparra (1 for 7) on the
day, flied to center against DeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate,'' Sox reliever Rod Beck said after a stretch
of a dozen games against the team's top two rivals in the AL East,
``that it's not September.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
