<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     06-26 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ WINLESS FOR 3D STRAIGHT START 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Pedro Martinez's teammates will acknowledge what the
Red Sox ace adamantly refuses to admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hurt, and everybody in here knows it,'' reliever Rod Beck
said Sunday in the aftermath of a 6-5, 13-inning loss to the
Toronto Blue Jays in which Martinez surrendered three home runs for
the second straight start and now has gone three starts in a row
without a win for the first time since last July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that when we sent him out there,'' said Beck, who was
one of five relievers who held Toronto scoreless until Carl Everett
misplayed Chris Woodward's two-out fly ball for a three-base error
in the 13th and Tony Batista followed with a single to produce the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea what all his ailments are, but if he's
willing to go out there and battle, he's still better than just
about everybody else on the staff even when he isn't 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's gutsy, that's (expletive) gutsy. That's why he's the
best there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Martinez, who insisted he was fine and at one point
sarcastically said, ``This was the best I've felt all season,''
catcher Scott Hatteberg offered candor instead of camouflage. Is
Martinez hurting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Hatteberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say. He won't tell anybody what's wrong.
I knew something was bothering him. I guess it was his side, but I
don't know. He won't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't warm up like he normally does. It was like he
was pacing himself. He wasn't throwing 90 (miles per hour) in
warmups. Normally, he throws 90 in his sleep. When I looked up at
the scoreboard and saw 87, I knew he wasn't right. Then he almost
hit Batista with a curveball, and I knew he was hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a valiant effort. He's in pain, but he knew that we
needed him bad, and he sucked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez hung a curveball to Shannon Stewart with his second
pitch of the game and Stewart hit it high and far into the
left-field seats. That was the first home run Martinez has allowed
to a leadoff hitter since Nelson Liriano of the Pirates took him
deep in Montreal April 20, 1996. Martinez had pitched in 139
regular-season games since then.
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez threw another curveball to the third Toronto
batter, Batista, that never broke and nearly clipped him, manager
Jimy Williams and trainer Jim Rowe both came to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him do something with his side,'' said Williams, mindful
that Martinez missed his scheduled start June 3 with a sore oblique
muscle on his left side and had been kept to a 100-pitch count in
his next two starts before stretching it out a little further last
Tuesday night against the Yankees, when he threw a 117 pitches in
eight innings in a 3-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he was pulling at his shirt or something,'' Williams
said. ``I thought I'd better ask, but he said it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a story line Martinez never wavered from, even after giving
up a two-out home run to Batista in the fifth inning, and a tying,
two-out, two-run home run to Carlos Delgado in the seventh, the
first homer he has given up with a man on base since Sept. 24,
1998, a span of 325 innings over 43 regular-season starts.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado's home run came one batter before Martinez finally was
lifted by Williams after throwing 133 pitches, the most he has
thrown in 26 regular-season starts, dating back to last July 7
against Tampa Bay, his last outing before the '99 All-Star break.
Twelve days later, after pitching brilliantly in the All-Star Game
then getting knocked out in the fourth inning by the Marlins in his
next start, Martinez went on the disabled list with a strained
muscle in the back of his throwing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   How can Martinez throw 133 pitches if he's hurt, especially when
he hit as high as 95 m.p.h. on the SkyDome radar readings later in
the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy wanted to take him out right after Delgado's home run,
but Pedro talked him out of it,'' Hatteberg said. ``Then (Brad)
Fullmer gets that cheap hit (a roller down the third-base line).
</P>
<P>
   ``He just took one for the team today and sucked it up. I don't
know what it was, but he seemed to get better as the game went
along. Maybe it loosened up for him a little bit, maybe it was
adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It may have been sheer will. He's an incredible
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has allowed seven earned runs in his last two starts.
That's just three fewer runs than he had allowed in his first dozen
starts combined. The six home runs he has allowed in his last two
outings are double what he gave up in his first dozen starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought I was hurting,'' Martinez said about Williams's
first-inning visit. ``It was just a bad day, and I had to pitch
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez blamed his problems on a lack of command of all of his
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from the start of the game,'' he said. ``It was a hard
day. I was trying to battle as hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The home runs?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good hitters,'' he said, his eyes smoldering with barely
contained anger. ``It's good hitters. I'm human. What am I supposed
to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that I gave up those five runs, so you don't think
I'm a robot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost relaxing for me, so you think I am normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez is not normal. The two-time Cy Young Award winner
is considered hands-down the best pitcher in the league and only
Randy Johnson challenges his status as the best pitcher in the
game. Three home runs in a game, two games in a row? Something
isn't right, and it isn't a secret.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
