u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-26 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIMBLEDON SEEDINGS A PAIN FOR SPANIARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The pain in Spain lies mainly in a plain called
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask those upstanding Spaniards Alex Corretja, Juan Carlos
Ferrero, and Albert Costa _ the No. 11, 13, and 15 tennis laborers
in el mundo _ who believe their prospective parade has been rained
on by the insensitive, subjective (perhaps overly patriotic?) chaps
who operate the eldest of all tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja and Costa believe that despite being regarded as
conquistadores at home, and in numerous other locations, they are
being treated like peons at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet
Club. As a result, they said Sunday night that they'll walk Monday
_ that is, boycott the unfolding 114th edition of the Big W. An
issue of honor and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant teenager Ferrero already was out, withdrawn because of
a back injury. But he had looked forward to his Wimbledon debut,
and would have joined his compatriots' protest were he healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing comparable has happened here since the Association of
Tennis Professionals (ATP) strike of 1973, when 79 men (among them
13 of 16 seeds, including such championship names as Arthur Ashe,
Rod Laver, John Newcombe, and Stan Smith) stayed away as a
counter-punch against the club's stiff-necked management of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As the trio's spokesman, the honorable Corretja was saying
earlier in the evening, ``Maybe we go on, play one game and quit.
It is a matter of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while it was: To play or not to play? However, there's no
Hamlet in these guys. They just feel like victims of the slings and
arrows of outrageous injustice because they aren't seeded while
colleagues ranked below them are. One of them happens to be a
homeboy, Greg Rusedski, pushed up to the 14th seed though he ranks
No. 21. Another is 1996 champ (thus a club member) Richard
Krajicek, seeded 11th, ranked No. 25. Is this taking care of your
own?
</P>
<P>
   The other two are Aussies Mark Philippoussis, No. 17 up to 10th,
and Patrick Rafter, No. 27 up to 12th. Also left out of the
seedings was No. 16, Moroccan Younes El Ayanoui.
</P>
<P>
   Seeding, traditional early-round protection given 16 players,
clearly has been earned by the Spaniards and El Ayanoui.
</P>
<P>
   The All England Clubbies obviously don't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniards feel stripped of their identities: ``The rankings
. . . we have earned around the world as professionals,'' said
Corretja, French Open semifinalist two years ago and winner of the
prominent hard court stopover this year at Indian Wells (Calif.).
``We should be seeded according to those rankings as everywhere
else. Wimbledon is a great tournament. But (the All England Club)
is not respecting us, not treating us like some of the best in the
world, just because we haven't done well on grass.''
</P>
<P>
   The AEC is the proprietor of a tournament that most of us call
Wimbledon, but is formally and simply entitled The Lawn Tennis
Championships, as if none other existed _ which was the case when
it appeared as though by divine fiat in 1877.
</P>
<P>
   That word ``Lawn'' is the catch. Once the primary surface, grass
began to wither in 1975 when the US Open opted for clay (three
years later, the present asphalt). Until then three of the four
majors were frolics on the green; the French forever European dirt.
Australia abandoned its lawn for asphalt in 1988, leaving Wimbledon
isolated in its elegance, a ghetto of greensward.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the planet was emptied of guys who understood how to
handle grassblades, which appeared so seldom on their dance cards.
Tricky stuff. Crazy, swift, low bounces. Different every day. A
unique test. The only one able to cope seems to be named Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon, the patriarch, always has tinkered with seedings,
catering to the cognoscenti of turf. It's also pretty much a law
unto itself, as it showed in 1973. Denying entry to the Yugoslav
ace, Nikki Pilic, because he was suspended by his country's tennis
federation for skipping a Davis Cup series, Wimbledon was trying to
bust the union, the newly founded ATP.
</P>
<P>
   Showing rare, principled solidarity, the ATP stood by its lodge
brother, declaring that if Pilic couldn't play, nobody else would
either. All but two members (Roger Taylor and Ray Keldie) hit the
bricks. Wimbledon, refusing to imagine that anybody would desert
the shrine, was emasculated for a year, and the ATP was in
business.
</P>
<P>
   It bungled that business this time by not supporting the
Spaniards. But four years ago, when the US Tennis Association
clumsily attempted to rig US Open seedings to give American guys an
edge, the ATP demanded _ and got _ proper seedings and a new draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted that,'' said Corretja. ``We sent a letter asking
that, but it was refused. We thought it was different this year.
This year the ATP insisted we play the four (majors) along with the
Masters Series, so we believe they should follow the rankings for
the seedings like the rest of the tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, underlining the fractured state of men's tennis, the
four majors go by their own rules, permitting them the prerogative
of disregarding rankings in awarding seedings.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon's new chairman, Tim Phillips, though considerably more
understanding of the players than most of his predecessors, defends
the seedings as ``in the public and the tournament's interest.''
He's running a show, and craves balance. That means making sure the
grass mavens don't bump into one another at the outset, regardless
of their rankings. Wimbledon is wary of so-called slow-court
players like the Spaniards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I haven't done well here, but I deserve the chance to
try to do better,'' Corretja said. ``My record, and Costa's,
deserves that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   It's respect against show business.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said, sincerely, that he respects the Spaniards but
that he has to do what's best for his baby. Don't think he's
celebrating the 488th anniversary of the English victory over the
Spanish Armada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel bad to miss this great tournament. A professional
should be here,'' said Corretja. ``But we feel strong a change is
needed. Maybe what we do will help.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips and ATP boss Mark Miles have agreed that an adjustment
needs to be made _ next year.
</P>
<P>
   The show goes on, sadly without the best of Spain. Corretja and
Costa go home, feeling like Don Quixote tilting against a gigantic
windmill on Church Road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
