<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RUN-PRE-LADN-(SLANG)     06-26 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-PRE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOBS NOT SURE WHAT TO RUN IN OLYMPIC TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Regina Jacobs is ready for a distance double in
the U.S. Olympic Trials next month. Which events, however, are open
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a two-time 1,500-meter silver medalist in the world
championships and American record-holder in the 5,000, was prepared
for a 1,500 and 5,000 double in the Trials in Sacramento. An 800
and 1,500 double became a possibility after Jacobs' victory in the
3,000 meters Sunday in the Adidas Oregon Track Classic on Sunday at
Lewis and Clark College.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, 36, timed a meet-record 8 minutes, 42.55 seconds to turn
back 1992 Olympic 10,000-meter champion Derartu Tulu of Ethiopia,
who was second in 8:46.32.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' victory came less than 24 hours after a personal-best
performance of 1:58.08 to finish second in the 800 in the
Prefontaine Classic in Eugene, Ore., on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I am going to encounter when I go to the
Olympics. Now, I just have to find another race for Tuesday,''
Jacobs said with a laugh. ``Right now, this if fine-tuning for the
Trials. This is really very positive. I am going to have to wake up
and run at 10 a.m. the first day and come back the next evening. It
really simulates the kind of fatigue that you have to run with the
second day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a 1981 graduate of Argyll Academy in Los Angeles (now
Campbell Hall) who lives in Oakland, had all she could handle in
Sunday's race with five runners in contention with two laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs broke free for a decisive victory from a pack that
included Tulu and Amy Rudolph, 1999 national 10,000 champion Libbie
Hickman and three-time defending U.S. cross country champion Deena
Drossin.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph was third in 8:47.13 with Hickman fourth in 8:49.75.
Drossin, a 1991 Agoura graduate, who towed the field through the
first four laps in 4:46.3, was fifth in 8:51.76.
</P>
<P>
   Despite temperatures in the high 80s, Jacobs was just off her
lifetime best and American indoor record of 8:39.14, run in placing
third in the 1999 world indoor championships. Tom Craig, Jacobs'
coach and husband, believes his wife is capable of running under
8:30 under ideal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs appeared to have plenty in reserve as she crossed the
line with her arms raised, followed by a victory jog down the
homestretch to loud applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of worried,'' Jacobs said. ``I was running behind
Deena for a while. I thought, `Oh my God. Oh my God, the crowd is
going to start clapping and they are just going to pick it up.'
There were four or five women who could have won that race.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs figures to contend for a top-three finish whether she
opts for the 800 or 5,000 as her second event in the U.S. Olympic
Trials in addition to the 1,500, an event in which she is an
eight-time outdoor national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs plans to make the final decision after running the mile
in the GMC Envoy Open at Stanford next Saturday in her last
competition before the U.S. Olympic Trials on July 14-23 in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) was more than I could have imagined,'' Jacobs said,
``since I don't get a lot of chances to run a lot of 800s. This is
really enticing if I can get in a race and have somebody pull me.
Then again, the 5,000 is going to be a fast race. If I am not in it
and someone goes under my 5,000 record, I am going to sit there and
wonder, `God, I wish I was in that race.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-GALLUP-AZR &LR;      06-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLUP-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-GALLUP-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Stuart grew up hearing stories about an event that took
place in his grandmother's Gallup, N.M., back yard four years
before he was born.
</P>
<P>
   Riots. Gunshots. Peace officers wounded and killed.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Phoenix attorney was casting about for a subject on
which to base his first novel, his father suggested that explosive
incident might provide fodder for a work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Stuart had his novel: (beginitalic)The Gallup
14(enditalic), gleaned from the trial of 14 Mexican immigrants and
striking mine workers held accountable when seven people were
wounded and three more left for dead after a bloody melee in April
1935. The local sheriff was killed - but by whom?
</P>
<P>
   Gallup native Stuart, a lawyer with the Phoenix firm Jennings,
Strouss &AMP; Salmon, had written several legal textbooks. Now he was
itching to try his hand at a novel.
</P>
<P>
   When his father recalled the saga of the Gallup 14, Stuart could
picture the alley where the incident had taken place. He'd played
stickball and hide-and-seek there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it very well,'' he said at his Phoenix home. ```That's
where the sheriff was killed,' Grandma would say.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Stuart began researching the story the way he
would have prepared for a trial. In Gallup, he pored over arrest
warrants and read 600 pages of court transcripts. He interviewed
almost 60 people.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in surrounding states had carried the story with
banner headlines.
</P>
<P>
   On April 5, the day of the shooting, the evening
(beginitalic)Phoenix Gazette(enditalic) put the news at the top of
its front page with a string of headlines: ``GUARDS ARREST 85 IN
GALLUP KILLING. RIOT IS PROBED; MAY CHARGE 20 WITH MURDER. Two Dead
as Unemployed Try to Free Trio From Custody.'' The next morning,
(beginitalic)The Arizona Republic(enditalic) announced, ``Jury
Holds 25 In Riot Death.''
</P>
<P>
   With help from an engineer, Stuart examined the likely
trajectory of the bullet that killed Sheriff M.R. ``Mack''
Carmichael. Although he formed a theory about whose gun launched
the fatal bullet, he's keeping it to himself. The shooting was
accidental, he says, the family would be hurt by such suspicions,
and it's pure speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Even a novelist can't take such liberties.
</P>
<P>
   To tell the story, Stuart invented two protagonists - young
attorney Billy Wade and his sweetheart, Mary Ann. Billy is all
fiction. The bright and feisty Mary Ann is based on Stuart's wife,
Kathleen.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) (enditalic)Through Mary Ann and Billy's narration,
(beginitalic)The Gallup (enditalic)(beginitalic)14(enditalic) winds
its way leisurely through the events of 1935: First the eviction of
mine workers from company-owned housing, then the riot that
exploded in an alley. Ten men shot, more than 180 suspects jailed,
14 indicted, 10 brought to trial. Bigotry worked against those
arrested - most were Hispanic, many of them communists.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart modeled his writing style after the historic novels of
Irving Stone. He's also a fan of lawyers-turned-authors Scott Turow
and John Grisham, though not of the latter's depiction of lawyers,
which Stuart sees as unrelentingly negative.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 10 months of research and a year of writing while
working at his law firm full time. The University of New Mexico
Press published (beginitalic) Gallup (enditalic)(beginitalic)14
(enditalic)this March. Now the book(beginitalic) (enditalic)is the
talk of Gallup, where Stuart and his wife still spend much of their
time. A favorable review from the bookseller's bible,
(beginitalic)Pubisher's Weekly(enditalic), has brought inquiries
from Hollywood, though no deals have yet been struck.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart would welcome a movie contract but has heard horror
stories from other authors, including his friend, John Nichols, a
screenwriter and author of (beginitalic)The Milagro Beanfield
War(enditalic). Robert Redford turned that book into a 1988 movie.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, burned by past deals that fell through, joked that he
will happily write the script for (beginitalic)The
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Gallup 14 (enditalic)''as soon as I get the
check.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart has written two more novels - ``somewhat experimental'' -
since (beginitalic)The(enditalic)(beginitalic) Gallup 14(enditalic)
and has no plans to publish them. But he is eagerly pursuing his
fourth, another historical novel about an outbreak of violence in
Gallup following the 1973 siege at Wounded Knee, S.D. The next day,
the young mayor of Gallup was beaten and taken hostage by Indian
protesters. Stuart was a classmate of Frank Emmett Garcia, who now
lives in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to tell the story of Wounded Knee,'' Stuart
said. ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere in the back of Stuart's mind is the seed of yet
another novel based on actual events. In 1991, Stuart served as
independent counsel in the notorious AzScam scandal, in which more
than a score of Arizona legislators and lobbyists were fingered in
a sting over inducements to legalize gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart says he'll wait about 10 years to write that story,
giving the events some perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Arizona in AzScam is fascinating,'' he said.
``And nobody knows it like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart, recently appointed to the Arizona Board of Regents and
now practicing law part time, is banking on a future as a novelist
- history a specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can achieve the acceptance with this fourth book as with
the first, I think I'll really have something I can expand,'' he
said. ``I'm just as thrilled as any human being can be. The psychic
and intellectual consequences of writing a novel are the thrill of
a lifetime.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0010 </DOCNO>
