<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINO ``RESURRECTION BLVD.' ISN'T AFRAID TO TAKE RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS renews the almost all-Black ``City of Angels'' for the fall
despite so-so ratings, acknowledging that the show's status as a
minority-heavy production made the network think twice about
canceling it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Showtime launches ``Resurrection Blvd.,'' a weekly drama
about an East Los Angeles family. The media, myself included,
dutifully report that the show is almost all Latino, both in front
of and behind the camera, giving the show more attention than we
would the latest Pauly Shore vehicle, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Seems as if you can make a pretty good argument that shows with
predominantly minority casts get treated differently than other
shows. Is this fair?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. But neither is ignoring large segments of the
population just because advertisers - the real power in television
- think it's easier to sell a lily-white show than one with brown
or black faces in it. And that's gone on for years.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Dennis E. Leoni, the Tucson native who created
``Resurrection Blvd.,'' knows that his show is getting more
attention than it might because of the color of his cast and crew,
and he's OK with that - up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about it is the old adage `There is no such thing as
bad publicity','' Leoni says. ``Obviously, I'm grateful for all of
the attention because we are the first Latino prime-time series in
front of and behind the camera, and all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at some point, I'm hoping that people will just focus on
the quality of the show. I feel it's important; it's about time,
all those things. On the other hand, I don't want people to start
feeling like `Resurrection Blvd.' is an affirmative action program.
It is not.''
</P>
<P>
   What it is, above all, is the story of a family, the Santiagos.
The patriarch trains his middle son to be a boxer, a sport that
touches all of the men in the family. Another son is a premed
student, one daughter works in a law firm, another is in high
school. No maids, no gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   `I got tired of looking at Latinos as secondary or ancillary
characters,` Leoni says, `because I'm primary in my home, and I
thought maybe somebody else wants to see a Latino who is primary in
a show and see what his life is like, as opposed to (being in)
servitude to somebody else.`
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Blvd.'' isn't perfect, but Leoni's determination
makes it a welcome change. The show sounds like a soap opera -
domestic strife, romantic troubles, that kind of thing. What lifts
it above that level is the acting. The cast, which includes Tony
Plana, Elizabeth Pena (EDITORS: tilde over``n'' in PENA), Michael
DeLorenzo, Nicholas Gonzalez and Marisol Nichols, all cq is
uniformly good.
</P>
<P>
   And the show occasionally touches on subjects - gang violence,
for instance - that might have been awkward for an Anglo writer to
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   `No one can say, 'Well, that's politically incorrect, and you've
got gang members in your show.'.` Leoni says. `Well, I do have
gang-bangers in Resurrection Blvd., and they are a fact of life.
They exist in East LA. And I show them.
</P>
<P>
   `But I also show the balance of Yolanda, who is trying to be an
attorney, going to law school and work in a law firm. And she's in
love with a Latino attorney who doesn't speak Spanish.... I think
what you have to do is show a balance, because that's really what
life is.`
</P>
<P>
   It's a better show than ``City of Angels,'' but even if it
weren't, ``Resurrection Blvd.'' wouldn't labor under at least one
of the pressures brought to bear upon that show: network Nielsen
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about Showtime is we're not on the hot seat,
sort of,''Leoni says.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he had much choice about who would make the show. He
found that out when he shopped an earlier, autobiographical script
about a Latino family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed it around to some people around the networks,'' Leoni
says. ``I showed it to some people at some various studios. All of
them thought that it didn't have a chance in hell of being made
because of its all-Latino cast.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironic, then, that that's what's attracting so much attention
now. And thanks to the strength of that cast, ``Resurrection
Blvd.'' should be good enough to keep it.Reach Goodykoontz at
Bill.Goodykoontz(at)ArizonaRepublic. or (602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-GALLUP-AZR &LR;      06-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLUP-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-GALLUP-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
