<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-LPGACHAMPIONSHIP-     06-26 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAJOR COUP FOR INKSTER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ For as long as Juli Inkster had played golf,
she never had been involved in anything quite like what was going
on at DuPont Country Club Sunday in the final round of the LPGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The wind was swirling, fairways were foreign land, greens were
impossible to hold, rough was swallowing golf balls, and trees were
getting in front of shots everywhere. ``I didn't think I was
playing that bad, but bogeys were so easy and birdies were so
hard,'' said Inkster, for whom the situation seemed made to order,
the toughest of competitors in the most demanding of conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the end it was, because Inkster defeated Italy's Stefania
Croce with a par on the second hole of a playoff to become just the
third back-to-back winner of this major championship.
</P>
<P>
   That Inkster, who shared the third-round lead with Wendy Ward at
7 under, won her sixth major is no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   That she won despite shooting a 4-over 75 for a 281, making a
bogey on the 72d hole, and hitting just five fairways and 14 greens
is rather shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I shot 4 over, but a win's a win,'' said
Inkster, who turned 40 Saturday but is certainly not slowing down.
``It proves I can still play with these girls, that I'm still one
of the top players.''
</P>
<P>
   The final round offered drama of a different sort than last
year, when Inkster finished eagle-birdie-birdie to win here. It was
more a survival test, with players taking turns falling back at a
rapid clip on a day when the top 11 finishers were a combined
11-over par, the field average was nearly 74.00, and just 10 of 73
players posted sub-par rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive of those was Croce, whose best finish since
joining the LPGA Tour in 1993 had been a third. Starting at
even-par, seven shots behind Inkster and Ward, Croce went out
birdie-birdie-birdie and said to herself: ``If I keep on going like
this, I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   She was laughing, of course, because Croce has been around long
enough to know that it is very hard to pass 13 players in one
round, ``so I just kept focused, but I didn't think I was going to
get into a playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Croce made the turn in 2-under 33, birdied the par-5 11th, then
came home with seven solid pars to share the day's low round of 68.
At 3-under 281, she was simply thrilled with what she figured to be
a top 5 finish because a few weeks ago she was near tears talking
about her game when she called her father, Angelo, a club pro in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have sounded awful because he came over two days
later,'' said Croce. ``This week has been like a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sentiment that was not echoed by those at the top of
the leaderboard. Ward, for instance. The 27-year-old Texan, who was
making her first run at a major, birdied the opening hole to get to
8 under and owned a two-shot lead because Inkster had bogeyed the
par-4 third.
</P>
<P>
   That was as good as it would get for her. Ward bogeyed four
times in a six-hole stretch, starting at the sixth, and fell to 4
under, two behind Inkster. ``Conditions were the toughest we've
ever seen,'' said Ward, who fell to third behind Nancy Scranton,
whose frontside 33 had pushed her to 6 under, tied with Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   But Scranton, whose only major win came nine years ago, became
unglued at the 528-yard 11th. First she topped her layup 3-wood,
then she missed a 5-foot birdie try. ``I got flustered,'' she
conceded, though her play said it even louder.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-4 12th, Scranton pulled her drive under a pine tree
where her swing was restricted. It led to a double-bogey. The 13th
was a three-putt bogey and the 14th is where she left the hunt for
good, again driving it beneath a pine tree and making bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Inkster were not appreciably better. At the par-3 13th,
Ward made double-bogey thanks to a one-shot penalty she called on
herself when her ball moved as she stood over a putt.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, but no thanks, said Inkster, who played the 390-yard,
par-4 14th like a 16-handicapper. She drove it right, then hit a
tree with her second shot. ``It was probably a stupid shot,'' she
said of her next attempt, which also hit the tree. ``I should have
just chipped out, got my bogey, and moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   The double-bogey, coupled with Ward's birdie, produced a
three-shot swing. Inkster was 4 under, Ward and Croce were a shot
back.
</P>
<P>
   When Ward (76) ran her approach through the green at 18 and
couldn't get it up-and-down, she fell to 2 under tied with Scranton
(73) and Se Ri Pak (71). Then she stood by to watch Inkster attempt
a 6-foot putt to save par and the win. Croce chose not to watch,
but to judge by the crowd's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they did not clap that hard, it meant I'm going to a
playoff,'' said Croce, who chipped a few balls, then heard groans.
Inkster, after burying her approach to the 72d hole into a bunker,
had fallen to 3-under with the bogey.
</P>
<P>
   In the playoff, the heralded Inkster and the unheralded Croce
each made par at the 18th. Then Croce's approach to the par-4 10th
went through the green into thick rough. She could not make the
near-impossible up-and-down to a pin cut tight on a green sloping
severely away from her, a situation that led to an easy two-putt
win for Inkster. But not to one of her trademark victory dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud of myself for hanging in, but I didn't have any
reason to dance,'' said Inkster. ``I was too tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
