<SLUG> BC-BBA-BLUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELGADO SMOKED THIS FASTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
 JAYS-DELGADO-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The scene was pure bliss, Carlos Delgado rocking in a
leather easy chair, puffing on a fat cigar, his smile kilometers
wide, Delgado acting as if he were king of the baseball world.
Which he just might be at this moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to enjoy a moment like this,'' said Delgado, puffing
out another cloud of smoke. ``Pedro makes good pitch and I make
good hit. You should enjoy it, you should react, you should let it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was Delgado's 28th birthday, but it was so much more. The
Blue Jays slugger had taken a curtain call from the 31,022 fans at
SkyDome. Delgado had had enough moments of flailing against Pedro
Martinez not to savor every delicious detail of that two-run homer
off Martinez in the seventh that tied the game and helped send the
Red Sox to a 6-5 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that good, me against Pedro,'' said Delgado of his history
against Martinez (3 for 24, 9 Ks, only 1 home run) when he stepped
to the plate in the seventh. ``I hit only one home run off him
before . . . only one . . . when he was with Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Delgado had looked tentative, awkward, off-balance, and almost
overmatched on each at-bat before Martinez threw that 3-2 fastball
in the seventh. But Delgado, the American League's home run leader,
got his only good swing off Martinez on that pitch, ``a fastball
out over the plate,'' as the Blue Jay put it. A fastball that
seemed to have little movement.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, said Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi, ``Pedro had
thrown 130 pitches (into the seventh). It was a real tough game for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So the cause, a tiring Martinez, and the effect, Delgado's 27th
home run of the season, were related. Just as two errors by the
shaky Boston infield on grounders that would have ended the second
and third innings caused Martinez to face four more batters than he
should have. The errors, by Nomar Garciaparra and Wilton Veras,
caused no immediate harm, but they may have caused the later harm
of Martinez firing a flat fastball on his 128th pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to enjoy it,'' said Delgado, blowing another puff
of smoke. ``Because this is a game we could have given up on
early.''
</P>
<P>
   A few lockers away, third baseman Tony Batista was detailing his
single in the 13th that finally ended this marathon and, yes, his
homer in the fifth off Martinez. ``I've hit only two off Pedro,''
said Batista. ``And this one, I think maybe he lose
concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most happy Blue Jay might not have been Delgado or
Batista, but left fielder Shannon Stewart. After the Red Sox scored
two in the first, seemingly ending most games started by Martinez,
Stewart drove Martinez's second pitch of the game into the seats,
the first time in 257 games Martinez has given up a leadoff homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, we got the momentum back with that homer,''
said Delgado of Stewart's homer. ``Right off the bat they score two
runs and it's hard to play catchup against anybody, especially
against Pedro. But we cut the lead right in half.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he got a curve, and was ``surprised that I got a
pitch to hit so soon. Usually against Pedro, when you get a pitch
to hit, you've got to hit it. And this was a hanging curve and I
hit it pretty well. It went out of the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Stewart next stepped in against Martinez, in the third,
the pitcher threw close to him on a 1-2 count, even closer on 2-2,
then hit Stewart on a 3-2 pitch. This caused a rankled Fregosi to
say, ``Pedro Martinez is very fortunate he pitches in the American
League. It's no coincidence he threw inside three times against a
guy who just hit a homer off him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart did his best to bite his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking, `That's Pedro being Pedro,' '' said
Stewart. ``He's a great pitcher and I don't know if it was
intentional. (Red Sox catcher Scott) Hatteberg told me it wasn't
intentional but, you know, any time you get hit after hitting a
home run, when a guy throws up and in two or three times, you're
left wondering.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was asked if, after the first inside pitch, he felt
Martinez had delivered his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I was just thinking you never want a ball thrown
at you,'' said the Blue Jay. ``Only Pedro knows if it was
intentional. People were saying Pedro was having control problems,
but the guy is the best pitcher in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And over in the manager's office, Fregosi was most pleased,
``because when you're behind, 4-1 and 5-2, against Pedro Martinez,
usually that game is over. But he had to throw a lot of pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   And Delgado was rocking in his leather chair, cigar smoke
billowing, his team having swept the Red Sox and sent Boston back
across the border a beaten-down team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
