<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD'S NOWAK A STAY-AT-HOME CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After dipping into the Swedish talent pool for their
first two selections (No. 7 and 27 overall Saturday), the Bruins
grabbed a homegrown player at the start of the second day of the
National Hockey League draft, which wrapped up in Calgary, Alberta,
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They picked Harvard center Brett Nowak, who is coming off his
freshman season, in the fourth round. Nowak, a 6-foot-2-inch,
198-pound native of New Haven, originally was rated much higher
than where the Bruins took him _ 103d overall. Central Scouting had
him ranked as high as No. 22 among North Americans, No. 14 in the
mid-term rankings, but a shoulder injury suffered after the World
Junior tournament seemed to cause his stock to drop.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gorton, the top aide to assistant general manager Mike
O'Connell, said Nowak has good size, protects the puck well, and
his skating is improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a lot of the year injured, with a harness on his
shoulder, so he wasn't as offensively productive as a lot of people
thought he would be,'' said Gorton. ``He had a good tournament at
the World Juniors and was used more in a checking role. He's always
been thought of as an offensive guy, so some people might have gone
just on his numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   In 24 games with Harvard last season, he had five goals and 15
points. He is expected to return to school for his sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth round (the Bruins had no fifth-round selection,
having traded it to Columbus Friday), Boston took Finnish
defenseman Jarmo Kultanen at No. 174. Kultanen, who is 6-2, 198
pounds, is 27 and was considered a late developer. He has been
playing in the Finnish Elite League the last several seasons.
O'Connell said that similar to the situation the Bruins had at last
year's draft, when they took forward Mikko Eloranta at the same
age, they believe Kultanen could be ready to step in and help shore
up the blue line this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh round, at No. 204, Boston grabbed center/left
wing Chris Berti, the only Canadian Major Junior Hockey League
player taken by the Bruins in this draft. Berti, who is 18, has
good size (6-5, 205) and is aggressive (131 penalty minutes in 62
games of junior hockey last year, with Berti estimating 100 of
those were from fighting majors) but is likely three or more years
from the NHL. Berti played for the Sarnia Sting (Ontario League)
last year and had eight goals and 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Czech native Zdenek Kutlak was the Bruins' eighth-round choice
(No. 237) and the 20-year-old defenseman is expected to attend
training camp. He's eligible to play in Providence if he doesn't
make the Boston roster. Kutlak is a big (6-3, 207) stay-at-home
defender but has been used on the power play with his Czech Elite
League team of Ceske Budejovice because of his powerful shot.
</P>
<P>
   Boston closed out the draft with a pair of ninth-round
selections. At No. 268, the Bruins chose defenseman Pavel Kolarik,
a 27-year-old native of the Czech Republic. Like Kultanen, the
Bruins believe Kolarik could make the team this fall. He played
last year with Slavia Praha of the Czech Elite League, where he had
five goals and three assists in 52 games. He's considered a strong
skater and played last year with former Bruin forward/enigma
Vladimir Ruzicka.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 279, which the Bruins acquired from Edmonton for Boston's
ninth-round selection next year, the team took left wing Andreas
Lindstrom, a 6-5, 210-pound native of Lulea, Sweden, who played in
the Swedish Junior League last year. Bruins Swedish scout, Svenake
Svensson, pushed hard for Lindstrom, which prompted the Bruins to
make the deal with the Oilers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
