A4697 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-B     06-26 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT OTHER MOVES, PROSPECTS AREN'T GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As inspiring weekends go, what transpired in Calgary,
Alberta, the last three days didn't exactly rekindle the fervor for
hockey here in the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, the Bruins' final line for Friday,
Saturday, and Sunday: No trades. No additions to the 2000-2001
roster. Two roster players sacrificed to expansion: Steve Heinze
and Mattias Timander.
</P>
<P>
   In Heinze's case, the Bruins had to sweeten the pot with the
addition of a draft pick to convince the Blue Jackets to take the
veteran wing in the expansion draft. That's right, it cost Boston a
draft pick to give the guy away. Imagine leaving an
old-but-functional gas grille out at the curb, with a ``Free _ Take
It'' sign taped to the front, and then having to resort to handing
some guy a sawbuck to heave it into his trunk. Ultimately, that's
what happened with Heinze.
</P>
<P>
   Bet the phone lines will be buzzing at the Causeway Street
season-ticket office this morning?
</P>
<P>
   While Mike Milbury ran amok in the process of bringing the
Islanders back from the dead with a flurry of trades and the
selection of Rick DiPietro as the No. 1 draft pick, Mssrs. Harry
Sinden and Mike O'Connell took the addition-by-subtraction route
for their Bruins. They lost two roster players. They then used
their first two selections in the entry draft Saturday to pick a
couple of Swedish prospects no one figures will be seen here for at
least a year or two. As with virtually all first-rounders, of
course, no one knows if they ever will be seen here (witness the
likes of Johnathan Aitken and Evgeny Ryabchikov).
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget that the Bruins traded Ray Bourque in March,
and it sounds like veteran Don Sweeney will walk next month. He
becomes an unrestricted free agent Saturday. Given how old friend
Milbury is tossing around the coin _ he picked up John
Vanbiesbrouck from the Flyers as a DiPietro running mate Sunday for
a 2001 fourth-round draft choice _ Sweeney likely can figure on a
three-year deal worth $9 or $10 million getting FedExed to his
house at about 12:01 a.m. July 1.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still updating your roster at home, that would mean no
Bourque, no Sweeney, and no Timander when the season opens in
October. Don't forget, we are talking about a team that missed the
playoffs last season for the second time in four years. OK, half
the roster finished the season in a body cast, but it wasn't like,
even with Bourque still around, the whole thing was humming along
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Let me ask the obvious here: other than the prospects the Bruins
received in the Bourque deal _ Slammin' Sami Pahlsson and Maulin'
Martin Grenier _ where's the fix?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, based on how coach Pat Burns was talking a couple of
months ago when he was invited back for 2000-01, has to be in the
free agent market. Doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   By the way Burns was talking that day in mid-April, the front
office finally was about to abandon one half of its ``Stand Pat''
approach and buy him some players. Sinden and O'Connell said they
would stand Pat behind the bench, and then stop standing pat with
their wallet, abandon their price chopper ways, and go out and
bring in some viable big league players.
</P>
<P>
   Well, as of this Saturday, shopping season officially opens. Now
we get to see the names Burns said brought a huge grin to his face
when he sat in the Causeway Street office and made friendly again
with Sinden and O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, there really isn't much in the free agent pool
that actually would make a grown man, uh, giddy. OK, as of Saturday
Eric Lindros could be a free agent, provided the Flyers don't want
to give him at least $8.5 million for another year's worth of
skating, shooting, checking, and shaking the cobwebs from his head.
</P>
<P>
   But, c'mon, L'Enfant Terrible here? For $8.5 million or more?
Tell me Habitat for Humanity is going to hand Jeremy Jacobs its
lifetime achievement award and I'll believe that first. Tell me
that ``Fenway 2 _ The Unbuildable'' is going to be constructed at
the old Fort Devens and I'll believe that second. But Lindros a
Bruin? The Bourque money ceiling ($6 million a year) has been
shattered, but that only means the shards fall on the shoulders of
those who are left.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have been a budget operation for a long time, and
they're going to remain a budget operation for a whole lot longer.
There is no reason to believe that's going to change with some
big-name signings over the next couple of weeks. Companies like the
Boston Bruins Professional Hockey Club help Alan Greenspan fall
asleep at night without the need to count decimal points.
</P>
<P>
   What I see possibly happening is O'Connell, finally handed the
general manager's title in full, going out and signing Lyle Odelein
for the blue line and Gary Roberts for up front.
</P>
<P>
   A guy like Odelein, technically Blue Jackets property for the
next 5-6 days, could be a dash of A-1 Sauce for the blue line.
Roberts, on the Hurricanes' negotiating list until the weekend,
would spice up the front line. One thing Burns's club needs is some
nastiness. Odelein and Roberts offer that, as does Shayne Corson
(soon expected to be an ex-Canadien).
</P>
<P>
   What we're going to see here, in short, is what we saw over the
weekend and what we witnessed throughout the '90s: business as
usual. A couple of thirtysomethings will come in, patches for last
year's flat tire, and the product will roll along into 2000-2001,
just another team in the Original 30.
</P>
<P>
   Just another team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBADRAFT-PRZYBILL     06-26 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNFINISHED BUSINESS AWAITS PRZYBILLA 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-PRZYBILLA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The general manager of the Orlando Magic, sitting on
three lottery picks in Wednesday's NBA draft, has presided over
workouts, interviews, and dinners with more than three dozen
prospective rookies. Among those seen by John Gabriel was
20-year-old Joel Przybilla, a center who may be around when/if
Orlando picks first (No. 5), might be around when/if Orlando picks
second (No. 10), and definitely won't be around when the Magic make
their last pick (13th).
</P>
<P>
   Przybilla is a raw, 7-foot-1-inch player who bolted the
University of Minnesota in February because of problems with a
different coach and the same old, academic requirements. He is a
shot-blocker, an interior presence, a true stopper. He has, like
most of this unfinished class, a lot of upside, which is the
scouts' favorite word to describe a player who isn't quite ready
for the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents what this draft is all about,'' Gabriel said.
``And that is development.''
</P>
<P>
   Przybilla will be right at home on draft night, sitting in the
green room at the Target Center in Minneapolis. It's not far from
his home in Monticello, Minn., where he became the most
sought-after high school player in the state since Kevin McHale.
It's even closer to the U _ the university _ where Przybilla played
for 1 1/2 seasons until tensions with coach Don Monson and his own
decision to stop attending class led to his departure.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 9, he had 33 points and 14 rebounds in an upset win over
No. 10 Indiana and, for the second time, was named Big Ten Player
of the Week. He never played another game for the Gophers. He was
suspended Feb. 15 for skipping classes and, four days later, left
the program and the school.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent much of the last six weeks answering the same
questions posed by Gabriel as well as other GMs and personnel men:
Why would he bail out on his team?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decision I made and I have to live with it,'' Przybilla
said in a recent telephone interview. ``It wasn't easy to do. I was
close to a lot of guys on that team. I'm not sure I'd even do the
same thing if it happened again, but it's over, and I've got to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, it came down to Monson. Przybilla had been
recruited by, and been close to, Clem Haskins, whose tenure as
coach ended after the revelations of academic fraud. Monson and
Przybilla did not hit it off; by the time Przybilla left school,
they hadn't spoken for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say that,'' Przybilla said, when asked if his
conflict with Monson was the main reason for his decision to leave
school. ``I was frustrated a lot. There wasn't a lot of
communication. I wanted to play for Clem Haskins. He was the main
reason I chose Minnesota in the first place and I'd probably still
be there if he was coaching. But it was hard, because I also felt I
should be loyal to the school.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't because he wasn't playing, or that he wasn't playing
well. He led the Gophers in scoring at 14.2 points a game, in
rebounding (8.4), and in blocked shots (almost 4 per game). He also
shot 63 percent from the field, but that is misleading in that he's
an around-the-basket scorer. He shot only 49.5 percent from the
free throw line. Those statistics were for 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   Przybilla was warned by Monson about repercussions for not
attending classes and study halls. He was well within the NCAA
guidelines for eligibility, but Minnesota had just instituted new
academic regulations in the wake of the Haskins scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a buildup of a lot of things,'' Przybilla said. ``It
was gradual.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took some flak immediately after leaving. Two days after
suspending Przybilla, Monson received a standing ovation when
introduced before the game with Illinois. Even worse, a fan was
booed during a halftime contest when it was revealed he also was
from Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Przybilla decided to leave school, his parents
already had talked to several player agents. All told them the same
thing: Your son is a lottery pick. The family settled on Bill Duffy
(a Minnesota alum) and he brought Przybilla out to San Francisco
for daily drills, weightlifting, and conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Przybilla put it, ``it was a lot of training.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the NBA lottery determined draft positions, Duffy started
setting up visits and workouts. Przybilla never made it to Boston;
the Celtics might like someone with his intimidation skills, but,
at 11, it's a reach. He just completed his final workout over the
weekend, visiting Chicago for a second time. He's also been to
Orlando, New Jersey, Vancouver, Houston, Cleveland, and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Of those teams, all are either in the hunt for a center or have
one who is on the edge of either free agency or retirement. The
Nets would take him only if they traded down _ there have been
rumors of a deal with the Magic _ while Vancouver seems a long shot
given it already has Big Country Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care where I go,'' Przybilla said. ``Every
place I've gone, the people have been great. But at the same time,
it's been tough. There are a lot of drills, and it's not like when
you're in college, when you can go back to the hotel and be with
your teammates. Here, you go back and you're alone.''
</P>
<P>
   How is he viewed? One general manager, preferring to remain
anonymous, said, ``he could be the next Jim McIlvaine,'' a
reference to the foul-prone, offensively challenged but
shot-blocking center for the Nets. ``McIlvaine was a shot-blocker
in college, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel thought that was a bit harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a big upside,'' Gabriel said. ``He is a legitimate
shot-blocker and there aren't many of them in the draft. Most teams
would like to have one. In workouts and interviews, he's been very
upfront and conscious of what he said and did and how it reflected
on him. I think it weighed heavy on him.''
</P>
<P>
   But all that is behind Przybilla now. He soon will become a very
wealthy man and an NBA player. That is what he envisioned when he
went to Minnesota. It's just coming sooner than he thought and
definitely not by design.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
