<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION PULLING TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ About 20 minutes after the conclusion of the
Revolution's 3-1 loss to Columbus at Crew Stadium Saturday night,
midfielder Leonel Alvarez instructed a teammate to close the door
to the coaches' office. Then, Alvarez gathered his Revolution
teammates around and, with Johnny Torres translating, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen a lot of teams in this league that have been doing
well go into a slump and start losing. It's normal. Let's forget
about this game. If we stay together, we will be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tension was broken, and the Revolution appeared
willing to follow Alvarez's advice. They need a rallying point
after failing to win for the third successive game and having their
advantage in the Eastern Division reduced to one point over the
MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get down on ourselves,'' said Revolution captain
John Harkes, whose misplay of an Alvarez pass led to the
tiebreaking goal. ``But we are still fighting for first place and
if we fight as a team, we will be stronger. Instead of fighting
individual battles, we need to stick together, and if we do that,
we will come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we are not in the position of D.C. United, where
there is pressure to win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution have completed nine successive weeks in
first place in the Eastern Division of Major League Soccer, which
makes them a candidate for most improved team of the year. But they
likely will lose their advantage to the MetroStars, who have
improved even more dramatically, and can gain the lead against San
Jose Wednesday. The Revolution will take two days off, then begin
preparing for a July 4 visit to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes could not resist making a comparison to D.C. United, his
former team, which remains in last place with 16 points. Harkes and
nearly half of his teammates have been rejected by their original
MLS teams.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Juergen Sommer made his first MLS appearance for the
Revolution after being acquired from Columbus, but was betrayed by
some ineffective defending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some amateur mistakes and on the road you can't afford
mistakes like that because the other team will punish you,'' Sommer
said. ``It's disturbing that all three of their goals came from the
6-yard box. But we all have to look at ourselves. We got to where
we are for a reason. We just have to get back to basics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are tied for third in the MLS in goals with 30
but their lack of offense against the Crew highlighted their need
for a high-profile striker.
</P>
<P>
   Director of soccer operations Sunil Gulati said the Revolution
remain in contention for Jorge Cadete of Benfica. Cadete, 31, would
fit the profile of another player who has been rejected, for a
combination of reasons related to age and salary.
</P>
<P>
   Cadete scored 74 goals in 209 games in Portugal playing for
Benfica and Sporting; 25 goals in 31 games for Celtic Glasgow in
1996-97; and eight goals in 36 games for Celta Vigo in Spain from
1997-99. Cadete's first move outside Portugal was to Brescia in
Italy's Serie B in the 1995-96 season and he was loaned to Bradford
City in England last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cadete accepted the Revolution's offer two weeks ago, but then
decided to take a vacation before making a final decision. Cadete,
a 5-foot-11-inch, 160-pound native of Porto Amelia, Mozambique,
also has been linked to Estrella Amadora, which hoped to take him
on loan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defender Mauricio Wright will return from suspension, but
midfielder Mauricio Ramos will miss the Miami game after exceeding
the number of caution points (20) allowed . . . The Revolution have
been outscored, 22-9, and have never taken a regulation win in
Columbus in nine games.
</P>
</TEXT>
