<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO WRAP UP PACKAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Yes, it's still possible to get a travel package to
Sydney for the Summer Games without paying Olympian prices. Cartan
is offering a Blue Mountains Special for $3,349 that includes
round-trip airfare from Los Angeles, six nights at a resort hotel
an hour west of Sydney, two meals daily, and event tickets. Cartan
also has one-, two-, and three-week packages using hotels,
Aussie-style ``pub'' accommodations above bar/restaurants, and host
families. Details are available online (www.cartan.com) or by
calling 1-800-818-1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too soon, meanwhile, to start lining up for tickets to
the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City. By registering online at
www.saltlake2002.com, you can create a ticket account and get
e-mail alerts. The Internet auction for 10 percent of the
high-demand tickets like the opening ceremonies and skating and
hockey finals will be held Sept. 6, with ticket orders accepted
Oct. 10-Dec. 12. Or, if you want the upscale option, you can rent a
suite at the venue of your choice. A 16-seater at Rice-Eccles
Stadium for the opening and closing ceremonies runs $120,000. Or
$154,000 for the figure skating and short-track speedskating at the
Delta Center. Or $230,000 for all 30 men's hockey games at the E
Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back to square one _ again _ for the US Olympic softball team.
After an arbitrator ordered the federation to reselect the team in
April when unchosen gold-medal veteran Julie Smith protested,
alternate Kelly Kretschman objected to being dumped from the new
roster. So the federation has to reevaluate the 39-player pool and
choose again. Meanwhile, the team is on a barnstorming tour. It
will play a split doubleheader (2:30 and 6:30 p.m.) against local
all-star teams Sunday at Worcester State . . . Most US swimmers
don't have a gripe with the new ban on bodysuits at the Olympic
trials in August. ``If everyone had a fair opportunity to wear the
suits, then it would have been OK,'' said Lenny Krayzelburg, world
record-holder in both backstrokes. ``But if some of us got an
unfair advantage over the other swimmers, then I don't think it's
fair. The fair way to make the Olympic team is everyone racing on
even ground.'' Though the Americans will be allowed to use
bodysuits in Sydney, their top foreign rivals (like Australia's Ian
Thorpe and the Netherlands' Inge de Bruijn) already will have used
them in competition . . . How dominant is The Thorpedo? His
teammate, Michael Klim, the world record-holder in the 200
freestyle, won't even swim the event in Sydney. He figures his
chances of winning five gold medals are better in the 100 free, the
100 butterfly, and the relays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Khalid Khannouchi saga isn't over. Though the new US citizen
will have missed both the US Olympic marathon and track and field
trials with a leg injury, he wants the US federation to put him on
the team anyway. Slim chance of that, though. Not only is an injury
waiver unprecedented (hurdler Greg Foster had to compete with a
broken arm at the 1988 trials), it would open the door for any
Olympic hopeful with a hamstring twinge . . . Even though Michelle
Akers hasn't played since last summer's World Cup and is coming off
shoulder surgery, US women's soccer coach April Heinrichs is
holding a spot for her _ for now. ``We're taking it week to week
with Michelle,'' said Heinrichs, who's also waiting on injured
captain Carla Overbeck. ``What we know is that even when she's
rusty, she's still a world-class player.'' . . . The US Olympic
rhythmic gymnastics trials, which will be held in Boston at the
same time as the August artistic trials, may be for naught. If
South Africa decides to send Michelle Cameron (who may be kept home
from Sydney because of the country's Olympic ``racial mix''
policy), the Americans won't move up from alternate status. Holding
her breath, meanwhile, is Jessica Howard, clearly the top US
contender. If she wins the trials, she may have to wait until the
Aug. 28 deadline for the South Africans to decide. Had Howard won
last year's Pan American Games (she missed by a thousandth of a
point), the US would have earned a wild-card spot . . .
Disappointing bowout for gymnast Jennie Thompson, who probably
would have made the US Olympic team but for a recurring ankle
injury. Thompson, who retired last week at 18, was a two-time world
team member.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Olympic rowing trials complete (except for the men's
lightweight four), the subjective part starts _ choosing the men's
and women's eights, the men's four, and the women's quad. Men's
sweep coach Mike Teti probably will select his four the week after
next for the last-chance Olympic qualifying event in Switzerland in
mid-July. Sculling coach Igor Grinko will pick a quad from eight
candidates for the Lucerne regatta. If it wins a medal there, odds
are it'll be the Olympic boat. If not, everybody's back in the mix
. . . The US rowers and kayakers may want to bring a weedwhacker to
Sydney along with their oars and paddles. The Penrith Lakes course
has some lush plant growth under the surface, which has snarled
some competitors during test events. The weeds will be cleared out
before the Games, organizers promise . . . Too bad that the
Olympics no longer has a team medal for modern pentathlon. The US
came home with the title at last weekend's world championships in
Italy as Velizar Iliev, Chad Senior, and James Gregory finished
6-10-15. Iliev and Senior will compete as individuals in Sydney . .
. With Russ Silvestri nailing down an Olympic spot at the recent
Finn world championships, the US sailors have qualified for Sydney
in all 11 classes. Returning from the 1996 squad are Lanee Butler
(women's Mistral), Mike Gebhardt (men's Mistral), Courtenay
Becker-Dey (Europe), Jeff Madrigali (Soling), Mark Reynolds (Star),
and John Lovell and Charlie Ogletree (Tornado) . . . Challenging
Olympic draw for the US men's water polo team _ World Cup champion
Hungary, Olympic runner-up Croatia, Yugoslavia, the Netherlands,
and Greece. The Yanks, who placed a disappointing seventh in
Atlanta, need to place in the top four to advance. The women,
making their Olympic debut, play a round-robin against the
Netherlands, Canada, Russia, Kazakhstan, and Australia . . . How
close did top US diver Mark Ruiz cut it at last week's Olympic
springboard trials? He was sixth after the second of six dives and
needed to be near-perfect on his final shot to make the team.
``There were no worries,'' shrugged Ruiz, who ended up first after
nailing his reverse 3 1/2 somersault with a half twist. ``I thought
I was out of it.'' Ruiz topped the platform trials Sunday . . . On
the board of the USOC'S new independent anti-doping agency is
Brockton's Peter Breen, the former ice dancer who competed with
Wellesley's Rachel Mayer in the 1992 Winter Games. Breen is now a
certified athletic trainer . . . How likely is it that US West will
have to pay $1 million to a lucky fan if Maurice Greene breaks his
world mark (9.79) in the Olympic 100. Not very, if history is a
guide. Only once has the mark in that event been broken at the
Games, by American Jim Hines at altitude in Mexico City in 1968.
</P>
</TEXT>
