<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT MARINERS THINK THINGS CAN GET EVEN BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tom Lampkin knew what he had hit. That would be a
grand slam _ one that came in the bottom of the eighth inning
Sunday to give the Mariners a 4-2 victory and a sweep of the
nose-diving Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   What Lampkin did not know was what hit (begin italics) him (end
italics) when the Mariners catcher ran back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, along with base runners Stan Javier, Alex Rodriguez and
Mike Cameron, was the first Mariner to run up the dugout steps to
congratulate Lampkin by all but bashing Lampkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that's an exciting time. It was a close game, their
starter was throwing an awesome game and it was low-scoring. For
awhile, it looked like a 2-0 game was pretty much going to hold up.
Then all of a sudden, he walks two guys, some magical things happen
and Lampkin makes a big hit,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream of moments like that as a hitter _ coming up to the
plate, two outs, bases loaded, you're down 2-nothing. That was just
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand that Buhner was wearing a fat grin while recounting
the winning moment at Safeco.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin, meanwhile, joked that he was a little shaken up by the
raucous celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been smacked around like that in the middle of a
game. I might wake up tomorrow with a sore neck. They were getting
me pretty good, not that I minded.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-fiving, back-slapping, head-pounding mob scene spoke
volumes about where this team is right now.
</P>
<P>
   And that place would be a confident, happy place, even if
Oakland keeps winning and denying the M's a chance to take first
place in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   All in good time, seems the message in Marinerville.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game you can feed off of. Things are great
right now,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you get on a roll, you feed off of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have won 16 of their past 21 games. They have won
their past seven series. If the season were to end right now, the
M's would be the wild card in the American League division series.
</P>
<P>
   But frankly, the Mariners do not seem eager to accept that
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the unofficial motto in Marinerville is: Oakland would
make an excellent wild card. The M's, of course, want the division
title and seem eager to make moves to enhance their chances.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of help do the M's need?
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, there was talk about Ken Caminiti, back before
the hard-hitting veteran found himself on the disabled list for the
next 10 weeks. Caminiti would have been perfect, especially since
he has a knack for getting big hits during September pennant
drives.
</P>
<P>
   The name Johnny Damon still sounds good, even if another
outfielder would clog things up with Rickey Henderson now on board
and contributing and Buhner having a solid season and Cameron
making everyone forget who used to play center field.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the Mariners are looking to upgrade. In fact,
there is a sense that some club officials are downright eager for
Pat Gillick to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always making contact just to see. This is the time of
year clubs have to figure whether they're in it or out of it,''
vice president of baseball administration Lee Pelekoudas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some clubs might not be happy we're calling since that means
we think they're not in it anymore. They might have a different
opinion. But you never know when a club might be willing to listen.
Either you're going to bolster your club or trade veterans to get
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are taking calls for left-handed bats and
infielders, even if they have shown a reluctance to give up
prospects like Ryan Anderson or Gil Meche.
</P>
<P>
   Pelekoudas said the Mariners may be overvaluing their own
players. Still, he said there are deals they would make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to seem too anxious. But you hate to wait too
long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the reason the M's are talking about their
desire to improve the club is to make sure Rodriguez knows that the
organization is serious about winning.
</P>
<P>
   They're not going to pick up a Juan Gonzalez or a Sammy Sosa
because, Pelekoudas said: ``We've got that guy (in Rodriguez).
We're trying to improve the club, not only to show him but to show
everybody we mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the team, the pitching (third-best in the AL) and the
defense and chemistry are undeniable. Every new player has been
able to find his role and contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a very relaxed clubhouse. There's not a lot of
media pressure. People can come in here and adjust real well. Lou's
a great manager, he just lets you come in and play,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody welcomes any addition that will help this
ballclub. And besides, look what they've done so far, making deals
to bring guys in here.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's are on a roll. No point in not trying to get a little
bit better. The M's say the phone lines are open.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
