<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ENDS AT ERSTAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Where would the Angels be without Darin
Erstad?
</P>
<P>
   That's a question for aesthetics on some days, but Sunday
evening the answer didn't require much philosophy, just math _
they'd simply be a game farther out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad homered to lead off the game, ran his way into being the
tying run in the seventh and then homered with two out in the
bottom of the 11th to deliver the Angels a much-needed 7-6 victory
over the Minnesota Twins before 19,391 on a hot, sticky evening at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time this season the Angels ended a game with a
home run, and it couldn't have come at a better time. The win kept
the flagging Angels 5 games behind Oakland and 4 behind
second-place Seattle in the AL West. It also lifted their spirits
after blowing an early three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to play well whoever we're playing,'' said Angels
manager Mike Scioscia, whose team begins a 10-game stretch Tuesday
against the Mariners and Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not halfway through the marathon yet, and we still have
our eyes on the leaders, but we need to get some momentum by
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   And nobody's playing better for the Angels this season than
Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   He ran his hitting streak to 10 games, upped his batting average
to .371, stole his team-leading 12th base, and his 57 RBI tie him
for the team lead with Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad production for a leadoff man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darin's not a leadoff man,'' Scioscia said. ``He bats No. 1 in
our lineup, but he could bat 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 in any lineup in the
league. Even by All-Star standards, he's having a phenomenal
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also took some heat off Scioscia, whose call for Orlando
Palmeiro to squeeze home the go-ahead run in the eighth with the
runners at first and third and nobody out backfired miserably when
Palmeiro popped into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad hit the first pitch he saw from Twins starter Mark Redman
and ripped it on a line just over the center-field fence. Garret
Anderson's three-run homer staked the Angels to a 4-1 lead in the
fourth, which looked good enough for Brian Cooper, whose sinker
earned him five double-play balls from an infield that included
reserves at third (Scott Speizio) and second base (Justin
Baughman).
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper, who might be sent back to Triple-A Edmonton on
Wednesday when Ken Hill is expected to be activated from the
disabled list, fell apart in the sixth. Denny Hocking, Ron Coomer
and Corey Koskie ripped doubles off him, and by the time Al Levine
ended the inning, the Twins led 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels tied the score in the seventh when they took
advantage of shortstop Jason Maxwell's error and Erstad's single to
put runners at the corners. Erstad stole second and Benji Gil's
one-out groundout scored Baughman from third and moved Erstad to
third. He scored on Tim Salmon's infield single.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad was surprised by his homer in the 11th, especially
because it came against left-hander Eddie Guardado, against whom
Erstad was 1 for 9 lifetime ``and the one was an infield hit,''
Erstad said.
</P>
<P>
   But Erstad, who popped up against Guardado in the ninth, drove a
1-0 slider over the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had my number,'' Erstad said of Guardado. ``He's one of
the best left-handed relievers, if not the best. It was probably
the first mistake he's ever made to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not trying to hit a home run. You just want to put a
ball in the gap with two outs and get into scoring position. For
me, if I start thinking about home runs, I'm in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Or exactly where the Angels would be without him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
