<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGLES-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOISCIA SAYS ANGELES NOT HOMER-HAPPY BUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL WITZ 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Angels, who have hit 119 home runs this
season, rank third in the major leagues in that category and are
nearly two-thirds of the way toward the club record of 192 despite
being two weeks shy of the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Garret Anderson became the third Angel to reach the
20-homer plateau, joining Troy Glaus, who has 23, and Mo Vaughn,
who has 20.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon, at 17, and Darin Erstad, at 16, could make the
Angels the first team to have four 20-homer players at the All-Star
break since at least 1973, which is as far back as Elias Sports
Bureau researchers have dug.
</P>
<P>
   But has all the homer-happiness lured the Angels into swinging
for the heavens? Manager Mike Scioscia doesn't think so, even
though in the six games on the homestand, the Angels have relied on
home runs to score 22 of their 33 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club has a lot more to offer than hitting the ball out of
the ballpark,'' Scioscia said, citing the club's .358 on-base
percentage, which ranks fourth in the league. ``My vision of this
club is more than hitting home runs, even though that's been
carrying us for the last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some situational hitters, some guys who can steal a
base or be part of a run-and-hit. This club can put a lot of
pressure on teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is the only one whose home runs are up _ he's two shy
of the career-high 21 he hit last season _ and whose batting
average (.241 compared to a career average of .300) has fallen off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've addressed that, particularly with Garret,'' Scioscia
said of players swinging for the fences. ``If all these guys were
hitting .210 and hitting home runs, then it would be something we'd
address.''
</P>
<P>
   A rare day off: !off!In what Scioscia termed a precautionary
move, Troy Glaus, after starting the first 73 games of the year,
took Sunday off after back spasms forced him from Saturday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus was in the on-deck circle in the eighth to hit for Justin
Baughman but was called back to the dugout after Orlando Palmeiro's
squeeze bunt backfired into a double play. Glaus is expected to be
in the lineup today at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to play 162 (games),'' Scioscia said. ``We could DH
him, but in the big picture, we need him to play third base.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Brian Cooper faced a pair of former USC teammates
Sunday. Minnesota catcher Chad Moeller and center fielder Jacque
Jones, who played with Cooper on the Trojans' 1995 College World
Series runner-up, each had a hit in two at-bats against Cooper....
Justin Baughman, after spending the past six weeks at shortstop for
Triple-A Edmonton, made his 2000 debut for the Angels at second
base. He went 0 for 4 with a run scored and he made an error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
