<HEADLINE>
MORI WINS JAPAN VOTE, BUT PARTY LOSES SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's gaffe-prone prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, can
hold onto his job. At least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese voters cast their ballots for the status quo Sunday and
returned Mori and his coalition government to power as expected.
But the Liberal Democratic Party lost seats in parliament and is
now dependent on its coalition partners to stay in power, casting
doubts on Mori's political longevity.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where fads and trends come and go with dizzying
speed, politics continues to change at a glacial pace. Despite a
decade of economic malaise, rising crime, and social anxiety, the
LDP has shown, yet again, that it faces no serious challenge to its
nearly half a century of dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Continuity and stability remain the guiding principles in
Japanese politics, particularly among the country's rural voters
and large elderly population. ``Even though Mori's character has
been criticized, my family has always voted for the LDP. It's
tradition, and I feel comfortable with it,'' said Sadao Naruse, 81,
after voting at a polling station in downtown Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP _ and its two coalition partners _ campaigned on
promises of continued public spending, in hopes of bolstering the
flagging economy, despite running up Japan's debt to the highest of
any industrialized nation. The economy grew slightly last year, but
unemployment remains near record highs.
</P>
<P>
   Election results have given Mori a reprieve, but he remains
unpopular _ both inside his own party and with Japanese voters, who
still consider the former rugby player a buffoon. He has made
several verbal blunders since taking office in April, when
then-Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi suffered a fatal stroke. Last
month, Mori called Japan ``a divine nation, with the emperor at its
core,'' a comment that rekindled memories of Japan's war-time
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, Mori is expected to face pressure to resign
from some factions within his party. On election night, the
bickering had already begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those men in the LDP are incompetent and change within the
LDP is needed,'' said party member Makiko Tanaka, as she celebrated
winning her second term.
</P>
<P>
   The governing coalition won 56 percent of the lower house seats,
compared with 65 percent in the previous government.
</P>
<P>
   Mori was considered such a hindrance in the election that few
district party offices invited him to their constituencies to speak
in support of local candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Voters say they cast their ballots not for Mori, but for his
party.
</P>
<P>
   The position of prime minister counts very much less than most
other parliamentary democracies. Japanese politics is a systematic,
intensely local affair, with voters supporting candidates based on
personal connections and pork barrel largesse.
</P>
<P>
   The election results have underscored how, in many ways, Japan
functions more like a one-party state than a democracy. ``It does
appear extraordinary, particularly if you're looking at it from a
Western political perspective,'' said Roger Buckley, professor of
history at the International Christian University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is the fact that the LDP has organized so well, it's
so experienced, it's had half a century of power, and the voters
are prepared to vote for the party almost regardless of who happens
to be the prime minister of the moment,'' Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, there is a disconnect between voters and
politicians. Many Japanese, regardless of who they support, express
a common belief that politics is becoming more irrelevant. They say
the problems affecting their lives cannot be solved by any kind of
politician. Even the lackluster economy, according to many voters,
is something they don't believe can be solved in the political
arena. Clearly, it's not enough in Japan to simply say ``the
economy, stupid'' to throw out a government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that people trust politicians less. It's that the
weight of politics has gone down. People don't feel they need
politicians,'' said political analyst Takashi Inoguchi.
</P>
<P>
   At 63 percent, voter turnout was the second-lowest on record.
Analysts say apathy _ combined with a rainy election day _ kept
voters away.
</P>
<P>
   Kana Fushimi, 28, who voted for one of the smaller opposition
parties, says she is tired of the inertia. ``Japanese people
deserve a government that never changes because no one makes any
effort to change things. I'm so fed up with that kind of
attitude,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many commentators consider the election results muddy. ``This is
an election that nobody won,'' observed one TV analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The fractured opposition, which had looked strong several weeks
ago, failed to capture voters' imaginations. They blamed the often
byzantine electoral system the LDP has managed to construct over
the decades. ``The walls of the voting system are thick,'' said
Kiyomi Tujimoto, who regained her parliamentary seat with the
opposition Social Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the largest opposition party, Minshuto, managed to gain
seats, even as smaller opposition parties lost ground. Analysts say
that could be a sign that Japan might slowly evolve into more of a
two-party system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
