u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      06-26 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRI SUBTLY TWISTING ARMS AS VOTE NEARS, OPPOSITION SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD VICTORIA, Mexico _ If one believes the opposition, the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party used to resort to blatant
election day tactics like ballot box stuffing and outright vote
tampering to make sure it did not lose elections in this northern
city called ``Victory.'' And then there was the time when party
workers reportedly buried two ballot boxes to keep the votes from
being counted.
</P>
<P>
   This year is different. Many specialists and government
officials predict that the presidential election on July 2 will be
the closest and cleanest in Mexico's history, thanks mostly to a
new independent agency that will oversee the balloting, a large
contingent of international observers, and stricter laws against
blatant abuses.
</P>
<P>
   But voters and opposition leaders say the only real change is in
the tactics of the governing party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their specialty used to be election day strategies, but they
know they can't do that anymore without getting caught,'' said
Gustavo Cardenas, former mayor of Ciudad Victoria and an opposition
candidate for Senate. ``Now, their methods are more subtle, but the
goal is the same _ winning by intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciudad Victoria is the capital of Tamaulipas, a border state
south of Brownsville, Texas, whose mix of industrial, agricultural,
and petroleum industries has long made it a PRI stronghold. But its
leaders say that it is not fraud but years of effective,
street-level organizing that has made the PRI the state's dominant
party and the odds-on favorite to win the state again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Its critics, however, allege a list of complaints involving
misuse of government workers: public workers being ordered to paste
bumper stickers on cars; professors at public universities being
told to gather signed pledges from voters to support the PRI; and
welfare offices withholding benefit checks one month only to
distribute two-month checks later at public ceremonies featuring
banners bearing the PRI's red, white, and green logo.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters and analysts say the Federal Electoral Institute, or
IFE, a nonpartisan watchdog agency established four years ago, will
help limit election day fraud. But PRI's opponents in Tamaulipas
are not taking their complaints to the agency. They say that
witnesses and victims are too scared to come forward or that PRI's
questionable methods, while unethical by international standards,
are not considered illegal under Mexican law.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things may be immoral, but they're not altogether
illegal,'' said Luis Miguel Rionda, a political analyst at the
University of Guanajuato and a member of the watchdog organization.
``IFE's power is limited in these situations because it's hard to
make connections between a benefit or a threat and someone's
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders in Tamaulipas flatly deny accusations of fraud,
subtle or obvious. The complaints, they say, are fabricated by
``lazy'' opposition parties that have not worked hard enough to
build their own political machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, the only way to win is to work hard, and no other party
does that in Tamaulipas but the PRI,'' said Juan Miguel Garcia, the
party's state general secretary. The opposition parties ``wait
until election year to work, and then they make up these
accusations as excuses when they lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia calls the party's Tamaulipas organization ``the PRI
army,'' and it's easy to see why. With more than 20,000 workers and
volunteers in this state of 3 million people, the party is by far
the dominant machine. It has organizers for each of the state's
1,739 voting precincts, who recruit 12,000 ``promoters'' to reach
out to voters.
</P>
<P>
   The party's main office is a four-story building near downtown,
one of the tallest and most easily recognized in the city. Across
the street, in a building named Fundacion Colosio, a civic
organization named after a PRI presidential candidate who was
assassinated in 1994, a half-dozen party workers clip and count
PRI-related articles from the state's 48 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the center-left opposition coalition is based in a
small two-story building, where the only two large rooms double as
offices and meeting rooms. The coalition has about 43 local groups
charged with forming ``base committees'' in each voting district,
but fewer than half are in place.
</P>
<P>
   PRI officials here are so confident of their prospects that they
have promised party leaders in Mexico City, who often use
Tamaulipas as an organizing model, to deliver more than 500,000
votes out of an expected total of 1.7 million. The governor, Tomas
Yarrington of PRI, has also guaranteed easy victories in the state
for presidential candidate Francisco Labastida Ochoa and all the
party's congressional hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents know that they have neither the organization nor the
money to compete with the PRI in Tamaulipas, so they rely on their
own tactics. To counter voter fears about PRI intimidation, workers
for both the center-left and center-right coalitions are reminding
residents that their votes are secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them to go ahead and sign those silly papers''
pledging to vote for PRI, said one volunteer for the center-right
opposition National Action Party, or PAN. ``But when it comes time
to vote, no one will know except them and God.''
</P>
<P>
   This presidential election is expected to be the tightest in
Mexican history and could unseat the PRI after 71 years of
uninterrupted rule. A national poll released Wednesday by
Reuters/Zogby showed Labastida and PAN candidate Vicente Fox
Quesada in a statistical tie. Former Mexico City mayor and Party of
the Democratic Revolution (PRD) candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas is a
distant third, followed by two others.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Alonso Perez, the PRD's general secretary in Tamaulipas,
and Gustavo Cardenas, the PAN senate candidate from Tamaulipas,
agree that their biggest challenge is to field enough precinct
representatives on election day to make sure the voting is clean
and fair. So far, the opposition parties say they've recruited
500,000 representatives to cover all of Mexico's polling places.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can just make sure that we have the people we need to
watch the polls to make sure people can vote without a problem,
then I think we can crack this machine,'' Cardenas said. ``But the
PRI is known for buying off our representatives, too. Getting a
good polling representative is almost as hard as getting someone's
vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
