<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SOCCER FANS LIVE DOWN TO IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Having watched their national soccer team beat Germany
for the first time in almost 34 years, English fans last week did
what comes naturally: They rioted.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the riot ended, 921 English fans had been arrested
by police in Charleroi, Belgium, where England had staged one of
its more dramatic victories in recent years, ending a drought
against the Germans that had lasted, in case you're counting, 33
years, 10 months, 14 days, 4 hours and 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had England defeated its arch rivals from the country
against which it had fought two world wars, its soccer hooligans
had reaffirmed their place as the most boorish, violent and racist
fans in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not exactly a good way to impress the international
committee weighing England's bid to stage the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Back here in the capital, which would host the title game in
soccer's _ and the world's _ ultimate tournament, the poohbahs who
run the Football Association, the ruling body for English soccer,
nervously tried to reassure World Cup organizers that the goons who
trashed parts of Belgium during the European championships would be
on a much tighter leash at home.
</P>
<P>
   Football Association head David Davies sounded exasperated when
he claimed that, ``We have done everything in our power to
eradicate the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the continually drunk and quarrelsome Gallagher
brothers, who front the rock band Oasis, there are few things more
embarrassing to English people than their soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   Letter writers to conservative newspapers suggested the
hooligans are the natural byproduct of a society that discourages
the celebration of English pride. Some blamed the violence on Prime
Minister Tony Blair, saying his government fostered self-loathing
among the English but was too liberal to allow police to round up
suspected hooligans before international competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, said it was time for the English to stop
excusing the inexcusable behavior of its fans by pointing
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Young, a columnist for The Guardian, said England deserves
to be banned from international competitions until it can prove its
fans won't trash every city they visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``English football has become a threat to England, a curse on
football, a menace to the citizens of every country where it's
played. And in Belgium, June 2000, it has run out of alibis,''
Young fumed. ``We are the experts in drunken violence, racist
aggression, head-banging nationalism, copycat provocation, serial
thuggery and the sniveling whine about other people's policemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheesh! Tell us how you really feel.
</P>
<P>
   Some here point to Young's self-flagellation as part of the
problem. This theory holds that the postimperial English are so
beaten down, as they have watched the Scottish and Welsh get their
own parliaments and the Irish run circles around them economically,
as the rest of Europe seems pointed in one direction and them in
the other, that the chaos on the streets of foreign capitals is an
understandable reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the Belgian cafe owners who watched English yobs
hurl their tables and chairs around like they were horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
   Some here pointed to the rioting in Los Angeles after the Lakers
won the NBA title on Monday as evidence that such behavior is not
limited to English soccer fans. And there was no serious trouble
after England's other matches in the European championships against
Portugal and Romania.
</P>
<P>
   But those games took place on weekdays. The Germany match was on
a weekend, when the yobs _ most of whom, contrary to stereotypes,
have jobs _ could show up to cause trouble.
</P>
<P>
   There is a great irony that the oafish behavior of English fans
probably will persuade World Cup organizers to reject England's bid
for the 2006 finals in favor of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Someone attending the World Cup in South Africa will have a
higher statistical chance of falling victim to crime than here in
England, where violent crime is far less prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   But they will have a considerable less chance of being beaten up
by some drunk named Nigel using the flag of St. George to cover his
beer belly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of The Boston Globe London Bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 0901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
