<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-BALLOTS-BOS &LR;      06-26 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-BALLOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS WEIGH IN ON ZIMBABWE'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NHEDZIWA, Zimbabwe _ Picking his way down the rocky dirt road
that leads through the center of this far-off village near the
Mozambique border, Jonathan Munjoma cut the profile of a diehard
supporter of Zimbabwe's ruling party. He is landless and poor and,
steadying his gait with a cane, belongs to the aging generation
that waged war against colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   But when Munjoma cast his ballot Sunday in elections offering
Zimbabweans a choice between truly competitive parties for the
first time in 20 years, Munjoma voted against his peers. More
striking still, he gave his support to one of President Robert
Mugabe's favorite villains _ a wealthy, white farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old guys, we know: Most things have changed for the
worse,'' Munjoma said. ``I grew up under a white government. They
did us a lot of good, unlike our leaders now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the racially charged atmosphere surrounding Zimbabwe's
parliamentary election over the weekend, some might have called
Munjoma's vote an act of treason. Faced with the threat of losing
power after two decades of unimpeded rule, Mugabe lashed out with
the rhetoric of a revolutionary, blaming white farmers, the British
government, and white South Africans for sabotaging Zimbabwe's
economy and starving the people of land.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the liberation war, goaded by the president, waged a
four-month campaign of terror against white commercial farmers,
invading their land, destroying crops, and beating their black
workers. Mugabe cast the opposition, which draws some of its
financial support from whites and South Africans, as a puppet of
the region's erstwhile racist regimes.
</P>
<P>
   But playing the race card may not have worked as well as Mugabe
hoped. Voters turned out in record numbers during the two-day poll,
which closed Sunday night. In Nhedziwa and other villages within
the voting district of Chimanimani _ one of only two rural voting
districts where white candidates are running against the ruling
party _ most black voters said Mugabe was blaming whites to mask
his government's record of economic mismanagement and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The only racists in Zimbabwe, many said, were the president and
his thugs _ and they said it was time for them to leave. ``Mugabe
wants people to go backward 20 years to the liberation war,'' said
Ngaazwni Machinguru, an elderly resident of Nhedziwa.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violent campaign season, in which at least 30 people
were killed, teams of international observers reported that the
voting went off with only scattered reports of intimidation. The
European Union's monitoring team said the ballot counting, which
began Monday, would have to be carefully monitored, but that the
voting process was largely successful. Results are expected
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There are 120 parliamentary seats at stake. At least 55 percent
of voters cast ballots, almost twice as high a turnout as in the
last parliamentary poll five years ago. Both sides said that the
enthusiastic response augured well for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe is history,'' said opposition leader Morgan Tsvangirai
Sunday. ``There is life beyond Mugabe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, retorted John Nkomo, chairman of the ruling party,
``No other party has a chance. . . . We have done our work and the
results will speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, hoping to tap into deep popular frustration over
high unemployment and rampant corruption, based its campaign on
severe economic decline. Mugabe's party exploited the land
question. Give white-owned farms to blacks, the president argued,
and the majority will finally control the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Land has always been a volatile issue in Zimbabwe. Farms became
battlegrounds during the liberation war. Twenty years after
independence, however, most of the best agricultural plots still
rest in the hands of a tiny white community, while much of the
black majority remains poor and landless.
</P>
<P>
   But in the months before the election, as the war veterans
attacked more than 1,300 commercial farms, many black Zimbabweans
said the ruling party was only deepening the country's economic
woes. The tobacco crop alone accounts for 40 of annual foreign
currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
   And when voters in Chimanimani district had a chance to elect a
new government, they did not seem bothered by the color of the
opposition candidate's skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism is something awkward to us,'' said Julius Zvarevashe, a
middle-aged man outside a cafe in the village of Wengazi. ``We
don't want to lose those people. They are Zimbabweans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
