<HEADLINE>
YOU HAVE ONLY YOURSELF TO BLAME FOR HIGH LONG-DISTANCE BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. has taken a lot of heat lately from government
regulators and consumer advocates for trying to hike the
long-distance calling rates of tens of millions of customers on its
basic calling plan, but I could care less.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission earlier this month signed
off on a deal lowering the costs of long-distance companies, hoping
those savings would be passed along to customers. AT&AMP;T responded by
eliminating the monthly minimum fee on its basic calling plan and
increasing the per-minute rate. Net result: Higher rates for most
customers on the plan. AT&AMP;T backed off, at least temporarily, after
the FCC squawked.
</P>
<P>
   What AT&AMP;T did was incredibly stupid from a public relations
standpoint, but I don't have much sympathy for customers on its
basic calling plan. The plan is AT&AMP;T's most expensive. It charges
26 cents a minute weekdays, 16 cents a minute weeknights, and 11.5
cents a minute on weekends. I figure the only people on it are
those who don't mind paying excessive rates or who are too lazy to
sign up for a discount plan.
</P>
<P>
   What concerns me more is AT&AMP;T's decision to discontinue as of
July 31 its connect'n'save service. Connect'n'save is a prepaid
phone-to-phone service that routes calls over the Internet. It can
be used to supplement your existing long-distance provider or
replace it entirely. It's available in major cities in
Massachusetts, Arizona, California, Florida, Georgia, and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Grant canceled his long-distance carrier and went with
connect'n'save because it was so easy to use. It cost 7.5 cents a
minute using a local access number and 15 cents using toll-free
access, and it came with none of the fees and charges typical of
long distance.
</P>
<P>
   Like Grant, more and more customers are looking for an
alternative to their existing long-distance providers. Dean Dakin,
for example, is tired of paying an 8.6 percent universal service
fee to AT&AMP;T, which amounted to $5.78 on a recent bill. (The
universal service fee, which varies dramatically from company to
company, finances Internet access for schools and libraries and
makes phone service affordable for low-income and rural residents.)
</P>
<P>
   Tauby Warriner began thinking about dumping AT&AMP;T after her
daughter moved back to Massachusetts. Her only concern was whether
there were any hidden pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who cut the chord to his long-distance carrier six
months ago, I'd say go for it. You will probably have to dial more
numbers to make a call, but you can control your costs better and
avoid all those annoying fees and taxes that show up on your
long-distance bill every month regardless of whether you make any
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you have to do is sever your ties to your
long-distance carrier. Your local phone company can handle that for
you. Bell Atlantic charges a one-time fee of $5 to make the switch.
It has been imposing a $1.04 monthly charge to cover the cost of
long-distance access, but that is slated to disappear July 1.
</P>
<P>
   There are several options for making long-distance calls without
a long-distance carrier. You can use prepaid calling cards or 10-10
dial-around services, which let you make calls with a special
access code and be billed monthly on your local phone bill. Many of
these services don't offer directory assistance, so you will have
to locate numbers using your local phone company, Internet
telephone directories, or directory assistance services that can be
accessed independently.
</P>
<P>
   What was nice about AT&AMP;T's connect'n'save service was its
simplicity. You purchased calling time in advance with a credit
card. To make a call, you had to dial a local access number or a
toll-free number, then punch in a personal identification number
and the number being called. (The PIN could be skipped when calling
from home.) There were no monthly fees, so if you didn't make a
call during the month, you weren't charged anything.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T launched connect'n'save in Boston in 1998 to learn about
carrying calls over the Internet. But after making a substantial
investment in Net2Phone, an industry leader in Internet telephony,
AT&AMP;T decided to drop its own service.
</P>
<P>
   Net2Phone's comparable service costs less _ 3.9 cents a minute
using a local access number and 6.9 cents a minute using a
toll-free number _ but it comes with a 99-cent monthly charge.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are other options. The 10-10 dial-around
offerings are easy to use, but they often come with a catch or a
hidden fee. Two popular ones are Excel's 10-10-297 and PT-1's
10-16-868. They charge 10 cents a minute and 7.9 cents a minute,
respectively, along with universal service fees.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid calling cards are popular, but require the buyer to go
shopping for one. They also often carry hidden fees. One of my
favorite prepaid cards is put out by Conexus. Its rates aren't the
lowest (10 cents a minute using a local access number and 15 cents
with a toll-free number), but there are no hidden fees and the card
can be recharged.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bell Atlantic, which is just entering the long-distance
market, is moving in the prepaid direction with a customer-friendly
offering. Its SmartTouch calling plan charges 8 cents a minute at
all times with no additional fees. And unlike calling cards or
10-10 offerings, you don't have to dial any extra numbers to place
a call.
</P>
<P>
   The best deal I've heard of so far is BigZoo.com. The price _
3.9 cents a minute all the time using a toll-free access number _
is great and there are no hidden charges. It does require you to
dial the access number, input a PIN number and then the number you
are calling, but for low-volume callers that's not too big a
burden.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Stevenson has been using BigZoo for months and loves
it. She says she has been charged occasionally for calls that
aren't answered or calls that get a busy signal (something that
shouldn't happen, according to BigZoo's Web site), but other than
that it's worked perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the other services I've mentioned, you can try
BigZoo as a supplement to your existing long-distance carrier to
see if you like it. ``The service has been flawless,'' Stevenson
said. ``I think this is definitely worth looking into.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
