<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANSWERS IN THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talking with astrologers who do market analysis is about as
mystical as a trip to the accountant. Too bad. The superstitious
investor had hoped for a little more ``Twilight Zone'' music _ OK,
a lot more ``Twilight Zone'' music _ being as the market has always
seemed just plain weird and under the spell of a very dark star, if
not the devil himself.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, says Henry Weingarten, who manages The Astrologers
Fund Inc. in New York, investing under $4 million for private
clients. He talks at Internet speed about expanding into a major
mutual fund in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   For him and others in the trade, astrology is just one more tool
on the desk. There's the economy, company earnings records, the old
buy and sell, stock market cycles, and, oh yes, the positions of
Jupiter and Saturn, which happened to be moving into conjunction
this spring and probably helped toss the Nasdaq into the dumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between one-third and one-half of all the market's surprises
are callable by astrology,'' says Weingarten in his machine-gun
delivery, adding that he also relies on good, solid math and logic.
</P>
<P>
   He gets written up in Barrons and leaves his predictions on his
Web site for years so that people can see if he was right _ which
he was about the 1987 US market crash, the 1990 Tokyo economic
dive, the Mexican financial crisis, and the sickly euro.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks New Age sensibilities are making people more
receptive to the ancient art of tracking the heavens, he snorts
into the phone. ``Look at the world,'' he snaps, ticking off wars
and famine and ethnic cleansing. There's only one reason astrology
is on Wall Street, he says _ it makes sense, in its place, as long
as a person doesn't go wacko with it.
</P>
<P>
   He's one more technocrat in an age of technocrats, marshaling
methodology and data to explain even the occult. He makes a person
long for a gypsy in a tent, someone who gazes trancelike into the
crystal ball and whispers: ``You will meet a tall, dark Scorpio
selling Lycos,'' or ``Beware of geeks bearing Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   The superstitious investor had hoped for a screaming nut,
someone who sported a garlic necklace and babbled about vampires on
Wall Street. Wouldn't we all feel a little better about investing
in a dud if supernatural forces had taken hold of the portfolio.
``Hey, man, it's vampires. No wonder I lost my shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   But market astrologers do not so much as twitch. Ray Merriman,
president of the International Society for Astrological Research
and author of the newsletter ``Merriman Market Analyst,'' launches
into a lecture on the cycle theory of economics.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with ``the Kondratieff wave,'' named for Russian
economist Nicolai Kondratieff, who studied 54-year trends. Then
Merriman explains that there are also 18-year, four-year,
three-year, and 22 1/2-month cycles, which experts study as
carefully as the position of Pluto.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the Scorpio with the Lycos, Ray? Moon in Libra.
Pisces rising. Married to a Cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astrology is just a study of static market timing,'' he says.
``You need the technical analysis along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if we don't want it? What if we'd rather go with
sunspots?
</P>
<P>
   Arch Crawford says that's fine, as long as we understand the
science. The Arizona author of the newsletter ``Crawford
Perspectives'' explains that storms on the sun cause
electromagnetic energy to hit the earth, which rattles the human
psyche and makes people uneasy _ so the market usually drops and
gold rises.
</P>
<P>
   He has been using astrology in his market analysis for nearly 40
years and has tracked astrological events against percentage
changes in the market back to 1896. ``Straight statistical
analysis,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using a horoscope is as good as using a balance sheet,'' says
Richard Mogey, who runs an Oregon money management firm. ``We use
technical analysis. We study economics, demographics, and trends.
And we use several indices that are strictly planetary.''
</P>
<P>
   Indices. Great. And the gypsy probably has them on a computer
now. (itals)Look deep into my indices. You will feel yourself
growing drowsy . . . drowsy . . . very drowsy.(unitals0
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
