<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      06-26 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING COULD HARDLY BE WORSE, BUT FUND CHOICES ARE FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I invested in my four funds on March 8, two days before the
stock market took a big loss. Should I take my loss of about $6,000
and change to other funds? All of my positions are negative, except
in the Index 500 fund. My investment time frame is nine years.
Would I have been better off if I had chosen Vanguard LifeStrategy
Growth Balanced, or maybe Vanguard Total Stock Market fund? I have
other funds with fixed-income portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   I.T., Tennessee &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, your timing certainly couldn't have been much worse. In
all likelihood, you'd be under water with this portfolio, whichever
funds you chose, given the date of your investment.
</P>
<P>
   I think you have the Vanguard LifeStrategy funds a bit mixed up.
There is a Vanguard LifeStrategy Conservative Growth fund, a
LifeStrategy Moderate Growth, and a Vanguard Balanced Index fund.
All of these are balanced funds, dividing their assets among the
stock and bond markets. LifeStrategy Conservative is the most
cautious of the three, holding 62 percent of its assets in bonds.
LifeStrategy Moderate Growth holds 43 percent in bonds, and the
Balanced Index fund has 39 percent in bonds. The use of any of
these funds would have moderated your loss _ but you would still be
under water.
</P>
<P>
   Since you mention you hold other funds and all of them have
fixed-income portfolios, I presume your thinking was that by taking
positions in the stock funds you would thus be creating a balanced
portfolio, similar to what a balanced fund would give you. Since
you set your investment time frame at nine years, that would be
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Your selection of funds was good _ all have proven track records
and all should deliver solid results in the long run. Only Janus
Mercury could be viewed as an aggressive investment, with a
portfolio concentrated in only 72 stocks and with a
price-to-earnings ratio of 53.5 as this is written; it was
doubtless much higher when you made your investment. The only thing
that wasn't appropriate, as it turned out, was your timing.
</P>
<P>
   Should you be ready to jump ship after only four months? If I
have correctly characterized your strategy _ building a balanced
portfolio by countering your fixed-income positions in other funds
with these four stock funds _ I think you should hang on. A
four-month period is simply too short to decide that your thinking
was wrong, and even a year would be inadequate to assess whether a
nine-year investment strategy was ill-conceived.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you feel the whiplash that can come from
stock positions is too much for you, you certainly would find that
any of the three balanced funds I started out discussing would
deliver a smoother ride. But by turning to one of these, you also
would be limiting the upside potential of your long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have no savings or investments; my expenses equal my net
income of $2,000 a month. In seven years, I will be able to retire,
receiving about $1,500 a month pension. My hope is to work part
time after retirement to make up the difference in income. Soon, I
will inherit about $120,000 and I am trying to decide how to best
put this money to use. I am considering paying off the mortgage,
making some renovations, paying off my credit cards, making some
charitable donations, and investing the remaining $5,000. After
paying off the mortgage, I hope to invest $600 a month until I
retire. Is this a wise plan?
</P>
<P>
   R.M., Austin, Texas &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's begin with the assumption that you have firmly decided
to pay off your credit cards, renovate your home, and make the
charitable donations. That leaves $80,000, all of which might be
invested, or most of which might be used to pay off the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose you decide to invest all of that money, selecting
as an investment the Vanguard Balanced Index fund. You might
reasonably expect the fund to deliver 9 percent average annual
gains over the next seven years. That would take the accumulation
from $80,000 to $149,837.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's project what would happen if you put $5,000 in the
same fund, adding $600 a month. After seven years with the same
presumed growth rate, you would have $79,214.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first case, you would still have the mortgage on your
hands, with another 20 years of payments ahead. I'm making the
assumption that about $190 of your monthly payment represents
taxes, and about $600 of it goes toward interest and principal.
Thus, I'm estimating that in seven years the balance would be about
$60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the figures, you would be about $10,000 ahead if you
invested in the fund and kept banging away at the mortgage, month
by month. But the next step is to reread the letter above, noting
how unhappy the writer is with his investments. Working out
projections of investment returns is easy _ you simply establish a
projected rate of return and bang the figures into the computer.
But there is no assurance those returns will be as estimated.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that having an extra $10,000 after seven years is
not worth the risk inherent in investing in funds with major
stock-market exposure. Moreover, the month-by-month saving
procedure you propose represents an investment discipline called
dollar-cost averaging, and it is much safer than making a lump-sum
investment.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it's up to you, but if it were my money, I'd take
the safer course and pay off the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am new to investments. When I asked my broker about
Vanguard funds, she said she had no information.
</P>
<P>
   L.J., Santee, S.C. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're not apt to find out much about Vanguard, or any other
no-load fund family, from a stockbroker, since there is no way for
a broker to collect a commission, either from you or the fund
family, when you buy a no-load fund.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean your broker is being mean or evasive? No. Brokers
provide a real and important service, particularly to investors who
have not yet gained very much experience. They will assess your
goals, risk tolerance, tax situation, and many other factors, and
then make a recommendation tailored to your particular situation.
If you decide to buy individual stocks or bonds, you will be
charged commissions, a good part of which goes to the broker.
</P>
<P>
   Stockbrokers can also sell mutual funds, but invariably there
will be a fee. With many funds, you can choose various classes of
shares with different fee structures _ either an upfront sales
charge, a sales charge sometimes called a level load that takes the
form of higher fund expenses, or a rear-end load, which is levied
when you sell the shares. However you buy the shares, the
stockbroker gets paid.
</P>
<P>
   No-load mutual funds are designed for investors who feel they
know enough to analyze their own needs, market conditions, and
their appetite for risk. Some no-load funds, such as those in the
Vanguard Group, merge no-load status with quite low expenses and
fairly conservative portfolio management. Since Vanguard is a
mutual company _ owned by the funds in the family _ there is no
parent institution looking for dividends. Other no-load funds are
managed by investment companies, which seek to reap a profit;
accordingly the expenses are usually higher, often much higher.
Remember, making an analysis of a fund's expenses is part of the
work you would be paying a broker to do if you bought a fund
through a brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   I encourage you to hesitate to invest until you're sure you have
educated yourself about what you are buying, the costs, what are
reasonable expectations of returns, the risk of losses, and so
forth. If you aren't confident that you fully understand what
you're doing, it might be wiser to go with your broker's advice.
</P>
<P>
   There a variety of ways you can educate yourself about mutual
funds, including literature from the funds themselves. Libraries
have a wealth of knowledge about mutual funds. And if you have a
computer, you can learn a great deal by going to the Web site of
Morningstar Mutual Funds, a company that tracks and analyzes them.
At www.morningstar.com you can find copious information about most
funds, including Vanguard's. But a better place to start are the
pages called Morningstar University, which you will see at the top
of Morningstar's home page.
</P>
<P>
   When you're ready to look at particular funds, call Vanguard at
1-800-662-7447, or write to Vanguard Group, Vanguard Financial
Center, P.O. Box 2600, Valley Forge, PA 19482.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
