<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-ANALYSTS-BOS &LR;      06-26 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-ANALYSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES OFFER ANALYSTS` REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without question, a handful of high-power analysts have the
ability to move markets. When the financial beau monde say a stock
is about to jump, Wall Street just wants to know how high.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, for example, Lehman Brothers analyst Dan Niles said
he thought Intel Corp. would earn $3.10 per share this year, up
three pennies from an earlier projection. Shares of the world's
biggest computer chip maker went crazy, gaining more than 8 percent
by the end of the day. Following Intel's lead, the Nasdaq Composite
index gained 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such influence works in both directions, of course, and on more
than a single stock.
</P>
<P>
   In prose only a Fed chairman could love, Goldman Sachs's leading
bull, Abby Joseph Cohen, wrote March 28 that ``the market is not as
undervalued as it was.'' Innocuous though it sounded, Cohen's
comment was the talk of the investing world that day, and the
Nasdaq tumbled 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Headline-grabbing comments, though, tend to be the exception for
the roughly 4,000 Wall Street analysts. More often, they spend
their days poring over corporate and financial minutiae to crank
out reports in relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Securities and Exchange Commission announced
that it was investigating ways to force analysts to disclose
conflicts of interest when they talk stocks up or down.
</P>
<P>
   And analysts have long been criticized for refusing to say
anything negative about companies they cover (out of fear they'll
lose coveted access to insiders) and for giving their reports to
high-roller clients days or weeks before turning them over to the
unwashed masses.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, critics contend, the real value of analysts' reports is
in the aggregate. Looking at the consensus earnings forecast of two
dozen analysts who follow a company _ and how the group's
collective opinion has changed in recent weeks or months _ might be
more valuable than reading one analyst's comments.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the price is better.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Web sites now offer varying degrees of free access
to databases of analyst predictions. To buy a single analyst report
through the normal channels, on the other hand, would set you back
anywhere from $5 to $300.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.bulldogresearch.com is the newest and strangest entry in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Launched last month, the site is built around the concept of
rating analysts based on the accuracy and consistency of their
forecasts. Peripherally, it includes consensus analyst numbers for
such areas as 12-month target price, quarterly and annual earnings,
price-earnings ratio and, of course, buy/sell recommendations (on a
scale of 1, ``strong buy,'' to 5, ``strong sell'').
</P>
<P>
   Using Waltham-based I/B/E/S International for its database of
3,000 analysts from 350 US companies, the site gives first-,
second-, and third-place ``Bulldog Awards'' to analysts whose
recommendations come closest to hitting the mark, both in the
latest quarter and over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at it strictly on the basis of its consensus numbers and
investment tools, Bulldog Research offers less than its peers.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing some accountability on analysts is a laudible goal,
though, and makes the site worth a visit. (Firms that haven't
agreed to participate are still included in the rankings, but their
analysts are identified only as ``unattributed.'')
</P>
<P>
   _ www.multexinvestor.com is a clearinghouse for research reports
from the major brokerages, including Credit Suisse First Boston,
Deutsche Bank, Goldman Sachs, J.P. Morgan, Lehman Brothers, Merrill
Lynch, and Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the reports are for sale, but a couple are always free.
When I asked for information on Microsoft shares, for example, the
site offered up a pair of (no-cost) reports prepared by Multex and
31 (at full cost) from the brokerage houses.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need Adobe Acrobat Reader on your computer to read any of
the reports, but it's a free and easy download. And the free
reports do a relatively good job of encapsulating the consensus
estimates in a wide range of areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.thomsoninvest.net uses Boston-based First Call as its data
provider.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, First Call will probably merge with I/B/E/S,
since The Thompson Corp. (parent company of First Call) bought
Primark (parent company of I/B/E/S) on June 5. Whether that will
mean consolidation in the number of sites that provide consensus
estimates remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Thompson Investors Network provides much the
same kind of service as Multex Investor. It offers a ``tip sheet''
that shows a stock's intraday and longer-term performance, along
with consensus estimates on earnings and buy/hold recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   If you want complete reports, which the site offers, it will
cost you. Most other investment tools on the site also require you
to subscribe to the service, which costs $34.95 a year for a basic
membership. (First Call reports are extra.)
</P>
<P>
   _ www.zacks.com gave my Netscape browser the most trouble of the
sites reviewed, but for good reason: It has so many things going
on.
</P>
<P>
   A full-service investment site, Zacks offers portfolio tracking,
charts, news, commentary, e-mail alerts, earnings surprises, an
earnings calendar, and plenty of information on analysts' reports.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to tracking and consolidating those reports, Zacks
is the best of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   After you punch in a ticker symbol, the site lists every analyst
who covers the stock _ not by name, but as either a regional,
national, or institutional broker. For each one, you can review the
quarterly and annual earnings estimates, the five-year growth rate,
the recommendation, and when that analyst's last report was issued.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer, you can skip the detail and head straight for the
consensus numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.stockselector.com is the best of a group of similar sites
that feature oodles of information about analysts' recommendations
and ratings, but not the consensus estimates. Others include
www.financialweb.com and http://investor.cnet.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
