<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-CO     06-26 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bedrock of our economy: Nine-tenths, 99 cents, 99
dollars
 &HT;    For release June 28, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't buy a precise gallon of gasoline because you haven't
got nine-tenths of a cent. Analysts tell us the average price of a
gallon of gasoline in the past two weeks has risen 4.11 cents to a
nationwide average of $1.7134.
</P>
<P>
   Question: If gasoline prices rise and fall by hundredths or
thousandths of a cent, then how come the pump price never
fluctuates from nine-tenths of a cent? Why is the price of gasoline
never something like 1.71 and three-tenths of a cent, if that's
what the average really is? You can bet it's posted as 1.71 and
nine-tenths of a cent, thereby lifting another six-tenths of a cent
out of your purse.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a U.S. quirk. As an example, in England, a liter of
gas will cost .799 pence; not 8 pence.
</P>
<P>
   What began as mind games has perpetuated itself.
</P>
<P>
   The original concept of nine-tenths of a cent is no different
than what retailers in the clothing industry do: everything ends in
95 up to 99 cents. A shirt never costs $34.25 or $34.00; it's
always $34.99 or $34.95. Its intent: to keep the number from
spilling over to the next highest dollar: $35. The psychology is
that you might balk at paying $35, but $34.99 appears to be a
dollar cheaper _ which, of course, it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateurs play the game as well: The poached salmon goes for
$16.95, not $17. The iced tea is $1.69, not $1.70. Some might argue
that this is saving the consumers a penny every time but we all
know that is not the case. The cost of a glass of iced tea or even
an entree in a restaurant is arbitrary, not market driven. It can
end in any fraction of a dollar, or _ heaven forbid! _ even be
rounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Down at the local office supply store, a package of copying
paper costs $3.19 not $3.20, toner for my laser printer is $39.99
not $40 and the ink cartridges are $23.99 not $24 and certainly not
$23.45 or $23.60.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is advertising its Think Paid Series 1250 at $2,099. Oh,
give me a break!
</P>
<P>
   You want to lease a car? Here are some options in today's local
paper: Jaguar 2000 at $499 a month, Infiniti I30 at $399 a month,
Volvo S70 at $399 a month. Plus tax, of course, which knocks the 99
cents barrier totally out of comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   In Virgin Atlantic Airlines advertisements for London travel
packages, each of the eight options ended in nine dollars.
Continental will take you on a package to Puerto Rico for $479; to
Bermuda for $589; to Mexico for $599; to Israel for $1,579 --
always it ends in ``9.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the psychology of marketing and sales.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is subliminal. Mark it $399 so it won't appear to be
$400; mark it 99 cents so it won't appear to be a dollar, 79 cents
so it won't appear to be 80 cents. I wish I had saved my last super
market register tape to see what percentage of the items I
purchased ended in 99 cents. Probably most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Question: when you pass a gas station and see the posted price
of $1.71 and nine-tenths of a cent, does your mind tell you that
gallon of gas costs $1.72, or does it tell you $1.71?
</P>
<P>
   I don't think I'm unique in seeing it at the lower price, until
my mind clicks up a notch and says it's really $1.72. It has only
been recently that I have managed to conquer this subliminal
brainwash.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us are running out of pennies -- and never had tenths of
a cent (called mills) at all. Interestingly, many restaurants (and
some convenience stores) now keep a little container near their
cash registers where you may help yourself to, or leave, a penny or
two when paying for your purchase.
</P>
<P>
   That proves how petty is the penny; it's a throwaway coin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, retailers continue to play the penny game on their price
tags and gasoline stations (and dealers) continue to manufacture
that nine-tenths of a cent vigorish at the pumps.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody seems to want to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
