<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX     06-26 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Death penalty, gay rights have America talking
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two matters that had seemed among the Great Immutables of
American life are showing distinct signs of wobble. It is unclear
where the startlingly sudden conversation about the death penalty
is headed, but the drift in what is loosely called gay rights seems
fairly clear. The surprise there is that the momentum is
accumulating so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-nine of the largest 500 companies now offer, or have said
they will soon, spouse-like benefits to the same-sex partners of
employees.
</P>
<P>
   That, as social change goes, is almost whiplash speed,
considering that the Human Rights Campaign Fund, which tracks such
matters, counts the big breakthrough as occurring just nine years
ago with Lotus, the software company.
</P>
<P>
   The process leaped ahead recently with the announcement that the
United Auto Workers union and the Big Three carmakers have agreed
to same-sex partner benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to figure that an even bigger step was taken just
days later when the Coca-Cola company of Atlanta made a similar
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is seen as almost the archetypal southern company, though
not altogether fairly. It has been a sophisticated international
corporation for years, its vestigial southern drawls richly salted
with a polyglot of accents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, totemistically and really, it does represent its region,
one that is widely counted the nation's most socially conservative
_ again a bit unfairly but, frankly, in this instance, fairly
enough.
</P>
<P>
   When the belle of southern commerce, at the very locus of the
Bible Belt, adopts benefit equity for gay households, it seems a
fair guess the decade will end with few of those 500 biggest
corporations still holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   For decades even to bring up capital punishment was considered
socially gauche and politically suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, support has slipped from well over 70 percent to just over
60 and even many in that majority are having doubts. The striking
drop in serious crime has cleared space for dialogue and DNA
technology has forced the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   So many on death rows have been cleared by that and other means
that the Republican governor of Illinois has called a moratorium on
executions, something the American Bar Association has been urging
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Bills in Congress would require even post-appeal DNA testing if
that becomes possible and would let juries be told that life
without parole is among the sentence options. Any reforms, to be at
all conscionable, must include a universal, skilled public-defender
system. The court-appointed attorney racket in Texas most
notoriously and in many other states is farcical and fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best reforms would leave the ultimate -- and, lest we
forget, our only irreversible _ sanction tilted against the poor
and the socially and emotionally marginal. Still, let not the
perfect bar the good.
</P>
<P>
   Little connects these two matters, except this: a welcome
reminder that the innate American sense of fair play can still kick
in when we aren't distracted from it. We've been too long
distracted.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
