r l BC-TECH-SAVVY0627-COX     06-26 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creating an umlaut easy
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Can you tell me how to type an umlaut?
</P>
<P>
   _ Horst Kuehne, Elyria, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Sue: First, let's explain what an umlaut is. It's used in Asian
and European languages that are written in the Roman alphabet. An
umlaut appears over a vowel to indicate a vowel change. The
characters would look like this: , I, O, E, A.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Ha, looks like a bunch of funny-looking smiley faces to
me. Just kidding. Creating an umlaut is easy whether you are using
a Mac or PC. On the PC, open the Character Map (depending on
whether you are using Windows 95 or 98, it's either in Accessories
or Systems Tools). Locate the vowel with the umlaut accent and
click it. Click Select, then Copy. Go to your document and paste in
the character where you want it to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: On the Mac, use your Keycaps application. It is usually
located in your Apple Menu Items pull-down menu. If you hold down
the Option key, you will see the umlaut character. Click it. You'll
then be able to select the correct vowel. Copy and paste it into
your document.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   What would cause a computer clock to suddenly show one hour
earlier? I put my PC on standby last night, and today, the time was
an hour earlier than yesterday. I got this computer in November
'99. Last year, my computer at work did the same thing. Whenever I
fixed the time, it would always go back an hour. I gave up. I later
left the company, so I don't know if it was ever resolved. Strange
that it happened again. Please solve the mystery!
</P>
<P>
   _ Ron Dombcik, Aurora, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: I was bitten by something similar awhile back. Do you
think there's a possibility that a change was made inadvertently to
your daylight saving time and/or time zone settings?
</P>
<P>
   Sue: It's definitely worth checking. To get to the Date/Time
Control Panel, click on the Start button, scroll up to Settings and
over to Control Panels. If you're using Win95, click the Time Zone
tab and see if ``automatically adjust clock for daylight saving
changes'' is selected.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Although your computer is fairly new, you might look into
the possibility that your system battery is malfunctioning if the
problem persists. The issues could mean the battery is losing juice
and needs to be replaced. That could be quite simple or extremely
tricky, depending on the computer manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Some batteries are removable; some are soldered to the
motherboard. You could look for a computer shop, or if you're up
for doing a battery install, go to hardwarecentral.com and click on
the Tutorials link for a how-to.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
