<SLUG> BC-TECH-HOMEGEAR0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A rough and tumble radio
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As much a contractor's job site radio as a
gadget for the home, the DeWalt Radio/Charger ($130;
www.dewalt.com) is sure to make Dad the Home Handyman feel like a
pro as he putzes around the house. Extremely durable and encased in
a rough and tumble cage, the DW911 is not just an
industrial-strength radio (complete with audio inputs for CD
players and the like), it's also a battery charger for 9.6-volt
through 18-volt DeWalt rechargeables that make all those must-have
DeWalt cordless tools go. The unit boasts a ludicrously speedy
one-hour recharge time, which effectively eliminates at least one
excuse for that backyard project delay. Also, the radio will run on
one of those rechargeable batteries just in case there's no AC
nearby. Get to work, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   TV AND DVD IN ONE
</P>
<P>
   The best part about entry-level products: A friendly price often
offsets the uncertainty factor. Enter Konka's TD138U ($349; www.
konkausa.com), a 13-inch color TV with a built-in DVD player and
full remote control. Suited to the college dorm, the guest room or
the cottage, this novel unit offers a compact taste of video
viewing in the digital age. Naturally unable to compete with
separate, high-end components of similar ilk, the TD138U's
combination feature is one of its stronger assets. More
importantly, picture and sound quality offered by even a
middling-caliber DVD player is still notably better than that of
VHS standards, a fact well illustrated on the sharp, clear screen
and diminutive stereo speakers. The TD138U also contains most of
the features associated with DVD, including malleable screen ratios
for widescreen viewing or the unabashedly hacked ``formatted for
TV'' look. There are also language and subtitle options, AC3
output, etc. The TV itself comes complete with modern conveniences
such as a sleep timer, trilingual on-screen menu displays, close
captioning and audio/video inputs for VHS tape players or video
game
</P>
<P>
   consoles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
