<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0627-     06-26 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBy Maurice Tamman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you have a high-speed connection to the Internet,
chances are your computer is being attacked daily.
</P>
<P>
   A novice hacker, with some basic networking knowledge, could
easily capture all of your Internet activity, including e-mails and
most log-ons and passwords. Even a neighbor, armed with mild
curiosity, could peek at every file on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Users can block most attacks by using firewalls and configuring
their systems correctly, but some of the attacks are invisible,
said Lincoln David Stein, author of ``Web Security: A Step by Step
Reference Guide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rely on your (Internet provider) doing it right,''
he said. ``And people who don't protect themselves could be
wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not a theoretical problem. The FBI's nine-person
computer crime squad in Atlanta receives several complaints a week
from high-speed Internet customers who believe they have been
victimized by hackers, supervisory special agent David Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes (consumers) don't realize the importance of
firewalls,'' said Ford, who heads the squad. ``Many people do
online banking. ... They have financial data, personal letters and
graphics files that they wouldn't want to share.''
</P>
<P>
   Providers of high-speed Internet access say they are gradually
upgrading equipment to fix many of the security problems. In the
meantime, however, your system could be a theme park ride for
hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, computer programmer David Green wanted to see how
easily his cable company's Internet traffic could be intercepted.
He ran a packet-sniffing program designed to capture data being
transmitted from any computer connected to his cable modem network.
</P>
<P>
   All Internet information undergoes a transformation as it
travels around the electronic universe. It is broken into packets _
small bundles of data _ before being transferred and then
reassembled when it is received. After the packets leave a
computer, however, they can be silently captured and viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Completely invisible to the other users, Green was able to make
a copy of virtually all the Internet traffic over the system. In
one hour, the software collected 20 megabytes of information,
including Web pages, e-mails and dozens of log-ons and passwords.
</P>
<P>
   By configuring the software to search for one Internet address,
he could have viewed everything a specific person was sending and
receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could easily get into a person's e-mail, read it ... and
the person would never know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those packets could also include information about logging on to
employers' computers and other password-restricted Internet sites
that allow access to remote computers, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Green said, encrypted Web sites _ including banking
and retail sites _ are safe from having passwords stolen from
packets. However, since many people use the same passwords for
everything, those sites could be vulnerable, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green, speaking of his activities, said: ``Am I going to get in
trouble for this? I don't see why, the cable company is the one
pouring this into my network cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said his five computers were attacked recently when
someone scanned his machines for a specific security hole.
</P>
<P>
   His firewall blocked the attack, and he tracked down the owner
of the Internet address where the attack came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had broken into his system and was using it to attack
other machines,'' he said. ``Once (the hacker) got on, he
downloaded his (port) scanning software to this guy's machine and
used it to gain access to other machines,'' masking his identity.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Flatt, director of broadband technology for CCS
Technologies in Norcross, said the growth of small-business and
home computer networks has increased the vulnerability
exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he visited a home to inspect a home network and
illustrate some of the security holes in other computers connected
to Charter Communications' cable modem network.
</P>
<P>
   He plugged his laptop into the network and in 15 minutes was
able to download and install a program capable of scanning other
computers connected to Charter's network.
</P>
<P>
   Flatt said cable modem and digital subscriber line users are
particularly vulnerable to such probes because they often use an
Internet number, or IP address, that never changes. In addition,
hackers can narrow their search because the addresses are made up
of a string of four numbers, separated by periods, that are in a
relatively close range.
</P>
<P>
   After five minutes of searching potential IP addresses, the
program found 97 cable company customers' computers.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, about 20 commercial and residential computers were
running software that permitted some level of anonymous access to
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet you most of these guys have no idea what they are
running,'' CCS Technologies' Tim Sunde said.
</P>
<P>
   He focused on a few computers that reported running Windows NT
or 2000, which come with software that enables the computer to
deliver Web pages and other remote access.
</P>
<P>
   He typed in the IP address into his Web browser, and the Windows
default Web page popped on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't even know what they are running,'' Sunde concluded.
</P>
<P>
   He then used another protocol and was able to log on to several
computers anonymously, free to upload and download at will.
</P>
<P>
   Given such access, it would be possible to plant viruses or
other stealth programs on a computer that could give complete
access to the machine by a hacker.
</P>
<P>
   Flatt doesn't believe sophisticated hackers are that interested
attacking small businesses or home users _ they are too busy
breaking into large corporate systems.
</P>
<P>
   Such threats, he said, come from novice hackers, often teens,
who are vaguely familiar with computer networking and can download,
as he did, a few network administrative tools from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some invasions, however, may also come from the least
sophisticated computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Flatt said some cable modem customers are able to browse the
hard drives of other computers connected to their system by
clicking on the Neighborhood Network icon on their PC's Windows
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it's harmless because the computer's hard drives are
not accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most users don't know how to set up a network correctly,''
he said. ``These are direct connections to the Internet, with all
the disadvantages and advantages of a direct connection. And if you
don't set it up correctly, you leave yourself wide open to anyone.
They can virtually take control of you entire machine.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistake is to allow a hard drive to be shared across the
network. Sometimes, Flatt said, new computers are delivered with
that feature turned on.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded when residential users install small
networks in their home, allowing families with more than one
computer to share each other's files and printers as well as one
high-speed Internet connection, Flatt said.
</P>
<P>
   If that network is incorrectly configured, or is not
password-protected, other cable modem customers could have complete
access to the family's network.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if a person knew the IP address of the home network's
primary computer, he or she could even browse that hard drive from
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Emmendorfer, a network engineer with St. Louis-based
cable company Charter Communications, said such lapses are the
greatest security threat to all high-speed Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, conveying that message has been left to the cable
modem installer.
</P>
<P>
   In the near future, however, his company will give its customers
a guide to network security that would, in part, explain how to
avoid the most common security mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to rigorously educate our customers,''
Emmendorfer promised.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
