<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4917 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0627     06-26 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some of TV's second fiddles shouldn't go solo
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Chester on ``Gunsmoke'' . . . Ethel on ``I Love
Lucy'' . . . Radar on ``MASH'' . . . Mimi on ``Drew Carey'' . . .
Jack on ``Will &AMP; Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   We love 'em, but only in small doses, and there's nothing wrong
with that. Some folks were born to twinkle brilliantly in the
background. We can't all be top stars, although some people insist
on standing front and center when they're better off shining from
the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   After a handful of failed attempts to star in his own TV series,
Tony Danza has finally realized his destiny is to be a supporting
player. He's joining CBS's ``Family Law'' this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Danza came to national attention in 1978 as a member of the
stellar ``Taxi'' ensemble and then bounced back in '84 as the
co-lead in ``Who's the Boss.'' But after that, his sitcom pilots
bit the dust on a regular basis. It became a running joke among
critics that at least one network would have a Danza sitcom every
September. And it would be gone by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Now Michael Richards, who leapt to fame as Kramer, the
wild-haired neighbor on ``Seinfeld,'' is starring in a new fall
sitcom on NBC. Most people don't even recognize Richards by his
real name, but just about everyone knows Kramer. NBC is hoping
millions of ``Seinfeld'' fans will follow Richards to his new gig
as a bumbling detective.
</P>
<P>
   But will they? If tradition holds, probably not. Richards has
``supporting player'' written all over his clumsy, lanky frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prediction is that 'The Michael Richards Show' probably
won't survive its freshman season,'' says Mike Greco, vice
president of broadcast research for the ad-buying agency OMD USA in
New York. ``That's based on the pilot and the scheduling. It's in a
really tough time period, opposite 'Millionaire' and 'JAG.' But
besides that, there are some roles that lend themselves better to
supporting characters than lead characters. He's not playing
Kramer, but he sort of is.''
</P>
<P>
   If Richards' show flops, as more than one media analyst has
predicted, maybe the actor will return later in the better-suited
role of co-star. Danza seems happy with his decision, and good for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's the actor viewers love in bits but can't take in
bulk; sometimes it's a character that's been too closely aligned
with the actor and bleeds into the next role. It's not impossible
to turn a co-star into a star, but it's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be done with the right writing and a good supporting
cast,'' Greco says. ``Star vehicles are always harder.''
</P>
<P>
   As funny as Jack is on ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and Mimi is on ``Drew
Carey,'' entire sitcoms devoted to those or similarly outrageous
characters would be too much of a good thing. Ted Knight, the
hilariously empty-headed anchorman on ``The Mary Tyler Moore
Show,'' landed his own sitcom, ``The Ted Knight Show,'' in 1978.
Although he played the head of an escort service and not an
anchorman, viewers saw him as Ted Baxter and were tired of him. He
was canceled in a month.
</P>
<P>
   George Wendt got his own self-titled show after ``Cheers,'' but
it was a quick exit, too. Viewers who loved him as Norm, the chubby
beer swiller who delivered zingers from a Boston bar stool, had no
interest in his new incarnation as half of a radio host duo
dispensing car advice.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions to every rule, and ``Frasier'' is ongoing,
brilliant proof that some supporting players can blossom into
full-blown stars. Through most of the decade-long run of
``Cheers,'' the snobby shrink was a minuscule contributor. He'd
swagger in for maybe five minutes a month to receive consolation or
ribbing about his sorry love life, hardly the stuff of a successful
spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were really skeptical about that one,'' Greco says.
``But the success of 'Frasier' goes beyond Kelsey Grammer. The show
has a terrific supporting cast and terrific writing. It takes a lot
of pieces for a show to succeed, and the actor is just one of those
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   In his spinoff, Grammer went from playing a lonely shrink in
Boston to playing a radio call-in shrink in Seattle who has a
hilarious brother, crusty old father, wacky radio sidekick and
charming English helper. Same character; different surroundings.
Another spinoff of ``MTM'' succeeded for the same reasons. When
``Lou Grant'' arrived, the blustery TV news director had become a
veteran newspaper city editor surrounded by interesting characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is shows make stars; stars don't make shows,''
Greco says. ``What a star does is bring viewers in to sample the
program, cutting through the clutter of the fall schedule. But the
show will live and die on its own merit. People will tune in to see
what 'Michael Richards' is all about, but they won't come back if
they don't like the program. That's why Kelsey Grammer made it and
Shelley Long didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   And unless the current revamping of ``The Michael Richards
Show'' is extreme, the former Kramer will be headed for
second-banana status again soon _ not that there's anything wrong
with that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
