r l BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0627-COX     06-26 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get a drink on Red Planet?
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Recent photos of Mars reveal that water may exist near
the surface _ a sign that life could exist on the planet. That
doesn't mean life definitely exists on Earth's neighbor, but
conditions on the planet make it possible, scientists say.
Never-before-seen gullies, trenches and channels appear in 250
photos taken by a special camera on the Mars Global Surveyor.
Scientists examining the images think the trenches and channels may
have been formed by sudden surges of water.
</P>
<P>
   The new images may reignite interest in NASA's Mars exploration
program.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER OF OUR DISCONTENT
</P>
<P>
   Soaring gasoline prices have fueled calls for a government
investigation into possible price-gouging at pumps in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are high throughout the nation, but states such as
Wisconsin and Illinois have been hit particularly hard. Average
prices in those states top $2 for a gallon of regular gas. The
national average is about $1.64.
</P>
<P>
   Rising oil prices and cleaner-burning gasolines could account
for some, but not all, of the price hikes, President Clinton says.
In some cities hit hardest, a price drop already has begun. Experts
predict price reliefthroughout the nation by the end of summer.
</P>
<P>
   GORE UNDER FIRE FOR FUND-RAISER
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official wants to know if Vice President Al
Gore lied about his fund-raising role during the 1996 campaign,
U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Conrad, the head of Justice's campaign finance task
force, has asked the attorney general to appoint a special lawyer
to investigate the matter. The uproar revolves around a 1996 event
at a Buddhist temple that raised $65,000 in illegal donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he didn't know the event was a fund-raiser when he
attended. He said he thought it was a ``community outreach'' event.
</P>
<P>
   P.E. NO LONGER REQUIRED
</P>
<P>
   Georgia middle school students are no longer required by the
state to take 90 hours of physical education and health classes
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the State Board of Education has told local school
districts to decide how much P.E. and health their students should
take. The change comes as part of the governor's school reform law,
which mandates that middle school students get an extra 30 minutes
a day of academic course work beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The P.E. change will take effect this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
