r k BC-KABAT-COLUMN0627-COX     06-26 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The key to happiness and fulfillment is in your hands
 &HT;    By Vicki Kabat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Everyone knows children get bored in the
summertime. It's part of what summer is about: free time, few
scheduled activities, letting the mind rest. When you get to middle
age, we call that a vacation and are darned grateful for it.
</P>
<P>
   Boredom in children may be annoying (especially to parents), but
it usually isn't a signal to a bigger problem. In adults, however,
it can be.
</P>
<P>
   In an article titled ``Do You Have the Silent Symptom?'' in a
recent issue of Prevention magazine, writer Linday Mooney cites
research in which 21 percent of Americans say they are regularly
bored. It is described as an ``overwhelming absence of feeling . .
. that can drive us to self-destructive acts.''
</P>
<P>
   If we don't do something about it, the article states, boredom
can manifest itself in depression, pain, illness, even death.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think adults say are the 10 most boring tasks?
According to a national survey by the Boring Institute (hey, that
sounds like a fun place to work), they are opening junk mail,
watching political debates, housework, weeding the garden or lawn,
exercising, dieting, meetings, commuting, laundry and No. 1:
standing in line.
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS SOMETHING TO DO
</P>
<P>
   Well, my mother used to tell me during those long boring summers
on the farm, where your nearest friend lived seven miles away, that
boredom was a choice. I can still hear her: ``It doesn't say much
about your powers of creativity if you decide to be bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't you hate it when moms are right? Don't you hate it even
more when you find yourself parroting your mother's advice to your
own children?
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, do we choose to be bored? This isn't rocket science,
people. If you're bored, mix something up a bit in your life. Do
something different. Do something a little crazy. Go parasailing or
bungee jumping. When you're free-falling tied to nothing more than
an elastic band, tell me then that you're bored. Sign up for a
class. Redecorate your house. Write a book. Get a new pet. Take
your mind off yourself and volunteer to help others. Read a good
book. Train for a marathon. You get my point.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we choose to be bored because we're lazy. It's much easier
to sit around griping about boredom than to do something about it.
Of course, this is true with any problem we encounter in life. It's
easier to complain about it than to change it. That doesn't make us
very pleasant or effective people, though.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE INITIATIVE NEVER HURT ANYONE
</P>
<P>
   Bored with your responsibilities at work? Think about ways you
can be more productive to the company, write it up in a proposal
and take it to your boss. Don't like the way your church committee
is operating? Focus on the problem the committee is addressing,
outline the pros and cons, identify strengths of individual
committee members and overhaul the process.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend your time around the office water cooler or the
church coffee pot denigrating the process, people or problem . . .
or you can spend your time thinking creatively about solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason we don't choose to make changes is because we
feel it isn't our responsibility. ``Hey, not my problem. I don't
get paid to worry about that. Let somebody else fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   If we're invested enough in a situation to be there, we ought to
bring all our faculties to it. We're all a part of the process. And
if you've invested in something for a long time with sincere effort
and you can't effect change, leave. Life is too short to settle for
less. Go where your gifts will be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Boredom is epidemic. Happiness and fulfillment can be, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
