<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN0627-COX     06-26 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floppies fade as files find fresh fields
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ We're turning the car around, I announced
to the tune of squealing tires. I had left a needed floppy disk at
home and had to go back for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A floppy?'' my son asked. ``How 1989.''
</P>
<P>
   And there I was again, being technologically quaint and caught
at it by a teen-ager. Shoot. I felt some small relief he hadn't
said 1889. He might as well have.
</P>
<P>
   As though a perfectly serviceable floppy disk _ carefully marked
``misc. files'' like six others scattered around the house _ was an
artifact fit for a glass case.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect this is an ancient intergenerational tension. ``But
da-a-a-d, people will think we're Hittites or something with that
old bronze spear. Everybody uses the steel now. We'll be the
biggest dorks in the raiding party.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is the age of the Internet, the Web-based virtual hard
drive, the rewriteable CD and teeny little thumb-sized hard drives.
Even Zip discs _ each one can hold a Gibbon's ``Decline and Fall of
the Roman Empire,'' a ``Complete Works of Shakespeare,'' the
archives of the Confederate Navy and still have room for a pretty
good solitaire program _ are beginning to seem a little too 1999
for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who try to keep just two steps behind
technology, I knew this day would come.
</P>
<P>
   The first clue came in 1998. I scoffed when Apple Computers
unveiled their classy iMacs. Sleek and small and colorful, but no
place for a floppy-disk. What were they thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Not needed, the Apple folks explained. Smart people move their
files on the Internet and over networks and software comes on CDs.
Need a floppy drive? Like 23-skidoo, man. How Blondie and Dagwood.
How 1989.
</P>
<P>
   I chuckled at this techno-arrogance, but it was a nervous laugh.
The laugh of a man who sensed what was ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead was going to be another box in the garage. Next to the one
with $100 worth software on the older five-and-quarter-inch floppy
disks. Next to the box of vinyl phonograph records, warped into the
shape of salad dishes from heat and humidity, but they have such
neat covers.
</P>
<P>
   (The unfairness of life: When my eyes were young and supple, I
lived in a world that had record covers with huge pictures and big
print. Now that I'm old enough to squint at details, CDs come with
album notes smaller than the legal disclaimers on aspirin bottles.)
</P>
<P>
   I'm not ready for much more obsolescence at home. Where my kids
react joyously to all that is new and better and cooler, I see only
more perfectly good hardware and software packed in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   But I had to face up to it. In my attempt to bridge my home
office with the newsroom, I have changed my ways. No more floppies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, this column was, at one point in its processing,
uploaded to a Web site that advertises itself as a free storage
place, a ``virtual hard drive.'' I dumped this column somewhere out
in the Internet ether and downloaded it back at the office.
Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of Web sites that do this _ Driveway.com,
i-drive.com, Xdrive.com, MySpace.com ... . It's very 1999 of me to
think this is new and exciting, but I was thrilled at the idea of a
free locker for my virtual stuff. I haven't the foggiest idea how
they intend to make money.
</P>
<P>
   All very cool, but I will miss the four-and-a-half inch floppy.
It could fit snugly in your front pocket. In 1990 this identified
you as a digital kind of guy. (Which is not as a great a
babe-magnet as it sounds.) And you could nervously flick their
little aluminum spring-loaded doors open and closed with a
satisfying snap while wondering if the system would come up again.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, you could convert promotional disks for your own
data use. Not like today's free CDs. Coasters are the best
alternative use I've found for the CDs America Online hands out. I
don't know if they'd work for skeet shooting and they make poor
Frisbees.
</P>
<P>
   Will our eyes well up some year in the future when we find these
things in attics? Will we look fondly on the simpler days of
unconnected computing? Can't say.
</P>
<P>
   But at least I'll be able to fit them all in a shoe-box when the
time comes. That shouldn't take up much garage space. You can't ask
much more of a technology.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
