<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SALT-SENSITIVITY0627-     06-26 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALT-SENSITIVITY0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salt sensitivity more of an issue for specific groups than
individualsBy Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Federal health bureaucrats have long talked about
high blood pressure as though salting food is barely more safe than
sprinkling it with chips of lead paint.
</P>
<P>
   Their single-minded harping on sodium is troubling to people who
research high blood pressure without a political agenda. They worry
that people will figure they can eat as many hot fudge sundaes as
they want as long as the peanuts are unsalted.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is recommending a diet based on the tops of margarita
glasses, and some people should restrict their salt very carefully.
For them, blood pressure goes up and down in concert with their
salt intake. Just as blondes and redheads must be more careful
about the sun than those who can get tan watching the Travel
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   It's even true that high salt consumption leads to high blood
pressure as a general rule, which is important news for general
people but of dwindling concern to individuals. Health and medical
research are progressing quickly beyond the crutch of most
one-size-fits-all directives and recognizing that variations in
diets and medications can affect different people quite
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we know about genes and individuals, the more we
understand that not everybody is salt-sensitive,'' says Dr. Suzanne
Oparil, who directs the vascular biology and hypertension program
at the University of Alabama-Birmingham and is one of the world's
leading researchers into salt and high blood pressure. Oparil spoke
at Wright State University's med school last month at about the
same time the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute (NHBLI)
reopened its attack on salt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is complicated, and so politicized,'' she says.
Researchers haven't found a gene for salt-sensitivity, but they
have identified groups of the population whose blood pressure is
more likely to respond to salt. They are blacks, the obese and
people older than 45, and the biological explanation appears to be
that they don't excrete sodium as efficiently as others.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Oparil discloses that she receives $3,000 a year
from the Salt Institute for telling it the same thing she tells
anyone else who asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the general population, salt restriction is not a
very wise thing to push,'' she says. ``Although it does help some
people, the general population is not helped all that much. I don't
think most people are all that salt-sensitive, and it's a very
unpleasant kind of diet to pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   She is talking about a diet with 1,500 milligrams of sodium a
day, which was one of three amounts in the recent DASH II trial,
named after the Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension research
that yielded the DASH diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``By reducing their dietary sodium to 1,500 milligrams a day,
all Americans, and especially those at high risk for hypertension,
can decrease their chance of developing high blood pressure as they
age,'' says Eva Obarzenek, a Ph.D. nutritionist with the NHBLI.
</P>
<P>
   The catch, says Oparil, is ``Nobody could eat only that on their
own.'' And at the other two measured levels, she says there was
little impact in dropping from 3,300 milligrams to 2,400,
especially for those without high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't just that the NHBLI is clinging stubbornly to
old ideas. It is that focusing on salt to control blood pressure
also diverts attention from the more proven techniques of limiting
calories or increasing activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will pick one that they're going to do,'' Oparil says.
``And if they pick the salt restriction, they'll get a very minor
benefit, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, salt scares distract us from more significant
warnings. Contrary to previous beliefs, the top-number systolic
blood pressure is more important than the diastolic as people get
older. The difference between the two numbers might be even more
important. And for people with diabetes or kidney disease, the
upper limits of 140 and 90 drop at least to 135 and 85.
</P>
<P>
   High blood pressure is a dangerous disease that kills 41,634
Americans and contributes to another 202,000 deaths a year,
according to the American Heart Association. It's increasing in a
society that's ``getting fatter and more sedentary,'' as Oparil
bluntly says, largely because so many jobs involve little exertion
beyond pushing elevator buttons.
</P>
<P>
   We can't afford to forget the most basic precautions of getting
enough activity, keeping our weight down, not smoking and eating
plenty of the fruits, vegetables and low-fat dairy in the DASH
diet. ``Rather than focus on one little nutrient,'' Oparil says,
``try to eat a balanced diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
