<HEADER>
A4926 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0627     06-26 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0627 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Did somebody say rhubarb?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``Got any rhubarb?'' Gene is asking Cal as I
pick up my morning cup of decaf and take it to the empty seat
between them. ``I'll trade you lettuce for some rhubarb.'' Cal
squints, nods and smiles. Being a newcomer, Gene thinks this means
he's got himself a deal but that's not it. It means Cal hasn't
heard a word Gene's saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet we've had 50 or 60 messes already, and it keeps
coming on,'' Gene explains. ``How much can you use?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mess a what?'' Cal asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lettuce. How much do you want?'' Gene answers.
</P>
<P>
   Cal cups his ear, and then turns to me. ``What'd he say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to know how much lettuce you want?'' I holler at his
good side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any lettuce,'' Cal says. ``Already got more'n we
can eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene looks surprised and asks, ``But what about the rhubarb?''
Cal answers. ``Don't need any thanks. Got more a that than we need,
too. Besides, I don't like it except in pudding.'' Then he looks
around the table and asks in general: ``Anybody need some rhubarb
for pies?''
</P>
<P>
   Gene, looking a little bumfuzzled, says he does.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of non-communication goes on every morning. Cal
doesn't hear very well. Says it's because of all the years he spent
on a noisy tractor. Gene hears a little better, but not much. Don't
know what his excuse is. He had a radio station before he sold it
and retired about a year ago to 10 acres and a row of tomato plants
just outside of town.
</P>
<P>
   About this time Amos walks in, the screen door slapping behind
him, and wraps his fingers around the handle of the cup Robin hands
him as he passes the counter. ``So,'' he asks, ``what're we talking
about this morning?'' Somebody says rhubarb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want some?'' Amos looks around for takers. Cal asks some what?
Amos leans over to Cal's good ear and hollers, RHUBARB!
</P>
<P>
   ``Why's everybody trying to give me something?'' Cal wants to
know. ``I got rhubarb and I got lettuce, and I don't particularly
like either one. Who wants some?''
</P>
<P>
   Amos says he doesn't. A couple of other guys say they don't
either. Cal looks at me. I shake my head a no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want some rhubarb,'' Gene says loud and slow. ``My wife is
in a good mood today and says she'll bake me a pie if I can find
some.'' Cal hears that and wisecracks that it must be pretty rare
for Gene's wife to be in a good mood, considering the guy she's
married to. Gene pulls a funny face and lets it go.
</P>
<P>
   Amos asks Gene what kind of rhubarb he wants and Gene says he
didn't know it came in ``kinds.'' Amos brings him up to speed. ``I
got Martha Washington rhubarb. It's been in my yard since my
grandmother planted it when she was new-married.'' Amos is 78.
</P>
<P>
   Cal says his plants are King George and he doesn't know how old
they are except they've been there as long as he can remember. Cal
is 77.
</P>
<P>
   Gene says the kind doesn't matter as long as it makes good pie.
He wants to know when's a good time for him to come dig some up.
Amos looks shocked and tells him rhubarb is cut, not dug like
lettuce. Gene's talking again when he should be listening and
hollers WHAT? at Amos who repeats what he just said, only louder.
</P>
<P>
   Cal catches the tail end of it. ``Why the holy heck does
everybody keep talking about lettuce when I'm talking about
rhubarb?''
</P>
<P>
   The confusion is becoming funnier by the minute because each of
them is processing only a portion of what he's hearing, but
everybody keeps on talking anyway. Since it's only rhubarb and
lettuce they're discussing, and not national defense, I stay out of
it.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm thinking that at the rate they're going, rhubarb season
is likely to be over before Gene gets his pie.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
