<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     06-26 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, June 26, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENT-FANS (San Francisco) _ Jerry M. Lewis, professor of
sociology at Kent State University, studies violent behavior by
sports fans, and his material never gets stale. England and Germany
meet in a soccer match in Belgium; hooligans trash a town square.
Lakers win the NBA title; police cars go up in smoke. Lewis
predicted Monday's flareup outside the Staples Center. He has
discovered a formula for crowd combustion, and the Lakers' win in
Game 6 met three of the criteria. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-CARD (San Francisco) _ The legendary Honus Wagner
tobacco card soon will be on the auction block again, and this
time, there's speculation it may become the first baseball card to
top $1 million. EBay, Robert Edward and MastroNet have entered into
a high-stakes partnership on the card, which will be auctioned on
eBay from July 1-15, and on Robert Edward's telephone auction July
15-16. By The San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-TIGER (San Francisco) _ Every journalist who covered the
U.S. Open has heard from friends in the business, ``You must be
running out of things to say about Tiger Woods.'' Well, no. He
doesn't allow that. Fans aren't tired of watching him, as evident
by the record TV ratings of his walk in the Pebble Beach park last
Sunday, and so the media have no cause to tire of writing about
him. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Michael Bannister lost his leg
in a climbing accident last year. This summer, just six months
later, Bannister is guiding rafting trips on rivers, climbing the
slopes of Mount Shasta, and was hired this month as a wilderness
guide and outfitter. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FIESTAWARE (Undated) _ Fiestaware, the art deco pottery from the
mid-1930s, became a mainstay in the dish cupboard because of its
soft pastel or bright and bold colors. It is easy to mix and match
this solid-color dishware to create table settings to go with any
decor. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bill Gates must be a little short on
pocket change, because a new issue of the consumer version of
Windows is on its way, and you have to decide whether to pony up
the bucks for an upgrade. Since an upgrade will cost around $100 _
and since the consumer version of the more robust Windows 2000 is
just around the corner _ chances are many users will take a pass.
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ Sometimes an employer facing
discrimination complaint can persuade the Office of Federal
Contract Compliance to change the violation to a lesser one. That
usually happens if the facts don't back up what the agency said was
the original violation or if the employer comes in with additional
evidence. Either way, it takes time and resources. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-BEETLE-SHOW (Roswell, N.M.) _ Even though the New Beetle is
different from the original, the first national New Beetle car show
in Roswell, N.M., proved a point: Beetle people like the New Beetle
as much as they did the old one. And there are a lot of young
people who never were around the original Beetle, but who have
become as enamored with the new one as we baby boomers were with
the old. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The Mercedes-Benz S-class sedan, a large
luxury sedan with equally large prices ($70,000 and up) leads the
list of passenger cars that have the highest insurance losses for
theft, according to new figures from the Highway Loss Data
Institute. The institute, which is supported by the auto insurance
industry, says the S-class' losses from theft are 10 times higher
than the average for all passenger cars. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS
III.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ When Mexicans go to the polls
on Sunday, they'll be electing more than a president: They'll be
choosing the kind of future they want and passing judgment on the
past. As they do that, they could remake their country entirely.
More than
</P>
<P>
   just a simple election, July 2 could be Mexico's version of
Berlin in 1989, or Chile's plebiscite on Augusto Pinochet in 1988 _
a change of regime rather than a change of administration. By SAM
QUINONES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUGS (San Francisco) _ While world leaders and
pharmaceutical behemoths wrangle over whether and how people in
developing countries get access to the expensive cocktail of drugs
that keeps HIV in check, activists in the Bay Area are collecting
surplus medicines and shipping them off to countries where most of
the world's AIDS victims are dying. By ULYSSESS TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   SF-SCHOOLS (Washington, D.C.) _ Arlene Ackerman, who will leave
her post as the District of Columbia schools superintendent July 17
to take the helm of the San Francisco public schools Aug. 1, is
shaped and motivated by inequities. ``In everything I do and see, I
ask whether it's equitable for all children,'' Ackerman said. ``My
job is not about making adults happy. I have little patience for
adult issues that get in the way of children.'' By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
