<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S HIS NAME AGAIN? 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Hawaiian researchers say that men
who eat two or more servings of tofu a week can experience
``accelerated brain aging.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   This does not surprise me very much because I've always thought
you needed to be suffering from accelerated brain aging to be
eating tofu in the first place. The way I look at it, if I want to
eat tasteless glop, I'll go to a McDonald's. They're more
convenient than Japanese health-food stores, plus they have
Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   The research is troubling for health-food nuts but it's also
troubling for people like me who don't eat tofu and yet still feel
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   I think I began experiencing the symptoms of accelerated brain
aging around age 20 when I realized I couldn't follow the Perry
Mason TV show. The plots took lots of twists and turns, sure, but I
don't think that was the problem. When Perry told his client,
``Don't worry about me fee,'' my mind would detach itself from its
moorings and begin floating on a sea of unreality where the
innocent are always vindicated and smug, chain-smoking district
attorneys never win.
</P>
<P>
   There are many possible signs of accelerated brain aging.
Attending a Monkees reunion concert is certainly one. Paying
$500,000 for a ride on the space station Mir is another. Recently,
I've lost the ability to remember names. While I can remember the
names of my wife and son (Teri and _ oh, whatsisname the tall kid
with big feet who likes to stand in front of the open refrigerator
until his nose hairs turn white _ Michael!), anybody I see fewer
than 10 times a day draws a blank. It is much easier to get around
this with men, whom I can simply refer to as ``big guy,'' ``hoss''
or the always-appropriate ``bubba.'' With women, it's more
difficult. Calling them ``sweetheart'' or ``hon'' seems
inappropriate at best and a sexual harassment suit at worst. I
usually opt for the more formal ``ma'am'' for females over the age
of 12 and ``young lady'' for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   How has this happened? Galloping senility is the easy answer,
but it's not a very comforting diagnosis for someone who is still
on the spry side of 50. It is tempting to blame it on the
tofu-eaters, who perhaps have the power to project brain-aging rays
into the heads of anyone standing in their vicinity. Still, if
tofu, which has all the snack appeal of unflavored wallpaper paste,
can cause that much damage, what about other, tastier foods like
double-bacon cheeseburgers, stuffed-crust pizza and fried chicken?
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Chicken Council, the average American
will eat a record 81 pounds of chicken this year, far outpacing
consumption of beef or pork.
</P>
<P>
   I eat at least that much chicken, most of it cooked on my
propane grill that was last cleaned around the time Al Gore
invented the Internet. The black, greasy smoke that pours out when
I fire it up can turn daylight into night and cause birds to drop
from the sky. The barbecued chicken that emerges from this smudge
pot is, like most highly carcinogenic foods, delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Can I blame my problem with names and my inability to follow
Perry Mason reruns on 81 pounds of scorched chicken wings? Or are
the names and the reruns the cause of my problems, not the
symptoms?
</P>
<P>
   A thorny question, to be sure. Better throw a few drumsticks on
the grill and think about it.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
