<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; JEM (AND SAM) &LR;  By Ferdinand Mount. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $13.95. This
novel of Restoration London is about a drinking buddy of Samuel
Pepys (and possibly the author's ancestor) who struggles mightily
to overcome his envy of Pepys' career, connections and wife. The
result is ``a brilliant pastiche of 17th-century prose'' in which
``the historical detail feels rich and accurate,'' Michael Upchurch
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMBRACING DEFEAT: Japan in the Wake of World War II &LR;  By John W.
Dower. Norton/New Press, $15.95. A historian assesses the impact of
the Allied occupation of Japan between 1945 and 1952 on modern
Japanese history. His nuanced account, which won a Pulitzer Prize
and a National Book Award, dissects the pretensions and practices
of the operation, as well as the ambiguities, bad policy-making and
bureaucratic bungling of the period. He finds much to praise and to
deplore in the occupation's legacy. Last year in The New York Times
Book Review, J.A.A. Stockwin called this ``a magisterial and
beautifully written book'' that includes ``many amazing documentary
photographs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WOMAN WHO CUT OFF HER LEG AT THE MAIDSTONE CLUB: And Other
Stories &LR;  By Julia Slavin. John Macrae/Picador USA, $12. These tales
of suburbia and the fears and self-destructive impulses underlying
family commitments are infused with the grotesque: One woman grows
teeth all over her body, while another swallows the yard worker she
lusts after. ``Slavin's uncluttered, room-temperature prose renders
the monstrous familiar, even beautiful,'' Charles Taylor wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HUNGRY OCEAN: A Swordboat Captain's Journey &LR;  By Linda
Greenlaw. Hyperion, $14. A female fisherman (not a fisherwoman, she
insists) describes her grueling seafaring life and her many voyages
off the Atlantic coast. ``It is a story of triumph, of a woman not
only making it but succeeding at the highest level in one of the
most male-dominated and most dangerous professions,'' Douglas
Whynott wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONE VOYAGER: The Extraordinary Adventures of Howard Blackburn,
Hero Fisherman of Gloucester &LR; , by Joseph E. Garland
(Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $13), tells of a sailor who survived
for five days alone in an open dory during a winter storm off
Newfoundland in 1883 by allowing his hands to freeze to the oars as
he pulled for land. This account of his ordeal (he lost all his
fingers) and his subsequent exploits is told with ``scrupulous
detail and much narrative skill,'' Henry Beetle Hough wrote in
1963.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNDISCOVERED CHEKHOV: Forty-Three New Stories &LR;  By Anton
Chekhov. Translated by Peter Constantine. Seven Stories, $16.95. By
the time he was 26, Chekhov had published more than 400 stories and
vignettes in popular Russian magazines. This collection of early
tales, which has been reissued with five additional stories, is a
``delightful compilation,'' Donald Fanger wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDNIGHT CHAMPAGNE &LR;  By A. Manette Ansay. Harper Perennial, $13.
This novel explores the thwarted romantic lives of guests at the
Wisconsin wedding of a young couple who have known each other only
briefly. The author ``weaves in and out of the sundry dramas with
grace, warmth and a good deal of humor,'' Laura Jamison wrote in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DREAMS OUR STUFF IS MADE OF: How Science Fiction Conquered
the World &LR;  By Thomas M. Disch. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $13. A
well-regarded science-fiction novelist argues for the genre's
literary merits while blaming it for encouraging delusory popular
fantasies and wacko religious cults. ``Disch is an eloquent
storyteller and polemicist'' and his book ``is consistently
rewarding,'' Alexander Star wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MORAL LIFE OF CHILDREN &LR;  By Robert Coles. Atlantic Monthly,
$13.50. Traveling to the world's trouble spots, a child
psychiatrist interviews a wide variety of children to examine the
way they develop their moral awareness.
</P>
<P>
   In a companion volume,  &UR; THE POLITICAL LIFE OF CHILDREN &LR; 
($13.50), also reissued by Atlantic Monthly, he studies the way
youngsters think about politics. ``There is no one who is more
interested in what children say, sing, don't say or don't sing _
and why _ than Robert Coles,'' Neil Postman wrote in 1986. ``He is
to the stories that children have to tell what Homer was to the
tale of the Trojan War.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHITE WIDOW &LR;  By Jim Lehrer. PublicAffairs, $12. Set in the
1950s, this novel revolves around a happily married bus driver in
small-town Texas whose life unravels when he becomes obsessed with
a mysterious woman passenger. The result is ``an oddly affecting
morality tale,'' The New York Times Book Review said in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUXTON SPICE &LR;  By Oonya Kempadoo. Plume, $11.95. This tale of
village life in Guyana, narrated in a rich creole by a girl, is set
in the 1970s during a period of racial turmoil. ```Buxton Spice' is
a superb, and superbly written, novel of childhood and childhood's
end,'' Patrick Markee wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
