<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, July 2)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending June 17 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. HANNIBAL, by Thomas Harris. (Dell, $7.99.) Seven
</P>
<P>
   years after his escape, the fiendish psychiatrist
</P>
<P>
   Hannibal Lecter is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   2. WHILE I WAS GONE, by Sue Miller. (Ballantine, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A small-town veterinarian, the wife of a minister, begins
</P>
<P>
   a flirtation with an old friend from her bohemian past.
</P>
<P>
   3. IRISH HEARTS, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Two previously published novels, now in one volume, about
</P>
<P>
   Irishwomen's lives in America.
</P>
<P>
   4. TOM CLANCY'S OP-CENTER: Divide and Conquer, created
</P>
<P>
   by Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik; written by Jeff
</P>
<P>
   Rovin. (Berkley, $7.99.) Traitors try to oust the
</P>
<P>
   president.
</P>
<P>
   5. IRISH REBEL, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette, $4.50.)
</P>
<P>
   The latest novel in a series about Irish families in
</P>
<P>
   America.
</P>
<P>
   6. ECLIPSE BAY, by Jayne Ann Krentz. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A man and a woman whose Oregon families are engaged
</P>
<P>
   in a longtime feud, fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   7. RIVER'S END, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.) The
</P>
<P>
   daughter of a glamorous Hollywood couple must cope with
</P>
<P>
   her family's horrifying past.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE BLUEST EYE, by Toni Morrison. (Plume, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of an 11-year-old black girl _ pregnant by
</P>
<P>
   her father _ who prays for blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   9. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British boy, neglected
</P>
<P>
   by his relatives, finds his fortune attending a school
</P>
<P>
   for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   10. PEARL COVE, by Elizabeth Lowell. (Avon, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Seeking help in solving the mystery of her husband's
</P>
<P>
   death, a woman finds romance.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and a
</P>
<P>
   missionary are brought together by a startling secret.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) TOMORROW'S PROMISE, by Sandra Brown. (Mira, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman learns that her husband, long missing in action,
</P>
<P>
   may be alive.
</P>
<P>
   13. TRANSFER OF POWER, by Vince Flynn. (Pocket, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A terrorist group descends on the White House and
</P>
<P>
   captures nearly 100 hostages.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is
</P>
<P>
   put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   15. ACTS OF MALICE, by Perri O'Shaughnessy. (Island, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Nina Reilly defends a man accused of murdering his brother
</P>
<P>
   on the ski slopes of Lake Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.) The
</P>
<P>
   story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single
</P>
<P>
   crew.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. EVERY MAN A TIGER, by Tom Clancy with Chuck Horner.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $16.95.) The novelist and a retired Air Force
</P>
<P>
   general examine the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   4.(x) THE HUNGRY OCEAN, by Linda Greenlaw. (Hyperion, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   A sea captain's account of her 30-day swordfishing
</P>
<P>
   voyage off the northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   5. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   7. I'M A STRANGER HERE MYSELF, by Bill Bryson.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $14.) The author describes what it's like
</P>
<P>
   to return to the United States after living abroad
</P>
<P>
   for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE MAJORS, by John Feinstein. (Back Bay/Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $14.95.) A sportswriter reports on the 1998
</P>
<P>
   Masters, U.S. Open, British Open and PGA golf
</P>
<P>
   tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   9. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man who
</P>
<P>
   survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE FIRST WORLD WAR, by John Keegan. (Vintage, $16.)
</P>
<P>
   A historian recounts the 1914-18 conflict from the
</P>
<P>
   viewpoint of the strategists and the men in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $10.95.) The author of ``A Child Called `It''' recalls
</P>
<P>
   his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor, $15.) A journalist explains the instant electronic
</P>
<P>
   global economy.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $15.) A presentation of superstring theory, which
</P>
<P>
   is an attempt to mediate between quantum mechanics and
</P>
<P>
   general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   An American remembers a spring and summer spent in the
</P>
<P>
   romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL III, compiled by
</P>
<P>
   Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   3. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways to
</P>
<P>
   lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. TAKE TIME FOR YOUR LIFE, by Cheryl Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A seven-step program for enhancing
</P>
<P>
   one's social, financial and spiritual well-being.
</P>
