<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: HARDCOVER BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, July 2) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for hardcover
books. See BESTSELLERS-HARD-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales for the week ending June 17, at almost
4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 50,000 other retailers
(gift shops, department stores, newsstands, supermarkets),
statistically weighted to represent all such outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) indicates that a book's sales are barely distinguishable
from those of the book above. A (b) indicates that some bookstores
report receiving bulk orders for a book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE INDWELLING, by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Tyndale, $22.99.) The seventh volume in a series about
</P>
<P>
   true believers who confront the Antichrist after the
</P>
<P>
   rapture of the saved. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. CRADLE AND ALL by James Patterson. (Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $25.95.) A former nun turned private eye works on a
</P>
<P>
   case involving two virgins who become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   3. HARRY POTTER AND THE CHAMBER OF SECRETS, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $17.95.) A British boy
</P>
<P>
   finds trouble when he returns to a witchcraft school.
</P>
<P>
   4. HARRY POTTER AND THE PRISONER OF AZKABAN, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $19.95.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy's life at a school for witchcraft is menaced when
</P>
<P>
   an infamous murderer escapes from prison.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE BRETHREN, by John Grisham. (Doubleday, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Three former judges, doing time at a federal prison in
</P>
<P>
   Florida, concoct a lucrative mail scam that goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   6. BEFORE I SAY GOOD-BYE, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Simon
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Schuster, $26.) A woman with ESP searches for the
</P>
<P>
   truth behind the death of her husband, who was killed
</P>
<P>
   when his boat exploded in New York harbor.
</P>
<P>
   7. EASY PREY, by John Sandford. (Putnam, $25.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The homicide detective Lucas Davenport investigates
</P>
<P>
   the strangulation of a famous model.
</P>
<P>
   8. OH, THE PLACES YOU'LL GO! by Dr. Seuss. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $17.) Finding your way through life.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE VINEYARD, by Barbara Delinsky. (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) When the owner of a vineyard decides to write a
</P>
<P>
   memoir, intended for children, she enlists the help of
</P>
<P>
   a woman who is unprepared for what is to follow.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE SEARCH, by Iris Johansen. (Bantam, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman and her golden retriever, part of a K-9
</P>
<P>
   rescue team, are forced to participate in a deadly
</P>
<P>
   mission.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE BLUEST EYE, by Toni Morrison. (Knopf, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of an 11-year-old black girl _ pregnant by
</P>
<P>
   her father _ who prays for her eyes to turn blue.
</P>
<P>
   12. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE EMPTY CHAIR, by Jeffery Deaver. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $25.) Forensic specialists pursue a
</P>
<P>
   disturbed teen-age boy who abducted two young women.
</P>
<P>
   14. OFF THE MANGROVE COAST, by Louis L'Amour. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $16.95.) Nine short stories ranging from the American
</P>
<P>
   West to Paris to the jungles of Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   15. ON SECRET SERVICE, by John Jakes. (Dutton, $25.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A young man joins the Union Army's espionage service
</P>
<P>
   and, on the night of April 14, 1865, finds himself on
</P>
<P>
   duty at Ford's Theater.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. FLAGS OF OUR FATHERS, by James Bradley with Ron Powers.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $24.95.) The story of the marines who raised
</P>
<P>
   the flag at Iwo Jima, by the son of one of the men.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE GREATEST GENERATION SPEAKS, by Tom Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $19.95.) What the people who fought in
</P>
<P>
   World War II confided in letters to the author.
</P>
<P>
   4. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom. (Doubleday,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of his weekly visits
</P>
<P>
   to his old college mentor, who was near death.
</P>
<P>
   5. PAYNE STEWART, by Tracey Stewart with Ken Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadman &AMP; Holman, $24.99) A biography of the golfer
</P>
<P>
   who died in a plane crash in 1999, by his widow. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. IN THE HEART OF THE SEA, by Nathaniel Philbrick.
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95.) The story of the whale ship Essex,
</P>
<P>
   whose disastrous fate in the early 19th century
</P>
<P>
   would later serve as inspiration for Herman Melville.
</P>
<P>
   7. IN A SUNBURNED COUNTRY, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) The author of ``A Walk in the Woods'' reports
</P>
<P>
   on his travels through Australia.
</P>
<P>
   8. ME TALK PRETTY ONE DAY, by David Sedaris. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $22.95.) A collection of autobiographical
</P>
<P>
   comic essays by the author of ``Naked.''
</P>
<P>
   9. DUTY, by Bob Greene. (Morrow, $25.) The columnist
</P>
<P>
   remembers his father, a soldier in World War II, and
</P>
<P>
   tells the story of Paul Tibbets, who piloted the
</P>
<P>
   plane that dropped the atomic bomb on Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   10. FROM DAWN TO DECADENCE, by Jacques Barzun.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $36.) A survey of 500 years of
</P>
<P>
   Western cultural life, from 1500 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   11. IT'S NOT ABOUT THE BIKE, by Lance Armstrong with
</P>
<P>
   Sally Jenkins. (Putnam, $24.95.) A memoir by the Tour
</P>
<P>
   de France champion and cancer survivor.
</P>
<P>
   12. DON'T MAKE ME STOP THIS CAR! by Al Roker. (Scribner,
</P>
<P>
   $24.) The television weatherman looks at the joys and
</P>
<P>
   perils of fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   13. HELL'S ANGEL, by Ralph ``Sonny'' Barger with Keith
</P>
<P>
   and Kent Zimmerman. (Morrow, $24.) The story of a notorious
</P>
<P>
   motorcycle gang, told by one of its members.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) KITCHEN CONFIDENTIAL, by Anthony Bourdain.
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomsbury, $24.95.) A memoir-expose by the executive
</P>
<P>
   chef at Brasserie Les Halles in New York.
</P>
<P>
   15. FAIR BALL, by Bob Costas. (Broadway, $21.95.) The
</P>
<P>
   sportscaster's critique of major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) PAPAL SIN, by Garry Wills. (Doubleday, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A chronicle of what the author sees as the evasions
</P>
<P>
   and distortions of the Vatican over the past two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. WHO MOVED MY CHEESE? by Spencer Johnson. (Putnam,
</P>
<P>
