<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-FAIRCHILD-UMA-THURMAN     06-26 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-UMA-THURMAN-AT-LANCOME-BUSINESS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANCOME INKS UMA THURMAN 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``f'' business news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PETE BORN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; From WWD &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MILAN _ Lancome has found its American beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past couple years, the French beauty brand has
assembled a glittering cast of megawatt spokesmodels, all of them
European. Two years ago, executives in Paris and New York began
casting about for a face that would strike a deep chord of
recognition within the U.S. market. The new beauty: Uma Thurman.
</P>
<P>
   Her entrance _ made at a gala reception on the edge of Paris _
was the climax of a special presentation of Lancome's new women's
fragrance, called Miracle. The scent, a major initiative of Lancome
and its parent L'Oreal, will be launched in Europe in the fall. And
Thurman, who has signed a two-year renewable contract, will be the
face of the global advertising.
</P>
<P>
   She is joining a glamorous group of Lancome faces: Juliette
Binoche, Marie Gillain, Cristiana Reali and Ines Sastre. As a
group, they collectively replaced Lancome's longtime face, Isabella
Rossellini.
</P>
<P>
   As for Thurman, known for her performances in ``Pulp Fiction''
and ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' starring in a fragrance commercial is
certainly a change of pace. And she enjoyed filming the new Miracle
ad in Provence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a total departure,'' she noted in a telephone
interview from Paris. And even though Thurman says she had never
thought about working in the cosmetics industry before the job was
offered, it doesn't seem alien to her. She had always been drawn to
the ``aesthetic of the (Lancome) advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Isabella and Juliette were portrayed, the way they
represented women in the way I as a woman would like to be
represented _ it was something that captured me as I would be
flipping through the pages of a magazine,'' Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   She sees her new role in the business world as an ``experiment''
at a time when there are other major changes in her life like
becoming a mother. But the actual work is not so different from
doing photo sessions for Vanity Fair or ``endless shoots'' to
promote her films.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's familiar terrain,'' she noted, ``but what is not so
familiar is how to open myself to being used in advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Thurman acknowledged an advantage to the exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, I feel empowered in making creative choices as an
actor,'' she said, indicating that having the Lancome work may give
her a little more confidence to become choosier in picking movie
roles.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Thurman says she feels ``flattered'' to be asked
to do modeling at age 30. ``Most people are being kicked out of
modeling at that age,'' she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman described the work as a mixture of modeling and acting
that allows her to be herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about me has to be changed. I don't have to become
something else. They don't have to clean me up or fiddle with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she's able to fold it into her artistic life. The
shoot for the Miracle commercial dovetailed with a scheduled
appearance in nearby Cannes for the screening of her two new movies
_ ``Vatel,'' a period drama with Gerard Depardieu and Tim Roth, and
a Merchant Ivory production of Henry James novel ``The Golden
Bowl,'' with Nick Nolte, Anjelica Huston and Jeremy Northam. Both
will be released in the fall. Then she headed north to Paris for
the Miracle presentation.
</P>
<P>
   She views it all in purely professional terms. Thurman says she
dislikes the term spokesmodel because it implies an expertise in a
particular subject that she doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of L'Oreal executives, she may be selling
herself a bit short. Luc Nadeau, senior vice president and general
manager of Lancome USA in New York, can barely restrain himself in
ticking off the pluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, she is international, uniquely beautiful and
women can relate to her as a wife, a mother and an actor,'' Nadeau
said. ``As an actress, she has shown great versatility,'' he added,
referring to Thurman's ability to float from directional art-house
films to local studio fare and back again.
</P>
<P>
   And her first project, Miracle, is of pivotal importance to
Lancome and L'Oreal. Like the decade-old Tresor, it's a broad-based
major fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not break out sales projections or reveal
promotional budgets. However, industry sources estimate that
Miracle could generate a wholesale volume in its first full year of
approximately $100 million worldwide. That would place it in the
top five women's prestige fragrances.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. target is an estimated $30 million to $40 million in
wholesale volume for the first year following its introduction in
March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the industry figure that Lancome will invest $10
million to $15 million in media to back the launch in Europe, which
is set for the end of September. The rest of the world will follow
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Details have not been set for the U.S. introduction, but sources
estimate the advertising budget will be similar to the European
one.
</P>
<P>
   Counting extra promotional costs, including point-of-sale
animation and sell-through specialists, the American budget could
climb as high as $15 million to $20 million, especially if sales
climb toward $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the possible significance of this launch goes well beyond
volume estimates and speculation about the size of the war chest.
Lancome has been locked in a worldwide duel with the Este Lauder
brand for at least two decades.
</P>
<P>
   L'Oreal executives say that Lancome has emerged from the fray
with the No. 1 global ranking in color cosmetics and skin care. But
Lauder moves ahead when the company's immense fragrance business is
added to the equation.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of Lauder's fragrance superiority, Lancome has
counterattacked with Tresor, which still ranks third in the world
and sixth in the United States, according to Lancome executives.
Poeme, which was launched in 1995, placed in the top 20 worldwide,
while O Oui, a 1998 entry, was a niche move aimed at attracting
new, younger customers.
</P>
<P>
   Miracle, therefore, could join Tresor in a second step toward
building a powerful fragrance stable. Marc Menesguen, director
general of Lancome International, stated, ``We definitely are No 1
(in color and treatment). We still have a way to go with
fragrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Menesguen noted that he expects good growth from fragrance in
the coming year. Then he added that the company intends ``to speed
the rhythm of fragrance launches.''
</P>
<P>
   The target audience for Miracle is similar to that of Tresor,
women aged 25 to 45, with a core of 25- to 35-year-olds. The price
points are slightly higher than Tresor's.
</P>
<P>
   But the positionings are strikingly different. Tresor, a floral
oriental, is a fragrance of intimacy with a positioning predicated
on private moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miracle is for a woman who is more open to the world, more
open and willing to make her life what it can be,'' Menesguen said.
``She knows she can create a Miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial that was shot outdoors in a village in Provence
shows Thurman gazing at a sunrise, ``signifying the miracle of
life, the miracle of love,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial was directed by Darius Khonji, and the
photographer for the print ad is Michel Comte.
</P>
<P>
   Lancome executives absolutely refused to discuss any terms of
their contract with Thurman. But industry executives, who have
experience making deals with superstars, speculate that Thurman was
paid $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   She will appear in Miracle advertising worldwide, and then
Lancome will use her image on ``two or three'' new cosmetics
products set to launch next year.
</P>
<P>
   All the launches will be global, and Menesguen stressed that
Lancome picks its models for their international appeal. He noted
that the company had been looking for the new spokesmodel for 18
months when Thurman was decided upon.
</P>
<P>
   Menesguen said the company was looking for someone with American
appeal, since about one-third of Lancome's global volume is done in
the United States. He was careful to say that the search was not
necessarily for an American, although the executive admitted that
there are few people with a high U.S. profile who aren't American.
</P>
<P>
   Lancome executives pointed out that Thurman, who has a Swedish
mother, is well known in Europe thanks to her movies.
</P>
<P>
   Menesguen seemed to take delight in pointing out that not only
did Lancome fall in love with Thurman, but she wanted to work with
them. ``She chose us,'' Menesguen proudly stated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pete Born is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
