<P>
   &UR; MEXICO: IT'S TIME FOR AN HONEST HANDOVER OF POWER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO-VOTES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change comes slowly to Mexico, the country with the world's
longest-serving ruling political party. Ever since the emergence in
the 1920s of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), power in
Mexico has changed hands through backroom deals in which the
incumbent president has chosen his successor _ whose subsequent
electoral victory was a formality, achieved when necessary by
fraud. No longer. That makes Mexico's presidential election on July
2 a historic _ and hopeful _ event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for JULY 2 election) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEWARE OF DANGEROUSLY DECEPTIVE DEMOCRACIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHONEY-DEMOCRACY-ECONOMIST-200&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the past decade has been a splendid time for
democrats. All over the world, dictatorships, whether communist or
military, have been in retreat; demand for ballot boxes, election
monitors and people who know how to run parliaments has been as hot
as for Pokemon cards. Indeed, for the first time in history, the
proportion of the world's population that lives in countries that
can claim to be broadly democratic has climbed past 50 percent.
Closer scrutiny, however, finds several imposters in the crowd:
countries still ``in transition'' towards full democracy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 150-word optional trim; 1,025 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE TIME BEING, PUTIN SHOULD REMAIN ON PROBATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POKERFACE-PUTIN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Vladimir Putin won Russia's presidency, some
ugly things have been happening in his benighted country. The new
man, a former KGB officer, has been cracking his whip. He has
sounded belligerent towards several of Russia's former vassal
states on its rim, and shows little sign of softening towards
Chechnya, the rebel republic devastated at his command. Things may
yet change but, for the time being at least, Putin remains on
probation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A DOSE OF HEALTHY LESSONS FROM HEALTH-CARE STUDY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPARING-HEALTHCARE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health-care spending is everywhere on the increase. In 1948, it
took 3 percent of gross world product; now, says a new report from
the World Health Organization, the figure is 7.9 percent and
rising. Governments and health-care providers have much to learn
from studying the structure and performance of other countries'
health systems. But what may matter more for public policy than the
rankings in the WHO report are four general conclusions about
health care. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S `WILL-YOU-BE-MY-VEEP?...IS-THAT-YOUR-FINAL-ANSWER?' TIME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VEEPSTAKES-GOREBUSH-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ America's quadrennial search for a designated
mourner at the funerals of foreign dignitaries _ otherwise known as
the vice president _ is in full swing. Short-lists are being drawn
up. Short-lists are being narrowed down... Is the veepstakes the
creation of bored pundits with too much time on their hands? Not
entirely. This time, there is a slim chance the choice of running
mate could actually make a difference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WHOM THE ROADS TOLL: SHOULD CALIFORNIANS PAY AS THEY GO? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALIF-TOLL-ROADS?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On June 22, the California Environmental
Dialogue, a new 32-member group including _ improbably _ General
Motors, Chevron, BP Amoco, the Sierra Club and Environmental
Defense, published a paper on the state's transport policy. In it,
they endorsed the principle that the ``user should pay'' for road
use and that ``tolls and congestion pricing should be utilized
whenever possible'' _ a first for the big oil and car firms.
Drivers' groups, however, are opposed to the idea. Kevin Murray, a
state senator from freeway-laced Los Angeles, calls road-pricing a
middle-class fantasy dreamed up by ``some dweeb in a dark room
doing quantitative analysis.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLOOD 'N' BALLOTS: ZIMBABWE'S UNFAIR ELECTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUGABE-BOGUS-BALLOT-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARARE_ In a free and fair election, the ruling party of
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe would stand no chance. His
government is violent, corrupt, incompetent and detested. But his
ZANU enjoys the advantages of incumbency. Yet despite that _ and a
vicious campaign of intimidation and killings _ the ruling party
could still lose its majority in this weekend's election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for this weekend's election, Zimbabwe) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word optional trim; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE THIN BLUE LINE: LEBANON, U.N. CLASH OVER ITS BORDER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORDER-BLUES-LEBANON-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ When is a border less than a border? When it is blue.
So, at least, runs the contention of the United Nations officials
trying to confirm the Israeli army's retreat from south Lebanon.
They have invented a new, blue ``withdrawal line'' where it thinks
the Lebanese border should run. But the Lebanese government, which
already has to cope with green, red, black and purple lines left
behind by the country's civil war, is reluctant to add another
shade to the spectrum. It argues that the new boundary leaves
several chunks of Lebanese territory inside Israel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `PHILOSOPHY COUNSELLING' IS LATEST MANAGEMENT FAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHILOSOPHY-FAD-BIZ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Company executives in search of wisdom are turning
from psychotherapy and religion to the cleverest thinkers of all:
ancient philosophers. For corporations, philosophy has become the
latest management fad. Tom Morris, author of ``If Aristotle Ran
General Motors: The New Soul of Business,'' earns $30,000 an hour
for teaching Socrates and Hegel to the likes of IBM, Campbell Soup,
General Electric and Ford. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATURAL GAS: UNNATURAL PRICES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATURAL-GAS-PAINS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``The big American gas crunch is coming,'' says Mark
Papa, the boss of EOG, an American energy company. Angry U.S.
drivers, paying record prices for gasoline, may think the crunch
has come already, but the gas market suffering this particular
price shock is largely unaffected by gyrations in oil price.
Although few outside the industry have noticed, prices for natural
gas in the U.S. have shot up in the past year _ a rise which has
surprised even old industry hands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WESTERN CARMAKERS DISCOVER THAILAND &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THAILAND-AUTOMAKERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMATA CITY AND SAMRONG _ They are cheap, educated, friendly and
fastidious, and Ralph-Rainer Ohlsen loves them. He smiles benignly
at the women and men assembling BMWs in the light-flooded,
squeaky-clean factory in Thailand's Rayong province that he opened
last month. ``Those Thais even take their shoes off when they get
in the cars,'' he enthuses. ``It's great.'' Following Ford last
year and GM in April, BMW is the latest western carmaker to set up
shop in Thailand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
