<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary and Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 400-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; QUICK LEARNER OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Lenora Fulani resigned from Pat Buchanan's campaign. Fulani, ``a
black, Marxist advocate of gay rights,'' objected to Buchanan's
``efforts to transform the (Reform) Party into a party of, and for,
only social conservatives.'' (Washington Post, June 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TWILIGHT ZONE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Coelho, Al Gore's campaign chairman, has a bizarre
connection with June 15. He was born on June 15, 1942; on June 15,
1974, he was diagnosed with epilepsy; on June 15, 1989, he resigned
from Congress; and on June 15, 2000 he resigned from the Gore
campaign for health reasons. A coincidence? (Hotline, June 16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEEK OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an expert on computers'' (Al Gore, ``inventor of the
Internet,'' on why he's lost lots of e-mails. Time, June 26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISSPENT YOUTH OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The London Sunday Times reported that in 1972, during his time
as a pilot in the National Guard, George W. Bush was grounded for
failure to take a medical exam that would have included a drug
test. The New York Times also reported that Bush was arrested for
disorderly conduct while at Yale _ he stole a Christmas wreath. The
charges were later dropped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEANCE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out a ouija board. I mean it, I'm totally clueless.'' (An
unnamed Bush advisor failing to speculate on the Bush vice
presidential front-runner. New York Times, June 19) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OH YEAH?: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``People view me as a sensitive person on this subject.'' (Bush
on the death penalty. A Newsweek poll found that 59 percent of
Americans thought political considerations motivated his recent
granting of a 30-day stay of execution.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FANTASY VICE PRESIDENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Both political parties are looking for the same candidate.
Both of them would like a Hispanic woman from a Great Lakes state,
who has raised a large family and has extensive foreign-policy
experience.'' (Michael Barone, CNBC, June 19) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHILANTHROPIST OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, who is expected to be nominated as the Green
Party's presidential candidate this weekend, has filed financial
statements with the Federal Election Commission which reveal his
net worth to be $3.8 million, and also that he donates more than 80
percent of his after-tax income to worthy causes serving the
interests of the consumer or the environment. (Washington Post,
June 18) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
