<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     06-26 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT MAJORITY CANNOT COERCE MINORITY TO PRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 19, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that public school
districts cannot authorize students to lead prayers at school
football games (Santa Fe Independent School District vs. Doe). It
is a sweeping decision that follows the core meaning of the
Establishment Clause _ a government entity cannot support or
endorse a religion and coerce those who do not believe in that
religion to participate in its worship.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling follows the rationale of the high court's 1992
decision (Lee vs. Weisman) which found graduation prayers a
violation of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   A peek at the underbelly of this case shows what can happen when
a school district puts its seal of approval on a particular
religion.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the pseudonym ``Doe'' in the title of the case was
used to protect the Catholic and Mormon students who brought this
case to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe Independent School District is a political
subdivision of Texas, governed by an elected, seven-person Board of
Trustees. The trustees apparently take the word ``Independent'' in
the name of their district too seriously. They openly allowed
prayer at graduation, despite the Supreme Court's 1992 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The federal district court that first heard this case noted that
one of the student plaintiffs, Jane Doe II was ridiculed by her
seventh-grade history teacher when he found out she is a Mormon.
The teacher, according to court documents, ``launched into a
diatribe about the non-Christian, cult-like nature of Mormonism and
its general evils.'' Jane Doe II's classmates picked up the
religious prejudice of the teacher and called her faith ``evil''
and ``kind of like the KKK.''
</P>
<P>
   The school district even tried to find out the names of the
students who had filed the lawsuit _ presumably to harass them into
dropping the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The district court had to warn the school administration,
teachers and other school employees to cease trying ``to ferret out
the identities of the plaintiffs'' or ``face the harshest possible
contempt sanctions from this court, and may additionally face
criminal liability.''
</P>
<P>
   The court explained it ``wants these proceedings addressed on
their merits, and not on the basis of intimidation or harassment of
the participants on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a warning is extremely rare and speaks volumes about
religious arrogance and intolerance in circumstances where a
religious majority thinks it has a right to harass, belittle and
treat religious minorities as if they do not matter. This is
precisely the underlying reason for the Establishment Clause _ to
keep religious liberty free of the tyranny of the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the liberties guaranteed by the Bill of Rights
cannot be overturned by the vote of a majority.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Santa Fe school district enacted a policy entitled
``Prayer at Football Games'' that allowed high school students to
vote to choose whether to ``deliver a prayer at varsity football
games.'' And then vote to determine who would deliver those
prayers. Apparently, the school district thought if students
conducted the prayers, the policy and district would be insulated
from a constitutional challenge.
</P>
<P>
   A later policy omits the word ``prayer'' and substitutes
``messages'' and ``invocations'' _ another transparent attempt to
get around the meaning of the Establishment Clause.
</P>
<P>
   The school district argued there was no government coercion of
students to participate in religious observances because the
invocations at football games was a product of student elections.
And further, there was no coercion because students didn't have to
attend their school football games.
</P>
<P>
   The district also argued the invocations were merely to
solemnize the football games. Whatever happened to singing the
``Star Spangled Banner''? one might legitimately ask.
</P>
<P>
   And most ridiculously, the district argued that these
``messages'' are private student speech, not public speech. Prayer
intoned over a loud speaker system at a school function cannot be,
by any stretch of the imagination, classified as private speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution, as interpreted by the high court, has never
prohibited public school students from voluntarily engaging in
private prayer during school hours. But prayer boomed out at a
football game is anything but private.
</P>
<P>
   None of the federal courts _ from district court to appellate
court to the Supreme Court _ were fooled by such obvious ploys.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens wrote the opinion for the 6-3
majority. Chief Justice William Rehnquist wrote a dissent which was
joined by Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens noted that the football game policy was voted on by the
district trustees. In other words, the district gave the students
permission to deliver prayers at games. He also noted the prayers
were delivered at a school function on school property using school
sound equipment _ all under school control. People who attended
these varsity football games would understandably think the prayers
given at the games were sponsored or endorsed by the school
district.
</P>
<P>
   High school football games in many small towns in Texas are
events which bring out the entire community. It isn't fair to
students in the religious minority to be subjected to the religious
majority's prayers in order to attend their own school's football
games and see their friends play.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens wrote: ``School sponsorship of a religious message is
impermissible because it sends the ancillary message to members of
the audience who are nonadherents `that they are outsiders, not
full members of the political community, and an accompanying
message to adherents that they are insiders, favored members of the
political community.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a sweeping conclusion, the decision states: ``Through its
election scheme, the district has established a governmental
electoral mechanism that turns the school into a forum for
religious debate. It further empowers the student body majority
with the authority to subject students of minority views to
constitutionally improper messages. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a system encourages divisiveness along religious lines
and threatens the imposition of coercion upon those students not
desiring to participate in a religious exercise. Simply by
establishing this school-related procedure, which entrusts the
inherently nongovernmental subject of religion to a majoritarian
vote, a constitutional violation has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   That essentially means the court will strike down any school
district policy that authorizes public school students to vote to
deliver prayers at a school function.
</P>
<P>
   Six members of the court understand the meaning of the
Establishment Clause.
</P>
<P>
   There is no hope for Rehnquist, Scalia and Thomas on this issue.
They simply ignore constitutional history. Their vote would allow
government policies that fracture communities along religious
lines, which inevitably leads to intolerance and religious
persecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
