<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN27-CO     06-26 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: World of difference separates
groups at execution
 &HT;    EDs: This is a re-worked version of a news feature that moved
last week.
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas -- Outside the walls of Huntsville prison, the
distance was hardly a hundred yards that divided the two designated
camps, those opposing the execution of Gary Graham and those
supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all the difference in the world -- the difference
between good and evil, truth and lies, justice and injustice, black
and white.
</P>
<P>
   Which was which depended on who you were and where you stood.
</P>
<P>
   G. George, 40, of Houston, who was holding high a sign that
said, ``Send Graham to Hell,'' knew where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   George, who identified his occupation only as being employed
inside the city of Houston, had been to protests before, but not in
a long time -- not since he was a little boy ``being dragged
around'' by his parents at Vietnam rallies in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when you ask him, he'll tell you he can't even remember
which side his parents were on.
</P>
<P>
   What he will tell you is that he wants to go back to that era as
far as Texas prisons are concerned, a time of ``electric chairs and
hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to eat, let them grow their own food. If they
want clothes, let them make their own. That's the way it used to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``Everything is out of balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, under a banner saying ``Give Innocence A
Chance,'' Lynn Furay, 67, also of Houston, looked exactly what she
was, a gray-haired, retired school teacher very much out of place
among those protesting the execution.
</P>
<P>
   But her feelings were the same as theirs: ``I'm against the
death penalty and in this case I think Graham did not have a fair
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 1989, when she moved to Houston from Michigan,
where there is no death penalty, that she became an activist.
Before that, ``I really didn't think about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But as a taxpayer, she said that she felt that she was ``in
cahoots with Texas executions'' unless she took a stand against it.
</P>
<P>
   Furay said she writes letters, lobbies, is very political but
also ``very bashful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like being here,'' she said, ``but I think it is an
obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaleb Ortiz, 29, a senior majoring in criminal justice at Sam
Houston State University in Huntsville, didn't seem at all bashful
about standing next to someone waving the Confederate Battle Flag.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a group like the Klan wouldn't have someone like
him, an Hispanic, for a member. Neither would the Nation of Islam
or the New Black Panthers, who were among those protesting across
the way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, who said he had visited both camps, ``can't hate anyone.
God loves everyone here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes speaking like a lawyer, sometimes like a preacher,
Ortiz said in any ``man-made'' system of justice there would be
instances of the innocent being punished and the guilty going free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say,'' he added, ``that in this particular case, I
think the state is justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Another young man, age 24, was of the opposite opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a mask fashioned from a mechanic's dirty red rag, he
declined to give his name, acknowledging only that he was a member
of the Revolutionary Communist Youth Brigade from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was there because he was ``very much aware of what is
happening to young black men,'' that ``they are being shot at,
arrested and harassed by racist police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under communism,'' he said, ``there wouldn't be a death
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Although white himself, he had suffered similarly, ``mainly
because they (police) didn't like the way I looked.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when he said he came to realize ``you need an
organization to spearhead the struggle for human rights for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't here to riot, ``but I'm not here to get beat
up either.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the masses of people here, I don't know what might happen
if the execution goes ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime before the execution went ahead, the young man went to
jail, chased down as he was running through police lines and waving
a giant red flag.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Ray, 48, a bookseller from Conroe, Texas, was here to
wave the Confederate flag and hold a sign that said, ``Die N-Word
Die.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he came because he was ``tired of the media glorifying
Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you will excuse me for saying so,'' he told a group of
reporters, ``the media has been acting like dogs in heat.''
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures in the 90s, the heat of the late afternoon had
members of the New Black Panthers using a Texas flag to wipe the
sweat from their faces, then throwing it down in the dust of the
street and stomping it with their boots.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Ashanti Chimurengh, a gray-haired black woman and a
member of the Gary Graham Justice Coalition, was speaking to the
crowd over a loud speaker, flanked by pictures of George Bush and
the message, ``The burning Bush burns black men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two black men children and everyday I face the fear of
them being killed by racist cops. Everyday we face it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what will happen today, but I'm a warrior
princess, and we're going to win this g_d_ war.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is important that whatever happens we must take this
struggle forward.''
</P>
<P>
   It was later that night that what was scheduled to happen, after
several legal delays, happened _ and nothing said or done outside
the walls of Huntsville prison had made any difference.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, in the months leading up the November presidential
election, it's scheduled to continue to happen on an average of
almost one a week.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
