<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKWOODS-DOCS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEBERRY FESTIVAL TOWN WINS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALAIS, Maine _ Three years ago, Ebrahim Haroon was presented
with a professional choice for which his training had not prepared
him: Mitchell, S.D., home to Mitchell's Corn Palace; Moultrie, Ga.,
deep in tobacco country; or Machias, Maine, proud host of the
Blueberry Festival?
</P>
<P>
   The one thing the three places had in common was that American
doctors won't take jobs there. Since 1997, the state Office of
Rural Health has placed 39 foreign doctors in Maine's most remote
corners. There's a Syrian pediatrician in Norway, an Indian
internist in Fort Kent, and two Filipino psychiatrists in
Washington County.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to work in underserved areas, they get a three-year
extension on their J-1 visas, which foreign-trained physicians
receive when they join US residency programs. Nearly a quarter of
the doctors practicing in the United States are foreign-trained,
according to the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The J-1 visa waiver is a new inducement to work in northern
Maine, but doctors have long been attracted to the region by the
National Health Service Corps, the model for TV's ``Northern
Exposure.'' Fifty-one NHSC doctors are in small-town jobs in
exchange for student loan repayments that can reach $120,000 over
four years, according to Sophie Glidden, director of the state's
Office of Rural Health and Primary Care Services.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 20 years, 300 doctors have taken jobs in rural
Maine through the NHSC _ in Washington County, psychiatrists Mary
Beth Lardizabal and Sue Bailey were placed through the program _
and retention studies show about half of those doctors chose to
remain in the towns to which they were posted, Glidden said.
</P>
<P>
   As he made his way across Washington County the first time,
Haroon heard Billy Joel's ``Moving Out'' on his car radio, and he
wondered whether he could make it here. In some ways, though,
small-town America makes better sense to Haroon, who came from
India, than big-city America. Family relationships seem closer than
he had come to expect from Americans, he said, and people's mood
disorders and emotional problems seem to spring from the closeness
of relationships rather than the absence of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like in India. They make eye contact a lot,''
he said. ``When you get on the subway in Boston, people pull up
their books and start reading.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WOMEN-FREEDOM-BOS &LR;      06-26 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-FREEDOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE CHOICE, HIGH PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE LOTH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1991, just as the Soviet Union was breaking apart, Madeleine
Albright joined a tour of 17 countries that surveyed public
attitudes about life in emerging democracies. Albright and other
consultants to the survey, conducted by the Times-Mirror Center for
the People &AMP; the Press, held detailed interviews with citizens from
Russia to Hungary to Bulgaria to Poland, and they uncovered a
striking theme:
</P>
<P>
   In place after place, women were less likely than men to embrace
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``A profound gender gap in attitudes towards democracy and the
change to a market economy was evident in every former Communist
country,'' the researchers concluded. Women were less likely than
men to believe that free speech rights should extend to people
expressing unpopular views, for example, and they supported greater
restraints on political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The female preference for safety over freedom is not confined to
developing countries. Increasingly, Americans are being asked to
choose between the liberty that is central to our democracy and the
safety we crave in a perilous world. And where these transcendant
American values clash _ from gun control to the V chip _ women are
less likely to fight for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   In an October 1999 poll of public attitudes and social values,
the Pew Research Center found that 60 percent of women thought
``books that contain dangerous ideas should be banned from school
libraries.'' Only 48 percent of men thought that.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four percent of women said freedom of speech should not
extend to groups like the Communist party or Ku Klux Klan. Only 33
percent of men thought that.
</P>
<P>
   And 50 percent of the women thought the police should be allowed
to search the houses of known drug dealers without a court order.
Only 40 percent of men thought that.
</P>
<P>
   These double-digit gender gaps recur in any number of other
contemporary social issues where freedom and security conflict. Gun
control is a well-known example, where women of both parties are
more likely to say controlling the use of firearms is a higher
priority than protecting the rights of Americans to own guns.
</P>
<P>
   Women generally support establishing buffer zones around
abortion clinics to allow patients to safely visit their doctors,
even though abortion protesters say their free speech rights are
curtailed unconstitutionally by such laws. The US Supreme Court
will take up a Colorado case on precisely those grounds sometime
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Women are more likely to support restrictions on lewd or violent
media, to censor the Internet, or to ban hate speech; they agree
with expanding the definition of sexual harassment to include the
creation of ``a hostile environment'' even if that means another
worker's right to hang a Playboy calendar in the office is
curtailed. They feel less confined by seat-belt laws or metal
detectors. They are even more likely to support antismoking
ordinances that pit the rights of smokers to pursue their habit
against the health and safety of nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``freedom gap'' may make sense in countries that are just
emerging from Communism. Albright, asked recently about it,
cautioned against ``placing our value system'' on women who don't
have the luxury of ideological debate. ``They were just worrying
about their daily lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about elsewhere? Why do women seem so dismissive of the
free expression rights that the United States were founded upon? It
could be that women _ and minorities and anyone too poor to own
property, for that matter _ were not extended these benefits when
the Bill of Rights was written and so have less invested in them.
All things being equal, women would just as soon have the
government step in and regulate the so-called freedoms that can
overwhelm or threaten them.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Marshall, the chief justice of the Massachusetts
Supreme Judicial Court, put it this way: ``People who are more
vulnerable are more willing to let the state protect them.''
Because women are also more likely to be the ones in charge of
caring for children, who are even more vulnerable, they are doubly
inclined to give up a few rights in the name of safety.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Minow, a family law professor at Harvard Law School, says
that security is in many ways a precondition for freedom. ``If
there is no social order there can be no exercise of any right,''
she says. `In the name of social order, society has thrown out lots
of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say it's not that women value liberty less, but that they
value community more. Some see the conflict not so much as freedom
vs. security but as freedom vs. equality, putting the First
Amendment at odds with the 14th, which guarantees equal protection
under the law.
</P>
<P>
   The idea here is that if women, minorites and others not in the
mainstream culture can't be heard, their free speech rights are
lost. So special efforts must be made to ensure the participation
of every American in public debate, even if that sometimes requires
the muting of other voices.
</P>
<P>
   Those supporting this view say that the founders' intent with
the First Amendment was primarily to ensure vigorous debate, as
opposed to civil libertarians who say it was all about individual
expression, indifferent to any social purpose other than to keep a
tyrranical government from squelching dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Those who support campaign finance reform laws, for example,
argue against the US Supreme Court's 1980 ruling that a campaign
contribution, i.e., money, is a kind of speech and so cannot be
restricted. The reformers say that money's ``voice'' is so powerful
it drowns out other voices, so caps or bans on contributions should
be allowed to endure open debate.
</P>
<P>
   Owen M. Fiss, Sterling professor of Law at Yale, is author of
``The Irony of Free Speech,'' in which he argues that free
expression can actually be enhanced by restrictions on the First
Amendment, by allowing other voices that would not otherwise be
heard to emerge from the oppression of the prevailing chorus.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the US Supreme Court has not validated this view. In the
most significant cases examining restrictions on free speech, the
court stuck to the precedents that were established in a case
called Chaplinsky v. New Hampshire in 1942, which said speech could
be restricted only when the words spoken ``tend to incite an
immediate breach of the peace,'' the old chestnut about shouting
''fire!'' in a crowded theater.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 Minnesota case (RAV v. St. Paul), the court ruled that
cross-burning was expressive speech, not action, and therefore
could not be prosecuted (except insofar as it violated trespassing
or other property laws). In the decision, Justice Antonin Scalia
raised the bar even further by requiring that any restrictions on
speech must be what he called ``content-neutral,'' which will also
be at the center of the Colorado abortion protesters' case before
the Court this year.
</P>
<P>
   And not a single hate-speech restriction on a public college
campus has been upheld by this Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   This is probably a good thing in a pluralistic society, where
almost anything said or done is likely to offend somebody. As Minow
put it, ``Any restriction on speech will be selectively
administered.''
</P>
<P>
   Better than cutting off expression would be taking steps toward
a society in which there is enough opportunity for every voice to
be heard. Society can isolate hate speech (or smoking, or abortion
protesters, or Ku Klux Klaners, or firearms) or make them socially
unacceptable. But it is too dangerous to our essential Americanism
to ban them.
</P>
<P>
   Women need to be brought into this equation. If the power
relationships are skewed in contemporary American society so that
the voices of women or minorities are not heard, we should attack
that reality _ the inequitable distribution of power _ until a
critical mass of all Americans can feel secure enough to fully let
freedom ring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Loth is editor of the Globe's editorial page. She researched
this article as a 1999-2000 fellow with the Radcliffe Public Policy
Center.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
