u e BC-BOOK-BAXTER-BOS &LR;      06-26 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BAXTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES BAXTER CHARTS THE COURSE OF TRUE LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE FEAST OF LOVE 
By Charles Baxter. Pantheon. 308 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you let loose Puck and his love potions on the flatlands of
contemporary Michigan, you're bound to come up with something
quirky and fabulous at once: comically wrong romantic interludes,
punk lovers with big hearts and body piercings, golden moments of
summer softball and empty football stadiums that nod to Van
Morrison as well as to Shakespeare. But where ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' performed its magic under the canopies of night and fairy
power, Charles Baxter has bestowed his novel with the enchanting
spell of a ventriloquist's touch. ``The Feast of Love'' is a marvel
of narrative voices, each one so genuinely crafted, then inhabited,
that it seems perfectly feasible to run into these characters at
Starbucks. But let's make that Jitters, which is the name of the
local coffeehouse in this Ann Arbor. Next to Jitters _ both for
human ambience and for dreamlike possibility _ Starbucks would
never stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   As a writer of novels and short stories as well as poetry,
Baxter has long been admired by his peers for his particularly
careful vision: He has the heart of a novelist but the sensibility
of a poet, a combination that has sometimes seemed to obscure his
work instead of illuminating it. He can bury something beautiful
and odd between a couple of commas: ``the moon, the earth's mad
companion, is belting out show tunes.'' Line by line, this trait
can make you want to follow him anywhere, but his past work has
generally seemed quieter _ more ethereal _ than a lot of the
pyrotechnics lighting up contemporary fiction's sky. ``The Feast of
Love'' is quiet and ethereal both; it is also luminescent. And its
story line _ the interweaving tales, past and present, of a motley
gang tumbling around in life's forest _ seems as charmed in its own
right as it is beholden to Shakespeare's romantic comedy. Through
half a dozen narrators and several years of memories, there's
barely a false note in sight.
</P>
<P>
   A little night music, in other words, soft and erudite and under
your skin in the best of ways. ``The Feast of Love'' opens with a
Puck-like Charles Baxter, wracked by insomnia, taking a
post-midnight walk around Ann Arbor's football stadium, where he
runs into a guy he used to know named Bradley. Soon enough Baxter
the character-author fades into omniscient oblivion: While his
initial appearance could seem self-referential or cerebral, it
instead serves the purpose of showing off the architecture of the
novel _ then opens it up to happenstance and witness, leaving its
heft and intent to the characters telling the tale. This is a risky
way to structure a novel, full of potential ego-driven or technical
pitfalls, and could have failed in a number of minor ways. The fact
that it doesn't is testimony to the book's authenticity and
control, so carefully rendered as to be invisible. Voice is
everything in ``The Feast of Love,'' whether it's the hapless
nice-guy tenor of Bradley or the querulous, rock 'n' roll soprano
of Chloe _ a girl-child waitress at Jitters who believes in karmic
whiplash, a recovering outlaw named Oscar, and the walk-in
fortunetellers up the road in Ypsilanti, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley and Chloe provide the two dominant voices of the
novel, it is their lucklessness in love and life that paves the way
for the rest of the cast. A painter manque turned coffee
entrepreneur, Bradley has two mismatch marriages behind him, the
first to a well-intentioned lesbian, the next to a fierce lawyer
named Diana who describes herself in one perfect phrase: ``I lack
usable tenderness.'' Chloe has found true love with her tattooed
and pierced ex-druggie, though Oscar's father _ a banal little
piece of evil nicknamed the Bat _ casts a shadow that seems as
prescient as it is oppressive. Providing the hovering wisdom of
this loosely linked community is a task best left to Bradley's
neighbors, Harry and Esther Ginsberg. A philosophy professor and
biochemist, the Ginsbergs have three grown children, one of them,
Aaron, a walking tragedy. In a small homage to the Rosenbergs, they
have named their goldfish Julius and Ethel _ hoping they'll have
better luck there than they have thus far with the prodigal son.
</P>
<P>
   These tendrils of plot only hint at the cumulative power of
``The Feast of Love,'' which lies in the elaborate map of human
depth and detail that each narrative helps to construct. Bradley is
a guy so sweet but clueless that he named his dog Bradley, too,
then had to kidnap him back from his Cruella De Vil sister. (``My
inner life lacks dignity,'' he confesses.) Taking pity on their
continually wifeless neighbor (as with a doomed restaurant
location, women keep moving into Bradley's house, then leaving),
the Ginsbergs go over for dinner one night and get a glimpse of his
paintings _ including the one he's buried in the basement, a
magnificent study in light and abundance called ``The Feast of
Love.'' Gasping with admiration, Esther asks her host why there are
no people in the canvas. Because, Bradley tells her, ``no one's
ever allowed to go there. You can see it but you can't reach it.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is a man intent on giving up his dreams, though the
omniscient mischief-maker meddling with his love life will not let
him off the hook so easily. Like Shakespeare's comedy, this
dreamlike story provides a smorgasbord of romance; it also, in the
classic tradition, has plenty of misery _ much of it salved by hope
but scarcely diminished. ``The Feast of Love'' is full of aches and
tensions and elbow pokes and dead-end alleys; if its foibles
provide its action, they also provide Baxter with material that is
sometimes downright hilarious. The Michigan scene pieces here, from
pay-at-the-door scenery to Mrs. Maggaroulian the psychic, are
delightfully rendered; so, too, is the concision with which Baxter
can describe something as weirdly commonplace as backyard ceramics:
``They had the mean cuteness of painted souvenirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Page by page, not a lot happens in ``The Feast of Love,'' until
the dramatic resolutions in its final third. That's part of its
gentle magnetism: This novel is like a finely edited version of
life, inhabited by a bunch of mildly familiar, substantive people
you wish hung around in your part of town. Like Lorrie Moore's
``Birds of America,'' ``The Feast of Love'' takes the ordinary woes
and minute-by-minute exhilarations of modern America and infuses
them with wit, irony, and sensibility. That Charles Baxter has done
so under the sleepy awning of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' simply
makes his work a sweeter testament to the powers at work in the
forest, whether you can see them or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
