<HEADER>
A5159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CRITIC-WOODY-BOS &LR;      06-26 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITIC-WOODY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOST ART OF WOODY ALLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When was it that a new Woody Allen movie became optional? How
long ago did palaver about Zabar's get old?
</P>
<P>
   The dates differ for everyone, but most of us broke our Woody
Allen habit ages ago. We moved on while he stayed in some Upper
West Side fugue state. Over the arc of his long out-patient career,
we first adored, then admired, then tolerated, and finally ignored
him.
</P>
<P>
   We knew his later work paled against his earlier films but we
excused him because of the warm spot in our hearts he earned back
before we all started therapy. He was, after all, our very own Boo
Radley. Forget that his acting was already old while Reagan was
still in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us even overlooked his gamy extracurricular life on the
theory that, like Pete Rose, the man should be judged by what he
does on the field. Reasonable people can differ here.
</P>
<P>
   But with his latest offering, ``Small Time Crooks,'' Allen's
decline as a filmmaker is so obvious that our denial about his
slide no longer works.
</P>
<P>
   That the movie has drawn good reviews and generous word of mouth
only proves that we have lowered the bar for Woody Allen to the
embarrassment of all concerned. He should take a break. Do stand-up
in Vegas. Write for radio. Grow orchids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks,'' which was sold out on a Saturday night at
the Chestnut Hill Mall theater three weeks after it opened, is a
very modest affair. There are laughs, but they come into view like
ocean liners. It's not horrible. It's worse than that. It's
forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's shtick is now as tired as his face, which is lined in
early Sharpei-like furrows. The mannerisms, the timing, the sad
looks, all remind us of someone we've seen on late night television
but can't quite place _ him.
</P>
<P>
   Others have noted that Allen needs to not be in his own movies.
``Small Time Crooks'' only reinforces the point. The film shines
early, when actors like Michael Rapaport populate the screen.
(Rapaport delivers malapropisms with drop-dead aplomb and utters
keepers like, ``We're all smart but he wears glasses.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the movie sags when Allen goes mano a mano with Tracy
Ullman, who plays his tacky wife with brio. He fares worse against
the great Elaine May, who surfaces here as another Gracie Allen. We
can approximate what he will say before he says it. We are never
unaware that he is acting. There are no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Also unfortunate is the pairing of two of the screen's major
mannerists _ Allen and Hugh Grant _ in the same small film. At
least Allen's affectations were captivating for years. Grant's, on
the other hand, seduced us only once, in ``Four Weddings and a
Funeral.'' By now, his relentless stuttering and fractured pauses
combine with Allen's Yiddish syncopation to make us yearn for the
cleanly delivered declarative sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons are cruel but inevitable. It is impossible to watch
``Small Time Crooks'' or last year's ``Sweet Lowdown'' without
dreaming of ``Annie Hall'' or ``Broadway Danny Rose.'' The pathos
and the emotional beauty of those two earlier films are nowhere to
be found today. The juice is gone.
</P>
<P>
   I rented ``Annie Hall'' two years ago to see if it would hold up
after two decades and, more interesting, if it would appeal to my
daughter, then 15. What would a teenager of the late-1990s make of
Annie Hall-speak? Talk about mannerisms, after all, Diane Keaton in
the title role created a look and an argot so powerful that it
moved at warp speed from instant classic to cliche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Hall,'' it turns out, really is timeless. Its humor is
seditious. Allen's whining works. Keaton is classic all over again.
Best of all, he breaks our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   An artist as good as Allen is entitled to make anything he wants
as long as he can dun the money from producers. He shows no signs
of slowing down. Good actors still appear for peanuts in his
movies. So we can expect a lot more more B matter like ``Small Time
Crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he puts those of us who once adored him in a tough
position. His new stuff is painful to watch. Most of it is labored
and thin. We want to remember him when he was good. We're still
immensely proud of his fierce independence from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   We love the idea of Woody Allen, in short, but we have our
standards and this really isn't working anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
