<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-RACE-BOS &LR;      06-26 1839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FILM, STAGE, TV, LOVE IS BECOMING COLORBLIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were to chart the history of race relations through
popular culture, you would have to conclude that the tensions of
the past are beginning to ease, particularly as measured by
attitudes toward interracial romance. From one of the summer's
hottest blockbusters, ``Mission Impossible: 2,'' to Tony-winning
musicals, prime-time TV hits, and novels, the races are mixing in
ways that would cause racists and ethnic purists _ but hardly
anyone else _ to lose sleep. Mixed-race couples are nothing new, of
course, but what might be new, along with audiences' easy
acceptance of them, is a turn away from ethnocentricity and toward
assimilation. That would portend a seismic shift in the culture
wars, given the primacy that everyone from Spike Lee to David Mamet
has given to keeping it all in one's ethnic family.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at culture filtered through the movie lens, there is a
huge attitudinal shift from ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner'' to
``Jungle Fever'' and now to ``Mission Impossible: 2'' and more or
less the same thing is happening onstage. As always in America,
economics rule and one of the reasons for more mixed-race couples
is that the three hottest stars in musical theater are black _
Brian Stokes Mitchell, who won the Tony for ``Kiss Me, Kate'';
Heather Headley, who won for ``Aida''; and Audra McDonald, who lost
to Headley but was up for her fourth Tony for ``Marie Christine.''
Beyond that, however, consider some of the messages in these and
other musicals:
</P>
<P>
   --``Marie Christine'' is the throwback of the group as Michael
John LaChiusa unsuccessfully tried to turn ``Medea'' into a story
of a black woman scorned by racist America.
</P>
<P>
   --In the best new musical of the year, ``Contact,'' Boyd
Gaines's life is saved when he turns from his shallow bourgeois
life and enters the funky multicultural stew of a dance club.
</P>
<P>
   --Headley plays the Egyptian slave in Disney's silly concoction
of Verdi's ``Aida,'' and the racial/class divide is too much for
her and Radames to overcome until they're reincarnated in
present-day America.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is the star of Cole Porter's 1948 musical, ``Kiss Me,
Kate'' which isn't about race at all. This is one of the
highest-profile cases of colorblind casting, in which the producers
say race doesn't matter to the essence of a character so let's just
find the best actor/singer we can _ regardless of the race of the
other half of the love interest (Marin Mazzie in this case). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reflecting the culture &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It might be easy to shrug off the significance of Broadway
audiences' attitudes as not reflective of the society at large. But
movie audiences are, and the biggest hit of the summer pairs Tom
Cruise and Zimbabwean-born actress Thandie Newton. (She is married
to a white man.) As in ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' race is never mentioned
in ``MI:2'' and although one presumes audiences aren't colorblind
about the duo, no one seems to mind. (Incidentally, Newton also
played the slave Sally Hemings, in ``Jefferson in Paris,'' and she
played the role in a seductive way that didn't sit so well with
many.)
</P>
<P>
   It would be insane to say that because race doesn't matter in
``Kiss Me, Kate'' and ``Mission Impossible: 2'' that race doesn't
matter in reality. But it would be equally wrong to reduce all of
these fictional relationships to past political models of
colonialism or even to Lee's concept of exotic attraction in
``Jungle Fever.'' For one thing, it's getting harder to define what
race is. This is what the golfer Tiger Woods, said at the US Open
five years ago. ``It is the final and only comment I will make
regarding the issue. My parents have taught me to always be proud
of my ethnic background. The various media have portrayed me as
African-American and Asian. I am both. I am the product of two
great cultures: One is African-American and the other Asian. I am
African-American on my father's side, and on my mother's side, I am
Thai. Truthfully, I feel very fortunate and equally proud to be
both African-American and Asian. The bottom line is I am an
American and proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In many of today's television programs _ ``Ally McBeal,'' ``Once
and Again,'' and ``Will and Grace'' _ the characters take for
granted that they are attracted to people of different races and
leave it to others to define their relationships or not. And is
America ready for the daughter of a president to keep dating, or
even marry, a black man? Such fears might doom the relationship in
``West Wing,'' but perhaps the audience is further ahead of the
curve than the producers are, particularly when the debate is
expanded beyond black and white. George W. Bush is expected to make
ample use in commercials of his nephew George P. Bush, the son of
his brother, Florida Governor Jeb Bush, and his Mexican-born wife,
Columba, to lure Hispanic voters into the Republican fold. Again,
this could be construed as exploitation but considering the party's
history in playing the race card, it is noteworthy that this is a
source of pride for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   When one looks across the ocean to England, matters of race play
out quite differently. There the model is closer to the old melting
pot ideal of America in the first half of the century, when
immigrants would be assimilated and one's ethnicity wouldn't
matter. There were problems then, and even more obviously now, with
such a scenario. The melting pot was always more of an ideal than a
reflection of how ethnic groups were treated, but there are
interesting similarities between past and present.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the progressives in America of the first half of the
20th century and in England these days are more
assimilation-minded. One gets the same sense of ethnic
claustrophobia in Clifford Odets's ``Awake and Sing!'' as in Ayub
Khan-Din's current movie, ``East Is East.'' In this film of his
play, it's the Pakistani father who has resettled in Manchester,
England (somewhat incongruously with a white wife), who is
demanding his children toe the ethnic line while most of his
children are far more interested in playing around, in more ways
than one, with the whole smorgasbord of neighborhood children. One
even tells his father, who's trying to arrange a marriage with
another Pakistani family: ``Dad, I'm not Pakistani. I was born
here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hope for the future &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the play opened in England, it was staged in a theater off
the beaten tourist path, the working-class East End district. The
audience was young and multiethnic, reacting to the play as if it
were a rock concert. One came away not only with a hope for the
future of theater but, more important, a hope for the future of the
play's vision.
</P>
<P>
   Asians in America tend to follow the same pattern. Witness the
recently released ``Chutney Popcorn,'' in which two Indian-American
sisters and their white lovers _ one straight, the other lesbian _
unite (albeit with some difficulty) to conceive a child that
neither couple could have on their own. A far cry from the World
War II days of ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' when love between a
white boy and Asian girl could not sustain itself.
</P>
<P>
   Not that things are now a piece of cake in the States. The young
Pulitzer Prize-winner Jhumpa Lahiri and the more established Gish
Jen, whose roots go back to different parts of Asia, both have
collections of stories just released in paperback that write about
the mixed romances of children of immigrants with a striking
balance of humor and pathos. In Lahiri's ``Sexy,'' from
``Interpreter of Maladies,'' an Indian woman complains to her white
friend, Miranda, about her cousin's husband leaving her for a white
woman. Miranda, it turns out, is now having a passionate affair
with a married Indian man herself. In the title story from ``Who's
Irish?,'' Jen puts herself in the position of a Chinese immigrant
looking disapprovingly at her daughter's marriage to an
Irish-American.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how she describes the Sheas' reaction to the child of
that mixed marriage: ``Everything just right, only her skin is a
brown surprise to John's family. So brown, they say. . . . They
say, Nothing the matter with brown. They are just surprised. So
brown . . . Seems funny, a girl named Sophie Shea be brown . . .
The Shea family talk is like this sometimes, going around and
around like a Christmas-tree train. Maybe John is not her father, I
say one day, to stop the train. And sure enough, train wreck. None
of the brothers ever say the word `brown' again.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks in America, of course, are for the most part not the
descendants of immigrants, but of slaves, and the difference can't
be denied in the collective consciousness of white and black
Americans. But a growing number of social critics are saying that
it's a legacy that need not define contemporary thinking.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most readable books in years, particularly for a
first novelist, is the young British writer Zadie Smith's ``White
Teeth,'' a story about two families and the multiracial society
they inhabit. As Salman Rushdie said, ``Zadie Smith's fizzing first
novel is about how we all got here _ from the Caribbean, from the
Indian subcontinent . . . and about what `here' turned out to be.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's interracial couples recognize the whole messy history of
the races _ the grandmother of one was ``taken'' by a British
colonialist. On the other hand, the contemporary relationship
between Clara, a Caribbean-born woman, and Archie, a working-class
white Englishman, is full of tenderness and a wacky kind of hope.
Also in the book, a Bengali sends his son back to East Asia to be
indoctrinated in the ways of the past and the result is someone who
comes back acting like David Niven. The other son flirts with a
separatist movement, but when he's told to take his essential
belongings during a power outage, he grabs Bruce Springsteen's
``Born to Run''; the Robert De Niro ``You talkin' to me?'' poster
from ``Taxi Driver''; a Betamax copy of ``Purple Rain''; Levi's 501
jeans; Converse sneakers; and Anthony Burgess's ``A Clockwork
Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, like Rushdie, is fully aware and writes eloquently of the
racism that her black and East Asian British characters have had to
deal with. The title refers to how an old colonialist soldier tells
how he used to spot people of color in the night in order to shoot
them. But as with other British writers, such as Rushdie, there is
the sense of the melting pot being more of a positive than a
negative. Smith's thoughts seem to be summarized by those of Irie,
the daughter of a white man and black woman who is now pregnant by
one of the men whose parents were Bengali:
</P>
<P>
   ``In a vision, Irie has seen a time, a time not far from now,
when roots won't matter anymore because they can't because they
mustn't because they're too long and they're too tortuous and
they're just buried too damn deep. She looks forward to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
