<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5162 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-BEETLE-SHOW-HNS &LR;      06-26 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-BEETLE-SHOW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VW LOVERS HOST AN OUT-OF-THIS-WORLD EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSWELL, N.M. _ The Beetle lives!
</P>
<P>
   OK, so this new one isn't really all that much like the old one,
when you consider that the engine is up front rather than tucked in
the rear, there is room for a couple of adults to sit comfortably
in the back seat, there is luggage space, the heater works, and you
can get one with air-conditioning that also works.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the New Beetle is a different animal, the first
national New Beetle car show June 17-18 in Roswell, N.M., proved a
point: Beetle people like the New Beetle as much as they did the
old one. And there are a lot of young people who never were around
the original Beetle, but who have become as enamored with the new
one as we baby boomers were with the old.
</P>
<P>
   There were hundreds of this new crop of Beetle fans at Roswell,
most of them having trekked here in one of four caravans that came
from the four corners of the nation to meet each other and show off
their Doodlebugs.
</P>
<P>
   They had met on a Web site (www.newbeetle.org) that caters to
New Beetle owners and had developed an Internet camaraderie that
carried over to the weekend's events in Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the event was ``all the little pods coming to
Roswell to reunite with the Mothership,'' from a New Beetle TV
commercial that suggested these cars were reverse-engineered from
an alien spacecraft that had landed in Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   (Roswell was the site of a famous 1947 UFO sighting and recovery
that the U.S. military at first acknowledged; the next day it
changed its position and attributed the event to a wayward weather
balloon.)
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the New Beetle gathering also reiterated a point
that perhaps had been forgotten in the wake of the untimely demise
of the original Beetle in the mid-70s: that Beetle people are a
different breed. They come from all age groups, occupations and
income brackets, but they have that one thing in common, that they
are not like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   And that made for a great weekend of New Beetle camaraderie, led
by people such as Lisa Linn of Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   She organized the event and was on hand with her New Beetle,
named Spacepod, from which she uplinked photos of the event every
few minutes to the special event Web site,
www.allpodsgotoroswell.net.
</P>
<P>
   The love and care that these people showed for their cars was
proof enough that Beetlemania is far from dead.
</P>
<P>
   The New Beetle owned by Debbie Duderstadt of New Braunfels,
Texas, had about the snazziest paint job, but there were lots of
other customizations evident among the more than 350 cars on
display at the Roswell Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Besides showing off their cars, though, these people sat and
talked and laughed and generally acted as though they were lifelong
friends, even though most had never met each other in person _ only
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think we're a little bit strange,'' Duderstadt
said. ``But the fact is that Beetle people are different. And it's
not just one age group or socioeconomic level. It's a diverse group
of people, young and old and everything in between.''
</P>
<P>
   The ones who traveled the farthest for the event were Brenda
Sheets and her two sons, Zachary, 13, and William, 10, of Chugiuk,
Alaska. Just like the rest, Brenda met all of the other New Beetle
owners on the Web site and made lots of friends via computer from
the far reaches of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wanting to tour the lower 48 states, so this seemed
like a good excuse to do it,'' she said. She drove 4,525 miles in
10 days to get to Roswell in time for the events.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these New Beetle fans refer to themselves as ``old
hippies,'' and they talk about all the old Beetles they used to own
way back when.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore that theme, there was the traditional tie-dyed
clothing booth set up in the convention center to cater to Beetle
fans who are into the garb that old Beetle fans used to wear. It
seems that as long as Beetles survive, so will tie-dye.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that I'm an unabashed Beetle lover, having owned
at least a half-dozen over the years, as well as a bunch of VW
buses, a Vanagon, a Squareback and a Fastback.
</P>
<P>
   Just like most longtime Beetle owners, I had to learn the basics
of working on these cars early on, so I could keep them running. It
was common to have to spend a couple or three hours every Saturday
morning working on my Beetle or Bus so it would run OK the next
week, to get me to work and back every day.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't a problem; the old ones were fairly simple to work
on, and there really wasn't much I couldn't do myself _ up to and
including replacing a fender or an engine.
</P>
<P>
   One common problem with Beetles and Buses was the ignition
points closing up while you were driving along, which of course
would cause the engine to quit.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I carried a feeler gauge and the screwdriver I needed
to reset the points on a rear-engine VW, just so I could stop
whenever I saw a broken-down bug and reset the points so the
hapless occupants could be on their way again.
</P>
<P>
   It was amazing how often I did that for people during the heyday
of the rear-engine VWs; but it was such a quick and simple fix, and
the people were always grateful.
</P>
<P>
   And that underscores another difference with the New Beetle.
It's really high-tech, and I'm not sure I'm ready to try to learn
all about its engine and other systems to become as proficient with
repairs as I was with the old Beetles.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, I probably won't have to. VW has come a long
way, and these New Beetles are truly works of art _ not just on the
outside, but under the hood, too.
</P>
<P>
   They won't need me to stop and reset their points, or to do much
of anything else, either. Besides, they don't even have points.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
