<HEADER>
A5163 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ORLANDO-SIDE25-COX     06-26 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORLANDO-SIDE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orlando's chills and thrills better all the time
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Bigger bangs. Zappier zaps. Loopier loops. Really real
virtual reality. At Central Florida's major theme parks, they all
mean the same thing: the never-ending search for a new wow.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing they're only as good as their latest thrill ride, the
parks have recently introduced a spate of new or revamped
attractions. With Kraken, a high-speed loop coaster that opened
earlier this month, Sea World hopes to borrow some of the good buzz
from the wildly popular Incredible Hulk ride at Universal's Islands
of Adventure. Eyeing the long lines for Buzz Lightyear's Space
Ranger Spin at Disney's Magic Kingdom, Universal Studios has fired
back with an interactive alien hunt of its own, Men in Black Alien
Attack.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Disney is offering a new gloss on some old
favorites: A 3D, virtual reality version of the classic Pirates of
the Caribbean opened this month at DisneyQuest; and a
reconstructed, sonically improved version of the stunning Indiana
Jones stunt show has debuted at Disney-MGM Studios.
</P>
<P>
   We recently visited the parks and gave the new rides the wow
test, grading each on a scale from 1 (ho-hum) to 10 (awesome).
Here's how they stacked up:
</P>
<P>
   Kraken _ Sea World Orlando
</P>
<P>
   Wow grade: 7
</P>
<P>
   This extra-twisty ``floorless'' coaster is the aging marine
park's latest attempt _ joining the Journey to Atlantis water flume
and the Wild Arctic flight simulator _ to appeal to a younger, more
thrill-thirsty crowd. With its 144-foot initial drop and seven
loops, including two vertical revolutions and a zero-gravity roll,
it's certainly gasp-inducing. But some riders felt that it paled
next to other rides, especially the Incredible Hulk coaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, it's in the middle of Orlando, so it's got so
much competition,'' said Wendie Pate, 27, who had traveled from
London with her husband, Steve, 29, to visit several Central
Florida theme parks. Even though the couple had just disembarked
from their third straight spin on Kraken, they pronounced it ``not
as good'' as Universal's rival coaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first drop is really something, but you know it's
coming,'' said Wendie. Whereas, she noted, the Hulk's
out-of-nowhere speed surge ``really takes you by surprise. On a
scale of 1 to 10, I'd give Kraken an 8 and the Hulk an 11.'' We
agree, and dock Kraken an extra point for its bland aquamarine
color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Men in Black Alien Attack
</P>
<P>
   _ Universal Studios
</P>
<P>
   Wow grade: 5
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1997 hit movie starring Will Smith, this flashy
interactive ride opened in April and instantly became one of
Universal Studios' most popular attractions. But the interminable
lines _ some guests have waited two hours or longer _ seem out of
proportion to the modest charms of what is essentially a glorified
video game.
</P>
<P>
   After strolling past cute animatronic dioramas depicting scenes
from the movie, riders board a two-tiered car equipped with laser
zappers. The car winds through a garishly lit chamber packed with
alien targets that spin, swoop and hop. Riders earn points by
shooting them with the lasers _ enough points and you're deemed
ready to join Smith as a full-time Men in Black agent.
</P>
<P>
   Though far from disappointing, the ride is too similar to others
to be a top-notch wow. It's very reminiscent of Buzz Lightyear's
Space Ranger Spin at the Magic Kingdom, and one rider dismissed it
as ``Mr. Toad's Wild Ride with guns.'' The long lines further lower
its grade, though that will likely change when Universal unveils a
ride reservation system similar to Disney's FastPass next month.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates of the Caribbean: Battle
</P>
<P>
   for Buccaneer Gold _ DisneyQuest
</P>
<P>
   Wow grade: 8
</P>
<P>
   There are glorified video games and then there are glorified
video games: This clever offering, which opened Wednesday at the
five-story interactive attraction in the Downtown Disney
entertainment, dining and shopping mall, puts participants inside a
virtual reality battle with pirate ships. Donning 3-D viewing
helmets, players stand on the bow of a ship, which literally rocks
in the ``waves.'' One player steers the ship while up to four
others man cannons and plug away at video vessels on a giant curved
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Sink one with a virtual reality cannon blast and you're awarded
a chest full of doubloons, but be careful of the toothy sea
monsters, which may take a bite out of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   While the novelty of virtual reality rides wore off years ago,
this multisensory experience puts a fresh spin on the genre. Even
so, it still can't top its animatronic inspiration, the original
Pirates of the Caribbean, still yo-ho-ho-ing along at the Magic
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Jones Epic Stunt Spectacular _ Disney-MGM Studios
</P>
<P>
   Wow grade: 10
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the coolest show at any Central Florida theme park,
this decade-old attraction recently reopened after a six-month
hiatus. During the down time, the elaborate stage, which simulates
scenes from the 1981 Harrison Ford smash ``Raiders of the Lost
Ark,'' was restructured and given a fresh coat of paint. The sound
and lighting systems were also updated.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the show's death-defying stunt effects needn't worry:
Every fight, fire and flipping truck is still here _ only the
choreography has been slightly altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a hit, we didn't want to change much,'' said
producer Joe Kivett, on hand for the first return show, along with
500 invited guests named Jones. But Kivett dubbed the sonic effects
``greatly improved. Pay attention to the way the wind whips across
the speakers during the first scene.''
</P>
<P>
   We did, and we could swear we felt a hot gust as the audio track
introduced the show's Indiana Jones double, Ed Knauf. And when
Knauf was later chased by that famous rolling boulder, we knew we
were in the hands of the best Disney dream-makers.
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The quest for more wows continues in the upcoming months.
Islands of Adventure will unveil two kiddie rides in early July:
Storm Force Acceleration, based on characters from the X-Men
comics, simulates a thunderstorm with light and sound; Flying
Unicorn is a gentle roller coaster that travels through faux cloud
banks. The park will also debut two new shows on July 2 _ the
sports extravaganza ``Xtreme Xventure'' and the interactive comedy
``Bullwinkle for President.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is keeping things hopping with the return of last
summer's hit, ``The Best of Michael Flatley's Lord of the Dance''
at Epcot. The 30-minute Celtic stepping performance runs through
Aug. 26. And SongMaker, another new interactive attraction now open
at DisneyQuest, invites guests to step into a sound booth and
create a tune with supplied lyrics and beats, which they then have
the option of purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   What will be the next theme park thrill? Stay tuned, and fasten
your seat belts ...
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Universal Studios/Islands of Adventure, 407-363-8000,
www.universalstudios.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sea World Orlando, 1-800-327-2424, www.seaworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Walt Disney World (including information on Animal Kingdom,
Disney-MGM Studios, Epcot and the Magic Kingdom), 407-824-4321,
www.disney.com. DisneyQuest, 407-828-4600, www.disney.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
