<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-MIRANDA (Washington) _ In a strongly worded opinion, the
Supreme Court refuses to overturn the landmark Miranda decision of
1966, ruling that law enforcement officers must warn suspects of
their rights to remain silent and obtain a lawyer. The high court,
voting 7-2, rejects a lower court's ruling that the
self-incriminating statements of a Maryland man can be used against
him even if the FBI did not first read him his rights. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRIMARY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
California's free-for-all primary election system that allows
voters to choose candidates without regard to party affiliation
violates the rights of state political parties. In a 7-2 ruling,
the court calls the state's system ``tremendously intrusive'' on
the right of a political party to define its own message and decide
its own candidates. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HISPANICS (Washington) _ George W. Bush announces a plan to
carve the Immigration and Naturalization Service into two separate
agencies _ one to handle enforcement and the other naturalization.
His plan would revamp the long, frustrating process immigrants now
endure to become citizens. In a bid to win the support of Hispanic
voters in his presidential campaign against Al Gore, the Texas
governor announces his proposal in a speech here to the League of
United Latin American Citizens. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Why would a Republican senator
release a Justice Department investigator's recommendation that an
outside counsel be appointed to probe Vice President Al Gore's role
in Buddhist temple fund-raiser? Why, indeed, given the facts that
the investigator acknowledges he has no evidence that Gore lied
about his role and that the event itself was not illegal? What's
going on is not a mystery: It's another partisan opportunity to
embarrass Gore and Attorney General Janet Reno. This is just one
more congressional witch hunt. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
