<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIESTAWARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIESTAWARE: ART DECO STAPLE RETAINS ITS STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fiestaware, the art deco pottery from the mid-1930s, became a
mainstay in the dish cupboard because of its soft pastel or bright
and bold colors.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to mix and match this solid-color dishware to create
table settings to go with any decor. Collectors often change colors
with the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fiestaware options include tableware, pitchers and sets of
mixing bowls.
</P>
<P>
   When Fiestaware was first designed in 1936 by Frederick H. Rhead
for the Homer Laughlin China Co., in Newell, W.Va., color choices
were ivory, light green, cobalt blue, yellow and red. Turquoise was
added a year later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, red was discontinued because the U.S. government needed
the uranium that was used to produce the color. Red made a comeback
by the late '50s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, production of Fiestaware ceased to make way for new
designs. The company went back to making the original style in 1986
to mark its 50th anniversary, using the original molds with updated
colors.
</P>
<P>
   To determine the age of a piece, look at the color and shade.
Colors came in and out of fashion, and were slightly different when
they were reintroduced.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are higher for collectible limited-edition colors (like
lilac and sapphire) and pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Although early Fiestaware contained lead, modern pieces are safe
to use, according to Andy Geller, co-owner of New Scotland Antiques
in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Early pieces may be safe as long as they are not cracked or
chipped. However, acidic foods could cause the uranium from old red
pieces to leach out through the glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, a tea cup and saucer or a dinner plate sold for 35
cents and a coffee pot cost $1.25. Depending on collectibility,
older pieces can cost thousands of dollars. Today, new Fiestaware
prices begin at $9 for a dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   Fiestaware can be found in antiques shops, department stores,
catalogs and on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
