<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-26 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GETTING THE FEDS TO ADMIT ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By L.M. SIXEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Ileana Trevino was surprised last month when she got a
report from the Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs
(OFCCP) that showed that the University of Houston treated women
employees differently than men employees.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, which issued the report after several months of
investigation, found that the university did not take appropriate
action to ensure that women were treated without regard to their
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Female faculty members who were interviewed had complained that
male colleagues had referred to them as ``girls'' and that while
men were called ``Dr.,'' women were called ``Ms.'' Female staff
members complained that although they are professionals, male
managers had asked them to ``fetch'' coffee.
</P>
<P>
   These were isolated examples reported by one or two women, which
hardly constituted the serious accusation of discriminatory
treatment, said Trevino, executive director of affirmative action
at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   So she called the agency to express her dismay about what she
saw as overreaching by the body that investigates federal
government contractors for their affirmative action compliance. The
university is subject to the agency's audits because it receives
$20.3 million in federal research grants.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Office of Federal Contract Compliance
Programs agreed with Trevino and immediately changed the violation
to read that some women who were interviewed believed they were not
treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino said the change is a much better reflection of what she
calls the isolated comments that were made. The investigation _ the
university's first _ was comprehensive. It included an examination
of compensation, affirmative action programs and employment
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the federal agency that investigates equal employment
back off its original report? After spending close to a year doing
an investigation, shouldn't the agency have its analysis nailed
down?
</P>
<P>
   Lois Jimmerson, district director of the OFCCP in Houston, said
she can't comment on open cases. But she said the agency's main
focus is obtaining a remedy to correct a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Meyer, an employment lawyer at Seyfarth Shaw in Houston who
represents management interests, said he has found that the agency
will, on occasion, withdraw violations or change its tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes an employer can persuade the agency to change the
violation to a lesser one. That usually happens if the facts don't
back up what the agency said was the original violation or if the
employer comes in with additional evidence, Meyer said. Either way,
it takes time and resources.
</P>
<P>
   The OFCCP isn't known as a barracuda in the employment
discrimination arena. It's willing to negotiate with employers if
it issues an assessment of violations that employers dispute, said
a source familiar with the inner workings of the OFCCP.
</P>
<P>
   It's also not known for an aggressive legal stance. Unlike other
agencies, the OFCCP, which is part of the Labor Department, doesn't
have its own flock of lawyers. It has to share lawyers with other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its agreement with OFCCP, the University of Houston
must send its managers and supervisors to sexual harassment
training and distribute to all employees a policy that prohibits
adverse treatment based on sex, that prohibits sexual harassment
and that prohibits intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   That type of requirement is common in discrimination cases. And
many companies and organizations routinely provide employee
training on discrimination and distribute anti-discrimination
policies to employees.
</P>
<P>
   The OFCCP also criticized the university for not having an
applicant tracking system in place when the on-site audit occurred
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino, who said she was aware of that shortcoming when she
took the job, put a system in place in September that will track
applications and hires based on race, sex and ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that information, the university will be able to
analyze trends on which applicants have been hired and promoted,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Trevino said, she is satisfied with the report. ``It's
about as close as you can get to a clean bill of health,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
