<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BACKWOODS-PSYCHIATRIS     06-26 1889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKWOODS-PSYCHIATRISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSYCHIATRISTS FACE STARK TASK IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACHIAS, Maine _ After the last shopping mall is long past, the
last bus station, the last stoplight, the road to Machias still
stretches out through the woods for an hour. On their way to their
new jobs, the three freshly minted psychiatrists had plenty of time
to think.
</P>
<P>
   Each knew that it had taken nearly six years to replace the last
psychiatrist practicing full time in this hardscrabble region, and
eventually _ through wry comments or dark warnings or small-town
murmurs _ they all found out that their predecessor had committed
suicide. Ebrahim Haroon, who arrived first, was thinking, ``It is
an ocean of quietness.'' Mary Beth Lardizabal was thinking, ``It is
the most beautiful place I have ever seen.'' Sue Bailey was
thinking, ``Let me test myself in Washington County.''
</P>
<P>
   With its combined remoteness and poverty, this county has a
reputation for driving mental health professionals out of the
specialty, or out of the region, or both.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly two years into their mission, the three are still
bewildered by the reservoir of need they found here, in a part of
the United States where mental illness is often handled within the
four walls of a household. From time to time, patients ventured
into their offices like visitors from another century: the
16-year-old autistic boy whose parents just considered him a
``loner;'' the patient who confided that her mother hadn't set foot
outside the house in 15 years; patients who had visited an
emergency room, certain they were dying, for a decade's worth of
anxiety attacks; the eccentric; the dotty; the different; the
touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does feel sometimes as if we are on the frontier,
both in terms of bringing psychiatric care to people who have never
had it, but also in terms of introducing the community at large to
the idea of psychiatry,'' Bailey said. ``I do feel that I am on an
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, in one of the last vestiges of the great Maine woods,
doctors of all kinds take on a culture that discourages asking for
help, and mental health workers, like dentists, find themselves
forced to sell the very idea of their specialty. In ``A Maine
Hamlet,'' her memoir of growing up outside Machias at the turn of
the century, Lura Beam recalled the townspeople's pragmatic
approach to acts of despair _ a butcher who shot himself was
presumed to have ``become melancholy from seeing too much blood'' _
and their dismissal of most medical treatment as weak-minded
``dosing.'' Looking back on her childhood home, Beam admiringly
described the region's ethic of stoicism: ``Health in the hamlet
may have been superior, or people may not have talked about how
they felt. The tradition was in favor of endurance and the tight
lip.''
</P>
<P>
   That tradition was only one of the obstacles thrown in front of
the new doctors who arrived from the city: Haroon, 43, the son of a
Madras, India, pediatrician; Lardizabal, 38, who was raised in a
tiny Maryland town where her father treated black-lung disease; and
Bailey, 46, a former college writing instructor whose fascination
with schizophrenia started with her own brother and sister. It
didn't take long for the county's three full-time psychiatrists to
meet over a cathartic breakfast, comparing notes about the strange
landscape onto which they had stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember asking one surgeon _ who will remain nameless _
what he did when someone needs psychiatric referral,'' Lardizabal
said. ``He said, `I send them out into the woods.' It was kind of
weird and frightening. I didn't know if he was joking or not.''
</P>
<P>
   With little access to psychiatric care, people such as Lillian
and Ray Hanscom, who moved into the county with a schizophrenic son
in his early 20s, were left to deal with his illness almost two
hours from the nearest mental ward. As they grew frailer and he
grew stronger, the anxiety forced the difficult decision to send
him to Bangor, where he lives in a roominghouse closer to the
services he needs.
</P>
<P>
   Then, say mental health professionals, there was another set of
people whose illnesses simply disappeared into country life _
wanderers who drifted into the North Woods, where their behavior
wouldn't bother anyone, or who were absorbed into a comfortable
role as the town drunk or the local eccentric. For those doctors
who stepped in to fill the gap, the pressure could be unbearable.
John A. Edwards, who has spent years recruiting personnel for
Washington County Psychotherapy Associates, has seen it too often.
</P>
<P>
   ``To bring one person into this community would be sealing their
fate,'' he said. ``I can guarantee that that would be the case. I
mean, they would be so bombarded.''
</P>
<P>
   No less important was the comfort of having colleagues to talk
to. Like mental health professionals in all of the nation's rural
and frontier country, Haroon, Lardizabal, and Bailey ran into a set
of conditions that challenged their urban training. The first was a
two-way lack of anonymity. Doctors find themselves breaking a
baseline principle of urban practice by treating multiple members
of the same family, carving out a position ``much more akin to the
old family doc,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are exquisitely conscious that every notation taken in
therapy might be transcribed, then filed by someone who lived in
their town. Therapists struggle with a desperate, bone-deep
resistance to telling their secrets. Christine White, who has
practiced psychiatry part time in Calais for three years, says that
several times a patient has ``opened up to (her) and then never
come back again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of safety is very different in a rural community,''
White said. ``If they actually, truly tell me their secrets, then
their experience 99 percent of the time'' was loss of control over
the information.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, mental health workers lose the professional
neutrality that typically accompanies the wing chair and the
waiting room. In small towns, mental health workers can't avoid
socializing with patients, opening up a world of unsolicited
information, not only about their patients' personal lives, but
about their own. Dana Bartone, who practices psychiatry in
Aroostook County, said he once had the unsettling experience of
looking over his shoulder on his way home and realizing that his
last patient was following him down the street, just to see where
he lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I walk around realizing that most people I pass know
who I am, but I don't know who they are,'' Lardizabal said.
</P>
<P>
   And while many of the doctors' complaints are the challenges of
treating poor people anywhere _ chiefly that managed care has made
mental health services less available and accessible _ the
residents of Maine's back country offered a different array of
problems from city dwellers. Here, in a county whose unemployment
rate is consistently one of the state's highest, major depression
is common among men. Bailey said she had been shocked at the number
of panic disorders she comes across, and, like White, encounters a
huge number of cases caused by abuse and trauma within families. A
particular marker of the cases White has found in small towns is
that abuse was common knowledge, said White, who has begun to think
that ``isolation breeds some brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   What they are less likely to see is the ``worried well.'' White,
a specialist in borderline personality disorders, said her practice
in Washington County has been notably devoid of ``attention-seeking
behavior'' like self-mutilation _ probably, she offers, because
there's no one around to notice it.
</P>
<P>
   Lardizabal, a child psychiatrist, has seen almost no eating
disorders. And there are some illnesses, schizophrenia, for example
that actually seem to improve in rural areas because there is so
little stimulus, White said.
</P>
<P>
   And small-town communities, they all agree, take on far greater
responsibility for taking care of their mentally ill _ to the
extent, Edwards said, that if a resident ``doesn't show up to talk
to the lamppost, neighbors will call the police to check up on him
or her.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, rural families such as the Hanscoms might have
gotten more, not less, attention. Rural areas have scraped by with
minimal mental health services ever since the early 1970s, when
progressives pushed to replace state mental hospitals with more
humane community-based services, said Gerald Grob, a professor at
Rutgers University and author of ``The Mad Among Us: A History of
the Care of America's Mentally Ill.'' Those services never
materialized in rural areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, central cities boast 17.2 psychiatrists per 100,000
people; rural communities with a population of less than 2,500 have
fewer than one psychiatrist per 100,000 people. Of the 711 counties
federally designated ``health provider shortage areas'' for
psychiatry, 70 percent are in nonmetropolitan areas. Rural patients
are so inaccessible that some mental health policy makers say the
best hope for reaching them lies in online counseling, despite
worries about confidentiality and effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Even in New England, home to more psychiatrists than any other
region in the United States, availability of treatment is skewed
toward city dwellers. Massachusetts has 26 psychiatrists per
100,000 people, the most of any state in the union; Maine has only
11 per 100,000, roughly the national average. Of those, more than
half practice in Cumberland County, the county that includes
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Washington County's sixth psychiatrist is due to open his
practice shortly. Still, demand for services remains strong, and
Lardizabal ventures the opinion that what they have seen is only
``the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so surprising, because for years you never heard
anything, and all of a sudden all these mentally ill people are
coming out of the woodwork,'' said Lillian Hanscom, 69, who as a
member of the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill lobbied the
state for years to fund a psychiatrist for the county. ``It's
almost like Jane Eyre, keeping them up there in the attic. They
just sort of kept them at home.''
</P>
<P>
   And the next question, for the doctors who took the chance of
coming here, is whether they will stay after their three- and
four-year assignments end. Lardizabal says yes. Haroon, whose wife
is also a doctor, says he is ``keeping an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who calls her work ``amazingly absorbing,'' isn't sure
she has it in her: She has begun to believe in the
character-shaping power of weather and to think that she, who spent
her girlhood in New Orleans, will never grow the right kind of
armor. There was one day last winter when she looked out at her
driveway, sheathed in ice, and thought: ``I can't do this. I can't
take Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   She pulled herself together, turned around, and trudged inside
to shovel out the ashes from her wood stove and scatter them. In
the end, it's the weather that she thinks could get to her. That,
or the isolation. Lura Beam recalled these woods a hundred years
ago, when the front door of every house faced south, toward ``the
town, a solid fact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A person going to the north,'' she wrote, ``was soon
absolutely alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
