<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Butterfly'' Filmmaker Jose Luis Cuerda evokes the
poignantly brief days of Spain's Republic, before it was snuffed
out by Franco. Its liberal expansiveness is personified by the
great Fernando Fernan Gomez, who plays an enlightenment figure, a
village teacher, in this handsomely crafted film that curiously and
stubbornly never takes wing. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``Chicken Run'' It's amazing how much life Britain's
Aardman animation gang can breathe into a load of clay, sculpted
into a flock of chickens, led by a plucky pullet and a randy Yank
rooster, looking for a great escape from a podgy, retro British
farm about to be turned into a concentration camp for chickens.
(G) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Chutney Popcorn'' Nisha Ganatra wrote, directed, and stars as
a lesbian who volunteers to serve as surrogate mother for her
married sister who can't have children. Before she knows it, her
own relationship is threatened and the family dynamic is even more
warped than ever. It's messy, tender, funny, and unpredictable. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``Groove'' Greg Harrison's loving and lovable celebration
of the San Francisco underground rave scene. It's never too dazed
and confused to generate a sweet communal vibe as its ravers juggle
a search for love and a need to appear cool, even while drugged,
under the big glitter dome that stands as a metaphor for the movie
itself. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
!!! ``Me, Myself and Irene'' Jim Carrey's farce about a Rhode
Island state trooper with a split personality will please fans
awaiting his return to the contortionist slapstick that made him a
star. Still, this Farrelly brothers film is frankly in and out. It
has laughs. It also has a lot of dead air and barely a plot. It
needs help, and gets a lot of it from the black triplet genius
rappers. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Sunshine'' There's much to admire in Istvan Szabo's
gorgeous, heartfelt generational epic about the high cost of
assimilation paid by three generations of a family of Hungarian
Jews over a century, dominated by Ralph Fiennes in three roles and
Jennifer Ehle as a spirited woman who shakes up the family's
self-defeating need for acceptance and respectability. But it's
broader than it is deep, and the male characters' blindness
depletes our sympathy for them. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
