<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Chief'' by David Nasaw (Houghton Mifflin, $35).
Exhaustively researched and straightforwardly told, the life of
William Randolph Hearst emerges from the shadow of ``Citizen
Kane.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Read and Why'' by Harold Bloom (Scribner, $25). The
eminent critic shares his thoughts on favorite books _ not in
deep-dish essays, but in epigrammatic reader's notes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Running Mate'' by Joe Klein (Dell, $26.95). Forget the
notoriety of Klein's first ``Anonymous'' political novel _ this one
proves once and for all that he knows Washington and knows how to
write. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Plowing the Dark'' by Richard Powers (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$25). Perhaps his best-executed story yet, crammed with erudition
and cutting-edge science but unmistakably human. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From Dawn to Decadence'' by Jacques Barzun (HarperCollins,
$36). A magisterial survey of the West's past 500 years, as
readable as it is learned.
</P>
</TEXT>
