<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU HAVE ALL THE TIME IN THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people's time is more valuable than other people's time.
</P>
<P>
   Their time is prime time. My time is off-peak, way off-peak.
</P>
<P>
   I answer the telephone, and I know I'm talking to someone whose
time is more valuable than mine because she doesn't ask, ``Are you
busy?'' or ``Am I interrupting?''
</P>
<P>
   She just launches into whatever she has to say because she can't
afford to waste any of her valuable time. And she keeps on talking,
and talking, and talking because she knows that what she wants to
tell me is more important than anything I might be doing.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes she puts me on hold so she can take a call
from somebody whose time is also more important than mine, even
though he may be calling in the form of a recorded message asking
if she'd like to take advantage of some fabulous,
once-in-a-lifetime deal on magazine subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Some people's time is so valuable they have someone else who
calls to make sure I'm there before they start talking. These
people can't afford to waste even a second. They want me to do
something for them right away, this minute. Their time must be
really precious because when I call them, they're always too busy
to talk. ``I'll have my people call your people,'' one of them may
say. If his people do call, they soon find out that I don't have
any people, which means my time can't be very valuable, so I can't
be worth talking to, until the next time one of them wants
something.
</P>
<P>
   My time seems to be especially worthless when I'm driving. That
guy talking on the phone and speeding past on the right in the
break-down lane? His time is really valuable. And that woman who
cut in front of me to get into the express lane? Normally that lane
is reserved for cars carrying two or more people, but she must have
a special sticker from the Precious Time Division of the DMV that
allows her to drive alone in the express lane.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell by just looking at certain cars that the drivers'
time is a lot more valuable than mine. BMWs. Saabs. SUVs. And
convertibles, in summertime. I get out of their way. I don't want
to hold them up, not that I could because they can see by my
10-year-old Geo Prizm that my time is of no importance, so they can
cut me off whenever they like. I have all the time in the world,
which is lucky for me because I need to spend so much of it
bringing my car to the shop for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the supermarket my time is of no value whatsoever compared to
that of the woman in front of me in the ``8 Items or Fewer'' line.
I can tell that her time is extremely precious because she didn't
want to wait in one of the regular lines, even though she has about
30 items. She has important things to do, no time to waste. It's
obvious. The cashier ringing her up can see how valuable this
woman's time is because she didn't say a word to her about the size
of her order.
</P>
<P>
   Salespeople seem to know instinctively who has time to kill and
who doesn't. I'm in a store, about to buy a sweater when the phone
rings. The saleswoman leaves me in mid-transaction and rushes to
answer. Is she expecting an important call? Could it be Regis
Philbin? Is she somebody's lifeline?
</P>
<P>
   No. It's a customer whose time is too valuable to squander on
shopping in person. The saleswoman spends several long minutes on
the phone with her, while I wait because my time is of no account.
They both know, shopper and saleswoman, that I won't mind waiting,
that I have nothing important to do. My time is their time,
literally. Why get upset? Time is on my side, in the long run, but
only in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
