<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YOU READ THIS, THE MCAS MAY NOT SEEM SO TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More and more states are requiring students to pass a
standardized test as a condition of getting a high school diploma,
and the complaints are flying fast and thick. These tests are
unfair, the grumblers grumble. They ask irrelevant questions, the
fumers fume. They subvert regular lessons. They force educators to
teach to the test. They aren't good yardsticks of what students
really know. They're racist.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the statewide MCAS test won't become a
graduation requirement until 2003. 12th-graders will be able to
meet that requirement by scoring just one point above failing on
the (itals)10th(unitals)-grade test. (Only math and English
questions will count; failure in science and history will not
prevent graduation.) But even that low hurdle is under fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MCAS doesn't take into account artistic talent or
vocational skills,'' a Cambridge girl writes in The Boston Globe.
``The fact that a child's future should be determined by knowing or
not knowing certain dates or formulas is ridiculous.'' An older
Cambridge resident finds it appalling that ``the difference between
a diploma and doomsday'' should ``come down to a byzantine trivial
pursuit.'' Who really imagines, they and others ask, that any
prospective employer will care if these students learned about the
1950s policy of containment, or if they know that Voltaire and
Rousseau are associated with the Enlightenment and not the
Industrial Revolution?
</P>
<P>
   A little perspective. Pupils, parents, and pundits who think
today's standardized tests are intolerable might find it
instructive to look at the kinds of tests high schools used to
administer.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, what students in California's Central
Valley were once expected to know. Here are some questions from the
history portion of the 1914 Kern County High School test. These
were not multiple choice; students had to write short essays, not
fill in a circle with a No. 2 pencil. (Some questions in this
column have been condensed or edited for clarity.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Give an account of the Lewis and Clark Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   --Connect these names with US history: Captain Perry, Robert
Fulton, Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, Lafayette, General Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   --Give an account of the causes of the Civil War. Name four
battles and the opposing generals in each.
</P>
<P>
   --Tell all you can of the events of the McKinley Administration.
</P>
<P>
   --Give a brief account of the construction of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   --Explain the effects of World War I on the commerce of the US.
On the revenue of the US. What remedies have been applied?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As kids are the same in every era, no doubt there were plenty in
1914 who resented having to master such ``ridiculous'' and
``byzantine'' details. What employer, some must have muttered, is
ever going to ask me about the Panama Canal?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some adult, overhearing this dissent, paused to explain
that there (itals)was(unitals) value in learning about the Panama
Canal and the Civil War generals _ value both in the knowledge
itself and in honing the intellectual tools needed to learn about
anything. Or perhaps this adult simply invited the disgruntled
students to consider the sorts of test questions their parents had
once grappled with.
</P>
<P>
   In 1895, for example, the graduation test in Saline County,
Kan., included 10 questions on orthography. A few of them:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --What are elementary sounds? How are they classified?
</P>
<P>
   --What are the following? Give examples: trigraph, subvocals,
diphthong, cognate letters, linguals.
</P>
<P>
   --Use the following in sentences: cite, site, sight, fane, fain,
feign, vane, vain, vein, raze, raise, rays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And some of the arithmetic questions:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --A wagon box is 2 feet deep, 10 feet long, and 3 feet wide. How
many bushels of wheat will it hold?
</P>
<P>
   --Find the interest on $512.60 for 8 months and 18 days at 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   --District 33 has a valuation of $35,000. What is the necessary
levy to carry on a school seven months at $50 per month, and have
$104 for incidentals?
</P>
<P>
   --What is the cost of 40 boards, 12 inches wide and 16 feet
long, at $.20 per inch?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too tough? Tell that to the New Jersey kids who had sat down to
be tested a decade earlier. In 1885, the Jersey City High School
exam covered algebra, arithmetic, geography, grammar, and US
history. From the geography portion:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --What is the axis of the earth? What is the equator? What is
the distance from the equator to either pole in degrees and in
miles?
</P>
<P>
   --Name four principal mountain ranges in Asia, three in Europe,
and three in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   --Name the states on the west bank of the Mississippi, and the
capital of each.
</P>
<P>
   --What are the principal exports of France? Of the West Indies?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hold students to high standards of learning, and odds are they
will meet them. Worry more about their self-esteem or the
``diversity'' of their textbooks, and they'll probably learn much
less. Are you amazed that high school graduates a century ago could
handle questions like the ones in this column? Actually, they could
handle far more. You see, the questions you've just read were all
from tests to get (itals)into(unitals) high school. They were
tests, in other words, of what the educated eighth-grader was
presumed to have mastered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Jacoby is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
