<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF RENO SAYS NO TO A COUNSEL, REAL ISSUES CAN BE TACKLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; There are many similarities between what happened to President
Clinton many months ago and what is now happening to Vice President
Al Gore and, on a lesser scale, to Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one big difference: Last week's call for an
independent counsel to probe Gore's fund-raising activities, and
the independent counsel's decision on Hillary Clinton's role in the
firing of the travel office, come in the midst of their election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that Robert Conrad, head of the Justice
Department's campaign finance task force, is urging Attorney
General Janet Reno to name a special prosecutor to investigate
Gore's 1996 fund-raising efforts is casting a large cloud over the
Gore campaign. Conrad's recommendation, which hinges on a campaign
event at a Buddhist temple four years ago, also puts Reno in a
no-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   If she turns down Conrad's request, which she has done with two
other such requests from other Justice Department officials, she
will be accused by the GOP of trying to protect the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno determines there should be an investigation, she would
have to appoint an independent counsel, since the Justice
Department would be seen as having a conflict of interest. Of
course, deciding to appoint an independent counsel could be
devastating to Gore's White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   As history has proved, an independent counsel's investigation
could go on, not for months, but for years _ through election day
and beyond. And the independent counsel could make allegations or
remarks that could influence voters and persuade them not to take a
chance on a candidate with an investigation hanging over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Reno could once again resist the call for an independent counsel
into Gore's fund-raising. Gore has said repeatedly that the
activity at the Buddhist temple was not a fund-raiser. But if she
decides against an independent counsel, she may end up taking more
heat from the Republicans on Capitol Hill than Gore is facing in
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, she is much better off than Gore at this point.
Despite Independent Counsel Robert Ray's strong views that there
was ``substantial evidence'' that she played a role in the firings
of the travel office employees, the fact that he decided not to go
forward with the investigation is a victory for her.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, of course, is not out to do the Clintons any favors; he
appeared from day one to want to do more damage to them than even
former Independent Prosecutor Kenneth Starr. Ray, unlike Starr,
said he may try to indict the president after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   If Ray felt he had enough to prosecute Hillary Clinton, he would
have done so. But even though he decided not to go forward, he
still damaged her by suggesting she had done something illegal _ it
was just that there was not enough evidence to convict her.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Clinton's Republican opponent for the US Senate seat in
New York, congressman Rick Lazio, will use Ray's mention of
``substantial evidence'' against her, just as Gore's rival, George
W. Bush, will capitalize on the issue in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the prospect of an investigation is gone for
Hillary Clinton _ which is more than Gore can say.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the alleged Buddhist Temple fund-raiser
has already resulted in the conviction of a longtime Gore friend,
Maria Hsia. Her conviction, currently on appeal, involved charges
she channeled more than $100,000 in contributions, including money
raised from the temple, to Democratic candidates in the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   Reno may decide to reject Conrad's call for an independent
counsel. She has rejected such calls in the past _ from FBI
Director Louis J. Freeh; from Charles LaBella, former head of the
campaign task force; from Robert Litt, a former official in the
Justice Department's criminal division.
</P>
<P>
   She had taken the heat on those rejections and is capable of
doing so again _ even though this time the official calling for the
probe, Conrad, is not part of the conservative right, and thus is a
bit more credible than some of Clinton's detractors.
</P>
<P>
   The electorate is by now both familiar with, and tired of, the
Buddhist temple controversy. Rather than a call for another
independent counsel, this issue should result in a call for
campaign finance reform that would virtually eliminate the need for
fund-raising and the controversies that attach to it.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno maintains her courage on this issue and rejects Conrad's
call for an independent counsel, Gore will at least have a chance
against the expected GOP onslaught on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   And the nation's voters will be able to focus on more important
issues that will help them decide which candidate they want to run
this country for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
