<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FIONA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORRIS CRAFTS COMPLEX TALE OF LOVE WITH `FIONA RANGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MONICA L. WILLIAMS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FIONA RANGE 
By Mary McGarry Morris 
Viking, 432 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary McGarry Morris has already won the literary lottery:
nominations for the National Book Award and PEN/Faulkner fiction
award, a novel made into a motion picture, an Oprah Book Club
selection, and a nod from Time magazine for one of the five best
novels of 1991. With her fourth novel, ``Fiona Range,'' Morris
reaffirms her place as one of the foremost contemporary novelists
of her genre.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Andover author will find themselves in familiar
territory. There are many thematic and schematic similarities in
her works: Set in small New England towns, the novels feature
pariahs as protagonists, people on the fringes of society. These
are suspenseful stories of losers and loners, family secrets and
lies. Fiona Range, like the haunted women in Morris's previous
novels, has a present complicated by her past.
</P>
<P>
   As the novel opens, Fiona awakens, hungover, with a man she
can't remember bringing home. To make matters worse, her bedmate
turns out to be the husband of one of her friends, Krissy Glidden.
Krissy and newborn baby are due home from the hospital that very
morning. Fiona has a habit of winding up in bed with the wrong man,
but this latest night of carelessness may be her biggest faux pas.
Weary of constant disapproval by the provincial townsfolk of
Dearborn, Mass., Fiona has vowed to change her reputation, but
change is difficult and often painful.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, Fiona is the small-town bad girl who can never make good.
A community-college dropout and waitress at the local greasy spoon,
the promiscuous protagonist is gorgeous, fiery, and tough, with a
huge chip on her shoulder. Abandoned by her mother as an infant,
Fiona has been raised by her aunt and uncle, pillars of the
community. But now she has been evicted from her apartment and
banished by her family for her association with her drug-dealing
former boyfriend. Desperate for a familial connection, she reaches
out to the man who is rumored to be her father, Patrick Grady, the
town eccentric who ignores her existence. Grady, a scarred Vietnam
vet with a dangerous nature, lives in a shack on the outskirts of
town. Much to her family's chagrin, the headstrong Fiona is
determined to find out _ through Grady _ just who she is.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to dismiss Morris's latest work as a
lightweight romance novel. But Morris has created a dimensioned
heroine with intricate problems. And every character, from Fiona's
querulous co-workers to her sardonic relatives, is fully developed.
Fiona is self-destructive, but always within sympathetic reach.
With depth and assuredness, Morris has crafted a grim and complex
tale of love: What is it? What do you do without out? What would
you do in the name of it?
</P>
<P>
   Full of mystery and suspense, ``Fiona Range'' is Morris's
lightest novel to date, but also her most focused. Readers will
fight the urge to fast-forward to the end as Fiona finds her way _
and as Morris keeps her literary footing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
