<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUMAN GENOME &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is devoting 42 columns, almost its entire
Science Times section, to stories, graphics and photos on the human
genome announcement.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Washington) _ Ledeall: President Clinton and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair joined scientists from around the world
Monday in announcing the completion of a working draft of the
instructions to make a human being. Clinton described the mapping
of the human genome as ``the most important, most wondrous map ever
produced by humankind,'' at a White House press conference linked
by satellite to Blair in London. They were responding to the
announcement by scientists that they had unravelled 97 percent of
the human genetic code, and 85 percent of the data had been
assembled in the right sequence. Hailing what it called a landmark
in knowledge, the international public consortium spearheaing the
research, the Human Genome Project said it had ``assembled a
working draft of the human genome _ the genetic blueprint for a
human being.'' (Summary from wires) By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With a PRIMER graphic, an illustrated glossary of genetic terms.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis: The genome is
long; it is pithy. It is a pigsty, bulging with nongenes and viral
detritus; it is a pearl, a model of high performance and
reliability. In short, the human genome exults in contradictions.
By Natalie Angier. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   See the Science Times budget for additional stories and
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUPREME COURT &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court re-affirms
Miranda, 7-2; the decision was written by Chief Justice Rehnquist.
By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRIMARY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court declares the
blanket primary unconstitutional. This system, in use in
California, puts all primary candidates on same ballot and allows
any voter to vote for any candidate. The system, put in place by
voter initiative, was used in 1998 and this year. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HATE-CRIME (Washington) _ The Supreme Court holds 5-4
that New Jersey's hate crime law is unconstitutional because it
gives the power to the judge in each case to determine if a crime
had been motivated by illegal bias. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Other court action: The Supreme Court
agrees to hear a case that raises the issue of whether it is legal
to make use of illegally intercepted phone conversations. In this
example, a radio show in Pennsylvania broadcast a conversation some
anonymous person had illegally taped. The court also agrees to hear
again cases involving the mapping of a Carolina congressional
district, student prayer at commencement, traffic arrests.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SURPLUS (Washington) _ President Clinton announces that
the 10-year fedral budget surplus will be about $1 trillion higher
than previously projected and that he will offer concessions to
Republicans on tax cuts in return for passage of his Medicare
prescription drug proposal. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Another spending bill passes
Congress, with amendments on gun suits. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-SPENDING (Washington) _ Spending on prescription drugs
increased a record 17.4 percent last year, with elderly people
experiencing the largest cost increases, a new study by a drug
benefits company says. The study comes during a week in which the
House is expected to vote on proposals to help provide prescription
drug coverage to Medicare benificiaries. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ The judge in the Wen Ho Lee case
hears a request from defense to suppress evidence gathered at Lee's
house last year on grounds that the warrant was not specific
enough. The defense also intends to file a motion supporting its
argument that Lee was selectively prosecuted and that Los Alamos
used racial profiling in its investigations of suspected
counter-intelligence. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ The Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez
are expected to file an appeal to the Supreme Court Monday, in an
effort to keep him from being allowed to return to Cuba on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore's campaign day.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IMMIG (Washington) _ George W. Bush, who says he's ``a
different kind of Republican,'' is working this week to convince
voters of that with speeches to Hispanic and black audiences and
promotion of welfare-to-work programs. In a speech Monday to the
League of United Latin American Citizens, the Republican
presidential contender and Texas governor planned to propose
splitting the Immigration and Naturalization Service into an agency
that welcomes new immigrants and another that strictly enforces the
nation's borders. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATOINAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-IRA (Dublin) _ In a gesture toward peace in Northern
Ireland, the IRA has for the first time opened its arms dumps to
independent inspection, two international monitors said on Monday.
By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ASSESS (Tokyo) _ A news analysis: Just when many seemed
ready to begin writing off Japan's democracy as hopelessly
moribond, the huge advance made Sunday by an opposition party once
seen as hapless has awakened the country to the possibility of
political change. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-ASSAD (Beirut, Lebanon) _ The Syrian parliament will
anoint Bashar Assad on Monday as sole presidential candidate. Plus
a look at the speedy succession, not even waiting for the 40-day
mourning period to end. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ The day after a Russian general says
that Russia will stop bombing and artillery attacks in Chechnya,
the Kremlin says they will continue. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ELECT (Harare) _ Developments in the weekend
parliamentary election. Results unlikely to be available. By Rachel
Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-POLAND (Warsaw) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
at democracy conference as part of a three-day visit to Poland. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-FATIMA (Rome) _ The Vatican released the text of the
Third Secret of Fatima, aiming to discourage any more speculation
about the last message that three Portuguese shepherd children said
they received from the Virgin Mary in 1917. The Vatican insisted it
is no doomsday prophecy as many have feared, but can be read as a
message of encouragement that humanity can save itself. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SKIMPY-FASHION (New York) _ Noontime in Manhattan, and the
strap-style T-shirt brigade is out. Though it may not come as news
to people in the fashion industry, or even to women who take their
cues about modesty and skirt lengths from television programs like
``Sex and the City,'' there has been a conspicuous change in the
sartorial landscape around Manhattan in the past two summers.
What's more, say retailers and social observers, this change isn't
confined to trendy urbanites and runway-ready 20-somethings. By
Leslie Kaufman and Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED (Washington) _ Economists generally think the Federal
Reserve's Open Market Committee is unlikely to push interest rates
higher at its two-day meeting that begins on Tuesday. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
