<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PYPER-BOS &LR;      06-26 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PYPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREW PYPER TAKES MURDER INTO VERY DEEP WATERS, INDEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
LOST GIRLS 
By Andrew Pyper. Delacorte Press. 388 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know what's more seductive about ``Lost Girls,'' author
Andrew Pyper's scabrously witty, darkly musical language or the
psychological pull of his plot. Then again, perhaps the chief
attraction is Pyper's imploding protagonist and narrator,
Bartholomew Crane, a spectacularly and mercilessly misanthropic
defense lawyer. Law school, Crane explains early in the book, ``was
the discovery of religion, albeit a godless one, with its Latin
prayers and shifting, manufactured convictions. Belief the weight
of the air in your lungs.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes so well that his dazzling word work _ reminiscent of
Martin Amis's _ occasionally draws attention to itself and briefly
away from the story. But this is less complaint than compliment:
The solution is to blink away the flashbulb effect and move on,
invariably with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, this is a mystery story about the murder of two
high school girls in Murdoch, Ontario, allegedly by a peculiar
English teacher named Thom Tripp. Crane is dispatched from his
Toronto law office for his first effort at a solo defense. In the
far-northern, rain-sodden town, he holes up in a hideous hotel
room, scarfing up cocaine and papering the walls with case notes
and photos of Ashley and Krystal, the dead girls. Crane is
determined to free the freaky teacher, guilty or not, despite the
circumstantial evidence that he lured the girls to nearby Lake St.
Christopher and drowned them.
</P>
<P>
   This is a novel of depth, a fully literary piece of fiction
that, while tremendously entertaining, is not merely an
entertainment. Remarkably, it is Pyper's maiden novel, first
published last spring in his native Canada, where it was, no
surprise at all, a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Pyper makes Crane's hatefulness intoxicating, exploiting it for
a number of overlapping purposes. Among them is wickedly funny
social criticism. A self-styled city slicker, Crane has an urbanely
Canadian distaste for wilderness. Driving up to Murdoch, he
observes that it is a ``place where the ratio of altered to
unaltered space gets shifted dramatically in the latter's favor and
there is little more ahead than an interminable expanse of
humanless.'' He loathes the Murdoch provincials, and his loathing
captures some of Western culture's cheesy TV-induced decline.
``People,'' he notes, ``know the psychologies of serial killers
better than their own these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Crane's ranting misanthropy yields insights into the larger
world but rarely into himself. But that will change. The case of
the lost girls, and a photo of them he pinched from a grieving
parent, ``their eyes staring back at me,'' begin to haunt Crane. So
does the murky decades-old legend of the Lady of the Lake. The
mother of two beautiful girls, she seems to have lived in the
surrounding woods, often surrendering herself to local townsmen
before a mob drove her onto the thin lake ice to watch her drop
through and die. Her spirit is said to lure young girls to a watery
grave.
</P>
<P>
   Crane is a kind of captive of the lake and the murders. The lake
pulls at him like a magnet, drawing him to its tangled shores,
where we discover that his long-dead parents had a cottage, now a
rotting ruin. He befriends the local librarian, a shrewd, sociable
dwarf with the Dickensian name of Pittle, who supplies him with
detailed local lore. The more he hungrily learns, the more fevered
become his drug-induced nightmares. Thus, Pyper engages the deeper
and more engrossing mystery in ``Lost Girls,'' the unraveling state
of Bartholomew Crane, the erosion of the defense lawyer's fortress
of self-defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Why would this cold, clever legal mechanic lose the thrill of
the courtroom kill? Why begin to turn on his diffident, wacko
client Tripp while seeing in him a twisted reflection of himself?
Why break out into the kind of moral sweat he hasn't experienced
since boyhood?
</P>
<P>
   Pyper brilliantly draws Crane toward a confrontation with his
past, a reckoning with long-repressed events that forged a young
man determined ``to wipe his hands clean of himself forever.''
There is nothing melodramatic about the halting, healing
transformation that begins as the novel ends. In the process, aptly
but still somewhat disappointingly, Pyper's prose loses its
ferocious edge. But one of many compensations is a scene of
piercing humanity that faintly, peculiarly echoes the surpassing
tenderness at the end of ``The Grapes of Wrath.'' Crane ministers
to an injured deer he sees on a roadside, cradling the creature's
head in his lap and, while gawkers speed by, comforting it while it
dies. ``Then something lifts from its skin and passes through me
before dispersing into the darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a book abounding with spirits _ mostly demonic but a few
redemptive, angelic ones, too _ and more than incidental insight
into human frailty and resourcefulness. It's also compulsively
readable and, more often than not and for all its seriousness of
purpose, downright funny. First novelist Pyper isn't a writer who's
going somewhere _ he's already arrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
