<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUMAN GENOME &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is devoting 42 columns, almost its entire
Science Times section, to stories, graphics and photos on the human
genome announcement.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Washington) _ Ledeall: President Clinton and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair joined scientists from around the world
Monday in announcing the completion of a working draft of the
instructions to make a human being. Clinton described the mapping
of the human genome as ``the most important, most wondrous map ever
produced by humankind,'' at a White House press conference linked
by satellite to Blair in London. They were responding to the
announcement by scientists that they had unravelled 97 percent of
the human genetic code, and 85 percent of the data had been
assembled in the right sequence. Hailing what it called a landmark
in knowledge, the international public consortium spearheaing the
research, the Human Genome Project said it had ``assembled a
working draft of the human genome _ the genetic blueprint for a
human being.'' (Summary from wires) By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With a PRIMER graphic, an illustrated glossary of genetic terms.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis: The genome is
long; it is pithy. It is a pigsty, bulging with nongenes and viral
detritus; it is a pearl, a model of high performance and
reliability. In short, the human genome exults in contradictions.
By Natalie Angier. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-NEXT (Undated) _ We have our genetic alphabet; now we
have to learn how to read. The sequencing of the genome is bringing
us new industries like bioinformatics and functional genomics, and
new technologies like gene expression chips. It forms the basis of
developing a human encyclopedia, a comprehensive reference on how
to build a human being. And it has the potential to bring about
many social changes that could perplex and convulse society. By
Nicholas Wade (2500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With NEXT graphic, laying out the new worlds of research.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-MEDICINE (Undated) _ How medicine has already
benefited from the genome project. By Kenneth Chang. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-MENTAL (Undated) _ The search for genes linked to
mental illness shows how difficult it will be to decipher the
causes of complex diseases, both mental and physical, like
schizophrenia and diabetes. By Erica Goode (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-HISTORY (Undated) _ The history of the genome,
largely through the eyes of James Watson, who with Francis Crick
discovered DNA's double helix nearly 50 years ago, and who prodded
the government into trying to decode every last letter. By Nicholas
Wade. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With TIMELINE graphic, an elaborate charting of milestones from
Mendel to Watson/Crick to the Age of the Genome.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-VENTER (Undated) _ A profile of Dr. J. Craig Venter,
the maverick president of Celera who entered the gates late and
nearly galloped off with the entire racetrack. By Nicholas Wade.
(900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-SKETCHES (Undated) _ Thumbnail sketches on Michael
Hunkapiller, who invented the sequencing machines that made all
this possible; Hamilton Smith, the Nobel laureate and chief
scientific collaborator; and Gene Myers, the eccentric master
mathematician.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-COLLINS (Undated) _ A profile of Dr. Francis Collins,
head of the NIH's National Human Genome Research Institute, the
geneticist who had to develop different skills to goad the bulky
consortium into meeting Celera's challenge. By Nicholas Wade. (600
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-CONSORT (Undated) _ Thumbnail sketches of three other
leading consortium scientists: John Sulston, Eric Lander and Robert
Waterston.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-WHO (Undated) _ Whose genomes were decoded and why it
doesn't matter. By Nicholas Wade. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-FUTURE (Undated) _ Francis Collins forecasts the
genomics future. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
