<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-RUSSIA-ROCK-BOS     06-26 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-RUSSIA-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ROCK BANDS FIND THEIR OWN VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It is midnight and air is at a premium at the popular
Moscow nightspot known as the Chinese Pilot Zhao-Da. Something
resembling trench warfare has broken out between security and the
patrons in the front row, who are being pushed inexorably toward
the tiny stage by the constant flow of more fans into the cramped
cellar venue. Cigarettes and body heat have overwhelmed the lone
air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   But no one seems to mind. As they slowly swelter in the stifling
pall, several hundred young Muscovites groove to the band's
ominous, thumping beat. Everyone knows all the words.
</P>
<P>
   The act this night is B-2, probably the world's only rock group
with roots in Moscow, Melbourne, and Minsk. More important, this
band is a prime example of everything that is right about Russian
rock 'n' roll at the moment. They play intelligent, well-crafted
music. They sing in Russian. They perform well live. And they play
out a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Just seven hours before the midnight set at the Chinese Pilot,
B-2 had waited out a severe downpour in a tent on an airfield to
perform in front of 30,000 freezing, soaked Muscovites as part of
Wings, a 12-hour rock marathon featuring 15 groups from around the
former Soviet Union. Out of the hailstorm, into the Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeez, it's hot in here,'' Lyova B-2 remarks as he gulps down
bottled water in between songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyova, ty klyovy!'' someone rhymes back. Lyova, you are cool!
</P>
<P>
   Rock lives in Russia. Huge rock festivals, radio stations that
promote local groups, rock performers with the chops and popularity
to overcome the vagaries of the elements, and bands that come from
Kiev, Moldova, and Melbourne for the chance to play here: These are
all part of Russia's new rock revolution. None of it would have
been possible just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   B-2 breaks into ``No One Writes to the Colonel,'' one of its
signature radio hits, a moody techno-grunge anthem to alienation
based on the novel by Gabriel Garcia Marquez. The crowd sings along
with Lyova B-2's fluttering, angst-ridden vocals, then everyone
goes wild as guitarist Shura B-2's slow, booming solo rocks the
club like a small nuclear strike. By rights, we should all be
collapsing from asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   But no one seems to mind. Everything is klyovy. Rock 'n' roll. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Uniting and taking over &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just like London in 1964,'' says Max Lyubimov,
drive-time disc jockey on Nashe Radio, a station owned by Russian
uberoligarch Boris Berezovsky that plays only rock bands from
Russia and the other former Soviet republics. ``Suddenly, there are
groups that are taking over the charts, taking over the world. The
Russian-speaking world, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyubimov has a point. The headliners at last month's Maxidrom
festival, Mumy Troll from Russia's Pacific port city of
Vladivostok, and Zemfira, from the Volga region of Bashkortostan,
have the tunes and musical ability to play anywhere. But like the
other 13 bands at the Maxidrom, including two from Ukraine and one
from Moldova, they choose to sing in their native tongue. While
that approach just about rules out the possibility of a Russian
rock invasion of the West, it has filled a void in post-Soviet
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``First there was no place for bands to play out, but then as
clubs begin to appear, people slowly realized they didn't want
covers sung in foreign languages, they wanted original music,''
Lyubimov says. ``This is a natural process. Radio stations like
ours promote new bands. They become popular. It's like a
snowball.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Wings or Maxidrom festivals are any indication, it is an
eclectic snowball. How to explain the connection between Chaif, a
distinctly Russian rock quartet that is the Siberian answer to
Springsteen or Mellencamp, and Zdob si Zdub, a Moldovan quintet
whose members dress like a Bessarabian wedding orchestra and whose
music incorporates elements of Henry Rollins-style rock rap and
Gypsy romance?
</P>
<P>
   Roman Yagupov, Zdob si Zdub's hyperkinetic lead singer, has an
answer to that. The idea is live music, energy, and passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a Gypsy sings, his throat bleeds,'' Yagupov says during a
rambling conversation during a quieter moment at the Chinese Pilot.
``We just try to play what comes naturally. . . . If I want to sing
about my new sandals, I sing about my new sandals.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Zdob's lyrics are in Moldovan, and therefore are
incomprehensible to many Russians. But the beat is irresistible.
When the band plays at the Pilot, the crowd spills out into the
street. It's hard to believe that this kind of thing nearly died
from lack of interest in the mid-1990s. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rocking in the freer world &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Live rock music peaked in Russia in the late 1980s, as the dying
Soviet police state slowly relinquished its grip on popular
culture. Legendary Soviet-era groups such as Chaif, DDT, Aquarium,
and Voskresenye, once the voice of a generation that equated rock
'n' roll with freedom from the strictures of communism, found
themselves playing to diehard followers in half-full clubs.
</P>
<P>
   They were, in a way, victims of Russian capitalism. Newly
deregulated television and radio stations created a venue for local
music that was quickly filled by simple computer-generated pop,
whose purveyors lip-synched their way through carefully
choreographed ``concerts.'' All a recording artist needed to become
popular was a producer willing to bribe television stations into
playing the new video.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone liked it that way. Mikhail Kozyrev, a rock fanatic
who spent the early 1990s studying the radio business in
California, was shocked when he returned to Russia in 1994. Just
about the only quality music on the air was imported from the West.
Homegrown rock was nowhere to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I felt the horror of what was going on here,'' Kozyrev
said, ``I decided to try to re-create what we had in the 1980s. . .
. My mission is to even the balance between plastic culture and
real culture.''
</P>
<P>
   As program director for Radio Maximum, a Russian-American joint
venture, Kozyrev started giving air time to new local groups. Three
years later, as program director of Nashe Radio he made development
of new music the priority.
</P>
<P>
   It was Nashe Radio that broke B-2's first single, ``Barbara,''
last year, when the group was still in Melbourne, recording its
eponymous album. When B-2 arrived in Russia to tour, they were
amazed to find that ``Barbara'' and ``No One Writes to the
Colonel'' were hits.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyova B-2 and Shura B-2, who formed their band in Minsk,
Belarus, in the late 1980s before immigrating to Australia (and
changing their last names to the group name), are not surprised
that rock has come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``People demand live music,'' Lyova B-2 said in an interview at
Shura B-2's modest Moscow apartment. ``Concert tickets have become
expensive, and people are tired of those pop sounds . . . and rock
music has become commercially viable.''
</P>
<P>
   The band has been helped by promotions _ such as a contest run
by Russian MTV in which a high school won a B-2 concert on the last
day before summer vacation _ and the fact that ``No One Writes to
the Colonel'' is the featured song on the soundtrack to Russia's
big summer gangster hit, ``Brother-2''. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Say you don't want a revolution? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What has changed about Russian rock is that socially conscious
texts are no longer a prerequisite for popularity. The words to
B-2's moody, atmospheric music, which some listeners might find
similar to the Cure, deal with alienation and unrequited love.
</P>
<P>
   The theme is even simpler in ``Tu-lu-la,'' the punky power pop
hit sung by 21-year-old Yulya Chicherina, which, translated, goes:
``You left me for that lame redhead / My mama wouldn't let me come
back home / My heart aches and my head is locked up / All I have
left is to sing what the wind blew in: Tu-la-lu-la.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that Russian rock is no longer about rebellion; it's
just that the scope has changed. Chicherina _ Yulya's surname is
the group's name _ is the definitive garage band. Yulya was
rejected by her neighborhood's youth choir because she couldn't
sing. ``So I just sang and yelled until I could,'' she says. With
no place to play, the group had to open their own club in an
abandoned building in her native city, Yekaterinburg. The scene was
very klyovy, but the group feuded with tax police and sanitary
officials until the makeshift club was closed down.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the band, known simply as Chicherina, learned
how to play live, if a tight, recent acoustic set in Moscow's
Respublika Beefeater club was any indication.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Tu-lu-la'' is best experienced as a video, for anyone who
believes that seeing the singer screaming from the hood of a
speeding car in winter, clad in only a wedding dress and slathered
in bear fat to protect against the subzero chill, is a good thing
for a nation's psychological well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Romanov, the singer-guitarist of Voskresenye, does. He
has seen it go the other way, from 1983 to 1990, when his band was
blacklisted by Soviet censors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening now is great by comparison,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
