<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-STING-BOS &LR;      06-26 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STING IS DELIGHTED TO BE ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they grow older, many pop acts hate to tour. They may still
enjoy making albums, but often treat touring with the same shudder
as a trip to the tax man. British superstar Sting, however, is an
exception. He has been on the road since the fall and still has
another year of shows to promote his latest CD, the Grammy-winning
``Brand New Day.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's just getting warmed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the road. I'm surrounded by guys I've worked with for
20 years who are all good at their jobs and give me a lot of
support,'' Sting says in a recent phone interview from Vienne,
France, where he's playing an ``antique Roman theater where I feel
a bit like a gladiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we're like English pirates _ latter-day English
pirates,'' adds Sting.
</P>
<P>
   Sting loves the road because it also provides a break from
fretting about his next musical direction, he admits. After a
career that has moved from his '80s rock years with the Police, to
seven solo albums that have spanned everything from stylish jazz to
leftist protest music to story songs and country honky-tonk, Sting
understandably has a lot of options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm touring for another year largely so I can avoid asking the
question of what is my next move,'' he says with a laugh. ``That's
the hardest question in my life, so touring postpones looking at a
blank page, wondering what to write.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many counterparts, especially U2, Sting does not write on
the road, nor does he have a portable studio with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little like being a sportsman,'' he says of his own
approach. ``You play the strokes every day. You don't think too
much, which is another one of its attractions. When I'm making a
record, I have to actually use my brain, which hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Sting listen to much music on the road. Whereas, say,
Adam Clayton of U2 brings out a huge stereo system and a
mountainous stack of CDs to listen to, Sting takes the opposite
tack. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Always analyzing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the road, I spend so many hours of the day playing
music that the last thing I want to do in my downtime is listen to
music. I tend to just want to be quiet and get myself together,''
he says. ``And whatever I hear, I have to analyze it. If I hear
music in the elevator, I'm cursed to have to analyze it, so there's
really no such thing as background music for me. I rarely sit down
and relax to music.''
</P>
<P>
   As for not writing on the road, he says, ``I avoid it unless
some idea occurs to me or some metaphor I think can be worked on.
But I tend to avoid even that, and then hope at the end of the tour
on my downtime that I'll be able to remember what has occurred to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   These are heady days for Sting, whose ``Brand New Day'' album
started slowly in the charts, but has since risen to, and stayed,
at Top 20 or Top 30 status virtually worldwide. His Grammy success
was a big help, but so is word-of-mouth among consumers looking for
an adult alternative to the ubiquitous boy bands, angry
hard-rockers, and chest-beating rappers who dominate the charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my albums sort of reveal themselves slowly,'' says
Sting. ``And I think that's good for longevity. . . . Long may it
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   While sometimes viewed as the quintessential English worrywart,
Sting surprised many fans with the optimism that runs through
``Brand New Day,'' starting with the title track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very aware of the millennium coming up,'' he says. ``I
was very keen that this record would be optimistic and would be a
positive look at the future, and I think that's largely true. The
record isn't all happy songs _ there are sad songs _ but generally
the trend of the album is positive.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the ``Brand New Day'' image, Sting says, ``It's not the
most original title in the world, I'll give you that. But it does
have a very direct, simple optimism. When I began this record, I
had no intention of dealing with the millennium in any way, but it
just kind of seeped into the work. And then to perform (`Brand New
Day') on top of the Rockefeller Center as the ball dropped on New
Year's Eve, was an amazing scenario. I couldn't have planned a
better scenario for the song.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Concert repertoire &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sting is performing ``about 80 percent'' of the latest album in
concert, along with various solo hits and highlights of his Police
career, including ``Every Breath You Take'' and ``Every Little
Thing She Does Is Magic.'' He remains, however, opposed to a Police
reunion, despite public demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very flattered that people are interested, and obviously
there's a great deal of affection for the band,'' he says. ``I'm
glad the legend is intact and that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the public also wonders when Sting might issue a
boxed set, either from his solo career or combined with Police
material. But don't hold your breath for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, a boxed set sounds like I haven't got any new ideas. If
I haven't got any ideas, I don't want to put anything out,'' he
says. ``I'll be quiet. Trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not like Sting has an endless vault of previously
unreleased songs to put on a boxed set. He usually just writes
enough tunes for an album, then hits the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, if I write 10 songs, that's it, I'm finished,'' he
says. ``I mean, some writers just keep writing and have 60 to 70
songs on the back burner. Not me. Get me on the road quick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
