outside the Texas prison in Huntsville last week. Yet, the separate
groups were divided by a world of difference. (Joe Murray, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ ``Got any rhubarb?'' Gene
is asking Cal as I pick up my morning cup of decaf and take it to
the empty seat between them. ``I'll trade you lettuce for some
rhubarb.'' Cal squints, nods and smiles. Being a newcomer, Gene
thinks this means he's got himself a deal but that's not it. It
means Cal hasn't heard a word Gene's saying. (Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Everyone knows children get bored
in the summertime. It's part of what summer is about: free time,
few scheduled activities, letting the mind rest. When you get to
middle age, we call that a vacation and are darned grateful for it.
</P>
<P>
   Boredom in children may be annoying (especially to parents), but
it usually isn't a signal to a bigger problem. In adults, however,
it can be. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
