<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      06-26 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW CHALLENGE LURES SCHOOL CHIEF FROM SEAT OF NATIONAL POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was the worst high school in a deeply troubled
district.
</P>
<P>
   Located in a neighborhood where taxi drivers refuse to go,
Ballou Senior High saw eight of its students murdered in one school
year.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting the sprawling school, District of Columbia school
chief Arlene Ackerman had an idea that surprised many: Get
President Clinton to visit Ballou. In January, the president did
just that. Ballou students had the polish and politeness of prep
schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman, who is leaving her post as the District's
superintendent to take over the San Francisco school system on Aug.
1, is motivated by inequities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In everything I do and see, I ask whether it's equitable for
all children,'' Ackerman said. ``My job is not about making adults
happy. I have little patience for adult issues that get in the way
of children.''
</P>
<P>
   After observing Ackerman in her daily routine last week, and
after interviews with her and with parents, teachers and community
activists who have worked with her since her arrival at the
district in late 1997, this much is clear: The flurry of changes
large and small made by this superintendent suggest change is
coming to San Francisco schools.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ackerman's toughest critics, who say she did not do enough
to enhance educational opportunities for students, acknowledge she
has done more than any superintendent in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has put many good things in place but it remains to be
seen whether most will work out,'' said Mary Levy, a lawyer with
the advocacy group Parents United. ``Managerially, the system is
only slightly better than when she took over. But that's not her
specialty. What has happened is the steady decline in student test
scores has not only stopped, but scores are up for the third year
in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman's programs, aimed at improving student performance,
included establishing large-scale Saturday and summer school
programs that focus on math and reading; creating a
performance-based system to reward, sanction or dismiss teachers
and principals; giving individual schools control over their
budgets; and creating a funding formula to ensure a more equitable
distribution of money based on enrollment and student needs.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman, 53, also examined spending practices with a magnifying
glass, school by school, employee by employee. ``There were
hundreds of people who were employed but weren't working,'' said
Ackerman who, with her staff, pressed the District's 146 school
principals to ferret out unproductive workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gained respect because I was so willing to be involved at
very detailed levels,'' Ackerman said. ``I wanted to know, down to
the last penny, how money is being spent.''
</P>
<P>
   She plans to do the same analysis of the San Francisco Unified
School District, which has been shaken by reports of fiscal
mismanagement and lack of oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very involved in that in my first six months in San
Francisco,'' Ackerman said. ``I'll bring some of my own people and
I'll solicit help from the business community. I want the community
to see and know where the money is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman's deputy superintendent in Washington, Elois Brooks,
said, ``People think Arlene is all nice and that I'm the tough one,
but she's as tough as nails. She has very little patience for
incompetent people. And she doesn't tolerate people who are
disloyal.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is considering joining Ackerman in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman, who will be the first woman and first black to
permanently lead California's fifth largest school district, is at
once compassionate and no-nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   She is disinterested in politics but adept at brokering deals
and making allies. She greets employees by first name and asks
about family members. She has fired more than 600 central office
and other employees in Washington's schools. To relax, she listens
to Motown or jazz, reads murder mysteries or shops at Neiman
Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an insatiable sweet tooth, she has the discipline to
limit herself to one chocolate chip cookie a day.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, David Ackerman, an elementary school principal, has
moved with her from Seattle, where she was chief academic officer
in the public schools, to Washington. And he will move again to San
Francisco, although he will look for a job outside the district,
saying of his wife, ``She can only be my boss at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman is a workaholic with a perfectionist streak. Wherever
she goes, business-as-usual ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go where the challenge is,'' Ackerman said over dinner at
the Willard Hotel, a Washington institution that is a stone's throw
from the White House. ``When I came here, everything was in a
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of District students read well below
grade level. Chronic maintenance problems and fire safety issues
routinely delayed the first day of classes. Because of bitter
political infighting and convoluted layers of oversight of the
school district, three superintendents were hired, fired or
resigned in the five years prior to Ackerman's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to Washington, Ackerman had worked in Seattle as a
top administrator and in St. Louis as a teacher and principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In D.C., politics is everything and everyone wanted a stake in
running the school system,'' said Maudine Cooper, who headed an
emergency board of trustees appointed by a federal control board,
named in part to save the nation's capital from bankruptcy, to
oversee the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, now president of the Greater Washington Urban League,
added, ``Arlene wasn't perfect. She wasn't always right. But, for
Arlene, it wasn't, `Is this in the best interest of the mayor? Of
the teachers? Of the Board of Education?' It was always, `Is this
in the best interest of children?''
</P>
<P>
   Although San Francisco Unified, with 64,000 students and a $550
million annual budget, is dogged by fiscal woes, having a hard time
keeping track of such basics as cash flow, the 70,000-student
District of Columbia school system, with a $650 million annual
budget, is in another league both academically and economically.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like this school district to prepare you for
anything,'' Cooper said. ``Arlene is coming out of the toughest
superintendent's job in the nation. San Francisco is going to
benefit from her work here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ackerman's knowledge of reforming a large and troubled
district will serve her well in on the West Coast. She also will
take with her contacts in the Congress, White House and U.S.
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the power or politics that attracted Ackerman to
the nation's capital. In fact, the bitter politics surrounding the
District of Columbia schools is what drove her to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place that's alluring, that's about power and
influence,'' she said of the nation's capital, sitting in the back
seat of a Lincoln Town Car driven by a former bus driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``You meet people that others only see on TV,'' she said. ``Some
people say they will hold onto their job at any cost. They want to
hold onto the influence and the power. When you do that, you lose
your integrity. I've been clear about my mission. No matter what
anyone says, my integrity was never in question. I stayed focused
on children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
