<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-VIOLENT-FANS-HNS &LR;      06-26 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENT-FANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROFESSOR CORNERS THE SCIENCE OF HOOLIGANISM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jerry Lewis should be finished by now. That's
Jerry M. Lewis, professor of sociology at Kent State University,
not to be confused with the comedian, although the professor has
found himself in some nutty situations.
</P>
<P>
   He studies violent behavior by sports fans, and his material
never gets stale. England and Germany meet in a soccer match in
Belgium; hooligans trash a town square. Lakers win the NBA title;
police cars go up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis predicted the flare-up outside the Staples Center in Los
Angeles. He has discovered a formula for crowd combustion, and the
Lakers' win in Game 6 met three of the criteria. If a team takes
its first championship in more than 10 years, if the series goes
longer than a few games, and if the score of the final game is
close, there will be trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been doing research on this topic for 25 years. His
database records events back in the early 1960s. Celebratory riots
are not a recent phenomenon. They're not even, in Lewis' view, a
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   When a young man jumped on top of a news van in L.A. last Monday
night, stomped all over the roof, ripped off an antenna and waved
to the mob gathered on the ground, I saw a lunatic _ out of
control, probably under the influence of a six-pack. Lewis saw
academic theory come to life.
</P>
<P>
   He believes celebration riots allow fans to pretend they are
accomplishing something, too. ``The young man on top of the van was
looking for approval,'' Lewis said. ``When the crowd cheered, and
he got approval, he threw up his arms in a victory sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly like an athlete after a huge win. If someone with a
microphone could get close enough to ask what's next for the
rioters, they'd probably say: ``I'm going to Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't dunk like Shaq, and they can't shoot 3-pointers
like Reggie Miller,'' Lewis said. ``So they start a riot.''
</P>
<P>
   The perpetrators are overwhelmingly young, white males, he said.
They tend to be aimless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alienated from major social institutions, like work and
education'' is how Lewis describes them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losers'' is the term I prefer.
</P>
<P>
   But I have to agree with Lewis on one point. He calls the riots
``a feat of skill,'' at least in the tiny minds of the hoodlums.
And, I have to admit, there does seem to be some order amid the
chaos. During the early sky-cam footage from L.A., I saw a fire
with a band of people gathered around. The scene looked more
ritualistic than chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rioters aren't crazy,'' Lewis said. ``They're anti-social.''
</P>
<P>
   English soccer hooligans, in particular, operate like organized
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to start fights before matches, rather than
celebrating like vandals. There are Web sites for soccer fans,
advising them to travel to international matches under assumed
names. Lewis has heard of hooligans carrying walkie-talkies so they
can inform each other when an opposing group of fans is showing up.
Some of them have calling cards, identifying them as fans of a
certain club, that they leave behind to taunt their victims.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of premeditation, a lot of squandered energy. It
must seem particularly pointless to Lewis, who witnessed the
National Guard shootings at Kent State during a Vietnam War
protest. He stood 20 yards away from one of the young women who was
killed. Lewis wrote two books on the subject, then turned to the
mayhem provoked by sports.
</P>
<P>
   He is 63 now, and he says he always acts like a coward (read:
rationally) when he encounters hooligans. But he does do
front-line, first-hand research. He remembers a time in Dusseldorf,
Germany, when a fight broke out, and he ducked into a doorway,
where he was soon joined by a British marauder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Would you mind doing an interview?' and he looked
stunned,'' Lewis said. ``Here's someone with an American accent
asking him: Can we talk?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to these up-close-and-personals, Lewis can debunk some of
the bad theories about rioting. ``Alcohol,'' he said, ``the old
devil rum made me do it. That's just not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Booze may remove some inhibitions, but most of the rioters
already have intent to commit mayhem. Lewis has interviewed plenty
of hooligans with unadulterated breath and clear heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to talk to them after they've been arrested, and
their first questions are about the process, how much the fine
is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Lewis has no evidence that media attention prods the
perpetrators. In L.A., a big-screen TV set up outside the Staples
Center was blamed for attracting troublemakers to a common spot.
Lewis believes the rioting would have happened anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that wide screen probably won't return for any more
championship events, and that's a shame. There were plenty of
civilized fans outside the Staples Center, unable to buy tickets,
who deserved a chance to be close to their team on title night.
They'll be shut out further in the future, leaving the arena
exclusively to the swells.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis watched what happened in L.A. and concluded it was a very
mild episode. Celebration riots tend to be intense and brief, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The police probably did the right thing by keeping
ticket-holders and players inside the Staples Center and letting
the riot outside cool down on its own. Arrests only create more
tension, and Lewis has found that convictions are hard to come by.
The troublemakers show up in court a few weeks later in pressed
shirts and ties, and juries can't envision them as rampaging
vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Lewis for a solution, a vaccine against fan violence, and he
is stumped. All he can do is keep studying. ``I wish,'' he said,
``that I were putting myself out of business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
