<HEADLINE>
GIRL STUFF: NATASHA LYONNE CHANGES MODES FOR `BUT I'M A
CHEERLEADER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Natasha Lyonne with Clea DuVall in a
scene from ``But I'm a Cheerleader.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    ``First of all, it was kind of ridiculous for me to play a
cheerleader, because I'm so pale and so untoned,'' Natasha Lyonne
says. ``I don't even have the required big calves!''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Lyonne stars in the quirky comedy ``But I'm a
Cheerleader,'' opening throughout July nationwide. And, to hear her
tell it over breakfast at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel, it
wasn't a pretty sight.
 &HT;    ``I did all my own cheers,'' she says, wincing. ``I thought I
could do those stupid cartwheels, but I'm the most uncoordinated
person in America. And everyone saw this on the rushes. The word
went out _ I heard, `We need reshoots. Immediately! She's a
klutz!'''
 &HT;    Shy, petite and engulfed in a mass of long, blonde curls, the
21-year-old actress shakes her head sadly. After all, part of the
point in making the movie was to play the kind of role her fans
wouldn't expect her to tackle.
 &HT;    ``I took this part because everyone asks me, `Why do you only
choose these wisecracking roles?''' says Lyonne, who caught
Hollywood's eye as Woody Allen's sharp-tongued daughter in
``Everyone Says I Love You'' (1996), and copped some more attitude
as a sarcastic teen in ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' (1998). ``The new
movie is anything but that sort of girl.''
 &HT;    That's for sure. ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' casts Lyonne as a
naive, Christian cheerleader from a small town in middle America.
 &HT;    ``But she has Melissa Etheridge posters on her wall, and her
hands keep slipping up the other cheerleaders' skirts when she's
doing lifts,'' the actress says. ``And one day she comes home and
RuPaul is there, plus all her friends and family. They're doing an
intervention on her, because they think she's gay.''
 &HT;    Soon she's shipped off to a rehab camp to cure her suspected
lesbian proclivities.
 &HT;    ``These camps do exist,'' Lyonne says. ``I know it sounds kind
of ridiculous and very strange, but it's true. And, frankly, I
wanted to make the film to expose these places _ I think they're
frightening. At the very least, kids should know what's out
there.''
 &HT;    Kids will probably pay attention, as they have since Lyonne
broke out into mainstream movies with the teen hit ``American Pie''
(1999), which has grossed more than $100 million.
 &HT;    ``What happened with `American Pie' was pretty amazing,'' the
actress says. ``It's strange, because all of a sudden my name is on
the map. I'm supposed to be one of the leaders of young
Hollywood.''
 &HT;    She laughs.
 &HT;    ```Young Hollywood?' Like I'm leading this wild lifestyle?
Please!'' she says. ``Hey, I'm just a homebody who watches movies,
listens to music and reads. Seriously, that's all I do. I don't
even get out much. So it makes me laugh when I hear, `There's hot
buzz on you.'''
 &HT;    The plus side is increased respect within the Hollywood
community.
 &HT;    ``I don't feel so desperate when it comes to getting acting
jobs,'' she admits. ``I'm in a much cooler place in my own head.
Now I'm sent the good scripts _ finally I'm seeing the good
material.
 &HT;    ``It's so hard for any of us who really care about acting to
find good material,'' Lyonne says. ``That's the most frustrating
thing, because here I am _ I actually have some heat, and I feel
there is so little I can actually do with it.
 &HT;    ``I refuse to take my heat and go make some schlocky teen
romantic comedy,'' she adds firmly, ``which is the bulk of the
stuff I get offered. Most of those scripts are trash. And that's
not what I want to do.''
 &HT;    Even if it means walking away from some big paychecks.
 &HT;    ``I do feel the pressure to take the money and run,'' she
concedes. ``But I can't approach a career thinking about my bank
account.''
 &HT;    Hence her continued attraction to independent films,
 &HT;    ``Some of them might never see the light of day,'' she says.
``That's a bummer. But it does show that I have a range _ maybe
somebody will see one of these films and say, `Hey, let's really go
against type and cast her in a period movie.'''
 &HT;    Born and raised in New York, where she still lives, Lyonne was
only 7 when she won a role on ``Pee-Wee's Playhouse'' in 1986,
playing the curious little girl Opal.
 &HT;    ``It's the work I'm most proud of when I look back,'' the
actress says. ``Even at a young age, I really created a character.
In fact, I was really into acting even as a kid _ I was in Opal
mode all the time, and I would watch the show and critique my own
performances.
 &HT;    ``I still think I'm pretty good on that show.''
 &HT;    Even now, she fumes when she recalls how Paul ``Pee-Wee Herman''
Reubens' career was destroyed after his arrest for indecent
exposure in a Florida gay-movie theater.
 &HT;    ``I still think Paul got a raw deal,'' Lyonne says. ``It's such
BS. It's so ridiculous to think that actors shouldn't have a
private life.''
 &HT;    Lyonne went on to make her movie debut in ``Heartburn'' (1986)
as one of Meryl Streep's nieces, but her career didn't really take
off until Allen cast her in his musical, ``Everyone Says I Love
You.''
 &HT;    ``I spent my time sneaking out in the middle of the night to go
sit on the roof and listen to my Walkman. I was hiding out to smoke
cigarettes,'' she says, laughing. ``I would never smoke cigarettes
on the set, because I thought Woody would think I was a gross
bacteria machine.''
 &HT;    But she adds that Allen taught her a few good lessons.
 &HT;    ``Simple stuff he said kind of sticks with me on every movie,''
Lyonne says. ``He told me, `Just be funny and don't put the
audience to sleep.'''
 &HT;    Apparently it's working, because Lyonne is on some kind of a
roll. She even has fans now: As she leaves the Four Seasons, young
girls come over to ask Lyonne about her boyfriend, actor Edward
Furlong. Bashful boys hang around the outskirts, staring but afraid
to approach her.
 &HT;    Lyonne is sweet with the fans, patiently signing autographs and
smiling for snapshots.
 &HT;    ``Fans are cool,'' she says. ``I can't understand actors who
want to be totally left alone. When I'm out, I'll turn around and
one or two people will be following me.
 &HT;    ``Hey, it's not a mob scene,'' Lyonne says with a laugh. ``But
it's a start.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``But I'm a Cheerleader,''
consult the official Web site at www.butimacheerleader.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
