<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5329 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      06-26 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: TRICKS FOR RIDING OUT THE WAVES OF MOTION
SICKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've known since childhood that I was susceptible to motion
sickness. I never could read in the back seat of a car, and in my
early 20s I got queasy as a passenger riding down a winding
mountain road (though I was fine if I drove). But I hadn't
experienced the full-blown syndrome until I took my sons on a
fishing boat in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   We left at noon and I hadn't had time for lunch. As the boat
rocked over the waves, I tried fishing from the side. As if that
were not enough to flip my insides out, I had to go below deck to
use the facilities. Upon returning to my rod, I fed the fish the
remains of my breakfast. I spent the rest of the expedition lying
flat on the top deck.
</P>
<P>
   It is small compensation to anyone feeling motion sick to know
they are hardly alone. Up to 90 percent of the population is
susceptible, given adequate stimulus. Lawrence of Arabia got sick
bouncing about on his camel, and Charles Darwin's discovery of
natural selection is said to have resulted in part because he was
so seasick he had to get off the boat onto those islands. I've
encountered any number of people who refuse to travel anywhere by
boat because they once became seasick and can't bear the thought
that it may happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Motion sickness is the result of a conflict between messages
delivered to the brain, with one signal coming from the inner ear
that controls balance and a disparate signal coming from the eyes
and pressure receptors of the skin and joints. The conflicting
messages are delivered to the nausea center of the brain. This is
why reading in a moving vehicle is such a common precipitant of
motion sickness; eyes are focused on a page while the body is being
bounced and turned on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Though infants are spared, children between the ages of 2 and 12
are often susceptible, but tend to do better as they get older.
Dogs, too, are often affected, especially as puppies. Even fish can
get seasick. Adults over 50 are least likely to become motion sick.
I love traveling with a 61-year-old friend who can read guide books
and road maps while I drive.
</P>
<P>
   Genetics plays a role in susceptibility. In a study of various
ethnic groups by Dr. Robert Stern and Dr. Kenneth Koch at
Pennsylvania State University's Hershey Medical Center,
Asian-American children topped the charts; 100 percent of them
became nauseated when a rotating drum created the illusion of
motion, and many requested an early end to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Genetics notwithstanding, there are any number of nonmedical
measures you can take to reduce your susceptibility to motion
sickness. First and foremost, take a tip from pregnant women with
morning sickness and eat something before traveling. A light,
starchy meal beforehand with periodic snacks on route of something
like bread or crackers is best for sustaining a normal blood sugar.
Starting the night before travel, avoid eating a heavy meal or one
high in fat and refrain from carbonated beverages, alcohol and
spicy foods. While traveling, avoid tobacco smoke and pungent food
smells.
</P>
<P>
   Locate yourself where there is the least motion. If at all
possible, ride in the front seat of the car and look straight
ahead. Or, better yet, drive yourself. The message entering through
your eyes and pressure receptors will better match the one from the
inner ear.
</P>
<P>
   On a plane, select a window seat over the wing. On a ship,
select a cabin in the center of the boat but spend as much time as
possible in a well-ventilated area. Sit on the deck facing forward
and watch the horizon. Try to avoid going below deck, where
everything looks static.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, lie down and close your eyes. Whatever you
do, avoid watching the waves or fast-moving scenery.
</P>
<P>
   While some of us can read with comfort in a moving vehicle (for
example, I can usually read without problems while riding in the
front seat on a smooth, straight highway without stop-and-go
traffic), those most prone to motion sickness should refrain from
reading. Listen to music, look straight ahead or sleep when you're
not driving.
</P>
<P>
   Both ancient and modern medicine can offer effective assistance
if the above measures are not enough to forestall motion sickness.
Ginger, long recognized as a gastrointestinal calmative, has been
shown in controlled studies to be very helpful, even for carsick
dogs and children. It has helped my dog, a neighbor's dog and my
sons and I found it helpful on rocky seas in the Galapagos, both on
the boat and while snorkeling.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger should be taken as a capsule or coated tablet to avoid
esophageal irritation. Various over-the-counter versions of ginger
capsules are sold in health food stores and pharmacies. One tablet
product, Queeze-Eze (the manufacturer is in DeBary, Fla.,
904-774-5277), contains several nutrients and fruit enzymes that
are said to prevent irritation and enhance quick action. The only
reported side effect of ginger is an occasional ginger-flavored
burp.
</P>
<P>
   Another modern version of an ancient remedy takes advantage of
the Nei-kuan acupressure point on the wrist. It lies between the
two tendons on the underside of the wrist two finger widths past
the main crease where the hand meets the arm. Stimulating this
point can prevent morning sickness as well as motion sickness, and
this remedy has absolutely no side effects and is safe for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   I first encountered the acupressure technique on a trip to the
Antarctic. As we crossed the infamous Drake Passage, the whole ship
was flattened except for one woman who sat on the deck reading. She
was wearing Sea-Bands, one on each wrist. They resemble elasticized
bracelets with a plastic button in the inner side that is aligned
to press against the Nei-kuan acupressure point.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Bands and several imitators are sold in pharmacies, health
food stores and travel shops. A pair costs $10 to $15. Another
product, called Acu-Band, has an adjustable wrist strap. It is sold
by Traveler's Checklist in Sharon, Conn., for $12.95 plus $2 for
shipping, (860) 364-0144.
</P>
<P>
   Much more expensive though possibly more effective is an
electronic version called ReliefBand, available from the Woodside
Biomedical order department in South Bend, Ind., (800) 973-0378. By
means of a three-volt lithium battery, it transmits an electrical
signal through the skin to the nerve underlying the Nei-kuan point.
</P>
<P>
   In studies it has been 90 percent effective in preventing nausea
and vomiting from many causes, including chemotherapy. It is safe
for everyone except those with cardiac pacemakers. Three
nonprescription versions are available, a 48-hour disposable
($49.95), a 144-hour disposable ($95.95) and a reusable ($164.50),
plus shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   In the drug department, there are over-the-counter
antihistamines, including Dramamine, Bonine and Marezine. Among the
choices, Dramamine is most likely to cause drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   The most potent of remedies, Transderm Scop, is available only
by prescription. After a four-year hiatus to enhance effectiveness,
this patch containing scopalamine is back on the market. One patch
placed behind the ear is effective for three days.
</P>
<P>
   The most common side effect is dry mouth. Other possible adverse
effects include drowsiness, temporary blurring of vision and,
infrequently, disorientation, memory loss, restlessness, dizziness
and hallucinations.
</P>
<P>
   It should not be used by anyone who drinks alcohol, women who
are pregnant or nursing or those with glaucoma. Consult your doctor
if you have a metabolic, liver or kidney disease or trouble
urinating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
