<HEADER>
A5333 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     06-26 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GRATEFUL MEMORY OF THOSE WHO FLEW THEIR FINAL FLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, England _ When the United States entered World War II
_ although it had been brought into the war by an attack on Pearl
Harbor by the Japanese _ the United States and its allies quickly
agreed that Germany was the more dangerous of the aggressors they
faced and should be dealt with first.
</P>
<P>
   There were four strategic objectives to prosecuting the war,
says a brief history written by the American Battle Monuments
Commission. All four required the effective use of Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Those objectives included keeping sea lanes open between the
United States and Great Britain; supporting other nations warring
against the Axis powers, including the opening of second fronts in
Africa and Italy to relieve pressure on the Soviet Union;
conducting intensive aerial bombardment of Germany; and launching
an invasion of the European continent across the English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these objectives, the south of England eventually
became an armed camp, piled high with supplies of war and with men
waiting to enter the ground war against Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The flat land in the south was perfect for airstrips from which
British and American bombers would conduct the war in the air _ the
British bombing by night and the Americans bombing by day.
</P>
<P>
   The land also was suitable for a grim byproduct of war.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge University donated 30.5 acres three miles west of the
town in 1943 so that the Americans could establish a temporary
military cemetery for those who lost their lives. It later became
the only permanent American World War II military cemetery in the
British Isles, dedicated in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   It is a peaceful site _ with an elegant chapel, sweeping green
lawns, a reflecting pool and the crosses _ occasionally mixed with
a Star of David _ spreading out row on row from a central flag pole
flying the Stars and Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the headstones represent multiple burials _ one of two
and one of three servicemen whose names are known but whose remains
could not be separately identified. There are 24 unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   There are 3,812 graves. And on a wall that stretches from the
entrance to the chapel are 5,126 names of Americans who also died
but whose bodies were never recovered or identified.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those buried or named here died in the Battle of the
Atlantic, or in the skies over Europe, or in training accidents in
the nearby countryside while they prepared to go to war.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Americans _ members of the choir at Broadway Baptist
Church on a tour of England _ visited the cemetery week before
last. Our English guide, Philip Baker, saw to it that we did.
</P>
<P>
   The chapel is lovely _ with the seals of the States of the
United States depicted in its windows. Its ceiling is tall, as
befits a memorial that serves primarily Army Air Forces dead.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling is painted blue, with faint clouds and American
aircraft of all types making a final flight accompanied by angels.
</P>
<P>
   On the ceiling is this inscription:
</P>
<P>
   ``In proud and grateful memory of those men of the United States
Army Air Force who from these friendly isles flew their final
flight and met their God. They knew not the hour the day nor the
manner of their passing. When far from home they were called to
join that heroic band of airmen who had gone before. May they rest
in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the visitors' center is a plaque given by a town in
England in gratitude to an American bomber crew that chose to ride
the plane into the ground _ and to death _ rather than let it crash
into the town.
</P>
<P>
   One of our number located the grave of a distant relative. All
of us read names of men we did not know _ and of one whom we did:
band leader Glenn Miller, who was lost over the English Channel on
Dec. 15, 1944, on a flight to a performance in Paris. It's
appropriate that there is no special treatment of his name _ it's
just one among thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the chapel, our choir gathered in a circle and sang two
verses of ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.'' Then we sang ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, as people wiped the tears from their eyes, someone said
that they were glad that we had come to this place.
</P>
<P>
   It's the least we could do, someone else said.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is vice president and editorial director for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
harral(at)star-telegram.com; (817) 390-7836; or P.O. Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
