w a BC-SHANNON-ELIZABETH-IN-     06-26 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANNON-ELIZABETH-IN-SCARY-MOVIE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCARY' TACTICS: SHANNON ELIZABETH REACHES FOR STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Shannon Elizabeth with Regina Hall and
Anna Faris in a scene from ``Scary Movie.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Not so long ago, Shannon Elizabeth was a teen-ager pretty much
like most others. One night she was sitting at home alone, glued to
the television, watching the creepy horror film ``He Knows You're
Alone'' (1981).
 &HT;    A light in the back yard suddenly blew out.
 &HT;    ``It scared the crap out of me!'' Elizabeth recalls, whooping at
the memory. ``I couldn't move from the chair until my parents came
home.
 &HT;    ``After that I was always a fan of horror movies,'' she says.
``I just like them.''
 &HT;    Fast-forward a few years. Elizabeth is 23 now, and enjoying some
Hollywood buzz for her role as a sexually uninhibited exchange
student in the surprise hit ``American Pie'' (1999). She's
leveraged that buzz into her own stab at the horror genre _ or,
actually, into a jab at the horror genre, since her current film,
``Scary Movie,'' is a spoof of the likes of ``Scream'' (1996),
which was originally titled ``Scary Movie,'' and ``I Know What You
Did Last Summer'' (1997).
 &HT;    Elizabeth plays Buffy, a blissfully stupid high-school student
who wears impossibly short skirts and just might be the next victim
of a vicious masked murderer with a habit of telephoning his
victims before filleting them with a fishing gaff. Director Keenen
Ivory Wayans overlooks no cliche and gleefully indulges in sick
jokes, gruesome violence, foul language and nudity _ even male
nudity.
 &HT;    Still, the idea of mocking the ``Scream'' movies, which were
themselves self-referential parodies of the horror genre, seems a
tad redundant. But Elizabeth, speaking by telephone from the
Manhattan offices of Dimension Films, doesn't see it that way.
 &HT;    ```Scream' and all of those movies took themselves very
seriously,'' she says. ``When the characters were supposed to be
scared, they were very scared. In `Scary Movie,' when the killer
comes around, we're like, `Ooh, we're so scared.'
 &HT;    ``We're very sarcastic and very spoofy in that sense,'' she
says. ``We didn't take anything seriously. We didn't take each
other seriously.''
 &HT;    Three minutes into a conversation with Elizabeth, it's obvious
that, while her character may be stupid, she herself is one smart
cookie. It's also clear that she takes her career very seriously,
which made playing Buffy all the more a kick for the exotic-looking
actress, the daughter of a Syrian/Lebanese father and a mother
whose mixed descent includes Native American blood.
 &HT;    ``It was so not me in high school,'' says Elizabeth, who was
born in Houston and grew up in Waco, Texas. ``I'm just not a ditzy
person, so I was a little worried that I wasn't quite doing it
right.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to do Buffy justice,'' she explains. ``I couldn't be
too big with it, and I didn't have to be myself, I didn't have to
be serious. I could just go overboard and have fun.''
 &HT;    Elizabeth landed her ``Scary Movie'' role after ``American
Pie,'' the surprisingly clever gross-out comedy in which she turned
heads _ and turned on millions of guys _ with her va-va-voom
portrayal of Nadia, the nubile and willing Czechoslovakian exchange
student.
 &HT;    The film pushed the envelope for pastry eroticism and offended
more than a few viewers, but pleased enough to take in more than
$100 million at the box office. In the process, it steered Mena
Suvari, Chris Klein, Jason Biggs and Elizabeth herself into the
fast lane to stardom.
 &HT;    ``When we were doing it, we loved the script and the directors
and everybody involved with it, but I don't think anybody knew what
it would do in general, much less for each one of us,'' says
Elizabeth, a former model and commercial actress whose previous
experience had been limited to television guest spots and
independent features. ``It was released at the right time. We were
in the right place at the right time.
 &HT;    ``Everything just went right.''
 &HT;    Her new fame doesn't seem to faze the young actress, who lives
in Los Angeles with her boyfriend, Joe Reitman, and seven dogs.
It's fun to be recognized, she says, and to sign autographs and
glam it up at premieres and awards shows.
 &HT;    Still, it has its awkward moments. One time, as she was leaving
a premiere, fans and photographers pounced on her car. On another
occasion, a man showed up on Elizabeth's doorstep, magazine in
hand, requesting an autograph.
 &HT;    ``Just the fact that he found us scared my boyfriend to death,''
Elizabeth says. ``He felt like he wasn't going to be able to
protect me.
 &HT;    ``It can get a little strange,'' she admits. ``But my boyfriend
gets more worried than I do, so I just let him do the worrying.''
 &HT;    Besides, Elizabeth is too busy mapping out the next steps in her
career to waste time worrying. She recently committed to
``Tomcats,'' a comedy with Jerry O'Connell and Jake Busey, in which
she'll play a police officer. Come autumn, she'll be a ubiquitous
presence in magazines as the star of Nautica Jeans' latest ad
campaign.
 &HT;    Actually, the biggest obstacle to her future success might be
the very thing that's gotten her this far.
 &HT;    ``I think I used my sexuality and my looks in `American Pie' to
get people to notice me,'' she says, by no means apologizing. ``And
now it's up to me what I do with that. Now it's up to me to pick
roles that display my talent more than my looks. I want to be a
chameleon.''
 &HT;    As role models, Elizabeth cites the protean Gary Oldman or
Cameron Diaz, a bombshell in her own right who nonetheless was able
to disappear into her role as a mousy housewife in ``Being John
Malkovich'' (1999).
 &HT;    ``I want to pick some roles that you'd just never expect me to
do,'' the actress says. ``My next role is a police officer, and
I've been working with guns and I've been doing ride-alongs and
handcuffings. It's been a great learning experience, but I like
that it is very different from my other roles.
 &HT;    ``I really want to do the best job I can,'' she says, ``and show
people that there's more behind what they see and what they think I
am.
 &HT;    ``Also, a lot of people see you as a character and think that's
you, that that's just who you are,'' Elizabeth concludes. ``I can
change that by how I show myself in interviews, because that's when
you get to be who you are.
 &HT;    ``But I also want to change that perception of me by the
different characters I play.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
