<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERWOMEN-OF-TELEVISION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WONDER WOMEN FOR THE NEW MILLENNIUM: TELEVISION'S SUPERWOMEN OF
SYNDICATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Lucy Lawless in a scene from ``Xena:
Warrior Princess.'') 
 By BRIAN HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before July 9, 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television superwomen started in the 1970s, with Lynda Carter as
the seminal Amazon in ``Wonder Woman'' (1976-1979) and Lindsay
Wagner as ``The Bionic Woman'' (1976-1978).
</P>
<P>
   But both had played out the string by 1980, and there the matter
stood until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated television has been a godsend to people who love
women who kick serious butt, however, as foreign and domestic
audiences alike have flocked to the exploits of a new generation of
superwomen.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at six top television wonder women for the new
millennium. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; LUCY LAWLESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Age: 32.
</P>
<P>
   Character: Xena on ``Xena: Warrior Princess'' (1995-present).
</P>
<P>
   Breakout role: A guest shot as Lysia on an early episode of
``Hercules: The Legendary Journeys'' led to a return appearance,
this time as the warrior Xena. And the rest is prehistory.
</P>
<P>
   Previous butt-kicking experience: Lawless played an undercover
cop on a 1994 episode of the action series ``High Tide.''
</P>
<P>
   Overview: The leather-clad, sword-wielding Xena is the yardstick
by which all other female action stars are measured. Her ability to
combine athleticism, heroism and hidden tenderness instantly made
her a fan favorite on ``Hercules,'' and her spinoff show has by now
outlasted its parent and made Lawless an international star.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``People assume that I'm a total Amazon, like I have to
duck to get through doors,'' Lawless told Maxim magazine last year.
``I've never been that physically coordinated or good at sports, so
the last thing I figured I'd become is an action hero. I thought
I'd be doing Shakespeare.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; VICTORIA PRATT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Age: 29.
</P>
<P>
   Character: Sarge on ``Cleopatra 2525'' (2000-present).
</P>
<P>
   Breakout role: Pratt played hard-nosed Mafia boss Jackie Janczyk
on John Woo's Canadian series ``Once a Thief'' (1997-1998).
</P>
<P>
   Previous butt-kicking experience: Pratt got primitive in 1998
for a two-part ``Xena'' episode, a role directly responsible for
her being cast in ``Cleopatra 2525.''
</P>
<P>
   Overview: Pratt has been the standout on this new sci-fi
half-hour about three women fighting against aliens to win back the
Earth for the human race. She plays ``Sarge,'' the silent,
large-armed soldier who shoots first and falls in love later.
</P>
<P>
   It's a role that Pratt is physically perfect for, impeccably
sculpted and yet softly beautiful. Fitness fans may recognize the
Canadian actress from her numerous cover appearances and columns
for workout magazines such as Oxygen and MuscleMag.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Sarge is a hard-ass,'' Pratt says. ``She's a bit of a
sex machine, too, but not out-and-out. She's very passionate and
yet low-key. Plus, she won't take no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so great to play,'' the actress adds, ``and I'm glad
Sarge is not simply a one-note character. She's tough but, you
know, she's got a vulnerable side.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; PAMELA ANDERSON LEE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Age: 32.
</P>
<P>
   Character: Vallery Irons on ``V.I.P.'' (1998-present)
</P>
<P>
   Breakout role: After a much ballyhooed Playboy spread, Anderson
landed a role as Lisa the Tool Time Girl on ``Home Improvement'' in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Previous butt-kicking experience: Anderson played the title role
in ``Barb Wire'' (1996), an unsuccessful feature based on the
leather-clad comic-book heroine.
</P>
<P>
   Overview: Though her character is admittedly bubble-headed,
Anderson weaves a fine line between toughness and naivete. The fact
that she can be downright hilarious while icing evildoers makes her
that much more desirable.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I get to do so many things within this character,'' she
says. ``I like the comedy, the lightheartedness and the action.
It's really my fantasy of what I would like to see on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I a role model?'' Anderson adds. ``Everyone in the public
eye is a role model, but people shouldn't base their lives on what
people do in the public eye.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; TIA CARRERE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Age: 32
</P>
<P>
   Character: Sydney Fox on ``Relic Hunter'' (1999-present).
</P>
<P>
   Breakout role: Carrere was discovered in a grocery store in her
native Hawaii, and landed a role on ``General Hospital'' in 1985.
But it wasn't until ``Wayne's World'' (1992) that she found
widespread acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Previous butt-kicking experience: Carrere has battled evil in
several low-budget films such as ``Zombie Nightmare'' (1986) and
``Road Raiders'' (1989). Hey, a girl's got to eat!
</P>
<P>
   Overview: There are dozens of Web sites devoted to Carrere and
``Relic Hunter,'' though it's no surprise that most of the sites
are little more than exhaustive photo galleries of the exotic
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   As Sydney Fox, a female Indiana Jones, Carrere combines book
smarts with kicks to the solar plexus, adding up to a complex
character who's as strong as she is beautiful. And, unlike a lot of
modern femmes fatale, Fox gets by on her wits and fists instead of
relying on guns and gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Carrere had a handle on her character from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' she recalls, ``I said that she should be
intelligent as well as sexy, as well as kick-ass. A modern,
well-rounded woman.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; GENA LEE NOLIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Age: 28.
</P>
<P>
   Character: Sheena in ``Sheena, Queen of the Jungle'' (debuting
in fall 2000).
</P>
<P>
   Breakout Role: Nolin started her on-camera career as a ``Price
is Right'' model, but won fame as Neely Capshaw for three seasons
of ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous butt-kicking experience: Nolin is new to the genre, but
she's buffing up for ``Sheena,'' and should be ready to handle
whatever fiends may come her way.
</P>
<P>
   Overview: It's about time Hollywood brought back one of
pop-culture's most exciting action stars. Sheena is based on a
comic book that, in turn, saw screen time as a short-lived series
in 1954 and as a feature film in 1984, starring Tanya Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Nolin has no trouble filling out her character's skimpy
animal-hyde bikini, and while it's true that Sheena bears a
striking thematic resemblance to Tarzan, it's clear that anything
he can do, she can do better.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``You have to keep a certain figure because millions of
people watch you, so you want to look good,'' Nolin told fans
during an Internet chat. ``But it's hard, because I'm from the
Midwest and love mashed potatoes and steak and that sort of
thing.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; CAROL ALT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Age: 39.
</P>
<P>
   Character: Karen Oldham in ``Peter Benchley's Amazon''
(1999-present).
</P>
<P>
   Breakout Role: The supermodel basically played herself in
``Private Parts'' (1997), the film biography of radio shock-jock
Howard Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Previous butt-kicking experience: Alt co-starred with wrestler
Hulk Hogan in the little-seen action flick ``Thunder in Paradise''
(1994).
</P>
<P>
   Overview: As the bold leader of six plane-crash survivors
stranded in the Amazon jungle, Karen braves warring native tribes,
deadly animals and dangerous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The role is a major departure for Alt, who began her career as a
supermodel. Once accustomed to star pampering, she now works 1,000
miles from the nearest salon _ yet somehow remains radiant under
all that dirt and grime.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I tell the writers that, when you write for my
character, write for a man and change it to a woman's name,'' she
says. ``It's like, `Someone's in trouble, grab the crossbow and
let's go.' Because that's how I am in my house. If something's
broken, you go fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brian Hartigan is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
