A5338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-AUSTRIAN-TEACHERS-     06-26 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUSTRIAN-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINING INSIGHTS AND NERVES OF STEEL IN NEW YORK CLASSROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judith Hergovich had only the vaguest expectations of
what lay ahead when she left her tiny village of Trausdorf,
Austria, in August 1998 to spend a year teaching math in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would be hard,'' said Hergovich, who was 25 at the
time and had been teaching only a year. ``I knew the students are a
little bit tougher than in Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   What she did not know was that her new workplace, Adlai E.
Stevenson High School in the southeast Bronx, had 3,500 students _
more than twice the population of Trausdorf _ some of the most
crowded, chaotic classrooms in the city, and one of its highest
dropout rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Hergovich plowed right in, teaching five classes a day and
soaking up life in New York _ which in her case meant an austere
apartment in the Pelham Parkway section of the Bronx, far from the
skyscrapers she knew from movies and postcards. Despite the
unnerving challenges she faced, she found the experience rewarding
enough to stay for a second school year.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tocqueville touring America in the 19th century, Hergovich
and the 45 other Austrians recruited to help ease a shortage of
math and science teachers have observed life here from an
outsider's vantage point, and they are bubbling with insights about
New York City's education culture. Almost all have struggled with
more serious discipline problems than they expected, and with the
quandary of how to teach students whose abysmal grades would
relegate them to trade school in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be more strict and more mean here,'' said Eva
Kailbauer, 28, who is teaching math at Franklin Delano Roosevelt
High School in Bensonhurst, Brooklyn. ``In Austria, if a kid says
they have to go to the nurse, they really have to. Here, kids take
every opportunity to really test you. I trusted them at first.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Austrian teachers have also been moved by the hardships
that many teen-agers here face. ``It's always your worst students
who have the biggest problems at home,'' said Lutz Holzinger, 30, a
biology teacher at Roosevelt who has signed up for a third year
here. ``One bad student who acts up all the time, I learn his
mother has AIDS and there is no father. I would freak out, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Holzinger and several others say they cannot
believe what they see as stubborn indifference among many city
students and the enormous tolerance of failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating that many students give up before they
enter the classroom,'' said Hergovich, who was transferred from
Stevenson to Dewitt Clinton High School, also in the Bronx, this
year. ``I never saw something like this in Austria. I don't know
who to blame here; I wouldn't say American culture. Just maybe the
circumstances of how they were raised and where they live.''
</P>
<P>
   Kailbauer and Holzinger said that to their surprise, other
teachers had told them not to blame themselves when many of their
students failed standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I was shocked because 50 percent failed the
tests,'' Holzinger said. ``But then I found out this is normal.
Chemistry, math, all classes. If 50 percent pass, it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Lepuschitz, 30, a math teacher at Roosevelt, said he did
not understand why New York State required even the poorest
students to take math and science to graduate. In Austria, he said,
students who do not excel academically are sent to trade school,
which he said was a more sensible route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our school system divides people who can do certain things and
people who can't,'' Lepuschitz said. ``The people who can't are not
lost; it's just a slower track.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education began recruiting in Austria in 1998,
after Alfred Posamentier, a professor of mathematics education at
City College, pointed out that Austria had a surplus of math and
science teachers, many with advanced degrees. The Austrian
government was enthusiastic because the teachers would come back
fluent in English, an increasingly sought-after credential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately wanted to go for it,'' recalled Holzinger, who
heard about the opportunity from a radio advertisement. ``I already
was planning to go to New York, and this was a chance to do
reasonable work instead of being a waiter or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lepuschitz applied for a job here in 1998 because he was 40th on
a waiting list for a teaching job in Austria. He had spent eight
months student-teaching in a private school. His first assignment,
at Walton High School in the Bronx, was terrifying, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students threatened me,'' said Lepuschitz, looking studious
and very young in jeans and a baggy sweater. ``They didn't
behave.''
</P>
<P>
   He requested and was granted a transfer to Roosevelt High School
last fall, after hearing from other Austrians that students were
better behaved there. But Roosevelt students tried his patience,
too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know how to solve an equation after you tell them
three times,'' Lepuschitz said. ``Out of 30 students, maybe 10 will
answer the question, `Three plus seven equals X, what is X?' And
that is a simple problem!''
</P>
<P>
   Holzinger, for one, seems to have mastered the discipline
problem by acting hip and unflappable. One rainy spring morning,
his students _ even the one whose T-shirt read, ``Rule by
Intimidation'' _ listened quietly as he explained the difference
between DNA and RNA. Kailbauer's approach was similarly
no-nonsense. After passing out work sheets to her ninth-grade
algebra class, she sat ramrod straight at her desk, surveying them
with a glare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of you who are not sure what to do,'' she said gruffly,
``just listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the Austrians say their personal lives in New York
City have been far less taxing than their professional ones. Many
share apartments with one or two other Austrians, typically in
far-flung neighborhoods in Brooklyn and the Bronx, furnished with
thrift-shop finds. They tend to stick together, venturing into
Manhattan on weekends to see movies and visit museums.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned to high schools in every borough but Staten Island, the
Austrian teachers have generally won praise for knowing their
material and speaking solid English. Adele Vocel, the principal at
Roosevelt, said the Austrian teachers fit right in at her school
because the teaching staff and the student body were already so
diverse. The students speak 32 languages, and many of the teachers
have thicker accents than the Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard there was a new wave and I saw we had the ability
to absorb some of them, I begged,'' said Vocel, who hired four
Austrians last year and four this year. ``These teachers are very
well prepared, and they work very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sandra Abrams, the principal of James Madison High School in
Brooklyn, said that although the Austrian teachers know their
subjects thoroughly, she had reservations about their
``chalk-and-talk'' style of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to have a lecture-style approach,'' said Dr. Abrams,
whose school had two Austrian teachers last year but none this
year. ``We like to see students involved in a very hands-on kind of
way rather than being passive and taking notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Harold Levy said in an interview that he was
interested in expanding the program and perhaps starting others
modeled on it. The number of teachers from Austria and other
countries may more than triple next year if 100 new candidates pass
muster. Board officials are interviewing them this week in Vienna
and Innsbruck, Austria. The new round of applicants includes
several teachers from the Czech Republic, Hungary, Italy and
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   New York City needs math and science teachers more than ever;
board officials anticipate needing to hire nearly 700 new math
teachers for the coming school year. Howard Tames, executive
director of the board's personnel division, said that most of the
400 math teachers the board hired this year were not certified in
math. He said the board would also try to recruit qualified
teachers from Canada, the Caribbean and perhaps India and the
Philippines over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
