<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BASEBALL-CARD-HNS &LR;      06-26 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-CARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RARE BASEBALL CARD EXPECTED TO FETCH $1 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GREGORY LEWIS and DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The legendary Honus Wagner tobacco card soon
will be on the auction block again, and this time, there is
speculation it may become the first baseball card to top $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   The hype certainly is pointing in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Edward Auctions, which is part of the hobby megacompany
MastroNet Inc., and the Internet auction house eBay held a news
conference in New York City to announce the sale of the T206
Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   EBay, Robert Edward and MastroNet have entered into a
high-stakes partnership on the card, which will be auctioned on
eBay from July 1-15, and on Robert Edward's telephone auction July
15-16.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, known as the ``Flying Dutchman,'' played for the
Louisville Colonels from 1897 through 1899 and for the Pittsburgh
Pirates from 1900 through 1917. He is considered one of the game's
greatest shortstops and was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame
in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just any old Wagner card, but the one that has
traveled around the hobby world a good bit, once winding up in the
hands of hockey great Wayne Gretzky and his then-partner, Bruce
McNall, who was owner of the Los Angeles Kings at the time. They
paid $451,000 for it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Wal-Mart bought the Wagner for a reported $500,000-plus
from Gretzky, after McNall wound up in financial and legal trouble.
Wal-Mart made it the top prize in a national contest, but the
winner, a postal worker, soon had to put it up for auction after
she realized what she would have to pay in taxes on the prize.
</P>
<P>
   That brought the card to high-rolling collector Michael Gidwitz,
who dropped $640,5000 _ a still-standing record _ on the card in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gidwitz, a Chicago investment adviser, will say goodbye to
it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't own everything forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-told (and perhaps true) story behind the card is that
Wagner objected to his image being used to help sell cigarettes
back in 1910 and demanded that he be removed from the T206 set.
</P>
<P>
   So, few were printed, and there are estimated to be only about
50 of the Wagner cards still in existence, and this one is a
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if it doesn't bring more than $1 million,''
said Rob Lifson of Robert Edward Auctions. ``This is the only
celebrity baseball card, so that seems reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding will start at a cool $500,000, and move up in increments
of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   New York autograph dealer Les Wolff has several recommendations
for anyone thinking of starting a vintage autograph collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, collectors should find something they like
and collect it,'' he said. ``But if you love baseball, I would
start out by collecting signed yellow Hall of Fame plaque cards.
They have the potential to go up in value tremendously, and while
you're collecting them, you can learn the history of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Wolff tips:
</P>
<P>
   ``New collectors should try to get Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig
autographs now. I've never seen their autographs go down in price.
It's like setting up a portfolio in gold. Everything Ruth and
Gehrig is gold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A rough estimate is that 75 percent of memorabilia collectors
don't have their collections insured. It's so important to have
insurance. I've heard a lot of horror stories about people who
didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
