<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 WHAT WAS THE GARY GRAHAM CIRCUS ABOUT? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, after all the propaganda and all the protests and all
the posturing by Gary Graham and his partisans, Graham got what he
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Having avoided execution for 19 years with an endless stream of
groundless appeals, Graham managed to delay justice another two
hours and 49 minutes Thursday as his lawyers launched a last,
desperate round of court filings. In the end, though, the cause of
law and order prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that the courts Graham hoped would rescue him from the
death chamber were looking for facts rather than celebrity
testimonials. And so the courts, including the U.S. Supreme Court,
ignored his phony pleas of innocence and said sorry, pal, your time
is up.
</P>
<P>
   Graham used his final moments to deliver a farewell address that
on-the-scene observers described as ``rambling,'' among other
things. He depicted himself as a martyr and called the state of
Texas a murderer for carrying out the lawful sentence of death
imposed on him by a jury of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Hollywood bleeding hearts such as Danny Glover, jet-set
dilettantes such as Bianca Jagger and
never-miss-a-chance-to-get-on-television charlatans such as Jesse
Jackson, the Gary Graham fan club bemoaned their hero's impending
doom right up until the state's lethal needle worked its magic by
silencing this brutal and vociferous sociopath who enlisted the
elite brigades of the anti-capital-punishment movement in a
relentless campaign to evade his rightful fate.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, but in mindless defiance of fact and
logic, the bleeding hearts chose to believe Graham's baseless claim
that he was railroaded by the legal system _ rather than accepting
the rock-solid eyewitness testimony of Bernadine Skillern, who
watched Graham gun down 53-year-old Bobby Lambert in a Houston
parking lot in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's naive _ or were they cynical? _ supporters parroted the
phrase ``innocent man'' so often that it began to sound like part
of his name. If he hadn't spent half his life on Death Row, perhaps
he could have been a pro wrestler or boxer: Gary ``The Innocent
Man'' Graham.
</P>
<P>
   You can't help but wonder what sort of ethical or moral standard
would cause someone to embrace a vicious animal like Graham. The
murder of Lambert, after all, was but the opening act in a weeklong
horror show that saw Graham callously rob, rape and shoot
unfortunate citizens as if they were images in a violent video
game.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you think that even the most passionate opponents of
capital punishment would occasionally stumble upon a criminal so
vile that they would be unwilling to occupy a seat on his
bandwagon?
</P>
<P>
   But then, all this weeping and gnashing over the plight of Gary
Graham didn't have all that much to do with Gary Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Law professor, attorney and world's foremost legal know-it-all
Alan Dershowitz spilled the beans on ``Larry King Live'' shortly
after Graham was executed. Larry asked Dershowitz if he was sad
about Graham's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have no sadness for this man Graham,'' Dershowitz
replied. ``He deserves everything he gets. This is not about
Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz said it's about the Texas justice system:
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas justice is the best we can do, that's the strongest
argument for abolishing the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, now we're getting somewhere. It's not about Graham, and it's
not really about Texas justice. It's about abolishing the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-capital-punishment agitators may be worried about
executing people for crimes they didn't commit, but they are
equally worried about executing people for crimes they did commit.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, judging from the nonsense we heard during the Graham
fiasco, the bleeding hearts don't want to punish anybody for
anything.
</P>
<P>
   We can't convict a defendant on the basis of eyewitness
testimony. We can't convict a defendant who doesn't have Perry
Mason heading up his legal team. We can convict a defendant on the
basis of DNA evidence _ unless, of course, the defendant has a
brilliant lawyer who discredits the DNA testing process.
</P>
<P>
   And every Gary Graham who comes down the pike will have such a
lawyer, if the bleeding hearts get their way.
</P>
<P>
   When Graham's supporters claim that he had inadequate legal
representation, what they're really saying is that his attorney
wasn't clever enough to conjure up a jury-fooling illusion of
reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz and others want ``indigent'' suspects to have the
best legal representation that money can buy _ which means that
they want the taxpayers to foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   They want society to hire cream-of-the-crop lawyers to help
vicious thugs beat the rap for their crimes against society.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Gary Graham hoopla isn't about Graham _ not just about
Graham, anyway. It's about making America safer for the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
