<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, June 27. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Washington) _ In a watershed in the history of
science, two rival groups of researchers said Monday that they had
deciphered the genome, the set of genetic instructions that defines
the human organism. ``Today we are learning the language in which
God created life,'' President Clinton said at a White House
ceremony attended by members of the two teams. The two leaders of
the teams, Dr. J. Craig Venter, president of Celera, and Dr.
Francis Collins, director of the National Human Genome Research
Institute, praised each other's contributions and signaled a spirit
of cooperation, even though the two efforts will remain firmly
independent. And both sought to capture the wider meaning of their
work, the eye-glazing stream of letters representing the four bases
in the genome's chemical code. ``We have caught the first glimpses
of our instruction book, previously known only to God,'' said
Collins. Venter spoke of his conviction, from seeing people die as
a medical corpsman in Vietnam, that the human spirit transcended
the physiology that is controlled by the genome. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With a PRIMER graphic, an illustrated glossary of genetic terms.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-ASSESS (Undated) _ The human genome, the sum of all
genetic material encased in nearly every cell of the human body, is
very, very long _ at least 3 billion chemical letters long, as many
letters as you'd find in 9,000 copies of the entire Sunday New York
Times. The human genome is pithy. The English alphabet has 26
letters, the Russian 33 letters, and Japanese 1,850 symbols. Yet
with just four distinct characters at its disposal, four nucleic
acid bases, the human genome has given rise to the creators of
every language uttered, every ballad sung, every Pokemon card
traded. The human genome is a pigsty, bulging with non-genes,
ex-genes, freeloader genes, viral detritus, pocket lint and chewing
gum. All but a few percent of it appears to be doing nothing at
all. The human genome is a pearl, a model of high performance and
reliability. Millions of times a year, egg genome meets sperm
genome, and the result is a human baby, its parts all in place, its
brain a universe of love and meaning. In short, the human genome
exults in contradictions. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   Plus a special section of Science Times.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SURPLUS (Washington) _ President Clinton said Monday that
the federal budget surplus over the next decade will be nearly $1.3
trillion higher than previously projected, putting a breathtaking
sum of new money on the table as the two parties and their
presidential candidates battle over tax cuts, spending and how to
prepare for the nation's long-term challenges. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court reaffirmed the
Miranda decision Monday by a 7-2 vote, ruling that because the 1966
landmark ``announced a constitutional rule,'' a statute by which
Congress sought to overrule the decision was itself
unconstitutional. With a majority opinion by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, the decision removed a growing shadow over the Miranda
ruling, cast by a combination of a long-ignored law by which
Congress had tried to overrule it 32 years ago as well as the
current court's perceived hostility to the original decision. The
chief justice said that the 1968 law, which replaced the famous
Miranda warnings with a case-by-case test of whether a confession
was voluntary, could be upheld only if the Supreme Court itself
decided to overturn Miranda. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRIMARY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court invalidated
California's blanket primary Monday, calling it a ``stark
repudiation of freedom of political association'' that stripped
political parties of the ability to control their own nominating
process and define their identity. Under the California system, an
extreme version of the more common open primary, all voters,
regardless of their own party membership, get a single ballot from
which they can select among candidates of any party affiliation: a
Republican for governor, for example, and a libertarian for the
state assembly. Alaska and Washington are the only other states
with such a system. The 7-2 decision cast serious doubt on the more
common open primary, in use in more than half the states, in which
any registered voter can request a particular party's primary
ballot. In some states, the cross-over privilege is limited to
independent voters and does not extend to members of a different
party. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-IRA (Dublin, Ireland) _ The Irish Republican Army
announced Monday that two international envoys appointed as weapons
monitors had inspected a number of its secret arms dumps, and the
pair confirmed the news in visits to Prime Minister Tony Blair in
London and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, here. The
announcement fulfilled a promise made by the IRA in May in response
to demands that it make moves toward dismantling its arsenal in
exchange for Britain's restoring the authority of the new
Catholic-Protestant, power-sharing Northern Ireland government. It
had been suspended in February over earlier IRA inaction on arms.
The IRA also confirmed Monday that it had ended its four-month
boycott of the international disarmament commission led by a
Canadian, Gen. John de Chastelain, and was actively cooperating
with the panel again. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHYNA (Moscow) _ One day after a top Russian military
commander announced a halt to artillery and airstrikes in Chechnya,
the Kremlin said Monday that the attacks would continue. The
reversal raised fresh questions about the Russian military's
pronouncements and was a setback for the government's effort to win
Western understanding for its military campaign. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IMMIG (Washington) _ George W. Bush called for splitting
the Immigration and Naturalization Service in two and for allowing
relatives of permanent residents to visit the United States while
their own immigration papers are being processed. Kicking off a
week aimed at showing he's ``a different kind of Republican,'' the
Republican presidential contender told the League of United Latin
American Citizens the INS should be split into one agency that
welcomes new immigrants and another that strictly enforces the
nation's borders. (Summary from wires) By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FED (Washington) _ After a period of rip-roaring growth that
fueled fears of inflation, the economy is showing enough signs of
slowing that the Federal Reserve will most likely leave interest
rate policy unchanged when it meets on Tuesday and Wednesday,
economists and analysts say. But as it looks ahead, the Fed faces
two big question marks that might lead it to go back to raising
interest rates later in the year. It is not at all clear, Fed
officials say, that the slowdown of the last few months will not
give way to another resurgence in growth and inflation pressures.
In each of the last two years, growth slowed in the spring, only to
come roaring back. And even if the economy is cooling off, the Fed
will have to decide just how cool is cool enough. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-UNION (Undated) _ Veering sharply away from its longtime
strategy of buying up banks and consumer-finance companies, the
First Union Corp. said Monday that it would take a $2.8 billion
charge against its earnings to close the Money Store lending
operation and get out of several other businesses. Most of the
charge will come from shutting the Money Store, which First Union
bought two years ago for $2.1 billion. About 2,350 Money Store
employees will lose their jobs, including as many as 300 in New
Jersey, where the unit was founded. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
