u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-26 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THIS IS REALLY RIDICULOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate who may
become the spoiler of the 2000 presidential race, was cool Sunday
to renewed calls for an outside counsel to probe what Vice
President Al Gore knew about a Buddhist temple campaign stop four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, dismissing that Republican-promoted idea, observed wryly
that ``enough is already known about Gore's fund-raising
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by now the subject is really boring. Gore raises lots of
money. Texas Gov. George W. Bush raises lots of money. They all do
it _ in both parties. So what is the big deal about the Buddhist
temple event, which was legal? It has been investigated over and
over. Nobody claims Gore did anything criminal.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose seems to have been to catch him in a provable lie
under oath so prosecutors could play ``gotcha'' as they did with
President Clinton on the subject of Monica Lewinsky. Gore, however,
has eluded them. Perhaps, just perhaps, he is telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department investigator, Robert Conrad, revived the
issue recently by recommending that Attorney General Janet Reno
toss it to a special counsel just to prove her independence and
integrity, already repeatedly demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated Conrad admitted that he had no new witnesses or
direct evidence to prove Gore lied when he denied knowing that the
event was a fund-raiser. In any case, it was not illegal and it
would not have been a crime if Gore had known.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Conrad based his recommendation on his own feeling that
it would look better to the public if Justice turned the matter
over to someone else. He was concerned about the process, not the
substance of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad said he wanted to ``lay it to rest.'' That could be done,
however, by giving up the whole useless exercise. Or maybe Conrad's
thinking was influenced by Clinton-basher Jesse Helms, the
Republican senator from North Carolina, to whom Conrad made a $250
re-election campaign contribution in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with this pose of judicial purity is that
investigations of vice presidents in the middle of presidential
campaigns do not happen in a neutral political vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Arlen Specter, conducting yet another hearing
into Democratic fund-raising practices, leaked Conrad's internal
recommendation. The senator added mysteriously that Gore's
statements about the Buddhist temple during an April interview with
Conrad differed in a ``stark'' way from the vice president's
previous statements on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Gore promptly released the transcript of that
interview, in which he said essentially what he has said before.
The excerpts reveal no ``stark'' contradictions that might imply
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, defending his actions in an ABC interview later,
conceded, ``I'm not saying that there's anything prosecutable but
there are a great many unanswered questions.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, what unanswered questions are left? The flavor of
the tea served? The shape of the cookies? The car Gore arrived in?
Gore has answered endless questions. Specter just doesn't like his
replies.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if there wasn't something peculiar about publicizing
a probe that came up empty-handed, Specter huffed, ``My record is a
strong one on running objective inquiries.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh? He was ``objective'' when he accused Anita Hill in 1991 of
perjury _ not just lying, mind you, but a crime _ because her
account of Republican Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas'
alleged sexual harassment contradicted Thomas' protestations of
innocence? Thomas was confirmed, but to this day no one could prove
which of the two was not telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's ``objectivity'' is a joke. He got what he wanted _
headlines repeating that Gore ought to be probed for something by
somebody. You had to read down into the fine print to understand
that there is no legal reason to go through the exercise of
appointing an outside counsel to investigate an a baseless
accusation. This is a political issue, not a legal one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not said the vice president has done anything wrong,''
Specter whined. So why does he want to tie up the Gore staff with
all kinds of legal entanglements and costs in the middle of his
presidential campaign? Let us guess. The chaos and confusion could
destroy Gore's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans have made a career out of pressuring
Reno for special counsels to probe Clinton administration
officials, and in fact she has appointed seven of them. But she has
repeatedly drawn the line at elevating GOP complaints about
Democratic fund-raising to that level of investigation. Even
Specter concedes that she is unlikely to suddenly capitulate and
name an outside counsel now.
</P>
<P>
   It's all for show, this latest round being an effort to undercut
Gore's credibility. Bush's surrogates do the dirty work while he
stays above the fray. He said only that the fuss indicates it is
time for ``a new tone in Washington, which is going to require a
new administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a new Congress, no longer controlled by subpoena-empowered
Republicans with nothing on their minds but investigating
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
