<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE TO SPOT AN OCELOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGUNA ATASCOSA NATIONAL WILDLIFE REFUGE, Texas _ Early on a
June morning, you can walk for miles here without seeing another
human being.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll likely see whitetail deer, cottontail rabbits,
roadrunners, Texas tortoises and colorful birds ranging from green
jays to roseate spoonbills. You might even spot an American
alligator or make a rare sighting of an ocelot.
</P>
<P>
   For a vacationing visitor from Fort Worth-Dallas _ weary of work
deadlines, road rage, pushy telemarketers and other urban plagues _
the refuge is a soothing slice of heaven. It's a 35-minute drive
from the beaches of South Padre Island at the southern tip of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe bet that most Texans have never heard of the Laguna
Atascosa, one of 18 national wildlife refuges in Texas and 521 in
the United States. But these refuges are becoming an increasingly
precious American treasure as the human population relentlessly
expands and as wildlife habitat is vaporized by bulldozers making
way for the latest addition to urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Refuges range from the tiny, half-acre Mille Lacs refuge in
Minnesota to the Arctic refuge in Alaska, a majestic expanse of
19.2 million acres that is roughly the size of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   As the refuge system nears its 100th anniversary in 2003, it's
important that Congress, and the American public, come to better
understand the refuge system's importance and the need to keep it
properly maintained. Compared to America's prized national parks,
our wildlife refuges are underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Many refuges possess scenic beauty. But they were created to
provide a haven for wildlife and crucial rest stops for migratory
birds. The refuges get $260 million in annual funding under the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Refuges lure 35 million visitors annually, a number easily
exceeding 10 percent of the U.S. population. But that number is
misleading because there are many repeat visitors, such as birding
and fishing enthusiasts who regularly frequent favorite refuges,
system spokesman Erik Eckl said.
</P>
<P>
   The Laguna Atascosa, covering 45,187 acres, is a birder's
paradise. The refuge's outdoor recreation planner, biologist Kevin
Stephenson, said 406 species of birds have been identified here _
more than at any other refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge includes grasslands, woods, impenetrable thornbrush
and coastal marshes along the Laguna Madre, the fish-rich waters
between the Texas mainland and Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge is a sanctuary for the ocelot, a small, reclusive
wildcat. Of the estimated 100 ocelot left in the United States,
about one-third are at Laguna Atascosa.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge draws more than 100,000 visitors annually, mainly
from October through April. Attendance is minimal in hot summer
months. But if you arrive at daybreak, you can see lots of wildlife
and have a great time hiking trails before the midday heat sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife watching is the biggest attraction at refuges. Many
allow some hunting, a practice that has enraged animal protection
groups but which refuge officials defend as a recreational pursuit
that helps stabilize populations. Laguna Atascosa has a short deer
hunting season that keeps its whitetail population at about 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, many refuge facilities are in disrepair, with
problems ranging from leaky roofs to crumbling boardwalks, Eckl
said. Laguna Atascosa wants money to pave a scenic drive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their funding limitations, the refuges are a priceless
asset to wildlife _ and to the humans who take great joy in
visiting them.
</P>
<P>
   When you quietly walk a refuge trail and see animals in the
wild, ``it's therapeutic,'' Stephenson said. ``It's good for the
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   President Theodore Roosevelt would doubtlessly be happy to see
how huge the refuge system has become since he helped create the
first refuge at Florida's Pelican Island in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Teddy Roosevelt were alive today, he'd be thrilled,'' Eckl
said. ``It's an amazing gift to our future generations that he
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Internet site for the national wildlife refuge system is
http:/refuges.fws.gov.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724 or
jzsmith(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
