<HEADER>
A5369 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-WHO-NYT &LR;      06-26 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-WHO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELER AND MOSAIC MAN STAND IN FOR EVERYONE IN THE GENOME PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(With main bar, SCI-GENOME; see SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET for a complete
description of sidebar stories and graphics.) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whose DNA was sequenced in the human project?
</P>
<P>
   Surely some fitting representative of the human species, some
Homo sapientissimus, someone chosen for special qualities of health
or intellect, some screen or sports star, maybe
technoplutocrat-in-chief Bill Gates. Or why not Dr. James D. Watson
or Dr. Francis Crick, the co-discoverers of the structure of DNA?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists and federal officials don't think in such terms. Both
the public consortium and Celera have chosen to do their decoding
at celebrity's opposite pole, with the DNA of anonymous
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Celera is sequencing the DNA of a single male (because men have
both an X and a Y chromosome, women two X's). The company will not
say who he is. Call him Celer.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's object of analysis is not an individual, but a
patchwork composite of DNA sections drawn from a number of men and
women it will not identify. Call him Mosaic Man.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that Celer and Mosaic Man are anonymous is the
revealing nature of DNA. In terms of public exposure, being
stripped naked in Times Square would be only mildly revealing
compared with having one's genome accessible on an open database.
</P>
<P>
   Probably everyone carries some gene variants that could
predispose them or their children to disease. By the time all such
genetic flaws are cataloged, it will be apparent that quite a few
are present in the decoded human genome. To preserve the privacy of
the donor _ and his family and descendants _ anonymity is the best
course.
</P>
<P>
   But anonymity is an anomalous kind of mask, because DNA is the
ultimate identifier. It is always possible that Celer and maybe
even the components of Mosaic Man could be recognized if their DNA
were to show up in any forensic database.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium has gone even further toward securing anonymity
by working on a genome where each section may come from one of
several different individuals. These include both men and women and
people of different ethnic backgrounds. Mosaic Man is truly a
nobody.
</P>
<P>
   A jury-size complement of 12 men and women have contributed the
DNA used in Mosaic Man. But they are not all making equal
contributions: The sample being most used for the consortium's
draft is from a single man.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists are just as happy with an anonymous genome as with a
celebrity's, because with one genome in hand to serve as a
reference sequence, it should be quite easy to catalog all the
common variants found in most human populations.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these variants are sites on the DNA where one unit is
changed to another, or a DNA unit is added or deleted. These single
unit changes are called single nucleotide polymorphisms, or SNPs,
and account for a large proportion of human genetic variation. A
variant SNP may change a gene's coding for its protein product,
leading to a protein with different properties.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, as far as is known, has the same set of genes, but
because of SNPs, many of these genes come in several different
flavors. Because everyone has a different combination of flavors,
no individuals are completely alike, save for identical twins.
</P>
<P>
   A catalog of the most common human SNPs should be valuable in
tracking down genetic dispositions to disease, particularly those
caused by multiple variant genes, each of which makes a small and
elusive contribution. By tracking the patterns of SNPs inherited in
families where a disease is prevalent, biologists hope to identify
the gene variants that contribute to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   With Celer's reference sequence in hand, Celera plans to detect
the DNA variations in six men and women of different ethnic
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the public realm, a second consortium, known as the SNP
Consortium, aims to identify 300,000 human SNPs and publish them
for general use. The SNP Consortium is supported by 11
pharmaceutical companies and the Wellcome Trust of London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5371 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-VENTER-ART     06-26 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-VENTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATION AND RIVALRY FUELED VENTER'S PASSION FOR GENETIC
DISCOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 3,5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With main bar, SCI-GENOME; see SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET for a complete
description of sidebar stories and graphics.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An intense focus on putting genes to practical use has propelled
John Craig Venter from an obscure federal researcher to a principal
decoder of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Born on Oct. 14, 1946, in Salt Lake City, he earned a doctorate
in physiology and pharmacology from the University of California at
San Diego and entered the world of biochemical research at the
National Institutes of Health. Frustrated at having to spend 10
years trying to isolate a single gene, Venter realized there was a
quick way to fish out the genes, which in the case of humans occupy
only 3 percent of the genome.
</P>
<P>
   The technique was to capture the normal copies of genes made by
living cells and to decode a few hundred DNA units from part of the
gene. These partial transcripts, known as ESTs (expressed sequence
tags), could be used to identify the gene-coding regions on the DNA
from which they came.
</P>
<P>
   Venter's use of ESTs had two eventful consequences. One was that
Dr. Bernadine Healy, then director of the National Institutes of
Health, decided to apply for patents on the genes he had found, a
move strongly opposed by Dr. James Watson, director of the NIHs
human genome office. The issue was among one of several differences
with Healy that led to Watson's resignation from that office in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   The other consequence was that Venter's work caught the eye of a
venture capitalist, Dr. Wallace Steinberg, who wanted to start a
gene-finding company _ with Venter as its head. But Venter insisted
on a nonprofit venture, so Steinberg set him up in the nonprofit
Institute for Genomic Research supported by a new company, Human
Genome Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   At his new institute, Venter generated thousands of ESTs to the
human genome. These became the intellectual property of Human
Genome Sciences which, under Dr. William Haseltine, has developed
far-reaching claims to many medical genes of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Venter then spotted another frontier where the DNA sequencing
machines might break ground, that of sequencing the genomes of
bacteria. The NIHs human genome project was then working on E.
coli, a widely studied bacterium, but progress was slow.
</P>
<P>
   In a prelude to later events with the human genome, Venter
figured he could be first to decode a bacterium with a novel method
called the shotgun technique. He applied for an NIH grant but
started the project with other money. When it was almost complete,
he has said, he received a letter from the NIH rejecting his
application because, in the view of an expert committee, it would
not work.
</P>
<P>
   The committee included scientists involved in the NIHs part of
the public consortium. Their rejection of Venter's idea set the
pattern of an adversarial relationship that has continued until the
last few weeks. Haemophilus influenzae, whose genome Venter
decoded, was the first bacterium and the first living organism, not
counting viruses, to have its full DNA decoded. The result gave
scientists their first glimpse into the set of genes necessary for
life. It set off a revolution in medical microbiology, inspiring
efforts to decode every major pathogen and learn the microbes'
entire playbook for attacking human cells.
</P>
<P>
   In setting up his institute and decoding the Haemophilus genome,
Venter showed he could attract talented people as colleagues. Much
of the essential work on Haemophilus was by Dr. Hamilton O. Smith,
a Nobel Prize winner, whose contribution Venter freely
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Venter's technical judgment and organizational abilities
appealed to Michael W. Hunkapiller, president of the company now
known as PE Biosystems, which made the leading brand of DNA
sequencing machine. When a new, labor-saving generation of his
machines was developed, Hunkapiller figured that a private company
using a large suite of the new machines could decode the human
genome faster than the government could. He persuaded Venter to run
the company, which came to be known as Celera.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving his institute in friendly hands _ its new president is
Dr. Claire Fraser, his wife _ Venter began Celera in May 1998. His
rivals in the public consortium were soon providing him with the
psychological stimulus he seemed to need, by pronouncing his human
genome decoding strategy certain to fail. Within a few months he
had hired a staff, set up a large plant and begun decoding.
</P>
<P>
   Although Celera is in business to make money, principally by
selling subscriptions to its genomic data base, Venter seems eager
for the academic world's approval and has continued to publish
scientific articles, maintaining a presence in both the science and
business worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Venter became wealthy when he left the NIH to set up the
Institute for Genomic Research, and superwealthy when he became
president of Celera. But apart from indulging his passion for
sailing, he has not let sudden riches divert him from his path.
Whether in working on ESTs to pull out the genes, decoding the
first pathogenic bacteria, or racing to complete the human genome,
he has been driven by getting practical results. Celera's corporate
motto, that ``Speed Matters'' for treating disease, is a little
hokey but reflects Venter's consistent focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been Craig's view that what is important is not
some abstract view of the genome but its utility,'' said Dr. David
Lipman, director of the National Center for Biotechnology
Information. ``Craig has always pushed in the right direction, and
the public program needed pushing. When he started Celera it made
the public program open their eyes and take a different approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5378 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-26 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTHLESS EQUALS HILARIOUS ON THESE `INSIDE TV' SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The initial fear ABC had with its critically acclaimed
inside-the-TV-world comedy ``Sports Night'' was that it was too
inside for the average viewer. And when ABC pulled the plug after
two seasons, it was indeed obvious that we media insiders were far
more tickled by it than those with Nielsen boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Such is potentially the problem for Showtime's ``Beggars and
Choosers,'' which premieres Tuesday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When Rob Malone (Brian Kerwin) opens the morning meeting of the
fictional LGT Network in ``Beggars and Choosers''' premiere
episode, he takes a few jabs at his development head about her
passing on the runaway hit ``The Sopranos,'' which is now killing
them in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing particularly funny about this _ except to those
of us who know and understand that in real life, a development
executive who waved off a series that goes on to become a breakout
hit for someone else would have their body chopped up in little
pieces and dispatched to relatives.
</P>
<P>
   As I cracked up over this, my viewing partner, whose TV tastes
fall within the purview of HGTV and the Weather Channel, sat
stone-faced.
</P>
<P>
   In both ``Beggars and Choosers'' and the superior Canadian
series ``The Industry,'' now airing on PBS, viewers are expected at
least to connect with the ruthlessness of the business, where
getting ahead means getting behind someone _ either to be carried
along by their tail wind or to push them out a window. (Hey, it
works for ``Survivor.'') The idea is that it's not as over-the-top
in other businesses, but everyone can relate.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Beggars and Choosers,'' Lori (Charlotte Ross), LGT's vice
president in charge of development, is the master at back-stabbing,
and the writers have cleverly fueled her chronic paranoia this
season by hiring a British development executive as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   When Lori tells her like-minded confidant, a scheming agent
named Brad (William McNamara), that she's worried about the new LGT
consultant, Brad does some background checking only to find that
the Brit is buddies with Prince Edward and is considered the 123rd
person in line for the throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that,'' ponders Brad, ``to have to knock off 122
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious and anal, Lori obsesses over her career and those who
can affect it, living and breathing every professional move she
makes (and the moves of others). You'd think she's capable of
murder to get ahead. She's destined to be one of the series' most
popular characters.
</P>
<P>
   A future episode shows the callousness of television production
when LGT puts in development an Asian sitcom, but only as an
apology to an angry Asian community for a star's politically
incorrect faux pas on a talk show. (At least it was original. Most
would have gone with African-Americans and have as its spokesperson
a loudmouth Baptist minister resembling Jesse Jackson.)
</P>
<P>
   But Lori and the doings at LGT actually pale in comparison to
Rick Mercer's portrayal of Richard Strong in ``The Industry,''
which offers the most savagely funny satire on the medium since
``The Larry Sanders Show.''
</P>
<P>
   To help bring back a popular series in which the star has died,
Richard re-edits the star's sick-in-bed scene to say not only that
he died but that the star wrote the episode himself ``knowing'' he
was dying. It becomes ``event'' television and draws a huge
audience, and no one gives a thought to what they've just done.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Roy (Peter Keleghan), head of the network, is described as
an unsentimental opportunist who made his money building low-income
housing. Now, says Richard, who moves the action along by talking
to the camera, mutters, ``He makes movies and television for people
who live in low-income housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Over two episodes, Richard sabotages a boss to get his job, and
the smartest, sharpest, more principled executives are usually the
first targeted for extinction. ``She's the smartest person here,''
Richard says of a co-worker, looking at her adoringly. ``She's got
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, ``Beggars and Choosers'' and ``The Industry''
mirror the real industry _ not only in its conniving nature, but
also in the lack of respect given the medium by those whose
livelihoods are connected to it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'm quite sure that my favorite line from ``The
Industry'' _''It's TV, not rocket science. It's small-engine
repair'' _ was told to me a year ago by an idealistic low-level
executive who burned himself out and is now, if rumor is true,
peddling flowers alongside a busy Los Angeles intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's where he'll bloom,'' was the last punch line I
heard about the guy. And this came from a colleague and ``good
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Television can go right ahead in its effort to parody its own
industry. But for real comedy, nothing can outdo the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
