<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-RAPSHEETS-COLU     06-26 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-RAPSHEETS-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WILL RAPPERS CUT THE CRIME? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, June 27, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   About the only smile-inducing element to be found within any
story about a rapper getting arrested is the publication of the
tough guy's sissy-sounding, parent-selected name.
</P>
<P>
   Flesh Bone is really Stanley Howse.
</P>
<P>
   Jay-Z is Shawn Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Snoop Doggy Dogg is Calvin Broadus.
</P>
<P>
   Mac the Camouflage Assassin is McKinley Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rapper to be booked on charges is one Nathaniel
Dwayne Hale, better known to the kids as Nate Dogg. (He's a protege
of Snoop Doggy Dogg's, hence the double-g deal with the canine
portion of his showbiz name.) Mr. Dogg was arrested by a SWAT team
in Pomona, Calif., after he held his girlfriend against her will,
assaulted her and set her mother's car on fire, according to
police. He has been charged with kidnapping, making terrorist
threats, domestic violence and arson, and is being held in lieu of
$1 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of Nate Dogg come yipping at the heels of the
gun-wielding antics of Marshall Mathers, aka Eminem, whose new CD
has gone triple-platinum in a heartbeat. In one crazy evening, the
self-proclaimed punk allegedly pulled a gun during a fight with a
member of the Insane Clown Posse's entourage and then took the gun
out later that night when he saw his wife kissing another man.
</P>
<P>
   Guess he should have stayed home and rented a movie.
</P>
<P>
   And if you would have told me that when I started this job I'd
one day be writing a paragraph that included the names Nate Dogg,
Eminem and Insane Clown Posse, I'd ask what time your spaceship was
returning to its home planet.
</P>
<P>
   Actually I've commented on the rap scene from time to time for
more than a decade now _ sometimes ripping it, sometimes giving the
form its due. I've said rap is the most vibrant and vital type of
pop music of the last 20 years, and I've mocked many of the
so-called artists who can't play instruments and just rip off tunes
by infinitely more talented musicians, and I stand by both of those
seemingly dichotomous statements.
</P>
<P>
   Most often though, when I'm talking about rappers in the news,
I'm talking about their crimes and tragedies, not their CDs and
concerts. Go lazy with your thinking and call that racist if you
will (even though many rappers, including the aforementioned
Eminem, are white), but it would be more offensive if I didn't note
the astonishingly, depressingly large numbers of rap artists who
have been in trouble with the law and/or have been seriously
injured or stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   It's practically an epidemic. In the last six months alone,
there have been at least eight incidents of rappers arrested, from
the Sean ``Puffy'' Combs mess at a New York City nightclub in
December 1999 to the multiple charges of felony gun possession
against Flesh Bone of Bones Thugs-N-Harmony to the prison stay
slapped on ODB (aka Big Baby Jesus) after he violated probation for
possessing alcohol _ a relatively benign offense until you consider
that ODB has a history that includes charges of shoplifting,
threatening a girlfriend, menacing security officers, possession of
crack cocaine, firing shots at police officers and illegally
wearing a bulletproof vest (a no-no for cons).
</P>
<P>
   You say it's unfair to condemn a whole genre of music because
some of its practitioners get into trouble? I say the cumulative
lineups of Lilith Fair have been in far less trouble than one
little ODB.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 years ago this month that rappers 2 Live Crew were
arrested in Hollywood, Fla., for performing obscene material
onstage. But so many rappers have been shot, stabbed, arrested and
convicted since then that the 2 Live Crew guys seem almost cuddly
by today's standards.
</P>
<P>
   You want to talk about a rap sheet? This is just a partial list
of rappers who have been arrested or or injured or killed:
</P>
<P>
   Tupac Shakur. DMX. Jay-Z. Sean ``Puffy'' Combs. Two members of
Naughty by Nature. Coolio. Foxy Brown. Nate Dogg. Two members of 2
Live Crew. Black Rob. Mac the Camouflage Assassin. Notorious B.I.G.
Flesh Bone. Steady B. ODB. Eminem. Two members of Digital
Underground. Flavor Flav.
</P>
<P>
   Not that getting into trouble with the law necessarily harms the
careers of these role models, or is of particular concern to the
corporate types who profit from their product; in fact, a police
record usually has the opposite effect, gaining the rapper some
much-desired ``street cred.'' Your songs about waving guns and
busting a cap and all that crap sound so much more authentic if
you're really doing it.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that'll stop a rapper's career cold is a
bullet that leaves him open-eyed in a pool of blood, and even then
the post-mortem releases keep on coming, and the scramble for the
profits only intensifies. It's just a lovely cycle.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
