<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-PRIMARY-HNS &LR;      06-26 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRIMARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT REJECTS CALIFORNIA'S `BLANKET' PRIMARY SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California's free-for-all primary election system,
which allows voters to choose candidates without regard to party
affiliation, violates the rights of state political parties, the
Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-2 decision, the court called the state's system a
``severe and unnecessary'' burden on the right of a political party
to define its own message and decide its own candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The system, known a blanket primary, allows any voter _ whether
registered as a Democrat, Republican, third-party member or
independent _ to vote for the nomination of any candidate from any
party for any race.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, Justice Antonin Scalia said California
violated the First Amendment's right to free association by
``forcing political parties to associate with those who do not
share their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no area is the political association's right to exclude
more important than in its candidate-selection process,'' Scalia
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means that California _ along with Washington state
and Alaska, which have similar systems _ will be forced to change
the way they conduct primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said the states could hold a nonpartisan blanket primary,
in which voters can choose any candidate, regardless of
affiliation, and the top two vote-getters move on to the general
election. The system he described would be similar to that adopted
by Louisiana in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Under such a plan, Scalia said, ``primary voters are not
choosing a party's nominee'' and therefore political parties'
rights of free association are not harmed.
</P>
<P>
   His opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter,
Clarence Thomas and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Justices John Paul Stevens and Ruth Bader
Ginsburg. Writing for the two, Stevens said the court should
``respect the policy choice made by the state's voters'' in
approving the proposition that created the blanket primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But George Waters, who represented the political parties before
the high court, praised the majority decision, saying parties have
the right to define their membership. ``The court agreed that
blanket primaries violate that right by inviting voters with no
loyalty to the party to influence the selection of the party's
nominees.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreeing, California Secretary of State Bill Jones noted that
the vast majority of voters supported the blanket primary system.
``I don't know who the parties are afraid of. The vast majority of
their members supported this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, California voters passed Proposition 198, setting up
the blanket-primary system, which allows voters, regardless of
their political registration, to cast ballots in such elections to
select any candidate for any office.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a voter could choose a candidate in the Democratic
presidential primary and, at the same time, vote for a candidate in
the Republican primary for U.S. Senate and then vote to nominate an
independent candidate for a House seat.
</P>
<P>
   California adopted the single-ballot, blanket form of primary to
give the state's 1.6 million independent voters their first chance
to vote in what had been a ``closed'' primary system limited to
party members.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state has used the blanket primary since 1935. Alaska
enacted a similar law in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Blanket-primary supporters argued that the system would
encourage voter turnout and lead to the nomination of more moderate
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But California's Democratic, Republican, Libertarian and Peace &AMP;
Freedom parties immediately challenged the system, contending it
violated their First Amendment right of ``freedom of association.''
</P>
<P>
   The national Democratic and Republican parties filed briefs
supporting that contention.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, U.S. District Court Judge David Levi ruled that the
blanket primary was constitutional. Levi said that although the
system was an ``intrusion on a party's traditional right to select
its own candidates,'' the burden on the parties was not enough of a
``significant burden'' to justify striking down the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed. It
thought so highly of Levi's ruling that it simply adopted his
opinion ``as the opinion of our court.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Supreme Court reversed that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for affording voters greater choice, it is obvious that the
net effect of this scheme ... is to reduce the scope of choice, by
assuring a range of candidates who are all more centrist,'' Scalia
said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision avoided deciding the validity of the more
common open primary system used in another 20 states. In an open
primary, voters are allowed to choose which party's primary they
will vote in. Such voters get to select the nominees of one party
only.
</P>
<P>
   This is the type of system that aided former Republican
presidential candidate John McCain in states such as Michigan,
where Democrats and independents were allowed to vote in the
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen states have closed primaries, which allow only party
members to vote in each party's primary. Another 13 states have
closed primaries but also let independent voters cast ballots in at
least one party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-NYTR &LR;      06-26 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY EMERGES AS DEFINING POLICY ISSUE OF 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL HULSE   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Social Security has often been used as a political
bludgeon, but the 2000 presidential campaign promises to raise
public discourse over the program to a new level and set the future
course of retirement living.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore and Republican contender George W.
Bush are articulating clear and contrasting visions of how they
would reshape the indispensable pension program, giving voters an
unmistakable choice in approaches to Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates typically dance around the edges of the politically
volatile issue, but not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember a presidential campaign that has given this
kind of emphasis to retirement issues,'' said Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in proposing that workers be allowed to invest a portion
of their own payroll taxes in personal retirement accounts, is
banking that Americans accustomed to 401(k) plans on the job will
see the appeal in having more control over their public pension. He
and his backers argue that individuals can do a better job handling
their money than the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a change yes, but it is a change for the better,'' said
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``It is going to give people a chance to
develop wealth and assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on the other hand, is proposing that people be encouraged
to invest in publicly subsidized retirement accounts as a
supplement to Social Security, earning a government match tied to
their personal contribution and income level. Backers of this
approach say it has the advantage of not tampering with Social
Security while giving workers an attractive new savings option.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan is Social Security plus, not Social Security minus,''
said Gore in trying to sell his program, which would cost an
estimated $200 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Now the two campaigns will spend most of the next five months
trying to show the flaws of the opposition's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, with assistance from a few moderate Democrats, are
attacking Gore's proposal as a pale imitation of Bush's approach
but one that does nothing to fix structural problems in the Social
Security system, which is projected to stop running a surplus in
about 2015 and run out of money in 2037. It would then be able to
pay about 70 percent of benefits using current taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creating a new government benefit does not keep Social
Security solvent for the baby boomers and beyond,'' said Sen. John
Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, his fellow Democrats and their allies say Bush's plan
is a risky strategy that would lead to cuts in benefits as the
drain of payroll taxes into individual accounts accelerates the
decline in Social Security surpluses. Plus, they say allowing
people to invest their own money makes the Social Security system
subject to the vagaries of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be able to rely on Social Security's guaranteed
benefit, not be forced to sacrifice their retirement security for
George W. Bush's political gain,'' said Doug Hattaway, a spokesman
for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Graham, the Florida Democrat who supports Gore's
initiative, said Bush is trying to wring too much out of Social
Security when it should remain the basis of retirement rather than
a way to build assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe there needs to be new opportunity for Americans
to be more aggressive and try to increase their retirement income,
and I believe there should be, Social Security is not the place to
do it,'' he said. ``Social Security is the net under the trapeze of
retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have traditionally scored politically on the Social
Security issue and expect to do so this time. Polls show that older
Americans in particular are leery of any attempt to ``privatize''
the program.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP believes that Bush can sell his plan to a public
comfortable with individual retirement accounts while burnishing
his credentials as a leader willing to tackle tough issues.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be just the presidential race that turns on this issue;
congressional elections will offer similar choices as Republican
and Democratic candidates align themselves with the top of the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security issues typically motivate older voters, but it
is those who have not yet reached retirement age who have the most
at stake. Bush and Gore promise to protect current beneficiaries
with phase-ins of their plans, leaving the potential financial
risks and gains to fall on those years away from retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the candidate who is best able to communicate his
Social Security message to those voters could cash in come
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political world has so far failed to catch-up to the
401(k) world,'' said Richard Thau, president of Third Millennium, a
group that tries to promote civic involvement among younger
Americans. ``But the politician who learns to convey a message
about the system of retirement savings in this country will be
ideally situated.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is the Washington bureau chief for the New York
Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
