<HEADER>
A5397 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-VEGETARIANISM-NUTRITI     06-26 1801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETARIANISM-NUTRITION-LIFEBEAT-1300&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGETARIAN A, B, C'S
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Ken McAlpine writes about health and fitness for ``Spirit''
magazine. &HT;     &HT;    
 By KEN MCALPINE 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Ken McAlpine.
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Each year roughly one million people turn to some form of
vegetarian diet. Many of these newcomers do so in simple fashion,
forking their steak aside to dine on the remaining garnishes;
potato salad, a roll or three and a bowl of lettuce backstroking in
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Happy news if you have stock in starch and fat, bad news if you
are the one eating like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good intentions gone awry,'' says Ann Grandjean, director of
the Center for Human Nutrition in Omaha, Nebraska. ``Plenty of
vegetarians eat a healthy, well-planned diet. But plenty of others
don't do their homework. And that can get you into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts lump vegetarians into various categories. There are the
semi-vegetarians who have dumped red meat but still eat chicken,
fish and dairy products. There are the lacto-ovovegetarians who
eschew meat, fish and poultry, but continue to consume milk, dairy
products and eggs. There's the lactovegetarian who goes a step
further and eliminates eggs. At the end of the line, there's the
pure vegetarian or ``Vegan,'' subsisting on an all-vegetable diet
devoid of animal foods, dairy products or eggs.
</P>
<P>
   These definitions really don't matter since you already know
what you are and aren't eating. But there is an important point
buried beneath all the syllables. Moving from the semi-vegetarian
to the Vegan, foods fall away. As they do, you need to be
increasingly vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' says Grandjean, who combines nearly 30 years of
nutrition expertise with a no-nonsense approach. ``Good nutrition
is about variety. And any time you start leaving out whole groups
of foods, you're losing that variety. The more restrictive the
diet, the more you need to think about your food choices.''
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason to move toward what experts call a
``plant-centered'' diet. While vegetarians on the fringe cite less
substantive evidence _ The Cow is Our Friend! _ science has found a
simple cause and effect. Reduce the animal fat you eat and you'll
reduce the fat clinging to your arteries and your waistline. Enjoy
a reduced risk of heart disease, and possibly lower your odds of
diabetes, high blood pressure and certain types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most transitions toward a plant-based diet result in a diet
that's lower in fat and higher in fiber and antioxidants,
naturally-occurring vitamins and minerals that may reduce the
incidence of some chronic diseases,'' says Nancy Ling, a registered
dietitian in Beverly Hills, California. ``There's still lots of
debate about the benefits of a vegetarian diet. But we do know that
it's a great way to cut back on cholesterol, calories and saturated
fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cholesterol, calories and fat, however, aren't all that's being
scraped off the plate. Drop red meat from your diet and you lose a
rich repository of iron, zinc, protein and B vitamins. Drop dairy
products and there goes your most reliable source of calcium.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that vegetarian fare lacks these nutrients. There are
comparable vegetarian substitutes. One cup of cooked soybeans
contains the protein equivalent of a quarter-pound hamburger or 18
ounces of milk. It's just that the vegetable world, for many, is
uncharted territory. Hunting for calcium, most Americans can
identify a glass of milk. But they wouldn't know a calcium-rich bok
choy or dandelion green if it bit them on the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you eat meat, dairy products and vegetables, getting
nutrients can be a no-brainer,'' says Grandjean. ``But vegetarians
have to be more aware of what they're eating. They have to know
what the sources are.''
</P>
<P>
   Being misinformed can lead to deficiencies and serious problems.
Teen-age girls who subsist on bread and salad have exhibited a rate
of bone fracture that would make the National Hockey League
blanche. Along with common sense, their diet is lacking in the
calcium they need to form strong bones.
</P>
<P>
   There once was a time when neophyte vegetarians were left
bawling and confused in the produce section. Today, all the
aspiring vegetarian needs to do is consult the Vegetarian Diet
Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you're eating foods from all these groups, every
day,'' says Grandjean. ``If you are, then you're fine. If you're
not, then you're at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vegetarian Diet Pyramid includes eggs and dairy products.
But for the pure Vegan, a nutrient-replete diet is still simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure vegetarians need to eat what they can from the vegetarian
food guide, and be aware of good sources of protein, calcium, iron
and zinc, which are a little more difficult to get in a strictly
vegetarian diet,'' says Ling.
</P>
<P>
   Grandjean and Ling also counsel athletes, raising some
interesting questions. Can a vegetarian diet help or hinder
athletic performance? Does the vegetarian athlete have special
needs?
</P>
<P>
   Since athletes are always looking for an edge and questionable
experts are always mining for a best seller, there are plenty of
myths. Fortunately, the truth is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that a vegetarian diet improves athletic
performance,'' says Ling. ``But it is true that a well-planned
vegetarian diet will have plenty of carbohydrates, which is what
athletes need if they are training heavily. On the other hand,
being a vegetarian won't decrease your power and endurance
either.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're a recreational runner, swimmer or stair-stepper AND a
vegetarian, do you need to be any more concerned?
</P>
<P>
   Grandjean is blunt. If you go to the gym five days a week for an
hour step class, your nutritional needs are little different from
those of the desk jockey checking your ID at the door. For the
recreational exerciser, following the Vegetarian Pyramid is enough.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a strict vegetarian who is training three hours and
up, six and seven days a week _ a collegiate swimmer, a marathon
runner _ you'll have to eat more, says Grandjean, to replace the
calories you're burning.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't, the body starts cannibalizing itself, using
protein in the muscles for fuel and stealing it away from its
preferred task of growth and rebuilding body tissues. Getting
enough calories from calorically light vegetarian foods can require
a trencherman's focus, and frequent snacking.
</P>
<P>
   One cup of brown rice and lentils, a large baked potato,
one-half cup of carrots, one-half cup of peas, a lettuce and tomato
salad, a banana, an apple, an orange and a half-dozen walnuts weigh
in at 890 calories. A college swimmer can burn 6,000 calories a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Protein can be a concern too. Protein is composed of amino
acids, and the amino acids present in broccoli are different from
those in steak. The proteins your body can best absorb are found in
animal products. Their amino acid combinations most closely
represent the human tissue the athlete is trying to build in the
weight room, or repair after a three-hour run.
</P>
<P>
   Grandjean once studied Japanese Olympians who ate a plant-based
diet. To build muscle, these athletes needed three times the
protein of mildly active sorts, and nearly twice the protein
required by meat-eating Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the amount of protein supplied by animal products
goes down, the total amount of protein required goes up,'' says
Grandjean.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarian athletes training heavily should also think about
iron and zinc. Found in healthy supply in meat, these minerals are
less concentrated in vegetarian fare. Since iron carries oxygen
from the lungs to the cells, and the cells use that oxygen to power
the muscles, a shortage of iron could pare back performance. Zinc
deficiency, says Ling, may register as more runny noses and nasty
flus.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions like this can produce another symptom, namely a
crimp in your brain.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get bogged down in details.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if you're vegetarian or not,'' says
Grandjean. ``Variety provides the nutrients you need. Any time you
don't get that variety, there's the potential for compromising your
health and your athletic performance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VEGETARIAN DIET PYRAMID &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Vegetarian Diet Pyramid is based on the traditional eating
patterns of vegetarian-centered cultures. It includes egg whites
and dairy products. Studies have linked this Ovo-lacto diet with
lower rates of heart disease, obesity and certain cancers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VEGAN OPTIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The strict vegetarian has a smaller pool of food choices, so
it's important those food choices be nutritionally rich. A
vegetarian diet will provide all the nutrients you need, provided
you know where to look.
</P>
<P>
   Protein: Soybeans, rice, peanuts, broccoli, lentils, chickpeas,
pumpkin and sunflower seeds, almonds, cashews and walnuts.
Soybeans, a rich source of vegetable protein, can also be found in
a range of pretty tasty meat and dairy substitutes _ soy hot dogs,
burgers, cheese, even bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Calcium: Soybeans, collards, kale, dandelion greens, mustard
greens, turnip greens, broccoli, bok choy (spoon cabbage), okra,
rutabaga, almonds and most dried fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Iron: Beans, lentils, nuts, hummus, raisins, dried prunes and
prune juice, potatoes with skin and processed foods that have been
fortified with iron. Foods rich in vitamin C enhance iron
absorption, so drink orange juice with iron-fortified cereal, or
toss sliced tomatoes and nuts into your salad.
</P>
<P>
   Zinc: Whole grains, wheat germ, tofu, tempeh, miso, nut, seeds
and legumes.
</P>
<P>
   B vitamins: Whole-grain and enriched cereals, bread, avocados,
dark green vegetables, green beans, lima beans, bananas, nuts and
potatoes. Vitamin B12 is found only in animal products. A strict
vegetarian can get this vitamin from fortified nutritional yeast,
B12 fortified soymilk or B12 tablets.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
