<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-FLIGHT-FEAR-LIFEBEAT-     06-26 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-FEAR-LIFEBEAT-743-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF FLYING? FLIGHT PHOBIA CAN BE TREATED WITH VIRTUAL REALITY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    ART ADV: (Photos of an airplane and of someone receiving virtual
reality therapy are available in JPEG format by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    Shawn O'Leary writes for HealthSurfing.com.
 &HT;    
 By SHAWN O'LEARY 
 c.2000 InterNetwork News 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Imagine you're in plane flying at 33,000 feet and confined to a
middle seat. Encountering routine turbulence, the plane begins to
shake. There's no way out and your life is in the hands of the
pilots up front. You begin to panic, hyperventilating, perspiring
and trembling.
</P>
<P>
   While flying is routine for many, this scenario, and ones like
it keep millions from traveling on airplanes or boarding flights
without several stiff drinks or anti-anxiety pills. The fear tends
to heighten after heavy media coverage of an airline crash.
According to one phobia treatment center, those who fear flying
feel view themselves as ``baggage that breathes.'' However, fear of
flying can now be treated with virtual reality therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Flying phobia is heightened anxiety that's out of control and
unreasonable. ``A phobia is a fear that has gone to a level where
you either avoid a situation or you experience it with intense
anxiety,'' says Dr. Brenda Wiederhold, a phobia psychologist at the
Center for Advanced Multimedia Psychotherapy at the California
School of Professional Psychology in San Diego, California.
</P>
<P>
   Phobias can seriously limit the experience of family and career.
A lot of people give up promotions, they haven't seen their
grandkids in years, they haven't gone to family reunions. ``It's
something that's causing them not to live life fully,'' says
Weiderhold, who is director of the Center.
</P>
<P>
   Today the one in six Americans who consider themselves fearful
flyers might be able to find help with an unusual treatment for
overcoming their emotional trauma. It's called ``virtual reality
exposure therapy,'' and it's the closest thing to being there.
Increasingly available through mental health practitioners and
clinics, this therapy is helping some people overcome the fear of
flying.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it works. In the controlled environment of a
therapist's suite, patients, watching a 3-D graphic animated movie
on a computer, experience a trip on an airliner, complete with the
sights, sounds and vibrations of flying. The animation is similar
to today's interactive video games.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual reality (VR) method accelerates traditional
treatments of exposure therapy and desensitization. By confronting
rather than fleeing the object of fear, a person becomes acclimated
to a situation, gaining a sense of being more in control. The
terror or dread that was once felt dissipates.
</P>
<P>
   Says Wiederhold, ``It's being used to treat a variety of
phobias: social phobia, fear of public speaking, fear of heights,
fear of driving.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech VR treatment is also being used to treat other
fears, phobias and stress disorders including headache stress,
Attention Deficit Disorder, temporomandibular joint disorders and
Raynaud's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Arachnophobes _ people with an abnormal fear of spiders _ and
child cancer patients who face painful chemotherapy, have also been
helped.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Lawry's fear of flying arose from a nightmarish,
turbulent flight many years ago. Since then, she has avoided
flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plane was rocking and rolling and honestly, I thought,
'This plane isn't going to make it,''' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   When she's been forced by circumstances to board a flight, she
suffers great anxiety about the weather. She's only been able to
fly with several glasses of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   With her, as with many others who fear flying, the feeling of
being trapped and the fear of crashing trigger air anxiety. Loss of
control is at the root of both.
</P>
<P>
   Eight to 12 sessions is a standard course of treatment that
yields successful results for many. Says Wiederhold, ``It doesn't
work for everybody, but we have a huge success rate and people can
be helped. They don't have to suffer with this forever.'' Some
patients require follow-up refresher sessions if fears return.
</P>
<P>
   Biofeedback is part of VR therapy. Therapists monitor vital
signs as patients imagine themselves on a plane that may have a few
bumps, but never crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they have rapid heart rate, sometimes they start to
hyperventilate,'' says Wiederhold. ``We try to get them to slow
their breathing (with) diaphragmatic breathing (and) thought
stopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Treatment programs in North America, Australia and Europe
include visits onto parked planes and meetings with pilots to
further promote desensitization.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Roberta Lawry will be ready to board a plane without having
to relax with alcohol. ``I don't want to not go somewhere just
because I don t want to get on a plane,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawry can take comfort from statistics that indicate flying is
safer than driving. On average, a passenger would have to fly daily
for 32,000 years before experiencing the worst case scenario _ a
crash.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
