<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SELLECK-WESTERN-NYTR-     06-26 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELLECK-WESTERN-NYTR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLECK SAYS WESTERNS ARE NOT RIDING INTO THE SUNSET 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE HUISKING   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ To the e-mail generation, westerns are about as
relevant as the Pony Express. At least that seems to be the
perception in Hollywood. But Tom Selleck doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The popular actor, who is riding tall in the saddle as the star
and executive producer of his new western, ``Crossfire Trail,''
thinks the genre still has plenty of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think audiences are hungry for those classic stories of
characters facing moral dilemmas,'' said Selleck, who introduced
``Crossfire Trail'' Saturday in its world premiere at the Sarasota
Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people, who didn't grow up with westerns as I did, seem
particularly hungry for stories that are entertaining, but that
also deal with certain standards,'' Selleck said. ``I work a lot
with at-risk kids, and that's the impression I get from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, most action-adventure plots follow that classic
western form. I mean, `Star Wars' was really a western. The
Hollywood studios think they have to put some new twist on the
form. And certainly you can shoot westerns in a modern way that
audiences will like better. But the form still works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossfire Trail,'' a TNT Original Film, is based on a Louis
L'Amour novel. Selleck plays a restless drifter who must uphold a
promise to a dying friend. The cast also includes Wilford Brimley,
Mark Harmon and Joanna Miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossfire Trail'' won't air on TNT until 2001. But in August,
TNT will broadcast ``Running Mates,'' a drama that stars Selleck as
a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, who first gained fame as the star of television's
long-running ``Magnum, P.I.,'' appeared last month in the
season-finale of NBC's ``Friends.'' It was his ninth appearance
over the years as a doctor in love with Monica (Courteney Cox).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flattered that they asked me back,'' he said. ``They
have treated me as a visiting member of the family. Their writers
are so good. They created a real character for me. It wasn't just a
case of stunt-casting for sweeps weeks. The cast members are a
great group of people who deserve all the money they're getting.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
