   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   GENOME _ WASHINGTON - Leaders of the effort to map the human
genome are to announce Monday that a crude map, something like a
national road map that shows only interstate highways, is complete.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GENOME-CELERA _ Profile of Celera, the private biogen company
that put the Human Genome Project on the fast track to completion.
Story will explore who has the right to patent human genes and
whether this particular intersection of science and commerce is a
smooth operation or an accident waiting to happen. Also: how the
stock market responds to today's announcement. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-THERAPY _ The completion of the Human Genome Project should
usher in a whole new revolution in medicine, but it may take a
while for the results to move from the lab to the doctor's office.
CDC genetics experts, and other specialists, say the completion of
the HGP places medical researchers at the starting line, not the
finish line, in the creation of new gene therapies. Said another
way: researchers have created a software program that allows PC
users to tell that they have emails messages in their systems; but
they haven't figured out how to open those emails to see what they
say and mean. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   DENTAL-EMERGENICES _Summer's in full swing, with baseball,
pick-up basketball, jungle gyms, roller skating and skateboarding.
The result: A season filled with chipped or knocked out teeth. What
is a parent to do? This is a step-by-step guide of what to do if
your child suddenly has a dental emergency. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-TRICLYCERIDES _ This story will be about the threat
triclycerides have on the heart that can subsequently lead to
death. A study released by the AHA said there is a high risk in
families that have history of this chemical present in the body.
(Anthony, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SALT-SENSITIVITY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Federal health bureaucrats
have long talked about high blood pressure as though salting food
is barely more safe than sprinkling it with chips of lead paint.
Their single-minded harping on sodium is troubling to people who
research high blood pressure without a political agenda. They worry
that people will figure they can eat as many hot fudge sundaes as
they want as long as the peanuts are unsalted. (Lamb, Dayton Daily
News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CARDENAS _ MEXICO CITY _ Apparently mired in third place,
leftist opposition presidential candidate Cuautehmoc Cardenas has
little or no hope of winning the July 2 contest. But some say that
handwriting has been on the wall for some time. Yet, Cardenas has
refused to call oFf his run for the presidency in favor of
combining with the leading opposition candidate Vicente Fox to
defeat the long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
Less than a week from this historic election, we ask just what this
career politician and former Mexico City mayor is trying to
accomplish here. Developing. (Ferris, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
