<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5410 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GENOME27-COX     06-26 1787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT, CORPORATE SCIENTISTS DECODE HUMAN GENOME
 &HT;    520&AMP;add. With GENOME-CELERA.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 3 billion-word human genome, a molecular ``book
of life'' that contains information for unimaginable new insights
into human biology, has been decoded, scientists announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the government-funded Human Genome Project and
officials from a competing private venture set aside a bitter
scientific race and joined President Clinton in announcing that
nearly all of the genome has been defined and sequenced.
</P>
<P>
   Separate completion of 97 percent of the human genetic map by
the government scientists and a team from the biotech company
Celera Genomics could open the way to a powerful new era of
curative drugs - and violation of human rights in ways never before
possible, both groups said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Venter, president of Celera, said understanding the genome
could lead to reducing cancer deaths to zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are learning the language in which God created
life,'' Clinton said. ``We are gaining ever more awe for the
complexity, the beauty, the wonder of God's most divine and sacred
gift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Venter, a pioneer genetic researcher, formed Celera two years
ago and set out to use supercomputers and laser-driven molecular
analyzing techniques to rapidly decipher the sequence of more than
3 billion ``base pairs'' that form the spiraling double helix of
human DNA.
</P>
<P>
   He announced that Celera had sequenced the genome of five
individuals _ two males and three females _ who identified
themselves as Hispanic, Asian, Caucasian and African American.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Clinton and Venter, Dr. Francis Collins, head of
the Human Genome Project, announced that an international network
of scientific collaborators had also produced a ``rough draft'' of
the genome.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups have agreed to publish their separate _ and
apparently nearly identical _ genetic maps in a
yet-to-be-determined scientific journal in September.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the race has been the sequence of four molecules
in the human gene.
</P>
<P>
   The molecules of human genetic material, comparable to rungs in
a twisted ladder, are known as ``base pairs'' and are identified as
``A,'' ``T,'' ``C'' and ``G.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of tens of thousands of appearances of the four
rungs may define a single gene. Altogether, the sequences define
30,000 or more human genes. The genes control human biology,
determining who has blue eyes and who has red hair _ but more
significantly, who is susceptible to which disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists called the base pairs words in the ``book of life,''
and said understanding what the book tells them should make it
possible to treat disease at the molecular level.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that personal genetic information could also be misused,
both Collins and Venter hailed Clinton's efforts to get laws passed
protecting Americans from discrimination by insurance companies,
employers and others on the basis of ``predictive'' genetic
information the new maps will make possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever needed a wake-up call to say it's time to do this,
isn't today that day?'' Collins said. ``The train is coming very
close. It is bearing down on us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Venter said his group has defined the genome in terms of the
sequence of 3.14 billion occurrences of the four molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the government-funded project had indications the
genome consists of 3.17 billion base pairs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scientists from the United States, researchers in
Germany, France, England and China collaborated in the genome
project. Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain joined Clinton by
satellite in hailing the new map.
</P>
<P>
   The race between Celera and the public genome project became
intense in the last year and has led to name-calling on both sides
_ most frequently by unidentified sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy that today the only race we are talking about is
the human race,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he went to an intermediary in early May and asked him to
see if Venter would be interested in a joint announcement. This led
to a series of meetings between the two scientific rivals and,
ultimately, to Monday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the cost of the genome project has been roughly
$300 million so far, or a nickel for each of the Earth's 6 billion
people.
</P>
<P>
   His project has posted the results of its sequencing work on the
Internet, with updates every 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Venter's company was founded with a $1 billion investment by the
Perkin-Elmer Corp., now known as PE Corp., maker of telescopes,
microscopes and other scientific instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Venter said the company did not expect to make a profit by
commercializing the gene code, but through selling the expertise it
acquired in the sequencing work.
</P>
<P>
   He announced at an afternoon press conference that during the
morning meeting at the White House, another pharmaceutical company
had contacted Celera about doing business together.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock rose sharply on the NASDAQ stock exchange
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As he opened the meeting in the White House East Room, Clinton
noted that in the same room, nearly 200 years earlier, explorer
Meriwether Lewis showed President Thomas Jefferson the maps from
the Lewis and Clark Expedition of what would become the U.S.
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a map that defined the contours and forever expanded
the frontiers of our continent and our imagination,'' the president
said. ``Today, the world is joining us here in the East Room to
behold a map of even greater significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Among about 100 scientists and their guests who gathered at the
White House was Dr. James D. Watson, who in 1953 co-authored a
scientific paper describing the structure of DNA. Nine years later,
Watson and his fellow scientist, British biochemist Francis Crick,
received the Nobel Prize for their discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Watson compared the mapping work to the invention of the
printing press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, let's print some books,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.nhgri.nih.gov/index.html, www-shgc.stanford.edu,
www.hgsc.bcm.tmc.edu/
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story CIDE IF BIAS MOTIVATED HATE CRIMES, HIGH COURT RULES
</P>
<P>
   By ROB O'DELL
</P>
<P>
   c.2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Juries, not judges, must decide whether hate crimes
were motivated by racial bias in order to be subject to lengthier
sentences, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled 5-4 that any factor, except for a prior
conviction, that increases the maximum penalty for a crime must be
charged in an indictment, submitted to a jury and proven beyond a
reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The decision overruled a New Jersey law that provides an
``extended term'' of imprisonment if a trial judge finds, by a
preponderance of evidence, that the defendant acted to intimidate
an individual or group because of bias.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that the basis for the extended term must be
found beyond a reasonable doubt by a jury instead of being decided
by the trial judge.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling overturned a 12-year prison sentence imposed on a
white New Jersey man who fired shots into a black family's home in
1994. The man is entitled to a jury trial on whether he acted out
of racial bias, the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, Justice John Paul Stevens said the case
was a question of procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Jersey procedure challenged in this case is an
unacceptable departure from the jury tradition that is an
indispensable part of our criminal justice system,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislative scheme removes the jury from the
determination of a fact that, if found, exposes the criminal
defendant to a penalty exceeding the maximum he would receive if
punished according to the facts reflected in the jury verdict
alone,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1994, Charles C. Apprendi Jr., was arrested for
firing shots into the home of a black family that had recently
moved into an all-white neighborhood in Vineland, N.J. Apprendi
made a statement _ which he later retracted _ that he shot at the
house because ``they (the residents) were black in color and he did
not want them in the neighborhood,'' the opinion said.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi pleaded guilty to two counts of second degree
possession of a firearm for an unlawful purpose, which carries a
maximum penalty of five to 10 years in prison. None of the counts
referred to a hate crime statute, and none alleged that he acted
with a racially biased purpose.
</P>
<P>
   However, the trial judge concluded that there was enough
evidence to sentence Apprendi under the ``enhanced'' sentence for a
hate crime, which carries a maximum penalty of 10 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge sentenced Apprendi to 12 years, and Apprendi
challenged the sentence on the ground that it violated the
Constitution's due process clause.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court rejected Apprendi's claim that the clause
requires that a bias finding be proved to a jury beyond a
reasonable doubt, a decision that was affirmed by the New Jersey
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned those decisions
Monday, and ruled Apprendi is entitled to a trial by jury to
determine whether he acted out of racial bias.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' opinion was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, David H.
Souter, Clarence Thomas and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Sandra Day O'Connor, Stephen G. Breyer and Anthony M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the dissenters, O'Connor said, ``Our court has long
recognized that not every fact that bears on a defendant's
punishment need be charged in an indictment, submitted to a jury
and proved by the government beyond a reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard P. Berkowitz, national chairman of the Anti-Defamation
League, said
</P>
<P>
   the ADL is disappointed by the Supreme Court's ruling on this
particular statute, but applauds the court's continued support of
hate crimes legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court did not back away from its previous ruling that
bias-motivated crimes are among the most destructive to victims and
to society, and that perpetrators of these crimes deserve more
severe sentences,'' Berkowitz said. ``The decision merely clarifies
the appropriate standard of proof for sentencing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court decisions: www.supremecourtus.gov or
supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Defamation League: www.adl.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
