<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-IRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL ENVOYS INSPECT IRA WEAPONS DUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ The Irish Republican Army announced Monday
that two international envoys appointed as weapons monitors had
inspected a number of its secret arms dumps, and the pair confirmed
the news in visits to the prime ministers of Britain and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors, Martti Ahtisaari, the former president of
Finland, and Cyril Ramaphosa, the former secretary general of the
African National Congress, reported to the two prime ministers that
they had seen ``a substantial amount of military material.'' They
said they had satisfied themselves that it was ``safely and
adequately stored'' and had made sure that ``the weapons and
explosives cannot be used without our detection.''
</P>
<P>
   They said they intended to revisit the hidden stockpiles
regularly to ensure that the weapons ``have remained secure'' and
noted that the clandestine guerrilla force had met all their
requests. ``The process that led to the first inspection visit and
the way in which it was carried out makes us believe that this is a
genuine effort by the IRA to advance the peace process,'' they
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The development was hailed by both Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
of Ireland and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain as a
significant advance in the effort to put into effect the terms of
the Northern Ireland peace settlement, which has been plagued by
the dispute over weapons. Blair stressed that the arms inspections
were a valuable ``confidence building measure'' but did not satisfy
the longer range goal of complete disarmament. ``It is not
decommissioning itself,'' he said. ``It is a step on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement fulfilled a promise made by the IRA in May in
response to demands that it move toward dismantling its arsenal in
exchange for Britain's restoring the authority of the new
Catholic-Protestant power-sharing Northern Ireland government. It
had been suspended in February over earlier IRA inaction on arms.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA also confirmed Monday that it had ended its four-month
boycott of the international disarmament commission led by a
Canadian, Gen. John de Chastelain, and was cooperating with the
panel again. The commission is charged with determining whether the
disarmament envisioned in the agreement is satisfactorily carried
out and is the body to which Ramaphosa and Ahtisaari will report
their findings. It is formally independent of the British and Irish
governments, which sponsored the talks that led to the April 1998
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA is thought to have an arsenal of automatic rifles,
pistols, machine guns, grenades, rocket launchers and ammunition
stashed in underground spots in woods and fields across Ireland and
in border areas of Northern Ireland. It was not known whether the
two high-profile inspectors were made aware of the exact locations
of the dumps they examined or what portion of the overall arms
cache they had inspected.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari and Ramaphosa gave no details of how they had
satisfied themselves that the weaponry they saw would remain out of
use, but Ahern said the bunkers they had visited would be entombed
and re-examined periodically to make sure the seals had not been
broken.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Northern Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson, said the
inspectors had given him ``a lot of confidence'' that the IRA did
not intend to remove or use weapons in the inspected dumps. ``There
is a device in place that would indicate whether or not that is the
case,'' Mandelson said. He said it was important not to disclose
more details because there were dissident republican groups who had
not declared cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   The two monitors said they had consulted arms-control
specialists with experience in inspecting and verifying weapons to
come up with ``credible'' means of doing the job themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the political arm of the
IRA, praised the IRA for being ``very, very courageous'' and called
Monday's action a ``huge step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and
Labor Party, who is the deputy leader of the new home-rule Northern
Ireland Assembly, said, ``It marks another step in realizing the
full potential of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, leader of the largest Protestant party, the
Ulster Unionists, and first minister of the legislature, was in the
Middle East and due back in the province on Tuesday. Sir Reg Empey,
an Ulster Unionist minister in the government and a close ally of
Trimble, said the announcement constituted a ``breakthrough'' but
cautioned, ``There is still a lot further to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the peace settlement were predictably harsher. ``I
have made it clear that the inspection of a few arms dumps does not
represent progress in itself,'' said Jeffrey Donaldson, an Ulster
Unionist challenger to Trimble's party leadership. The Rev. Ian
Paisley's hard-line Democratic Unionists dismissed the development
as a ``complete and total gimmick, not a complete and total
cease-fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the IRA and Protestant paramilitary groups have observed
cease-fires for more than three years. For much of that time, the
IRA has argued that its success in silencing its guns should be
proof of its commitment to a peaceful resolution of Northern
Ireland's troubles. But more recently it has had to take steps like
the one announced Monday to meet insistent political demands for
taking guns out of the politics of Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong feeling within the republican movement that
disarmament constitutes surrender, and it has made the IRA
extremely reluctant to turn over arms. Adams called the move to
permit inspections by independent outsiders an ``imaginative'' way
to meet the IRA's pledge last month to put its weapons ``completely
and verifiably beyond use.''
</P>
</TEXT>
