r e BC-MUSIC-VIDEOGAMES-TEX     06-26 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VIDEOGAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANDS MAKING TRACKS FOR VIDEO GAMES IN HOPES OF BROADENING THEIR
FAN BASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ During its April show at local punk-rock
pitstop the Galaxy Club, Suicide Machines singer Jason Navarro had
a question for the audience: ``Any of ya heard of Tony Hawk's Pro
Skater?''
</P>
<P>
   One might have expected a few hands to be raised. Rather, the
entire audience let out a collective howl.
</P>
<P>
   When the Detroit-based Machines launched into the track, one of
many that's featured on the popular skateboarding video-game for
the Sony PlayStation, several kids in the crowd sang along.
</P>
<P>
   That night perfectly epitomized the way video games and music
are becoming more entwined.
</P>
<P>
   Stroll through any video-game shop and you'll find dozens of new
PlayStation, Sega Dreamcast and PC games that feature music from
high-profile bands and artists, from well-established acts such as
the Chemical Brothers to new groups like Apartment 26 and the
Suicide Machines, and even veterans such as David Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent examples:
</P>
<P>
   Several tracks from David Bowie's last disc, hours ... are
featured in Eidos Interactive's action/adventure PC and Dreamcast
game, Omikron: The Nomad Soul.
</P>
<P>
   The PlayStation's destruction derby title Twisted Metal 4 uses
songs from metal pundit Rob Zombie and hip-hop outfit Cypress Hill,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   Grind Session, a new skateboarding PlayStation title, contains a
smorgasbord of alternative rock tunes from Sonic Youth, Black Flag,
NOFX and KRS-One.
</P>
<P>
   Hugely popular punk outfits the Offspring and Bad Religion have
songs prominently featured in Sega Dreamcast's Crazy Taxi title.
</P>
<P>
   This marriage of games and music is, bands and game-industry
experts say, broadening the fan base of artists and giving the
games more depth. And the games and bands are reaping the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure's the No. 1 thing,'' says Suicide Machines bass
player Royce Nunley. ``Something like this is great if you're a new
band and you wanna get your music out there. Kids that play video
games may hear a song (on the game) they like, say, `Hey, this
sounds cool,' then go out and buy the record. It just leads to more
kids hearing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Having cool music pump in the background, as opposed to the
clinky music of video games of yore, adds a new dimension to the
gaming experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It benefits the games more than anything,'' says Umi Tangalin,
store manager for video-game shop Funcoland in Fort Worth. ``Used
to be, all you had was cheesy video-game music that looped over and
over. Now you have decent music that loops over and over. It
definitely sets a mood. The music on Tony Hawk gives you the
skateboarder feel. I used to skate and always had punk music on a
jambox playing. Tony Hawk really reminds me of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing cluster of games that tout tunes from name
brand artists, the intertwining of rock music and video-games dates
to the dawn of home gaming. Back in the '80s, lite-metal outfit
Journey, for instance, had its own game for the Atari 2600.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend really took off with the advent of the CD-based
Sony PlayStation home gaming unit and the rising popularity of PC
CD-ROM games. Road Rash, a PC and PlayStation title in which
players manned a maniacally driven motorcycle, was one of the first
games to use music from well-known artists, Pearl Jam among them.
</P>
<P>
   The titles that really opened the door to this trend, though,
were Wipeout and its sequel, Wipeout XL, a pair of futuristic,
Hovercraft-racing games for PlayStation that used hypnotic techno
tunes from the Chemical Brothers and Prodigy. An instrumental
version of the Prodigy's Breathe, spotlighted in Wipeout XL, helped
pave the way for the vocal version, which later became a hit for
the British techno band.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't surprise me,'' says Paul Baldwin, vice president
of marketing for Eidos Interactive, when told Wipeout XL helped
expose the Prodigy. ``If you look at the game consumer, the 18- to
34-year-old male, it's the same demographic for music as it is
games. People who buy games are just as aware of movies and music.
There are 50 million game systems in the U.S., so it's inevitable
they would converge.''
</P>
<P>
   So how do bands get picked for video games?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two ways,'' says Rob Alvarez, product manager for Sega of
America. ``They approach us, we approach them. But how we pick who
we're going to use depends on the game. We look at the content,
then evaluate what type of music fits in the game. It's like the
movie industry. They want to pick songs for a movie that set an
emotional tone. We try to do the same thing. We wanna create a
sense of fear, love, tension. We want to totally immerse the gamer
into a compelling world.''
</P>
<P>
   As Alvarez says, the trend is becoming so popular, several
artists are now approaching game companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jackson approached us about doing some music for the
new Ready to Rumble (wrestling game),'' says Baldwin. ``People like
him are realizing that gaming is a viable form of entertainment.
For a lot of people, it's their top choice of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
