<SLUG> BC-ECOM-HONEYWELL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE I-BUSINESS IS CONCERNED, HONEYWELL IS JUST GETTING STARTED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Color photos are available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   DANBURY, Conn. _ Think of the Internet. The imagery that comes
to mind is romantic and exciting: dot-com billionaires barely out
of school and colorful Web sites offering all sorts of wares and
intriguing ways to shop. What definitely does not come to mind are
Sherrell Coppedge and Kara Sylvia, seated recently at two ordinary
desktop computers in a plain, windowless room at Honeywell Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For eight weeks, four hours a day, Coppedge and Sylvia have been
trying to trip up the new Internet ordering system that Honeywell's
consumer products group, based here, is installing. Soon 2,000
customers _ auto dealers, parts distributors, lube centers, retail
chains _ will be logging on to Web sites to place orders for
Autolite spark plugs, Fram oil filters and Prestone antifreeze. No
more orders by telephone or by fax, and much less paperwork. But
first, the speedy new system has to function.
</P>
<P>
   Working from thick loose-leaf notebooks, Coppedge, 34, and
Sylvia, 26, carefully type in complicated, quirky orders, each a
probe for shortcomings in the system's software. When a flaw
appears, Jon Nehlsen, a 25-year-old Internet specialist, takes
charge of the fix. All three are salaried employees earning less
than six figures, the two women much less. None of the windfalls
from wildly lucrative dot-com stock offerings come their way. And
yet they and thousands like them are laboriously making the
Internet a backbone of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, with its endless Web sites, is already a
miraculous storehouse of information, an instant communicator, a
new medium, a vast electronic shopping mall, a link to Wall Street.
But for all the excitement over the prospect of an Internet
connection in every home, this is not where the big money is. What
companies spend buying and selling goods and services to one
another dwarfs consumer spending. The score last year was $14
trillion to $3 trillion. Like Honeywell, brick-and-mortar companies
are just beginning to shift these intercompany sales to the
Internet. Until they make the full transition, the Internet age
will not truly have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   And it is slow in coming. A lot more is involved than just
logging on. Honeywell's consumer products group, for example, has
three disparate, aging computer systems that track 17 factories and
more than $1 billion in annual sales. Getting those computers to
talk to other companies through the Internet is not easy. When
Coppedge and Sylvia _ simulating outsiders _ hit a trouble spot, it
is often because one of their orders placed through a Web site
failed to enter the company's internal computers. Some version of
Honeywell's painful progress is popping up everywhere in corporate
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lion's share of American companies are in the throes of
this conversion,'' said Clyde R. Moore, chief executive of the
Thomas &AMP; Betts Corp. in Memphis, which makes electrical switches
and connectors. A multi-million computer investment is just being
completed. The more sophisticated system updates the company's
inventories more quickly than before, for example, thus reducing
the risk of selling a connector over the Internet that is not in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites for consumers are easier to create, and many companies
now have them. They put these sites on computers dedicated to the
Internet. A car buff, for example, can pull up a Honeywell site and
find the filter he needs to change the oil in his car himself.
Punch in a ZIP code and the site lists the nearest retail outlets
selling the filter _ along with maps and directions on how to get
there. The entire database is maintained separately from
Honeywell's internal computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer is clearly the hare in this race. Still, the
tortoise, even in this difficult early stage, has already moved out
front. Intercompany transactions over the Internet totaled $90
billion last year, a drop in the bucket given the potential but
nevertheless more than five times the $16.7 billion that consumers
spent over the Internet, according to the Gartner Group, a
consulting firm that tracks such data. The $16.7 billion included
brokerage fees to trade stocks online.
</P>
<P>
   But what route the tortoise will take to the finish line is
still unclear. Business-to-business commerce over the Internet
means that companies will have access to the data in one another's
computers, like access to a stranger's bedroom. ``What the Internet
does is make the boundaries between companies much more fuzzy,''
said Paul Osterman, an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Sloan School of Management. With boundaries fading,
mergers, and challenges to antitrust law, may multiply.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is also giving fresh impetus to trends already well
under way. American companies, for example, find that the Internet
gives them easier access to suppliers overseas. Competitive
Internet auctions are forcing suppliers, here and abroad, to cut
prices more than in the past. And stockpiles of unsold goods _ a
burden in hard times _ are likely to shrink; the Internet helps
companies place smaller orders more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   There is one unambiguous benefit: labor productivity. The
Internet should make possible more output, or at least the same
output, from fewer hours of work. The 28 employees in Honeywell's
consumer products group who now take orders by fax and phone will
eventually be reassigned, their tasks automated as corporate
customers shift to ordering online _ 2,000 this year and the
remaining 2,000 thereafter. Some of the 28 might be reassigned as
traveling sales reps to sign up more customers. Business would then
grow without having to hire more workers, another gain in labor
output.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential exists for the nation to achieve real
productivity gains,'' said Alan Blinder, a Princeton University
economist. The gains are just beginning to kick in, Blinder noted,
as business-to-business commerce over the Internet _ almost
nonexistent in 1997 _ finally takes hold and spreads.
</P>
<P>
   More noticeably, the incipient Internet age is breeding a new
type of electronic marketplace. Beyond one company selling goods or
services to another, companies in the same industry are offering
their products jointly on a common Web site, inviting buyers to
choose from among their joint offerings. A new marketplace, to sell
plywood or chemicals or steel or accounting services, is announced
almost weekly. Honeywell's avionics division is participating in
one, to sell aircraft parts and repair services. The main customers
are airlines and the owners of corporate jets.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers are also setting up joint marketplaces, the best known
being one announced earlier this year by General Motors, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler. Most of the $240 billion a year in parts and
materials that the Big Three purchase to make vehicles are to be
listed on common Web sites, and thousands of suppliers will bid
online for the business, almost certainly pushing down their
prices.
</P>
<P>
   There is a catch, however. Lacking expertise, the
brick-and-mortar companies are relying on outside contractors to
design and maintain their electronic marketplaces. Often the
contractors are young, profitless dot-coms scrambling for a
permanent foothold. Whether they will share in the control of these
marketplaces, and the revenue they generate, or simply collect fees
as technical agents is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell, for example, took the lead in setting up the
marketplace for aircraft parts and repair services but offered
shares to the United Technologies Corp., another big maker of
aircraft parts. ``To attract the likes of United Technologies, we
had to be willing to share ownership,'' said Michael R. Bonsignore,
Honeywell's chief executive. The necessary expertise in Internet
technology _ to set up and run the marketplace _ comes from a
start-up, i2 Technology, which also has an ownership stake but not
much leverage. It lacks any merchandise to sell on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few dot-coms are trying to mimic the New York Stock
Exchange, which owns and runs the principal trading house for
corporate stocks. FreeMarkets Inc. in Pittsburgh is in hot pursuit
of this goal. Big manufacturers like Emerson Electric, Honeywell
and United Technologies now turn regularly to FreeMarkets to round
up suppliers, who then bid against one another on auction-style Web
sites set up by FreeMarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our FreeMarkets is going to be a major node, and we are now a
major business-to-business marketplace,'' said Glen Meakem, the
35-year-old founder and chief executive, whose four-year-old
company, for all its success, is losing money. ``We are too far
along for that to be taken away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   From the early days of the Industrial Revolution, business has
struggled with the problem of unwanted inventories, which are the
stockpiling of goods that later cannot be sold. Computers have
helped to keep inventories in check, and now business-to-business
commerce over the Internet offers corporate America, particularly
manufacturers, a new and perhaps powerful tool in this struggle.
That is because the Internet is turning out to be the least
expensive system developed, so far, in which companies can talk to
one another through their computers.
</P>
<P>
   But to hold down inventories, the hookup has to go in two
directions: to customers at one end, as Honeywell's consumer
products group is doing with its new order system, and to suppliers
at the other end. Then when one of Honeywell's customers _ the
Jiffy Lube chain, for example _ orders a thousand oil filters, the
suppliers at the other end will instantly know this and begin to
make the metal casings, filter elements and tops, shipping them to
Honeywell factories for final assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The broad goal is to manufacture only what is needed, when it is
needed. In good economic times, companies everywhere have tended to
overproduce and stockpile, fearful _ for lack of timely information
_ that they could not meet a flood of orders. These are good times,
and Honeywell still has ``$3.5 billion in working capital tied up
in inventory,'' Bonsignore said.
</P>
<P>
   Stockpiles, although smaller than in the past, are still a
shadow over the economy. When slowdowns inevitably arrive,
production is cut back abruptly, exacerbating the hard times until
inventories are reduced. The great hope is that production swings
in the Internet age will be less abrupt.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet hookups that link customers to their suppliers
are still in their infancy. Only a few companies have completed the
process: I.B.M., for example, and Wal-Mart. A decade ago, before
the Internet, Wal-Mart connected the cash registers in its stores
to its thousands of suppliers so that a shirt sold in Omaha
registered with the company that made it in South Carolina. That
pioneering system, however, required a huge investment in special
computers and dedicated phone lines. Few other companies matched
Wal-Mart's achievement, and in 1998 Wal-Mart itself switched its
network entirely to the less expensive, more flexible Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Most American companies are more like Honeywell than Wal-Mart.
Honeywell's consumer products group is only now about to go online
with its order system for business customers, and its avionics
group in Olathe, Kan., only recently hooked into the computers at
Cessna, a big customer for the cockpit controls and navigational
devices that Honeywell makes.
</P>
<P>
   Far more quickly than in the past, Honeywell is now privy to
Cessna's shifting production schedule _ not only how many planes
Cessna will make in the months ahead, but also how many of each
model and their delivery dates. ``Honeywell takes this data, runs
it through its computers and explodes it down to parts numbers for
its suppliers,'' said David Oppenheim, Cessna's supply chain
manager and chief of its e-business.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. The explosion down to Honeywell's suppliers has not
happened yet. But it will soon, the company promises. Links through
the Internet to 12 of its 800 suppliers are about to go live. In a
conference room at the avionics group's headquarters in Olathe,
Jeffrey C. Small, manager of supply chain infrastructure, recently
demonstrated the new system, flashing Web sites from his laptop on
to a big white screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day when a supplier logs on, he will see his situation
with us,'' Small said, displaying a dummy supplier Web site filled
with hyphenated parts numbers, new and old orders, parts needed
quickly, others needed not so quickly. ``It has taken 18 months to
develop this system and it seems like it has taken forever.''
</P>
<P>
   More visible is the Internet auction house operated by
FreeMarkets. The auctions are a novelty even for a technology full
of novelties. Suppliers worldwide bid over Web sites on their
laptop computers. Giant mother versions of these Web sites, several
feet high, cover most of a wall at FreeMarkets' headquarters in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   As the bidding proceeds from the laptops, the numbers change on
the mother Web sites, which have bluish backgrounds that glow in a
slightly darkened room the size and shape of a small college
lecture hall. As the auction proceeds, sometimes for three hours,
young people (average age 31) counsel the bidders by telephone.
They have designed the Web sites to call attention to the big
justification for Internet auctions.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent column of numbers tells the big corporate buyer
how much money the company is saving from the last time it bought
this particular item. More often than not, that last purchase was
pre-Internet style, through sealed bids. Opening these envelopes,
the buyer then chose the lowest one. In the Internet auction, the
competing suppliers see one another's bids. And if the falling
numbers are not prod enough to keep shaving bids, separate graphs
on the glowing Web sites plot the action downward.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell's avionics group, in this new world, saved $400,000,
or 19.5 percent, in the May purchase of various parts for $1.7
million. Owens Corning bought $24 million worth of corrugated
packaging through an online auction, saving 7 percent. And the
Carrier Corp. saved 16 percent on the purchase of air-conditioner
motors, mostly from Asian suppliers for the company's Asian
factories.
</P>
<P>
   Carrier's parent, United Technologies, has bought a stake in
FreeMarkets, which has frequently issued new stock to raise much
needed capital. That may help to explain the enthusiasm of Edward
Williams, Carrier's vice president for purchasing. ``We spend $3
billion a year on suppliers, and we are running $100 million of
this through FreeMarkets,'' he said. ``I would like to keep that
number growing.''
</P>
<P>
   What is less talked about are two changes in American business
practices that the Internet auctions encourage. One is the tendency
to ignore long-term relationships with suppliers and award the
business to the qualified bidder offering the lowest price, or to
the long-term supplier if it cuts its bid. Japanese companies had
favored long-term relationships with suppliers, without forcing
them to discount, and in the 1980's, when corporate Japan seemed so
successful, American companies went that way, too. Now the pendulum
is swinging back, thanks in part to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese companies tried to partner a lot,'' Meakem of
FreeMarkets said, ``and the Asian crisis proved that noneconomic
cozy relationships don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The other change is the new encouragement to seek less expensive
suppliers overseas, a trend well under way before the Internet. The
Internet makes worldwide bidding feasible and dramatic, although
the recruiting of overseas suppliers remains a rather old-fashioned
task. Half of FreeMarkets' 497 employees spend their time not
running electronic auctions but searching for suppliers in
trade-association directories and trips abroad, painstakingly
building up a huge database of potential bidders.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the May auction, Honeywell's avionics group
received from FreeMarkets a list of 600 possible bidders from this
database. By auction day, the list had been trimmed to 22 that met
Honeywell's standards, some from as far away as Israel and China.
That was still far more than the three or four suppliers that
traditionally mailed in sealed bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason why we could not have recruited many more
suppliers in the past if we had made the effort,'' said Doug
McCambridge, e-business project manager at Honeywell's avionics
group. ``The Internet is now pushing us to make the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: SMALL CHANGES START TO ADD UP
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, with its easy accessibility, is generating various
small corporate efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Chubb Corp., the big insurer, for example, provides workers'
compensation insurance to multinational corporations at their sites
worldwide. Before the Internet, the executives in charge of
workers' compensation at Chubb's client corporations gathered
information about accidents by telephone, fax, e-mail, even floppy
disks mailed to the home office.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Chubb's claims adjusters arrived by similar routes.
With the data finally entered in a central computer, the executives
could pinpoint the most frequent types of accidents, where they
occurred most often and other trends that, if reversed, might
reduce accidents and thus the company's insurance premiums. Now Web
sites set up by Chubb provide all this information more quickly, in
greater detail and with new analytical tools for spotting trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is leveraging a public infrastructure just
as truckers leverage public highways,'' said Doug Nordstrom,
Chubb's manager of business technology planning. ``And our
customers are demanding that we use the Internet to give them
information in real time. If you don't give it, you are at a
disadvantage. Someone else will and take away the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Controls Inc. in Milwaukee, which makes temperature
controls and other products, uses Web sites to help its field
representatives repair controls installed in commercial buildings
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The field representative logs on to a company Web site and
``accesses our huge database until he finds a similar problem and
solution,'' said James H. Keyes, chairman of Johnson Controls.
There is much less need for costly experts at the other end of a
phone line to answer a representative's questions, Keyes added,
``and the repair job is faster.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
