<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ECOM-VENTURE-CAPITALI     06-26 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-VENTURE-CAPITALISTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 MONTHS, 10 MINUTES, $10 MILLION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 By COURTNEY BARRY  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ 8 a.m. Thursday, May 4. Nervous, bleary-eyed,
already highly caffeinated, 21 finalists in the Texas Venture
Capitalist Conference wait for the lineup at the Four Seasons
Hotel. Today they will pitch their business plans, each in a span
of 10 minutes, each hoping to secure the start-up money to become
an overnight Internet success, complete with initial public
offering and a listing on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The partners in WebTaggers.com _ Rudy Rouhana, 24, Sean
McCullough, 25, and his twin brother, Craig _ have been working
nonstop toward this moment since last July, when Rouhana and Sean
McCullough, graduates of New Mexico Tech University, ran into each
other in Austin, had a beer and tossed around ideas for a new
company.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea had to do with posting messages on Web pages,
but that has evolved. Now the company's business plan describes
WebTaggers as ``an application service provider that delivers
highly targeted content for e-merchants,'' enabling retailers from
Barnes &AMP; Noble way down to Bob's Books to learn the preferences of
potential customers who surf their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   WebTaggers had to clear high hurdles to get here. Two-hundred
twenty companies across the nation applied for a place at this
morning's conference, according to David Gerhardt, the president of
Capital Network, the nonprofit economic development firm in Austin
that organized it. Capital Network's team of early-stage investors
winnowed that number to 21.
</P>
<P>
   On this warm and humid May morning, WebTaggers' three
principals, along with David Chevalier, their 45-year-old chief
executive, are putting the finishing touches on Chevalier's
10-minute pitch. For the last 18 hours they have allowed me to
observe their last-minute preparations, and between cups of
lukewarm coffee and frantic phone calls, they have been filling me
in on their short, eventful history.
</P>
<P>
   The three young partners made their first official move last
August, hiring a law firm _ Gray Cary Ware &AMP; Freidenrich of San
Diego _ and working on patent issues. By fall, they had raised
their first million dollars in venture capital, from an Austin
company called AVLabs.
</P>
<P>
   From that experience, Rouhana said, he and his partners learned
an interesting business principle: ``Once you have a venture
capitalist, everyone wants to start dating you.''
</P>
<P>
   AVLabs took the partners through a ``think and drink''
conference, at which potential investors and chief executives meet
entrepreneurs over a cocktail to see whether they are a good match.
(As Sean McCullough later noted, ``We were asked if we were old
enough to drink.'')
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, they met Chevalier. They needed a leader, said
Rob Adams, the founder of AVLabs, adding, ``They were
optimistically naive _ they didn't know what they didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevalier, a tall, dapper former vice president at Dell
Computers who has led six other start-ups to success, stepped on
board Dec. 1. His job was to develop the company's structure, hire
people and, most important, get financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At certain stages,'' he said, ``CEOs of dot-coms spend 90
percent of their time raising money.'' And that is his job today,
at what he calls the ``beauty pageant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In that 10-minute pitch I've got to give the whole story,''
Chevalier said. ``And ask for $10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4 P.M. WEDNESDAY, MAY 3 &LR;  Seventeen hours to go. Craig
McCullough, tired, head in hands, sits in WebTaggers' office in
north Austin in front of a computer, barely keeping his eyes open.
Computers are everywhere; desks are strewn with papers.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McCullough, slim, quiet, with a goatee and a nose stud, is
reviewing resumes for the six positions they must fill. Rouhana,
tall, confident, eager and sharp-witted, is on the phone talking to
potential investors who are not part of the venture capital
conference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8 P.M. &LR;  Craig McCullough takes the business plan to a printing
shop downtown to make copies. Chevalier is rehearsing his pitch on
his trip back to Austin from San Francisco, where he has just met
with another start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McCullough and Joe Gorman, the company's marketing
director, are writing final code and planning screen shots for the
company demos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9:30 P.M. &LR;  Tomorrow's audience, the venture capitalists, are in
the lounge of the Four Seasons. They are well groomed and
prosperous looking: casually dressed but exuding confidence. They
are here to have a good time, drinking in the lounge, but are
restless, as though ready and eager for the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Rouhana is here, working the venture capitalists. He talks shop
with Bryan Steffen, of the Berthel Fisher Co. A round of drinks
arrives. Nobody seems daunted by Rouhana's clothing, which is pure
grunge: T-shirt and baggy, faded olive-drab military pants. (At the
pitch the next morning, he will be wearing the same outfit.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 11 P.M. &LR;  Throughout the night, phone calls have been flying
back and forth. At 11, Rouhana learns there is a problem with the
printing job for the business plan: the shop, backlogged, does not
have the right binders.
</P>
<P>
   Craig McCullough and WebTaggers' network administrator, Vance
Shtraikh, roll up their sleeves and head over to help with the
print job. Back at the hotel suite, Sean McCullough is trying to
open a port on WebTaggers' server: They must be able to connect
from the hotel to show the demos. Sometime after midnight, Sean
succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2 A.M. THURSDAY &LR;  The partners have connected with Chevalier,
whose flight from Dallas was delayed and who has just made the
four-hour drive to Austin in a rental car. He had been told by the
event's sponsors that on the night before the pitch, there would be
a dress rehearsal of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `No problem, you guys come in any time _ we'll be
there,''' Chevalier said. ``Well, with all my flight delays and
having to drive from Dallas, I ended up at the Four Seasons at
midnight or 1 in the morning, and nobody was there in the hotel
ballroom. Basically it was just me and all the hotel employees,
setting up the chairs and tables. And so I said the hell with it. I
just got up and rehearsed my pitch on my own to the hotel
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3, after debating whether to try to get some sleep, the
partners and Chevalier decide to get breakfast at an all-night
diner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7 A.M. &LR;  The conference kicks off with a buffet breakfast. A
Nasdaq representative, Chris Santiago, tells the audience how the
exchange has added 228 companies just since January.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, but is anyone paying attention? People look up,
acknowledge that he is talking, turn back to their tablemates and
sip their coffee. Eyes skirt the room; the venture capitalists seem
to be wondering, ``Who should I be talking to here?''
</P>
<P>
   The room is awash in business cards floating from hand to hand.
In the lobby during the presentations, there is a friendly
competition among the service providers, and perhaps a biting envy
lurking beneath.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and accountants have booths with slick slogans
(``Winning Matters''). They smell money and are dying to land these
new companies as clients. At one law firm booth, representatives,
friendly at first, offer me a book on Silicon Valley; when they
realize I am not a presenter, they dismiss me with a curt ``Enjoy
your book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8:01 A.M. &LR;  One hour until showtime. Craig McCullough calls
Rouhana from the print shop. The business-plan copies are done at
last. Chevalier is suited up and ready for the pitch, so ready that
he sits in on the four other company pitches before his.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9:18 A.M. &LR;  Chevalier speaks before an audience of more than 600
investors, developers, service providers, lawyers, accountants and
others. He opens with a joke about an incident involving his
family, but it is his delivery that is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of the presenters, who cling to the lectern, he uses
the front of the room as a stage, walking confidently around as he
speaks. He seems to know intuitively what the venture capitalists
want to hear. ``Very smooth,'' one says.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a success? The WebTaggers guys say they will not know
until the wire transfer date, Aug. 15, when WebTaggers anticipates
that funds from investors will have traded hands.
</P>
<P>
   After that? Jan. 1, 2001, the ``fume date,'' which no one really
wants to think about _ the point at which, if no venture capital is
coming in, the partners must admit defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not going to happen,'' Chevalier said, and there
was reason to hope that he was right. Though the recent skid in
technology stocks has made venture capitalists want to ``look for
deals only with bulletproof economic models,'' as he put it in an
interview in late May, the company is showing a profit. And any day
now, it is expecting to receive its first formal proposals from a
short list of potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtney Barry, a writer in Austin, Texas, has just finished
her first novel.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
