<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTERMANDING MILITARY, MOSCOW RENEWS ATTACKS ON CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ One day after a top military commander announced a halt
to artillery and air strikes in Chechnya, the Kremlin said Monday
that the attacks would continue.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal raised questions about the military's
pronouncements and was a setback for the government effort to win
Western understanding for its military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the commander of Russian forces in Chechnya, Col.
Gen. Gennadi Troshev, said his troops were suspending major combat
operations, including air and artillery strikes. Troshev commented
after meeting Akhmad Kadyrov, the Chechen official whom President
Vladimir Putin chose this month to administer Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to the common conclusion that the war, as such, is
over on the territory of Chechnya,'' Troshev said. ``An agreement
was reached that the Unified Army Group is not conducting offensive
operations and not carrying out aviation or artillery strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks were consistent with the Kremlin's basic line that
the war would soon be won and that the republic would soon return
to peaceful life. But the promise of a moratorium on artillery and
air strikes was new and appeared calculated to boost Kadyrov's
standing with the Chechen public.
</P>
<P>
   Although he opposed the Russians in the first Chechen war, from
1994 to 1996, Kadyrov cooperated with Moscow after the second
Russian military intervention, in September.
</P>
<P>
   Aslan Maskhadov, president of the breakaway Chechen republic
before the intervention, has condemned him as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov has been trying to present himself as a unifying figure
in Chechnya and to mobilize opposition to Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev's comments also appeared calculated to ease Western
concerns, particularly on the part of the Council of Europe. At the
council, representatives have criticized the Russian military for
carrying out indiscriminate attacks in Chechnya and they have
discussed whether to expel Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini of Italy recently led a
delegation from the council to Russia. Russian officials assured
him that the military was scaling back its operations in Chechnya.
Apparently persuaded, Dini said over the weekend that Moscow had
declared a ``de facto cease-fire.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday it turned out there was no cease-fire, de facto or
otherwise. The bombing continued as usual, as SU-25 planes and
helicopters hit rebel positions in the mountains. Russian news
agencies reported that dozens of air attacks had been carried out.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Russian government, Sergei Yastrzhembsky,
scrambled to explain and qualify Troshev's comments. In an
interview, Yastrzhembsky said the government was not presenting a
new initiative. Rather, he suggested, Troshev had merely been
trying to describe the fact that the military is relying less on
artillery and air strikes as the rebels have increasingly turned to
guerrilla tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no particular initiative, only a confirmation of the
current state of affairs,'' Yastrzhembsky said, adding that he
spoke to Troshev Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzhembsky said the military would continue to use artillery,
but that it ``would be conducted on rare occasions and outside of
populated areas.'' Russian forces would also continue air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only natural that if militants are seen in the forest,
we will use aviation and artillery,'' Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
   A significant number of troops had been withdrawn from Chechnya,
he said, but did not provide specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's field generals have become accustomed to appearing on
television, giving news conferences and making pronouncements,
often eclipsing the civilians in Moscow. Their comments have not
always been consistent with those of military or civilian spokesmen
in Moscow, adding confusion to the already jumbled situation in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, military commanders have said there had been
information that the rebel commander, Shamil Basayev, was dead and
that Maskhadov was wounded, assertions that have yet to be
confirmed, and the commanders have sometimes clashed with other
pronouncements in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev's comments on Sunday were taken seriously because he was
so explicit and because he was talking about forces under his
direct command. Troshev, a generally garrulous officer, was quiet
Monday, allowing the Kremlin to do all the talking.
</P>
</TEXT>
