<SLUG> BC-UNCERTAIN-SEARCH-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CERTAIN CHARM OF UNCERTAIN, TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCERTAIN, Texas _ Lexie Palmore of Uncertain, Texas, is haunted
by what lies beneath her steamboat as she negotiates the shadowy
channels of Caddo Lake.
</P>
<P>
   She is certain, or nearly so, that what she wants to find is
there, maybe scattered among the underwater roots of bald cypress
trees, maybe seen by the lake's alligators or red-eared slider
turtles, but not by any human in 133 years and 134 days.
</P>
<P>
   It was that long ago that the 150-foot, steam-powered paddle
wheel Mittie Stephens, loaded with hay, cotton and gunpowder,
burned and sank in Caddo Lake about midnight Feb. 11, 1867. Sixty
of the 100 passengers and crew drowned.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago, Palmore, 52, a licensed riverboat pilot,
moved from her home in Tyler to Uncertain in far East Texas, with a
certain goal. She wanted to hunt for pieces of the wreck. She
immersed herself in the lake, searching in the murk for artifacts.
Caddo is a 26,700-acre maze of channels, and the lake twists and
turns around fingers of bayou. Palmore searched just one portion of
the lake. Its depth fluctuates, and always has. These days it is
mostly about 6 feet deep. She'd break the lily pad-laden surface as
she came up for air, then dive again. She never found a thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mittie Stephens remains in an uncertain place.
</P>
<P>
   And Palmore is not certain where _ or if _ she'll ever find any
remnants of the wreck. Meanwhile, she's found something else
instead in the small town bearing the Uncertain name.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain, Texas, lies at 32 degrees latitude and 94 degrees
longitude on the shores of Caddo Lake, near the Louisiana and
Arkansas borders. Nowadays TV broadcasters insist on calling the
border area by the ungainly name of ``Arklatex.'' Locals don't. Not
in Uncertain or along Big Cypress Bayou or near any of the
wonderfully named regions of Caddo Lake _ Whangdoodle Pass,
Whistleberry Slough, Devil's Elbow or Death Hole.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the semitropical environs of Uncertain are ``Texas.''
It just looks a lot like postcards of Louisiana bayous.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain has its roots as a place where definitions _
certainties _ shift like the shadows of the swaying Spanish moss.
Governments couldn't agree on who owned the region. Steamboats
couldn't always navigate the fluctuating lake levels or find
landings.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1800s, the flag of Spain flew over Texas. To the
east, the United States had staked out the Louisiana Territory. The
border between the Spanish and U.S. territories was disputed. The
area that is now Shelby, Panola and Harrison counties of Texas was
then a lawless place known as the neutral ground, where no one knew
their legal nationality. When Texas became a state in 1845, the
border between Louisiana and Texas was drawn and split the lake
between the two states.
</P>
<P>
   Steamboats making their way from New Orleans and Shreveport to
Jefferson, north of Caddo Lake on Big Cypress Bayou, passed by the
region in the mid- to late-1800s. Then, before lake levels dropped
enough to hinder navigation, Jefferson became the second largest
port in Texas, after Galveston. But more than one steamboat sank in
the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Duck hunters and bass fisherman started setting up camps along
Caddo Lake in an area known as Uncertain Landing, believed to have
been named because the fluctuating water levels made docking an
iffy prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing changed in Uncertain for about a half-century. A cluster
of buildings along the shore made up a rustic resort. Then W.L.
``Beer'' Smith came to the area in the 1950s with ideas on how to
enlarge Uncertain. He built an air strip to attract visitors,
although the prospect of an ``Uncertain Airport'' must have made
some pilots balk. He wanted to build a better water system, because
existing wells were uncertain to yield clean water. He wanted to
run a liquor store, but liquor sales were illegal in Harrison
County. Anyone who wanted a drink rowed out to ``beer boats'' that
moored mid-lake. So Smith led the effort to incorporate Uncertain
in the early 1960s, his daughter, Dottie Carter, 61, says.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
