<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5435 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-HISPANICS-HNS &LR;      06-26 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH URGES RULE CHANGE TO HELP IMMIGRANT FAMILIES ENTER U.S.  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush told a leading Hispanic
American organization Monday that he wants to change immigration
rules to make it easier for foreign nationals to join their
families already in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also told several hundred delegates at the annual
convention of the League of United Latin American Citizens that, if
elected president, he would press Congress to breakup the
Immigration and Naturalization Service into two separate agencies.
One agency would include the U.S. Border Patrol and would combat
illegal immigration and the other agency would expedite the
applications of legal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, sprinkling his remarks with phrases in Spanish, said U.S.
immigration regulations should be changed to reflect ``family
values'' by permitting immediate family members of legal permanent
residents in the United States to obtain visitor visas while
waiting permanent entry to join their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department about 1.1 million spouses and children
under 18 have won approval to reside in the United States with
relatives who are either U.S. citizens or are legal permanent
residents. But the approved immigrants often wait for years to
permanently enter the United States under the annual worldwide
quota of 425,000 for all family members seeking entry in the United
States to take up permanent residence.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee, echoed
traditional Republican calls for ``tough'' enforcement measures
against illegal immigration along America's borders, calling
enforcement the ``responsibility'' of government.
</P>
<P>
   But he said enforcement needs to be carried out in ``a humane
way'' and emphasized that the INS has equal responsibility to
expedite the processing of legal immigrants entering the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as people are coming to feed their families, our
country must be mindful that they are human beings as well,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials should be asking would-be legal immigrants ``how
can I help you'' rather than emphasizing ``how long the line will
be'' to process an application for admission, said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be saying loud and clear to people that the INS is
to help families and to understand the maze of rules and
regulations,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar breakup of the INS is the goal of bipartisan
legislation sponsored by Reps. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, Silvestre
Reyes, D-Texas, and Harold Rogers, R-Ky. The bill is pending in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Vice President Al Gore, the presume Democratic
presidential nominee, are locked in a tight race, according to the
latest nationwide poll, completed for Newsweek magazine and
released Saturday. Each has 45 percent of the vote, according to
the survey with a margin of error of 4 percentage points. In a
survey that pits Bush and Gore against the two third party
candidates who are running in the fall, Green Party nominee Ralph
Nader and expected Reform Party nominee Pat Buchanan, Bush leads
Gore 42 percent to 40 percent, with Nader drawing 3 percent and
Buchanan 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic voters potentially make up a swing constituency in 10
states with 213 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads Democrat Al Gore in five of the 10 states, including
Texas, Florida, Illinois, Colorado and Arizona, according to the
latest statewide polls. The five states account for 94 of the
electoral votes needed to win the presidency. Gore leads Bush in
four states with large Hispanic populations, including California,
New York, New Jersey and Massachusetts. The four states account for
114 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore are tied in New Mexico, a state offering the
winner 5 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who won re-election to a second term as governor of Texas
with almost half the Hispanic vote in Texas, is hoping to expand
that appeal to Hispanics elsewhere around the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeatedly emphasizes his open-arms approach to Hispanic
Americans in an effort to draw a sharp contrast with the
anti-immigrant rhetoric used by then-California Gov. Pete Wilson in
the early 1990s. Unlike Wilson, Bush has opposed restrictions on
the educational or social welfare benefits extended by the state of
Texas to the children of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is shadowing Bush's overtures to Hispanics.
Dag Vega, a Gore campaign worker and former White House press
official, worked his way from reporter to reporter during Bush's
remarks at a Washington hotel to hand out a five-page Gore campaign
analysis of Bush's record of assistance to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's ties to anti-immigrant Pete Wilson, his refusal to
support minority appointments and his opposition to Hispanic issues
such as the census, higher education and health care show that
Hispanics would be left behind under a Bush administration,'' the
Gore campaign release said.
</P>
<P>
   Vega criticized Bush for failing to intervene with GOP leaders
in Congress to clear the way for Senate confirmation of Enrique
Moreno, a lawyer from El Paso, Texas, who is awaiting Senate action
on his nomination to serve on the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
Texas Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison, both Republicans,
have opposed Senate action on President Clinton's nomination of
Moreno, saying the lawyer who has practiced since 1981 does not
have the judicial experience to join an appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm and Hutchison have urged Senate Judiciary Committee Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, not to approve Moreno's nomination because Moreno
has ``not achieved the level of experience necessary to be fully
engaged and effective on a court one notch below the United States
Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore speaks to the same LULAC convention on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
