<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-CONSORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS ON CONSORTIUM TEAM: SCIENTISTS TURNED CARTOGRAPHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Texas, Mass., England, Australia)   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With main bar, SCI-GENOME; see SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET for a complete
description of sidebar stories and graphics.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROBERT H. WATERSTON
</P>
<P>
   A physician interested in muscle disease, Robert H. Waterston,
56, was persuaded to study muscle disorders in the C. elegans worm,
then being established as a laboratory animal by biologists in
Cambridge, England. Waterston then became drawn into the project of
decoding the worm's genome. As director of the genome sequencing
center at Washington University in St. Louis, he and his English
colleague Dr. John E. Sulston decoded the worm's genome in December
1998; it was the first animal genome to be sequenced.
</P>
<P>
   Building on these methods, Waterston's center became the
spearhead of the National Institutes of Health's attack on the
human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, he wondered if with an earlier start the
consortium might not have done even more. ``John and I,'' he said
last week, referring to Sulston, ``were on record in 1994 as trying
to push things and saying the time was at hand. The people close to
the field saw it could be done and were impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHN E. SULSTON
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John E. Sulston, 58, is a biologist who directs the Sanger
Center, near Cambridge, England, which is the National Institutes
of Health's major partner in the Human Genome Project. Financed by
the Wellcome Trust of London, the center has decoded one-third of
the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Sulston is well known for having traced every cell in the C.
elegans roundworm, now a standard laboratory organism, from the
single cell of the egg to the 959 cells of the adult worm, a
10-year tour de force of assiduous microscope work.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his interest in the worm, Sulston began to decode its
DNA. The task, undertaken with Dr. Robert H. Waterston of
Washington University in St. Louis, became a pilot project for the
human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Within the community of worm biologists, Sulston championed the
view that knowledge and research tools should be free to all, an
ethos he carried over to the Human Genome Project. He and
Waterston, as well as the rest of the consortium scientists,
decided to release their genome data nightly as a gift to the
world's researchers.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD A. GIBBS
</P>
<P>
   Born in Australia, Dr. Richard A. Gibbs, 42, is director of the
sequencing center at the Baylor College of Medicine, the smallest
of the big three centers.
</P>
<P>
   He was drawn into DNA sequencing through an interest in
technology. ``It was apparent to me that technical advances could
increase our understanding and help answer very profound and simple
questions, like why are we different to chimps?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But DNA sequencing is a demanding process. ``To be a scientist
you have got to love it, because at a certain level you would be
disappointed so much of the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have got to love the unpeeling of knowledge; otherwise it
is very difficult to stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ELBERT BRANSCOMB
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elbert Branscomb, 65, directs the Joint Genome Center at the
Department of Energy, under the supervision of Dr. Ari Patrinos,
the associate director for biology. The department's human genome
project began as an outgrowth of its interest in radiation biology.
</P>
<P>
   ERIC S. LANDER
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a mathematician, Dr. Eric S. Lander, 43, became
interested in biology, and with the help of a MacArthur award
switched to the study of human disease genes. This interest led to
involvement in genome sequencing. Lander is now director of the
genome sequencing center at the Whitehead Institute in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   An early mathematical interest in the number 17 seems to have
come full circle as Chromosome 17 was among those Lander's center
was assigned.
</P>
<P>
   From his interest in human biological variation, Lander has
worked with Affymetrix, a maker of DNA chips, to develop a device
that would scan a patient's genes, pinpointing those that differed
from the consensus human sequence and that might make their owner
prone to certain diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
