<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-SKETCHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S WHO ON CELERA'S TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(With main bar, SCI-GENOME; see SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET for a complete
description of sidebar stories and graphics.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICHAEL W. HUNKAPILLER
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Hunkapiller, 51, is a co-inventor of the first DNA
sequencing machine, and is now president of PE Biosystems, a
subsidiary of the PE Corp. He estimated that a company using a
dedicated suite of his most recent model, the Prism 3700, could
obtain the human genome sequence faster than the public consortium
of academic centers, and persuaded Dr. J. Craig Venter to head the
project. At a stroke, Hunkapiller thus doubled the market for his
$300,000 machines.
</P>
<P>
   HAMILTON O. SMITH
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hamilton Smith, 68, shared the Nobel Prize in 1978 for the
discovery of restriction enzymes, a kind of molecular scissors used
by bacteria to cut up threatening viruses and by biologists as an
essential tool for manipulating DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a major scientific player in Venter's operations. He
has the critical task of preparing the libraries of cloned DNA
fragments for the DNA sequencing machines to work on. Venter has
made no secret of his reliance on Smith's work.
</P>
<P>
   EUGENE W. MYERS
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eugene Myers is a computer scientist and a leader in the new
field of bioinformatics, or computational genomics, the designing
of computer programs to analyze the genome.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 he and a colleague proposed the whole genome shotgun
method of sequencing the human genome, an idea rejected by the
public consortium. Venter, who had used the shotgun method before,
embraced the idea and hired Myers, who has written the programs for
assembling and analyzing Celera's human genome.
</P>
<P>
   MARK D. ADAMS
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Adams, 37, is another key member of Celera's scientific
team. His major role is to see that the whole operation _ DNA
libraries and clone-handling robots and DNA sequencing machines _
produces the range and quality of data required by Myers for his
genome assembly program.
</P>
<P>
   TONY LEE WHITE
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of the PE Corp., Tony White, 54, is the
architect of Celera. He was the one who bought Hunkapiller's human
genome idea and made the bold decision to convert Perkin Elmer, a
traditional scientific instrument maker, into a genomics company.
</P>
<P>
   Selling off the instruments and even the Perkin Elmer name,
White has organized the PE Corp. into two main divisions, Celera
and PE Biosystems. Celera's aim is to become a genomic database; PE
Biosystems sells DNA sequencing machines, to the public consortium
as well as to Celera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
