<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-PELOSI-WHIP-HNS &LR;      06-26 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-WHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI, WITH EYE ON LEADERSHIP, RAISES $1M FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Rep. Nancy Pelosi, who is campaigning to
become majority whip if Democrats win control of the House, said
Monday she had raised more than $1 million to help Democratic
candidates win seats this November.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Pelosi well ahead of her closest rival for the No. 3
leadership post in the House of Representatives, Rep. Steny H.
Hoyer of Maryland, who has raised $460,000 for Democratic
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the good news, I've raised more than a million,''
Pelosi said in an interview. ``The better news is that there is
more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   A liberal who represents San Francisco, Pelosi said it was
``becoming clear that I have an excellent chance to become the
Democratic whip.'' To do that, the Democrats must win at least six
seats to regain a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party believes the Republicans, who took control
of Congress in the 1994 election, are vulnerable because of voter
dissatisfaction with their handing of the impeachment of President
Clinton and their strident positions on issues such as gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Were Democrats to take control of the House, Rep. Dick Gephardt
of Missouri is likely to become speaker. Rep. David E. Bonior of
Michigan, the party whip, would become majority leader, leaving
open the post of majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi is maneuvering to win that No. 3 job by investing in
campaigns in hope of gaining support in the Democratic leadership
vote that would follow the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am demonstrating very clearly that I have a large
base of donors,'' she said. ``I'm in a good spot because I've been
working on this for years and it's all sort of coming together
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The whip is the party's top vote-counter, one charged with
keeping lawmakers in line on critical votes. ``Whipping'' requires
organizing coalitions, listening to members and sometimes twisting
their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the money she had raised ``all springs from the
strength that I have within my caucus and that people believe I
have a reasonable chance to win this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hoyer spokeswoman Deborah DeShonge discounted Pelosi's
fund-raising prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is a small part of running for whip,'' DeShong said.
``The big part is getting the House back.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Hoyer has been traveling the country recruiting
candidates since 1995. ``He's been doing this for several years,
not just when there is a whip race,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the contest is ``about wining the House and getting
the money out to the candidates.'' She said she has made ``a
special effort'' to donate to the campaigns of women.
</P>
<P>
   Leo McCarthy, a former lieutenant governor of California and now
Pelosi's treasurer, said the bulk of the money she has raised has
come from Northern California, with donors including ``mostly
business and professional people.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said Pelosi has donated to candidates even if they are
supporting Hoyer or Rep. John Lewis of Georgia in the whip's race.
Pelosi's average contribution to House candidates is $12,000,
McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi created a political action committee, called PAC to the
Future, which she uses to raise money and contribute to selected
candidates. Federal law limits her PAC to $5,000 contributions to a
candidate in the primary election and $5,000 for a candidate in the
general election. She may also donate $2,000 in an election cycle
from her own campaign treasury.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
