<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spinal Fluid
</P>
<P>
   Q. What organ produces spinal fluid? Should people eat certain
foods to make sure there is enough?
</P>
<P>
   A. Spinal fluid, or more properly cerebrospinal fluid, is
chiefly formed by a network of veins, called the choroid plexus,
that projects in tufted, fringelike folds into the pia mater, the
innermost of the three membranes, or meninges, that cover the brain
and spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   The fluid is clear and colorless and contains small amounts of
glucose and protein. Beyond eating a healthy diet and drinking
enough water to maintain a proper fluid balance, there are no
specific nutritional recommendations for making sure there is
enough spinal fluid.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fairly complex circulation pattern for spinal fluid,
which flows through the central canal of the spinal cord, in the
cavities of the brain and into the space under the meninges, called
the subarachnoid space. The fluid is eventually absorbed into the
venous system.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, spinal fluid leaks or is drawn out in a spinal
tap. Usually, the chief danger is not the loss of the fluid, but
the possibility of infection by contamination from outside the
body. A constant, sustained leak could cause low fluid pressure,
which can lead to chronic headaches; it would probably require
surgical correction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
