<HEADLINE>
SUNSET FOR JAPAN'S RULERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a sharp warning from Japanese voters to the entrenched
Liberal Democratic Party in Sunday's parliamentary election. Losing
its outright majority and being forced to rely on two coalition
partners to remain in government, the LDP was chastized for failing
to cope with Japan's entrapment in a cycle of deflation and debt.
</P>
<P>
   The message from the voters was not only that the LDP has not
been able to solve Japan's problems but that it is a prime cause of
those problems.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a prime minister's advisory council submitted a
report entitled ``Japan's Vision for the 21st Century.'' The
council expressed ``an anxiety that Japan might go into decline if
things stay unchanged.'' The report recommended innovations that
would be radical for Japan. Among the proposed changes were a
serious acceleration of deregulation, a reduction in the lavish and
unneeded public works spending that has mired the country in debt,
and direct election of the prime minister _ a reform that would
endow the head of government with a popular mandate, enabling him
to escape the coils of the bureaucracy and special interests.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret to Japanese voters that the LDP has followed a
stop-and-go policy on deregulation and has conferred construction
contracts on its cronies. The party also remains unaccountable, a
perennial governing party enmeshed with Japan's permanent,
policy-making bureaucracy and beholden to parochial corporate and
rural interests.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a decade of stagnation and $6 trillion in
debts rung up by local and national government. That debt amounts
to 1.3 times Japan's gross domestic product, or $48,000 per capita.
This deflation and debt endangers not only Japanese workers and
pensioners, but other Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   Any warning that Japan's unresponsive political elites must
change their ways is for the good. They and their favored friends
have to end their state-directed allocation of capital and their
protection of the ``keiretsu,'' or interlinked enterprise groups.
The electoral decline of the LDP will be healthy if it foreshadows
a Japanese economic recovery rooted in a flowering of truly free
markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
