<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DISABLED OUTDOORSMAN STILL RESPONDS TO THE CALL OF THE
MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was a beautiful, sunny day when the life
fortunes of Michael Bannister turned in a single moment.
</P>
<P>
   Bannister, 29, was climbing limestone cliffs in Thailand last
year, and after having made the top of one precarious ledge _ and
celebrating with a shout _ he stopped on his way down at a belay
ledge to help another climber.
</P>
<P>
   ``That climber was about 80 feet directly above me,'' Bannister
said. ``I was looking up right at him. Then I watched one of his
hand-holds tear loose from the wall and it was immediately followed
by a truckload of rock. I knew I was in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Those rocks came hurtling down at him, boulders the size of
grapefruits and television sets. Bannister reacted instinctively,
trying to press his body against the wall to avoid them. He almost
succeeded. But one large boulder struck his left leg with such
force that it nearly severed it just above the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hurt at first,'' Bannister said. ``It was a dull
crushing feeling and I kept holding on to the climber's rope,
keeping him safe up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannister was packed out in a make-shift stretcher by other
mountaineering experts. In the following days, before he could
return to the United States, the injury became infected. Weeks
became months. Back in California, surgeons attempted to repair the
damage, but never seemed able to. Finally, after 10 operations and
continued pain and immobility, Bannister agreed to have the leg
amputated.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, just six months later, Bannister is guiding rafting
trips on rivers, climbing the slopes of Mount Shasta, and was hired
this month as a wilderness guide and outfitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the decision on my own to have my leg amputated,''
Bannister said. ``I was looking at spending the rest of my life in
a ridged leg brace, and after doing a lot of research, it was clear
to me that I would have more freedom and mobility with a
prosthesis.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannister, who turned 30 last month, had the operation in
January. But it didn't heal and the limb became infected yet again.
That required two more operations, and finally, in March, doctors
got it right, and then in April, his prosthesis arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty shaky at first, because I had been on crutches
for a year,'' Bannister said. ``My leg muscles had atrophied. It
was almost as if I had to learn how to walk again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a month, though, he was getting around in his hometown of
Mount Shasta, ``feeling better every day,'' and the yearnings for
adventure began surfacing again.
</P>
<P>
   On May 22, Bannister made his first rafting trip, a trial run
with other guides, running a paddle boat down the Upper Sacramento
River for 12 miles, featuring 27 Class III rapids.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was a little bit apprehensive,'' Bannister said.
``When I hit the first rapid, I had an adrenaline rush, like I
didn't know what was going to happen. But after the first rapid,
the dance of the river came back to me like a long, lost friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a raft is pointed downstream, you do not have a lot of
choice in the matter, he noted. And by the end of the day, he had
triumphed for the first time since his catastrophic climbing
accident. In the month since, he was hired by Turtle River Rafting
and has guided seven days on the Klamath River.
</P>
<P>
   This turned out to be perfect therapy, he said. When facing a
rapid such as Dragon's Tooth on the Klamath, Bannister said he did
not have time to think about the past, about those rocks falling
out of the sky, right at him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when facing severe white water, he reacted with his
natural, athletic instincts and years of training.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, in the back of his mind, the call of the
mountain never would go away. In April, he ventured off on his own,
headed up to the 7,000-foot level on Mount Shasta and snowboarded
down for the first time since the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt, but it also felt great to ride down the mountain,''
Bannister said. ``Euphoric.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, Bannister has been taking his passions to
another dimension. He completed a guide training seminar with
Shasta Mountain Guides, a former employer, and after getting
approval from owner Michael Zanger, was re-hired to teach
mountaineering skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope soon to be guiding summit trips again,'' Bannister
said, envisioning one day again standing atop 14,162-foot Mount
Shasta.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he is experiencing much pain, Bannister shook his
head and added: ``It's more like phantom pain, but it's real. I
have pain in my foot, but I look down and it isn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Only now are the other guides realizing the ordeal he has
experienced, and how he is driven by a zest for life, an
exhilaration for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The way Bannister looks at things, every day is a page, every
year is a chapter. He plans on filling the rest of his life book
with his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most arduous task of my life,'' Bannister said,
``but it has made me find more inner strength and clarity than I
ever thought was possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
