<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-FATIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO GREAT MYSTERY': VATICAN RELEASES COMMENTARY ON FATIMA SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Seeking to end the mystery surrounding the so-called
third secret of Fatima, the Vatican Monday released a photocopy of
the handwritten manuscript with a commentary explaining how the
Vatican concluded that the prophecy referred to the 1981
assassination attempt on Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican news conference, broadcast live on Italian television
and on a worldwide satellite feed, was supposed to be the final
word on a long undisclosed prophecy that has fascinated Fatima
conspiracy theorists for decades and that was not fully put to rest
when the Vatican first revealed its interpretation last month.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that some people may remain ``disappointed or amazed
after all the speculation it has stirred,'' Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger, head of the Vatican's Congregation for the Doctrine of
the Faith, said: ``No great mystery is revealed. The future is not
unveiled.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did try to explain one of the more intriguing enigmas
woven into the Fatima legend, namely why the Vatican kept the third
secret under wraps for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a matter of dogma, but of prudence,'' Ratzinger
said in reply to a question. ``We didn't want to present an
undecipherable vision that would unleash speculation and insults.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, in books, doomsday cults and most recently, on Web
sites, Fatima enthusiasts speculated that the third secret,
revealed by an apparition of the Virgin Mary to three Portuguese
shepherd children in the village of Fatima in 1917, predicted the
end of the world, or an ideological rift in the Roman Catholic
church. Three popes saw the secret, according to the Vatican, and
decided not to release it. Finally, on May 13 at Fatima, the
Vatican secretary of state told an audience of 600,000 believers
that the secret actually referred to the attempted assassination of
John Paul II, a ``bishop clothed in white.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatima fanatics had held hunger strikes _ one even hijacked a
plane _ to try to force the Vatican to disclose the secret. Some
devotees were not fully convinced by Monday's revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no excuse for not releasing it sooner if this is all
there is,'' complained the Rev. Nicholas Gruner, director of the
Fatima center in Fort Erie, Ontario, who has lobbied for full
disclosure since 1978. He said he suspected that the manuscript
released by the Vatican was an authentic first draft, ``but not the
full statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican described the photocopy released Monday as the full
text, saying it was written on Jan. 3, 1944, by Sister Lucia, now
93, a Carmelite nun who is the only surviving witness to the
apparitions that believers say began on May 13, 1917. In her
recollection, the Virgin showed the three children an ``angel with
a flaming sword,'' and ``a bishop dressed in white _ `we had the
impression that it was the holy father.''' The letter goes on to
describe how the pope, ``half trembling with halting step,
afflicted with pain and sorrow,'' reaches the foot of a cross and
is ``killed by a group of soldiers who fired bullets and arrows at
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratzinger's commentary said the images were not to be taken
literally, but rather ``synthesize and compress against a single
background facts which extend through time.'' The vision reflected
the martyrdom of the church in the 20th century, and its warning
became clear, he said, in 1981. ``When, after the attempted
assassination of 13 May 1981, the holy father had the text of the
third of the secret brought to him, was it not inevitable that he
should see in it his own fate?''
</P>
<P>
   The pope has always credited the Virgin of Fatima with saving
his life. Archbishop Tarcisio Bertone, secretary of the
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, said Monday that the
pope did not see the third secret, kept in the archives of the
congregation, until after the 1981 attack, when he asked that it be
brought to him in the hospital. He added that Sister Lucia
confirmed the Vatican's interpretation in an interview he had with
her on April 27 in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Ratzinger, who explained that belief in the visions at Fatima
was up to individual Catholics and not an obligatory part of church
teaching, also spoke rather gingerly about Fatima's significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the intention of the church to impose a single
interpretation,'' he warned. ``But in light of history, we can
decipher the vision.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed the underlying message of free will, saying, ``The
future is not in fact unchangeably set, and the image which the
children saw is in no way a film preview of a future in which
nothing can be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican also stressed that the pope's would-be assassin,
Mehmet Ali Agca, who was pardoned and extradited to Turkey this
month by the Italian government with Vatican approval, had acted of
his own free will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must totally discount fatalistic explanations of the
`secret,' such as for example, the claim that the would-be assassin
of 13 May 1981 was merely an instrument of the divine plan,''
Ratzinger wrote in his commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``secret'' of Fatima was a vision of hell; the second
predicted World War II and warned that the collapse of Communism
would require that Russia be consecrated to the Virgin. Those
visions lent the shrine an anti-Communist mystique throughout the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to a question, Ratzinger suggested Monday that in
hindsight, the focus on Russia was perhaps too limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communism was classical atheism, but other systems, including
Nazism, were also radically atheist,'' he said. ``There is no
exclusivity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
