<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ALBRIGHT-POLAND-NYT &LR;      06-26 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-POLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE CAUTIONS ALBRIGHT CONFERENCE ON IMPOSING DEMOCRACY ON
NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ France offered an antidote Monday to some of
the celebratory tone of the conference on democracy here that was
spearheaded by the United States, saying that imposing democracy on
a country could have the opposite result.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine of France cited Fidel Castro and
Saddam Hussein as examples of authoritarian leaders who had only
been reinforced either by military force or economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he contended, while President Carter clearly did not
intend to bring about the Islamic revolution in Iran, his policies
had essentially helped bring about that result.
</P>
<P>
   Morton H. Halperin, chief of policy planning at the State
Department, parried Vedrine's statements, saying the conference was
not about the ``export'' of democracy but about enabling countries
that had ``chosen'' democracy to help one another.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine spoke to the gathering in the chamber of the Polish
Parliament after opening remarks by the host, Foreign Minister
Bronislaw Geremek. Vedrine then went out of his way to brief
American reporters on his thoughts about democracy and how his
philosophy on democracy differed from what he saw as the themes for
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   He was careful not to attack the particulars of the conference,
saying he had nothing to do with its organization and had come at
the express request of Geremek, his friend. He did not mention
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, whose conference this
essentially is and who is seeking to make the theme of democracy
the lodestar of her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lending itself to easy converts, perhaps like
religion, he said, democracy is ``always a process of evolution.''
And, he said, it overwhelmingly involves long maturing internal
processes within nations such as in economics, the collective state
of mind and _ in the end _ politics.
</P>
<P>
   Definitions aside, the French foreign minister appeared vexed
about the appearance that developed democracies are lecturing
others. Nobody, he suggested, has a magic formula for
``transforming Russia into a huge Finland, or China into a huge
South Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not be self-congratulatory,'' Vedrine added. ``Our
democracies still have room for improvement.'' He singled out the
role of money in influencing policy in developed democracies as
``terrifying'' and bemoaned the apathy of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from more than 100 countries, including foreign
ministers from many of them, are meeting here under the rubric
``Toward a Community of Democracies.'' The notion is to encourage
deeper democracy in the world by having countries commit themselves
to a set of principles laid out in what is being called the Warsaw
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have argued over the last few days that while
the number of countries with democratic attributes has vastly
increased _ by their count from 30 to 120 since 1974 _ much needs
to be done to consolidate democratic gains in the weakest nations
and stop backsliding in others.
</P>
<P>
   Countries that were judged by a seven-nation vetting committee
to be at least aspiring to democratic standards were invited.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, whose formal sessions began Monday and will
close Tuesday, is split into two entities: speeches and panels at
the Parliament for government leaders and a parallel gathering of
nongovernmental organizations in a building across town.
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent groups, the Washington-based Freedom House, and
the Stefan Batory Foundation, which was founded in Poland by the
financier George Soros, were asked by the State Department to
organize the parallel meeting, featuring speeches by human rights
figures from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials called the parallel meeting the World
Forum on Democracy, seeming to echo the title of the annual
conference at Davos, Switzerland, the World Economic Forum. And
they said they hoped the forum would take on a life of its own and
become the equivalent of a ``Davos of Democracy.'' Leaders of some
groups grumbled Monday that they found the comparison demeaning
since they had been working on building democracy at the
grass-roots level for many years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the emerging themes of the discussions Monday was the
issue of national sovereignty, raised most frontally by Vedrine but
also by others, who took a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   In a moving appeal on video, smuggled out of Burma and shown to
the foreign ministers this morning, the Burmese dissident, Daw Aung
San Suu Kyi, urged ``the peoples of the free world to work harder
toward bringing true democratic progress everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   She was not specific about what kind of action she wanted from
the outside world, but she hinted that some kind of intervention
was necessary. ``Words need to be backed up by action by action
that is united and that is focused on essentials,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his speeches, Geremek said that in ``normal
situations'' there should be no collision between sovereignty on
the one hand and human rights and democracy on the other. Nor, he
said, did he anticipate that globalization would abolish the idea
of the nation state.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``exceptional situations,'' which are ``not in fact so
very exceptional,'' he said, human rights and democracy take
precedence. One such example is when the state, instead of
protecting its citizens, becomes a threat to them. In this and some
other cases, the international community cannot stand by and watch,
he said, and must say, ``It's human rights, stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1838EDT &QL; 
