<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will erupt in the warm, humid air mass
along the East Coast as a cold front moves to the region later in
the day. Local flooding is possible in New England as storms move
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary between sultry air over the South and more pleasant
air across the Middle West will stall from the southern
Appalachians across the Tennessee Valley and into the southern
Plains. Clusters of thunderstorms will be common from northern
Mississippi to northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Damp, cool conditions will dominate the western Plains and
eastern Rockies. Numerous showers and storms will dampen Colorado
and New Mexico with fewer thundershowers over Utah and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest will stay dry and hot with a warming trend in
California. Fog will be nestled along the Southwest Coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: OUT OF AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, satellite pictures have shown a vast plume
of dust spreading gradually across the eastern tropical Atlantic.
The dust was initially lofted into the atmosphere by currents of
hot air rising from the floor of the Sahara. At this time of year,
it is common for weather disturbances moving east from the Africa
carry dust from the Sahara toward the Caribbean and the Americas.
Recent research suggests that dust from Africa makes up at least
half the particles that residents of the Southeast inhale on a
typical summer day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
