<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPLESS AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Jiri Vanek hasn't been able to sleep for three nights.
When he does doze off, it is the fitful snooze of the condemned. He
feels like an early Christian, penciled in for a date with lions at
Rome's Colosseum.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Vanek had joked about it, sort of gallows humor, even
though he didn't believe it actually would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he told friends, ``I've never played Wimbledon so
I'll probably draw Sampras in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his coach, Wojtech Flegl, got the word from London, and
relayed it: ``You play Sampras in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No way!'' screeched Vanek. Sounding like a convicted man
hearing the judge pronounce the direst of sentences, he shook his
head so hard that his shoulder-length flaxen locks flapped.
</P>
<P>
   But every year somebody has to be the sacrifice. They throw a
body into the arena called Centre Court for the reigning champion
to devour, and another Wimbledon is under way. Only twice in the
two previous centuries, 1967 and 1994, has this rite of swing
backfired. Charlie Pasarell disdained the role of lamb while
dismembering the 1966 champ, Manolo Santana. Lori McNeil did
likewise to the 1993 champ, Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Vanek does not emulate Pasarell or McNeil, but he isn't chopped
liver, either. More like a moderately tough cut-rate steak. He was
beaten, 6-4, 6-4, 6-2, by the champion but his family and neighbors
watching via TV in the village of Holysov, Czech Republic, can be
nothing but proud. Their Jiri is the lone tennis player produced in
a two-court town better known for its truck factory, and he has
been a necessary spare part in opening the Millennial Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon changes subtly, a new staircase there, a new press
center here, but seems unaltered beneath its coats of dusky green
paint. The usual queues of eager, early-arriving communicants
stretched in lines of almost a mile, patiently moving ahead until
they could purchase grounds tickets. At the gates, campers already
were pitching tents in order to get a head start in today's queues.
</P>
<P>
   The usual shower knocked out play for a couple of hours but was
welcomed by the usual array of roses and hydrangeas. They show off
beautifully, but no advertising blooms anywhere. It's a commercial
venture all right, yet done so tastefully that nobody notices.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne gurgled. Strawberries-and-cream and other edibles,
even hot dogs, tempted the throng of 35,941. A Dixieland band near
the refreshment court brassily offered, ``The Blues My Naughty
Sweetie Gave to Me.''
</P>
<P>
   And everybody's sweetie, Anna Kournikova, whose 10,000 Web sites
are hit more often than all the blackjack players in Las Vegas,
boogied perilously to a Centre Court victory over Sandrine Testud
after butchering three match points, 7-5, 5-7, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards of Kournikova peddling a sports bra flood London,
along with her advice (``Only the balls should bounce!'') but will
not be on view at the Big W.
</P>
<P>
   There is bounce yet in the tournament elder, 35-year-old
Gianluca Pozzi, even though he looks like a weary, straphanging
commuter with sore feet. Unlike the undistinguished wine from his
Puglia region, this Italian ages with distinction. He showed it
with delicate touch, in a slick, slice-and-dice 6-3, 6-4, 3-6, 6-1,
victory over Czech Jiri Novak, who defeated Pete Sampras two months
ago in Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm improving; I'll be better in three years,'' said Pozzi, a
lefty who ranks No. 59. Italian novelist Gianni Clerici said,
``Pozzi plays the kind of tennis we used to love. But Gianluca's a
bit self-delusional: He thinks he's still playing with a wooden
racket.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was no delusion for the 22-year-old Vanek as the genuine
Sampras appeared by his side shortly before 2 on a bleak, cool
afternoon. Vanek, who has been courting insomnia thinking and
fretting about this moment, nevertheless realized a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play the greatest player on the Centre Court at
Wimbledon,'' Vanek said. ``What more could a player want? Yes, I
was very nervous, but not after two games. I did not want to be
embarrassed, and I don't think I was.''
</P>
<P>
   No, he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:59 the ballboys and girls march onto the court in their
lilac shirts and green shorts (the All England Club colors). Then
the umpire and line judges follow in teal blazers. Finally, at 2,
come the combatants in pristine white.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mistaking the big-shouldered, dark-haired champion,
but the man next to him, just about as tall at 6 feet 1 inch and
sprouting a goatee, was recognized as a total stranger: Vanek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never heard of him,'' said Sampras of No. 84 Vanek,
considered the best of the young Czechs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking on,'' said Vanek, ``it was like a movie in slow
motion. I looked around. Wonderful. So green. The grass was like a
fine carpet, so soft on the feet. So many people around me. Many
more than in my town. I never bowed before, but they told me to
follow what Sampras did. We stopped, turned and bowed to the Royal
Box. I guess it was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had't been on a grass court for five years, only once then.
Lost here in the juniors, first round. Oh, they let me practice an
hour yesterday. My game is clay. But to play against Sampras . . .
he looks too big. He's everywhere. At the net there's no space to
put it past him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be with him, it was a great school. A learning. Why should
I be nervous to play anybody now? I've been on Centre Court with
Sampras. Something to tell people about, maybe grandchildren some
day.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right there on the campus of Sampras Tech, where
everybody flunks.
</P>
<P>
   Jiri Vanek was no different. But, he said with smile after his
masters class of 84 minutes, ``Tonight I will sleep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
