<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-WINNERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING GOVERNMENT JOLTED IN JAPAN BALLOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Sunday's elections may have returned Japan's ruling
government to power, but the nation is still trying to figure out
who won and who lost.
</P>
<P>
   A better gauge than the election tally might be the pictures of
politicians in newspapers and on television. The somber faces
belong to Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori and members of his
three-party coalition, stunned at how many seats they lost.
</P>
<P>
   The bright, smiling face belongs to Yukio Hatoyama, leader of
the four-year-old Minshuto party, Japan's largest opposition party.
It gained substantial ground, increasing its share of seats in
parliament to 127 from 95 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling coalition remains in power. Publicly at least, all
three members still support Mori, who announced he will form his
Cabinet on July 4. But many within Mori's Liberal Democratic Party
hold the prime minister, who has made several politically incorrect
gaffes since taking office in April, responsible for causing the
party to lose its majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the LDP leaders will start to undermine him from
behind, and a replacement might come in the future,'' said
political analyst Takashi Inoguchi.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts regard the Mori government's unconvincing
victory as further evidence of the Japanese public's preference for
the status quo, others see a faint sign that voters want change,
and that they have found a party to guide them there.
</P>
<P>
   The Minshuto party's slogan during the campaign was ``If you
move, Japan will change.'' Whether the party, which advocated
raising taxes to reduce the deficit, captured the voters'
imagination or was just well-positioned to absorb an LDP protest
vote, is not clear.
</P>
<P>
   Hatoyama, meanwhile, is relishing his party's gains, calling the
vote ``an important step toward realigning the political world into
two major parties.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past half-century, Japan's opposition parties have had
little success in mounting a challenge to the ruling LDP. For
decades, dozens of parties have morphed in and out of existence,
with politicians hopscotching between them. In the early 1990s, a
coalition of several opposition parties managed briefly to break
the LDP's hold. Another group, the New Frontier party, managed to
garner a large number of parliamentary seats in the mid-1990s, but
wound up imploding after four years.
</P>
<P>
   Hatoyama, 53, is typical of a Japanese opposition figure. Like
many, he started as an LDP member. He departed in 1993 to join
another party and left that to start Minshuto.
</P>
<P>
   A former university professor with a doctorate from Stanford
University, Hatoyama comes from a long line of politicians,
including his grandfather, a prime minister in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Minshuto's gains came at the expense of smaller
opposition groups, such as the Japan Communist Party, which had
been expected to garner a great number of protest votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, says political analyst Steve Reed of Chuo University
in Tokyo, it looks like voters wanted to support a larger party
like Minshuto ``because that's more than a protest. That's the way
you eventually kick the rascals out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if it is going to build on parliamentary wins, Minshuto
is going to have to work hard to convince the Japanese public,
including its supporters, that the party is worthy of someday
leading the country.
</P>
<P>
   Akiko Oki may have cast her ballot for Minshuto, but in reality
her vote was simply ``not LDP,'' as she put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want change, even though I don't think the policies of the
other parties like Minshuto are strong enough yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The main issue in Japan remains the lackluster economy, upon
which the government and the opposition sharply disagree. The Mori
government plans to keep its free-spending ways as an economic
stimulus. The opposition, in addition to calling for higher taxes,
had campaigned heavily to cut spending and bring down Japan's
skyrocketing debt.
</P>
<P>
   Hatoyama says the party will continue to push unpopular ideas.
As he said during the campaign, ``To win, you have to believe in
the conscience and good sense of the voters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
