<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5464 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRA-DISARM-BOS &LR;      06-26 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRA-DISARM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAPONS INSPECTION BOOSTS IRISH PEACE HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The peace process in Northern Ireland got a huge boost
Monday when the two men responsible for making sure the IRA's
weapons remain locked up said they had inspected several arms dumps
and that all their requests had been met satisfactorily.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time that the Irish Republican Army, one of
the world's most resilient, defiant revolutionary groups, had
allowed outsiders to inspect its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Prime Minister Tony Blair at 10 Downing St.,
Martti Ahtisaari, the former president of Finland, and Cyril
Ramaphosa, the former chief negotiator of the African National
Congress, announced that they had inspected several IRA arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ensured that the weapons and explosives cannot be used
without our detection,'' the inspectors said in a statement,
without elaborating on their verification methods. ``We plan to
reinspect the arms dumps on a regular basis to ensure that the
weapons have remained secure. The process that led to the first
inspection visit and the way in which it was carried out makes us
believe that this is a genuine effort by the IRA to advance the
peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   While the announcement caught some off guard, the British and
Irish governments were anxious that the first inspections took
place before the height of the annually contentious marching season
the second week of July, when Protestant groups try to march
through Catholic neighborhoods where they are not wanted.
</P>
<P>
   According to senior Irish and British diplomats, there was even
more pressure to hold the inspections because Ahtisaari is
scheduled to undergo knee surgery soon. Ahtisaari, who helped
broker the end of NATO's war with Yugoslavia last year, was limping
noticeably as he left Downing Street, shaking hands with Blair and
Peter Mandelson, the British secretary of state for Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, welcomed the
news. Ahern met with the inspectors in Dublin after they met here
with Blair.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's May 6 offer to allow inspections of its arms dumps in
the Irish Republic breathed life back into a dormant peace process.
It convinced a majority of the Ulster Unionist Party to go back
into a power-sharing government with Sinn Fein, the IRA's political
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process had stagnated noticeably in the past few weeks
as extremists on both sides tried to create havoc. Monday's
announcement was widely welcomed as momentum for those who want to
transform one of Europe's longest-running violent conflicts into
one that can be resolved politically and peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   After the arms inspectors' announcement, the IRA issued a
statement saying it had reestablished contact with the
international commission overseeing the disarming of paramilitary
groups in Northern Ireland. The IRA had broken off contact with the
commission in February after the power-sharing government was
suspended because it would not commit itself to disarming or say
its war was over.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming that an unspecified number of its arms dumps had been
inspected, the IRA said, ``These dumps contained a substantial
amount of material including weapons, explosives and other
equipment. The leadership of the IRA have consistently sought to
enhance the peace process. This initiative demonstrates once more
our commitment to securing a just and lasting peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Belfast, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
called the IRA gesture courageous and imaginative, and said it was
unprecedented in some 200 years of ``armed struggle'' by various
incarnations of Irish republican rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble called the inspections an
encouraging first step.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, which calls for
power-sharing and equality between Protesant unionists who want to
remain British subjects and Catholic nationalists who aspire to
unity with the Irish Republic, were not assuaged. Some dismissed
the inspections as a public relations exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed,'' said Peter Robinson, deputy leader of
the Democratic Unionists, who oppose power-sharing with Sinn Fein.
``The IRA is still engaged in an active terrorist campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari and Ramaphosa were deliberately vague about when,
where, and how many dumps they inspected, saying only they had
viewed several. Many observers have been openly skeptical over how
a limping, very large elderly Finn and a black man in a country
where there are few black people can secretly inspect hidden arms
dumps.
</P>
<P>
   But an Irish diplomat scoffed at that skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Ireland,'' he said, ``and anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspections were widely seen as vindication for Trimble, who
had convinced a majority of his skeptical party to go back into
government with Sinn Fein on the promise that the IRA would allow
international inspectors to verify that its arms dumps are secure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even moderate unionists like Reg Empey, a Trimble
confidante, said the IRA has to eventually get rid of its weapons
so that democratic politics can take root and bloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first step,'' said Empey. ``It is a breakthrough,
but it does not resolve the arms issue. There is a lot further to
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
