<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-DAVIDIANS27     06-26 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DAVIDIANS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI agents should have been rescuers, not demolition team
 &HT;    Editorial from Waco Herald-Tribune
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ While the nation hoped against hope that children
would be rescued safely from the Branch Davidian compound and that
lawbreakers would be arrested peaceably, FBI agents in armored
vehicles showed more interest in ramming techniques.
</P>
<P>
   That's what former assistant deputy FBI director Danny Coulson
implied in the federal civil trial continuing this week over the
April 19, 1993, events at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy authorized for ousting David Koresh and his
followers, Coulson said, was a slow and deliberate introduction of
tear gas through the windows. Instead, to the horror of most,
including FBI superiors, the vehicles began ramming holes in the
buildings. This was a demolition crew.
</P>
<P>
   In whatever way they commenced, flames finished off the
destruction. Government officials assert that the Davidians set the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Piecing these events together yields the image of a
then-brand-new attorney general, Janet Reno, giving orders and
watching them be overridden. It shows a cowboy mentality behind the
wheel of those armored vehicles, one manifested in several ways.
The vehicles also were used to destroy crime-scene evidence after
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Armored vehicles certainly were justified. The Branch Davidians
repeatedly demonstrated their willingness to fire upon government
agents. But the vehicles were misused. With innocents behind those
walls, government shouldn't have been poking holes in them. That's
what doors and windows are for.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to excuse Koresh and his gunmen, who could have
saved every life by surrendering peaceably on Day 1. Ultimately,
they are the most culpable parties for their end-of-the-world
armaments and hair-trigger recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the hideous sins that should have resulted in
Koresh's arrest in the first place _ sexual abuse of little girls.
The man should have been locked up long before he became a
household name.
</P>
<P>
   But wrapped around these atrocities are repeated instances in
which federal authorities acted recklessly, deceitfully and
capriciously with the alarming likelihood that innocent people
would be harmed in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Who put the children in harm's way? David Koresh and their
parents. Who failed to assure that the impasse would be resolved
without the loss of life? The United States government.
</P>
<P>
   The agents in the tanks got a commendation for bravery. Instead
they should have been cited for reckless driving. Some will call it
vehicular homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
