<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CANCERSURVIVOR-MEDSTU     06-26 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCERSURVIVOR-MEDSTUDENT-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER SURVIVOR FOLLOWING IN HIS DOCTOR'S FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Time was running out for Kurt Weiss. Osteosarcoma, a
rare bone cancer afflicting adolescents, was spreading quickly, and
tumors had developed in his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons operated to remove the tumors, and the 15-year-old
Weiss underwent chemotherapy. But the tumors returned, and he
underwent surgery and chemotherapy treatment again. And again. In
13 months, Weiss had three surgeries, followed by the debilitating
chemotherapy. Finally, his doctors told him they had done all they
could. They urged him to enjoy whatever time he might have left.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of miles from Weiss' home in Pittsburgh, Dr.
Eugenie S. Kleinerman, a professor of cancer biology and clinical
pediatrics at the University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center
in Houston, was making news by developing a technique to treat bone
cancers that spread to the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   M.D. Anderson is renowned as one of the world's foremost
teaching hospitals and as a leader in cancer research. Thus, when
Weiss' sister read a newspaper article about Kleinerman's work, she
clipped it and sent it to her brother and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt's father, Frank, called Kleinerman, and on June 1, 1990,
Kurt, accompanied by his mother, Joanne, boarded a flight to
Houston, where they had an appointment at M.D. Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Weiss says he was scared when he entered Kleinerman's
office. ``I was in very, very bad shape,'' Weiss says. ``Things
didn't look good at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says the doctor put him at ease; she was able to discuss
his treatment in layman's terms. He and his parents were certain
that if anything could be done to save his life, Kleinerman could
do it.
</P>
<P>
   There was something else, though, that Weiss says he found
reassuring. Participating in the trial not only might save his
life, but it might ultimately save others.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very important to me,'' Weiss says. ``I knew for me
to be going for experimental therapy, if I was going to die,
somebody was going to learn something.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kurt Weiss, 26, has been cancer-free for 10 years. A
recurring infection from the surgeries did claim his right leg in
1996, but for Weiss, having his leg amputated is a small price to
pay after a bleak prognosis. Sometimes he has to pinch himself, he
says, to make sure he isn't dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very blessed because without this therapy I would've
died,'' Weiss says. ``As you're going through these things, you
don't have the luxury to think about how bad everything is. Now I
look back and wonder how in God's name I ever got through it.''
</P>
<P>
   His battle with cancer also inspired Weiss to choose a new
career path. He had planned to follow in his father's footsteps and
become an engineer, but now Weiss attends Jefferson Medical College
in Philadelphia, where he is studying to become a surgical
oncologist.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Weiss _ newly married _ was reunited with Kleinerman
when he returned to M.D. Anderson, not as a patient, but to
participate in a summer research program as part of his studies.
</P>
<P>
   For two months Weiss worked alongside the doctor who saved his
life as she and her team continued their cancer research, trying to
develop new therapies for treating osteosarcoma. His presence
inspired the research team; he was proof of what their work could
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very rewarding for the people who worked so hard
to see the fruit of their labor,'' Kleinerman says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The doctors in Pittsburgh were treating Kurt Weiss' osteosarcoma
in the prescribed manner _ a combination of surgery to remove
tumors, followed by chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' Kleinerman says, ``is in 90 percent of cases,
the tumor has already spread to the lungs. What makes this disease
even more insidious is you can't see it by X-ray or MRI. But we
know if we cut out the tumor and don't do anything else, 95 percent
of patients will come back six months later, take chest X-rays and
boom, there's the tumor.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the two-pronged approach of surgery and
chemotherapy had a success rate of only 65 percent. That wasn't
good enough, Kleinerman says. ``I felt that chemotherapy was not
going to be the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, while attending an annual meeting of the American
Association for Cancer Research, Kleinerman heard a lecture about
the use of a drug called muramyltripeptide (MTP) in animal studies.
</P>
<P>
   MTP is an agent that helps bolster the immune system, enabling
patients to fight the disease with their own antibodies. In
contrast, whereas chemotherapy destroys cancer cells, it also kills
healthy cells, thus weakening a patient's immune system and making
the patient more susceptible to infections and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinerman speculated that immune therapy treatment such as MTP,
which is administered intravenously, might be effective in
prolonging survival rates or even curing osteosarcoma.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   She began extensive research at the National Cancer Institute in
Bethesda, Md. Because large dogs are often stricken with
osteosarcoma, she tested her theory by amputating the cancerous
limbs of dogs and then treating them with MTP. The results were
remarkable: Dogs that received MTP survived longer; many were
cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed it worked in mice, showed it worked in dogs, and got
the pharmaceutical company to manufacture it for patient studies,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Kleinerman launched phase one of the trial, examining
the toxicity of MTP. Two years later she began phase two, studying
patients who had osteosarcoma that had spread to their lungs. This
trial was conducted nationally with two groups: patients who
received only chemotherapy and those who received chemotherapy and
MTP.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 patients from around the country took part in the
trials. And the results provided the first breakthrough in treating
this type of cancer, which affects about 2,000 young people
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Although patients reported flulike symptoms during the first 24
hours of being treated with MTP _ fever, chills, fatigue and muscle
aches _ they did not experience the debilitating side effects
commonly associated with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to measuring the toxicity of MTP, Kleinerman
monitored each patient's immune system to determine the proper
dosage of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   During the second phase of the trial, Kleinerman administered
MTP to osteosarcoma patients who had undergone surgery to remove
tumors, then redeveloped the tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took out the tumors we could see and gave them MTP,'' she
says. ``We were able to cure 33 percent of the patients.'' These
are patients who have been cancer-free for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those is Kurt,'' Kleinerman says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Since it accepted its first 10 patients in 1944, M.D. Anderson
has treated more than 400,000 people with cancer. There are now
6,000 patients participating in 531 clinical trials, each of those
trials having the potential to prolong survival rates or cure
specific types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than 500 active protocols here,'' says Dr. Robert
Bast, vice president of translational research at the center.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, Kleinerman, 51, juggles laboratory research
with various other responsibilities. She teaches, makes patient
rounds, and often writes papers for scientific journals or for
grants funding her work.
</P>
<P>
   She also serves on a National Cancer Institute study section
that reviews grants three times a year; she is vice chairman of
M.D. Anderson's Institutional Review Board, which ensures patient
protection and informed consent for clinical trials at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She is married to Dr. Leonard Zwelling, vice president for
research administration and a professor of medicine and
pharmacology at M.D. Anderson. Their lives are devoted to fighting
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Zwelling says it has taken the medical community almost three
decades to understand how cancer works.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1961 when (President) Kennedy said we were going to the
moon, the principles governing how we got to the moon were known,''
he says. ``In 1971, when President Nixon declared the war on
cancer, we didn't know what the problem was.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwelling says doctors now know cancer is a disease of the genes,
and the major characteristic of cancer cells is their uncontrolled
growth. Not only are these cells malfunctioning, but cancer cells
suppress the immune system, so normal cells are malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   He says the goal is to find treatments that will selectively
kill cancer cells, leaving the normal ones standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the dawn of the age where that finally may be
possible,'' Zwelling says.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Kleinerman's research and subsequent trials has
helped make that possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this may not be a home run, it might be a double,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   But even successful trials do not guarantee that cancer patients
will benefit in time to prolong or save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The MTP trials, for example, were closed in 1998, and the drug
is not available on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason is economics, which frustrates researches such
as Kleinerman. Because osteosarcoma is rare, it is simply not
financially feasible for a pharmaceutical company to manufacture
the drug and go through the process of having it approved by the
Federal Drug Administration. The expense is considerable and the
return negligible.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinerman says that the company manufacturing MTP during the
trials stopped but that a small company then agreed to make the
drug. That company, she says, went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had calls from many patients and doctors and I have to
tell them the same thing _ there is no drug,'' Kleinerman says.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she continues her research into treating
osteosarcoma, her interest in this disease dating 20 years to when
her husband took her to see Promises in the Dark, about a doctor's
unsuccessful struggle to save a girl with osteosarcoma.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kleinerman pursues the next step in fighting
osteosarcoma; she is working to develop an aerosol treatment for
the disease in which patients use an inhaler that would spread the
treatment directly to the lungs. ``We've shown that this is
effective in our animal osteosarcoma model,'' she says, ``and so
once the dose is determined by the phase one trial we hope to go
into a phase two trial.''
</P>
<P>
   An aerosol would help reduce side effects of most cancer
treatments. ``If you have ants in the kitchen, you want to spray
the counter where the ants are; you don't want to set off a bomb in
the whole house,'' Kleinerman says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kurt Weiss is back in school, counting the days until
he graduates in 2002. His dream is to return to work with his
mentor on her research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be real blessing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
