<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      06-26 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX TROUBLES LEAVE THEM REELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Red Sox are in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   They lost a game in which sacrificial lamb Chris Carpenter
started for Toronto against Pedro Martinez _ as one-sided a matchup
as there can be in baseball _ they lost a game in which they went 3
for 17 with runners in scoring position, and they lost a game in
which only the steady glove of second baseman Jeff Frye prevented
them from a true baseball rarity, the starting infield going for
the cycle of each committing errors.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot hit. They cannot field. They cannot win close games.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are in trouble. Serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And a former Red Sox pitcher, Blue Jays set-up man Paul
Quantrill, said it's about time the rest of baseball realizes the
team to fear in the American League East is not Boston or New York,
but the team north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get the attention we deserve,'' said Quantrill. ``The
Red Sox and Yankees get it all. The Yankees always have a lot of
focus on them, and Boston _ I've played there for a few years _
it's such a rivalry there's always that focus on the Red
Sox-Yankees rivalry. And I hope it stays that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Yankees are in trouble and the Red Sox are
unraveling. While Boston and New York have taken huge steps
backward in June, it is the Blue Jays, with that fearsome lineup,
who have stepped forward and grabbed a clear lead in a division
just waiting to be taken.
</P>
<P>
   In Quantrill's view, the Red Sox ``are beat up'' and ``the
Yankees don't even know who their starters are. They're scuffling
just to find starting pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fairly comfortable with our situation and not because
we're playing well,'' said Quantrill. ``Both those teams are good
teams and they're going to get going, but I like the fact we are
where we are. We've got the pieces to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the Blue Jays have David Wells. While the focus
has been on Martinez as the American League's best pitcher, Wells
quietly has gone out and compiled a scintillating 12-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more than dependable,'' said Toronto manager Jim Fregosi.
``When we need him, he always comes through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays were able to sweep the Red Sox even without Wells
taking the mound at SkyDome. In Quantrill's mind, this was huge
``because the Red Sox and Yankees both kicked our butts last year
and we've been able to beat them this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Darrin Fletcher out of the lineup and Homer Bush
hitting in the .180s, ``there's no letup in our lineup,'' said
Quantrill. ``We'll get Fletcher back before long and once Homer
gets going, the lineup'll really be something.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Blue Jays' foes, Quantrill said he fears the beat-up Red
Sox more than the Yankees. Boston, despite its obvious lack of
talent at key positions, battles hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox, I give them credit,'' said Quantrill. ``The Red
Sox are the scrappiest team. They really play hard and just really
play well with what they've got. They're going to give you a tough
time every time. The Yankees have been the team the last few years
but, to be honest with you, we've got as many pieces as they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays' most telling weakness, said Quantrill, ``is the
lack of experience. We've got a lot of young guys, unlike the Red
Sox and Yankees, and that's why it's important for us to come in
and play well against Boston and New York. As a lesson for the
young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Quantrill qualified all of his comments with ``right now,'' as
in, ``Right now, this is is how it looks, but there's a long way to
go.'' Fregosi was more blunt, saying the division won't really come
into focus until July 31, when the teams have made whatever moves
they must make before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``But obviously we can hit,'' said Quantrill, and just as
obviously the Blue Jays have a much more fearsome lineup than
Boston or New York. ``Our pitching just needs to come together, but
that's true for all three teams. The Red Sox are beat up completely
and have a lot of injuries and the Yankees are scuffling.''
</P>
<P>
   The zany schedule-maker now sends the Blue Jays off on a
two-week road extravaganza, like the one the Red Sox had in early
June and the one the Yankees are now experiencing. And for Boston,
the only bright light is that the Baltimore Orioles now move into
Fenway Park. The Orioles have been playing worse than the Red Sox.
Baltimore has lost nine in a row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
