<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-SOSA-GONZALEZ-NYT     06-26 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-GONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES MIGHT HAVE HAD SOSA, WILLIAMS, GONZALEZ OUTFIELD YEARS
AGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An outfield of Sammy Sosa, Bernie Williams and Juan Gonzalez
just might have been the greatest outfield ever assembled. It's not
a fantasy outfield. It's not a Rotisserie outfield. It could have
been the Yankees' outfield.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees would not have had to trade all of the prospects
in their minor league system to get Sosa and Gonzalez. They had
both youngsters within their grasp before they signed their first
professional contracts with other teams. Sosa, Williams, Gonzalez.
They would have been this era's Tinker to Evers to Chance,
memorialized in poetry and song.
</P>
<P>
   And just how would the Yankees have accomplished this master
stroke? By signing Sosa when he was in their tryout camp in the
Dominican Republic in 1984 and taking Gonzalez more seriously, in
1985, when their scouts saw him and when Williams talked about his
friend, who happened to be Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Some, though not all, of the Gonzalez story has been told
before. Sosa related his Yankees experience in his autobiography
that was published earlier this year. But Fred Ferreira, a
remarkably candid executive with the Montreal Expos, added
perspective to both stories this week in the face of the Yankees'
efforts to acquire Gonzalez or Sosa in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira was the Yankees' international scouting director when
Gonzalez and Sosa were approaching the age when they could sign
with major league organizations. Sosa came first, arriving at the
Yankees' complex in San Cristobal just after he turned 16 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw myself into every drill,'' he recounted in ``Sosa,''
written with Marcos Breton and published by Warner Books, ``and I
stayed for a while, hoping that the elusive offer would finally
come, that I would finally get a real contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa added that ``everything was going well with the Yankees''
until a trip to the bathroom changed the course of baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks into the camp, or school, Sosa and his fellow
hopefuls were ``just hanging out after a practice'' when Sosa
needed to use the bathroom. He was wearing only his underwear, and
it was apparently against camp rules to wander around in underwear.
When he went to practice the next day, Sosa related, he was told
that ``I'm thrown off the team.'' He protested, but to no avail. He
went home, his goal unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent him home,'' Ferreira said in a telephone interview
Sunday night. ``My man in the Dominican called me and said, `You
know the kid you saw the other day and liked a little bit? He just
did this tonight.' I said, ``Oh really? Tell him to pack his bag
and get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira said he had never told the story before but that ``it's
absolutely true,'' and he stood front and center in acknowledging
that it was his decision to jettison the young prospect who would
grow up and hit 129 home runs in the last two seasons of the 20th
Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked him; I sure did,'' Ferreira said. ``But even today, if
a kid messes around, you have to have some sort of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira recalled that during the players strike in 1994 he went
to the Dominican Republican and while there encountered Sosa.
``Sammy was all decked out,'' Ferreira related. ``He looked at me
and said, `I remember you.'
</P>
<P>
   It was the summer of 1985 when the Yankees had their shot _ no,
two shots _ at Gonzalez in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Rivera, a Yankees scout on the island, found Williams
and also noticed a friend of his. But Rivera went away without
pursuing Gonzalez, who was a year younger than the 16-year-old
Williams. And the reason Rivera wasn't interested in Gonzalez was
that he would dance in the outfield during a game. Rivera felt
Gonzalez was horsing around and didn't have the right approach to
the game. He said he wanted to sign a player, not a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira said he was unaware of that story, but he readily
related another as an addendum to the Williams signing story, which
has been told before.
</P>
<P>
   Having discovered Williams, the Yankees could not sign him,
under the rules, until his 17th birthday, which was a couple of
months away. Rivera recommended hiding young Bernie, and that's
what they did, putting him in a baseball camp in Connecticut near
the home of Doug Melvin, then the team's scouting director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We convinced his mother if he was going to play professionally
it would be best for him to become acclimated to the U.S.,'' said
Melvin, now the Texas Rangers general manager. ``He flew home the
night before he turned 17.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira arranged Williams' trip to Connecticut. ``Just before
Bernie went to the camp,'' Ferreira disclosed, again accepting the
consequences of his decisions with class, ``he asked me if there
was a chance of him bringing a friend with him. I didn't want to
ask Mr. Steinbrenner for more money to hide another kid so I said
no. That kid turned out to be Juan Gonzalez.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers wound up signing Sosa and Gonzalez 10 months apart.
Now they are both available as established high-priced talent. The
Yankees may wind up with one. They could have had both.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
