<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5498 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GENOME-CELERA27-COX     06-26 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-CELERA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A PUSHY UPSTART, CELERA DROVE SEARCH FOR GENOME MAP
 &HT;    With GENOME.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Craig Venter traces his interest in human genomics
to his service as a medical corpsman in Vietnam 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned firsthand how tenuous our hold on life can be,'' he
said at a White House ceremony Monday that hailed the combined
efforts of his Celera Corp. and an international network of
government-funded scientists in deciphering the human genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   ``That experience inspired my interest in learning how the
trillions of cells in our bodies work and interact to create and
sustain life,'' Venter added.
</P>
<P>
   The trillions of cells in Venter's own body seem to interact in
ways that lead him to be labeled _ depending on who's labeling _ as
a shallow, slapdash researcher or a visionary scientist and
corporate executive.
</P>
<P>
   As president and chief scientific officer of Celera, Venter has
presided over a private gene sequencing venture that in a few
months overtook and nearly passed the government consortium in the
race to define the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Venter was a researcher at the National Institutes of Health
until 1992, when he left in a dispute over his efforts to patent
genes he had discovered as part of the government-funded Human
Genome Project.
</P>
<P>
   He founded the nonprofit Institute for Genomic Research in
nearby Rockville, Md., that same year, and in 1998 founded Celera
with backing from Perkin-Elmer Corp., a company that manufactured
telescopes (including the faulty lens of the Hubble Space
Telescope), microscopes and other scientific instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The word Celera was crafted from the word celerity, which means
``rapidity of motion or action.'' The company was well named.
</P>
<P>
   Using a Perkin-Elmer device called the ABI-PRISM 3700, which
essentially examines a stretch of human DNA and identifies
different segments by the way they respond to a laser beam, Celera
set out to sequence large quantities of DNA very rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The genetic strands were first chopped into thousands of tiny
segments, and the patterns by which key molecular components
appeared along the strands were recorded by several hundred of the
automated ABI-PRISM machines.
</P>
<P>
   A supercomputer analyzed similarities at the opposite ends of
each strand to determine how they fit together, much like the
pieces of a jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   By last April, less than two years after the company was
founded, Venter announced Celera had sequenced the genome of one
human being. That meant the ABI-PRISM had identified all the
pieces, but hadn't yet put the jigsaw puzzle together. The
computers were being used to assemble the pieces, and the virtual
completion of that task was what was announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the government program posting the results of its own
sequencing efforts on the Internet and Celera committed to make its
own work public in a scientific paper to be published in September,
Venter was asked Monday how he expected to make any money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort to make a financial return for our investors will
be from understanding that information,'' he said. Already, he
said, the company was advising pharmaceutical manufacturers,
biotech firms and universities on how to understand the human
genome.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.celera.com
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
