<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-GENOME-SHREEVE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE GENOME LEADS US 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, June 27, and thereafter. Spelling
of Neandertal is CQ.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JAMES SHREEVE    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The race to map the human genome, which has arrived at the
finish line in a carefully prearranged tie, has been portrayed from
the first as a classic pitting of privately and publicly funded
science. The moral overtones in much of the commentary have favored
the Human Genome Project, led by Dr. Francis Collins and financed
by the National Institutes of Health, over the profit-driven Celera
Genomics and its flamboyant lead scientist, Dr. J. Craig Venter.
But what the race really demonstrates is the value of scientific
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was a race, the post-genomic era of biomedicine
has arrived at least five years ahead of schedule. And it is not
wildly optimistic to say that this translates into hundreds of
thousands of lives saved or prolonged 10 or 15 years from now, at
about the same time the baby boom generation becomes most prone to
cancer and other common killers. As one of those boomers, I take
this matter to heart.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I got a graphic demonstration of what genomics
will mean to cancer research from Richard Klausner, director of the
National Cancer Institute. In a briefing at the National Institutes
of Health in Bethesda, Md., Klausner showed slides of cells taken
from two women. The slides told identical stories: the cells in the
women's lymph glands were bloated, diffuse and dividing out of
control. Using the slides, doctors had diagnosed B-cell lymphoma in
both women. Both were given a 45 percent chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Then Klausner flashed a second set of images on the screen,
showing what these two women's cancers looked like from the genomic
perspective. Scientists conducting a research study had washed
solutions containing the women's lymph cells over lymphochips, bits
of glass about the size of a nickel that had been studded with
thousands of short strands of DNA representing known human genes.
What resulted were patterns of red and green dots, like a grid of
traffic lights, revealing which genes were active and which were
dormant. Neither pattern looked anything like the one seen in
healthy lymph cells. But they didn't look like each other, either.
Down at the molecular level, where cancer originates, the chips
showed that the women actually had two quite different diseases,
caused by different mutations in their genetic codes.
</P>
<P>
   By comparing their lymphochips with those from other cancer
patients, the scientists predicted that one woman might actually
have an 80 percent chance of survival; the other, a grim 20
percent. The wider meaning is that with the genome finished,
researchers in other studies can now compare such patterns to begin
investigating what leads cells to run amok in cancer in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   This is just a taste of what will be possible once researchers
begin to exploit the information in the entire human genome, which,
in a remarkably amicable ending to what was a genuinely hard-fought
race, Celera and the Human Genome Project revealed in tandem
Monday. They are expected to publish their ``rough draft'' versions
simultaneously later this year, and both sides now stress that
their methods proved ``complementary.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both scrambled feverishly to try to be first, though
with differing aims: Celera to exploit a window of time to sell
access to genetic information that only it could provide, the
public program to prevent such information from becoming entangled
in intellectual property rights. The scientists on both teams also
wanted a share in what everyone knew would be a magnificent
scientific achievement.
</P>
<P>
   It is not my habit to go around touting the virtues of free
enterprise. But having watched this race intimately over the past
two years, I have little doubt that if the competition from
industry had not come along to challenge the government's genome
program, it would still be fixed on a noble but distant goal: to
slowly piece together, by 2005, a highly accurate, finished
rendition of the 3 billion-letter human genome that would ``stand
the test of time,'' in the often repeated phrase of Collins. This
more refined version of the code will still be produced, though
sooner because of the competitive pressure _ the delivery date has
now been moved up to 2003. It will be an invaluable tool for
researchers for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   But Venter and his associates at the Perkin Elmer Corp. in
Connecticut, who conceived the idea of a private human genome
initiative in the first place, understood that this generation of
scientists needs a version of the genome to work with now, even if
it isn't perfect, and even if it costs drug companies a few million
dollars a year and university researchers a little grant money to
use it most effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Because the government was galvanized into supplying a competing
product that will be freely available, there is no chance that the
human genome will be tied up by the private sector, if there ever
was such a threat. And Celera, to make a profit, must, with its
commercial competitors, now entice researchers and the
pharmaceutical industry with even better genomic information and
with complex software that will help make sense of all this new
data. This should further accelerate the battle against disease.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question who has won this contest. It is those
people who will live longer because it took place. I may be one of
them, and so may you.
</P>
<P>
   (James Shreeve is author of ``The Neandertal Enigma'' and a
forthcoming book on the race for the human genome.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
