<SLUG> BC-HITACHI-STORAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITACHI SAYS NEW STORAGE MACHINES MOST POWERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The data storage market continued to heat up
Monday as Hitachi Data Systems of Santa Clara, Calif., announced a
new line of storage devices that it claims will be more powerful
than top-of-the-line machines sold by market leader EMC Corp. of
Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi's announcement is the latest in the chaotic, fiercely
competitive $35 billion annual market for devices capable of
storing massive amounts of digital information.
</P>
<P>
   It comes less than two weeks after Sun Microsystems Inc. made a
similar run at the storage market with the introduction of a line
of inexpensive modular machines.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the Internet, the demand for data storage has
exploded as companies accummulate mountains of information about
individual customers, and as the Web becomes a medium for
delivering data-intensive voice and video content.
</P>
<P>
   With demand for storage projected to grow by double-digits each
year for the next five years, companies such as Hitachi, Sun,
Compaq Computer Corp. and IBM Corp. have recently piled into a
once-sleepy market pioneered by EMC in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi's new Freedom Storage 9900 products take aim at EMC's
high-end Symmetrix devices. Unlike Sun, which touted its product's
relatively low price, Hitachi is seeking to compete on performance,
saying its machines can store twice as much as EMC devices and can
operate several times as fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's four to six times faster than anything else on the market
today,'' said Robert Ward, director of product management at
Hitachi in Santa Clara, Calif. ``It will clearly also be the
largest capacity storage subsystem available today.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers will have to pay for that performance, however.
Hitachi executives estimate their new systems will cost on average
30 percent more than Hitachi's current storage devices. Depending
on the model, prices will range from $600,000 to $12 million for a
configured system.
</P>
<P>
   EMC officials downplayed Hitachi's announcement, saying the
Hopkinton company's service and software are superior to Hitachi's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sense is that if Hitachi wanted to make a frontal attack
on EMC, they picked the wrong area,'' said Don Swatik, vice
president of strategic planning at EMC. ``Hitachi has been
historically weak in software and support. And that's where we have
a legendary reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi last year scored against EMC by luring Hewlett-Packard
as a reseller of Hitachi storage devices. HP had, until then, been
a reseller of EMC products.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi Data Systems, a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi Ltd.
in Japan, doesn't disclose its storage revenues. But Dave Roberson,
chief operating officer of Hitachi Data, said its storage business
is growing more than 20 percent a year and accounts for two-thirds
of the subsidiary's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp. estimates that Hitachi Ltd, the parent
company that operates two storage units, had 4.3 percent of the
external storage systems market in 1998 and just 3.8 percent in
1999. By contrast, industry leader EMC had 19.9 percent of the
market in 1998 and 22.7 percent last year, according to EMC.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson said Hitachi Data Systems' biggest clients include
telecommunications and financial services firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the two fastest-growing customer segments,'' said
Roberson. ``Virtually every one of our customers in those areas
(is) looking at very large orders.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Internet is spawning a new crop of companies
that sell online storage, including Storage Networks, a start-up in
Waltham. ``That is an example of a customer that wasn't even on our
radar screen a year ago,'' Roberson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
