<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GIBSON-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      06-26 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIBSON-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEL GIBSON'S FAMILY TAUGHT LESSONS FOR `PATRIOT' ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mel Gibson isn't too handy with a tomahawk, and he doesn't own
any guns, so his prowess with a musket is open to question. But
toss out those two skills and Benjamin Martin, the conflicted
freedom fighter Gibson plays in the new Revolutionary War epic
``The Patriot'' is a pretty close fit for the actor.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious parallel comes from the fact that Gibson, like his
counterpart in ``The Patriot'' (which opens in theaters Wednesday),
is the father of seven children. But the connection goes deeper
than family ties. Both men share a fear of themselves and their
past transgressions, a foreboding that's neatly summed up in
Gibson's first words in the film: ``I have long feared that my sins
would return to me and the cost would be more than I could bear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel had a clear sense of the religious and moral aspects of
the script,'' says ``Patriot'' screenwriter Robert Rodat (``Saving
Private Ryan''). ``If anything, he put us on the hot seat about
turning up the volume on those things. He really wanted to take a
scalpel to the character.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, those tortured opening words, spoken from Martin, a
character who looks back on his days as a hero of the French and
Indian War with a mixture of revulsion and regret. And while Gibson
isn't ready to bear his soul to Barbara Walters, he does offer
several clues about his own regrets and fears, most of which
revolve around marriage and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The karma thing in the script is the key to who that guy is
and it's actually the key to parenthood and the key to all your
fears,'' Gibson says. ``With me, yeah, I have some regrets, but
that's what happens over time. You've got to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for me, family ... it can just evaporate in a heartbeat,
which is one of my greatest fears,'' Gibson continues. ``The older
I get, the more I don't want to be away. Things can really fall
apart in your family, so you just want to stay close. There's more
fear attached to that than there used to be, which is funny, isn't
it, because I've devoted a little more time. The scary bit is the
fear probably arose from a greater familiarity (with his family).
And the sad news is that that familiarity probably wasn't there
before as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, 44, has been married for 20 years and he and his wife,
Robyn, have seven children, ranging in age from 19-year-old
daughter Hannah to his 14-month-old toddler son, Tommy. Gibson's
proficiency as a father inspired screenwriter Rodat, who wrote the
part of Martin with the actor in mind, believing that Gibson could
convincingly play a family man who puts his children before his
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even put the number of kids at six in an early draft, kind
of as a signal to the powers that be that Mel Gibson should be this
man,'' Rodat says. ``After we signed him and his son was born, we
increased the number of kids to seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds ``Patriot'' co-producer Dean Devlin: ``Mel brought
something to the movie that you can't act, and that's his
experience as a father. You'd watch him off-camera and you could
clearly see that this was a guy who's at ease around kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson says any appearance of ease is misleading, particularly
when it involves his own brood. (His other children _ all boys _
include twins Edward and Christopher, 16; William, 14; Louis, 12;
and Milo, 9.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm far from an expert on child-rearing,'' Gibson says.
``We've just been making up the rules as we go along and doing the
best we can, hoping and praying we're not doing any permanent
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson laughs off the last comment, but it's clear he's still
beating himself up over some of his past absences from his family's
life. Early in his marriage, he had problems with alcohol,
resulting in a drunk-driving arrest in Toronto in 1984 while making
``Mrs. Soffel'' and splashy tabloid headlines in 1990 when a
college student sold snapshots of a wild weekend with Gibson that
included two other attractive co-eds.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson missed the birth of his daughter in 1981, and laments not
forging a relationship earlier with her. ``Then when she needed me
when she was a teen-ager, we didn't have that foundation, and it
was a little rocky,'' Gibson says, choosing his words slowly.
``Again, time passes, you live, you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Owning up to his mistakes doesn't come that easily, but Gibson
says there isn't anything he won't discuss with his children. To
him, it's the best way to illustrate the difference between right
and wrong and the consequences of making the improper choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see them going off the rails, I'll say, 'You know, I did
that,''' Gibson says. ``And they'll say, 'Really?' 'Yup, and I
gotta tell you right now, it doesn't pay.' And you tell them stuff;
you admit doing the stuff that you don't want them to do. It really
hits home and makes a point for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I almost need to do that in order to explain myself.
Otherwise they don't know what the hell I'm talking about. It's a
riddle. But if you say, 'Hey, let me shed a little light on this. I
got into a car once after having drunk too much and this is what
happened. Don't !ital!do it. It's really stupid.' Then they'll
listen and maybe learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it is is saying that you're part of the same miserable
condition that they are,'' Gibson concludes. ``You know they aren't
going to make the right choices all the time because they're human,
too. You just try to make them understand how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the sixth of 11 children, Gibson is well-versed in the
dynamics of large families. But he's never been forced to defend
his family in the manner that Martin must in ``The Patriot,''
although he has no doubt about how he'd act if his children were in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a bona fide coward, but it's amazing what
you'll do if you need to,'' Gibson says. ``I remember when I was
about 15, I woke up to the sound of my sister screaming. And she
said, 'There's a guy out back and he's beating your father up.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I ran out the back and there was indeed some kind of
intruder, but it was quite the opposite way around. My old man was
kicking his a--. He kicked him in the a-- and put his face through
a window. And the guy was taking off and I found myself chasing him
with a frying pan, just running down the road in my underwear. I
wanted to kill the guy. It offends you so badly that anybody would
come and try to (mess) with your family.''
</P>
<P>
   With his own children, Gibson says the worst he's had to do is
heel a man whose hands were getting a little too friendly with his
daughter. When it comes to his boys, Gibson's usually the one
protecting other people from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be a handful at times,'' he admits. ``But they're
good kids.''
</P>
<P>
   As for becoming a father again in his 40s, Gibson says ``it's
just the greatest thing,'' even if it means changing diapers once
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm even savoring that,'' he says with a laugh. ``You have to
because they grow up so fast. You know, at first when we found out,
we wondered, well, can we start this again? We're not exactly
spring chickens anymore. But having a baby tends to make you a
spring chicken. It's a funny thing. The little guy is just
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
