<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5513 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-MIRANDA-HNS &LR;      06-26 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-MIRANDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUPREME COURT LEAVES MIRANDA WARNING INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civil libertarians won a major victory Monday when
the Supreme Court refused to overturn a landmark decision of the
1960s, ruling that police must continue to warn suspects of their
rights to remain silent and obtain a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-2 vote, the highest court decided not to discard the
so-called Miranda ruling of 1966 and replace it with an obscure,
less-stringent federal law, passed in 1968, that allows voluntary
confessions to be used against suspects even when police fail to
give the warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miranda announced a constitutional rule that Congress may not
supersede legislatively,'' Chief Justice William Rehnquist wrote
for the court majority. ``We decline to overrule Miranda
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a generation of police dramas in movies and on
television, the Miranda warnings have become familiar to most
Americans. The warnings stem from the 5-4 Miranda vs. Arizona
decision, which said police must warn suspects of their rights
before questioning them.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings state that suspects have the rights to remain
silent and to have a lawyer even if they can't afford one, and that
anything suspects say may be held against them in court.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Rehnquist acknowledged the pervasive role of the
Miranda decision in modern society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miranda has become embedded in routine police practice to the
point where the warnings have become part of our national
culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day
O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, David Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and
Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he was pleased the Miranda warnings were
``resoundingly'' upheld. ``They have worked for law enforcement by
providing clear standards for our officers and they have worked to
protect the rights of our citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Shapiro, legal director of the American Civil Liberties
Union, also praised the court, calling the original Miranda ruling
``an emblem of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro added that ``doing away with the police warnings would
have sent a terrible message about our criminal justice system,
that effective law enforcement depends on keeping people ignorant
of their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the ruling provoked an unusually harsh dissent from
Justice Antonin Scalia, who was joined by Justice Clarence Thomas.
Both conservative justices are frequently allied with Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   In the dissent, Scalia said Monday's decision ``converts Miranda
from a milestone of overreaching'' into one of ``judicial
arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia also accused Rehnquist, O'Connor and Kennedy of turning
their backs on previous rulings in which they had questioned the
constitutional underpinnings of the 1966 Miranda decision.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the majority decision, Robert Scully, president of
the National Association of Police Organizations, said it ``will
only increase the amount of litigation on this point in state and
federal courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Scully said the case ``was not about whether giving the warnings
made good public policy, which many law enforcement officers
support. Rather, it was about the automatic exclusion of
incriminating statements if there was a technical violation of the
Miranda guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling ended a long-running challenge to the Miranda
decision by conservative critics, who never accepted its
legitimacy. These critics maintained that the court of the 1960s _
much more liberal than the present court _ had overstepped its
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The critics said that the warnings tie the hands of police,
discourage suspects from confessing and sometimes allow the guilty
to go free when a law enforcement officer fails to give the
warnings at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to those complaints and to rising crime, Congress in
1968 passed an anti-crime measure, known as section 3501 of the
federal criminal code, that said confessions ``voluntarily given''
may be used in court regardless of what the Supreme Court had said
in the Miranda decision.
</P>
<P>
   But that law lay dormant for three decades as law enforcement
agencies and the courts chose to ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   The law, however, was applied by an appellate court in the case
of Charles Dickerson, accused of an $876 bank robbery in
Alexandria, Va., on Jan. 24, 1997. During the robbery, a witness
took down the license plate number of the getaway car, a white
Oldsmobile. Three days later, FBI agents showed up at the Takoma
Park, Md., apartment of the car's registered owner, Dickerson. The
car was out front.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson said the agents busted in. They say he opened the
door. He agreed to accompany them to an FBI office but refused to
let them search his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Agent Christopher Lawlor later testified that he had noticed
a wad of cash on the bed as Dickerson picked up his coat. During
Dickerson's questioning at the FBI office, Lawlor left the room,
called a magistrate and got permission to search the suspect's
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor returned to the interview room and told Dickerson he had
obtained a search warrant. Dickerson then confessed to driving his
car in a series of robberies.
</P>
<P>
   But Dickerson gave his statements before being read his Miranda
rights. Later, he asked a U.S. District Court to throw out his
confession based on the 1966 decision, and the trial judge agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond
overturned the trial court decision, ruling that the Miranda
requirement had been superseded by Congress' 1968 crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also said the warnings imposed by the Miranda
decision were never constitutionally mandated.
</P>
<P>
   But in Monday's decision, Rehnquist made it clear that in
Miranda, the high court intended to safeguard the Fifth Amendment's
clause stating that ``no person shall be compelled in any criminal
case to be a witness against himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist wrote, ``Miranda, being a constitutional decision of
this court, may not be in effect overruled by an Act of Congress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 1966 decision was based on the case of a Phoenix truck
driver, Ernesto Miranda, who was accused in 1963 of raping an
18-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda confessed, was convicted and was sentenced to 20 to 30
years in prison. But his lawyers appealed to the Supreme Court,
arguing that he should have been informed of his rights to remain
silent and to consult a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The high court agreed, excluded Miranda's confession from
evidence and sent the case back to Arizona for a new trial. In
1973, Miranda was convicted of the 1963 rape at a second trial,
sent to prison and paroled. In 1976, at the age of 34, he was
stabbed to death in dispute over poker.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
