<HEADLINE>
SALARY SITE TO ANNOUNCE DEAL WITH YAHOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salary.com, a Web site offering information about how much
people are paid in different jobs in various US cities, will
announce Tuesday that top Web portal Yahoo Inc. has contracted to
offer its ``Salary Wizard'' search service to Yahoo's more than 50
million monthly visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Founded a year ago, Salary.com uses a secret list of sources,
including government data, trade associations and research by its
own analysts, to compile listings of salary ranges for 1,200
different jobs in cities across the United States. It is aiming to
increase salary coverage to 3,000 or 4,000 jobs by December.
</P>
<P>
   Salary.com is not disclosing what Yahoo will pay for use of its
site, which is also syndicated to over 20 other Web services.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Web sites that ``signed a deal with America Online
or Yahoo . . . could file immediately for an IPO,'' or initial
public offering, said Salary founder and chief executive Kent
Plunkett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that that's the case today, but this is
definitely a big boost for us,'' Plunkett said. ``It moves you up
to a different league'' and puts pressure on other Web portals to
consider adding the Salary feature as a link.
</P>
<P>
   With no publicity, Yahoo added a link to the Salary Wizard site
last Wednesday night that quickly led to a 20 percent increase in
traffic to the Salary site. Plunkett said the site, which has
increased from one to 18 Web servers in the last year, has added
eight more servers in anticipation of an avalanche of Yahoo
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Boston last November, 35-person Salary recently moved
to a Wellesley, Mass. office building once held by DirectHit.com,
which was acquired by search service Ask Jeeves in January in a
deal then valued at $532 million in stock. ``We think the space has
good karma,'' Plunkett said.
</P>
<P>
   Salary aims to make money by charging other Web sites for access
to its site and selling aggregated information about who visits the
site. In August, it plans to begin running banner ads.
</P>
<P>
   Plunkett said Salary executives think they are well ahead of
their competition among compensation comparison services, both in
the breadth and quality of their information, and believe it will
prove a compelling site for most working people to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is like sex on the scale of human needs,'' Plunkett
said. ``People just need to know if they are making enough money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
