<HEADLINE>
STREAM INTERNATIONAL PLANS $60 MILLION EXPANSION WORLDWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stream International Inc. of Canton, Mass. will build up to a
dozen new call centers worldwide as part of a $60 million expansion
it plans to announce Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Closely held Stream provides technical support for customers of
companies including Microsoft Corp. and Excite(at)Home. It now has
about 7,000 employees at 14 centers, including about 1,000 workers
in Canton. An expansion over the next year will add another 6,000
employees, including about 255 in Canton, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Stream's call-center business is booming as hardware and
software companies hire outsiders to answer questions about their
products. The business is known as ``outsourcing,'' and it spares
companies from having to talk to live customers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stream had revenue of about $340 million and income
of about $10 million. This year, it expects income of around $30
million. ``We think we're key in the customer equation,'' said
Scott Murray, president of Stream. Customers who order software
over the Web tend to select vendors on the basis of service, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stream competes with other outsourcing companies, including
Sitel Corp. of Omaha, Teletech Holdings Inc. of Denver, and
MyHelpdesk.com of Norwood, Mass. Stream is a descendant of a
company known as Corporate Software and got its start in the
call-center business in the early 1990s as a support center for
users of Microsoft's DOS and Windows programs.
</P>
<P>
   It became a majority-owned unit of R.R. Donnelly &AMP; Sons Co. of
Chicago in 1995, then was spun off in a management buyout last
December with backing from Bain Capital, which owns 62 percent.
Managers, including Murray and chief executive Steve Moore, own 23
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now Moore and Murray are preparing to open 10 to 12 more
call-centers, big warehouses of office cubicles costing about $10
million each. Costs are usually split between Stream and its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Canton and seven other domestic sites, Stream has
facilities in Amsterdam, Paris, Berlin, Northern Ireland, and
Japan. Altogether, its employees field 35 million phone calls and
send out 6 million e-mails a year.
</P>
<P>
   New sites will include buildings in Montana, New Mexico, Canada,
and northern Spain, among other places. Stream also said it will
hire 600 workers in Bombay, to provide support via e-mail. In
Canton, Stream plans to upgrade its infrastrucure and add about 55
new corporate staff employees, 100 software support workers, and
100 new employees for hardware support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
