<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED EXPECTED TO PASS ON ANOTHER RATE HIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Federal Reserve's interest rate-setting committee begins
two days of meetings Tuesday, there is wide agreement among
economists that Fed members will stand pat and won't raise interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1999, the Federal Open Market Committee has
systematically raised rates seven times. The biggest of these
moves, a one-half percentage point hike last month, pushed the
federal funds rate to 6.5 percent. As they debate the nation's
money policy, Fed members seated around an enormous table are
likely to base a decision of restraint on data showing that the
economy is beginning to slow, that rate hikes in the pipeline are
beginning to bite.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed's decision may be transparent, most economists
said the Fed must base its decision on murky evidence and
conflicting data. For example, new home sales fell in May,
indicating a slowdown. But existing home sales surged in May, a
bizarre twist in an industry sensitive to interest rates. The
country that month also turned in its weakest jobs report in years,
yet few economists believe the data reflect reality.
</P>
<P>
   Add election-year politics to the mix, and economists argue the
Fed would be wise to tighten now _ long before the November
presidential election _ to insulate itself from charges of
partisanship that might influence the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Available economic data ``do not show any clear change'' in the
economy's direction, said Lakshman Achuthan, managing director of
the Economic Cycle Research Institute in New York. The institute's
data is said to be closely watched by Fed chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Achuthan said the service sector, for example, generates half of
gross domestic product and is barreling along. ``It's critical to
have a service sector downshift to have a soft landing, and we
don't see that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed does not act during this meeting, some economists
predict a rate hike at its August meeting is assured.
</P>
<P>
   But with each FOMC meeting, the risks of error grow in an
economy that is as difficult to calibrate as a finely tuned violin,
economists said. Inflation, though still benign, is clearly
accelerating. A decision not to raise rates could open the Fed to
accusations it gave inflation the oxygen it needs to ignite.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed is likely to focus on the government's May
employment report, which showed the private sector reduced payrolls
by 116,000 jobs. It was the biggest monthly decline in business
hiring since the early 1990s recession and indicated the engines of
job creation may be finally hitting limits.
</P>
<P>
   Fed members who argue it would be prudent to hold off and await
more data confirming a slowdown are expected to prevail. Many
politicians agree, saying that as long as inflation remains low,
the Fed should let the economy expand, creating jobs and prosperity
in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very much a political hard sell for the Fed to
move next week when the prices are still so benign, and job numbers
and retails sales are showing signs of slowdown,'' said Wayne
Ayers, chief economist for FleetBoston Financial Corp., summing up
a view held by many of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists, including Ayers, believe the May job
numbers were an aberration, because the Bureau of Labor Statistics
conducted its survey of employers too early in the data-gathering
cycle to fully count all hiring that took place in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't do it (raise rates) in June, they'll do it in
August certainly,'' Ayers said.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments in favor of a rate hike demonstrate the difficulty of
getting monetary policy right when the data indicate it is such a
close call, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Yamarone, chief economist for Argus Research Corp. in
New York, is among a small minority who predict the Fed will act
now and is telling his firm's clients to expect a rate hike.
</P>
<P>
   He forecasts June will bring much stronger job gains of 470,000,
compared with average monthly job growth this year of just over
300,000.
</P>
<P>
   A hard-charging job market is just one reason a Fed rate
increase of one-quarter percentage point will be announced
Wednesday, after the two-day meetings conclude, Yamarone said. He
also cited Monday's report by the National Association of Realtors
that sales of existing homes rose 4.3 percent in May. Home sales
are supposed to be extremely sensitive to rate hikes, but the
housing market's reaction to rising rates has been mixed, with
sales falling one month and rising the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the Fed's biggest fear: They refrain from doing
anything and hot data start to appear. You already see it here, one
day before they meet,'' he said. Fed members will be forced to make
their call without the June jobs figures, which will be reported by
BLS the following week.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed doesn't act, it may also trigger another surge in the
stock market, he said, adding fuel to the economic engine by
encouraging consumers to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   But inflation _ not job growth or home sales or Nasdaq gains _
is the Fed's central fear.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly consumer price data show inflation remains benign but is
accelerating. The consumer price index has risen 3.1 percent over
the past year, ending in May. That is a full percentage point
higher than the CPI for the year ending in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Economists largely attribute that to oil prices, which have a
temporary impact on inflation. But Fed governor Laurence Meyer, the
inflation hawk on the FOMC, is expected to reiterate an argument
made recently at the Boston Club that the so-called ``core''
inflation rate, minus oil and food prices, is also rising. While
the core CPI rose only 2.4 percent during the past nine months,
core inflation spiked 3.2 percent in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also closely watches a future inflation gauge, known as
FIG. Calculated by the Economic Cycle Research Institute _ based on
a variety of data, from inflation abroad to America's debt levels _
FIG hit an 11-year high in April and moderated slightly in May.
``It's screaming inflation and it's one of Greenspan's favorites,''
Yamarone said.
</P>
<P>
   Even economists who think the Fed will not act say the decision
is an extremely difficult one.
</P>
<P>
   That's contrasted to a year ago, said William Cheney, chief
economist for John Hancock Financial Services Inc., when ``there
was a feeling all the risks were on one side: The only serious risk
was they wouldn't tighten enough, and inflation would get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the risks have changed. Given ``hints'' of a slowdown,
Cheney said, ``it is a more difficult decision and that's apart
from the issue of whether you're seeing any increase in
inflation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
