<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BOOKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER LIST WILL KEEP YOUNG BOOK LOVERS HAPPY ON THESE LONG, LAZY
DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once ``Harry Potter'' fans grab J.K. Rowling's next installment,
which goes on sale July 8, they'll burn through those pages like
Popsicles on hot pavement.
</P>
<P>
   All 752 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Well then, wise parents, you help kids round out their treehouse
library with a thoughtful selection of picture books, poetry and
zingy non-fiction. Plus chapter books _ escapist or reflective.
</P>
<P>
   Use our annual Read 'Em While They're Hot summer list as a guide
to some of the best new reading for kids. Then kick back and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   PICTURE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Marco and Polo,'' by Dieter Wiesmuller
(Walker &AMP; Co., $16.95). Ages 3-8.
</P>
<P>
   In this charming buddy tale, Marco Monkey explores the frigid
Antarctic with his new friend, Polo Penguin. Shivering, Marco
returns to his tropical home with Polo, who admires the scenery but
swelters in the heat. Can their friendship survive? High-quality
paper gives a luxurious feel to the lush, exuberant artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Do Dinosaurs Say Good Night?'' by Jane Yolen, illustrated
by Mark Teague (Blue Sky Press, $15.95). Ages 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   Do baby dinosaurs pout at bedtime and slam their tails and roar
and shout for one book more? Not these little guys. They tuck in
their tails and give a hug and one kiss more. (Get the hint, kid?)
Delightful nighty-night tale with goofy-sweet illustrations that
extend to the decorative endpapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Tim and the Brave Sea Captain,'' by Edward Ardizzone
(Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shepard, $16). Ages 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   Little Tim wants very much to be a sailor, but his parents say
he is too young. When he stows away on a steamer, he learns how
hard sailors work, especially when a storm nearly sends them to
Davy Jones' locker. This enchanting 1936 tale launched a series
that ran until 1977. The wispy, pen-and-ink artwork proves how
fetching line drawings can be. See also ``Tim to the Rescue'' and
``Tim and Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Jabe,'' by Jerdine Nolen, illustrated by Kadir Nelson
(Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shepard, $15.95). Ages 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   In this original tall tale, a slave with the strength of John
Henry and the leadership of Moses mysteriously spirits slaves away
to freedom, one by one. Compelling storytelling, original page
design and emotional watercolor/gouache illustrations give this
book a literary feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Lonely Sea Horse,'' by Saxton Freymann and Joost Elffers
(Arthur A. Levine Books, $15.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Another vege-tale from the duo that created ``How Are You
Peeling?'' (A New York Times Best Illustrated Book) and ``Play With
Your Food.'' As before, exotic produce is fashioned into characters
suggested by their colors, shapes and textures. Here Bea the lonely
``sea horse'' (actually chioggia beets with a face) finds
companionship with two crabs, three puffer fish, four lobsters,
etc., a k a shiitake mushrooms, horned melons and ginger root.
Predictable doggerel coupled with photo illustrations that are oh,
so clever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue and Green Ark,'' by Brian Patten with 11 illustrators
(Scholastic, $18.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than an alphabet book, this is a lyrical tribute to the
natural wonders of our fragile earth, the ``blue and green ark
adrift in the dark.'' Illuminated gold-leaf letters are the thread
of consistency in a hauntingly beautiful book illustrated by 11
British artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lizzy and Skunk,'' by Marie-Louise Fitzpatrick (DK Ink,
$14.95). Ages 3-5.
</P>
<P>
   Lizzy is afraid of dark shadows, spiders and making mistakes.
But her hand-puppet, Skunk, is fearless _ until he gets lost. Now
Lizzy's the brave one, searching under the bed, in the attic and up
a tree to bring her beloved Skunk safely home. A warm tale of
friendship and bravery told with pleasing simplicity, illustrated
with gently whimsical watercolors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practically Perfect Pajamas,'' written and illustrated by
Erik Brooks (Winslow Press, $16.95). Ages 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   Percy the polar bear loves everything about his red, footed
pajamas _ except the ridicule they inspire in the other bears. A
clever suggestion by an arctic fox puts everyone on the same
fashion footing. The ending is a bit contrived, but bold,
expressive artwork sings in this debut by a Seattle author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sally Goes to the Beach,'' by Stephen Huneck (Harry N. Abrams,
$17.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Sally, a black Labrador, visits an island in the ocean,
</P>
<P>
   where she meets lots of dogs and has many fun adventures. Simple
story, great presentation. You can't help but smile at this
oversized book, strikingly illustrated with color woodcuts and told
from a doggy point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``When They Fight,'' by Kathryn White, illustrated by Cliff
Wright (Winslow Press, $14.95). Ages 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   A young badger describes how frightening it feels when his
parents fight (``The world shakes, the house quakes ... mighty
monsters make me quiver'') and how happy he is when they are
friends again (``When they are friends, the sun comes out. ... I am
as strong as a lion''). The simple text and endearing pictures _
charming in that English, ``Redwall'' way _ provide an opening for
young children to share their own anxieties. It might even inspire
parents to ``think of the children'' when tempers run high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ebb &AMP; Flo and the Greedy Gulls,'' by Jane Simmons (Margaret K.
McElderry/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14.95). Ages 3-7.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fun day at the beach until seagulls raid the picnic
basket. Flo blames the theft on her hapless pooch, Ebb, who goes
off to sulk in the rowboat. By the time the real thieves are
fingered, Ebb is adrift in a stormy sea. All ends well in this
heartwarming tale, amplified by colorful, smudgy pictures ripe with
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost! A Story in String,'' by Paul Fleischman, illustrated by
C.B. Mordan (Henry Holt, $15.95). Ages 5-9.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by a loop of yarn, Grandma tells of a resourceful mountain
girl who uses her wits to find her way home in a snowstorm. Learn
how Grandma contorts the yarn into the shape of a dog's head, the
north star and other story elements. Illustrated with ink on
clayboard for a woodcut effect.
</P>
<P>
   CHAPTER BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   ``Dovey Coe'' by Frances O'Roark Dowell (Atheneum, 181 pages,
$16). Ages 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   This stunning debut novel, set in the Appalachians of North
Carolina in 1928, is among the best reads of the season.
Suspenseful and beautifully written, it features one of the
strongest heroines since Scout Finch. Twelve-year-old Dovey openly
disdains her sister's spoiled suitor, a rich townie who looks down
on mountain folk and taunts her deaf brother, Adam. ``I hated
Parnell Caraway as much as the next person,'' she announces in the
first paragraph, ``but I didn't kill him.'' You're hooked. Rich in
mountain dialect and nuanced characters, it carries us along as
Dovey develops a hard-won understanding of herself and her world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharaoh's Daughter,'' by Julius Lester (Harcourt, 182 pages,
$17). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   Lester, a distinguished black writer who converted to Judaism in
the early 1980s, immersed himself in the history of ancient Egypt
to write this fictitious account of the young Moses, born into
slavery and raised by the pharaoh's daughter. Told alternately by
an older sister and by young ``Mosis'' himself, it explores the
conflict inherent in being born Hebrew under a single God but
raised Egyptian under a pantheon of gods. A very human story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuck in Neutral,'' by Terry Trueman (HarperCollins, 116
pages, $14.95). Ages 10-up.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn McDaniel, 14, loves living in Seattle. He's blessed with
total recall and a great sense of humor. The bad news: He has
cerebral palsy and is severely developmentally disabled, with no
ability to move or communicate. And he thinks his father is
planning to kill him. Author Trueman, who lives in Spokane,
explores tough issues in a novel inspired by his own severely
disabled son. Is there intelligent life inside that useless shell?
Is ``mercy killing'' ever justified? A grippingly original, if
grim, exercise in empathy and imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White Fox Chronicles,'' by Gary Paulsen (Delacorte, 281
pages, $8.95 hardcover). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   Paulsen, a polished literary writer, steps outside the box in
this action-adventure page turner that's perfectly pitched for the
``reluctant reader.'' It's the year 2057 and America has been taken
over by an evil confederation. Fourteen-year-old Cody Pierce, a k a
White Fox, must break out of an enemy camp, elude capture and
return to free the other children. The sentences are short, the
heroes and villains are in sharp relief, and the action is non-stop
and often violent, in the manner of a blockbuster summer movie.
Escapist fun with no literary pretensions whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star in the Storm,'' by Joan Hiatt Harlow (Margaret K.
McElderry Books, 150 pages, $16). Ages 9-12.
</P>
<P>
   When a surly farmer turns the village of Bonnie Bay against her
gentle Newfoundland dog, Maggie must keep him safe. But the dog is
needed desperately when a gale overcomes a coastal steamer with 100
passengers. Maggie knows Sirius can help with the rescue, but if he
emerges from hiding, will his life be at risk? A heartwarming and
gently paced dog story with factual details of daily life in
Newfoundland in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Likes of Me,'' by Randall Beth Platt (Delacorte, 244
pages, $15.95). Ages 14-up.
</P>
<P>
   Cordelia, an albino girl who is half Caucasian and half Chinese,
feels freakish and unwanted growing up in a Western Washington
logging town of 1918. Her infatuation with a reckless youth named
Squirl leads her to Seattle's colorful Luna Park. The naive girl
lodges with Squirl's half-sister, the local madam, and lets the
smooth-tongued Squirl turn her into a mystical sideshow star _
until tragedy upsets their plans. The story falters in
believability after a splendid start, but you can't fault the
originality of this coming-of-age novel, replete with
larger-than-life characters and local color.
</P>
<P>
   ``River Boy,'' by Tim Bowler (Margaret K. McElderry, 155 pages,
$16). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   Weakened by a heart attack, Jess' irascible grandfather insists
the family take him to his boyhood home by a remote river in
England. He can't rest until he finishes a painting called _
mysteriously _ ``River Boy.'' Jess, his soul mate, senses the
fleeting presence of a boy along the river and must discover its
connection to her ailing grandfather. This reflective novel, which
won England's Carnegie Medal, has a metaphoric quality and is slow
to get to the point. But it's comforting in its gentle treatment of
family, loss and renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angus, Thongs and Full-Frontal Snogging,'' by Louise Rennison
(HarperCollins, 247 pages). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   This comically angst-filled diary has been likened to an
adolescent ``Bridget Jones's Diary.'' Here Georgia Nicholson, a
spunky but confused 14-year-old, frets over boys, breasts, acne and
``snogging,'' British slang for kissing. It's fun and light, a good
beach read. But Sue Townsend did this far better (using a male
protagonist) in ``The Secret Diary of Adrian Mole, Aged 13}'' and
``The Growing Pains of Adrian Mole,'' which are funnier, sadder,
deeper and more complex (and better appreciated by adults).
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddy and Mr. Camphor,'' by Walter R. Brooks (Overlook Press,
244 pages, $23.95). Ages 8-up.
</P>
<P>
   The delightful, if somewhat dated, middle-reader series about
Mr. Bean's talking animals ran from 1927 to 1958 and is being
reissued, two volumes at a time. Here the intrepid and poetic pig
takes up houseboat life as summer caretaker of a country estate.
But his hoped-for tranquillity is shattered by portrait-gnawing
rats, the cook's ne'er-do-well relatives and a pesky horsefly named
Zero. This 1944 title has allusions to Gen. Douglas MacArthur, the
wartime labor shortage and an amusing campaign to get hungry
insects to patriotically bypass victory gardens in favor of
roadside weeds. Like all Freddy books, it's great fun. (Note: Page
222 contains a single but jarring reference to a well-liked jail
inmate known as ``Joe the Gimp.'' Your call.)
</P>
<P>
   NON-FICTION
</P>
<P>
   ``The Anti-Boredom Book,'' by the editors of ``Owl'' and
``Chickadee'' magazines (Owl Books, 128 pages, $12.95 paper). All
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 133 boredom busters grouped under the headings of
Magical Fun, Kitchen Fun, Party Fun and Outdoor Fun. Some, like
tongue twisters and optical illusions, require no materials at all.
Others use simple items like newspaper, keys, brooms, etc. With
lively color photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls Think of Everything,'' by Catherine Thimmesh,
illustrated by Melissa Sweet (Houghton Mifflin, 57 pages, $16).
Ages 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   Meet some ``mothers of invention'' _ from Sybilla Masters of
1715, who devised a new way to clean and cure corn, to 10-year-old
Becky Schroeder, who in 1974 became the youngest female to receive
a U.S. patent (for glow-in-the-dark writing paper). Paper bags,
windshield wipers and bullet-proof Kevlar: Where would they be
without these visionary women? Lively, illustrated profiles and
brief info about the patent process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantastic Flying Fun With Science,'' by Ed Sobey, illustrated
by Bill Burg (McGraw-Hill, 90 pages, $11.95 paper). Ages 8-12.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of Sobey's projects is they use common household
items, they're simple, and they're fun. Make a workable paper
airplane or flying disc, build a pingpong-ball launcher using PVC
pipe and a hair dryer, turn cut paper into a flutter mobile or
build a low-riding hovercraft. Sobey, a Redmond oceanographer and
president of the Northwest Invention Center, explains the science
and tells how to extend the fun and games into science-fair
projects. See also ``Wacky Water Fun With Science.''
</P>
<P>
   POETRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Salting the Ocean: 100 Poems by Young Poets,'' selected by
Naomi Shihab Nye, illustrated by Ashley Bryan (Greenwillow,
$16.95). Ages 8-up.
</P>
<P>
   These poems are the real thing _ deep-down honest, fresh and
spare. Nye gathered them through 25 years of poetry workshops with
kids in grades 1 through 12. (``I feel like a puppy that can't
catch up to his mother. Like a creek that runs fast but can't reach
the ocean ...'' As a footnote, Nye tracked down these former kids
and found ... grown-ups. Dentists, surveyors, teachers, actors. And
poets all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
