<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-FREELANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REFUSES TO GRANT GLOBE FREELANCERS AN INJUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Superior Court Judge Carol S. Ball denied a request
Monday for an injunction that would have prohibited The Boston
Globe from enforcing a controversial new ``license agreement'' with
its freelance contributors beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gives the Globe the right to reproduce
freelancers' past and future work in other forms, including online,
without additional compensation. About 750 of the paper's
freelancers are facing a July 1 deadline to sign the agreement or
stop working for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The freelance plaintiffs accuse the Globe of trying to take
their intellectual property while the paper says its agreement,
which allows contributors to retain their copyright, is more
equitable than many in the newspaper industry.
</P>
<P>
   At a court hearing last Friday, the plaintiffs argued for an
injunction to set aside the July 1 deadline and prevent the Globe
from enforcing the agreement with those who have signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiffs here, artists all, believe with honest and
compelling conviction that they have been wronged by the cold,
cruel realitites of the e-commerce business world,'' said Ball in
her ruling denying that motion. ``It is not clear however, that the
business practice at issue violates,'' the law. ``The plaintiffs
may ultimately have a remedy at law, but the issuance of emergency
injunctive relief would be inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased, and I hope the judge's decision will cause
(the plaintiffs) to think long and hard about whether they want to
continue the litigation,'' said Globe attorney William Berkowitz,
adding that the paper will soon file a motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorney Indira Talwani indicated Monday that the
plaintiffs are eager to contest the merits of their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that even though this is the new world of e-commerce,
the same old rules apply,'' she said. ``This case is about the
Globe refusing to do business unless the plaintiffs agree to turn
over valuable rights for which the Globe is not offering additional
compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal reaction is that I think we've got a strong case
and finally, quite outside the legal issue, there's the moral
issue,'' said Elijah Wald, a member of the Boston Globe Freelancers
Assocation and supporter of the plaintiffs. He characterized the
Globe position as ``give us the rights to everything you've written
or never write for us again.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe spokesman Richard Gulla, while expressing pleasure with
Ball's ruling, said, ``We hope those freelancers who haven't signed
the new license agreement will do so. For the Globe's part, we wish
to continue a long-standing relationship that we believe has been
beneficial to both the Globe and its freelance contributors. We
have always valued their contributions and we always will.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulla also said that freelanders who do not sign by the July 1
deadline would not be precluded from ever working again for the
paper, adding that ``if somebody wants to sign beyond the July 1
date, that's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
