<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BIZMAG27-COX     06-26 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAG27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expect fewer market gyrations, report says
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Financial sailing may be a little calmer in the months
ahead. That's the consensus of the gurus at Barron's (June 26)
midyear forecast roundtable.
</P>
<P>
   They foresee fewer market gyrations in the second half, thanks
in part to the interest-rate medicine doled out by the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   They're buying financials, which have taken a beating because of
concerns about interest rates. Citigroup, Wells Fargo and MONY
Group all make the grade.
</P>
<P>
   So do energy shares, such as Frontier Oil, Exxon Mobil, Royal
Dutch, BP Amoco, Apache and Anadarko.
</P>
<P>
   Philosophy counseling: Corporate bosses no longer consult
psychotherapists and ministers for wisdom, says the Economist (June
30). They're turning to the cleverest thinkers of all: ancient
philosophers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Morris, author of ``If Aristotle Ran General Motors: The New
Soul of Business,'' earns $30,000 an hour _ one of the highest fees
for a non-celebrity speaker in America _ teaching Socrates and
Hegel to the likes of IBM, Campbell Soup, General Electric and
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Marinoff, who wrote ``Plato, not Prozac! Applying Philosophy
to Everyday Problems,'' is heading the rise of ``philosophy
counseling,'' with roots in Europe in the early '80s but new to
America. He's a bargain at $100 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Best Web sites: Quite a few finance and investment magazines
have discovered that a practical service they can offer is to help
harried readers find their way among the thousands of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latest, Smart Money (July), The Wall Street Journal's
personal finance magazine, offers ``the 52 best Web sites to save
you time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Internet Life (July) goes one better and offers the 50
``most incredubly useful'' Web sites, for those who ``thought you'd
seen everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern tech magazine: Theoretically, the Internet has rendered
geography meaningless. Reality is another matter, say two
technology magazines that look at the South as a future Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A new tech magazine that claims to cover ``the New South's new
economy'' _ digitalsouth (July/August) _ looks at venture
investment in seven leading tech hubs: Atlanta; Austin, Texas;
Baltimore; Dallas; Research Triangle Park, N.C.; South Florida, and
Washington/Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In a package of articles on the venture capital industry, Upside
(July) also looks at what it calls the ``Silicon South,'' or
``investing with a Southern accent,'' focusing on Atlanta and on
North Carolina's Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venture capitalists in this region straddle the traditional
finance world and that of the new economy,'' writes Jason Kelly,
who happens to be editor in chief of digitalsouth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
