A5532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-RESULTS-BOS &LR;      06-26 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-RESULTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-PARTY RULE ENDS IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ As the first results trickled in late Monday
night from polling stations around the country, it became
increasingly clear that Zimbabwe's weekend parliamentary election _
widely seen as the nation's most important vote since the poll that
ended colonial rule two decades ago _ has broken the grip of
one-party rule.
</P>
<P>
   But after a bitter and violent campaign, neither President
Robert Mugabe's party, nor its rival, seemed eager to practice the
politics of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In the anxious lull between the voting and the announcement of
full results, expected Tuesday, polling agents painstakingly
counted close to 3 million ballots by hand, international observers
cast a wary eye for signs of fraud, and the two main parties began
staking out their turf.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Morgan Tsvangirai, claiming a mandate before
the first tallies were even reported, vowed to impeach Mugabe if he
refused to share power. The president, whose term does not end
until 2002 and who has sole authority to name his Cabinet, shrugged
off that demand, rejecting a joint government regardless of the
poll's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe may be forced to reconsider. The two parties were running
neck and neck, with the opposition claiming 30 seats and the ruling
party 32 in early counting. Whatever the final tally, political
observers say, the political landscape has been fundamentally
transformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe cannot stem the tide. The wish of the electorate is
pluralism in parliament,'' said Mike Mataure, a former legislator
from the ruling party who is now starting an institution on
democratic governance. ``If he denies the opposition participation
in his government, he is asking for trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 65 percent of voters cast ballots over the weekend _
more than twice the turnout in the last parliamentary vote five
years ago. Election officials said the high participation slowed
counting. Although delays exacerbated fears around the country of
vote rigging, international observers reported no serious problems
in the counting.
</P>
<P>
   Political dissent has had a tough time gaining a foothold on the
African continent. The post-colonial period, starting in the late
1950s, ushered in nationalists who replaced foreign rule with their
own forms of oppression. Mugabe, one of the last of that generation
of ``strongmen,'' has shown no patience with dissent during his
long rule.
</P>
<P>
   But economic decline, hastening over the past three years to the
current point of crisis, gave his critics an opportunity. The
trade-union movement met tax hikes with strikes. Lawyers and
human-rights groups launched a civic forum for constitutional
reform. Last September, these forces coalesced around the labor
movement to create the Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe doesn't have to look far for examples of accommodation
between political rivals. To it's south, South Africa defied all
predictions of civil war when the black and white communities
negotiated a peaceful end to minority rule, paving the way for
democratic elections in 1994. To the east lies Mozambique, where
two guerrilla movements ended 17 years of civil war through
dialogue, and last December contested their second peaceful
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Few expect Mugabe to embrace powersharing. The president and his
party ``have a very low threshold for tolerance,'' said John
Makumbe, a political scientist at the University of Zimbabwe in
Harare. ``Mugabe does not tolerate any elements that have a
different view, even within his own party. Working with a another
party in parliament would require that he take a totally fresh
approach to governance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's highly unlikely, Makumbe said, which means Zimbabwe may
find itself in an awkward new era of divided governance, with the
legislative and executive branches controlled by different parties.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has vowed to impeach Mugabe if he does not
include them in his government. Unless it wins a two-thirds
majority in parliament, however, it would need support from within
Mugabe's party. That's unlikely for two reasons. First, few
expected the opposition to win even a simple majority, since the
constitution allows Mugabe to appoint 30 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The president, Makumbe also said, would sooner destroy his own
party than let it dictate the terms of his retirement: ``Below
Mugabe, there are many in the party who are progressive, but they
are dead scared of him. He will still find ways to bulldog them.''
</P>
<P>
   The election, it appears, has moved a bitter political contest
from the campaign trail to the halls of government. Both sides
claim a right to power, but both could be mistaken. Popular
mistrust in the ruling class does not equal confidence in the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In countries like Kenya, Uganda, and Zimbabwe, the strength of
the opposition is the same: The people are fed up with the
government,'' said Mahmood Mamdani, a Ugandan academic at Columbia
University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   With joblessness, inflation, and interest rates all soaring
above 50 percent and gas pumps constantly running dry, voters are
clamoring for urgent economic improvement. Like it or not, the two
sides will be forced ultimately to seek consensus.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Mamdani said, ``all the social problems will still be
there on the morrow of the election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
