<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A FORT WORTH BAR, A CLOSE ENCOUNTER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BONNIE AND CLYDE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From 1932 to 1934, when they were terrorizing Texas, Oklahoma,
Missouri and Arkansas, Bonnie Parker and Clyde Barrow often came to
Fort Worth _ but to hang out, not hold up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used Fort Worth as a place to rest,'' says Sue
McCafferty, former president of the North Fort Worth Historical
Society. ``I don't know of anyone left who actually saw them, but I
knew people who did.''
</P>
<P>
   When the couple stayed overnight in Fort Worth, it was usually
on the wild north side, McCafferty says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they would be in separate hotels,'' she adds. ``That would
make it harder for them to be taken by surprise and captured. Clyde
stayed at the old Stockyards Hotel, and I think Bonnie was in The
Oasis, which was diagonally across the street.''
</P>
<P>
   McCafferty's favorite Bonnie and Clyde Fort Worth tale ``was
told to me by a man who said he was there when it happened,'' she
says. ``Clyde was in a north side bar one night, drinking with some
old boy, and all of a sudden Bonnie walks in. Now, that old boy
didn't know he was standing next to Clyde Barrow, and he didn't
recognize Bonnie Parker. He starts to shoot his mouth off to Clyde
about her. You know, things like, `Look at that doll!' Then he
starts on Bonnie, trying to impress her. She just tells Clyde,
`Let's go,' and they do, with that old boy hollering after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were gone, somebody said to him, `Are you out of
your mind? Do you know who that was? Bonnie Parker probably had a
big enough gun in her purse to blow your head off!' And I expect
that man never talked out of turn to a strange woman again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Guinn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
