<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-0627-     06-26 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RECORD SURPLUS PROMPTS ELECTION-YEAR DEAL FROM CLINTON
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics
categories
 &HT;    BY BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. government is on track to take in a record
$4.2 trillion more than it will spend in the coming decade,
President Clinton announced Monday, touching off a new round of
partisan jockeying over how to use the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated surplus _ a whopping $1.3 trillion more than the
White House projected just last winter _ points to the persistent
strength of an economic expansion that continues to exceed the
expectations of analysts, both public and private.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to shield the windfall from Republican calls for tax
cuts, Clinton laid out a plan for using $2.7 trillion for debt
relief and another $1 trillion for an array of Democratic
priorities including low-income tax cuts and efforts to shore up
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered congressional Republicans an election-year deal,
however, saying he would go along with a tax cut of up to $250
billion, over 10 years, to reduce the so-called marriage penalty,
if Republicans would match that dollar-for-dollar with a program to
provide prescription drug benefits for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal would allow each party to claim a legislative
victory in an area important to their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good-faith offer where I want to meet them
halfway, I want them to meet me halfway,'' Clinton told White House
reporters. ``We can clearly afford this, and we ought to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, were wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with the president,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said in a prepared statement.
``What I will not do is engage in political horse trading that
gives short shrift to the long range challenges we face as a
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans have proposed a tax cut of $150 billion over
five years to reduce what they regard as a penalty paid by married
couples who file joint income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate Republican aide said the party wants to reach an
agreement with Clinton on prescription drug benefits and the
marriage penalty, but it rejects the approach of bargaining over
the issues on a dollar-for-dollar basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make sure the policy's right,'' said the aide,
``before we start trading off numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the rhetoric lies a historic political debate over what
to do with the massive surpluses the government expects to generate
over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   Just last February, when Clinton submitted his fiscal 2001
budget proposals to Congress, those surpluses were projected to
total up to $2.9 trillion over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   In its summer Mid Session Review of budget matters, though, the
White House projected Monday that the surplus could total as much
as $4.2 trillion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, the federal surplus is projected to hit $211
billion _ the largest ever _ and it's likely to grow to $228
billion next year, the White House projects.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surplus, in both years, comes from the Social
Security program, which is currently taking in more in employee
premiums than it is paying out on retirement and worker disability
benefits. Budgeting practice establishes a firewall that treats
Social Security premiums separately from general tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Setting Social Security surpluses aside, the surplus for this
year is projected to be $39 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The rosy budget outlook assumes the economy _ still growing, at
an annual rate of 5.4 percent during the first quarter of this
year, after more than nine years of expansion _ will continue to
grow by 3 percent a year, on average, over the coming decade.
That's up from the projected 2.7 percent average growth rate
assumed in the February projections.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the federal debt is complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed dedicating $2.7 trillion in surpluses _ $2.3
trillion from Social Security and $403 trillion from Medicare_ to
debt reduction over the coming decade. That, he said, along with
the debt repayment already scheduled, would enable the Treasury
Department to wipe out the $3.5 trillion publicly-held debt by the
year 2012.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly-held portion of the overall federal debt is what
the government owes to banks and private investors, on which it
pays more than $200 billion a year in interest _ or 12 cents for
every federal tax dollar the government collects.
</P>
<P>
   The overall federal debt _ the product of three decades of
deficit spending _ would continue to increase, rising from its
current level of $5.5 trillion to $6.5 trillion, under White House
projections, by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   That reflects the growing obligations of the Social Security
program to working baby boomers who begin retiring en masse a
little more than a decade from now.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in Social Security obligations would build with or
without the budget surpluses. The increased Social Security
obligations are, in part, a symptom of the growing economy, as the
more jobs there are, and the more that workers own, the more they
pay into the system, on the promise of receiving retirement
benefits in the future.
</P>
<P>
   NETTAG: http://www.gpo.gov/usbudget
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans e-mail address is Bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
