<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-SOSA-VOTES27-COX     06-26 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-VOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa's votes to go with him if he switches leagues
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ National League votes cast for Sammy Sosa won't be
wasted if the Chicago Cubs trade the slugging outfielder to an
American League team before the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig has decided that Sosa's votes will go
with him if he switches leagues. The All-Star Game is July 11 at
Turner Field in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is third among outfielders in the next-to-last National
League vote totals, released Monday. With 801,404 votes, Sosa is
behind Cincinnati's Ken Griffey Jr. (1,000,924) and San Francisco's
Barry Bonds (873,847). Montreal's Vladimir Guererro (724,352) is
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   American League vote totals will be released today. Last week,
the top AL outfielders were Jermaine Dye of Kansas City, Bernie
Williams of the Yankees and Manny Ramirez of Cleveland. Sosa might
finish with more votes than any of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Voting at ballparks ends today, but fans can continue to cast
votes on the Internet through Saturday. New York Mets catcher Mike
Piazza is the leading NL vote-getter with 1,239,531.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game starters will be announced July 4. The
pitchers and reserves will be selected the next day by the
managers, Bobby Cox of the Braves for the National League and Joe
Torre of the Yankees for the American League.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting race in the American League is at
shortstop, where Seattle's Alex Rodriguez went into this week with
a lead over the Yankees' Derek Jeter and Boston Nomar Garciappara.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Garciaparra narrowly won the starting spot despite
having 25,000 votes thrown out because they were cast on the last
day by a Red Sox fan through a computer program.
</P>
<P>
   Because of computer ballot-stuffing, Major League Baseball took
steps this season to ensure that votes are legitimate. No more than
25 votes will be accepted from any one e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   Balloting at stadiums also was limited to 25 games for the first
time. In the past, some teams had advantages because they had more
home games during the voting period.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is expecting a record 14 million votes to be cast this
year, with at least 2 million coming from the Internet. Votes can
be cast at team Web sites and two others
(www.majorleaguebaseball.com and www.seasonticket.com).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
