<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5536 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SHARANSKY-ART-     06-26 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHARANSKY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARANSKY, A JEWISH HERO, AGAIN EXERCISES THE POWER OF RESISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ It has been 14 years since Interior Minister Natan
Sharansky began making the transition from icon to man when he
emigrated to Israel. It has been four since he morphed further from
man to politician.
</P>
<P>
   But his experience as a prisoner of conscience in the former
Soviet Union not only stamped him forever; it also shaped others'
expectations of him in unyielding ways.
</P>
<P>
   To Israelis and to Jews worldwide, Sharansky is somewhat frozen
in time behind the bars where he sat for nine years while they
invested in him as a hero and fought for his freedom. And
everything that he does is judged as a return on that investment,
which means some amount of disappointment for everyone, left and
right, secular and religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody marched for me,'' Sharansky, 52, said in an
interview Monday. ``And everybody feels I owe them.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Sharansky is fighting an uphill battle to persuade
Prime Minister Ehud Barak to join hands with the rightist Likud
Party to form a national unity government. He portrays this, too,
as an outgrowth of his days as a Soviet dissident. In his old
punishment cell, he says, he did not distinguish between different
kinds of Jews, and ever since meeting the divided reality of the
Jewish nation, he has sought to forge a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Some lionize him for this, and contend that Sharansky would be
an ideal national leader, much as he would break the mold with his
thickly accented Hebrew and a military record that consists of
three weeks in the national guard.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of Sharansky, who tend to be disillusioned friends
and former supporters, contend that for all his talk of healing, he
is a divisive force.
</P>
<P>
   Doves here long ago stopped expressing their disappointment that
Sharansky, a former human rights champion, ended up taking a hard
line on peace and joining the nationalist camp. Now, though, they
say their disappointment has turned to anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Since last week, Sharansky, through publicized letters to the
prime minister, has been demanding that Barak apply the brakes
instead of pedaling furiously toward an Israeli-Palestinian summit
meeting in the United States. If Barak does not stop to brief his
coalition in detail and take into account opposing points of view,
Sharansky said, he will not accompany him to a summit conference
and he will quit the government.
</P>
<P>
   Quitting is a threat that Sharansky has made before, not only to
Barak but also to Benjamin Netanyahu, the rightist prime minister
who preceded him. But right now it is a threat with real teeth
because a pullout by Sharansky would endanger Barak's fragile
coalition during a tense round of peace negotiations. Even though
Sharansky's party, Yisrael B'Alyia, holds only four seats in
Parliament, his departure would be unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're talking about the size of his party, he's a somewhat
peripheral figure,'' said Yaron Ezrahi, a Hebrew University
political scientist. ``But his power exceeds his party's stature,
both because the government is now extraordinarily fragile and
because he is Natan, ne Anatoly, Sharansky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is like an epic hero of the Jewish people for the 20th
century, even though something happened on the way from Anatoly to
Natan,'' Ezrahi added, referring to the Russian given name and the
chosen Hebrew one.
</P>
<P>
   Former associates say that what happened is politics. ``He
survived the Gulag, and now he's applying the same rules of
survival to the political arena,'' said Hirsh Goodman, a columnist
for the magazine Jerusalem Report who used to be a close friend of
Sharansky. ``He's wooing a constituency, and turning his back on
the liberal human rights personality that he was. I think he's an
obstructionist, and intellectually and politically dishonest, but,
hey, that's just playing the brutal rules of the political game in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky's fans maintain the exact opposite, that only he rises
above the political swamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffering does deepen people, and he's the least petty person
in the country,'' said Jonathan Rosenblum, a columnist and a
spokesman for Am Ehad, an Orthodox advocacy group. ``He really
believes in compromise not as a necessity of government, but as a
fundamental principle.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sharansky went on a television program recently, the host
made a word play on his name, calling him ``Psharansky,'' which
incorporates the Hebrew word for compromise. Sharansky took it as a
compliment. But his media adviser was horrified because he knew
that Israelis _ and especially Russian-Israelis _ would read it as
an insult, a synonym for ``weak.''
</P>
<P>
   The editor of Vesti, a Russian-language newspaper here, says the
immigrants are applauding Sharansky's ``very strong and very tough
position of recent days.'' Sharansky's constituency tends to be
antagonistic to the idea that Israel, such a small country compared
with the former Soviet Union, would make territorial concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to give grades to our politicians,'' said Elia
Naymark, the editor. ``But in the last few days, his score is very
high. Because a lot of immigrants from Russian support the
right-wing position. They kept waiting for him to speak up. And now
that's what he's doing, what has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sharansky and his fellow former refuseniks have
gravitated through the years to the right of the Israeli political
spectrum. Their experience in Russia apparently taught them to
disdain concessions to an ideological foe. Reared in an empire,
they also never quite understood the logic of ceding territory to
an adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky does not precisely share his constituents' concern
about land. To him, the ideological obstacle to plunging into
peacemaking is that he would be hesitant to trust an agreement
forged with what he sees as an authoritarian regime, like that of
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader. He thinks that Israel is
giving and not getting, that it should be demanding
democratization, changes in Palestinian textbooks and the
confiscation of illegal weapons in exchange for territorial
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to live in the abstract love of the people of
the world, and the so-called new Middle East,'' he said. ``Everyone
will be kind and good if we just sign on the bottom line. But
that's a good way maybe to commit suicide, not to build a real
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Many, including critics, are charmed by Sharansky personally.
Short and bald, he is nobody's blow-dried politician, and he seems,
in all ways but intellectually, quite unpretentious. He sits in the
front seat beside the driver of his government-issued Volvo, for
instance, instead of in the back. He hangs on his office wall a
rubberized caricature of himself, a puppet from a political satire
show.
</P>
<P>
   Next to his desk sits a chessboard suspended in mid-game. It is
part of his lore that he is a chess wizard who played in his head
when he was imprisoned. Now, as then, he said, he is always in the
middle of a game with himself, but ``the board helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who once admired him worry that he is cultivating a
cult-like following. ``In his thinking, it is not the immigrants
who sent him to the Parliament, but he who brought them there,''
said Roman Bronfman, who split from Sharansky last year to form a
small left-secular Russian party. ``He feels like a messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would describe his evolution since the Soviets
released him and allowed him to emigrate to Israel in 1986,
Sharansky said longingly that everything used to be black and
white. ``The main principle then was: no compromise,'' he said.
``In the morning, you said no to the KGB, and in the evening you
said no. You could feel yourself a tzaddik.'' That is a holy man.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the free world,'' Sharansky continued, ``it is a lot more
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sharansky weighs in on broad national issues like
peacemaking, some here accuse him of overstepping his bounds. His
party is supposed to be what they call here a kielbasa party _ that
is, only interested in its next handout. Sharansky said some people
say to him, ``How dare you take big stands when your people are
only interested in sausage!''
</P>
<P>
   He says he thinks that Barak is trying to co-opt him by inviting
him to attend a summit meeting, if there is one, in Washington. He
thinks Barak will make it impossible for those who oppose an
agreement to reject it, because ``the impatient world'' will be
applauding Israel ``in front of all the cameras.'' Israel would
risk international isolation to turn its back on such approbation.
</P>
<P>
   So that, he said, is why he is acting to halt things in their
tracks, and urging Barak to form a partnership with Ariel Sharon,
the rightist Likud leader. Sharon, he said, will abandon his
uncompromising positions once he is inside the circle of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5537 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-1100(3     06-26 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-1100(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRAIL OF BONNIE AND CLYDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``You have heard the story of Jesse James,
</P>
<P>
   Of how he lived and died.
</P>
<P>
   If you are still in need of something to read
</P>
<P>
   Here is the story of Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Story of Bonnie and Clyde,'' a poem written in jail by
Bonnie Parker
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GIBSLAND, La._ The lonely stretch of backcountry road doesn't
look much different now than it did on the morning of May 23, 1934.
</P>
<P>
   It was called Sailes Road then; it is Louisiana State Road 154
South now. Once gravel, it's now paved. But the narrow, two-lane
corridor is still flanked on both sides by thick scrub and trees.
The road winds left and right, up and down, making it impossible to
drive too fast, just like 66 years ago. And there's one particular
spot, at the foot of a fairly steep hill, fronted by a heavy clump
of trees and brush, that offers excellent sightlines and ample
cover to anyone wanting to shoot directly across the two lanes.
</P>
<P>
   So the brush is the same, and the winding road pretty much the
same. But, of course, the monument wasn't there that morning _ the
graffiti-stained, half-chipped-away lump of granite with the
inscription, ``This site, May 23, 1934, Clyde Barrow and Bonnie
Parker were killed by law enforcement officials.'' That was erected
a few years later by Bienville Parish residents eager to cash in on
their community's newfound notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Barrow gang's getaways ended, almost instantly turning
this otherwise unremarkable stretch of road into a pilgrimage spot.
After all these years, people still come from all over the world to
see the ``death monument.''
</P>
<P>
   About six miles from the site, in Gibsland (pop. 1,200), City
Hall is a Bonnie and Clyde souvenir store, offering coffee cups and
bumper stickers and T-shirts festooned with photos of the couple
brandishing guns. There are also bricks for sale ($10 for whole
bricks, $5 for fragments), allegedly from chimneys of local houses
where Bonnie and Clyde slept. Proceeds pay for an annual
re-enactment of the ambush that killed the famous outlaws. It's
going on seven decades since the bloody, one-sided shootout that
lasted at most three minutes, but tourists still come to see where
and how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We draw from 3,000 to 5,000 visitors every year,'' says
70-year-old Billie Jean Pollard, chairman of the local committee
that oversees the re-enactment. ``They come from England, Spain,
Holland, Japan. Year after year, people never, ever, stop coming.
They can't hear or see or learn enough about those two.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``They class them as cold-blooded killers
</P>
<P>
   They say they are heartless and mean
</P>
<P>
   But I say this with pride
</P>
<P>
   That I once knew Clyde
</P>
<P>
   When he was honest and upright and clean.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The ``death monument,'' like Graceland for Elvis fans, is the
one place Bonnie and Clyde enthusiasts feel they must visit. But
this rural Louisiana parish near Shreveport is hardly the only
community that can lay claim to the Barrow gang. Dallas, in fact,
has the most substantial hold on the famous outlaws _ it is where
they grew up, began their life of crime and are buried. In fact,
starting from the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex, it is possible to
combine Dallas; Fort Worth; Stringtown, Okla.; and Gibsland, La.,
into a sort of ``weekend Bonnie and Clyde getaway'' that would sate
the desires of the most devoted chronicler of the outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   For chronology's sake, though not convenience', begin with the
old Barrow garage in Dallas at the intersection of Singleton and
Borger roads. Amazingly, the building at 1221 Singleton, where
Clyde's father operated his garage, is still there, but Clyde
probably wouldn't recognize it. A subsequent occupant painted it
bright blue, yellow and green. The front stands empty, but the back
half of the small building and its yard are still used as an auto
repair shop.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde tried to eke out a grease-stained existence here during
the early days of the Depression, though fixing cars certainly
wasn't what he had in mind for his future.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde wanted to be a jazz musician. He had taught himself to
play guitar and saxophone, but in 1930, there were few
opportunities to get started in professional music, and the
21-year-old's day job was helping his father in the elder Barrow's
struggling business.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-year-old Bonnie Parker had even grander dreams. The
slender, attractive girl, who wore a size 2 dress, hoped to become
a movie star. Life hadn't cooperated with her dream, either.
Married at 16, Bonnie's husband was in prison, and she was
waitressing in a dumpy Dallas cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in January 1930, the scar-crossed couple met for the
first time at the home of a mutual friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just clicked, and everybody around them felt it,'' says
Phillip Steele, an historian whose recently published book, ``The
Family Story of Bonnie and Clyde'' (Pelican Press, $9.95), was
co-authored with Marie Barrow Scoma, Clyde's younger sister.
``Together they still had big dreams, but they lived in a time when
nobody had money for gas or sugar, let alone luxuries. They had no
money. Clyde's big treat was sneaking into movies. He couldn't
afford a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoma, who died last year at age 81 just after the first draft
of ``The Family Story of Bonnie and Clyde'' was finished,
desperately wanted a book ``that told the truth about them,''
Steele says. ``I guess hundreds of books on the subject have been
written. But none had access to Marie's memory. So, understanding
that there were some truthful things Marie didn't enjoy including
about her brother and Bonnie but that still had to be in there, we
tried to create a book with valuable insights.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Barrow family lore, the Parker family considered
itself superior _ at least to Clyde's kin. The Parker house in
dingy west Dallas (Bonnie's late father was a bricklayer) was nicer
than the Barrows'. Clyde tried to make a good impression when
calling on Bonnie at her mother's home. But their fledgling
relationship was interrupted when police from Denton arrested Clyde
for car theft in that city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clyde and his older brother Buck had started stealing
things,'' Steele says. ``That's what lots of young men did during
the Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Bonnie and Clyde are the Barrow gang,
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you all have read
</P>
<P>
   How they rob and steal,
</P>
<P>
   And how those who squeal
</P>
<P>
   Are usually found dying or dead.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5539 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-2ndTak     06-26 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
GIBSLAND, La.: dying or dead.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For Clyde, imprisonment _ and then a daring breakout and
recapture (Bonnie smuggled a gun into his Waco prison cell) _
followed his arrest in 1930. Clyde's crimes and jailbreak earned
him a 14-year sentence at Eastham Prison Farm near Huntsville. But
he was not to be rehabilitated during his stay. Just the opposite,
in fact: A diary kept by Clyde's mother records that Clyde was
sodomized by another prisoner there, an incident she said hardened
a previously sweet-natured young man.
</P>
<P>
   After Clyde was paroled in February 1932, he briefly moved to
Massachusetts in a half-hearted attempt to go straight. Within
weeks, he returned to Texas and Bonnie. The spark between them was
still very much there, and, together again, this time forever, they
soon began the crime spree that would make them famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the real story of Bonnie and Clyde starts, at
least in most people's opinions,'' Steele says.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the legendary Barrow gang were, however, strictly
small-time crooks, bypassing banks in favor of mom-and-pop stores
and gas stations. But their minor misdeeds suddenly turned big time
in late April 1932 when they killed for the first time _ by
accident. One of the gang tried to shoot open a safe; the bullet
ricocheted and killed the owner of the Hillsboro store, who was
being held nearby at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The Barrow gang was now on the hook for murder, and they headed
north to Stringtown, a town that would become pivotal in the
creation of the Bonnie and Clyde of lore.
</P>
<P>
   Stringtown is about a three-hour drive northeast of Fort Worth,
following Interstate 35W north, U.S. 82 east to Sherman and U.S.
75/69 north.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Aug. 5, 1932, a dance was being held in
Stringtown at an outdoor pavilion adjacent to the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just me and one other fellow playing at the dance,''
recalls 86-year-old Duke Ellis of Atoka, who witnessed the night's
events. ``I was on guitar. He was on fiddle. We were up on this
raised platform, playing some of the popular tunes of the day. A
good crowd had turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   About 9 p.m., a car pulled up into the gravel lot by the
bandstand. Ellis recalls it was ``a Ford, maybe a '31 model. There
were three men in it _ Clyde Barrow, Raymond Hamilton and a third
gang member named Milligan. Well, they took turns getting out, one
at a time, to dance while the other two stayed in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   More than music was available at the dance; Ellis says someone
passed around ``wildcat whiskey _ you know, moonshine. It was
prohibition but people drank.'' The Barrow-gang trio gulped down
their share, looking, Ellis adds, ``just like everybody else there.
I never did see them disturbing the peace in any way, but most
every law officer in Atoka County was at the dance, too, and
Sheriff Charley Maxwell started telling folks he was going to
arrest those men in the car _ for drinking, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell walked up to the Ford, put his foot on the running
board, and leaned over to tell Clyde and Hamilton they were under
arrest (Milligan was on the dance floor).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just finished playing `Way Down Yonder,' maybe it was,
when I heard a noise like a car backfiring,'' Ellis says. ``I
looked over and the sheriff's body went flying back off that
running board. Harry Bryant, a man who was not a deputy or
anything, grabbed the gun off Charlie's body and started shooting
at the car. Clyde, he started trying to drive away fast, but he hit
a culvert and the car turned over on its side.''
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Barrow and Hamilton scrambled clear, guns blazing. Deputy
Eugene Moore was hit and killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullets were flying everywhere,'' says Ellis, who tried to
take refuge behind a nearby garage. ``One girl who was near me kept
hollering she knew she was going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Clyde and Hamilton eventually snuck back into Stringtown, where
they stole the first in a series of cars to make their getaway back
to Texas. (According to Ellis, the gang member he identifies as
Milligan was left behind and later captured.)
</P>
<P>
   Back at the outdoor pavilion, Ellis was recruited to help carry
the badly wounded sheriff to a nearby bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blood just soaked through that bed from him,'' Ellis says.
``He only lived because a woman who was a bootlegger kept pouring
whiskey down him. He had six bullet holes in him _ I counted
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor pavilion is gone now; a fruit stand is in its place
at the side of U.S. 69. Parts of the gravel parking lot remain.
Bessie Childress, who runs the fruit stand, is glad to show
visitors where Sheriff Maxwell's body fell. (''Right here by this
tree.'')
</P>
<P>
   The Stringtown gunfight was a turning point for the Barrow gang.
After the murder of a police officer, Bonnie and Clyde, with
nothing left to lose, became cold-blooded killers _ and
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   The gang (eventually joined by Clyde's brother Buck and Buck's
wife, Blanche) continued its pattern of robbing small businesses.
Now there was gunplay as often as not. During the next two years,
they killed perhaps a dozen people, including two Grapevine police
officers. Sometimes there were car chases down twisting roads. The
gang had a huge advantage _ most guns used by law enforcement
officers weren't powerful enough for the bullets to penetrate the
bodies of cars. Clyde didn't have that problem; his weapon of
choice was a Browning Automatic Rifle (BAR) that could blow a hole
through any auto.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``penny dreadful'' novelists of the era loved
Bonnie and Clyde. Steele guesses hundreds of short, sensational
novels about the duo were published from 1932 through 1934.
Newspapers across the Southwest also competed to write the most
lurid stories about their exploits, both real and imagined. Clyde
and Bonnie loved it _ though not one particular story in the
Star-Telegram. The gang came to Fort Worth on a handful of
occasions, usually to hang low and regroup on the city's rollicking
north side, where it was relatively easy to go unnoticed. They took
lots of pictures of themselves, which were widely distributed. But
though Bonnie, who once dreamed of being a famous movie star, loved
the publicity, she was incensed about a report that she smoked
cigars, insisting she only posed with one for a joke photo.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
