<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-ART-2TAK     06-26 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGHEST OBSTACLE FOR TAIWANESE BUSINESSMEN MAY BE CHINESE
GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Ask Stan Shih about personal computers, the
Internet or his native Taiwan, and he holds forth enthusiastically.
Not for nothing is Shih, the voluble founder of the computer maker
Acer, regarded as the head cheerleader and unofficial spokesman for
corporate Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Shih whether he favors an independent Taiwan, and he
turns monosyllabic. ``No,'' he says, as his Cheshire-cat smile
tightens.
</P>
<P>
   Shih, 56, has good reason to be wary. As the chairman of one of
Taiwan's biggest multinational corporations, he has major
investments in mainland China. Since Chen Shui-bian, a strong
supporter of Taiwanese independence, was elected president in
March, being identified as a person who supports independence _ or
one who even seems to _ has become a sure way to derail one's
prospects in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always neutral in election campaigns,'' Shih said. ``The
fact is, President Chen appointed me as one of his advisers. I
couldn't say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Shih says he did not even vote this year. Yet his advisory role
looked awfully close to a vote of confidence. And worse, he
appeared to be endorsing a man whose party espouses independence
for Taiwan. Beijing considers Taiwan to be a vital part of Chinese
territory that was separated during the civil war that ended in
1949, when Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists fled to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of the Chinese government to Chen's election was
swift and angry: It put out the word that Taiwanese businessmen
with ties to the new president or who favored independence for
Taiwan were putting their China operations at risk. The statement
was widely interpreted as a warning to Acer and Shih.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Shih is one of several captains of industry here who have
been caught in the treacherous political waters between Taipei and
Beijing. Some, like the plastics tycoon Hsu Wen-lung, have been
frank advocates of independence. Others, like Chang Yung-fa, a
shipping magnate, are longtime supporters of Chen. Still others,
like Shih, simply like to oblige future leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Beijing is scrutinizing the political
beliefs of Taiwanese business leaders and warning those who stray
from the official line that there is only one China. Political
analysts say the crackdown could undermine the historic role of
commerce as a bridge between Taiwan and China, binding the
countries closer together even when they diverge politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last election, China came to realize that businessmen
can play a very strong role in Taiwanese politics,'' Tien Hung-mao,
Taiwan's foreign minister, said in an interview last month. ``So
China has begun politicizing the economic relationship between the
two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Tien worries that Taiwanese business executives may be forced to
take a loyalty oath to protect their investments in China. Those
who refuse may become the targets of tax audits, surprise
inspections and other forms of harassment by the Chinese
government. In the worst case, some companies may be forced to
leave China and take their capital and skills with them.
</P>
<P>
   Since China opened its doors to Taiwan two decades ago, trade
across the Taiwan Strait has proved to be remarkably resistant to
politics. In the first quarter of this year, while Beijing was
threatening military action if the Taiwanese elected Chen, Taiwan
exported $6.2 billion worth of goods to China, a 16 percent
increase over 1999. It imported $1.3 billion, a 33 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   But Taiwan's investment in China is showing signs of weakness.
While the amount of investment contracts increased 46 percent in
the first quarter, the actual volume of Taiwanese money flowing
into China declined 9.5 percent, to $420 million, according to the
Foreign Trade Ministry in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that could be an early barometer of trouble. Even
investors like Shih, who were once wooed by Beijing to build
factories with promises of tax breaks and reduced import duties,
acknowledge they can no longer plow money into China without
thinking twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be concerned,'' Shih said. ``But I cannot control
their opinion. If they welcome me, I will contribute to their
country. If they don't welcome me, I have so many other things to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Shih is not as passive as he sounds. He traveled to a technology
conference in Beijing in April, enduring a snub when high-level
officials did not meet with him. And he plans to return in August
to promote a new Web site, which features a series of lectures by
him. By sharing his insights on entrepreneurialism with mainland
students, Shih clearly hopes to mend fences.
</P>
<P>
   Acer has a lot riding on Shih's charm offensive. Earlier this
year, the company opened a $50 million factory in the province of
Guangdong to make personal computers. Several more plants are on
the drawing board. The company is also testing an Internet service
in Shanghai. It hopes to roll out the service commercially, which
would make it a pioneer in China's interactive communications
business.
</P>
<P>
   For Acer, China is the linchpin in its plans to become a global
leader in the technology industry. Shih said Taiwan, with 23
million people, was simply too small to supply it with enough
workers or customers to compete with giant overseas rivals like
Dell Computer or IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Acer is also struggling in the fiercely competitive American
personal- computer market. The company is counting on rapid growth
in China to offset its tribulations in the United States. Shih
believes that despite the political uncertainty, Taiwanese
companies are still the best-positioned to dominate the mainland
market. Someday, he predicted, Taiwan and China will be parts of
the same greater China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long it will take,'' he said, ``but sooner or
later, after China becomes more competitive and self-confident, we
will treat China as our home market.''  &QL; 
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody shares Shih's optimism. Dennis Chao, the managing
director of a Taiwanese sportswear manufacturer, opened a factory
in the southern city of Guangzhou in 1987. He said he was drawn by
the Chinese government's promise of favorable treatment for Taiwan
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, however, Beijing stopped treating Taiwanese
differently than other foreign investors. Chao, 48, said that
losing breaks on import duties on machinery and raw materials has
made it uneconomical for him to install new equipment or otherwise
expand his factory, which employs 1,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the last month, the Chinese government warned Taiwanese
investors in the provinces of Guangdong and Fujian that they would
be subject to unspecified sanctions if they advocated independence
for Taiwan. Chao says he has studiously steered clear of politics.
But he said such threats only added to China's reputation as an
impossible place to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not enemies; we're all Chinese,'' Chao said as he shook
his head. ``It's enough to drive you crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said China's crackdown has been fueled by its
irritation with a few high-profile personalities in Taiwan rather
than any overall objection to where most business leaders stand on
the issue. In particular, Beijing is angry with Hsu Wen-lung, the
chairman of Chi Mei Industry, a petrochemical giant.
</P>
<P>
   Hsu, whose company has six factories in China, staunchly
supports Chen and has proclaimed his desire for an independent
Taiwan. The Chinese government has subjected Chi Mei to numerous
inspections and ordered state companies not to do business with it.
It is the only known case of retaliation so far.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said Beijing could play hardball with Hsu because it had
a large and competitive domestic petrochemical industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a policy of selective sanctions,'' said Andrew Yang,
the secretary general of the Chinese Council of Advanced Policy
Studies, a research organization here. ``It is not a unified policy
toward Taiwan companies.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Yang said China would be unlikely to take Draconian
steps against Acer, which, as a high-technology company, provides
expertise and thousands of skilled jobs. Despite the contretemps
with its founder, Acer has not lost its license to test Internet
services in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Shih is going out of his way to protest his political
innocence. He says he hopes for the eventual reunification of
Taiwan and China. In case there is any misunderstanding, he adds,
``I also agree with the Chinese government's position that
businessmen shouldn't support independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here say that Shih, who learned business by helping his
mother sell duck eggs and stationary, was probably turned into more
of a symbol than he ever wished during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan Shih has been very conservative his whole life,'' said
Antonio Chiang, the editor of The Taipei Times, an English-language
newspaper that supports Chen. ``But he is sympathetic to the cause
of reform. Chen Shui-bian is the only one who can reform Taiwanese
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts say Beijing does not pay attention to such
subtleties. They believe the Chinese government is using commercial
ties as a lever to subdue Taiwan. Beijing pursued a similar
campaign with Hong Kong investors before the former British colony
reverted to Chinese rule in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, even tycoons who had been knighted by Queen
Elizabeth swore fealty to Beijing. Some experts say the lure of the
mainland market is so Strong that it will get similar allegiance
from Taiwan's tycoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early days, China relied heavily on Taiwanese
investment, but now foreign investors from many countries are in
China,'' said Liang Su-Yung, head of the Strait Peaceful
Reunification Association, a pro-China lobbying group. ``Taiwanese
companies need China more than it needs them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5542 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-3rdTak     06-26 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIEANDCLYDE-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
GIBSLAND, La.: a joke photo. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Amon,'' his biography of Star-Telegram publisher Amon
Carter, Jerry Flemmons tells about a letter Clyde sent to Carter
after being displeased with printed comments about Bonnie: ``You
better think, decide and make up your mind and not let your Editor
make another remark about Bonnie like you did the other day,''
Clyde wrote the publisher. ``They called her my cigar-smoking
woman. Another remark about my underworld mate and I will end such
men as you mighty quick. I know where you and your reporters
live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter scared the hell out of Amon,'' Flemmons adds. The
letter ``was never mentioned in the Star-Telegram, but until the
couple's ambush and death in Louisiana, Bonnie was never again
called a cigar smoker.''
</P>
<P>
   Though their time in Fort Worth was peaceful, there were
headline-grabbing shootouts in Missouri and Arkansas, plus
innumerable close calls after holdups in Texas and Oklahoma. Then
the gang's luck began to turn bad. Bonnie was horribly burned in a
June 1933 car accident; on one of her legs, Steele says, bone
showed through in two places. In July, the gang was cornered in
Iowa. Bonnie and Clyde escaped, but Buck was shot (for the second
time in five days), and he and Blanche were captured. Buck died
from his wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Scoma told Steele that, no matter where they had been or what
they had done, Bonnie and Clyde always returned to Dallas for
regular visits with their families. At first these were happy
occasions. Scoma recalled her big brother bringing her a new
bicycle, an almost unimaginable gift for a child during the
Depression. But after Buck's death, the gatherings were more
somber.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense that their time was running out,'' Steele
says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think they are too tough or desperate.
</P>
<P>
   They know the law always wins.
</P>
<P>
   They have been shot at before
</P>
<P>
   But they do not ignore
</P>
<P>
   That death is the wages of sin.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   All roads eventually would lead back to Dallas, where the
families of both Bonnie and Clyde lived. But when they returned for
the last time, it would be in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Texas authorities had had enough. Bonnie and Clyde
were making them look bad, and, in the darkest days of the
Depression, the powerful image of glamorous outlaws out to get
something for themselves was one that authorities wanted
desperately to snuff out. So Frank Hamer, a legendary Texas Ranger
with scars from 23 bullet wounds, was named to head a posse
devoting itself exclusively to hunting down Bonnie and Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   The first problem was obvious. A car recovered from an earlier
shootout with the gang had more than 100 dents from bullets _ none
had penetrated the metal. The posse needed Browning Automatic
Rifles, and there were eight stored in Texas' National Guard
Armory. But the law prohibited the rifles being loaned to
nonmilitary personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they came to me, I turned 'em down,'' says 95-year-old
Col. Weldon Dowis of Hot Springs, Ark., then a 29-year-old National
Guard captain. ``It was against the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas congressman Hatton W. Summers wrote Dowis a letter saying
he would take responsibility for the loan. Reluctantly, Dowis
handed over two of the rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to show them how to shoot 'em on our range,'' he
recalls. ``They said they figured they'd know pretty soon where
they could catch (Bonnie and Clyde).''
</P>
<P>
   They were right. In January 1934, the Barrow gang added Henry
Methvin, a young hood whose family had a farm in Louisiana's
Bienville Parish. Bonnie and Clyde had established a previous
pattern of hiding out in the family homes of gang members. Hamer
knew Henderson Jordan, the Bienville sheriff. They arranged a
meeting with Ivan Methvin, Henry's father, and offered a deal: If
Methvin helped the posse ambush Bonnie and Clyde, his son would be
pardoned for his crimes in Texas and Arkansas. Methvin agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Barrow gang showed up in Bienville. Ivan Methvin
welcomed them, then contacted the authorities. The posse was
summoned, the terrain scouted, and, on May 22, Methvin warned his
son to stay away from Bonnie and Clyde the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning, Bonnie and Clyde and Henry Methvin drove
into the sleepy town of Gibsland. Henry made himself scarce. The
infamous couple went to a cafe and ordered sandwiches. Bonnie was
still eating hers when Clyde spotted a police car on a nearby
street and told her they had to get back to the car. There was no
concern about Henry's whereabouts; he could easily find
transportation home.
</P>
<P>
   The outlaws took Sailes Road back toward the Methvin farm. They
probably didn't hurry; they were enjoying their stay in the area
and weren't too concerned about local residents recognizing them.
Ninety-year-old Pauline Evans, who lived in Bienville Parish at the
time, remembers Clyde pulling his car over to talk to her as she
stood by her family's mailbox. He politely introduced himself _
Bonnie was also in the front seat _ and asked if she wanted a ride.
She declined.
</P>
<P>
   The posse had taken up its position in the brush alongside the
road hours earlier. About 9 a.m., a lookout spotted Clyde's car
coming and gave a signal. Ivan Methvin pulled his truck opposite
the ambush site, parking on the side of the road. Clyde spotted his
host's vehicle as he crested a small hill, and stopped to see if
Methvin needed help. As the car halted, Methvin dived under his
truck. The six members of the posse leaped to their feet and opened
fire.
</P>
<P>
   When it was finally silent, the officers gingerly opened the car
door. Bonnie was still clutching the remnants of her sandwich. A
.45 pistol was in her lap. Clyde had a sawed-off shotgun beside
him; his beloved saxophone was in the back seat, beside the other
guns he hadn't had time to use. Each of the partially dismembered
bodies had more than 40 bullet wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Two outlaws had been silenced. And, with a monument to the deed
soon erected, a town's prominent place on the map was established.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day they will go down together;
</P>
<P>
   And they will bury them side by side.
</P>
<P>
   To a few it means grief,
</P>
<P>
   To the law it's relief,
</P>
<P>
   But it's death to Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie got part of it right. She and Clyde died together. He was
25, she was 23. The posse had their bodies removed from the
bullet-riddled car and shipped back to the Barrow and Parker
families in Dallas, with one delay. The Bienville Parish locals
demanded to see the corpses, so they were put on brief public
display in nearby Arcadia first.
</P>
<P>
   But the outlaw couple weren't buried side by side. Bonnie was
interred in Dallas' relatively upscale Crownhill Memorial Park
Cemetery, at 9700 Webb Chapel Road. Clyde was buried next to older
brother Buck in cramped Western Heights Cemetery a few miles away
at 1617 Fort Worth Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Like the back road where they died, their graves are still
pretty much unchanged. Bonnie's marker reads, ``As the flowers are
all made sweeter by the sunshine and the dew, so this old world is
made brighter by the likes of folks like you.'' A receptionist at
the cemetery says that ``lots of people come to see Bonnie.'' They
leave flowers and notes and business cards.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde's grave is harder to find. Western Heights Cemetery is
surrounded by a high chain-link fence, and its gates are often
padlocked, with no visiting hours posted. But people do get in;
part of the fence by the gate has been pulled down to make a
convenient foothold. Clyde and Buck's marker says simply, ``Gone
But Not Forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she died, Steele says, Marie Barrow Scoma hoped her
brother's remains could be moved next to Bonnie's in Crownhill
Memorial Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think it would be a tourist attraction and a good
thing for Dallas,'' Steele says. ``Surely someone could contact the
Barrow family and the Parker family and see if it could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
