<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-ADVANCE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sub Serlenga making most of playing opportunity
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ It's one thing for Cindy Parlow to be bagging
hat tricks. Parlow is a fixture at forward on the U.S. women's
soccer team that won the World Cup last year and is favored to keep
its Olympic gold medal in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But for Nikki Serlenga, her future Atlanta professional club
teammate, multiple-goal games are a rarity. The 22-year-old
defensive midfielder is getting her first taste of senior team
competition this year, and she rapidly is becoming a serious
candidate to make the final Olympic cut later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Serlenga scored her first international hat trick in
an 8-0 rout of Costa Rica. For the moment, Serlenga is backing up
starter Lorrie Fair while Michelle Akers recovers from a shoulder
injury.
</P>
<P>
   She appears to have gotten over some initial jitters about
rubbing shoulders with the biggest names in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, you're kind of in awe of them,'' Serlenga
said. ``But you can't play like you're that. If you train like
you're just happy to be here, then you won't be here for long.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Serlenga, Parlow and goalkeeper Briana Scurry were
allocated to the Atlanta franchise in the Women's United Soccer
Association. Parlow, leads the U.S. with 14 goals in 13 games this
year, including four hat tricks. Scurry is missing the Gold Cup
with a shin injury.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach April Heinrichs, who rested several starters Sunday,
figures to field her top lineup tonight in the Group A finale
against Brazil. That would relegate Serlenga and some of the other
younger players to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes our younger players struggle with the fact that
there are so many good players on the team,'' Heinrichs said. ``We
are trying to push several little buttons that will help their
confidence and development.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner tonight avoids China in Saturday's semifinals. If the
two teams play to a draw, a coin flip would determine the group
winner, because they would be tied on head-to-head play, goal
difference and total goals. Brazil and the U.S. both beat Costa
Rica 8-0 and Trinidad and Tobago 11-0.
</P>
<P>
   For players such as Serlenga, Heinrichs' concerted effort to
break in the next generation of players in an Olympic year has been
the ideal proving ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more opportunities I get to play, the better I think my
chances are (of making the team),'' Serlenga said. ``I can't
control that, but I'm just going out every game and trying to prove
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
