<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WEBVAN27-COX     06-26 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebVan to acquire online competitor HomeGrocer
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Online grocer WebVan announced Monday it would acquire
Seattle-based competitor HomeGrocer for about $1.2 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, where residents have been ordering Webvan groceries
since May 1, would have been one of a handful of cities where the
two companies would have competed head-to-head for online grocery
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked as though Atlanta was going to be the first market
where two online grocers were going to be battling it out,'' said
Jupiter Communications analyst Ken Cassar. ``In a way it's too bad
for Atlanta, because there could have been bitter price war that
could have put one of them out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Webvan, based in San Francisco, will pay 1.076 shares, or about
$9.39, for each HomeGrocer share, 16 percent more than HomeGrocer's
closing price Friday.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer is 21.6 percent owned by Amazon.com. Some analysts
say speculation about Amazon's possible financial troubles may have
hastened the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Cassar said the deal makes a good sense. ``The online grocery
business in terms of delivery and infrastructure is extraordinarily
expensive,'' he said. ``At the same time, the market is relatively
small. The market cannot support multiple players competing in the
same market.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a merger was probably inevitable, but most analysts
thought it would come later. ``We thought they were going to wait
until they were head-to-head in a number of markets, but I think
it's prudent they didn't wait. They saved themselves a lot of
money. ``
</P>
<P>
   George Shaheen, WebVan's chief operating officer, said the
merger is a simple matter of economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to enter new markets more cost efficiently and
realize additional cost savings,'' he said. ``We will eliminate
overlap, save money and reduce the time spent marketing to win the
loyalty of online shoppers and the total shopping experience.''
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer had originally planned to launch its service in
Atlanta June 14, but delayed the opening indefinitely, saying it
was a marketing decision. Shaheen and HomeGrocer chief executive
Mary Alice Taylor revealed Monday that the company was in the
middle of acquisition negotiations as HomeGrocer was planning the
Atlanta launch.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGrocer has already built a distribution facility in
Lawrenceville, Ga., and had purchased additional property in
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said it was uncertain how VebVan would integrate those
properties into its Atlanta operation. WebVan's central
distribution center is located in Suwanee, Ga., with smaller
distribution centers across metropolitan Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan sells groceries in Atlanta and the San Francisco Bay
areas. The company plans to reach to 13 metropolitan areas by
year's end. Webvan plans to sell groceries in Atlanta, Baltimore,
Bergen County, N.J., Chicago, Dallas, Los Angeles, Orange County,
Calif., Portland, Sacramento, Calif., San Diego, San Francisco,
Seattle and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen says the deal will be finalized later this year. Webvan
founder Louis Borders will remain as chairman of the board and
WebVan's Shaheen will remain as president and CEO. Taylor will
leave the combined companies.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen said the new company will have increased buying power
and smaller operating costs. ``We can spend money much more
efficiently. If you could have it one way or the other, why not
have one clear winner in the marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
