A5555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAX-HAVEN-NYT &LR;      06-26 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-HAVEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEALTHY NATIONS BRAND 35 PLACES AS HAVENS FOR TAX EVADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Type ``tax haven'' into an Internet search engine
and the following come-on is less than a second away:
</P>
<P>
   ``Gibraltar _ professional services for using Gibraltar as a
financial center and tax haven.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies and rich people have used offshore financial centers
to avoid paying income, corporate and capital gains taxes in
industrial countries for generations. The Internet now makes it a
snap to do so without leaving the office.
</P>
<P>
   But wealthy nations, which have lost tens of billions of dollars
year after year, declared Monday that they had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-member Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development publicly declared a list of 35 mostly exotic island
getaways, including Samoa, Tonga and the U.S. Virgin Islands, that
have tax laws intended to attract assets from companies and people
who want to evade actual tax payments or potential tax liabilities
in their home countries. The organization named 47 other places
that have ``potentially harmful'' tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 havens have generally declined to cooperate with foreign
investigators who seek to catch tax dodgers. They were given a year
to overhaul their tax laws or face sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Globalization of business and the point-and-click ease of moving
large amounts of money around the world have transformed remote
havens into profitable financial centers. The United States
strongly backed the ``name and shame'' campaign. Unlike some other
developed nations, the United States imposes taxes on the earnings
of its citizens and companies anywhere they are made. It loses
billions of dollars in tax revenue each year because offshore
financial centers help people hide income from the Internal Revenue
Service, Clinton administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, wealthy nations publicized another list, of 15
countries and territories they accuse of declining to crack down on
money laundering. Several lands, including the Bahamas, the Cook
Islands and Liechtenstein, appear on both lists.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the havens are either colonies, former colonies or
protectorates of European countries, especially the United Kingdom.
Britain has been increasingly willing to put pressure on these
territories, and a British official hailed Monday's announcement as
``a vital step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The full OECD tax haven list includes: Andorra, Anguilla,
Antigua and Barbuda, Aruba, Bahamas, Bahrain, Barbados, Belize, the
British Virgin Islands, Cook Islands, Dominica, Gibraltar, Grenada,
Guernsey, Isle of Man, Jersey, Liberia, Liechtenstein, the
Maldives, the Marshall Islands, Monaco, Montserrat, Nauru, the
Netherlands Antilles, Nieui, Panama, Samoa, Seychelles, St. Lucia,
St. Christopher and Nevis, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, Tonga,
Turks and Caicos, the U.S. Virgin Islands and Vanuatu.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the named territories objected to the campaign by the
organization. One of them, Jersey, issued a statement calling the
report ``absurd'' and said that wealthy nations had applied a
stricter standard for the Pacific and Caribbean countries and
territories than they did for Switzerland and Luxembourg, which
also have reputations as tax havens. Switzerland and Luxembourg are
members of the OECD. U.S. officials have said that the two
generally cooperate with investigations into tax dodging and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Six countries and territories - Bermuda, the Cayman Islands,
Cyprus, Malta, Mauritius and San Marino - slipped off the
short-list of places to be named as tax havens last week after they
pledged to meet international norms by 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
