<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MLBPROBE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Box brouhaha leaves announcers banned from Braves flights
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves were angry that TBS aired video
Saturday showing that the Turner Field catcher's box had been
altered. As a result, the Braves have banned the cable channel's
four baseball announcers from the team's chartered flights.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Caray, Joe Simpson, Don Sutton and Pete Van Wieren usually
fly with the Braves players, coaches and staff on trips. But now,
they will have to travel on commercial flights, beginning with the
road trip to Montreal and New York starting today. The length of
the ban was not known.
</P>
<P>
   The four announcers are employees of TBS. Time Warner Inc. is
the parent company of both the cable channel and the baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Monday for comment, Braves president Stan Kasten
replied, ``No, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, reached at his home Monday, declined to comment. The
other three could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   TBS was quiet on the issue, because it is caught between
defending its broadcasters and producers without causing more
friction with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The channel aired the footage on the catcher's box in the top of
the first inning of the game Saturday night. Van Wieren and Sutton
were the announcers on the air at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire John Shulock called a balk on catcher Fernando
Lunar for lining up with his right foot outside the catcher's box.
After the balk call, which led to Bobby Cox's ejection, TBS
superimposed video of Friday night's catcher's box over Saturday
night's version. Saturday's was about 4-5 inches smaller. The
Braves do have the standard 43-inch-wide template to trace the box.
</P>
<P>
   The balk helped figure in the Brewers' first run in what turned
out to be a 2-1 loss for the Braves and pitcher Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Many Braves pitchers, including Maddux, like to have the
catcher's targets set up wide of the plate, so that they miss off
the plate rather than on it. But opposing managers point out that
it increases the chances of umpires calling an outside pitch a
strike rather than a ball.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Brewers manager Davey Lopes had made that
complaint and urged the umpires to make a call that is rarely seen.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball said that it is looking into the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation we're reviewing in the overall context of not
only the box and how it was drawn but the subsequent decision taken
the following day,'' said Sandy Alderson, MLB executive vice
president for baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catcher's box is designed as its name implies,'' Alderson
said. ``A lot of that goes to the way balls and strikes are called.
It's a situation we're looking at. I wouldn't say it's at the top
of our list.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario for the Braves probably would be a fine,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves flew to Montreal for a two-game series, today and
Wednesday. Then, they go to New York for the greatly anticipated
four-game series against the Mets, Thursday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has not played the Mets since beating them in the
National League Championship Series in October, and the Braves have
not played in New York since reliever John Rocker's controversial
statements were published in Sports Illustrated in December.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
