A5564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-HIGHPICKS27     06-26 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-HIGHPICKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Over the years, Hawks rarely draft too high _ or too well
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Hawks have been caught in the ``Catch-22''
of the NBA. They have been good enough to make the playoffs most of
the time but not good enough to chase a title. And they never have
been so bad that they draft high enough to get a crack at a Tim
Duncan or a Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   That situation won't change Wednesday night, when the Hawks make
the sixth pick of the draft. No one sees a franchise-maker in this
draft class, although Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin or 18-year-old
Darius Miles could rise to that level.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks expect to get a bright, serviceable player with the
sixth pick but not necessarily a star _ although general manager
Pete Babcock won't concede the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all potential,'' Babcock said Monday. ``It's all
potential and youth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have had five shots at the lottery in the previous 15
years. They earned their way into the lottery in 1985 and took Jon
Koncak with the No. 5 pick. Because then-coach Mike Fratello and
Stan Kasten, then the GM and now president, were determined to
draft a center, they missed out on Chris Mullin (6, Golden State),
Charles Oakley (9, Cleveland) and Karl Malone (13, Utah).
</P>
<P>
   Twice, the Hawks traded into the lottery. They selected Stacey
Augmon in 1991 after dealing veteran point guard Doc Rivers for the
pick. They dealt again last June, using another point guard, Mookie
Blaylock, so they could draft a rookie at the position, Jason Terry
at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Two other times after missing the playoffs, as they did this
season, the Hawks selected Rumeal Robinson in 1990 and Adam Keefe
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks say they will draft for talent, not position. They
haven't always done so, Babcock said, ``because the lower you are
in the draft, the fewer great athletes are available. The talent
issue is gone, so at that point you try to fill specific needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
