u f BC-FED-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-26 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED LIKELY TO WANT MORE EVIDENCE BEFORE RAISING INTEREST RATES
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a period of rip-roaring growth that fueled
fears of inflation, the economy is showing enough signs of slowing
that the Federal Reserve will most likely leave interest rates
unchanged when it meets on Tuesday and Wednesday, economists and
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   But as it looks ahead, the Fed faces two big uncertainties that
could lead it back to raising rates later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all clear, Fed officials say, that the slowdown of
the last few months will not give way to another resurgence in
growth and inflation pressures. In each of the last two years,
growth slowed in the spring, only to come storming back.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the economy is cooling, the Fed will have to decide
just how cool is cool enough. The central bank will have to resolve
an internal debate over conditions sufficient to slow growth to a
pace that would keep unemployment at its current level of around 4
percent, or whether it will need to push harder on the brakes and
drive unemployment up, perhaps to 5 percent or higher, to ensure
that inflation remains in check.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised its benchmark interest rate by 1.75
percentage points in six increments over the last year, to 6.5
percent. Economic indicators from the last month have suggested
that the higher rates are beginning to rein in the economy by
dampening consumer spending, slowing the pace of job creation and
taking some steam out of the supercharged stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But Fed officials have been wary of declaring that economic
growth is under control. In public and private statements recently,
officials have indicated that they need to see a few more months of
data to be sure that the economy is responding as they want it to.
And in public appearances in recent weeks, a number of them have
emphasized not the evidence that growth is slowing, but rather
signs that ``core'' inflation _ excluding often volatile food and
energy prices _ is beginning to creep up.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent data, Robert Parry, the president of the Federal
Reserve Bank of San Francisco, said in a speech this month, ``makes
it pretty clear that we've reached a stage where inflation is no
longer falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fed officials have done nothing to counter the impression
among investors and analysts that they are willing to put policy on
hold until August, when they meet next, to give themselves more
time to assess the effect of higher rates on the economy. As
concerned as they are about inflation, the last thing Fed officials
want to do is tighten policy so much that they stamp out the
nation's longest economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if the economy is behaving the way it should under
tighter monetary policy,'' said Allen Sinai, an economist at
Primark Decision Economics. ``The Fed can wait and define the
slowdown and the inflation response more clearly before taking any
further action.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed were to buck the conventional wisdom and raise rates
this week, it would probably be in part because of a desire to keep
the financial markets from rallying and fueling a rebound in
growth. Analysts said the central bank's policy-setting Federal
Open Market Committee would probably deal with that matter by
issuing a strongly worded statement about the continuing threat of
inflation, putting investors on notice that further rate increases
are possible, if not likely, starting in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to talk tough,'' said Stephen Slifer, an economist
at Lehman Brothers in New York. ``If they chose not to talk tough,
the markets will think they are out of the picture, and if there
was an incipient slowdown it would disappear pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   In both 1998 and 1999, the economy slowed substantially in the
second quarter and then picked back up again to growth rates that
fanned inflation fears among Fed officials.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the economy grew at a 5.4 percent annual pace in the
first quarter, and economists think it has slowed to an annual rate
below 4 percent in the second quarter, which ends on Friday. There
is some reason to think that this slowdown will last longer than
its counterparts the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the Fed has tightened monetary policy
substantially in the last year. Moreover, the slowdown appears to
be spread more evenly across the economy, and to have encompassed
consumers more than in the slowdowns in 1998 and 1999. And higher
oil prices relative to the last few years could dampen economic
activity at both the corporate and consumer level by making
everything from a tank of gasoline to raw materials more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the acceleration in the growth rate of
productivity, or output per hour, economists are increasingly
convinced that the economy is capable of sharply higher rates of
non-inflationary growth than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, economists believed that the economy's
non-inflationary speed limit was annual growth of about 2.25
percent. Most estimates now put trend growth at around 4 percent,
or about the estimated current rate of growth.
</P>
<P>
   But to project possible inflationary pressures, the speed limit,
or ``trend'' growth rate, is often looked at in conjunction with
the concept of a ``natural'' unemployment rate, or the jobless rate
at which trend growth or higher will set off an inflationary cycle
of wage and price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, does not put much stock in the
natural unemployment rate concept, but some of his colleagues at
the central bank do, most notably Laurence Meyer, a Fed governor.
While some economists say the evidence suggests that the natural
rate is now down to about 4 percent, Meyer puts it at 5 percent to
5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy is slowing, the debate within the Fed could soon
turn to whether a combination of 3.5 percent to 4 percent growth
and 4 percent unemployment will ignite any smoldering inflation
pressures, or whether the Fed should push growth down further to a
level that sends the unemployment rate back up toward 5 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The major question,'' Meyer said in a speech earlier this
month, ``is whether slowing the economy to trend alone will get the
job done, or whether we need a period of below trend growth to
unwind an imbalance between the levels of aggregate demand and
supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer's concern is that inflation has been suppressed until now
in part because of temporary factors that are likely to wear off,
and that when they do, imbalances in the economy like the tight
labor market will again put upward pressure on wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   When the temporary factors dissipate, Meyer said, ``not only
will there be some rebound in inflation, but unless a transition is
made back to sustainable utilization rates, there will be a risk of
a continuous upward movement in inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: unemployment would have to rise back to the 5
percent level Meyer considers sustainable to ensure that inflation
cannot get a foothold.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said he puts more faith than many of his colleagues at the
Fed in the idea that there are predictable tradeoffs between
growth, unemployment and inflation. But he is far from alone in
questioning whether the Fed might still have to turn the interest
rate screws tighter later this year, even at the risk of taking
political criticism as election day draws near.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is widely viewed as being more open to the idea that
the economy can sustain a combination of strong growth and low
unemployment without inflation, largely because of his optimistic
outlook about continuing improvements in productivity growth.
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of other Fed officials, Greenspan is likely to
resist any calls for further rate increases on the basis of a
theoretical relationship between growth, unemployment and
inflation. He will probably be guided more by concrete evidence of
how the economy develops in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting, however, that the two camps are not debating
whether the economy needs to go into recession to wring out any
chance of inflation, only whether it should slow to 4 percent or 3
percent or, at the low end, 2 percent _ still a healthy
performance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
