<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5570 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-COURT-MIRANDA-BOS &LR;      06-26 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-MIRANDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS CONSTITUTIONALITY OF MIRANDA WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court put down the most significant
challenge to its 1966 landmark Miranda ruling Monday as Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist led a 7-2 majority in reaffirming that
under the Constitution, accused persons must be informed by police
of their right to remain silent and to consult a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Court declines to overturn Miranda,'' Rehnquist wrote for
the majority, noting that it would require ``special
justification'' for the high court to ignore the precedent it set
in Miranda v. Arizona 34 years ago. ``There is no such
justification here. Miranda has become embedded in routine police
practice to the point where the warnings have become part of our
national culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians hailed the high court for upholding Miranda
and defending the constitutional right of suspects against
self-incrimination at a time when allegations of police misconduct
and racial profiling have given rise to waves of tension in the
criminal-justice system.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he was pleased the police warnings were
so ``resoundingly'' upheld. ``They have worked for law enforcement
by providing clear standards for our officers and they have worked
to protect the rights of our citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist formed the majority with Justices John Paul Stevens,
Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer. Justices Antonin Scalia, joined by
Clarence Thomas, sharply dissented and argued the court displayed
``judicial arrogance'' in following the precedent set by a case
that was wrongly decided 34 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am aware, the public is not under the illusion
that we are infallible,'' Scalia wrote. ``I see little harm in
admitting that we made a mistake in taking away from people the
ability to decide for themselves what protections (beyond those
required by the Constitution) are reasonably affordable in the
criminal investigatory process.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision moots a federal law, passed in 1968, that
was aimed at overturning Miranda. Called section 3501, it allowed
federal prosecutors to take a voluntary confession from a suspect
before the Miranda rights were read. The law had never been
enforced by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Supreme Court reversed a federal appeals court
in Richmond, Va., that ruled last year that under Section 3501, the
voluntary confession of Charles Thomas Dickerson, an indicted bank
robber who had not been read his Miranda rights by FBI
interrogators, was admissible in court.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling created an uproar among civil-rights advocates. The
US Justice Department disavowed Section 3501 and refused to defend
it before the high court. Attorney General Janet Reno took the
unusual step of signing the government's pro-Miranda brief as a way
to bolster public confidence in the judicial process. The Supreme
Court appointed Paul G. Cassell, a professor at the University of
Utah College of Law and the country's leading scholar-critic of
Miranda, to argue the case, which was heard in April.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell called the court's decision disappointing and
``superficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sad day for victims of crime and law-abiding
Americans,'' Cassell said in an interview. ``The tragic result will
be that thousands of confessed, dangerous criminals will go free
just because police officers have made a mistake in following the
highly technical Miranda rules.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Robert T. Scully, executive director of
the National Association of Police Officers, said the decision
means that no matter how professional the police are in obtaining a
voluntary or uncoerced confession, the risk is high it will be
thrown out under the Miranda rules. ``Miranda has become a vehicle
inviting routine efforts to exclude voluntary confessions, and the
Dickerson case will only increase the amount of litigation in state
and federal courts,'' Scully said.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors and defense lawyers said it is quite uncommon
now for police to ignore Miranda warnings or for criminals to go
free because their rights were violated. Indeed, they say, the
recitation of Miranda rights _ ``You have a right to remain silent;
anything you say can be used against you in a court of law; you
have the right to the presence of an attorney; if you cannot afford
an attorney, you have the right to have an attorney appointed for
you'' _ has gone beyond standard police procedure to becoming as
American as ``Law and Order,'' the Pledge of Allegience, and apple
pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court (Monday) said, `We created something that worked,
and there is no reason to mess with it,' '' said Robert Ullmann, a
former federal prosecutor and now a criminal-defense lawyer in the
Boston firm of Nutter, McClennen &AMP; Fish.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Maclin, a constitutional scholar at Boston University
School of Law, said that when the Supreme Court handed down Miranda
there were dire warnings that ``police would lose convictions and
there would be rapists out on the street.'' Instead, Maclin said,
the police now use the Miranda rules to their advantage -- reading
the warnings quickly, playing down their importance as they deliver
them, and suggesting to suspects they may be better off if they
waive them. ``It's given police the green light,'' Maclin said.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Rehnquist noted the court has, over three
decades, made exceptions and ``refinements'' to the Miranda rule.
He acknowledged that the court now sitting might not have decided
the original case in the same way as the court in 1966, and he
conceded that the ``the rule's disadvantage is that it may result
in a guilty defendant going free.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the chief justice said, none of that outweighed the fact
that ``Miranda, being a constitutional decision of this court, may
not be, in effect, overruled by an act of Congress.'' Moreover,
Rehnquist said, ``while there are more remedies available for
abusive police conduct than there were at the time Miranda was
decided...these additional remedies do not in our view render them,
together with (federal law) 3501, an adequate substitute for the
warnings required by Miranda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
