<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROADTRIP27     06-26 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROADTRIP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road trip has Braves anticipating playoff atmosphere
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nobody _ neither John Rocker nor anyone else _ can
predict what awaits the Braves and their controversial reliever at
Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Atlanta opens a four-game series against the Mets
in their first meeting since October's National League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Since telling Baseball Weekly that he would ride the No. 7 train
to Shea, Rocker has said only, ``Probably so'' about his mode of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But the start of the Mets series is only two days away, after
two games in Montreal. And the Braves do know that they are ready
to find out what happens and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been feeling that way for two months,'' NL MVP Chipper
Jones said. ``Let's go play, and whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Sports Illustrated article in December, Rocker insulted and
denigrated New Yorkers and their city, particularly the commuters
that ride the No. 7 train.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Rocker snapped at a reporter who asked him whether
Major League Baseball or the Braves had recommended he not take the
No. 7 train. ``That's why I don't like to do interviews, because of
questions like that,'' he said. ``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had been a target of the wrath of Mets fans in October,
after he suggested during the Braves' September series win in New
York that Mets fans go home and put on their Yankees gear.
</P>
<P>
   He also knew how to diffuse some of it, by the way he charmed
fans during the offseason when collecting his MVP Award in a
ceremony in New York. He kidded fans for reminding him that is real
name is ``Lar-ry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has a best-case scenario for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go in and sweep and John wouldn't say anything to garner
anymore headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   And worst-case scenario? ``Anything's possible, but you don't
like to think about those things,'' Jones said. ``I'm not fearful
of anything. I certainly hope nobody gets hurt and people act
responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball and the Mets have taken significant steps
to try to ensure the Braves' safety. Some 450 to 500 police
officers are expected to work the games, and a barricade will be
built over the visiting bullpen to prevent objects from being
thrown on pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg said he has his own plans, especially after
watching the fan sprint onto the field to moon Rocker at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't catch me standing anywhere near him, put it that
way,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg is one of several of Rocker's teammates to have
spoken out against him taking the train to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be foolish to ride the train,'' he said. ``I
think it would be in his best interest to keep his mouth shut and
keep as low a profile as he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Braves are bracing for a playoff atmosphere,
given the hoard of media expected and the hype surrounding the
series and Rocker. ``It's hard enough to go to New York and play
the teams they have up there, because they're so good,'' Jones
said. ``Then to have these outside distractions, you shouldn't have
to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
