<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIVENDI-MESSIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIVENDI TOUTS WEB SYNERGIES WITH SEAGRAM WHILE ANALYSTS PONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the next three months, Vivendi's chairman, Jean Marie
Messier, plans to dash between Paris, New York and London,
ebulliently selling the concept of a wireless Internet world where
Vivendi's acquisition of Seagram will reap a windfall.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Since the announcement of Vivendi's $41 billion deal to acquire
Seagram last week, analysts have been squinting to see the
synergies between Messier's company _ which owns environmental,
waste disposal and communications businesses _ and Seagram, which
owns a major record company, film studio, theme park business and
liquor operation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday, Messier, Vivendi's 43-year-old
chairman and chief executive, said Seagram's Universal
entertainment businesses would help lure subscribers to Vizzavi _
Vivendi's Web portal venture with the British telecommunications
carrier Vodafone PLC.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, he said, Vizzavi could promote Universal, for example,
enabling subscribers to download new Universal music albums.
</P>
<P>
   But Messier follows a long list of media executives who have
embraced the concept of vertical integration: mergers that marry
programming and distribution. And those deals, most notably the
Walt Disney Co.'s 1996 purchase of Capital Cities/ABC, have often
proved troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the stock performance of both Seagram and Vivendi
since the deal was announced last week indicates that investors on
both sides of the Atlantic remain skeptical. Since reports of the
merger, Seagram shares have risen 17.7 percent, closing at $59.56
Monday. That still leaves a gap between the market price and
Vivendi's offer of $70.44 a share for Seagram. Vivendi's shares,
meanwhile, are down 20 percent, closing at $88.05 Monday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Three different analysts said Monday that they could not see why
Vivendi needed to buy Seagram to get synergies in a merger,
particularly when Vivendi would be paying 18 times cash flow for
the entertainment operations with no apparent cost savings to be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Messier said he was most interested in the music division, the
cornerstone of which is Polygram, for which Seagram paid about 13
times cash flow just two years ago and achieved cost savings by
combining operations with the other Universal Music labels. If
music is so important, why didn't Vivendi buy Polygram alone when
it was on the market at a lower price?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit early,'' Messier said.
</P>
<P>
   Messier said he now sees an opportunity because the distribution
technology will be global _ the Internet _ and Vivendi, through the
Vizzavi venture with Vodafone, could establish an early stronghold
in Europe, where wireless Internet access is growing much faster
than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But because Universal Music will have every incentive to make
its albums available to Vizzavi's competitors, too, analysts are
wondering why Vivendi could not get access to the music without
taking on the financial costs of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   As for Universal's film business, Messier was quick to say that
the French did not intend to run the Universal's rebounding movie
business, and he praised Stacy Snider, chairwoman of Universal
Pictures. But he failed to mention Ron Meyer, president of
Universal Studios, which oversees Snider's operation. Only after
being asked, did Messier say that Meyer's future was up to him,
seeming to imply that Meyer was dispensable.
</P>
<P>
   Film industry executives say that if the French ultimately want
to dismiss Meyer, who is five years through a 10-year contract, it
could cost Vivendi as much as $100 million. Meyer declined to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
