<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-EGOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARP RIVALRIES MARK GENOME PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a scientific enterprise, the race to map the
human genome bears resemblance to the Manhattan Project, the
furious World War II rush to develop an atomic bomb before Nazi
Germany. Both involved unprecedented gatherings of scientists who
worked toward a once unthinkable goal in a brief time.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the genome, however, the race was not between
warring nations but mostly-friendly rivals: J. Craig Venter of
Celera Genomic Inc. and the federal government's $300 million Human
Genome Project. The majority of scientists at Monday's historic
announcement to mark the near-completion of the genome map said the
effort by the two groups, who used different techniques to arrive
at a surpisingly similar result, was, in the end, productive.
</P>
<P>
   At the head of the government effort is Dr. Francis Collins, who
once explored the wilderness of the genomic frontier as discoverer
of the gene for cystic fibrosis in 1989, but now heads a research
consortium of almost 1,000 scientists in five countries.
</P>
<P>
   Collins sat to the left of President Bill Clinton, who emerged
as a peacekeeper in the war of words over the genome project. On
the president's right was Venter, the brash Vietnam veteran whose
radical but ultimately successful genomic mapping techniques were
rejected by the government but embraced by private industry. There
he found a home, funding, and, perhaps most important, the computer
power that enabled him to match the government's effort.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was privately concerned about some of Venter's
public criticism of the Human Genome Project, praised him for
``truly visionary pursuit of innovative strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the audience applauding both men was James Watson, who,
with Francis Crick, discovered the double-helix structure of DNA
almost 50 years ago _ a pivotal discovery in the path to the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, in a brief interview, said it was ``wonderful'' how
quickly the genome had been decoded, adding, ``I think we'll see
this in history as the equivalent of inventing the printing
press.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging over the whole day, however, was a sense that the world
had entered uncharted ethical waters. Will people be discriminated
against based on their genes? Will babies be genetically
engineered? Such possibilites remain far off, but most of those
present said that strict ethical guidelines must be set early on to
prevent such abuses, which most scientists conceded could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Both Collins and Venter urged Congress to pass a ban on genetic
discrimination. A bipartisan bill that would do just that was
introduced in Congress last year. Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, speaking via satellite feed, both suggested an
international genomic ethics panel be created.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of race also repeatedly surfaced, with Clinton
commenting that racial differences seem superficial given that all
humans are almost genetically identical. Venter revealed that
Celera's genomic project utilized DNA from three women and two men
who were white, black, Hispanic and Asian. He noted that ``there is
no way to tell one ethnicity from another'' by looking at their
genomes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the announcement, with its back-slapping and broad
smiles, was the product of some deft scientific diplomacy. On May
7, Venter and Collins were summoned to the house of Ari Patrinos,
who ran the federal Department of Energy's piece of the genome
effort. The war of words between the two sides had escalated, and
each was on the verge of making its own separate genome
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beginning was tense,'' Patrinos said in an interview.
``There was this history of acrimony. There were a lot of bruised
feelings. . . . Both sides felt as if they had been intellectually
dissed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Patrinos kept the meetings going. Finally, last Wednesday,
the agreement to make the joint announcement was sealed. When asked
about the race between Celera and the Human Genome Project, Collins
said, ``The only race we're going to talk about is the human
race.''
</P>
<P>
   But questions and disagreements still exist. Celera wants to
keep its genome data on its own Web site rather than the government
site that most of the scientific community has enbraced.
</P>
<P>
   And who will own gene discoveries? Dozens of companies already
have patents on the functions of some genes but many scientists and
policy makers are uncomfortable with parceling out these molecular
pieces of life's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Collins said, ``is the end of the beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
