<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS SPENDING ROSE 17.4 PERCENT ON PRESCRIPTION DRUGS IN
1999 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Spending on prescription drugs increased a record
17.4 percent last year, and elderly people saw the largest cost
increases, a new study by a drug benefits company says.
</P>
<P>
   The study, issued Monday by Express Scripts of St. Louis, said
about half of the total increase in drug spending resulted from
higher costs for a typical prescription. Greater use of
prescription drugs and the introduction of new drug products were
responsible for the remainder of the increase, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Express Scripts manages drug benefits for 9.6 million people and
derived the study from that data.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett Toan, president of Express Scripts, said last year's
increase accelerated a trend observed since 1993, when the company
began monitoring changes in drug spending.
</P>
<P>
   New drugs were a significant factor contributing to the increase
in spending last year, as doctors and patients quickly accepted two
drugs used to treat arthritis, Vioxx, made by Merck &AMP; Co., and
Celebrex, marketed by Searle and Pfizer, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, it said, drugs introduced since 1992 accounted
for a remarkable 41 percent of drug spending last year and for 25
percent of all prescriptions filled last year.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes just two days before the House is expected to
vote on proposals to provide prescription drug coverage to Medicare
beneficiaries. One-third of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries
have no insurance to help pay drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics compiled by Express Scripts show why elderly people
feel a pressing need for such coverage and why many members of
Congress worry about the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on prescription drugs averaged $387.09 a person last
year, up 17.4 percent from the average of $329.83 in 1998, Express
Scripts reported. But costs rose most rapidly for older Americans,
it said.
</P>
<P>
   The average price for a prescription last year rose 18 percent
for women aged 70 to 79, 20 percent for women 80 and older, 9
percent for men age 70 to 79 and 11 percent for men 80 and older,
the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that Enbrel, a new drug for rheumatoid
arthritis, contributed more to the increase in drug spending last
year than more celebrated drugs like Viagra. Enbrel, produced by
genetic engineering, may cost $1,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, Express Scripts made these observations:
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of prescriptions for antihistamines increased 18.4
percent last year. In 1999, as in the two prior years, use of
antihistamines increased more than the use of any other type of
drug. The increase was driven by heavy advertising for products
like Claritin, Allegra and Zyrtec.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cholesterol-lowering drugs were the second-fastest growing
category last year, as the number of prescriptions increased 18.1
percent. Lipitor, made by Warner-Lambert, and Zocor, made by Merck,
accounted for much of the growth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use of antidepressant drugs increased 11.3 percent last year.
As the stigma of mental illness is reduced and more people become
aware of the symptoms of depression, they are more likely to
receive drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use of gastrointestinal drugs increased nearly 10 percent last
year, in part because of advertising for products like Prilosec.
</P>
<P>
   Express Scripts said the unit price of prescription drugs rose
an average of 5.4 percent last year, which was substantially more
than the increases for other major goods and services like food,
housing and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of generic drugs rose an average of 7 percent last
year, while prices of brand-name medications rose an average of 5.8
percent, the report said. Generic versions of brand-name drugs
typically cost less, but federal officials say they are
therapeutically equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the drugs with the largest price increases last year were
thyroid medications, narcotic painkillers and estrogen replacement
products.
</P>
<P>
   Synthroid, a synthetic thyroid hormone sold by the Knoll
Pharmaceutical Co., accounted for much of the increase in thyroid
drug costs, while Premarin, made by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories to
treat symptoms of menopause and osteoporosis, accounted for much of
the increase in estrogen therapy prices, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
