<SLUG> BC-GENOME-IMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH FIRMS RUSH TO CASH IN ON GENOME PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of the next generation gene-based drugs, whose development
is expected to be accelerated by the completion of the human genome
map, will be made in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Already, dozens of pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies
that employ hundreds in the state have launched quests to develop
the next blockbuster drug and become the financial beneficiary of
the human genome project. Of the estimated 140 biotechnology
companies in the state, about half are working in areas related to
genomics.
</P>
<P>
   While most have been busy well before Monday's historic
announcement, the scramble to move faster for scientific leadership
and fame as well as patenting rights is now in high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Friday Cambridge-based Millennium Pharmaceuticals
signed a $450 million deal with Aventis SA, Europe's fourth largest
drug maker to jointly develop and produce a family of
anti-inflammatory drugs based on Millennium's cutting-edge gene
research tools and technology. The partnership will share in the
development of medications that treat the underlying causes of such
diseases as arthritis, asthma and multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have identified the most human genes, particularly in the
anti-inflammatory area where we know which genes are turned up and
down so we understand the pathways and the causes of the
diseases,'' said Mark Levin, Millennium chief executive whose
company is focused on cancer, metabolic diseases and inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc. signed an $800 million
deal with Novartis AG, Europe's third biggest drugmaker, to develop
as many as eight drugs in the field of kinases natural enzymes that
are linked to cancer, heart disease and nervous disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the human genome project, medical research will never be
done the same way,'' said Josh Boger, Vertex founder and chief
executive. ``What Novartis sees in us today could not have been
done five or 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' strategies underline the growing power of strong
biotech firms with extensive genomics capabilities in their
relationship with pharmaceutical giants. Increasingly the major
U.S. and European drug makers are joining with biotech firms for
their next generation of therapeutics _ gene based medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Enabling all drug companies to develop and mine genomic datases
are a panoply of players in the field of bioinformatics _ the use
of high speed computers and extensive databases and mathematical
analysis software. They provide researchers with tools to drill
down into the oceans of data and come up with useful information
for developing gene-based drugs.
</P>
<P>
   So robust is the market, that bioinformatics tools and services
could generate more than $2 billion in revenues within five years
compared to $160 million last year, according to estimates from
Oscar Gruss &AMP; Son, a New York investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly-based Proteome is working with Spotfire Inc., of
Cambridge, to develop new ways for researchers to see their results
matched against published scientific data.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are amazingly busy times for us,'' said James Garrels,
president of Proteome, which functions as a curator of biotech and
genomic infomraiton, seling access to its databases to Millennium
and other drugmakers for $200,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The push to commercialize genetic information has also led to a
flood of patents and patent applications, providing full employment
to patent attorneys. Just last year there were more than 550,000
applications for genetic patents and this year, there several
companies looking to file upwards of 10,000 patents each.
</P>
<P>
   But some attorneys maintain that the U.S. Patent and Trademark
Office will change the rules soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patent office has said it is going to have a higher
standard for showing a partial or full gene sequence linked to the
gene function,'' said Kathy Williams a biotech patent attorney at
Palmer &AMP; Dodge, acknowledging that overall, attorneys familiar with
the biotech and genomic patent issues ``kind of do well when the
biotech industry does well.''
</P>
<P>
   The last four years were also good for Compaq Computer Corp.,
whose Alpha high-speed computer chips in computers were used in by
human genome project's main investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Compaq sells server computers built around the
Alpha design, which the company acquired as part of its purchase of
Digital Equipment Corp. in 1998. The latest versions of the chips
can process nearly a trillion operations per second, making them
useful for researchers at Celera Genomics, the Whitehead Institute,
and others involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq sold the equipment as part of its regular commercial
operations, but issued a press release about its involvement Monday
as part of a broader campaign to promote Alpha, which faces
increased competition from Intel and others.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha chips, and their accompanying software, are developed in
Shrewsbury, Marlborough, and in Nashua, N.H., though Compaq has
shut down local Alpha assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ross Kerber of the Globe business staff contributed to this
report).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
