<HEADER>
A5587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      06-26 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: JAPAN'S STAID VOTERS ISSUE A WAKE-UP CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Just when many seemed ready to begin writing off Japan's
democracy as hopelessly moribund, the huge advance made on Sunday
by an opposition party once seen as hapless has awakened the
country to the possibility of political change.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Democratic Party overcame discouraging opinion polls,
bad weather and an electorate often seen as apathetic to emerge
from parliamentary elections as a solid challenger to the Liberal
Democratic Party, which has held power almost without interruption
since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Japanese political analysts describe the weeks
ahead as completely uncharted _ a highly unusual situation in a
country where politics usually seem carefully scripted. What seems
certain is that despite morning-after headlines here that strangely
spoke of a vote for continuity, more change _ perhaps dramatic
change _ is on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Despite party denials that Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori would be
removed any time soon, the catastrophically loose-tongued leader
who oversaw the Liberal Democratic Party's debacle is already being
spoken of in some quarters in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens next very much depends upon whether Mori remains
in office after the G-8 Summit,'' said Hidekazu Kawai, a professor
of comparative politics at Gakushuin University in Tokyo. ``I
believe that he is already on the road toward what we call an
honorable retirement. But if he does not retire, strife within the
LDP will only become stronger, because people will be afraid to
fight another election under his leadership.'' Japan's next
parliamentary election, an Upper House vote, is due next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government has been gearing up for a full year to
host the G-8, a meeting of leaders of major industrial powers.
According to this view, Mori's success as a host of the event will
serve as a dignified occasion to bow out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberal Democrats have far more to worry about than a
feckless prime minister who needlessly provoked independent voters
by urging them to ``just stay in bed'' on Election Day rather than
play havoc with his encouraging poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The largely unheralded story of the past decade or so has, in
fact, been the creeping demise of a party that has been in power so
long that analysts must reach for comparisons to a place like
China, rather than the Western democracies, for parallels.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the Liberal Democratic Party governed easily with
its comfortable parliamentary majority, stifling debate and
co-opting other parties with budgetary sweets to secure their added
support as needed. The party suffered a momentary setback _ its
only loss of power _ in 1993, when Morihiro Hosokawa, leader of a
small reformist party, formed a brief-lived government.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Liberal Democrats have been back in power,
firmly at first, but less comfortably with every passing election,
as the number of independent voters has increased, and as their
support has tilted toward opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's predecessor, the late Keizo Obuchi, achieved a large
ruling majority only by forming a controversial and awkward
coalition, bringing together a pacifist, Buddhist-backed party that
favors social spending, New Komeito, with the Liberals, a hawkish,
Thatcherite party.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Sunday's vote, the Liberal Democrats are
left with their awkward allies, and are hobbled with a weak
coalition that even together holds only a slim majority.
</P>
<P>
   Many factors seem to have contributed to the ruling party's
fading hold on the electorate. For one, urban voters in particular
seem to have grown disgusted with the government's free spending in
rural areas. Endless projects like ultramodern airports for small
farming prefectures and an ever-expanding, but money-losing bullet
train network, have cost Japan a half trillion dollars during two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Such projects are justified in the name of pump priming to keep
the country's economy afloat _ and that barely, after a decade of
decline. But voters, particularly urban voters, seem to have caught
onto the game and decided that this is really about nothing more
than buying the support of the countryside for the Liberal
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the impression that Japan is a country divided in two,
a rural and an urban country,'' said Yoichi Masuzoe, an independent
who unsuccessfully ran for governor of Tokyo. ``In the capital, and
in other urban areas, L.D.P. candidates lost, including many of its
big names. Their traditional way of distributing money, in the name
of public works, has only worked with rural voters. The salary man
in Tokyo is more concerned about what is happening to the country,
and they have shown their desire for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question now is whether Japan will stick to a traditional,
dirty way of handling matters, favoring the rural areas, or whether
it is choosing a new way, a more open and rational policy-based
approach. The next two years will tell, but I believe this is
really a historic transition period.''
</P>
<P>
   If a major transition is under way, many people feel that the
outcome will be a more stable two-party system, or at least a
system involving two large, rival coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Through its performance, the Democratic Party took a major step
toward becoming a leader of one of those coalitions. And many
analysts said that the way that it did so bodes well for the future
of Japanese politics.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than compete with the Liberal Democratic Party on the
basis of seductive promises, the Democrats took the usual tack of
warning voters that substantial pain lies ahead for Japan after
years of overindulgence and drift.
</P>
<P>
   Most specifically, in a campaign that most often resembled a
competition between poster hangers rather than a contest over
ideas, the Democrats distinguished themselves by promising new
taxes and specific spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Although few people are willing to credit the Democratic Party
with having a full-blown platform on how to run the economy, or,
many say, the maturity yet to govern, many analysts saluted this
act of electoral courage as a sample of the kind of spine that will
be needed to revive the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
