<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5590 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-26 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LOOKING FOR MR. RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our topic for today, people, is The Proper Mate for Women in
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   We are looking at today's state legislative primary in Goose
Creek, S.C., in which Rep. Shirley Hinson is being challenged by
her estranged husband, Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the issues,'' says Hinson, who was arrested in 1998
for making a death threat against another state representative he
believed was having an affair with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desperate tactics for a desperate person,'' said Ms. Hinson,
who once took out a restraining order against her husband, accusing
him of stalking her at the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   We have been down this road before, more or less. There was the
case of Rep. Coya Knutson of Minnesota, whose bid for a third term
in 1958 ended in disaster when her alcoholic husband published a
``Coya Come Home'' letter, accusing her of having an affair with
her administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Langley got elected to Congress from Kentucky in 1926
after her spouse, Rep. John Wesley Langley, was sentenced to the
federal pen for bootlegging. She talked Calvin Coolidge into
pardoning him, and the newly sprung Langley immediately ran against
her for his old seat. The third candidate, not married to either
one of them, won.
</P>
<P>
   But our modern version of the disastrous political spouse
generally tends more in the direction of overzealousness.
</P>
<P>
   We are thinking, for instance, of Albert Pirro, a lawyer in the
New York City suburbs who devoted a great deal of energy to
promoting the career of his wife, Jeanine, a rising Republican star
and the current Westchester County district attorney. One of
Pirro's 33 companies produced a cable TV show starring Mrs. Pirro.
Another hired a political consultant to advise her on what to do
when she developed one of those ``nanny'' tax problems that were
all the rage in the early 90s. (The consultant's advice, which
seemed to work well, was that Mrs. Pirro should come clean on her
TV show.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Pirro deducted this stuff as business expenses,
along with the family's six cars and an $1,800 wrought iron fence
for the Vietnamese potbellied pigs. Last week he was convicted of
tax evasion, and Mrs. Pirro's career is toast. However, women of
the future may be able to pick up helpful hints from her story,
such as the advisability of sticking to cocker spaniels as
household pets. They may also conclude that when a spouse starts
doing business through 33 different companies, it's time to start
thinking separate tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   New York has never had much success at getting women elected to
high office, but we're an absolute databank of what can go wrong in
a political marriage. This year, of course, we've hit the jackpot
with Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has already taught the world
everything it needs to know about the perils of a dual-career
candidacy. Never again will anyone running for anything promise the
voters they will get two for the price of one.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, politicians would all follow the example of
the president in ``West Wing'' and marry physicians. Doctors can
generally get a job anywhere, and you seldom see them wandering
around the Capitol lobbying for legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Our latest Senate candidate, Rep. Rick Lazio, had the good
judgment to marry a nurse. (Yes, Lazio was the guy chosen to run
against the first lady after the mayor's marriage imploded and the
Westchester DA's husband failed to convince a jury that the cost of
fighting a paternity case was a legitimate business deduction. Is
this a great state, or what?)
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Patricia Lazio does not seem to be under threat of
indictment, nor was she exiled to the Food Channel for the duration
of her husband's career, like Rudy Giuliani's estranged wife, a
former TV anchor. She works part time at a hospital breast cancer
unit. Everything seemed perfect until Lazio told reporters about a
talk they had during a controversy over his stock investments.
``She said: `Listen, you know what? We're honest, decent people. I
clean my own house. We have nothing to be ashamed of,''' he
recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lazio is currently trudging from Horseheads to Ogdensburg
in support of her husband's Senate campaign, while caring for two
small children and doing her job at the hospital. If she gets no
help around the house, I think he can kiss the working women's vote
goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
