<HEADLINE>
LUCENT CREATES A NEW BRAND NAME TO MARKET TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to create a strong new force in the market for office
telephone systems and networking equipment, Lucent Technologies
Inc. intends to announce a new brand Tuesday for its unit that
sells communications products to business customers, people close
to the division said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, which Lucent calls its Enterprise Networks division,
is in the process of being spun out of Lucent as an independent
company. Lucent plans no initial public offering of stock in the
new company, which has $8 billion in annual revenue. Instead,
Lucent intends to distribute all of the shares in the new company
directly to its shareholders by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Monday just what the new company would be called.
A Lucent spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter the name of the new brand, Tuesday's announcement
will not answer the main question that many of Lucent's investors
are asking these days: does the company plan to spin-off its
fast-growing microelectronics unit? Lucent's top management has at
least considered such a move, but it does not appear that a final
decision has been made. Any announcement of such a move probably
would not be made for at least two weeks, according to one person
close to the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that the microelectronics division, which
makes chips and other components used in advanced communications
equipment, has annual revenue of $3.5 billion to $4 billion.
Nonetheless, because it is growing quickly and because investors
are currently infatuated with comparable companies like JDS
Uniphase and Broadcom, the microelectronics division could enjoy a
stand-alone market value of $50 billion or more. Lucent does not
report financial results for its microelectronics business, but the
larger business unit to which the microelectronics section belongs
reported revenue growth in the most recent quarter of 38 percent,
to $1.7 billion, over the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the enterprise networks group has twice the revenue
of the microelectronics operation, it is likely to have a much
smaller market value. That is because the Enterprise Networks group
is actually shrinking, at least in its current form. For the most
recent quarter, Lucent announced that the division generated $2
billion in revenue, down 8 percent from the comparable period of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   At least in part, Lucent wants to spin out the Enterprise group,
which includes among its products office phone systems and office
communications cables, because it is dragging down the growth rate
for the overall company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
