<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Global influences abound on plates of city's eateries
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta ($3.50) takes a world view with its July cover story on
the city's booming ethnic restaurant scene. Researching the article
was adventurous in many ways, says dining critic Christiane
Lauterbach. In addition to sampling sea slugs, brains, monkfish
liver and goat, Lauterbach ventured into places where men dined
behind curtains and female companionship was included in the price
of appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   Other articles of note include Thonnia Lee's report on Atlanta's
growing community of African-American women writers, Scott
Freeman's update on the elusive bombing suspect Eric Rudolph and
Mary Jo DiLonardo's profile of golfer Rosie Jones _ ``the best
professional athlete you've never heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Waving the flag: Apparently the last couple of issues of
George ($2.95) were not a fluke; the magazine founded by John F.
Kennedy Jr. is improving editorially (financially, too, notes
editor Frank Lalli, who reports that circulation has increased by
25 percent to 500,000). In the July issue, Richard Reeves takes a
look at new American patriots such as Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.),
singer Patti Smith and radio talk show host Don Imus. Actor Mel
Gibson talks about some of the myths of 1776 that were dispelled
during the filming of ``The Patriot.'' It seems our original
citizen-soldiers were a bunch of whining malcontents and deserters
who relied on mercenaries to win the war.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calorically overwhelmed: Life for many American kids is one
Happy Meal after another. At least that's the way it appears in
Newsweek's ($3.50) cover story on Generation XXL. One in three kids
faces long-term health problems because they are overweight, says
writer Geoffrey Cowley. The convenience of fast food and snacks is
one factor, Cowley says, but adding to the problem is the removal
of physical education programs from many school systems. The worse
things parents can do is nag or restrict food, says psychologist
Jane Laubross. Instead, she says, set an example and focus on
health and more physical activities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Between the covers: Larry McMurtry not only writes books _ he
collects them by the thousands and sells them in a four-store
complex in the town that was the inspiration for ``The Last Picture
Show.'' Book ($4.95) magazine visits McMurtry at Booked Up, his
``book ranch'' in Archer City, Texas, where the author displays an
impressive selection of first editions such as Eudora Welty's ``The
Golden Apples,'' George Orwell's ``Shooting an Elephant'' and
Dalton Trumbo's ``Johnny Got His Gun.'' Also featured in this issue
are an interview with Georgia poet laureate David Bottoms and a
list of 10 first novels you shouldn't have missed. Included are
Toni Morrison's ``The Bluest Eye'' and John Updike's ``The
Poorhouse Fair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: The lad mags this month are filled with scantily
clad actresses as well as some interesting reading. Maxim ($3.95)
features ``X-Men'' stars Halle Berry, Rebecca Romijn-Stamos and
Famke Janssen in a cover story on the much-anticipated summer
blockbuster. ... Gear ($3.50) also weighs in on ``X-Men'' and the
history of other comics that were made into movies, from ``Jungle
Jim'' to ``Men in Black'' ... FHM ($2.99) offers a revealing
interview and photo layout of Alicia Silverstone and an equally
revealing profile of Irish-American dancer Michael Flatley.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Newcomer: Southern Living has launched Southern Living
Weddings ($4.95), a publication aimed at brides-to-be and newlyweds
who want to maintain certain traditions. One issue is planned for
this year, but more are expected in 2001, says spokeswoman
Katharine Carroll. The magazine features a directory of regional
experts and resources, articles on gracious Southern weddings, and
post-ceremony suggestions for decorating a first home and
stress-free cooking for two.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
