<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECT-HOUSEWARES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interest brewing in teakettle designer Graves
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Graves may be internationally renowned in design
circles, but the architect has hardly been a household name.
</P>
<P>
   A whimsical little teakettle he designed for Target, however,
may bring fame to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I went to see my products in the store, there
was a little girl there who looked at her mother and said, 'Look,
Mommy, at all this cool stuff,''' Graves said. ``Her mother said,
'Yes, dear, it's very nice, and, you know, I do need a new kettle.'
Then they went over to my decorative objects, and the girl said,
'These must be by the same people because they're cool, too!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter that the stuff was by Michael Graves,'' he
said. ``They got it.''
</P>
<P>
   What they ``got'' is that good design doesn't have to be
expensive. Big-name designers like Graves are seeing to that.
</P>
<P>
   The post-modern architect and product designer _ whose kettle
and initial dozen other housewares for Target now total more than
600 products _ tonight addresses the Georgia chapter of the
American Society of Interior Designers at Atlanta's Swissotel.
</P>
<P>
   Pairing Graves, whose architectural designs range from Humana's
headquarters in Louisville, Ky., to the Michael C. Carlos Museum
renovation in Atlanta, with mainstream America has brought the
65-year-old designer national acclaim. ``I expected a wave or two
but nothing like what's happened,'' he said by phone from his
Princeton, N.J., office.
</P>
<P>
   Graves and his team agreed to design two categories of products
for Target _ teakettles, toasters and mixers, and decorative
objects. Next month, they'll roll out telephones, radios and CD
players.
</P>
<P>
   Because the products are priced widely _ $3.99 for a Hipper
Flipper spatula, $40 for the ``Toast Modern'' toaster, $499 for an
Indonesian hardwood patio set _ there's something for everyone.
More important, middle-income consumers are getting the message
that good design is good design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to tell people I'd spend as much time designing a
stainless steel teapot for Target as I would if I were doing a
sterling silver service for Cartier,'' Graves said. ``It's just as
hard _ or harder because of the cost restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton University architecture professor created a
tempest in a teakettle of sorts when the Target line debuted in
February 1999. Graves' sleek $34.95 kettle had a striking
resemblance to one he'd designed in the '80s for Alessi, the
European housewares giant, which sells for $115. Alessi steamed,
but the comparison made Target's egg-handled kettle _ and Graves _
all the hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in addition to product design, Graves' firm is juggling
30 building projects, including a bid for a major design at a
Singapore university. Emory University also had sought his
involvement for a planned addition to the Carlos Museum, where he
headed a 1982 renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who also designed Midtown's 10 Peachtree Place building
where Coca-Cola has offices, is well aware of Atlanta's penchant
for tearing down. ``To save good buildings, you have to have a very
strong government and people with very strong feelings to care for
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the key to reducing sprawl is good urban schools
that will entice suburban families to live downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that impresses everybody about Atlanta is your great
old mansions, the gardens and rolling hills of green,'' Graves
said. ``When you drive into some of those neighborhoods, I know why
people live there. It's truly wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   ASID Design
</P>
<P>
   Excellence Awards
</P>
<P>
   6:30 tonight. $100 for public; $75 for ASID members (includes
cocktail reception, silent auction, dinner). Swissotel, 3391
Peachtree Road N.E. Information: 404-872-3100.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
