<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rome Reduces Traffic by Limiting Tour Buses
</P>
<P>
   All roads may lead to Rome, but these days not everyone
traveling on them can reach downtown. Since April 6, tour buses
have not been allowed to circulate freely or park within the
historic center. City officials passed the regulations to avoid
potential traffic jams as many thousands of pilgrims visit Rome in
the Jubilee Holy Year.
</P>
<P>
   Today, tour buses entering Rome must pass through one of six
checkpoints on main roads into the city. (As the system becomes
increasingly computerized, they will be reduced to three.) At the
checkpoint, the bus is registered and upon payment of a fee, which
can be paid in advance, is issued a permit. Different kinds of
permits exist, some giving access to a parking spot at one of the
18 new lots inside the city limits. Most of them are open 24 hours
a day and are guarded around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, tour-bus drivers would park wherever they could,
and this often contributed to Rome's notoriously congested traffic.
Since the measure went into effect, buses found without a permit,
or illegally parked, are fined.
</P>
<P>
   After registration, buses can circulate freely outside the
third-century Aurelian walls, but they can only venture into the
historic center _ delineated by the walls _ to drop off and pick up
passengers near the principal tourist attractions, hotels and
restaurants. The designated parking lots are within walking
distance of public transportation (city buses, trams or the subway)
and the new J-line Jubilee buses that connect the principal
pilgrimage sites as well as Rome's monuments. There are nine J-line
buses, all air-conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations, which were hotly contested by tour
operators and bus drivers before the city relaxed those regarding
the drop-off sites and cost of the permits, have most Romans
breathing a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Information is available at the Romotur Web site:
www.romotur.it.
</P>
<P>
   By Independence Hall, a New Ritz-Carlton
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton Philadelphia, the chain's first new hotel in
the United States in almost 10 years, is now open at 10 Avenue of
the Arts, occupying two landmark buildings near Independence Hall.
Amenities include such innovations as a technology butler to solve
problems without charge for laptop-carrying guests and a bath
butler to draw one's bath and supply, at extra charge, Champagne
and truffles or exotic scents.
</P>
<P>
   The neo-Classical Girard-Mellon Bank buildings, with a rotunda
copied from the Pantheon in Rome and a tower dating from the early
1900s, were designed by McKim, Mead &AMP; White. The renovation cost
$88 million, giving the hotel 331 rooms, including a
2,100-square-foot penthouse, and 20,000 feet of meeting space, two
restaurants and two lounges.
</P>
<P>
   Guest rooms, with extra-large windows, are done in gold and
azure or gold, burgundy and green, with wood accents and moldings
reminiscent of grand European hotels, along with prints of historic
Philadelphia sites on the walls. There are cordless phones and
outlets for high-speed Internet connections. The two-bedroom
penthouse has an exercise room, a sauna, a kitchen and a living
room. Guests on the four Club Floors below the penthouse have
access to the services of a concierge and a lounge where free
meals, snacks and drinks are served.
</P>
<P>
   Rates range from $320 a night for a double room, $420 for a Club
room and $3,500 for the penthouse. Reservations: (800) 241-3333 or
(215) 735-7700.
</P>
<P>
   Another Delay For Amtrak's Acela
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak suffered another setback last month in getting its
high-speed equipment into service between Washington and Boston.
Officials believe the earliest possible starting date for the Acela
Express is now late August.
</P>
<P>
   The new delay, from a hoped-for late July start, came when bolts
broke on the trucks of new electric locomotives after 40,000 miles
of testing. Rick Remington, an Amtrak spokesman, said that the
locomotive manufacturer, Bombardier of Montreal, had not told the
company how long the bolt replacement and testing would take. He
said engineers, after a rough ride, found that one bolt was broken
and one missing. All the locomotives were then inspected.
</P>
<P>
   Although Amtrak has been operating some renovated Acela cars on
the Northeast Corridor, they have been coupled to older engines and
the trains have not reached the 150-mile-per-hour speeds expected
from the new locomotives. Hopes for getting the all-new equipment
into service last winter were dashed when the wheels wore
excessively in high-speed tests.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Touring a Street of Gems
</P>
<P>
   Much of New York City's diamond industry is concentrated on West
47th Street between Fifth Avenue and Avenue of the Americas. A
two-hour tour designed to help visitors investigate and navigate
the hundreds of jewelry merchants lining the block was recently
introduced by a company called FINY (Fun in New York).
</P>
<P>
   The tour group will hear five or six merchants talk about
various types of jewelry _ diamonds, colored gems and precious
metals, for example _ and offer shopping tips as well as
information and legends about different types of gemstones.
</P>
<P>
   Participating merchants provide coupons for discounts ranging
from 20 to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamond District tour is offered every day but Sunday, 11
a.m. and 2 p.m. The cost is $15. Reservations are required at least
one day in advance: (203) 894-8043.
</P>
<P>
   High Notes and High Rides in New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   Defying nature, Jazzland Theme Park opened recently east of New
Orleans with a spectacular 4,000-foot-long roller coaster, 29 other
rides and French Quarter-style architecture constructed on a
platform four feet above what was formerly a soggy playground for
alligators, armadillos and nutria.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The casual visitor will be unaware that much of the 55-acre park
is built on a massive but unobtrusive steel and concrete shelf
resting on 18,000 wood pilings, 50 feet tall, sunk deep into the
soft, damp earth of Louisiana's Mississippi River delta. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Originally planned as an attraction focusing primarily on the
infectious homegrown rhythms that attract millions of people
annually to the New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival, the French
Quarter Festival and the city's music clubs, Jazzland was expanded
to include a variety of rides with names like the Muskrat
Scrambler, Lafitte's Pirate Ship, Zydeco Scream and the Voodoo
Volcano.
</P>
<P>
   A children's section, Kids' Carnival, offers an interactive
playground and scaled-down versions of some of the adult rides. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the music attractions is a Cajun-style dance hall near
17-acre Jazz Lake, where the last remaining alligators were ousted
to make way for a five-times-a-day water-ski show. Popular
Louisiana musicians perform at the dance hall daily from 4 to about
9 p.m. Dance hall food will include such Louisiana dishes as
grilled or smoked Creole chicken ($6) and seafood boudin ($5).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pontchartrain Beach section, offering fried catfish po-boys
for $6, recalls the city's smaller, Art Deco lakeside amusement
park that closed in the early 1980s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Developed at a cost of $110 million, Jazzland is at 12301 Lake
Forest Boulevard about eight miles east of the French Quarter near
the intersection of I-10 and I-510; (504) 253-8100.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $31; $26 for children. Open daily from June 2 to
Aug. 20. The hours during May vary. Open weekends only from Aug. 26
to Oct. 29, and closed during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
