u a BC-NY-BRONX-DEVELOP-ART-     06-26 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-DEVELOP-ART-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEL COMMUNITY IMPROVEMENT ASSOCIATION VICTIM OF MISMANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT15,16 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By AMY WALDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This spring, the grievances at 1084-1086 Home Street
in the South Bronx piled up like the garbage in the courtyard:
sporadic heat and hot water, unpaid light bills, water-cracked
walls, rats swaggering through like neighborhood bullies. Hallway
graffiti cursed the landlord, who had not bothered to paint over
it.
</P>
<P>
   The building's state was not the handiwork of a profiteering
landlord. Rather, the overseer of 1084-1086 Home Street is the
Banana Kelly Community Improvement Association, a Bronx nonprofit
community development corporation once praised as a national model
for residents who want to restore failing housing and reclaim lost
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Today, its own properties are increasingly troubled, whether by
periods without heat, as at 1100 West Farms Road, or by unrealized
plans, as with a former synagogue, empty and encrusted with
scaffolding and graffiti, on Fox Street.
</P>
<P>
   For a group that got its start rehabilitating abandoned
buildings, there may be no symbol more dispiriting than 866 Beck
Street, a Banana Kelly building that deteriorated so much that it
was emptied of tenants and boarded up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our savior has become a slumlord,'' said Marta Rivera, the
chairwoman of the local community board and a tenant at 1084 Home
Street since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism, if harsh, is understandable, given what Banana
Kelly, which drew its memorable name from the curve of the Bronx
street where it was born, once meant in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, foundations, reporters and government officials
flocked to the Hunts Point-Longwood neighborhoods to see how Banana
Kelly had transformed drug-infested, derelict tenements into
livable spaces, and had created low-income, low-rise housing co-ops
that proved the salvation of a once-devastated area.
</P>
<P>
   To its critics, the decline of some of Banana Kelly's properties
is a physical reflection of the group's internal disarray, which is
sketched in remarkably consistent terms by current and former board
members, former employees and financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   Local merchants have shunned, and in some cases sued, the
organization because of unpaid debts; at least one oil company
began demanding cash on delivery. Former employees who have exited
through its revolving door accuse top officials of using program
money for international travel, a charge that, according to one
federal law enforcement official, the Federal Bureau of
Investigation is also examining. The group's board, the essential
instrument for accountability, has withered to a tiny group that
rarely meets.
</P>
<P>
   Banana Kelly's revenues from foundations, government grants and
development projects dropped from nearly $6 million in 1994 to
barely $3 million in 1998. It currently has no city financing. Its
debts, meanwhile, have mounted into the hundreds of thousands of
dollars. It is in arrears on six city mortgages, and behind on its
payroll taxes. At times, its employees say, their offices lacked
for toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   Grand plans, most notably a big paper recycling plant proposed
for the South Bronx, have stalled or failed. Many residents have
lost faith.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years after its formation, Banana Kelly is one of the
Bronx's major landlords. It manages 41 buildings that house
formerly homeless and low-income and working-class families. Over
the years, it has expanded into a multiservice agency employing 95
people who do everything from managing its properties to counseling
AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Its many triumphs have included a 1996 award from the city as an
outstanding community-based organization and another at a United
Nations conference that year. But its critics say its recent awards
reflect an organization coasting on past glories.
</P>
<P>
   The group's chairwoman, Yolanda Rivera, disputed the critics,
saying that it is a wonderful time for Banana Kelly, and that she
was bringing renewed vigor to righting it financially. She cited
the high school the organization started in 1997; the Board of
Education has authorized the construction of a new building for the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera denies any allegation that money was misused. She said
many of the property problems were caused by tenants who had never
learned how to live independently, and said politics or
``mischief'' motivated many of her critics. She said that the city
had been little help in alleviating the organization's debts, and
that she deserved credit for keeping the organization afloat in a
trying period. ``I'm not ashamed that we continue to operate, that
we are healthy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her defenders say that she is paying the price for being a
successful Hispanic woman. Joe Hall, who worked at Banana Kelly for
eight years, said Rivera embodies ``the great paradox of community
development in New York'': foundations and other institutions say
they want to cultivate indigenous leaders like Rivera, but then are
threatened when they succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, Banana Kelly's situation is less paradox than
parable, illustrating some of the dangers inherent in the recent
history of government's relationship with poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   During the last few decades, government has stepped back from
direct involvement in areas like housing and health care, and
instead encouraged community development organizations like Banana
Kelly to step into the breach.
</P>
<P>
   Neither adequate resources nor oversight have always followed.
When nonprofit organizations have struggled, government overseers
have often been ill positioned or unwilling to attempt reform. No
government agency even has a complete sense of Banana Kelly's
finances.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Banana Kelly's very purpose has protected it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
