A5599 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSHLULAC27-COX     06-26 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHLULAC27-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush says he wants to break INS into two parts
</P>
<P>
   By Jena Heath
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush told the League of United
Latin American Citizens on Monday that he wants to make the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service more consumer friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed to chop the INS into two agencies _ one for law
enforcement and one for helping immigrants. It's a plan similar to
one that U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, has been unable to push
through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as people are coming to feed their families, our
country must be mindful that they're human beings ,'' Bush told
LULAC's 71st annual convention. ``And I must stell you that the INS
sends a different message at times. It's too bureaucratic. It's too
paperwork-oriented. It is an agency that sends mixed signals to
people we're trying to help. I intend to reform the INS.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bush angered some Latino leaders when he skipped
meetings of LULAC, the National Council of La Raza and the National
Association of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, as the race for the Hispanic vote has intensified,
both Bush and Vice President Al Gore have aggressively courted
Latinos with ad campaigns and speeches. Bush's effort to attract
the Hispanic vote also has included appearances by George P. Bush,
24, the Spanish-speaking son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and his
Hispanic wife, Columba.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain addresses LULAC Thursday and Gore, the
presumptive Democratic nominee, appears Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore spoke to the National Association of Latino
Elected and Appointed Officials; Bush spoke to the National
Association of Hispanic Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Bush and Gore are scheduled address the National
Council of La Raza's annual conference in San Diego. Bush was set
to address the Congress of Racial Equality in New York Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party is making an all-out effort to woo the
fast-growing, traditionally Democratic Latino constituency.
According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the Latino population
increased from 22.4 million in 1990 to 31.8 million in 1999.
Hispanic voters also are concentrated in vote-rich California,
Texas and New York. Those states total 202 electoral votes; 270 are
needed to win in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not address several key issues in his speech, including
President Clinton's choice of El Paso lawyer Enrique Moreno for the
5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and the use of statistical
sampling in the 2000 Census. Texas senators Phil Gramm and Kay
Bailey Hutchison, both Republicans, are opposing Moreno's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   LULAC President Rick Dovalina said he spent 20 minutes with Bush
before the speech and that Bush told him he would look into the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   On the census issue, Democrats charge that sampling _ using a
formula to determine the count _ is the only way to insure that
traditionally undercounted minorities are represented as states
draw congressional and legislative districts. Republicans counter
that Democrats are simply trying to find ways to inflate the
numbers of voters friendly to them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not said how he would handle the issue if he makes it
to the White House, but has said he favors an actual count. Rep.
Charles Gonzalez, D-San Antonio, wrote to Bush for the fourth time
Monday seeking clarification.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that he had described Bush as, ``parading around with
his taco politics,'' after the governor failed to attend last
year's LULAC annual conference in Corpus Christi, Texas, Dovalina
said Bush has improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we did here today has changed that,'' he said.
``Because I spent 20 minutes with him back there and he was very
receptive and listening as opposed to telling us what (he feels)
are the Hispanic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would support Bush in November, Dovalina said he
didn't know. He said he couldn't remember if he voted for Bush in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall,'' he said. ``I'm a Democrat so I don't think I
did. But he does really have a lot of support in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
