<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-BRONX-DEVELOP-ART-     06-26 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-DEVELOP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: protected it.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Not-for-profits in these communities on the housing side are
so critical a resource,'' said Jerilyn Perine, the first deputy
commissioner at the city's Department of Housing, Preservation and
Development. ``We want to see them succeed. We don't want them to
fail. Their importance goes simply beyond their own organization.
It's not as if if they disappeared, someone will take their
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the Ruins _ A Radical Idea: Save Buildings
</P>
<P>
   Banana Kelly bloomed from the ruins, at a time when housing in
the South Bronx was being burned, not built. In the 1970s, a group
of residents on Kelly Street united to stop the demolition of three
buildings on their block.
</P>
<P>
   The group revamped those buildings and won title to them and
others from a city desperate to divest itself of abandoned or
deteriorating housing. The city provided loans for rehabilitation
or gave Banana Kelly newly renovated buildings to manage, usually
asking only a symbolic pittance in return.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Banana Kelly incorporated as a nonprofit corporation
providing housing and services. Its adopted as its motto, ``Don't
Move. Improve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was coming in to see how we did this, how did we get
people together,'' recalled Pearl White, a founding member who said
she could still remember the splinters stinging her hands as she
helped rehabilitate the buildings. ``It was a tourist attraction,
almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Banana Kelly brought tens of millions of dollars in investment
to its community and rehabilitated more than 2,000 units of
housing; it also suggested that the tide of hopelessness could be
turned. Its methods, like sweat equity, allowed residents to trade
work for ownership, and its performance won it federal, state and
city contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Banana Kelly Community Improvement Association is an
umbrella organization for the limited partnerships and low-income
co-ops that own the buildings it manages. It is supposed to collect
rents, do maintenance, pay real estate taxes, and make mortgage,
water and sewer payments.
</P>
<P>
   Like many community-based housing developers, it is in a
difficult financial position. The group's rents are low, and its
tenants vulnerable to falling behind in payments. While Banana
Kelly has been taken to Housing Court dozens of times, it has had
to bring hundreds of delinquent tenants there, incurring legal
expenses each time.
</P>
<P>
   The city also handed over properties in need of more work than
it provided financing for, said Harold DeRienzo, Banana Kelly's
founder, and Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rivera, who became the organization's chief executive in
1991, Banana Kelly undertook a variety of social service
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Saying she wanted to wean both tenants and the organization from
dependence on government, Rivera also turned to large-scale
economic development. In 1992, Banana Kelly joined with the Natural
Resources Defense Council, a national environmental advocacy
organization, to develop a paper recycling plant to be built in the
South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The plant was designed by Maya Lin, best known for the Vietnam
War Memorial in Washington, and praised by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But it has yet to be built _ financing and politics have
postponed it indefinitely _ and like a castle in the air, it
drained personnel and attention from an organization struggling on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-BRONX-DEVELOP-ART-     06-26 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-DEVELOP-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the ground.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Staff Turnover _ A Poor Record Of Management
</P>
<P>
   As Banana Kelly grew, its infrastructure was being stretched.
When Rivera took over, she dismissed a number of the staff, saying
an excess of professionals had distanced the agency from the
community.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years, new employees and executives have come, but
few have stayed long. Many have been fired in the agency's many
purges during the last eight years. Even today, Rivera said, most
of the staff is brand-new. But the influx of new ideas and energy
was beneficial, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency eventually became overwhelmed, current and former
officials said. Financial backers of Banana Kelly describe almost
willfully incompetent financial management. They say Banana Kelly
never found a workable system for collecting and tracking rents and
expenditures, and did a poor job of separating its various
operations. It missed tax advantages, and a $2 million state grant
awarded in 1998 to renovate 866 Beck Street and another building is
being withheld because Banana Kelly has not provided an updated
audited financial statement, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the nearly $1 million owed for water and sewer
services, more than $500,000 in real estate taxes, the overdue
$127,000 an oil company is trying to collect, the liens and
lawsuits over the years from accountants, hardware stores and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Former employees describe continual pressures to use money
earmarked for specific programs to offset those debts, and say
programs and maintenance operations had to run on shoestrings.
Superintendents reached into their own pockets to buy everything
from paint to oil; the group's former president said he had to take
out a loan to make the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as employees were scrounging, Rivera and a few associates
were traveling, as part of an international venture the group
established several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By Rivera's own admission, some part of the organization's
dwindling resources _ what she calls general, or unrestricted funds
_ were used to pay for that travel, including a trip to a
conference in Kenya for her and several associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a good group rate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, as part of an investigation into Banana Kelly's finances,
the FBI is looking at whether federal program money was used to pay
for that trip and whether Rivera's relatives went with her, a
federal law enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on the Africa trip was a Bronx-based consultant who
did particularly well under Banana Kelly's auspices. By the time
the consultant, Aureo Cardona, left the organization last year, his
company, Crescendo Inc., was being paid $15,000 a month to manage
Banana Kelly's properties, and he had been given access to a
$50,000 expense fund _ to be replenished as needed _ to do
``national and international engagements'' for the group. And,
under a contract he signed with Claude Gooding, the organization's
former president, he was to receive $1 million if the recycling
plant went to financial closing, which it has not.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera says she knew nothing about that contract, and the two
parted ways after The New York Post reported the deal last year.
Cardona is now suing Banana Kelly for back pay, saying his contract
was breached, and would not discuss his history with the group.
</P>
<P>
   Another frequent traveler was Hall, who was named president of
Banana Kelly International. Hall, who said his salary was $55,000,
lived in a Banana Kelly apartment at 814 Manida Street, which is
supposed to house low-income tenants exclusively under the
agreement by which the city transferred the building to Banana
Kelly in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he did not know the building was for low-income
tenants; Rivera said she thought it was for low- to moderate-income
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rivera has been at the center of controversy almost since she
took charge of the organization in 1991, after having been
chairwoman of its board since 1985. She has retained her board
chairmanship during her tenure as chief executive, an arrangement
that her predecessor, Getz Obstfeld, called ``fairly uncommon,''
and that her critics assert insulates her from accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can tell you another nonprofit that does it,''
Obstfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the board has shrunk, with as few as three
members, including Rivera, usually attending no more than one
meeting a year, the minimum required by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Banana Kelly's bylaws say that ``board members are not to be
directly involved with management.'' Yet over the years, in
addition to Rivera, various board members have been employed by
Banana Kelly, including Rosemonde Pierre-Louis, a member since
1996, who became the organization's president last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Rivera has elevated those she considers loyal, her
critics say, she has sometimes vindictively dispatched those she
believes are not. In February, she fired five longtime building
superintendents without notice, making a variety of accusations
that she conceded in an interview may be difficult to prove. She
has since been trying to evict them from their apartments, although
the dismissals await union arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the law in Banana Kelly,'' one of the fired
superintendents, Agripino Morales, said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tenants Make Do _ Buildings Worsen, Repairs Go Undone
</P>
<P>
   But neither deep resentment nor financial travails seem to have
affected Banana Kelly, its critics say. As its city financing has
dwindled to nothing, it has simply turned to the state and federal
governments.
</P>
<P>
   City officials could foreclose on Banana Kelly's mortgages, but
feel that doing so would set the community back 20 years. While
housing officials have been aware of Banana Kelly's management
problems for years, in April 1999 the housing department turned
four more buildings over to the group for a down payment of $4.
</P>
<P>
   So tenants make do with the landlord they have.
</P>
<P>
   In Lydia Rios' third-floor apartment at 788 Fox Street, an April
visit by a city housing inspector left a checklist of violations,
from no smoke detector to a leaky ceiling. She shrugged. Each year
the housing inspector orders repairs, and they go undone, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaky ceiling comes as no surprise to the owner of the
building's ground-floor bodega, who points to the water damage
pressing down on his ceiling and his $2,000 monthly rent bill and
asked, ``Isn't Banana Kelly supposed to be an organization for poor
people, to help the community?''
</P>
<P>
   Banana Kelly's financial backers and city officials say they
have become particularly concerned in recent months because of
deferred maintenance to Banana Kelly's properties.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said the organization is seeking a loan to pay off back
taxes and rehabilitate 788 Fox Street and several other buildings.
But, she said of tenants, ``If conditions were as bad as they
sometimes say, they would have moved out.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the organization's roots, that sentiment sits poorly with
Pearl White, a cosmetologist who has sat on Banana Kelly's board
since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   As a board member, she said, she has futilely challenged
Rivera's actions and demanded more records. She was warned, she
said, that if she spoke publicly about her concerns, she would be
removed from the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see any of the buildings end up like the
condition we were in,'' she said, sitting in the apartment on Kelly
Street she helped bring back to life with her bare hands more than
two decades ago. ``I don't want to see Banana Kelly ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
