u e BC-KYLIAN-DANCE-NYT &LR;      06-26 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KYLIAN-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANCE FEAST WHERE FUN FLOWS ACROSS THE AISLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Given the customary abstraction of contemporary dance,
it is easy to see the metaphor behind Jiri Kylian's use of bridges
as the theme of his show celebrating the 40th anniversary of the
Nederlands Dans Theater and his own 25 years as the company's
principal choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always tried to build bridges,'' he explained,
``bridges between people, races, nations, continents.''
</P>
<P>
   But for this show, ``Arcimboldo 2000,'' which is touring eight
European cities this spring and summer, the Czech-born
choreographer has done more than use bridges as symbols. He has
also built real bridges from the stage over the orchestra pit into
the audience. Significantly, these are bridges crossed by both the
performers and the public. Here, at least, there is no curtain
separating illusion and reality.
</P>
<P>
   Before the show, spectators encounter video cameras recording
their arrival, with the scenes replayed on a screen onstage. They
are then guided behind and below the stage to discover a score of
dancers, bedecked in feathers, moving in slow motion and hidden in
odd places, like spirits who people the darkened theater.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, visitors arrive on stage and cross the bridges into the
theater to take their seats. Once the show begins, it is the
dancers' turn to go in the opposite direction, popping up in the
audience before crossing onto the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all in one boat, under the same roof,'' said Kylian, 53,
who gave up the administrative duties of artistic director of the
company last fall to concentrate entirely on choreography. ``The
public becomes performers too. The whole idea is to include
everyone in the fun. It's all about entertainment, it's a feast, a
big multicolored gateau, a mosaic. That's why I thought Arcimboldo
would be an appropriate title.''
</P>
<P>
   Best known as the 16th century painter who created bizarre
portraits using fruits and vegetables, Giuseppe Arcimboldo was also
Master of Ceremonies at the court of Rudolph II in Prague and, as
such, had the job of organizing banquets, tournaments, fireworks
displays and other assorted fun and games. Appropriately, after
``Arcimboldo 2000'' opened in The Hague in May, it traveled first
to Prague, then to Paris, and it ends its tour at the Edinburgh
Festival in September.
</P>
<P>
   It is the spirit of Arcimboldo, rather than his fruits and
vegetables, that sets the mood of the show, a potpourri of
sequences that include some pieces in the company's repertory and
others created for the occasion. To keep the tone festive, the
accompanying music is a cheerful medley of extracts from works by
Tchaikovsky, Steve Reich, Aare Merikanto, Morton Feldman, John
Cage, Bach, Schubert and others.
</P>
<P>
   Kylian has designed the spectacle to display the multiple
talents of the company. So five dancers have also created works:
Jorma Elo made the video recordings of spectators and performers
before the show; Karine Guizzo conceived and organized the
backstage mise-en-scene; and Johan Inger, Patrick Delcroix and Paul
Lightfoot created their own choreographies. Only 40 percent of the
first half of the evening is signed by Kylian, although most of the
second half is his.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the company's three troupes, which frequently tour
separately, are now in the same show and, for the finale, dance as
one ensemble: the 28 dancers of NDT1, the main troupe, founded in
1959: the 16 members of NDT2, formed in 1979 for dancers 17 to 22
(many graduate to NDT1); and the four ``seniors'' of NDT3, which
Kylian created in 1989 to allow them to keep dancing ``between 40
and death,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Kylian has a soft spot for NDT3 _ and not only because
it includes his German-born wife, Sabine Kupferberg. In fact,
``Arcimboldo 2000'' opens with Gerard Lemaitre, the 63-year-old
French dean of the company, who is soon joined by Kupferberg, 49,
David Krugel, 41, and Gioconda Barbuto, 43. They take their seats
at a table and, as other dancers spin around them, do a comic turn
spoofing the solemnity of dance auditions.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Way a Lone: To Somebody No Longer Here,'' a piece by
Kylian that was performed at last year's Lincoln Center Festival,
Lemaitre, Krugel and Kupferberg become contemporary clowns in a
clever interplay between dancers on screen and onstage. At the end
of the show, after all the dancers have performed a splashy finale
decked out in bright red costumes, it is again the NDT3 four who
complete the cycle by wiping off their makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``With NDT3, it's not about what they cannot do, but what they
can do better than the others,'' Kylian explained in an interview
before ``Arcimboldo 2000'' was presented at the Palais Garnier in
Paris this month. ``They can stand onstage and do nothing. Their
energies are very different. Many old dancers are still performing
around the world but they are pretending to be 30. I think they
should dance their age and experience.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that since the choreography was designed for each member
of NDT3, there was no question of a second cast. ``With the young,
I'm more like a teacher,'' he went on, ``and the work is less
linked to their personality. Young dancers injure themselves very
easily because they don't yet know how to handle their bodies. NDT3
has only four dancers but they know their bodies, their
limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the younger dancers provide much flair, as in Inger's
sequence, ``Modern Furies,'' where five women appear in leather
jackets, high heels and dark glasses as mafia molls, and Delcroix's
``Strange Animals,'' in which 18 dancers interact in green costumes
that give them the appearance of insects. As always with the
Nederlands Dans Theater, stunning costumes are very much part of
the show, in this case designed by Joke Visser and Yoshiki
Hishinuma, who began his career working with Issey Miyake.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview a year ago, Kylian said: ``Every piece should
give you something to take home with you.'' In this case, he said,
``Arcimboldo 2000'' is intended specifically as ``a present to our
public,'' a party from which the guests take home a gift. Indeed,
the choreographer has come up with a pun to explain what he is up
to: ``Yesterday is history, tomorrow is mystery, but today is a
gift; that is why we call it the present.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
