<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-LAWSUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUITS BROUGHT AGAINST 6 MANAGED CARE COMPANIES UNDER
RACKETEERING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Miss., Ill., Calif.)   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new batch of lawsuits accuses six big managed care companies
of misleading health plan members. The suits were filed Friday in
U.S. District Court in Miami, where a judge recently promised a
speedy decision in a similar suit against Humana Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Humana suit, the latest court actions accuse the
insurers _ Aetna, Cigna, Foundation Health Systems, Pacificare
Health Systems, Prudential Health Care and United Healthcare _ of
failing to disclose to plan members that they offered rewards to
doctors and other employees who denied payments for care and
limited hospital admissions.
</P>
<P>
   The suits also contend that the companies defrauded members in
violation of the federal antiracketeering law, which provides for
treble damages.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, who were involved in huge settlements in earlier
suits against tobacco companies, said they would seek to combine
dozens of suits against Humana and the six insurers in a single
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it would lead to a faster resolution to have
everything in one court,'' said Stephen Neuwirth, a partner of
David Boies of Armonk, N.Y. Boies was recently appointed as one of
two lead plaintiffs' lawyers in the Humana case. Richard F. Scruggs
of Mississippi is the other lead plaintiffs' lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Boyle, a lawyer for Humana, said the company did not want
the consolidation of the latest suits to slow down a ``fast track''
schedule that the judge had set, to consider a Humana motion for
dismissal. He contended that the suits were ``without legal merit''
and should be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court recently ruled, in a unanimous decision, that
an Illinois woman could not claim a breach of fiduciary duties,
under a federal pension and health care law, to sue her health
plan. While the high court did not address the disclosure issue,
Boyle said, the decision will be ``very very helpful to
defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, plaintiffs lawyers insisted that the Supreme
Court ruling did not apply to their suits.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation, a big California managed care company, ``will
contest the consolidation in Florida,'' a spokesman said. Industry
lawyers have contended that the companies have different products
and policies and should not be lumped together.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle said 11 suits against Humana had been consolidated at the
company's request. Judge Frederico Moreno set a July 7 deadline for
Humana to submit its dismissal motion and scheduled a hearing on it
Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge lets the case proceed, the plaintiffs must file
their arguments for seeking class-action status by Aug. 15 and
Humana must respond by Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides expect to add two more suits against
Humana, which were filed on behalf of doctors. Archie Lamb, a
plaintiffs' lawyer in Birmingham, Ala., said his group also wanted
to include suits by doctors against Aetna, Cigna, Foundation,
Pacificare, Prudential (now a unit of Aetna), and the Blue Cross of
California unit of Wellpoint Health Networks. Lawyers for the other
defendants declined to comment, saying they had not seen the new
suits, which only became available in Miami Monday. Neuwirth said
the Boies-Scruggs group would seek to have the cases consolidated
by the multidistrict panel of federal judges in late July.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Lane, a managed care analyst at Salmon Smith Barney,
said that 33 suits seeking class-action status had been filed
against insurers between Oct. 3 and May 25. Most were filed in
federal courts. None has been certified as a class action.
</P>
<P>
   The suits also argued that the managed care companies conspired
to adopt similar operating practices at industry meetings sponsored
by companies selling guidelines; by standard-setting and
accrediting groups; and trade groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
