A5606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-HNS &LR;      06-26 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Spadea, Serena Williams finally taste victory again
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ Over the past few years, Greg Rusedski and Tim
Henman have provided the natives with hope that the Wimbledon men's
trophy will one day return to Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the first day of the Wimbledon fortnight, that hope
was cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   American Vince Spadea, who brought a tour-record 21-match losing
streak into The Championships, upset the 14th-seeded Rusedski 6-3,
6-7 (5), 6-3, 6-7 (8), 9-7. The five-set marathon lasted nearly six
hours, included a two-hour rain delay and barely finished before
darkness set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was outrageous,'' Spadea said. ``I felt like I won the
match 16 times. It's been a rough year, a rough patch in my life in
tennis. I put things together. I competed well today. I'm a
fighter. We were like gladiators out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Spadea, who hadn't won a match since October, had to scratch and
claw for this one after Rusedski saved two match points in the
fourth-set tiebreak to force the fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski was a Wimbledon quarterfinalist in 1997 but lost in the
first round the following year before making it to the fourth round
last year. Spadea reached the second round for only the second time
in six attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Henman, with a pair of quarterfinal and two semifinal
appearances over the last four years, is now Great Britain's lone
hope. The eighth seed begins play today against Paradorn
Srichazphan of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, Serena Williams had a triumphant return
from a 2{-month layoff because of tendinitis in her left knee.
Looking as big and strong as when she won the U.S. Open last year,
but displaying a game that she called ``better'' than the one she
had in New York, Williams knocked off Sweden's Asa Carlsson 6-3,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is off right now,'' said Williams, when
asked which part of her game was lacking after such a layoff. ``I'm
in shape. I'm looking better. I'm more fit. I think for a normal
person, I would say physique.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams proved she wasn't a ``normal'' person when she won the
U.S. Open as the seventh seed last year. She is seeded eighth here
_ a drop that reflects the time off _ and said she is eager to get
her ranking up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel comfortable down here,'' Williams said. ``I'm
always itchy. I feel weird. It's just not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon could give her the boost she seeks. Although she has
played here only once _ a third-round loss in '98 _ Williams came
off the court exuberant Monday, convinced that grass is her best
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel free,'' Williams said. ``I can breathe freely. This is
really my surface. I play a fast game. I should be dominating
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a couple of long games Monday, she did dominate, needing
only 1 hour, 9 minutes to defeat Carlsson. Williams had her serve
broken only once, despite facing eight break points. She broke
Carlsson four times on four opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the knee that was injured before the Amelia
Island tournament in April held up fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK now,'' Williams said. ``It's not like, you know, 200
percent, but it's pretty far up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Big sister Venus Williams also had an easy opener, beating Czech
Kveta Hrdlickova 6-3, 6-1 in a match that lasted less than an hour.
Venus utilized her serve-and-volley, winning the point on about
half of her net approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me to serve-and-volley every point,'' Venus said.
``I have a good volley. I'm confident in my volleys. The only thing
I think that you have to worry about is getting passed, but the
person can't pass you every time. It's going to be difficult,
especially with my wingspan.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters feel they are better prepared than most players
simply because they have each other for practice partners, which
makes every workout seem like a tournament final.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is that we have these practices, because we
always are hitting with each other,'' Venus said. ``If anything, we
should be the most prepared for the next opponent or if we play
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters are in the same half of the draw and would not play
each other until the semifinals. Venus, however, would first have
to get past top-seeded Martina Hingis, whom she could meet in a
quarterfinal match.
</P>
<P>
   In other first-round matches, three-time defending champion Pete
Sampras had an easy time against Czech Jiri Vanek, winning 6-4,
6-4, 6-2 and extending his Wimbledon record to 47-1 dating to 1993,
including 32-1 on Centre Court. Hingis, who was upset in the first
round last year, made quick work of Spain's Angeles Montolio 6-1,
6-2, and unseeded Anna Kournikova weathered a rain delay to oust
No. 10 Sandrine Testud of France 7-5, 5-7, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
