<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-STAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOPPLE THE QUEEN! ENTHRONE YOURSELF ON A STAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Canada Journal) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ For Canadians tired of maple leaves or
airbrushed photos of the queen on their stamps, Canada Post
suggests the 21st-century alternative: Personalize your postage
with a photo of the new baby, the new graduate, the happy couple or
the loyal dog.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity stamps, the latest product for an ego-centered age, made
their debut in Canada on May 6, and the response has been
overwhelming. ``We are getting 400 to 500 orders a day,'' said Tim
McGurrin, spokesman for Canada Post, the state-run postal service.
``The buzz has tipped us off that we are really onto something
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at Calgary's main post office, sales clerks were handing
out photocopied order forms only one week after the national
launch. A clerk said apologetically, ``They only gave us 50
brochures, and they are gone already.''
</P>
<P>
   From Ottawa, McGurrin, who has ordered one sheet of stamps
featuring his own photo and one sheet featuring his 2-year-old
daughter, explained that people wanting to personalize their
postage needed only to fill out a form, mail in a photo and send
payment. (Order forms and instructions can also be downloaded from
the Canada Post Web site, www.canadapost.ca).
</P>
<P>
   Within about three weeks, applicants receive in the mail a sheet
of 25 self-sticking printed ``gilt frames,'' marked ``Canada'' and
``46'' _ for Canada's domestic letter rate. This comes with a
second sheet of 25 ``personalized self-adhesive photo stickers,''
or ``vignettes autocollantes'' in French. After sticking the frame
on the upper right hand side of an envelope, the letter writer
places the photo sticker in the center of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Each sheet costs $24.95 Canadian, plus tax, or more than double
the cost of a sheet of 25 normal domestic-rate stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada Post is ripping us off again,'' grumbled Dwayne Miner,
owner of Stampede City Stamps, a stamp shop next to the main post
office here. ``It costs a dollar, but you only get 46 cents of
postage. Who's going to pay a buck to mail a letter?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his grumbling, Miner confessed that he, too, had fallen
for Canada Post's latest promotion to milk money from collectors
and the public. He said that at a national stamp show in Winnipeg
in late April, where the personalized stamps were previewed by
collectors, he had joined an hourlong line to have stamps made of
``my beautiful self.'' Now he is ordering stamps of ``Simon _ he's
my buddy, a Bernese mountain dog.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Australia, Britain, Singapore and Switzerland
have started to offer customers the option of buying stamps with
their photo printed on attached tabs.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service, however, has no plans to allow
Americans to personalize their postage. Don Smeraldi, a Postal
Service spokesman, said in an interview, ``Having an individual on
a stamp would personalize it to the extent that we wouldn't have a
good return on printing stamps, because we print them in the
millions.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Canada is exploring more ways for people to express
their individuality with stamps. Along with the photo stamps,
Canada Post has issued five different greeting stickers that can be
placed in the gilt frames. These stickers, which include a heart, a
pen and the word ``Surprise,'' ``will allow customers to customize
their correspondence according to mood or message,'' said Micheline
Montreuil, Canada Post's director of stamp products.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Australia led the way in personalized postage tabs,
Canada Post goes one step further by creating a truly custom
stamp,'' reads the current issue of Canada Stamp Details, a Canada
Post publication for collectors. ``Canada Post holds the worldwide
patent for the double-sticker greeting stamp and is investigating
more possible uses for this creative offering.''
</P>
<P>
   In early July, Americans will be able to buy instant
personalized stamps when Canada Post sets up its traveling
personalized stamp printing machine at a major stamp show in
Anaheim, Calif. Collectors say that this essentially is a legal way
of printing money, since few American collectors will use their
stamps to mail letters from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   For collectors, personalized stamps pose a challenge because
variations could be as extensive as names in the telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   Charles J.G. Verge, president of the Royal Philatelic Society of
Canada, said, ``I think they're going to be more popular with the
general public than they'll be with collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his three daughters in college, he predicted more
orders: ``They're all graduating in the next three years, so I
imagine I'll do stamps of their graduation pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   McGurrin said Canada Post had also fielded a number of calls
from small businesses asking if they could order stamps with their
logo. His response: ``Absolutely! Anything within good taste is
pretty much going to be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid legal unpleasantness, customers signing ``picture
postage'' order forms must confirm that they have ``the necessary
copyright and consent permission'' for the images. In addition,
Ashton Potter Canada Inc., the Ontario printer that has started
printing the photo sheets, vows to reject all obscene, racially
biased or any other content deemed inappropriate ``for any
reason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
