<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FITTING TAXIS FOR WHEELCHAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City has started on a road that may lead to taxicabs
that are able to accommodate wheelchair users in their chairs. The
Taxi and Limousine Commissioner, Diane McGrath McKechnie, has
submitted a proposal requiring that the city's medallion taxi fleet
include such cabs, which are usually minivans modified to provide
ramps that fold down in the back or on the side.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Americans With Disabilities Act, the federal civil rights
law dealing with hotels and motels, trains and buses, airports and
public arenas, does not cover taxicabs. But at least 14 cities in
the United States and 7 in Canada have accessible cabs in
operation, according to research by the Eastern Paralyzed Veterans
Association. These cities include Chicago, San Francisco, Los
Angeles, Fort Lauderdale, Boston and Las Vegas. A number of them
enacted rules requiring these vehicles, almost all since the ADA
was signed by President George Bush in 1990.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Accessible taxis have been a goal of McKechnie's since she got
her job in 1996, according to Allan J. Fromberg, the Taxi and
Limousine Commission spokesman, but the industry has so far failed
to respond. Her proposal, scheduled for a hearing June 29, says
that effective July 1, 2001, all vehicles equipped to serve as
medallion cabs would have to be accessible, as would livery cabs,
black cars and limousines unless the dispatching companies elected
to arrange for equivalent service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston has 50 accessible cabs in its medallion fleet of 1,775,
and expects to get as many as 50 more by the end of the year. Mark
Cohen, the director of licensing for the Boston Police Department,
said that after seven years of accessible cabs there, it was still
a work in progress. The first batch of vans, for example, used side
ramps, and the vans were so low to the ground that they plowed
snow. One company that modified vans for wheelchair entry has gone
out of business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medallions for modified minivans cost less, to offset the cost
of the modifications and the higher cost of operation. The
operating life of the vans is also shorter, Cohen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The demand for use has not been so great as expected but, he
said, ``it was a good idea.'' The modified vans are travelers'
favorites, he said, because whole families with luggage, with or
without a wheelchair, can pile in at the airport. The vans can be
hailed on the street or called through a radio dispatcher of any
major cab company. ``I don't see how any city could get away
without having any,'' Cohen said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the consumer services commission oversees taxicab
regulations. Commissioner Caroline Orzac Shoenberger, a former New
Yorker, said her city was probably most like New York. Although
there is a great marketing potential for accessible cabs, she said,
``unfortunately, the cities have to mandate.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said that Chicago was asked for accessible taxis by the
Multiple Sclerosis Society in 1997 and she got the mayor to
allocate $15,000 for a pilot conversion process. She set up a
meeting but industry representatives said they should be able to
charge wheelchair passengers more because it took longer to get
them in and out of a cab. ``Not a good argument,'' Shoenberger
said, pointing out that loading and unloading strollers also took
extra time. She added that state discrimination law if not federal
law would look unkindly on a differential.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Chicago law was enacted in 1997 and the first accessible cabs,
which are side-loading, were on the streets in 1998. If a company
has 15 or more medallions, it must have one or more accessible
cabs, she said. There are 31 or 32 on the streets now; there will
be 35 by September and 8 more by the end of the year. To get one, a
customer should call the radio dispatcher of a major company.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shoenberger said that her last case as a lawyer in private
practice was a mother with a wheelchair child who had to take on an
entire suburban school system, and that this probably influenced
her views. ``Transportation should not be a barrier to people's
living fruitful lives,'' she said. ``If tourists know they aren't
going to be stranded at the airport or the museum, they are going
to come. Everyone gains.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Lauderdale, Rick Bannister oversees the wheelchair
division of the Yellow Cab Co., where 21 out of 541 Yellow Cabs
have been modified, with rear ramps. The vans can carry a
wheelchair user, four other passengers and the driver.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such taxis have been in existence for nine years, and there has
been a slow but steady increase in use. On the weekends, Bannister
said, they probably do 25 trips a day between the airport and the
cruise-ship pier. The fare to the Fort Lauderdale pier is $10, and
to the Port of Miami $55. The company got into this area because
the owner, Jessie Gaddis, had a friend who used a wheelchair and
had trouble getting a cab. Yellow Cab: (954) 565-2800. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas has 14 cab companies, according to Ken Smith, an
investigator for the Las Vegas Taxicab Authority, and there are 27
accessible cabs in operation, two to a company except for one new
operator. Las Vegas cabs are dispatched by radio, and a call to any
company should bring an accessible cab. The city has had accessible
vans for at least 10 years, Smith believes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, companies were required in 1996 to see that 2
percent of their fleets were accessible cabs. Doris Smith, a senior
investigator in the Los Angeles City Department of Transportation,
said that 127 were now in service with 10 major companies, all
available on call to the dispatcher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iram Rashada, assistant general manager of Los Angeles Checker
Cabs, (800) 300-5007, said that 24 of the company's 290 taxis were
accessible and have been in the fleet for three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, according to Nathan Dwiri, president and general
manager of the Yellow Cab cooperative there, has authorized 75
accessible cabs, but only 55 are in service. Yellow Cab, (415)
626-2345, has 30 of these ``ramp taxis,'' Dwiri said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York livery company, Symphony Transportation, has five
Chrysler minivans with side ramps. John Acierno, the head of the
overall company, Executive Transportation, said it was a joint
project begun in the last year with Easter Seals, whose mission is
helping people with disabilities. Easter Seals donated the
minivans, each adapted to carry two wheelchairs plus three
passengers and a driver, and provided driver training. The company
operates the vans, does licensing, call-taking, billing and the
like. The reservation number is (800) 253-1443. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it by advance arrangement,'' Acierno said, ``and some on
an as-soon-as-possible basis. Our goal is to provide an instant
response.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said that Executive Transportation would like to see the
project expand, and that through his board position in the Black
Car Industry Association was talking about how to go further.
``It's time to get up to critical mass,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The taxi and limousine commissioner, McKechnie, said: ``The goal
is to see a reasonable number of taxicabs and livery vehicles
accessible. It was time to move the process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
