<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S OPPOSITION IS ELATED AS ELECTION LOOKS TIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Supporters of the opposition party cheered
and danced early Tuesday as election results from the weekend's
parliamentary elections showed the fledgling party running neck and
neck with the governing party that has dominated Zimbabwe for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   The final result was unclear, but with about half the vote in
from counting stations across the country, tallies quickly
established that the nine-month-old party had become a powerful
opposition force in Zimbabwe _ a feat considered unimaginable just
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For years, President Robert Mugabe's governing party has
controlled all but three seats in parliament. But the new
opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change, easily
surpassed that figure, quickly winning 31 seats and claiming
lopsided victories in urban districts, where voters have been
squeezed by skyrocketing inflation and deepening unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party carried 32 mostly rural districts, where the
party's support has traditionally been strongest. Political
analysts predicted that the votes would continue to split along
urban and rural lines for the 120 parliamentary seats up for
election as the counting continued through the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials continued to insist that they would win a
majority of seats in the end, but they publicly acknowledged that
for the first time they had misjudged the mood and needs of people
in the cities.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe and party officials had campaigned heavily on the pledge
that they would make good on their promise to redistribute fertile
land, which is still mostly owned by the tiny white minority here.
They supported the invasions of hundreds of white-owned farms by
black squatters and were widely blamed for condoning a campaign of
intimidation and violence that left at least 26 people dead, most
of them opposition supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But the message clearly had little appeal for urban voters, who
had grown weary of fuel shortages, corruption and unfulfilled
promises. And here in the capital and in the second-largest city,
Bulawayo, people flocked in droves to the new party that promised
an improved economy and clean government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not being swept away by these elections, but we're
getting a kind of wake-up call,'' said Jonathan Moyo, the spokesman
for the governing party, the Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front, known as ZANU-PF. ``They're doing better
than I expected them to. It's a reality check for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first results, which had been expected on Monday afternoon,
trickled in slowly last night. In a nation where elections have
been characterized by voter apathy in recent years, about 60
percent of the more than 5.8 million registered voters cast ballots
during the polls on Saturday and Sunday and election officials were
quickly overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation waited anxiously, the officials spent hours
checking ballot boxes and ballot slips for any evidence of
tampering or election rigging. Angry young supporters of the
opposition, who waited eagerly for the results outside the office
building of the election directorate here, grumbled suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, observers from the European Union had condemned
Mugabe's party, accusing it of supporting the violence and
intimidation that marred the run up to this weekend's vote. And on
Monday, the government quickly deployed police officers around the
country to prevent any outbreaks of violence and urged the public
to remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my appeal that the Zimbabweans continue to be calm,
peaceful as they have displayed during the voting period,'' said
Augustine Chihuri, the national police chief. ``Those ones who win
must win gracefully and not target the losers. Those ones who lose
must accept losing with honor so that they don't spark problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the night reportedly passed peacefully with most
people glued to their television sets and radios, waiting nervously
for the votes to come in. It was the first time since blacks won
majority rule in 1980 that an opposition party had challenged the
governing party in every single district.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the first time in nearly two decades that many voters
had gone to sleep without knowing for sure what the morning's
election result would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long night, a long wait,'' said Ian Makone,
an official in the MDC's election directorate. ``I think a pattern
is emerging. We're going to be very strong in the urban areas. But
it's going to be a nail-biting experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
