<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SKIMPY-FASHION-ART-71     06-26 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIMPY-FASHION-ART-715(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE OF LESS: SCANTIER CLOTHING CATCHING ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN and CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Noontime in Manhattan, and the strap-style T-shirt
brigade was out.
</P>
<P>
   Mali Heled, a 26-year-old doctoral candidate at Cambridge
University in England, was taking a break outside a sandwich shop
across from the New York Public Library, where she had spent the
morning reading James Joyce manuscripts. She wore a flimsy fuchsia
skirt and the sort of white ribbed undershirt one associates with
Arnold Schwarzenegger changing a tire on his Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the library I wear a jean jacket because I like to be a
little more covered,'' Heled said, surveying the many women passing
by in similarly skimpy attire, often with bra straps showing. ``But
out here I think it's perfectly OK to dress like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Bryant Park near Times Square, Nicola Thompson,
25, was catching some sun before heading back to work. Thompson, a
paralegal at a Midtown law firm, was wearing a rose-print dress
with spaghetti straps _ a style that, until the advent of more
casual business dress codes, one might have seen in SoHo on a
weekend but rarely on a Tuesday in Midtown. Thompson said she has
no hesitation about wearing this kind of dress to work, though she
usually covers it with a sweater. ``It's a young law firm _ my boss
is only 33,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of women interviewed on the street, Thompson
suggested that more liberal office dress policies aren't the only
force behind an explosion of tank tops, bare-toe high heels, clingy
skirts and midriff-revealing knits. ``I think American women are
much more comfortable now showing more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It may not come as news to people in the fashion industry, or
even to women who take their cues about modesty and skirt lengths
from television programs like ``Sex and the City,'' but there has
been a conspicuous change in the landscape in the past two summers.
It wasn't all that long ago that such seemingly chaste styles as
sleeveless dresses and open-toe shoes were verboten in most
offices. And as for going without stockings _ that, too, was
something you didn't see except around the offices of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   But like mushrooms after a rain, all these styles are popping up
with a persistence and an elan that suggest a change in the way
women view themselves and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, say retailers and social observers, the attitude
isn't confined to trendy urbanites and runway-ready 20-somethings.
Banana Republic says a stretchy strap-style tank top (with built-in
breast support) is among its most popular looks. Ellen Tracy, a
label for midlevel career women, says its button-down work shirt
cropped to show off the bellybutton is a hit. And the surge of
bare-it fashion is also attracting older women and heavier women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a decided shift to a sexy, glamorous, almost
trashy interpretation of fashion,'' said Connie Marsh, trend and
design manager for Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., whose 860 stores serve
middle-income people across the country. ``Performing best are more
bare items like very plunging necklines on T-shirts or halter
tops.''
</P>
<P>
   The appetite for styles that hug the figure or reveal much of it
is causing a shift in the retail world. American Eagle Outfitters
and Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, whose baggy silhouettes made them the cool
shops for teen-agers of the mid-1990s, have suffered a slowdown.
But banner comebacks are being reported at Guess, which grew to
prominence in the 1980s showcasing the curvaceous bodies of Anna
Nicole Smith and Claudia Schiffer in revealing tops and skintight
jeans, and at the Limited, with its streetwise style.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that sexy was this big was the 1970s, but fashion
historians see a big difference between the satin-blouse braless
look popular in the disco era and the styles today. ``Then that
kind of outfit was for partying,'' said Susan Bordo, a humanities
professor at the University of Kentucky who has written several
books on body image. ``Now it has a place in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordo said that popular culture, in particular ``Ally McBeal''
and ``Sex and the City,'' have contributed to the change. ``A
decade ago, the feminist ideal was to have a great career and a
family,'' she said. ``Now the ideal is to have a great career and
dress like a sex kitten, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But in this new era, dressing like a sex kitten does not
necessarily mean wanting to be one. States of public undress do not
connote licentiousness as much as a decade ago. ``The trend toward
skimpiness does not seem to be correlated to sexual liberation the
way it was in the 1960s and '70s,'' said Valerie Steele, a
historian at the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing's former signals are disappearing. ``Fashion has lost
its meaning as a signifier,'' said Simon Doonan, the creative
director of Barneys New York. ``Someone can be showing lots of leg
_ it doesn't mean they are a lap dancer, the same way having a
pierced body part no longer means you are an interesting person.
Everyone is doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, dressing sexily is as much about power and entitlement
as about attracting mates. Younger women are moving the
unapologetically sexy look into even the most buttoned-down
corporate suites. Mati Bonetti, 27, recently left a marketing job
at the tobacco giant Philip Morris, where she felt totally at home
wearing capri pants, sheer skirts and mules. Asked what she would
say to a supervisor who questioned her attire, Bonetti, who is
about to start a job at MTV, replied, ``I'd say, `Well, I don't
think I am insulting you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bonetti, who has a graduate business degree from Columbia
University, added, ``You know, a lot of women say to themselves: `I
have an MBA under my belt. I work hard. I don't have to prove
anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   At a big accounting firm, a 22-year-old recruit (who asked not
to be named for fear of repercussions) has been defying the dress
code by wearing sleeveless sweaters, T-shirts in clingy polyester
and knee-high boots. ``I know it might not be 100 percent
appropriate,'' she confessed, ``but I fault those who would judge
me on what I wear.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger generation's sense that it is fine to look sexy _
very much cultivated by the fashion magazines and retailers _ has
spread to older women and heavier women, who in previous fashion
cycles shied from provocative clothing. ``I never hear shoppers
saying, `This is too young for me,' the way they did a decade
ago,'' said Joe Denofrio, senior vice president of Macy's East.
``Though sometimes I wish we did.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kirna Zabete, a chic SoHo boutique, Beth Shepherd, a
co-owner, said that not long ago a personal shopper requested ``a
little nothing skirt'' for a client, a woman in her late 50s.
Shepherd said she asked if the woman planned to wear a layer under
the see-through garment, and the shopper retorted, ``She doesn't
wear slips.''
</P>
<P>
   And at Lane Bryant, cotton stretch tube tops in bold colors and
Hawaiian prints are emerging as favorites among customers who wear
large sizes. ``They are blowing out the door not only in our small
sizes, 14 and 16,'' said Chris Hansen, the executive vice president
for marketing, ``but across the board, all the way up to sizes 26
and 28.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bryant applauds the change among its customers. ``It has
taken us four years to move the fashion offering and the confidence
of our shopper to the point where she feels she is deserving of the
same looks as a size 4,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Alderfer, a high school student and an aspiring actress
in Manhattan, described her own shift in size 16 clothes. ``I've
recently gotten into halter tops, because they show off my back,''
she said. ``I've only recently become more comfortable with my body
type, but the reaction is pretty positive. People say, `Why not?'''
</P>
<P>
   If the fashion cognoscenti are right, the desire to undress will
not end with hot weather. Style watchers expect an equally
provocative fall. Handkerchief halter tops in cashmere and alpaca
have been ordered by stores in record numbers. Also hot are suede
boots with stiletto heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``For fall and spring 2001, we think sexy will be even bigger,''
said Denofrio of Macy's. ``This fall, leather will be the uniform,
and you are going to see it for men's as well. Forget baggy pants.
The form-fitting rib-neck, stretch pants and leather blazer _ that
will be the uniform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
