<HEADLINE>
BOEING WINS 777-X ORDER FROM EVA AIRWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. notched an important
billion-dollar-plus win Monday for its new 777-X program, and
snatched a potential order away from rival Airbus Industrie in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's EVA Airways Corp., the country's second largest
airline, announced it will be one of the launch customers for the
ultra-long-range Boeing jets known as the 777-300X and 777-200X.
The carrier will buy a mix of 7 of the new jets for delivery
beginning in the fall of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was especially sweet for Boeing. Even though
EVA operates an all-Boeing fleet of 35 planes, the airline had
signaled it might buy new jets from Airbus for the first time to
meet its future long-rage transport needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the airline turned around,'' Seddik Belyamani, Boeing's
executive vice president of commercial airplane sales, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great win for us and a great endorsement of the 777
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus had been pushing hard to sell EVA on its its
ultra-long-range A340-500 and A340-600. EVA had even signed a
letter of intent to buy the Airbus jets, Seddik said.
</P>
<P>
   The A340-500 will compete with the 777-200X and the A340-600
will compete with the 777-300X. The Airbus jets are supposed to
enter service in 2002, a year before the Boeing jets. But Airbus
recently said the program is behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A firm order from EVA for the Airbus planes would have been a
big blow to Boeing, which lost an important bid last year to sell
Taiwan's state-controlled China Airlines a dozen 777s. Instead,
China Airlines signed a $1.8 billion deal for seven Airbus
A340-300s.
</P>
<P>
   EVA is the second customer to publicly announce a launch order
for the 777X planes.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Airlines, one of the launch customers for the original
777, said in April that it ordered eight of the 777-300X jets to
replace older 747s on international routes.
</P>
<P>
   EVA will buy four of the -300X models and three of the -200X
models.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing announced the launch of the two planes in February. They
are targeted for Asian airlines looking for 21st-century widebody
jets that have the range to fly more than 300 passengers non-stop
between Asia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The 301-seat 777-200X will be able to fly up to 10,100 miles
before refueling, and the 359-seat 777-300X will be able to fly up
to 8,314 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has landed around 30 firm orders for both planes worth
more than $5 billion, and has another 15 to 20 orders pending,
according to sources. But JAL and EVA are the only customers to
publicly announce launch orders so far.
</P>
<P>
   Belyamani said he expects three or four more more launch
customers to publicly announce orders before the end of the
Farnborough International air show, which will be held near London
in late July.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how much the EVA order is worth, since Boeing
has not yet published the list price for the 777-300X and 777-200X.
</P>
<P>
   The 777-300 has a list price from $167.5 million up to $192.5
million, depending on the configuration and customer options. The
777-200 has a list price from $150 million to $170 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since the the 777X planes will certainly be more expensive than
the current versions, the EVA order is probably worth more than $1
billion at list prices. But launch customers typically get big
discounts of as much as 25 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Belyamani would not say how much of a discount Boeing gave EVA.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are heavily negotiated,'' he said. ``They took
advantage of their launch-customer status. But it is still a
win-win situation ... We make money and they get a good deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
