<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ECUADOR-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOR PINS HOPES ON SHIFT TO DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that promises to make one of South America's
lesser-known tourist destinations more appealing to American
visitors, Ecuador, whose attractions include the Galapagos Islands,
spectacular volcanoes and Amazon jungle, is abandoning its
currency, the sucre, in favor of the dollar. Both currencies are in
use at the moment, but the transition to the dollar is expected to
be complete by September. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shift comes after the value of the sucre dropped from 6,200
to the dollar at the beginning of 1999 to 25,000 to the dollar in
January of this year, when dollarization was decreed. That plunge
in value made Ecuador probably the biggest bargain for visitors to
Latin America, a distinction it is likely to retain for the
foreseeable future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the drastic devaluation that occurred in the
year leading up to dollarization, the price of our packages was
reduced 15 to 20 percent,'' said Pablo Burbano, president of
Metropolitan Touring, a leading travel agency in Quito, the
Ecuadorean capital. ``The dollar goes a long way here, and even
though dollarization means things will get a little more expensive,
we are going to continue to be a cheap destination for the next few
years.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For American tourists, the new system simplifies typical tourist
transactions. ``Visitors are not going to have to worry anymore
about changing money or things like what the commission is on
traveler's checks compared to cash,'' said Maria Carmen Granizo,
president of the Ecuadorean Association of Tourism Companies, a
trade group. ``All they need to do is bring their dollars and use
them directly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador is not the first country in Latin America to adopt the
dollar as its national currency. Panama did so soon after gaining
its independence from Colombia in 1903, and Argentina in recent
years has maintained the peso at a one-to-one parity with the
dollar; the two currencies can be used almost interchangeably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in Ecuador, an Andean country of 12.5 million people
notorious for its political and economic volatility, the shift to
the dollar has proved controversial. Undertaken in hopes of
providing stability, the change had barely been announced when a
military coup overthrew President Jamil Mahuad. Dollarization
protests by Indian and labor groups continue, but there has been no
reported hostility toward American visitors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One consistent complaint of dollarization opponents, somewhat
odd coming from people who are used to calculating prices in
multiples of 10,000, is that the new system is too complicated and
hard to use. There has also been a spurt of inflation, as stores
and businesses round prices up to the nearest dollar, but that is
expected to abate soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, because we did not have a strong currency, we
were always having to change prices and our interest rates were
very high, which discouraged investors,'' said Rocio Vazquez,
minister of tourism and environment. ``Our prices have always been
competitive, but now we think we can also compete with the quality
of our product,'' he said, and attract, for example, more
international hotel chains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, however, that Ecuador's domestic tourist industry
will have to adjust. Most leading hotels were already billing
customers in dollars, based on the exchange rate of the day, to
protect themselves from currency fluctuations and thus are likely
to be unaffected. But for tour operators, the new system will
require more efficiency and foster greater competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the exchange rate has always been used as a
cushion against any unforeseen problems or costs,'' Granizo said.
``If the exchange rate was 15,000 today, you knew it was going to
be 18,000 tomorrow, so you were protected if, for instance, you had
to suddenly contract an extra bus at the last moment. But that
buffer has now disappeared.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another result of dollarization is that Ecuador is likely to
make a greater effort to draw American visitors to a country that
is only a four-hour flight from Miami. In the past, tourism efforts
have focused much more on Europe, to the extent that, according to
the Ecuadorean Embassy in Washington, Ecuador does not currently
even have a tourism information and promotion office in the United
States. But Ecuador's tour operators are planning what they call a
caravan to visit the United States later this year to promote
all-inclusive and other packages aimed at the American market. Of
the 508,000 tourists who visited Ecuador in 1999, down slightly
from 1998, barely one third were from the United States, and many
of those came to study Spanish in low-budget exchange programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the atmosphere of social agitation our country
experienced, our image abroad was hurt,'' Vazquez said. ``But to
the extent that the economy stabilizes as the dollarization plan is
implemented, we expect that the flows of visitors and of capital
will resume.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
