<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: please note that the Q&AMP;A sent last week and held is STILL
HELD. We expect to release those questions for use Sunday, July
9.) 
(For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Will there be events in England to celebrate the publication
of the fourth Harry Potter book? _ Ivan S. Moughton, St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. There will be quite a bit of fanfare for J.K. Rowling's new
book about the adventures of Harry Potter, the young wizard who has
generated such a frenzy among younger readers. However, precise
details of the events are surrounded by mystery. Even the title of
the book will not be officially revealed until July 8, the day of
publication. That is also when a three-day celebratory train tour
is scheduled to begin. Bloomsbury, the publisher of the book and
the organizer of the tour, will not reveal details about the
train's route and related events until later this week. A
spokeswoman suggests that you watch the company's Web site,
www.bloomsbury.com.
</P>
<P>
   The steam train, painted red and named the Hogwarts Express
(from the train that is featured in the Harry Potter books) will
leave London with J.K. Rowling on board and will travel between
London and Scotland on July 8, 9, and 10, with stops for
book-signing events along the way.
</P>
<P>
   On July 17, 18 and 19 the author will sign books in stores
around London and in Brighton, on the south coast of England. On
July 17, Rowling will make an appearance at Harrods between 9 and
11 a.m; tickets will be given to the first 750 people to enter the
store at door No. 5 in Hans Crescent. Between 1 and 2 p.m., Rowling
will read and autograph books at Waterstones in Piccadilly. Tickets
for this event are also limited and must be won in a competition at
the shop on July 8 between 8:30 a.m. and 11 p.m. Entrants, 17 years
old and under, must answer three Harry Potter-related questions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brest for Families
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in Brest with my wife and sons (14-year-old twins)
for a few days and would like information on activities that will
appeal to all of us. _ Larry M. Silverten, Hartford  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Brest, on Brittany's Atlantic coast, is one of the most
important military and commercial ports in France. While little
remains of the old city center, which was bombed during World War
II, there are many activities for tourists of all ages, most of
them related to Brest's status as a maritime hub.
</P>
<P>
   The recently expanded and renovated aquarium Oceanopolis, with
its three large pavilions recreating tropical, temperate and polar
ecosystems, is modeled on the Monterey Bay Aquarium in California.
The complex, about 10 minutes from the center of Brest, also houses
several restaurants with ocean views.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission is $13 (calculated at a
rate of 6.9 francs to the dollar); $10.15 for children 4 to 12
years old. Information: (33-2) 98.34.40.40; www.oceanopolis.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another place worth visiting is the Maritime Museum, housed in a
portion of the Chateau de Brest, a medieval fortress overlooking
the harbor. The museum focuses on the history of Brest and its
port, through maps, boat models, paintings and sculptures. A walk
between the chateau's towers and outer walls provides panoramic
views of the coast and the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is open daily from 10 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. Admission is
$4.20, $2.60 for children under 18. Information: (33-2)
98.22.12.39.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies offer boat tours around Brest. These vary from
one-day excursions to overnight cruises, and all are suitable for
families and English speakers. One option is aboard La Recouvrance,
a replica of an early 20th-century military schooner. The boat has
different itineraries of varying lengths. Information and
reservations: (33-2) 98.33.95.40.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame de Rumengol, a boat built in 1945 to transport sand,
has been renovated and converted into a tourist boat and was
classified a historic monument by the French government in 1990.
Smaller than La Recouvrance, this boat tours not only the coast and
harbor of Brest but also several nearby rivers, stopping at small
fishing ports along the way. Adults $26, children under 18, $15.20.
Information: (33-2) 98.20.06.58.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Van Gogh Packages
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are Boston hotels offering packages for the Van Gogh
exhibition at the Museum of Fine Arts? _ Randall Gorstein, Miami
</P>
<P>
   A. Many hotels are offering packages that include passes to
``Van Gogh: Face to Face,'' at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston.
The show, which starts today and runs through Sept. 24, includes
more than 60 paintings and drawings. It is likely to draw
formidable crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, which cost $18 on weekdays and $20 on weekends, are
valid only for a specific time and date. Most of the tickets
offered by the hotels are more flexible: Weekday passes can be used
all day Monday through Friday; weekend passes, are good all day on
Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel packages include one night's stay for two and two tickets
to the Van Gogh exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hotels offering packages are these: Boston Back Bay
Hilton, starting at $239, (800) 445-8667; Boston Harbor Hotel, from
$450 to $650, (800) 752-7077; Four Seasons Hotel Boston, $595 to
$810, (800) 332-3442; Gryphon House, $220 to $280, (617) 375-9003;
MidTown Hotel, $249, (617) 262-1000; Ritz-Carlton, $415, (800)
241-3333; the Regal Bostonian Hotel, $349, (617) 523-3600; Boston
