<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS TO REVIEW SPITTING ACCUSATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Mexican striker Luis Hernandez's tenure with the
Galaxy took another strange turn Saturday night when Kansas City
Wizards defender Matt McKeon alleged Hernandez spit on him
following the Wizards' 2-0 victory in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer officials said Monday they will review the
incident this afternoon and decide whether a suspension is in
order. The Galaxy visits defending MLS champion D.C. United on
Wednesday, then travels to meet Dallas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spit on me three times and then when (teammate) Chris
(Klein) came over, he spit on me again,'' McKeon told reporters
after match. ``You can't do that in this league. He has no respect
for the American players. There's no need for that. That's a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Wizards players claim they saw Hernandez spit on McKeon,
but Hernandez said afterward he couldn't remember spitting on anyo
``Words are one thing, but the spitting is another,'' K.C.
goalkeeper Tony Meola said. ``I hope we're in for more soccer from
him and less of that other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid remembers the incident differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at the tape; the only thing I can see is Klein
throwing an elbow at Luis as he stepped between Luis and Matt,''
Schmid said Monday by telephone. ``There was just a lot of
frustration involved. I don't know about the spitting. Luis said he
didn't spit.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Machnik, vice president of MLS game operations, has reviewed
videotape of the incident but could not confirm that Hernandez spit
on McKeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see players milling around, then the camera breaks away
and comes back after 15 or 20 seconds and players are still milling
around,'' said Machnik. ``Looking at it the first time, I didn't
see anything on that particular tape that showed Hernandez
spitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and McKeon were clearly arguing at close range.
Hernandez's head jerked forward, but there was no video evidence
that he spit on McKeon. However, he might have unintentionally spit
on McKeon while the two shouted at each other.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Machnik said the incident would be reviewed today
with MLS commissioner Don Garber and MLS executive vice president
Ivan Gazidis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's still an alleged spitting incident,'' said
Machnik. ``I imagine that we will interview several players and
gather information. Certainly, if it happened, the league would
consider it a very bad thing and a serious offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, MLS handed down the biggest fine and
suspension in league history. San Jose striker Khodadad Azizi was
suspended three games and fined $7,000 after shoving a referee.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, acquired last month from Tigres of the Mexican First
Division, has already been called a $4 million flop by an MLS
assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hernandez's arrival, the Galaxy was cruising along,
unbeaten at 5-0-5. After Saturday's loss, the team dropped to 2-4-2
with Hernandez and 7-4-7 overall. The two-time Mexican scoring
champion and league MVP is without a goal or assist and is not
making friends with his MLS rivals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
