<SLUG> BC-WARNACO-KLEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNACO FILES COUNTERSUIT AGAINST CALVIN KLEIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Warnaco Group Inc. answered a lawsuit by Calvin Klein
Inc. by filing its own set of unusually personal charges against
the designer and his namesake company Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Warnaco, which makes underwear and jeanswear under the Calvin
Klein label, is seeking nearly $1 billion in damages from Calvin
Klein Inc. and the designer. The complaints against the company
include defamation, breach of good faith and interference with its
business practices. Warnaco is also claiming Klein was essentially
absent at the helm of his company and that his lack of direction
hurt its jeanswear business. In addition, Warnaco is suing Klein
himself, claiming that he defamed the company with ``malicious
public statements.''
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement, Linda J. Wachner, Warnaco's chief
executive, said her company was forced into the suit to protect its
reputation and the Klein trademarks, which are a valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warnaco is acting on behalf of its shareholders to protect its
business interests as well as its co-ownership of the Calvin Klein
trademarks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As of 5 p.m. Monday, Calvin Klein said it had not seen the suit.
But in response to a statement by Warnaco, the company said,
``Warnaco's announcement is a thinly veiled attempt to divert
attention from the fact that Warnaco has been systematically
violating its agreements with Calvin Klein Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their business goals, the suit and countersuit have
taken on a personal tinge. Last month, Klein surprised the fashion
world by seeking to end his relationship with Warnaco, his largest
licensee, accounting for roughly 40 percent of Calvin Klein Inc.'s
estimated $160 million in annual design and royalty fees, the
overwhelming bulk of Calvin Klein's revenue. Klein accused Warnaco
and Wachner of willfully ``diluting'' the quality of his brand by
distributing merchandise in unauthorized channels like Costco and
B.J.'s Wholesale Club. He also accused Wachner of being
unprofessional and abusive.
</P>
<P>
   The timing could not have been worse for Wachner. The chief
executive was already under pressure from at least one irate
investor because Warnaco, which also makes underwear and clothing
under numerous names besides Calvin Klein's, had repeatedly missed
earnings estimates, and its stock has been in decline for almost a
year. The Klein suit pushed down the stock to a new low of under $7
a share, though it gained 18.75 cents Monday to close at $7.1875.
Soon after the suit, one of the company's biggest shareholders sent
a scathing letter to Warnaco's board saying that Wachner was to
blame for the company's problems.
</P>
<P>
   To make his case, Klein appeared on Larry King Live soon after
filing his suit and criticized Wachner and her company.
</P>
<P>
   Wachner filed a motion to have the Klein suit dismissed, but has
been biding her time for a response until filing the countersuit
with the U.S. District Court in the Southern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Warnaco complaint has two parts. In the first part, Warnaco
asserts its right to distribute products in any venue that has
products consistent with ``the reputation, image and prestige'' of
the Calvin Klein brand and insists that the warehouse clubs meet
these criteria because they ``showcase some of the world's most
prestigious brands.'' The lawsuit includes copies of Costco Web
pages showing items from such luxury brands as Coach, Prada, Gucci
and Baccarat.
</P>
<P>
   In part two of the suit, Warnaco accuses Klein of using the law
suit to ``wrest control of the lucrative Calvin Klein trademarks''
to make the company more attractive to prospective acquirers. Last
October, Klein and his long-time partner, Barry Schwartz, engaged
the investment firm of Lazard Freres to find a buyer for their
private company. Though several companies perused the books _
including Tommy Hilfiger Inc., Liz Claiborne and Warnaco _ none
were apparently willing to meet Klein's minimum asking price, said
to be $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Warnaco also accuses Klein of a ``vicious public relations
campaign'' to regain control of the licenses. On Larry King Live,
he told a seemingly surprised host that the quality of Calvin Klein
jeanswear now in stores had been ``compromised'' and much of the
merchandise was ``not up to standards.'' The Warnaco suit calls
these statements ``deliberately false and malicious'' and
identified them as among the sources of their trade libel claim.
</P>
<P>
   The apparel manufacturer further alleges that these statements
have already hurt its business, most specifically by scuttling a
contract to produce almost $400,000 of Calvin Klein jeanswear
business for a Canadian retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most curious of all, Warnaco accuses Klein of abandoning
his responsibility to design new jeans. `` Klein apparently no
longer has any personal involvement in the design of the products
that bear his name,'' the Warnaco suit states. ``Indeed, since
September 1999, Klein has not attended a single regularly scheduled
design meeting. Instead, he has surrendered his responsibilities to
a constantly changing cadre of low-level inexperienced designers.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Klein denied the charges. ``Calvin Klein
actively sets the design philosophy and direction and has an
accomplished design team in tune with that philosophy to execute on
the direction,'' the company spokesman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is not expected to help Warnaco's standing with
investors in the short run. ``In the near term, it is going to be a
distraction,'' said Harvey Robinson, an apparel analyst with the
Baltimore-based Chapman Co. ``It will not help the stock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
