u i BC-WORLD-BANK-CHINA-NYT &LR;      06-26 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SCOLDS WORLD BANK FOR APPROVING FUNDS FOR TIBET FARMERS'
RELOCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. SANGER AND JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a scathing internal assessment, a World Bank
inquiry has found that the bank violated its rules when it approved
a Chinese antipoverty plan that would have involved relocating
58,000 farmers on the edge of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The project raised a storm of protest last year from
environmental and human rights groups. Those groups contended that
the bank was aiding China's effort to dilute the minority Tibetan
population, which the Communist leadership has long regarded as a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bank plan, $40 million would be spent to relocate some
of China's poorest farmers to more fertile land, outside Tibet's
boundaries. A result would be to put ethnic Han Chinese farmers
into Qinghai, territory that Tibetans consider part of their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, the exiled spiritual leader of Tibet who was
born in the resettlement region, met President Clinton last week.
After the meeting, he said that the bank initiative ``would be a
source of more problems'' and that the project should not proceed
for the present.
</P>
<P>
   But the arguments over the project have quickly expanded beyond
questions of Tibet, becoming a test of whether the World Bank is
sufficiently sensitive to the political and social ramifications of
some of its projects.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the project pitted James Wolfensohn, the
politically savvy president of the bank, against the Clinton
administration, which recently re-appointed him to his post while
declaring its opposition to the China project.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfensohn suspended a part of the project last year, referring
the dispute to an internal ``inspection panel,'' after the United
States, Germany and a few other nations charged that the entire
program had been mishandled within the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bank planned to release the result of its harshly-worded
report last week, but decided against releasing it at the last
moment. A copy of the 160-page document was provided Monday to The
New York Times by sources hostile to the project.
</P>
<P>
   The report refers repeatedly to ``confusion'' among the bank's
staff, which seemed unable to agree on what standards to use in
judging the project's effects. The report also describes a
``disturbingly wide range of divergent and, often, opposing views''
on how the bank should interpret its own policies on handling
environmental and social policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   It suggested, without quite saying, that the bank bent its rules
to accommodate China's leaders, who wanted to borrow millions of
dollars for the project interest-free under a program for
underdeveloped nations. The project was approved last year just
days before China's eligibility for those loans permanently expired
because of its rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that the huge bank has been accused
of ignoring its own rules to bend to the wishes of a major client.
Another internal report, more than a year ago, concluded that the
bank overlooked the corruption of former President Suharto's regime
in Indonesia, another major client of the international lender.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical element of the new report was its conclusion
that the bank never seriously considered alternative locations for
the farmers _ locations that would not raise the sensitive
political questions of whether the bank was helping China's leaders
dilute the concentration of Tibetans in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The board's report prompted a sharp response from Wolfensohn in
a private letter to members of the World Bank's board. He argued
that the bank's guidelines for assessing projects like this one are
not hard and fast. The inspection panel, he wrote, is trying to
``push the bank in the direction of a literal and mechanistic
interpretation of its rules.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton administration officials view the inspection
report as a vindication of their views, bank officials said the
inspection panel's heavy-handed criticism sounded similar to
complaints about the project registered repeatedly by private
charity and activist groups. ``The panel is out to change the bank
and this was a stalking horse,'' said one bank official, who asked
to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank board is scheduled to decide July 6 whether to
authorize a new, 15-month, $2 million study into the environmental
and ethnic impacts of the resettlement, exploring many of the
issues raised in the inspection panel's report.
</P>
<P>
   Peter L. Stephens, the bank's spokesman for Asia, said the panel
made several valid observations about oversights in the way the
bank handled the resettlement project. He said that bank officials
now agree that they should have classified the resettlement project
as requiring a higher level of environmental scrutiny than they did
originally. Bank officials also did an arguably poor job of
assessing the ethnic impact of the project, Stephens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were clearly areas in the surveys that did not give
confidence that the results were reliable,'' he said. `These were
judgment calls and they made some errors.`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
