<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TRUCKERS-HOURS27-COX     06-26 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKERS-HOURS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Government proposal changes 65-year old rules for truckers
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you think America owes much of its current
prosperity to industry's fabled ``just-in-time'' system of
flawlessly choreographed shippers, suppliers and stores, think
again, says Brent Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   He and other truckers say the nation's supply chain of
last-minute deliveries and minimal inventories _ touted by
economists as one of the nation's major productivity advances in
decades _ is actually built on a foundation of countless wasted
hours of waiting and unpaid labor by truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a waiting game,'' says Perkins, who was headed
for Kent, Wash., last week with his wife and driving partner,
Kathleen Perkins, and a load of carpet.
</P>
<P>
   They had just spent the night waiting with 20 other truckers in
a parking lot in Dalton, Ga., to pick up loads.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said he and his wife, team drivers for Kennesaw
Transportation Inc., also had waited 10 hours the previous day for
their trailer to be unloaded at Publix Super Markets' warehouse
near Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And while those hours of waiting generally don't cost Publix or
other shippers a penny, they do extract a heavy cost along
America's highways. About 755 deaths and almost 20,000 injuries per
year result from accidents involving fatigued truckers, researchers
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   They say truckers, who are paid by the mile, not by the hour,
routinely violate federal duty hour limits to make up for time lost
on waiting or loading and unloading.
</P>
<P>
   The recently minted Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration
hopes to force truckers and shippers to clean up their acts by
retooling the Transportation Department's 65-year-old ``hours of
service'' rules controlling how long truckers can work and drive
each day before resting.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's proposal, announced in April, will
be the subject of a public ``listening session'' at the Atlanta
South Truck Stop in Jackson on Thursday and Friday. The public has
until Oct. 30 to comment on the new regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would, among other things, put drivers' work and
rest periods on a 24-hour day to better fit human sleep cycles.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules also would do away with an abused system where
drivers currently record their work time in log books. Instead, the
logs would be replaced with onboard electronic recorders to track
when regional and long-haul drivers are actually driving.
</P>
<P>
   The feds hope the new rules will eliminate about 115 fatalities
and almost 3,000 injuries annually from fatigue-related truck
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules are a strong message from the federal
government that trucking companies ``have to reform their own
shop,'' says Gerald Donaldson, senior research director for the
insurance industry-supported Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety.
He says three-fourths of long-distance truckers violate the current
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a completely pervasive scofflaw culture out there,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed regulation already is losing some air; critics
from both industry and highway safety groups have knifed about half
of the proposal's tires.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted earlier this month to block funding to
implement the new regulations, but the issue will come up again
when a conference committee considers the House and Senate versions
of the appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   Safety advocates praise the proposed regulation's call for
electronic monitoring. But they also say the proposal is flawed by
ignoring its own fatigue research. The new rules would allow
truckers to drive 12 hours without a break _ two hours longer than
the current rules allow _ despite research showing the risk of a
fatigue-related crash rises dramatically after 10 hours of driving.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Izer knows well what happens when drivers push too long.
</P>
<P>
   Her 17-year-old son and three friends were run over and killed
in 1993 by a truck driver who apparently had fallen asleep behind
the wheel after working illegally long hours and keeping a
fraudulent log book. She founded Parents Against Tired Truckers in
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatigue is the No. 1 problem in the industry,'' she says. But
it's an under-reported cause of truck-car collisions , she adds,
because truck drivers are far more likely than other drivers to
survive to tell their stories.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, who plans to speak at the hearing this week in Georgia,
says he doesn't see how the proposed regulations will solve the
fatigue problem.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the truck isn't moving, he says, the ``black boxes''
to monitor drivers won't be able to distinguish when drivers are
resting or when they're still working, but not driving, such as
loading their trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he says, the new rules would cut his and his wife's
incomes by thousands of dollars per month and often strand them far
from home during mandatory two-day rest periods each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to shut down a lot of trucks,'' he says,
when drivers are forced to take longer rest breaks each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's going to affect is drawing people into the industry.
Can they make as much money as they made before?'' asks Andrew
Flanagan, vice president of Kennesaw.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which employs 120 mostly husband-wife teams to
shuttle carpet and produce between the West Coast and Georgia in
refrigerated trucks, also would have to buy more trucks, hire more
drivers and raise its rates if the proposed regulations take
effect, he says.
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service is likewise concerned it would risk
violating the proposed rules during the Christmas rush, when its
delivery drivers routinely work overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody that has a higher commitment to safety than
us,'' says Norman Black, a UPS spokesman. ``(But) on first blush,
we are not seeing any flexibility here to recognize special
situations like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Trucking Associations says the federal proposal
would raise shipping costs by billions of dollars and put at least
100,000 more trucks and drivers _ already in short supply _ on the
road to replace those on rest breaks. The industry group estimates
that trucking companies already are short 80,000 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But safety advocates counter that the trucking companies' dire
predictions are overblown. The solution to the fatigue issue, heavy
driver turnover, and short capacity, they say, is sitting under the
industry's nose _ in clogged warehouse parking lots across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an incredible amount of productive time that's going
down the rat hole right now,'' says Donaldson, as truckers rush to
meet rigid delivery deadlines, then wait, and wait some more.
</P>
<P>
   Counting driving, waiting and loading time, he says, truck
drivers routinely work 3,000-4,000 hours a year vs. about 2,000 for
the typical office worker.
</P>
<P>
   About a fourth of that is wasted time ``sitting around waiting
for loads,'' he says. If unproductive time were reduced 25 percent,
no new trucks or drivers would be needed, he argues.
</P>
<P>
   Kennesaw's Perkins agrees that many drivers are working _ but
not logging _ many long days of waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Under current rules, truckers are allowed to drive up to 10
hours and spend up to 15 hours on duty before they must take an
8-hour break. They must take a 24-hour break after accumulating 60
hours on duty in seven days or 70 hours in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would require most drivers to be off 12 hours out
of 24. But most long-haul drivers now routinely work up to 125
hours a week if you count the time they spend waiting near a
warehouse to be called to a dock, says Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife make about $40,000 each per year. They haul
carpet out west from Georgia, and meat and produce from California
and Washington back to Georgia, making several round trips per
month.
</P>
<P>
   But in between each load, they must wait, half-sleeping and
half-listening to the radio until their truck is called to be
loaded or unloaded. Drivers often have to load trailers themselves
or hire ``lumpers'' to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be sitting up all day long monitoring that CB (radio),
then you drive all night long,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins is paid 40 cents a mile. He generally isn't paid for
roughly 40 hours per week he spends waiting, loading or unloading,
though much of that time is supposed to be logged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to find anybody that logs that waiting
time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers, especially owner-operators with truck loans to pay,
have little bargaining power compared to shippers like Wal-Mart or
Ford Motor Co. They are now the biggest dispensers of time in
so-called ``just in time'' distribution systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they are held hostage to shippers and receivers,''
says Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   One of trucker drivers' protections disappeared in 1962, he
explains, when federal regulations that tied truckers' working
hours to a 24-hour day were replaced with the current 10 hours on,
8 hours off schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Motor Carrier Act of 1980, which deregulated the
trucking industry, ``raised the ante for truckers to remain
competitive,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One casualty of deregulation that helped create today's marathon
truckers, he says, was the fading away of ``detention'' penalties
that shippers had to pay if they made truck drivers wait too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to bring the shippers explicitly under the
sanctions,'' he argues.
</P>
<P>
   The Truckload Carriers Association, a trade group for regional
and long-haul trucking firms, is trying to jawbone shippers into
cutting waiting times to two hours. Their surveys show their
drivers average more than 40 hours a week of waiting, loading and
unloading time.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed regulations likewise pressure trucking firms to
wring out inefficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   But ``it's out of carriers' hands. They can't do it by
themselves,'' says Robert Rothstein, general counsel for the
association. ``A lot of the time, they don't have the bargaining
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
