<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5626 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-IOWA-MASONCITY     06-26 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-IOWA-MASONCITY-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE IOWA PRAIRIE,   A REAL RIVER CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Editors: the 3rd take is a 350-word information box.) (For release Sunday, July 2) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prof. Harold Hill is back on Broadway, flashing $8 million worth
of smile and what Meredith Willson termed his calling card of a
suitcase. Nightly, the ``bang beat bell-ringin'
ever'-time-a-bull's-eye salesman'' dissolves into a lovesick puppy
as theatergoers wallow unashamedly in the old-time corn-pone
verities.
</P>
<P>
   Today's message: It isn't all make-believe. Out in the heart of
what Willson called the ``hailstone and sarsaparilla belt'' exists
the real River City. Its true name is Mason City, Iowa, and it is
indeed a place of marching bands, barbershop quartets and dandy ice
cream parlors. But it is more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Mason City, where Willson was born in 1902, has transformed his
boyhood home into a Victorian gem, put a collapsing Frank Lloyd
Wright house back together and plans to restore a Wright bank and
hotel. Beyond Wright, it boasts one of the nation's finest
collections of Prairie School architecture in an achingly
picturesque, if slightly too arboreal, setting. What's more, the
town's museum of antique trucks is nothing to sneeze at.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly charming attraction is the largest collection of
puppets made by Bil Baird, another native son. Local lore has it
that he gave the ``l'' in his first name to Willson.
</P>
<P>
   Mason City (population 29,040) is a few miles east of Interstate
35 about halfway between Minneapolis and Des Moines, and, truth to
tell, represents nothing so much as a failed dream. Mason City was
a big-thinking burg that figured it might be the next Chicago. As a
local history book published in 1911 put it, the then 60-year-old
dot in Iowa's rolling prairie amounted to ``the most important town
in a wide belt of the country extending from the Great Lakes to
where the Golden Sands of our Western Coast receive the waves of
the Great South Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time ``The Music Man'' is set, the early 1900s, Mason
City had five rail lines, four newspapers and four vaudeville
houses. Local banks had assets of over a million dollars and, in
the 1930s, would be paid the high compliment of a visit by John
Dillinger's gang, which robbed the largest of $52,000.
</P>
<P>
   This bountiful sense of significance explains why Wright and
people like Walter Burley Griffin working in the same direction _ a
genuinely new American architecture _ were invited to build things.
It was reflected in an emphatically middle-class appearance, from
picket fences to the ample, instrument-filled home of Willson's
youth.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the tranquil, timeless part of Mason City is now
surrounded by strip malls, Wal-Mart and its imitations and enough
fast-food joints to choke a teen-ager. There is no passenger train
to the town anymore, though there is talk of revving up the
putt-putt electric trolley that once ran to neighboring Clear Lake
(it has occasionally been run for shorter distances). But the rosy
vision of ``The Music Man'' resonates still in the footbridge
across Willow Creek (alas, many times modified) and the stately
oaks presiding over squeaky-clean streets.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that America turned out differently from the
dreamers' dreams. Chicago remained Chicago. But there are moments,
particularly around twilight, when time seems to have stalled in
Mason City, Iowa. It is almost possible to think it stopped
entirely in 1912, the year of ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is strongest in the summer when most visitors come:
it has been a generation since disease killed the elms, but green
canopies again blanket the streets, and cars with license plates
from any number of states prowl about. In July and August, Mason
City is hot and humid and feels like a destination.
</P>
<P>
   The Willson house, which was built in 1895, is suffused with
light from expansive windows, a few of them stained glass. People
have always wandered by to take a look, but five years ago it was
acquired by a local foundation and opened to the public from May
until October, otherwise by special appointment. What made our tour
special was the lively commentary of Caralee Miller, one of 30
docents.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Meredith's cradle, covered with the quilt his
grandmother made. We learn that at 14{ pounds he was the biggest
baby born in the county for many years afterward. We learn that his
mother, Rosalie, taught the town's first kindergarten class in her
home. We learn that Meredith, the third child, had a sister, Dixie,
who taught herself to play the harp in two weeks so she could give
a recital at the Congregational Church. She later joined the circus
and wrote a good book about her elephant-riding experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Instruments, many of which actually belonged to the family, are
scattered about. The calendar is stuck forever on January 1912.
There is evidence of Meredith's ultimate achievement on a
blackboard where he choreographed stage movements for ``The Music
Man,'' easily the most valuable thing in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Already you could sense the scale of his eventual
accomplishments: attending what became the Juilliard School of
Music, then becoming John Philip Sousa's principal flutist and
piccolo player without an audition, then first flutist for the New
York Philharmonic. Cracking wise about Mason City on the radio with
George Burns and Tallulah Bankhead. Writing ``May the Good Lord
Bless and Keep You,'' on the basis of his memories of the Sunday
school where his mother was superintendent of the younger grades.
When he died in 1984, he was buried in Mason City to the salute of
76 trombones.
</P>
<P>
   Miller mentioned some coincidences uncovered as local volunteers
put the house together as a period piece. One was that the roller
organ in the parlor can play only one song, ``Stars and Stripes
Forever.'' This was the song for which young Willson dreamed of
playing the piccolo solo in Sousa's celebrated band.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to the Willson house is Marjorie's Tea House, which
opened last August. It was the home of one of Willson's childhood
chums, Marjorie Sale, who now lives in Virginia and is crowding
100. It is a nice little restaurant, offering Greek stew, roast
pork and a light chicken sandwich on a typical day. The homemade
brownies with butterscotch sauce were scrumptious.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the beginning of Mason City's entrepreneurial
approach to its heritage. A $10 million Music Man Square is being
built next door to house theaters, a museum, rehearsal rooms and an
indoor streetscape modeled on ``The Music Man'' set. It is opening
gradually; the partly finished building was dedicated at the town's
annual band festival last month with a thousand-member barbershop
quartet and 76 used trombones dangling from the ceiling.
Ultimately, there will be a pool hall, soda fountain and
barbershop, among other working stores, all to be finished by 2002,
the centenary of Willson's birth. Rosemary, Willson's widow, now 78
and living in Southern California, is supplying $5 million and two
grand pianos.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   The Mason City Foundation is also remodeling a nearby mansion as
a bed-and-breakfast, and has its eye on an adjacent antiques mall
as a site for a working bakery in honor of the yeasty profession of
Willson's father.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the Willson house is the Mason City Public Library,
a large Georgian-style brick structure built in the 1940s and still
in use. Here dozens of handwritten notes from famous authors are
displayed, among them Washington Irving, Samuel Johnson and George
Bernard Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Next door is the Charles H. MacNider Art Museum, a truly
captivating place given by the philanthropic family who lived
there. One is struck by the view of the creek and woodland from
wide Tudor windows, but there is more. Lithographs by Grant Wood
and George Bellows are outstanding, and Thomas Hart Benton's
exuberant painting, ``Spring Tryout,'' depicting a young man trying
to ride a spirited horse, is of a stature one expects of New York
or Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But the most whimsical attraction is the collection of Bil
Baird's work from Broadway, the movies, television and two world's
fairs. Virtually all the puppets from his production of ``The
Wizard of Oz,'' performed in his Greenwich Village theater in the
early '70s, frolic in one case. Another displays the puppets used
in the film ``The Sound of Music.'' There are more than 400 puppets
in all, as well as the artist's sayings and scribblings. ``When I
make a puppet, I hang myself on straps like a lab specimen to make
sure the motions are right, as written,'' one quotation said.
Baird's Mason City roots are apparent from the display of the noted
puppeteer Tony Sarg's production of ``Rip Van Winkle'' at a local
theater during his teens. The show, he said, impelled him into the
world of marionettes.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor leaving the museum finds himself on a street that is
parallel to Willow Creek. This and the street across the creek are
called the Rock Glen-Rock Crest National Historic District and are
home to Prairie School houses designed by Wright's contemporaries.
Walter Burley Griffin designed five of the eight houses, including
one of craggy rock that local residents call The Castle and
architectural historians term one of the first modern houses of the
20th century. Griffin would shortly go on to design Australia's new
capital, Canberra, but his Mason City work is viewed as the Prairie
School's apotheosis.
</P>
<P>
   It is a short walk, one accompanied by woodpeckers and
songbirds, to another truly amazing building. Local people worked
for years to painstakingly restore and move a house designed by
Wright in 1908 to a nearby site. It was based on a famous plan for
a $5,000 house Wright published in Ladies' Home Journal. At its
lowest ebb, the Stockman House had become a dilapidated photo
studio. Its restoration is intriguing because it is half pure
Wright, including china patterns from Tokyo's Imperial Hotel. The
other half reflects the tastes of the relatively affluent doctor's
family who lived there. There is a bearskin rug and furniture from
the Arts and Crafts Movement.
</P>
<P>
   The docents here are wonderful too. We caught up with one of
them, Dr. Robert McCoy, a retired surgeon who lives in a nearby
Griffin house. He told how borings were taken to determine the
original paint, revealing hues considerably more autumnal than
anticipated. He pointed out that Wright designed storm windows to
be loaded from the inside, something not commonly done until after
World War II. Most important, he showed how the house, built around
a huge fireplace, flows organically. ``Every room is a
destination,'' McCoy said. ``No room is a passage to another
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of Wright should then head promptly for the corner of
Federal Avenue and State Street. Here are a somewhat deteriorated
bank, designed to resemble a vault, and a hotel, in the Prairie
School style, that have lapsed into different uses. But the
exteriors still clearly show Wright's intentions. The roof of the
hotel is being rebuilt with state money.
</P>
<P>
   There is more in Mason City. In the town's Central Park, the
newly restored monument to the 24 local sons who fell in the Civil
War, is impressive. So is the tiny Suzie Q Cafe, which has nine
stools (almost always filled), no tables and a fabulous pork
tenderloin sandwich. For dessert, there is Birdsall's, an
old-fashioned ice cream parlor that sells a swell ``turtle,'' a
concoction involving ice cream, hot fudge, caramel and nuts. I had
mine with black walnut ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   We wandered by Ransom's Pool Hall with its cigar store Indian,
but my 12-year-old son, Roy, was deemed too young to enter. The
click of balls sounded so enticing. Had that dratted Professor Hill
beat us to the punch?
</P>
<P>
   We then headed for the Van Horn Collection, which specializes in
trucks built before 1930, the year Lloyd Van Horn was born. There
are wonders in this place, including some 50 trucks. There is a
1920 General Motors circus truck with working calliope. A Saurer
beer truck from 1912. A John Deere manure spreader from 1914.
Antique gas pumps. The first snowmobile, made in 1917 from a Model
T, and an immense collection of antique cream separators. Plus free
coffee and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   There are even inspirational signs from an earlier time: ``If
you are a self starter, the boss won't have to be a crank.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a good time for a drive. A few miles northwest of the
airport, there is a spot in a cornfield visited by people from all
over the world. It was here that a plane carrying the
rock-'n'-rollers Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens and the Big Bopper
crashed in February 1959. Just about anyone can tell you how to get
there. The final half-mile is a hike across rich black loam. The
site is marked by a small monument, a stainless steel guitar and
records with each singer's name.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic flowers and handwritten notes were strewn about. There
was a plastic pair of glasses like those Buddy Holly wore. The wind
blew and in the distance trucks hummed along the Interstate.
Somebody had written words those ``by God stubborn'' Iowans in
``The Music Man'' would surely endorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray not for a lighter burden but a stronger back,'' the note
said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO SEE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Willson Boyhood Home, 314 South Pennsylvania Avenue;
(515) 423-3534. Open May to October, Friday, Saturday and Sunday 1
to 4 p.m.; other times by appointment; call (515) 424-0700.
Admission: $3; $1 children under 12; under 6 are free.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright Stockman House, 530 First Street NE; (515)
421-3666. Open June through Labor Day, Thursday to Saturday 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m. and Sunday 1 to 5 p.m. (same hours weekends Labor Day
through October). Admission: $3; $1 children under 11; under 6
free.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Horn Collection, a museum of vintage and antique trucks,
is two miles north of town on Highway 65, at 21220 Orchid Avenue;
(515) 423-0550. Open daily May 25 to Sept. 22, Monday to Saturday 9
a.m. to 4 p.m., Sunday 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission: $5; $1.50
children under 12; under 6 free.
</P>
<P>
   The Charles H. MacNider Art Museum, 303 Second Street SE, (515)
421-3666, has a collection of American works and more than 400 Bil
Baird puppets. Open Tuesday and Thursday 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.;
Wednesday, Friday and Saturday 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sunday 1 to 5 p.m.
Closed Mondays and holidays. Free, but contributions appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE TO EAT  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie's Tea House, 320 South Pennsylvania Avenue; (515)
421-8066. Entrees average $7 to $8.
</P>
<P>
   Suzie Q Cafe, 14 Second Street; (515) 423-5021. Pork tenderloin
sandwich with fries $4; omelet with cheese $3.05.
</P>
<P>
   Birdsall's Ice Cream, 518 North Federal Avenue; (515) 423-5365.
Open daily. Turtle sundaes: $1.85, $2.25, $2.65 and $3.90. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PLACES TO STAY  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Convention and Visitors Bureau can help with lodgings at
(515) 423-5724 or (800) 423-5724.
</P>
<P>
   A charming place to stay is Blue Belle Inn in St. Ansgar at 513
West Fourth Street; (515) 736-2225. This bed-and-breakfast 30 miles
from Mason City has five rooms in a Victorian house painted
periwinkle blue, rose and mauve; $65 to $140. A typical breakfast
is apple streusel bread pudding with hot rum sauce and sausage.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Clear Lake, which has a lovely glacial lake,
lodgings include motels and B &AMP; Bs. Information: (800) 285-5338.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
