<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-ART-NY     06-26 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS A DEAL TO DIVIDE GROWING BUDGET SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton raised his projection of the
federal budget surplus Monday by nearly $1.3 trillion for the next
decade, putting a breathtaking sum of new money on the table as the
two parties and their presidential candidates battle over tax cuts,
spending and how to prepare for the nation's long-term challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we use these surpluses in this moment of prosperity will
determine America's future for decades to come,'' Clinton told
reporters in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The new estimate brought the total surplus projection to just
under $4.2 trillion for 2001 through 2010, including $2.3 billion
from the Social Security system and almost $1.9 trillion from
general tax receipts. Seeking to frame the debate over how the
money should be used, Clinton immediately proposed a deal to divide
a portion of the windfall with the Republican majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would agree to a Republican proposal to cut
taxes for married couples by roughly $250 billion over 10 years if
the Republicans would go along with his $253 billion proposal to
add prescription drug coverage to the Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   In setting out his budget framework, Clinton also stressed that
he would put the government on a path to eliminate the $3.5
trillion national debt by 2012, a year ahead of his previous
schedule, and to use a portion of the non-Social Security surplus
to help extend the solvency of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction to Clinton's proposed deal from the two top
Republican leaders, Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois and Sen.
Trent Lott of Mississippi, fell somewhere between skeptical and
dismissive. And despite Clinton's desire to bring prescription drug
coverage to Medicare on his terms before leaving office in seven
months, it was unclear whether the two sides would even be able to
negotiate during an election season in which they are eager to
highlight their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Clinton's offer suggested, the surplus, if it
materializes, is big enough to give both parties much of what they
want, and its sheer size has left Democrats and Republicans alike
struggling to get a handle on the politics of potential plenty.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several years, divided government has led to
gridlock on tax cuts and major new spending initiatives. The latest
round of surplus numbers _ which are likely to be followed within
days or weeks by a similar set of new projections from the
Congressional Budget Office _ will only raise the stakes in the
election, with both sides asserting that they have a more prudent
plan for making the most of the fiscal bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign said the new figures
vindicated his contention that the nation can afford the large tax
cut he has proposed and still have money to create private
investment accounts within Social Security, improve education and
health care, build a national missile defense system and reduce the
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's campaign said the new figures
highlighted the benefits of fiscal responsibility and the contrast
between Gore's emphasis on shoring up Social Security and Medicare
and Bush's push for a tax cut that would give most of its benefits
to the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The new surplus projections are to some extent subject to
changes in the economy, and any nasty economic surprise could dim
the chances of the surpluses materializing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged as much Monday. He said it would be a
mistake to allocate all of the projected surplus at this point, and
he proposed a $500 billion ``reserve fund'' that would be held
aside until the fiscal situation becomes clearer and voters send a
message about what they want to do with the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The projections could be wrong,'' Clinton said. ``They could
be right. That's why we shouldn't spend it all now. And moreover,
we're having a debate in which the two candidates have very
different notions about what should be done with this moment of
prosperity, and the American people ought to have some say in
this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton said, the nation could not be ``blind
to the fact that we have an enormous opportunity here.''
</P>
<P>
   The two parties have already agreed that the Social Security
surplus should go only to reducing the national debt or shoring up
the retirement system to help it weather the aging of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the gain in the numbers released Monday was in the
non-Social Security portion of the budget, bringing to almost $1.9
trillion, from $746 billion under the administration's old
calculations, the pot of money that is up for grabs over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said the surplus projection was driven up by a
combination of the economy's current strength and an expectation
that at least some of the improvement in the economy will be long
lasting.
</P>
<P>
   Since late last year, they said, the economy has performed
substantially better than anticipated. Because the economy is
bigger now than previously foreseen, it would generate
larger-than-anticipated tax revenues even if economic growth from
this point on did not exceed the rates that the White House had
assumed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House's Office of Management and Budget also
revised upward its economic growth assumptions, reflecting a
general consensus among economists that the United States is
capable of higher rates of noninflationary growth than previously
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 10 years covered by the projection, the administration
is now assuming average economic growth of 3 percent a year, up
from 2.7 percent under its previous budget projection, made in
February. Many economists think the nation's potential
noninflationary growth rate is actually closer to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the total increase of $1.275 trillion in the 10-year surplus
projection, $984 billion comes from the improved economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   The projection also includes $375 billion in additional revenue
over the decade from technical changes in the estimates of tax
receipts (the increases are offset by an $84 billion reduction in
projected receipts stemming from legislation passed so far this
year).
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest of the technical changes is an upward revision
in personal income tax revenues, in part from a surge in capital
gains that taxpayers are reaping from stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In offering to swap a tax cut for his prescription drug plan,
Clinton was to some extent insulating Gore and Democrats in
Congress from criticism by Republicans, who accuse them of opposing
popular tax cuts. Republicans have been pressing to address what
they call the ``marriage penalty,'' the quirk in the tax code that
leaves many two-income couples paying more in taxes than they would
if single. But the bills they have proposed would give tax cuts to
nearly all married couples, even if they do not pay a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also seemed intent on sparking one last round of
negotiations with the congressional leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a proposal for true compromise,'' Clinton said. ``It
asks each party to accept some of the positions of the other party
in the name of progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
