<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-IMMIG-NYT &LR;      06-26 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLED `THE NEW FDR,' BUSH MAKES APPEALS TO IMMIGRANTS AND BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George W. Bush continued Monday to present
himself as a ``different kind of Republican,'' describing an
immigrant-friendly approach to the bureaucratic Immigration and
Naturalization Service, and making a broad appeal to black voters
in an address Monday night in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush lauded racial harmony in the dinner speech before the
Congress of Racial Equality at a midtown hotel. He said he wanted
to fund mentoring programs for children whose parents are in prison
and rally ``the vast armies of compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those on the dais were Wayne LaPierre, executive director
of the National Rifle Association; Bob Grant, the conservative
radio talk-show host; Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, and descendants of
Thomas Jefferson and Sally Hemmings, Jefferson's slave, and his
first wife, Martha.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Bush, Roy Innis, chairman of CORE, said: ``He
loves people, he relates to people, he is the new FDR.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen P. Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said Bush was dedicating
himself this week to making a broad appeal across party lines to
groups that traditionally lean Democratic. Tuesday he plans to
discuss welfare-to-work programs in Michigan, and Wednesday he
plans to speak in Ohio about removing barriers to those with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   On immigration, the Texas governor said he would propose
legislation to split the INS into two separate agencies, one to
deal with law enforcement and the other to provide services to
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   For years, officials across the political spectrum have
supported restructuring the unwieldy immigration service, and two
bills are moving through the Republican-controlled Congress to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was addressing the League of United Latin American
Citizens at a conference Monday in Washington, spoke in brief
generalities, saying that as president he would ``reform the INS''
and that he wanted a ``more humane'' approach to immigration.
</P>
<P>
   But his aides said later that while he would propose his
legislation, he favored the approach being advanced by Sens.
Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., and Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.. Their
bill is viewed by pro-immigration groups as more helpful to
immigrants than the bill in the House proposed by Republican Reps.
Lamar Smith of Texas and Harold Rogers of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The chief difference between the bills is that Abraham's, in
splitting the agency in two, would put one person in charge to
supervise both the law enforcement and service functions to make
sure that they would be taking consistent legal and policy
approaches. It also sets deadlines for processing visas, rather
than letting them drag on.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-immigrant groups worry that if the agency is split into two
separate entities with two separate top executives, the law
enforcement branch would consume most of the money and that the
services for immigrants would get short shrift. The enforcement
side gets the lion's share of the agency's money now, but backers
of the Abraham bill hope that would change.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman, said that the governor was not
endorsing any particular legislation but added, ``There are no
differences between the governor's bill and Abraham's bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's language was vague and his view seems to differ
little from that of the Clinton administration and Vice President
Al Gore, the point was to distinguish himself from the immigration
Republican politics of yore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outreach, it's the governor following through on his
promise that the Republican Party has to be the party of inclusion,
for single moms, for new citizens coming to America,'' Fleischer
said. ``It's different from a lot of the sights and sounds that
people have been hearing from the Republican Party in recent
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has been working to live down the reputation
the party gained in 1996 when some prominent Republicans, including
Pete Wilson, then the governor of California, backed Prop. 187 in
California to deny medical and education services to children of
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not comment directly on Prop. 187 at the time, saying
he did not want to tell another state what to do, but said he would
educate all children. And in speaking to the Latino group Monday,
he reiterated his opposition to ``English Only'' programs, saying
he favored ``English Plus,'' which teaches children English but
encourages them to learn other languages.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would grant tourist visas to immigrants who were
waiting for their visas if their spouse or child had already
received permanent legal residency status. Now, such family members
are ineligible to visit, on the theory that they would try to stay
in the United States illegally if their spouse or parent had legal
status.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sharry, executive director of the National Immigration
Forum, said in a telephone interview that Bush's advocacy of
splitting the immigration service in two was ``not exactly a
profile in courage,'' since almost everyone supports it.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was more interesting that Bush had not mentioned
other issues of importance to Latino voters and especially
immigrants, like the H-1B visa bill, which would raise the number
of visas granted to high-tech workers from abroad. Bush supports
increasing the number of visas, but Republicans _ and Democrats,
particularly those from organized labor _ are divided over whether
this is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't speak to the tough issues, though he's trying to
present himself as a new kind of Republican,'' Sharry said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is also courting the Hispanic vote, is to address the
Latino group on Friday. Douglas Hattaway, a Gore spokesman, said
the vice president wanted to streamline the immigration agency.
``Bush would start from square one and we don't think that's
necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting more broadly on Bush's approach, Hattaway said:
``Bush is clearly trying to make himself out to be a different kind
of Republican by appearing friendly to immigrants. But under his
leadership in Texas, Hispanics are not doing as well as other
residents.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Hispanics in Texas were disproportionately poor, in part
because Texas has a minimum wage of $3.35 an hour, compared with
the federal minimum of $5.15 an hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
