<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS &LR;      06-26 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWIST IN THE PEDRO STORY: THE OBLIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It sounds so obscure, this muscle that may be causing
Pedro Martinez so many problems of late.
</P>
<P>
   The oblique.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a muscle that is used in almost any daily activity
that requires a twisting motion. Take away the fancy name, and
you're talking about your side muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you do normally that is not straight ahead involves
some twisting activity, which means you're using your oblique
muscles,'' said Dr. Timothy Kremchek, chief orthopedic surgeon for
the Cincinnati Reds. ``Golfers hurt their oblique muscles.
Construction workers, who do a lot of twisting on the job, they can
get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   There are internal and external oblique muscles. The internal
oblique is a small, thin, deep muscle of the abdomen that extends
from the hip bone to the cartilage of the lower ribs. It protects a
weak point in the abdominal wall and works with the external
oblique to help twist the torso.
</P>
<P>
   The external oblique is a large, thin sheet of overlapping
muscle that runs along the side of the torso. It is divided into
two portions that meet at the waist. This muscle is involved in
flexing the spine when the trunk twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   Kremchek, who did his residency at Tufts and spent time at both
New England Baptist Hospital and New England Medical Center, has
never examined Martinez, and emphasizes that he is not offering an
assessment of what may be ailing the Red Sox ace. For him, it bears
repeating: He does not pretend to be qualified to speak to
Martinez's case directly.
</P>
<P>
   Kremchek will, however, talk in general terms about oblique
muscle injuries. Among his patients was former Red Sox pitcher
Steve Avery, who was never the same after straining his oblique
muscle while with the Atlanta Braves. Avery, who signed with the
Reds after leaving the Red Sox following the 1998 season, told
Kremchek he changed his mechanics to compensate for the pain in his
side and never was able to regain the form that made him one of the
premier lefthanders in baseball when he came to the big leagues in
the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Avery underwent surgery for a torn rotator cuff and
is now back in the Braves' system, attempting a comeback. Kremchek
said there is really no way of knowing for certain whether Avery's
shoulder problems were related to the strained oblique muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oblique muscle injuries are not uncommon at all,'' Kremchek
said. ``You tend to see them more often early in spring training,
but they can occur during the season, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem we find with throwers who have an oblique
muscle injury is they start changing the way they throw because
they're unable to twist in their delivery and follow through like
they normally would. And when you start changing your motion, that
can lead to elbow and shoulder injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we try to get the pain away, maintain the range of
motion and make sure the pitching coach is watching closely that
the pitcher is not changing his motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Kremchek said there is no way to know why some players are more
susceptible to oblique muscle injuries than others. Martinez said
he developed soreness on his left side while throwing during a side
session a couple days after his 2-0 mastery of Roger Clemens and
the Yankees May 28 in New York. By that Friday in Philadelphia, the
Sox announced that Martinez would be scratched from his next day's
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' Martinez insisted at the time, adding that
he has had occasional problems with the side since the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no different than runners who develop Achilles'
tendinitis,'' Kremchek said. ``Some get it, some don't. It depends
on how they run. Same thing with pitchers. It depends on how they
twist their body to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers use their oblique muscles on both their windup and
follow-through. And if a pitcher can't twist like he normally does
because he hurts, he sometimes compensates by opening up too soon.
We've learned over time that pitching goes from the foot to the
knee to the hip to the back to the elbow to the shoulder. If one is
not working rhythmically or is weak, a pitcher starts opening up
too much. If one muscle is not working right, a pitcher will use
other muscles to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's pain, that will change a pitcher's approach to his
command and his approach to his velocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who gave up five runs in 6 2/3 innings Sunday and
allowed three home runs for the second start in a row, acknowledged
that his command was very much off. His velocity also was down, and
while he insisted he wasn't hurt, his teammates said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hurt, and everybody in here knows it,'' reliever Rod Beck
said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Kremchek said, is that oblique muscles heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not obvious like a broken bone or a torn ligament,''
Kremchek said. ``Your player is going to be your best guide as to
how much it hurts. And your pitching coach should be able to tell
how much it inhibits him.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatment?
</P>
<P>
   ``Stretching, strengthening, and time,'' Kremchek said. ``You
don't want to get him back too soon. But it also depends on the
caliber of your pitcher, how badly you need him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you want to get him right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
