<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPADEA COURTS FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ To him, each boo was a bouquet, each teardrop a
champagne toast, each curse a hosannah.
</P>
<P>
   Let them rant and whine and wail, all 11,429 of them; Vince
Spadea didn't care. Nothing was going to diminish his moment of
redemption. And so he turned and bowed and waved his arms wildly
and smiled exultantly toward each corner of Court 1 at the All
England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club Monday. None of these hostile
witnesses could appreciate what he had been through: the longest
losing streak in tennis history, 21 matches, until this glorious,
if torturous, first-round Wimbledon victory over No. 14 seed Greg
Rusedski, 6-3, 6-7, 6-3, 6-7, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken him 3 hours 56 minutes, interrupted by a 1-hour
45-minute rain delay, and five match points to get this anvil off
his head. And even his grand moment illustrated his wretched
fortune. He was not the crowd's conquering hero but the conqueror
of their hero: Rusedski, who along with Tim Henman is annually
anointed the savior who will bring Great Britain its first local
Wimbledon champion since Fred Perry in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so their wait has been 64 years; Spadea's had seemed
longer, even though it dated back only to last October in Lyon,
France, when Yevgeny Kafelnikov had provided Spadea's last taste of
victory before Lleyton Hewitt began the steady diet of defeat. So
he wasn't about to rush out of paradise. He was going to linger and
enjoy the moment, and he was going to make these people enjoy it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   And darned if he didn't do it. By the sheer force of his
determination and the incandescence of his celebration, he won them
over just as he had won over their man. You've convinced us, they
conceded. Good show, chap. And suddenly, the catcalls and
imprecations turned into cheers and applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to enjoy the moment and give myself a good
reward for the accomplishment I made today,'' said Spadea, a
loosey-goosey 25-year-old from Bacon Raton, Fla., whose futility
supposedly epitomized the imminent demise of American tennis once
Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi leave the world stage. ``I think the
crowd kind of appreciated it, too. We're out there fighting like
gladiators. I just feel like the crowd deserves some kind of
communication, too.''
</P>
<P>
   What was communicated to the crowd was nonstop gripping tennis,
even if on many occasions it appeared Spadea and Rusedski were
gripping their own throats.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski, a carpetbagging Brit who was born in Canada but
transplanted himself to a more receptive tennis clime to capitalize
on his mother's status as an English native, landed only 48 percent
of his 130 mile-per-hour first-serve rockets in a desultory first
set. And he seemed on the brink of bowing out meekly when he
trailed, 5-3, in the second, bouncing his racket off the grass to
demonstrate his frustration. But then the rains and the recovery
came. Rusedski closed to 5-4 before the suspension, and when play
resumed, he outlasted Spadea, 7-5, in the eventual tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Now the match was even, and this was Spadea's cue to wilt. He
began playing the role of the collapsing churl, staring ominously,
shaking his head disgustedly over each line call that aggrieved
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what it's all about,'' said Spadea, ``just kind of being
a real person, showing your emotions, doing what you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski felt like escaping after his debacle. With an
unexpected, and unwanted, fortnight's vacation now awaiting him, he
announced his plans: ``Go as far away from this place as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he wouldn't leave peaceably, even after a tepid third-set
loss. Facing match points at 5-6 and 7-8 in the fourth-set
tie-break, he resurrected himself, eventually nailing a cross-court
backhand for a 10-8 survival.
</P>
<P>
   And in the palpitating fifth set, he actually found himself
serving for the match at both 7-6 and 8-7, while Spadea was
thinking, ``Here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so difficult,'' Spadea said. ``I'm starting to think
there's no such thing as fate, man. You create it. Gee, when he was
8-7, 7-6, I was just like, `Hey, man, I can't believe life works
this unfair.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't this time. After extricating himself from both chasms,
Spadea squandered two more match points, then kissed the heavens as
Rusedski brought the melodrama to a close by sending a forehand
return long.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his wandering through the desert, Spadea never gave
up on himself, though he might have had Monday's outcome gone the
way of all those others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had lost this match, that would have been the lowest
point,'' he said. ``I was thinking, `Holy goodness, where do I go
from here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But all in all, ``I wasn't playing poorly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski concurred: ``He's too good a player to lose as many
matches as he lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Rusedski and his adopted countrymen, he served
as the proof of that Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
