<SLUG> BC-TEN-WILLIAMS-SISTERS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hingis, Williamses coast
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Three favorites for their tennis and one
favorite for other reasons won on the opening day of Wimbledon play
Monday at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   Top seed Martina Hingis and sisters Venus (No.5 seed) and Serena
Williams (No.8) all easily moved into the second round with
straight-set victories. Unseeded tabloid star Anna Kournikova
struggled against 10th seed Sandrine Testud but finally pulled off
a 7-5, 5-7, 6-4 upset on her fourth match point.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis defeated Spain's Angeles Montolio 6-1, 6-2 and was
pleased with her performance, particularly after losing in the
first round here a year ago to Jelena Dokic, then ranked No.129.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I) definitely feel better than last year,'' Hingis said.
``Coming into this tournament with a victory, with a little bit
more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, playing in just her second Wimbledon and after
a two-month layoff, defeated Asa Carlsson 6-3, 6-2 but didn't serve
and volley nearly as much as her father had directed.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, dad and coach, joined his daughters in England
this year for the first time while their mother, usually the
traveling coach, stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   He probably was happier with Venus Williams' serve-and-volley
performance. She used the style almost every chance she got and
beat Kveta Hrdlickova 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me to serve-and-volley every point,'' Venus said,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova kept her ever-attentive fans happy with her victory,
enduring a 1-hour, 45-minute rain delay and defeating a top-10
player on Centre Court at her favorite tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova thought Testud relaxed and improved when she got
behind, making it difficult for Kournikova to complete the win. But
she said the three missed match points didn't take anything away
from her feelings afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good,'' she said. ``It's probably the happiest
that I've felt after a match. This is probably the most meaningful
because it's at Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras criticizes Spaniards: Top seed Pete Sampras easily moved
into the second round, ending Jiri Vanek's Wimbledon debut 6-4,
6-4, 6-2, and afterward wondered why Alex Corretja and Albert Costa
didn't show their unhappiness with the seeding by winning matches
instead of withdrawing in protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Alex and Albert feel like they should have been seeded,
but grass is a unique surface that you have to make exceptions
for,'' the six-time defending champion said. ``They went home,
which is obviously disappointing, but this tournament will probably
still go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite rankings of No.11 and 15, respectively, both were
unseeded this year. They felt it was unfair the ATP required them
to play but the tournament had the freedom not to seed them. Juan
Carlos Ferrero, ranked No.13 and also unseeded, joined in the
protest but withdrew because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said he wouldn't object to surface-specific rankings
throughout the tour, which were suggested as ways to solve the
problem universally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't get seeded at the French, I'd go out there and try
to do well to prove to the event that I'm worthy of being seeded,''
he said. ``You really try to rise above it instead of being a
little childish about it and going home. It's a bit disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest event we have in the game. Everybody
should play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
