<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE-N     06-26 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A MARQUEE FOOD-TOBACCO DEAL, WITH LAWSUIT FEARS
LURKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NABISCO) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The pursuit of tobacco companies as public enemies
has now produced the following:
</P>
<P>
   One tobacco company, Philip Morris, gets to buy a food company,
Nabisco, at a relatively low price.
</P>
<P>
   Another tobacco company, R.J. Reynolds, gets about $1.5 billion
in cash as a sort of litigation gift.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholders who used to control the food company get less
than they might have received, because of fear that class-action
litigation may yet bankrupt the tobacco companies. Still, they are
doing much better than before Carl C. Icahn put Nabisco into play.
</P>
<P>
   The complex transaction by which Philip Morris, the nation's
largest cigarette company, will buy Nabisco _ a company that used
to be part of a company that owned Reynolds, the No. 2 cigarette
maker _ is a monument to the fear that class-action suits will
drive the tobacco companies into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   That is the part of this arrangement that gives the deal its
most unusual aspect: the gift of $1.4 billion to $1.5 billion in
cash to R.J. Reynolds. That reflects the possibility that Nabisco
Group Holdings, as the former corporate parent of Reynolds, may
have a residual liability for Reynolds debts if Reynolds is driven
into bankruptcy by tobacco litigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was one company for which that residual liability would be
unimportant: Reynolds itself. It is taking on no additional risks
by guaranteeing its own debts. And it will clear $1.4 billion to
$1.5 billion just by giving that guarantee, assuming that the deal
is completed as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, that might outrage owners of Nabisco
Group Holdings stock, who by accepting an offer of $30 a share are
effectively agreeing to take 16.7 percent less than the value of
their company's assets, based on the $55 a share being paid to the
shareowners of Nabisco Holdings, the food unit. But there are not
likely to be many complaints, since the shareholders will be
receiving more than the stock has traded for in recent years _ and
more than three times the price in the open market only a few
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual corporate structure for Nabisco stemmed from a long
series of corporate machinations. First, R.J. Reynolds acquired
Nabisco in 1985. In 1989, the new company, RJR Nabisco, was taken
private in a leveraged buyout by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The public was allowed back into RJR Nabisco in 1991, when stock
was sold in an initial public offering at a price well above its
current value.
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis got out of the company in 1994 by trading much
of its stake for ownership of Borden, an underperforming food
company. In 1995, with litigation pressure growing on tobacco
companies, RJR Nabisco sold a minority stake in Nabisco Holdings to
the public. If the idea was to show that the parent company ought
to have a higher stock price, it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, RJR Nabisco spun off its ownership of R.J.
Reynolds to its shareholders. The parent company was renamed
Nabisco Group Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   After that spinoff, an owner of one share of Nabisco Group
Holdings effectively owned 0.655 share of Nabisco Holdings, the
food company. But that parent company also faced the possibility of
being held liable if R.J. Reynolds was unable to pay its bills. The
size of the discount reflected just how worried investors were.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the spinoff, the discount was 22 percent. But the
discount deepened to nearly 60 percent early in February. Then
Icahn became involved, setting off the process that culminated in
the latest deal, which was well received on Wall Street Monday.
Philip Morris shares rose $3.50, to $27.125; Nabisco Group Holdings
added 93.75 cents, to $26.50; Nabisco Holdings rose $1.125, at
$52.75; and Reynolds gained $1.50, to $28.375.
</P>
<P>
   Now Philip Morris will own a huge food company, composed of its
old Kraft and its new Nabisco units. It plans to sell a minority
stake in that to the public. When that happens, it will become
clear that Philip Morris, like RJR Nabisco before it, is worth less
than the sum of its parts. Then, Wall Street will start talking
about how to realize the value of that food operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
