u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-26 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON'T SQUASH ALL SUSPENSE WITH A WALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The greatest baseball team of the 20th century and all time, as
the New York Yankees have often been called the last two
championship seasons, is suddenly running scared of the Toronto
Blue Jays and a couple of small-market teams with cut-rate
payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken less than half a season for an organization that
methodically won the World Series three of the last four years to
shudder at the possibility of competing for its rightful place in
the playoffs against teams from that former Class AAA outpost, the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   How pathetically unbecoming for a team with the Yankees' pride
and pedigree to be portrayed as shouting from a rooftop for someone
to come save them from the White Sox, from David Wells, from the
Junior-less Mariners and the financially challenged A's, who two
summers ago considered Rickey Henderson their most productive
player and, gulp, veteran leader. Don't look now, Boss, but your
homeys from Tampa are only eight and one-half games behind you.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it's become apparent that the Yankees may have to sweat
to survive September, the city chorus has taken up George
Steinbrenner's ``do-something'' cue and began calling for the kind
of acquisition that won't mean anything unless the pitching gets
straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   If what we have seen from David Cone and Roger Clemens is all
there is, then the Yankees should save those young prospects for
the pitchers' sale that is sure to come. Otherwise, it will soon be
the 1980s all over again, when pitching was as sparse &UR;  &LR; as parking,
and Steinbrenner will be starting his new television network with a
$120 million payroll and the Bronx chapter of the Cleveland Indians
as his main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Until this all works itself out, Yankee fans should sit back and
enjoy, for a change, some regular-season ballgames that, you know,
mean something. They're in Detroit this week and Tampa this weekend
and their mission, though paling compared to Tom Cruise's, is to
put some distance between themselves and .500.
</P>
<P>
   People around New York can't seem to believe the Yankees are in
this unenviable position so close to the _ gasp! _ All-Star break.
Out of first place. Out of the playoffs, if they were to begin
today.
</P>
<P>
   It should be a cause for celebration that there is new blood
flowing in the American League, not an excuse to spend another $20
million and further distort the imbalance that already exists
between big and small markets. Remember this: when the Braves were
beset with injuries last year, they toughed them out, and played
inspiring ball down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four years, how many regular-season series weren't
just showcases for a team already penciled into a division title or
the wild-card berth? As wonderful a team as the Yankees have been,
the Mets reminded us last year that the regular-season struggle is
still what makes baseball great, and what separates it from the
other team sports. It can't be coincidence that the more the
regular season has become a formality, the more World Series
ratings have declined.
</P>
<P>
   If Yankee fans believe this team should not have to actually
scratch and claw anymore during the regular season, then they are
as spoiled and unrealistic as the owner. Steinbrenner has a payroll
that exceeds $90 million. For that kind of investment, they are
apparently supposed to settle the issue of the postseason by late
May and allow Joe Torre to work on his October rotation for the
next four months.
</P>
<P>
   Except it doesn't always work out that way, as the disappointed
people in Baltimore and Los Angeles could tell you, and thank
goodness for that. Over the last couple of years, the Orioles and
Dodgers have been the last vestiges of hope that you can't buy the
championship, and the only reasons to not picket America's
ballparks until Bob Costas becomes commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Good for Steinbrenner if he sneered at Juan Gonzalez's asking
price. If he wants Sammy Sosa, he's probably going to get him, one
way or another. Too bad. Assuming the pitching improves _ and if it
doesn't, this whole issue is moot _ it would be nice to see the old
gang in a hot summer race.
</P>
<P>
   By all means, add a solid lefty bat. Get another quality
starter. Nobody will object. But you can tell from the snippiness
coming out of the clubhouse from typically sanguine sources such as
Joe Torre and Derek Jeter that the proud Yankees are tired of
hearing how much they need Sosa or Gonzalez to rescue them.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that Jeter and O'Neil and even Knoblauch are
scared by the Toronto Blue Jays and the Oakland A's, or by the
prospect of a real playoff race. Not nearly as much as Steinbrenner
often sounds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
