<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST UNION TO SHUT DOWN MONEY STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abandoning its longtime strategy of growing by gobbling up banks
and financial companies, the First Union Corp. said Monday that it
would close the Money Store lending operation, get out of some
businesses and scale back others.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said the overhaul would reduce earnings by $2.8
billion, most of it stemming from the decision to immediately shut
down the Money Store, a second-mortgage lender pitched relentlessly
in television ads by the retired baseball players Phil Rizzuto and
Jim Palmer. About 2,350 Money Store employees will lose their jobs,
including 360 in New Jersey, where the operation was founded.
</P>
<P>
   First Union, the sixth-biggest bank in the country, bought the
Money Store for $2.1 billion two years ago in one of the last big
purchases in a long string of deals engineered by its former chief
executive, Edward Crutchfield. Now, Crutchfield's successor, G.
Kennedy Thompson, is repudiating much of that growth strategy by
shrinking the company, which is based in Charlotte, N.C., to focus
on its core businesses of banking and brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we're saying we made a bad
acquisition,'' Thompson said, referring to the Money Store. He said
First Union was unlikely to buy any more banks and had no plans for
any significant acquisitions any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of making that reversal is high. First Union said it
would take charges against earnings and reserves for future losses
that would total about $3.8 billion. The savings from the changes
should add back $1 billion, for a net reduction in earnings of $2.8
billion over the next few quarters, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson surprised analysts by projecting that First Union would
earn between 72 and 74 cents a share in the second quarter, before
restructuring charges of at least $3 a share. The consensus
estimate of analysts had been 85 cents a share before the
announcement, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   First Union's shares gained 6.25 cents Monday, to $27.875, as
some investors expressed relief that the bank's new management was
taking the painful steps to refocus on its core businesses. The
stock had dropped more than 27 percent in the last three weeks as
fears of bad news spread among investors when the bank stopped
talking about its earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Flannigan, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. reduced her
near-term rating on First Union's stock but kept her long-term buy
rating on it. ``This restructuring is really a move by the new
management team to put the missteps of the past behind,'' Flannigan
said. ``We're going to see a great deal more focus, accountability
and financial discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes First Union plans are the sale of its
mortgage-processing operation to Wells Fargo, the sale of its
credit-card business and the cleansing of its loan portfolio by
selling $500 million of nonperforming loans. First Union also plans
to sell or close about 90 bank branches. Mostly in the Southeast
and mid-Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   First Union is closing all 38 of the remaining branches of Money
Store, 12 of which are in New Jersey and New York. Money Store also
has processing operations in the New Jersey towns of Warren and
Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said First Union would set aside $620 million to
``immunize ourselves against further losses'' from the Money
Store's $12 billion loan portfolio. But he said he did not suspect
fraud in the representations that were made by the Money Store at
the time of the sale, nor did he blame the investment bankers from
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. who received an undisclosed fee
from First Union for performing due diligence on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Money Store's advertising-driven lending business had been quite
profitable for the Turtletaub family that ran it until First Union
bought it. But in the late 1990s, as other lenders began competing
for so-called subprime borrowers. Money Store's customers started
repaying their loans early by refinancing them elsewhere. Early
repayment is the bane of lenders like Money Store because it
decreases the value of a loan that the lender, in turn, has
borrowed against to raise money to make more loans.
</P>
<P>
   The subprime lending business has been through a classic
boom-and-bust cycle on Wall Street in the last several years. After
flourishing for a few years, high-risk consumer lending crashed,
sending some lenders into bankruptcy and others into the arms of
acquirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subprime lending has come full-circle,'' said Marni Pont
O'Doherty, an analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods. ``A couple of
years ago, Wall Street was falling all over itself to underwrite
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Conseco, a big insurance company, is trying to sell Green Tree
Financial after Green Tree, which specializes in mobile-home loans,
caused huge losses at Conseco. With Green Tree already on the
auction block, First Union recognized that it would have had
trouble finding a buyer for the Money Store and chose to cuts its
losses, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Doherty noted that Conseco's purchase of Green Tree closed on
June 30, 1998, the same day on which First Union completed its
purchase of Money Store.
</P>
</TEXT>
