r a BC-DAVIDIAN-TRIAL27-COX     06-26 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIAN-TRIAL27-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Expert debunks arson evidence in Davidian trial.
</P>
<P>
   By MARK ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - An expert witness for the plaintiffs Monday
attacked the government's contention that the Branch Davidians
started the fire that destroyed the sect's complex in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And a surviving Davidian, Marjorie Thomas, described a narrow
escape from the flames to U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr.
and the advisory jury hearing the $675 million wrongful-death
lawsuit against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kennedy, a Chicago investigator who helped write
industry standards for fire investigations, told the plaintiffs'
lead attorney, Mike Caddell, that the government can't prove the
Davidians set fires in three locations simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the government's reliance on an infrared video to
prove arson is ``completely erroneous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been used before,'' Kennedy said. ``It's never been
used since. There's no scientific evidence that you can tell
anything from a FLIR (Forward-Looking Infrared video). There is no
literature in fire investigation about using a FLIR.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the government also can't prove that accelerants
were used in the three locations _ dining room, chapel and
southwest corner of the Mount Carmel complex _ where fires seemed
to start simultaneously April 19, 1993, leading to the deaths of
David Koresh and 75 followers.
</P>
<P>
   Samples were taken from all three areas to test for arson,
Kennedy told Caddell.
</P>
<P>
   A dog trained to alert at the smell of accelerants made 100
alerts going through the rubble of Mount Carmel, Kennedy said.
Thirty hits came back positive for accelerants. Not all three
areas, however, tested positive for accelerants, Kennedy said. The
dining room, for example, tested negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (fire) code is clear,'' Kennedy said. ``If you don't get a
lab test, you don't get a positive for accelerants.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy rattled off several explanations for the simultaneous
fires: arson; the leaking of fuel throughout Mount Carmel from the
numerous propane cylinders, many of which were crushed; and the
lack of firewalls, which can cause a fire to race through a
structure's walls.
</P>
<P>
   The fire's cause can only be labeled as undetermined, Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt the plowing of tanks into Mount Carmel
accelerated the fire, Kennedy testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made the fire burn hotter,'' Kennedy said. ``It made the
fire burn faster. Those incursions can't be ruled out as the cause
of the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a survivor who suffered third-degree burns on half her
body, gave the court a harrowing description of her escape from the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said she felt the building shake as a tank delivered tear
gas into the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roof of the building lifted up and dropped back down,''
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said she tried to throw out the tear-gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hot,'' Thomas said. ``I made a few attempts. I
was able to throw one out of the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas testified that she stood guard the night before the fire.
That prompted government attorney Michael Bradford to ask if she
would have shot an FBI agent trying to enter Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't use the word `shoot,''' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What word would you use?'' Bradford asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protect,'' Thomas replied.
</P>
<P>
   Thick smoke hampered her efforts to escape once the fire
started, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hear rushing, screaming, crying, people praying,''
Thomas said. ``... I stopped where I was. I couldn't see anyone. I
didn't know what had happened until it got quiet. I thought maybe
they had found a way out, and I was still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire pushed her back after she entered a hallway leading to the
dining area, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was making my way to the dining area, but the flames blocked
my way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire eventually caught up with Thomas, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel the jacket I was wearing melting,'' Thomas said.
``By this time, my legs were moving out of control. They were
burning.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling her way along walls, she got lost, Thomas said. Then she
saw a ``little flicker of light,'' actually daylight, coming from a
room. She entered and escaped through a window.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas denied that the Davidians made suicide plans on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   However, Thomas told Bradford there had been a plan to commit
suicide if Koresh died. His body was to be put on a stretcher and
taken outside, accompanied by his wives and children. Grenades
would be taken, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What were the grenades going to be used for?'' Bradford asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be used to end our lives,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith instructed the jurors they were only to use that portion
of Thomas' testimony in considering whether the government acted
reasonably in not allowing firefighters to enter Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he expects to wrap up his case today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
