<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-PRIMARY-REACT-     06-26 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRIMARY-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPONENTS OF CALIFORNIA'S VOIDED BLANKET PRIMARY VOW TO FIND
SUBSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with SCOTUS-PRIMARY) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supporters of the California blanket primary law that was ruled
unconstitutional Monday by the U.S. Supreme Court say they will
seek passage of a new measure that might be acceptable to the
court, yet still achieve the goal of opening primaries to more
voters.
</P>
<P>
   In blanket primaries there is only one ballot, and voters,
regardless of party, vote for candidates, regardless of party.
Republican and Democratic Party leaders, and other opponents of
such primaries, hailed the court ruling as validation of their
argument that political parties should be disciplined, cohesive
entities with the final say in who can vote in their primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Fleischman, executive director of the California Republican
Party, saw the court's decision as recognition that ``our members'
right of association is paramount'' and that blanket primaries
should be consigned to history's trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking for blanket-primary advocates, Nicholas Tobey,
chairman of Californians to Protect the Open Primary, vowed that an
effort would be made to pass a new law ``as soon as our lawyers can
study the court's decision and figure out the course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just beginning to fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Tobey and other advocates read the decision, it did not, at
first glance, make the right of association paramount and close
every door on their effort to open up the voting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know exactly how to write the new law yet, but we
hope to have something new on the books within another year or
so,'' Tobey said. ``Best we can tell, it looks like if you keep
things as nonpartisan as possible and then send the top two
finishers in each contest on to November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louisiana has a system along those lines,'' he added. ``The
main thing is to get more people involved, let them have a say too,
not just Democrats and Republicans, but everybody _ independents
and smaller parties, just everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   California's chief election official, Secretary of State Bill
Jones, a Republican, broke with his party and sided with the
blanket-primary advocates, warning that the Supreme Court decision
would make California, once again, a state that ``the parties
solely control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who the parties are afraid of,'' said Jones, who
won office with the help of some Democratic and independent votes.
``The vast majority of their members supported this.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to a 1996 ballot initiative in which
Californians overwhelmingly approved the blanket-primary system.
Until then, the state's voters could participate only in their own
party's primary, a system known as a closed primary.
</P>
<P>
   California's governor, Gray Davis, a Democrat who, like Jones,
won office with the help of voters outside his party, also broke
with his party on the primary issue, saying that he would do
``everything possible'' to find a substitute blanket primary
system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
