<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-DAVIDIANS-TRIAL-TEX     06-26 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAINTIFFS' WITNESS SAYS HE HEARD FELLOW DAVIDIAN SAY `LIGHT THE
FIRE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A member of the Branch Davidians testified on
Monday that he heard a fellow sect member say ``light the fire''
just minutes before their wood-frame headquarters erupted in flames
on April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of some 80 sect members, including leader David
Koresh, were later found in the ashes of the headquarters, about 10
miles outside Waco. The fire came 51 days after a Feb. 28, 1993,
gunbattle that erupted when members of the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms tried to serve search and arrest warrants on
sect members.
</P>
<P>
   Four ATF agents and six Davidians died in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Branch Davidians and their families hope to
convince U.S. District Judge Walter Smith Jr. and an advisory jury
that the government may have contributed to the final fire. They
also hope to prove that FBI agents were negligent in preventing
fire trucks from entering the complex immediately after the fire
started.
</P>
<P>
   The multimillion-dollar wrongful-death suit entered its second
week on Monday. The plaintiffs may wrap up their case as early as
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Videotaped testimony by Davidian Graeme Craddock, presented by
the plaintiffs' attorneys, appeared to support the government's
assertion that the Davidians started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Craddock said he heard fellow Davidian Pablo Cohen say, ``Wait!
Wait! Don't pour it inside. Pour it outside.'' Then he said he
watched as Cohen rushed toward someone pouring fuel in the chapel
of the headquarters, known as Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Craddock said he heard someone yell ``light the
fire.'' When he returned to the chapel, flames were traveling up
the corner wall, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Craddock, however, said he did not actually see anyone light a
fire, nor was he aware of any plans to start a fire or to commit
mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   After the day's testimony, lead plaintiff attorney Michael
Caddell said the plaintiffs believe that the government started two
of three fires and that the Davidians may have then started the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kennedy, a fire investigator hired by attorneys for the 100
or so plaintiffs, said the FBI tanks that destroyed much of the
Davidians' complex couldn't be ruled out as a cause of the fire.
The tanks were used to insert tear gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   A tank could have cut a fuel line, spreading the propane that
the Davidians used to provide light for their rooms, he said. The
destruction of the walls certainly allowed the wood to burn easier
and added air holes that fanned the flames, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make your kindling, then blow on it,'' Kennedy said.
``It's like starting your campfire out in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy testified that the government's investigation of the
fire was inadequate and that expert conclusions that the Davidians
deliberately started cannot be supported scientifically.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, sect member Marjorie Thomas testified that she
was sitting on the floor in an upstairs bedroom when she began to
feel the heat beneath her. A gap in the wooden beams allowed her to
see the flames, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, thick smoke made it impossible to see, but she
testified that she could hear ``rushing, screaming, crying, people
praying.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, it grew quiet, and Thomas said she was afraid the others
had found a way out without her.
</P>
<P>
   ``By this time, my legs were moving out of control _ they were
burning,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   A glimmer of daylight allowed her to find a second-floor window
and jump out, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas testified that she never considered suicide. But
government lawyers introduced a sworn statement from a 1994 trial
in which Thomas said that she was once told by Koresh to commit
suicide and that she almost carried out his instructions before he
sent word retracting the instruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Davidians had a pact that ``if David died, we were to end
our lives,'' Thomas continued in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   She said on Monday that she didn't remember making those
statements and that she was heavily medicated at the time for her
burns.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Davidians also presented videotaped testimony
from Mira Slovak, a contractor who said he called the FBI office
near his home in Ventura County, Calif., about 10 days before the
fire to offer an armored Soviet tank that had been retrofitted with
firefighting equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI twice asked him to send more information, but he never
received a request for the tank, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, the judge gave Caddell permission to read aloud
a portion of a March 7, 1993, memo by FBI negotiator Peter Smerick
warning the FBI commanders in Waco that using tanks could have dire
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we physically attack the compound, and children are killed,
(even by Davidians), we, in the FBI, will be placed in a difficult
position,'' Smerick wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news media, Congress, and the American people (who are
currently applauding our negotiating efforts) will ask questions:
Why couldn't you just wait them out? What threat did they pose to
anyone, except themselves? Why did you cause children to be
killed?''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Michael Bradford, who is representing the
government, described the memo as part of a disagreement among FBI
negotiators that looks significant only in hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
