<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN OFFICIAL OPPOSES WORLDCOM-SPRINT MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO and DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The top antitrust officer of the European Commission said Monday
that he would advise the commission to block WorldCom from buying
Sprint unless the companies significantly altered the terms of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   In another development in the rapidly consolidating
telecommunications industry, Qwest Communications International's
$57 billion takeover of US West received final federal regulatory
approval Monday, allowing for the closure of a transaction that
nearly fell apart when Qwest considered dropping the deal in favor
of a buyout offer from another company.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Qwest's choice to conclude the deal may come at
the cost of a potentially more lucrative link-up with Deutsche
Telekom, Europe's largest telecommunications concern. The German
company entered into, and then abruptly broke off, merger talks
with Qwest earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Apprehension over whether the Denver-based Qwest lost an
opportunity has grown in recent days with signs that regulatory
authorities in Europe could block WorldCom's takeover of Sprint.
That could make the No. 2 and No. 3 American long-distance
companies potential takeover targets for Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's top antitrust officer, Mario Monti, citing his concern
about the amount of Internet traffic the merged telecommunications
WorldCom and Sprint would carry, said Monday that the companies
would have to devise an ``exceptional'' remedy before the
commission's July 12 deadline to win his approval.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and lawyers for WorldCom and Sprint continued to meet
with officials from the Department of Justice Monday in an attempt
to salvage the proposed $115 billion deal that they announced in
October, according to people close to the negotiations. Among the
possibilities is the sale of Sprint's long-distance and Internet
businesses, leaving WorldCom with only the Sprint PCS wireless
division.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials are worried primarily about the
effect the combination would have on phone rates within the United
States. The Europeans, meanwhile, are concerned about the size of
the companies' Internet businesses, which carry Web traffic between
local phone companies and large service providers like America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Monti, the head of the commission's competition ministry, took a
hard line Monday, saying the companies had failed thus far to make
an acceptable proposal and that the time for such plans has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deadline for remedies is over,'' he said, according to
Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   He added that, with its deadline looming, the commission would
consider a new plan only under ``exceptional circumstances.'' He
declined to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for WorldCom and Sprint declined to comment. Shares of
WorldCom fell 25 cents, to $37.50, while Sprint's stock was down 25
cents, to $59.5625.
</P>
<P>
   For Qwest, the approval from the Federal Communications
Commission Monday came after a review of the company's plan to
divest parts of its long-distance business in 14 states, a
requirement of the Telecommunications Act of 1996. Touch America, a
unit of the Montana Power Co., is buying some of Qwest's assets for
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This leaves us in the position to complete this merger,'' said
Matt Barkett, a spokesman for Qwest. ``A deal with another company
would have to come at another time.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reason a deal between Qwest and Deutsche Telekom did
not materialize was because US West was opposed to it out of
concern its own takeover by Qwest would not be finalized, a
development which could have led to a drop in the company's share
price. US West, also based in Denver, went so far as to suggest a
protracted legal battle would ensue if Qwest backed out of its
intent to acquire the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans have a hole burning in their pocket, they want to
buy something so badly,'' said Scott Cleland, the managing director
of the Legg Mason Precursor Group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's intentions to create a global network are
well known. And in an effort to expand across the Atlantic, the
company may be seeking to use its stock, which is thought to be
highly valued, as a currency to acquire a large American
telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   When the Qwest-US West deal is completed, it will be the first
major combination between large local and long-distance telephone
companies. Shares of Qwest rose 56 cents to $52.9375, while US West
climbed $1.28, to $90.375. The prospects for Qwest remain bright to
some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Qwest, it's either acquire or get acquired after it
digests U S West,'' said Andrew Hamerling, a telecommunications
analyst with Banc of America Securities. ``I think Qwest is
terribly attractive to any company seeking to expand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
