<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SAMPRAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS IS UNVEILING HIS OUTSPOKEN SIDE ON SPANIARDS' BOYCOTT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Maybe it is easier speaking from the top of
the men's draw, but Pete Sampras had little sympathy for the
boycott by Alex Corretja and Albert Costa, both of whom withdrew
from Wimbledon after being snubbed by the All England Club's
seeding system.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon is the only Grand Slam event to ignore the tour
rankings and create its own seedings. But if, say, the French Open
chose the same route, then the clay-court awkward Sampras could be
left with a tougher draw as a lower-seeded player _ if he was
seeded at all.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' response to such a situation is simple: just play.
``You know if I didn't get seeded at the French, I'd go out there
and try to do well to prove to the event that I'm worthy of being
seeded,'' said Sampras, whose best finish at the French Open was as
a semifinalist in 1996. ``You really try to rise above it instead
of being a little childish about it and going home. It's a bit
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' fault-finding with Corretja and Costa came as a bit of
a surprise considering the criticism he has received in the past
for his light tennis schedule, spotty commitment to the Davis Cup
team and noncommitment to play in the Olympics. Usually, Sampras is
more reserved in his critiques of his fellow players. But he seems
more open these days, more at ease with who he is. &UR;  &LR;  To illuminate
this further, he was asked just how he proposed to his fiancee,
Bridgette Wilson. Was he a romantic at the moment of truth?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me,'' Sampras said to a chorus of laughs. ``I'm not
so boring after all.'' Gloss Is Not a Problem
</P>
<P>
   Anna Kournikova's omnipresence inside London's tube _ adorning
posters that reveal her in a sports bra with the slogan: ``Only the
balls should bounce'' _ has only added to the hype and frenzy
surrounding the tour's It Girl.
</P>
<P>
   There is resentment by some players toward so much attention
being given to a player who has yet to win a title on the tour. But
with an eye for fashion, and love for attention-getting outfits
herself, Serena Williams dismissed those who see Kournikova as all
gloss and no game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with Anna,'' Williams said. ``I get along
with her just fine. What's the problem? I don't see a problem with
what she's doing. I don't even see what she's doing. She's just
being herself. It seems like everyone has a problem with it.''
Enjoying the Perks
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis has had her ups and downs on the grounds of the
All England Club, but she still enjoys the yearly luxuries of being
a past winner (1997). With the pedigree of Wimbledon champion, she
gets ownership of a members' badge. That is as good as the key to
the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``A better parking lot,'' Hingis said, outlining her perks with
a smile. ``And you get, like, two tickets every year till you
die.'' No Excuses
</P>
<P>
   Vince Spadea's celebration Monday was Greg Rusedski's low
moment. Although he was born in Canada, Rusedski has adopted
Britain as his home. Despite having the crowd behind him, he could
not extend Spadea's record losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Like Spadea, Rusedski has struggled. Almost inexplicably, he has
been tinkering with his serve even though at around 130 miles an
hour it is one of the best in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any excuses,'' Rusedski said. ``It's
just not going very well at the moment.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
