<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-26 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPADEA SNAPS HIS WRIST, AND HIS 21-MATCH DRY SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A series of match points led Vince Spadea
from his abyss only to turn into trapdoors that teased his tortured
psyche. But hour after hour, he survived the jabs at his shaken
confidence and the windburn generated from Greg Rusedski's serve.
Set after set, Spadea ignored the isolation of playing on Court 1
in front of the flag-waving Britons cheering their own and propped
up his crumbling faith.
</P>
<P>
   He just kept talking to himself between each point, lunging for
desperate lobs while tumbling on the seat of his pants and fending
off doom by relying on the one element of his game that hadn't
deserted him during his tour-record 21-match losing streak. Once
the 19th-ranked player in the world, the free-falling Spadea still
had that lion tamer's snap in his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   As the five-set match inched four minutes in front of the
four-hour mark Monday, Spadea whipped a forehand from the baseline
that darted in on Rusedski. On Spadea's fifth match point, the
10th-seeded Rusedski could only block a backhand volley long. At
that instant, Spadea raised his fists and tilted his head toward
the drab skies like a farmer celebrating the end of a drought.
</P>
<P>
   On a first day of Wimbledon that refused to fade quietly into
the night, Spadea's losing streak was snapped just before dark, at
9 p.m. Even the crowd, which supported the British transplant
Rusedski, clamored to its feet in wild applause after the 6-3, 6-7
(5), 6-3, 6-7 (8), 9-7 victory that gave Spadea his first breath of
success since October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it doesn't ever come until the time when you're not
ready for it,'' said Spadea, who had 31 unforced errors to
Rusedski's 52. ``Then all of the sudden, you're like, `Oh, my gosh,
what's happened to me?' But it was outrageous. I thought I won 16
times, man. I felt like freaking. It's been a rough year, a rough
patch in my life in tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Spadea was just part of confidence reclamation day. Just before
Wimbledon was christened with a drizzle that stopped play for 1
hour 45 minutes, No. 1-seeded Pete Sampras shook loose the
tightness in his back and dispatched Jiri Vanek, 6-4, 6-4, 6-2.
Regrouping from her first-round exit a year ago, the top-seeded
women's player, Martina Hingis, put away Angeles Montolio, 6-1,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just sometimes you have to _ you're searching for something,''
said Hingis, who was unfocused and flustered in a brief split with
her mother this time last year. ``You have to find your line. You
have your own ideas, your own mind. Sometimes you have to
experience things. People go to school and do worse things than
what I did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was painted as the Williams sisters' arrival. Then
both vanished from sight as a Grand Slam duo after dominating the
U.S. Open. Monday, the fifth-seeded Venus Williams and her
eighth-seeded sister, Serena, looked healed from their springtime
injuries as they advanced to the second round with straight-set
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Serena was the less polished of the two in her first match since
mid-April. She labored against her Swedish opponent, Asa Carlsson,
in a 15-minute first game to hold serve, but swiftly regained her
confidence in a 6-3, 6-2 victory. With blond streaks in a mane
bound into a ponytail by a feathery tie, she looked at ease in an
environment she once believed was too stuffy for her style.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did feel that way, I tell you one thing, I don't feel
that way now,'' Serena Williams said. ``I feel free. I can breathe.
I can breathe freely. This is really my surface. I play a fast
game. I can't believe it if I ever felt that way. I should be
dominating here.''
</P>
<P>
   She just might. But this wasn't a day marked by the way the
stars cruised, but about the tension created once the tarps were
peeled off the grass to clear space for two players who have been
mental wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   On Court 1, there was the anguished Spadea. On Center Court,
there was the Web site darling Anna Kournikova. Opposite
10th-seeded Sandrine Testud, Kournikova was trying to silence the
cynics who chide her glam-girl status. She was trying to stop a
yearlong ranking slide that left her unseeded at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   It was closing in on 8 p.m. when the rubbernecking between
Spadea's match and that of Kournikova bordered on ridiculous. At
the same minute, Spadea and Kournikova had match points.
Kournikova, who had frittered away service in the second and third
sets with nervous double faults and timid ground strokes, finally
composed herself. On Kournikova's fourth match point, Testud sent a
backhand into the net that allowed Kournikova to escape with the
upset, 7-5, 5-7, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   One hour later, Spadea finally tucked away his last match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents left,'' said Spadea, a resident of Florida. ``They
saw the draw and said, `Vince, man, good luck, but I don't know if
that will help you.' They're in Miami right now, on the Internet,
breaking the keyboard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
