<HEADER>
A5707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FITE-PAYOFF-NYT &LR;      06-26 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FITE-PAYOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTER TESTIFIES HE PAID IBF TO LIFT BAN ON SOUTH AFRICAN
FIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Cedric Kushner, the boxing promoter who grew up
in South Africa, told a jury in federal court Monday that he had
initially begun paying bribes to the leaders of the International
Boxing Federation in 1987 to get the sanctioning organization to
lift its ban on ranking boxers from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Without rankings from the IBF, Kushner said, the boxers he
represented could not qualify for lucrative televised bouts and
title fights.
</P>
<P>
   He said the IBF executive committee had met informally in 1987
to hear the plea of one of his black African boxers, who sought to
have the federation, which is based in East Orange, N.J., overturn
its policy of ignoring South African fighters because of the
country's racially restrictive apartheid system.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Kushner said, the IBF agreed to recognize and rank
black and white South African boxers and their bouts in the United
States. Kushner said he paid the IBF rankings chairman at the time,
Colin Douglas Beavers, $10,000 after the vote and continued to give
him payments of from $2,500 to $10,000 three or four times a year
until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner said he had made the payments to Beavers in cash in the
belief that they were being shared with other leaders of the
sanctioning group. Asked by Jose Sierra, an assistant United States
attorney prosecuting the case, why he continued to make payments,
Kushner said he did so on the advice of Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You know how it works,''' Kushner said. `` `They
could vote to change it back.' The sense was that what you paid for
didn't last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Kushner's testimony came at the start of the 10th week of the
bribery and racketeering trial of Robert W. Lee Sr., 66, the
founder and president of the boxing federation, and his son and
aide, Robert Lee Jr., 38. The two men are charged with extorting
$338,000 from fighters and their managers over the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner, like the promoter Bob Arum and the boxing manager
Roland Jankelson, told jurors that he made the payments to Beavers
with the understanding that he was representing Lee, whom Beavers
referred to constantly as ``the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kushner began his testimony, the graying, heavyset promoter
described his rise from a sixth grade education in Cape Town,
through a period as a merchant seaman and a Ferris wheel operator
in Asbury Park, N.J., to relative fame and fortune in the 1970s as
a promoter of rock concerts featuring the Rolling Stones, Fleetwood
Mac, Queen, the Grateful Dead and Joni Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 he began dabbling in boxing promotion. He said he had
reached out to the newly created IBF to try to alter the
international status of South African boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other promoters and managers who have testified at
the trial said that their payments to Beavers and other IBF leaders
were for specific actions by the group to favorably rate their
fighters. Kushner presented his payments as part of a broader
lobbying effort to improve the atmosphere in the United States for
South African boxers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was double punishment for the fighters who got no
opportunity in their own country and couldn't get any opportunity
elsewhere,'' said Kushner, who said he represented black and white
South African boxers at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner said he arranged for Welcome Ncita, a black South
African flyweight, to present to the IBF executive committee the
plight of black fighters, who were forced to train without
gymnasiums and used milk cartons for gloves because ``they could
not afford proper gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever give cash to anyone of the IBF officials besides
Beavers?'' Sierra asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Kushner said, adding that he had alluded to meeting with
Beavers in some conversations with Lee as a way of indicating to
Lee that he had made some payments.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had done that, Kushner said: ``I was giving the
money to make Lee happy, not Beavers. If Bob was happy, more was
going to happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
