<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHELSEA CLINTON TO DO SOME CAMPAIGNING WITH HER MOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton had her second City Hall news
conference in four days Monday, but this time she brought with her
a slight young woman who listened quietly on the edge of the crowd:
Chelsea Clinton, her 20-year-old daughter, who said she would be
campaigning on and off with her mother this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be seeing some of me,'' Clinton said shyly to reporters
who suddenly noticed her standing in their midst. She added that
she finished her junior year at Stanford University two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   As brief as they were, Clinton's words were nonetheless rare
comments from a daughter whose parents have aggressively shielded
her from the press for most of the seven and a half years that the
family has lived in the White House. She rarely appeared at her
father's side during his campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the second time that Clinton has appeared in public
with her mother since the first lady began running for the Senate.
The first time was at Mrs. Clinton's campaign announcement speech
in February at the State University of New York in Purchase, where
Chelsea also appeared as a baby in a campaign video about her
mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   And although the news conference was called to publicize the
plight of 13 Iranian Jews accused of spying for Israel _ and also
to put the Democratic Senate candidate in the same picture frame as
Malcolm Hoenlein, the conservative and influential Jewish leader _
one of the first questions to Mrs. Clinton was about her daughter's
plans to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to be coming and going as she chooses,'' Mrs.
Clinton replied. ``I believe in permitting her to make those
decisions. And you'll see her sometimes, which will be a delight
for me, and that's all I can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Clintons' daughter has moved slowly but
increasingly into more of a public role. Last week, she stood in
for the first time for her mother at a White House arrival ceremony
for King Mohammed VI of Morocco. Although Mrs. Clinton, who was
campaigning in New York, made it to Washington in time for the
state dinner, it was her daughter who stood by the president's side
and formally welcomed the king and his sister, Princess Lalla
Meryem, as a 21-gun salute and a trumpet fanfare sounded on the
South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Clinton accompanied her father on a trip to South
Asia, and stood in for her mother at a formal arrival ceremony at
the presidential palace in New Delhi. Last summer, she vacationed
with her parents in the otherwise sleepy Finger Lakes resort town
of Skaneateles, N.Y., and was mobbed by reporters when she ventured
downtown to the library.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, her most conspicuous public role was to
walk between her parents, holding their hands, as they left the
White House for a summer vacation on Martha's Vineyard in August
1998 immediately after her father's public admission that he had
had an affair with Monica Lewinsky. While on the Vineyard, she
surfaced a few times in public, poised and gracious.
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference Monday, Clinton and her mother went
separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton appeared at the news conference with Hoenlein, the
executive vice chairman of the Conference of Presidents of Major
Jewish Organizations. She termed the trial of the Jews in Iran a
``miscarriage of justice'' and called upon the government to
release them, including a 17-year-old boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
