<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN-HOMEGROCER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LEADING ONLINE GROCERS MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The peach has been bagged.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland-based HomeGrocer.com, whose peach-decorated delivery
trucks have become a fixture on the streets of Seattle, was sold
Monday to rival Webvan Group Inc. in a stock deal valued at about
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The merger brings together two of the leading online grocery
stores and positions the company _ to be known as Webvan Group _ as
a powerhouse in the overnight delivery of food, liquor, electronics
and office supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger combines the strengths of the two premier online
shopping and delivery companies both with the capabilities to
deliver the last mile of e-commerce,'' said George Shaheen, chief
executive of Foster City, Calif.-based Webvan.
</P>
<P>
   Both HomeGrocer.com and Webvan have been burning through cash as
they attempt to expand their distribution network, build brand
recognition and change the way consumers shop for everything from
fruits and vegetables to diapers and dog food. But as the two
companies spent heavily to attract customers, investors lost
patience with consumer e-commerce companies. That has caused
consolidation in the online grocery market.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Safeway Inc. invested $30 million in GroceryWorks.com
while Dutch supermarket chain Royal Ahold NV spent $73 million to
bail out struggling Peapod Inc. Westwood, Mass.-based Streamline
Inc., which is backed by Nordstrom and others, announced last month
that it hired an investment bank to explore its financing options.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is out there with a big bag of money handing out cash
to B2C (business-to-consumer) companies,'' said Peter Swan, an
analyst at Pacific Growth Equities in San Francisco. ``So to a
certain extent this merger is a function of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, with more than 4,200 employees and 264,000
customers, will have operations in nine markets with plans to
expand into four new cities by the end of the year. By merging
upcoming expansion schedules in Baltimore, Washington, D.C.,
Chicago and Bergen County New Jersey, Webvan will be able to save
between $200 million and $300 million in operational costs and $20
million to $30 million in headquarter and marketing costs. It will
also be able to compete more aggressively against brick-and-mortar
competition such as Albertsons Inc. and Safeway, both of which have
made moves onto the Internet in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the merger both companies had to expend money to win
customers from brick-and-mortar alternatives and then each had to
spend money to win the customer from each other,'' said Shaheen.
``Total spend now can be more directed on brick-and-mortar
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the possible cost savings, Wall Street reacted
negatively to the news, sending shares of both companies down more
than 14 percent. Webvan fell $1.41 to close at $7.31 while
HomeGrocer.com lost $1.22 to close at $6.88. Both companies have
lost nearly half of their value since issuing shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably surprised the market,'' said HomeGrocer.com Chief
Executive Mary Alice Taylor, commenting on the dip in the stock
prices. ``There is still some digesting of what it means and how it
plays out. But this deal just makes good sense.''
</P>
<P>
   With the capital markets emphasizing profitability and the large
supermarket chains getting more serious about Internet initiatives,
HomeGrocer.com`s Taylor said the merger was a ``no-brainer.'' The
former Federal Express executive who was recruited to lead
HomeGrocer.com in September said the deal came together after
George Shaheen gave her call about six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``George picked up the phone, gave me call and said: `What do
you think?,' '' said Taylor. ``And that is really what got the ball
rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who will not have a management role in the new company,
said it was premature to discuss layoffs at HomeGrocer.com's
Kirkland headquarters. Executives at Webvan said they have made no
decisions about headcount, although it would be looking at
``eliminating headquarter redundancies.'' Plans to open a
350,000-square-foot distribution center in Kent this October are
still on track, said a Webvan spokesman. Meanwhile, the
HomeGrocer.com distribution facility in Renton will be shut down
and employees, most of whom work in delivery and grocery picking,
will be transferred to the new building.
</P>
<P>
   While the two companies Monday touted their similarities, they
have taken alternative paths in the online grocery war. Founded in
an old Bellevue warehouse by three Canadian entrepreneurs,
HomeGrocer.com has focused on quickly moving into markets and
establishing brand recognition. It currently operates seven
warehouses in Seattle, Portland, Los Angeles, San Diego and Dallas
and processes about 2,300 orders per day. Delivery trucks park
directly at the warehouses and then in midmorning begin
transporting orders to customers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Webvan, formed by Borders Books founder Louis
Borders, has attempted to build massive automated warehouse
facilities in the 300,000-square-foot range. Using what it calls a
spoke-and-wheel approach, the company transports goods by
semi-truck trailer to smaller distribution hubs where items are
then offloaded onto vans. Drivers deliver goods in a 30-minute
window, compared to 90 minutes at HomeGrocer.com. The company does
not bill itself as an online grocery store, but rather as a last
mile e-commerce provider, delivering everything from patio
furniture to DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts questioned the possibility of combining the two
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaheen, who will remain chief executive of Webvan, said
bringing together the two companies will ``be quite seamless'' and
will ``dovetail very nicely and smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest online retailer, Seattle's Amazon.com, will
be following the merger closely. Amazon holds a 21.6 percent stake
in HomeGrocer.com and has expressed interest in combining its
retailing operation with delivery services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't to a place yet where Webvan is a direct threat to
Amazon. Amazon is seeing that and didn't want it to come up and
bite them,'' said Adam Hamilton, a research analyst with McAdams
Wright Ragen in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close in the late third quarter or early
fourth quarter. Webvan will pay 1.076 shares, or about $7.86, for
each HomeGrocer.com share. Jim Barksdale, partner of The Barksdale
Group and an early investor in HomeGrocer.com, will join Webvan's
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Kathy Mulady contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
