u s BC-GLF-HALFWAYPOINT-HNS &LR;      06-26 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HALFWAYPOINT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Woods towers over PGA Tour at midway point
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   What we know about the PGA Tour at the midpoint of the 2000
season is that nobody beats Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he might lose the odd tournament. But in the long haul, he's
so far removed from the pack these days that it's senseless to even
speculate on who might be his most legitimate challenger. There
isn't one.
</P>
<P>
   He's too talented, too strong, too long, too driven and too
smart to have any peers right now.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he reminds people from a generation older than Woods
of another young stud who already had lapped the field the moment
he arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things he's doing now are the same things Jack Nicklaus
was doing when he started out,'' says Butch Harmon, Woods' swing
coach who, at 56, has been around long enough to know what it was
Nicklaus was doing in the early '60s. ``Jack came out and was
instantly better than everybody else. And he worked hard to make
sure he stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tom Watson adds: ``He's raised the bar. And Tiger is the only
one who can jump over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The victories continue to pile up. Woods has five of them in
2000, and getting 10 official wins this year is certainly within
his reach, something that hasn't been done since Sam Snead won 11
times in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   But the records don't mean much to Woods. He's merely in this
game for one reason _ to gauge himself against the best. And that
means using Nicklaus as a yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus' 18 major championships are the ultimate goal for
Woods. The Golden Bear's 70 tour victories would be next.
</P>
<P>
   Woods already has three majors at age 24. Nicklaus also had
three at the same point in his life.
</P>
<P>
   But staying power is going to determine whether Woods can keep
pace. It won't be easy. Nicklaus averaged a major win each year
starting in 1965. He also finished second in majors 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   Woods knows what is in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to try to keep getting better,'' he says.
``Mentally, that won't be a problem. I've always been strong
mentally. Hopefully, I won't have any major physical problems,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' dominance has overshadowed a number of wonderful story
lines this year on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for Woods, the success of Phil Mickelson, Jesper
Parnevik and Hal Sutton would be the toast of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's performance is perhaps the most uplifting. After a
terrible run in the '90s when his golf game and personal life went
through deep depressions, he has built both back to a wonderful
level.
</P>
<P>
   He, wife Ashley and 1-year-old twin girls are the picture of
happiness, and Sutton's golf game is bulldog tough. He may not be
hitting the ball to the moon like Woods, but Sutton's staring down
of Woods during the Players Championship was the most riveting
moment in the sport this year, save for the U.S. Open blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, meanwhile, had openly lamented about not being
involved in the Mercedes Championships at the start of this year.
That tournament is only for winners from the previous year, and in
'99 Mickelson saw a streak of six consecutive years with at least
one win come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's won three times in 2000, and he, like Sutton, went
head-up against Woods and came out on the plus side when he won at
the Buick Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   As for Parnevik, he has done wonders this year, producing three
wins with his game and countless upset stomachs with his pants,
which run from putrid to nauseating in their color schemes.
</P>
<P>
   But remember this about Parnevik: He has become the dominant
European player in the states. He's better than Sergio Garcia. He
plays a full U.S. schedule, unlike Colin Montgomerie. And he's even
surpassed Fiji's Vijay Singh in international rankings. Singh was
the biggest foreign money-winner on tour last year, finishing
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss Sweden, especially during the summer,'' Parnevik said.
``But I want to play golf against the best, and that means playing
a lot in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   And playing a lot against Woods.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
