<HEADLINE>
WATER POLO TEAM READY FOR TUNEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ Tony Azevedo has spent his entire life
asking his father water polo questions.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ricardo Azevedo, Tony's father and former coach at Wilson
High in Long Beach, Calif., who first put his son in the pool with
a water polo ball in hand. It was Ricardo, who is now the men's and
women's coach at Long Beach State, who taught Tony the skills that
have made the younger Azevedo one of the country's best in the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   It is also Ricardo who, at least until recently, has patiently
fielded every question _ no matter how big or small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I come home these days, I have 10 more questions to
ask him,'' said 18-year-old Tony, who will be heading to Stanford
in the fall. ``I think I drive him crazy sometimes. He keeps
telling me to settle down, relax and everything will take care of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions, by the way, mainly concern what to expect when
Azevedo and his teammates on the U.S. National Water Polo team get
on a plane in September for the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go to sleep at night, take a nap or have some
free time, it's on my mind,'' Tony said. ``It's something I've
dreamed about forever.''
</P>
<P>
   However, before that dream gets under way, the U.S. team has to
finish some work. Included in that work are five days of workouts
per week that are packaged in two-a-day sessions and can total as
much as six hours.
</P>
<P>
   The training, however, will take a back seat for the next six
days while the U.S. team takes part in a pre-Olympic dress
rehearsal known as the UPS Cup at the U.S. National Aquatic Center
in Los Alamitos.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, which also includes Olympic squads from
Australia, Croatia, Yugoslovia and Italy and a team of U.S.
collegiate stars known as Team UPS, will begin at 6 p.m. today with
Croatia playing Team UPS and end with the title game at 3 p.m.
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
