<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5832 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKO-DELUSION-LADN-(SL     06-26 1883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-DELUSION-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY OR NOT, HERE THEY COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Four years ago, Kobe Bryant stood at a podium at
Lower Merion (Pa.) High and announced he would declare for the NBA
draft rather than accept a college scholarship to Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash was immediate. During the following few weeks,
Bryant was criticized, ridiculed and berated for shunning college
for the NBA. One national publication questioned the tactics and
motives of his parents, accusing them of vicariously living through
their gifted 17-year-old son rather than tending to his best
interests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Pete Sampras quietly dropped out of Palos Verdes
(Calif.) High after his junior year to join the pro tennis tour.
Not a word was said. Two years later, the 19-year-old Sampras
became the youngest men's champion in U.S. Open history and
everyone applauded. Sampras never finished high school, let alone
college, and no one seems to care.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was vindicated this year when he and Shaquille O'Neal
powered the Lakers to their first NBA title in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Sampras and Bryant traveled similar paths to
stardom and success, yet their decisions were met with decidedly
contrasting reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke and I can't understand it,'' said Sonny Vaccaro,
an Adidas shoe executive. ``Every day kids leave high school to
play pro baseball or tennis and no one says anything. But a kid
goes from high school to the NBA or leaves college early for the
NBA and it's a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   !ital!Big issue? This year alone, 29 underclassmen and two high
school players are eligible for Wednesday's NBA draft. Last year,
22 players left early, and 28 came out the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Some are players you've never heard of and probably never will.
They range from college dropouts with desperate dreams to
beer-drinking frat brothers who fax their name to the NBA on a
dare.
</P>
<P>
   But many who have come out early developed into NBA stars,
including Vince Carter, Rasheed Wallace, Bryant and Shareef
Abdur-Rahim. These are losses that concern the NCAA, which is
afraid that the never-ending, ever-growing exodus of impact
freshmen and sophomores will dilute its talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, college fans followed the career arc of great
players such as Larry Bird, James Worthy and Michael Jordan,
witnessing their growth from freshmen to experienced juniors and
seniors.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the most recognizable players leave after their
first and second years, making it difficult for the NCAA to
cultivate stars. Consider: If Bryant had gone to Duke and stayed
all four years, he and former North Carolina star Vince Carter, now
with the Toronto Raptors, could have met in a titanic Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they were making millions for themselves and the NBA
while the Final Four consisted of no-names outside of experienced _
but hardly star- struck _ Michigan State, the eventual champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet it's a problem,'' said Purdue coach Gene Keady. ``And
we need to come up with something to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   u u u
</P>
<P>
   Critics of players leaving school early _ or not going to
college at all _ insist players are risking an education for fool's
gold. The danger, they say, is that players find out too late that
they aren't meant for the NBA, and by the time they do, they have
nothing to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   Once a high school player declares for the NBA draft, he
forfeits his college eligibility. College players can return to
school if they aren't satisfied with their draft status but only if
they haven't signed with an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The naysayers might be surprised to know that all but two of the
10 players who skipped college over the last five years made it in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a good ratio, it's a great one,'' said Vaccaro.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers aren't as good for college players who declare as
underclassmen. Last year 10 of the 22 American underclassmen went
undrafted; the year before, 12 weren't chosen.
</P>
<P>
   But that stat is misleading. For every Carter or Wallace leaving
early, there are guys such as Albert White and Adam Roberts, who
weren't highly regarded college players, let alone pro prospects.
The fact that they never made it isn't a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Kevin Garnett made immediate impacts, and over the
next few years guys such as Tracy McGrady, Jermaine O'Neal, Al
Harrington and Rashard Lewis _ all of whom spurned college and
landed jobs in the NBA _ will make their mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``What impresses me is how polished some of these guys are,''
said Tom Nissalke, a former NBA and ABA coach and now a Utah Jazz
broadcaster. ``It's not the same as it was a few years ago. These
kids play AAU ball year-round and travel all over. In a way they're
already professionals or semiprofessionals by the time they leave
high school. I'm impressed not just with their talent but their
maturity level.''
</P>
<P>
   Nissalke offers a unique perspective. He was the head coach of
the Utah Stars in 1974 when Moses Malone went from Petersburg (Va.)
High straight to the pros. Malone wasn't as socially advanced as
Garnett or Bryant, but physically he was more than ready to step
in. In his first year, Malone averaged 18.8 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was terrific from the very start,'' Nissalke said. ``He
just wasn't a very sophisticated person at that point. But
nowadays, these kids travel all over the country and people have
been giving them things since they were 12 years old. It's totally
different.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recent success rate could eventually lead to trouble.
Kids see Bryant and Garnett flourishing in the NBA and they think
they can do the same. It doesn't help that their egos are stroked
by summer- and travel-league coaches with questionable motives,
many of whom try to latch onto young players, hoping for a big
payday later on.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens now is you've got juniors in high school rather
than in college already thinking about how quickly they can get to
the NBA,'' said San Diego State coach Steve Fisher, who coached the
Fab Five at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Former UCLA coach Jim Harrick, now at the University of Georgia,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys have a double-double and they come back saying, 'Hey
coach, I'm ready to go to the NBA. I'm outta here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For some _ such as Carter, Garnett and Bryant _ it's the right
decision. All three were confident they were ready. But others base
the choice on potential riches rather than ability.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, who left Michigan State in 1979 after his
sophomore year, counsels young basketball players on leaving early.
He's concerned some athletes focus on the wrong factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the part of being poor and trying to take care of
your family,'' Johnson said. ``But can you take care of them for a
long time or is this gonna be a short-range thing, because a lot of
these guys won't get drafted. It's not no shoo-in just because
you're coming out. I was a shoo-in, I already knew I was gonna be
number one. But you can't equate me to other guys. It's a whole
different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   As the relatively new phenomenon of high school players and
college underclassmen declaring for the draft grows, so will the
number of players who don't make it. The NBA is aware of the
danger, but legally it is handcuffed. Since the league can't
prevent someone from making a living, it just hopes players are
wise enough to gauge their ability honestly.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, who will be there to pick up the pieces when
things don't work out? ``It's a risk they take, no question about
it,'' said Jack Ramsay, a former NBA coach and general manager.
``And it's a harsh lesson to learn if it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   u u u
</P>
<P>
   If a kid averages 30 points at a small school in rural Kansas,
he thinks he can do the same at Indiana University. The inner-city
point guard with the nifty cross-over dribble is convinced he's the
next Allan Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   Ask them both and they'll tell you they'll be in the NBA
someday, convinced by their high school success and the people
around them feeding their egos.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they get to college _ !ital!if they get that far _
they think they're ready for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They watch a guy in the NBA on TV and they have no perspective
of how tough it really is,'' said James Hodges, who has played
professional basketball overseas for seven years. ``They see a guy
hitting a jump shot and they think they can do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges has carved out a nice career since leaving
Wisconsin-Whitewater University in 1992. By keeping things in
perspective and not overestimating his ability, he's been able to
make more money than most of his college buddies, buy a nice house
and car. He's amazed at how many players oversell themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear it all the time, see it all the time,'' Hodges said.
``So many of these guys think they should be in the NBA. The
problem is a lot of them went to a big school and they had alumni
people and boosters telling them they'll be in the league after
college. But the reality is most of these guys have no idea what it
takes to play at that level. They have absolutely no concept.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago Nissalke spoke to a college basketball team as a
favor to its coach, a good friend. Nissalke urged the players to
focus on their education and the importance of having a back-up
plan should basketball not work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on that night, I had dinner with the coach and I asked
him what kind of reaction I got from his players,'' Nissalke said.
``He just sort of laughed and said, 'They all thought you were
crazy,' Everyone of those kids was convinced they'd eventually play
in the NBA. And as I recall, not one of those guys really ever had
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   u u u
</P>
<P>
   Why does anyone care if kids go from high school to the NBA or
leave college early for the potential riches of pro basketball? Why
is that an issue and not the hundreds of kids who report directly
from high school graduation to minor-league baseball or kids who
play pro tennis as teen- agers?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of hypocritical when you think about it that way,''
said Sacramento Kings executive Jerry Reynolds, a former NBA coach
and general manager. ``In the small town I grew up in Indiana, if
you had offered any of the fellas a hundred bucks and a new glove
to sign a pro contract to play minor-league baseball, I'll bet
everyone of them would have done it. I would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because college baseball and tennis are not
high-profile sports. College basketball, on the other hand, is
extremely popular. For selfish reasons, it makes sense that a UCLA
basketball fan would want his favorite players to stick around all
four years, increasing the chances the Bruins will win big.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccaro can appreciate that. Just don't disguise your selfish
reasoning by insisting you're more concerned about the players'
education or that the talent pool will dry up, leaving college
basketball to a bunch of 6-foot YMCA rejects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to camps all the time where there are 200 or 300
fantastic players,'' Vaccaro said. ``Basketball is like a
never-ending stream of trout fish. There are great players all over
and there's plenty to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   College basketball better hope so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
