<SLUG> BC-NJ-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRENTON, $21.5 BILLION BUDGET IS APPROVED IN COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Appropriations committees in the Assembly and
Senate Monday unanimously approved a proposed New Jersey budget of
$21.5 billion, an increase of nearly 10 percent from the spending
plan signed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The budget, which awaits floor votes in both houses on Thursday,
includes another record surplus, 870 million, and $228 million more
in spending than Gov. Christine Todd Whitman requested in January.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, $122 million, roughly twice as much as a year ago,
consists of lawmakers' gifts to their districts _ from $3,000 for
an electronic speed-monitoring device for Bethlehem Township to $3
million for unspecified redevelopment projects in Mercer County.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the budget bill, however, is a $45 million sum
requested by Whitman for aid to inner-city school districts. The
governor's spokesman, Pete McDonough, said lawmakers were expected
to appropriate that money on Thursday in a last-minute rush of
supplemental spending measures for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But that $45 million expense will reduce the surplus anticipated
for next year's budget to $825 million, well below the $850 million
Whitman has set as a minimum for New Jersey to maintain its strong
bond rating, McDonough said. That, in turn, means that the governor
will use line-item vetoes to cut at least $25 million in spending,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman will have until midnight Friday to announce her
line-item vetoes in time for the new fiscal year. But she cannot
unilaterally increase any spending, so the value of any items she
rejects will inflate the projected surplus.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the proposed budget authorizes spending
$21,480,950,000 in state revenue _ a 9.7 percent increase from last
year's budget law _ and $8,000,437,000 from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $228 million in additions to the budget since January,
McDonough said the governor had asked for $85 million in extra
school aid, but that lawmakers had come up with the other $143
million.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Whitman said she was concerned
about the level of ``discretionary'' spending included in the
budget but acknowledged that demands from constituents were hard to
resist in times of plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a lot of nice projects out there,'' she said.
``When you have money coming in, people say, `Well why can't you
spend it? Why not do it?'''
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers have relied on the booming economy to justify
their liberal spending on pet projects, Leonard Lance, the
Republican chairman of the Assembly's budget committee, sounded a
note of caution. He said income tax receipts had risen drastically
over the last four years but were ``likely to be slightly less
dramatic than in the red-hot late 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   People earning more than $100,000 a year account for 78 percent
of the state's income taxes, Lance said, and much of their earnings
in recent years has come from bonuses, capital gains or investments
instead of from salaries. ``When the economy matures, as soon as
two years from now, perhaps, that income, which is heavily
dependent on Wall Street, may not be as great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Barbara Buono, the ranking Democrat on the budget
committee, called the size of the state budget ``unimaginable'' and
raised concerns about the state's debt burden, which will require
$1.5 billion in interest payments next year. But she signed the
bill along with the 10 other committee members, praising increases
for additional human services caseworkers and for reversing cuts in
aid to nursing homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
