<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   MONEY IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Big money continues to roll into the Republican Party. Data
released Monday show that in May the party and its committees
raised $12.2 million in soft money. That brought the party's
fund-raising total for the 2000 election to $106 million. The
Democratic soft-money totals have not yet arrived at the Federal
Election Commission. But data that include some of May's
fund-raising has the Democratic soft-money total at $86.4 million.
Republicans received many checks in the $200,000 and over level,
with most coming from Texans and Californians, according to Public
Disclosure Inc., a company that tracks campaign contributions.
Texans with open checkbooks were David Saperstein of Five S capital
($250,000), J. Virgil Waggoner of Sterling Chemicals ($250,000) and
Richard D. Kinder of Kinder Morgan Energy Partners ($240,000). As a
group, the other big givers were from Oregon, especially timber
companies. Their combined contributions to Republicans came to $1.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   LETTER HELPS OPPONENT
</P>
<P>
   To help the Democrats pick up one of the six seats they need to
regain control of the House, Mayor Wellington E. Webb of Denver
sent out a fund-raising letter in March on behalf of Ken Toltz, the
Democrat challenging Rep. Thomas G. Tancredo, a freshman Republican
from Colorado's Sixth District. But the letter, which urged
financial support for Toltz, a businessman in his first run for
office, and characterized Tancredo as ``a right-wing extremist,''
has helped raise more than $50,000 for Tancredo. His campaign
mailed the same letter to Republican loyalists, hoping that other
things Webb had to say, like, ``This race could decide the majority
in Congress,'' might work to Tancredo's advantage. So far, it has.
``And we're not finished yet,'' said Dave Pearson, Tancredo's
campaign manager. ``Money is still coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: New York and Wayne, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Philadelphia and Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
