<HEADLINE>
ABC NAMES ITS BOXING ANALYST PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC named Alex Wallau, one of its longest-serving executives,
who also is be the network's boxing analyst, to the position of
president of the ABC Television Network on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wallau will be responsible for most of ABC's business and
programming divisions, including news, entertainment and sports. He
succeeds Patricia Fili-Krushel, who left ABC three months ago to
become chief executive of the consumer division of Healtheon/WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Wallau, who has served as interim president since the departure
of Fili-Krushel, will report to Robert Callahan, the president of
the ABC Broadcast Group. Previously Wallau had been president of
ABC's administration and operations.
</P>
<P>
   Wallau said Monday he would retain the duties of that job. ``I'm
not replacing myself in that position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallau also said he would continue to serve as the on-air
analyst for boxing matches covered by ABC Sports, a role he has
performed since 1986. ``I do enjoy it,'' Wallau said. ``I find
boxing to be a good metaphor for being president of a network.''
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that ABC broadcasts few boxing events now. Wallau
did the commentary on a match on June 17, but that was the first he
had done in more than a year. And he said ABC Sports had no other
boxing matches scheduled at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   What is scheduled for Wallau is a move from New York to Los
Angeles. As with other senior positions in ABC's management, the
job of president was moved to Los Angeles after the network became
part of the Walt Disney Co., which is in Burbank, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Fili-Krushel said the necessity to move to Los Angeles was one
factor in her decision to leave ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Wallau said Monday, ``This does mean a move to the West Coast,
and I'm looking forward to that, even though I'm a New Yorker and I
know I'll be moving back someday in my dotage.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he would be in New York frequently since so many
of the network's divisions, including news, sports, and advertising
sales, would continue to be based in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Wallau expressed confidence in the current leaders of ABC's
programming division, and singled out the entertainment division
under Stu Bloomberg and Lloyd Braun for being ``ahead of the pack''
in the current trend toward reality shows imported from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed confidence that ABC's hit game show, ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire,'' would continue to ``have great impact.'' The
show is being expanded to four nights a week starting in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
