<HEADLINE>
WORLD BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY ON RISE
</P>
<P>
   The number of people living on less than a dollar a day is
rising, the United Nations General Assembly was told as it began a
weeklong meeting in Geneva to examine poverty. Since 1995 those
living in absolute poverty has grown to 1.2 billion from about 1
billion, according to United Nations figures. The United Nations,
the World Bank, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development and the International Monetary Fund issued a report
detailing poverty's spread and urged measures to halve the
proportion of those living in poverty by 2015.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: STATE OF EMERGENCY
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid declared a civil state of emergency
in the eastern islands of Maluku, where violence between Christians
and Muslims has killed scores of people in the past week and
thousands over the past 18 months. ``The situation is out of
control,'' he said. Protesters at the American Embassy in Jakarta,
above, called for international peacekeepers to be sent to the
islands.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: AUTONOMY PLAN APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The Jammu and Kashmir state provincial assembly approved a
contentious resolution for greater autonomy that seeks to end
political discontent in the region. The resolution provides
restoration of pre-1953 relations between the federal and state
government under which the federal government will control defense,
foreign affairs and communications. Members of the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which leads the federal
coalition government, walked out in protest.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: HAUGHEY TRIAL PUT OFF
</P>
<P>
   A Dublin court indefinitely postponed the criminal trial of
former Prime Minister Charles J. Haughey, 74, ruling that Haughey,
who faces charges of obstructing a 1997 government inquiry, could
not receive a fair trial because of a rash of negative publicity
from politicians and the press. In a newspaper interview, Deputy
Prime Minister Mary Harney said Haughey should be convicted, and
posters throughout Dublin display his face under the slogan ``Jail
the corrupt politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: U.S. ENVOY'S NEW JOB
</P>
<P>
   Raymond A.J. Chretien, Canada's ambassador to Washington since
1994, has been named ambassador to France. The switch comes less
than a month after the press interpreted a speech by Chretien as an
implicit endorsement of Vice President Gore in the presidential
race. Aides to the ambassador said he was merely assessing the two
American candidates' familiarity with Canada. Chretien, a career
diplomat, is a nephew of Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
</TEXT>
