<HEADER>
A5855 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-MUMMY-SCAN-SPI &LR;      06-26 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUMMY-SCAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUMMY'S CT SCAN AN EYEOPENER FOR MUSEUM RESEARCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``Nellie,'' the Burke Museum's resident Egyptian
mummy, slid through a wrap of red laser light into the white vault
of the University of Washington's high-speed CT scanner.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant 2,000 years of mystery fell away from her.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's CT scan, a first for both the mummy and the medical
center, revealed missing bones, a healthy set of teeth, a better
guess on her age, and a few other surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data we got is just overwhelming,'' said Laura Phillips,
the Burke's archaeology collections manager. The museum asked for
the CT scan to help figure out a strategy for preserving the mummy,
which has become more fragile from years on display.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Burke has owned the mummy since 1902, no one knew
much about what was underneath the elaborate linen wrappings.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have guessed that the mummy is the remains of a
non-royal adolescent woman who lived during the Ptolemeic period
between 305 and 34 B.C., a period that concluded with the reign of
Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scan today shows all the growth plates were fused, so she
probably died as an adult,'' said Dr. Udo Schmiedl, the University
of Washington radiology professor who read the CT scan. He and the
museum staff hope that the 800 or so images collected during the
scan will yield additional information about how ``Nellie'' lived
and died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her teeth were in remarkably good condition,'' said Phillips.
That could indicate she died at a relatively young age.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also learned that someone had inserted a metal rod
into the chest cavity to stabilize the body. And there may be other
modern materials, such as plaster or rubber, filling out her chest
cavity.
</P>
<P>
   The new materials were most likely added during investigations
in 1916 and 1962, when museum staff rummaged through the mummy's
remains for gold and amulets, said Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   What they found instead were two water lily bulbs, symbols of
immortality, that were wrapped inside the mummy's chest cavity.
</P>
<P>
   The museum still has the lily bulbs, along with the bones that
were removed during those investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the data gathered Monday added to the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   One leg, for example, is shorter than the other, and researchers
are puzzled over a dense substance in the skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear yet whether it was put there during the
embalming, or was part of later efforts to stabilize the mummy,''
said Linda Roundhill of Arts and Antiquities Conservation in
Woodinville, Wash., the expert hired to do the mummy's
conservation.
</P>
<P>
   And for now, the gender of the mummy is still a guess.
Generations of schoolchildren have known her as ``Nellie,''
apparently nicknamed after Nellie Cornish, founder of the Cornish
College of the Arts here.
</P>
<P>
   The museum hopes to X-ray the pelvic bone, which was removed
earlier, to settle the question of her sex.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the earlier probes, everyone involved in Monday's CT scan
took care not to disturb the mummy.
</P>
<P>
   The mummy arrived near dawn in an unmarked gray funeral company
van, driven by Bill Metcalf of Wiggen &AMP; Sons Funeral Home &AMP;
Crematory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought her over the right way,'' said Metcalf, who watched
solemnly while medical technicians and museum staffers readied the
mummy for her ride into a 21st century version of a sarcophagus.
</P>
<P>
   First she was lifted gently out of a powder blue coffin box,
then laid on the gliding platform in front of the ``square donut''
that houses the X-ray tubes, detectors and electronics. Technicians
used laser beams to center her exactly in the field of the
detectors.
</P>
<P>
   As the scan progressed, the distinct image of a skull appeared,
and the small crowd of medical staff who had gathered to see the
unusual patient suddenly hushed. The crowd murmured remarks as each
new anatomical landmark appeared in sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was just the gray-shaded image of her toes on the
screen, like a footprint fading in sand.
</P>
<P>
   Frany Backus, granddaughter-in-law of Manson Backus, the
University of Washington regent who donated the mummy to the museum
nearly a century ago, watched the images unfold from a front-row
perch next to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Friends raised more than $27,000 for the conservation project
and presented the money to the museum as a gift in Frany Backus'
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people will be struck by the contemporariness of her
life,'' said Backus, 85, who wore a purple hat for Monday's
occasion. ``Still, after 2,000 years, she has an influence, and
she's expanding the minds of people who see her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
