<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BIOLOGY-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH INSTITUTIONS FORMING BIOLOGY STUDY CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three large New York research institutions will form
a $160 million biology research center, paid for in part with a
donation from an anonymous patron.
</P>
<P>
   The program, a venture by Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center, Rockefeller University and the Weill Medical College of
Cornell University, is the latest of several efforts among major
New York medical and research centers to collaborate on large
scientific projects.
</P>
<P>
   Joint projects, anathema in New York research circles only a few
years ago, have become increasingly necessary as the cost of such
work has skyrocketed and as the work has become too complex for
most centers to undertake on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The new joint initiative, known as the Tri-Institutional
Research Program, is expected to be announced Tuesday. It is to
consist of shared laboratories and equipment and will recruit
faculty members from all over the country in the next five to 10
years to conduct research that will focus on chemical,
computational and cancer biology.
</P>
<P>
   The gift, although not the largest to a medical institution, is
especially substantial for an anonymous donor.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, New York's medical schools, hospitals and research
institutions have guarded their own research. States like Maryland
and California, on the other hand, have invested more public and
private funds in the development of biological research and product
development and have reaped huge financial and intellectual
rewards.And New York, once the the biggest recipient of federal
grants, has slipped to third. Not a single New York research
institution was chosen to participate in the human genome
sequencing project, whose results were announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these three institutions had done this 10 years ago,'' said
Arnold Levine, president of Rockefeller University, ``we might have
been one of the centers in which genome sequencing would have
occurred. We have now found that we must collaborate to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Other major collaborations have been announced in the last few
years by New York's medical research centers. One is the New York
Structural Biology Center, a consortium of 10 medical institutions
using magnets to study molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, the Academic Medicine Development Co., was formed
a few years ago with 34 institutions around the state for joint
purchases and research. Among its projects is a $12 million cancer
study that will track the health habits of 300,000 residents.
Another is the Biomedical Research Alliance of New York, which
works with manufacturers on drug trials.
</P>
<P>
   The human genome project has raised the bar for all medical
researchers and pushed them to collaborative efforts to advance
scientific research, leaders from the three institutions in the new
venture said Monday. ``Having the chance to interact more easily
with neighboring colleagues is a tremendous boon,'' said Harold
Varmus, president of Sloan-Kettering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2325EDT &QL; 
