<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE'S ANTITRUST CHIEF MAY BLOCK WORLDCOM DEAL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The top antitrust officer of the European Commission, Mario
Monti, said he would advise the commission to block WorldCom from
buying Sprint unless the companies significantly altered the terms
of the deal before the commission's July 12 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In another telecommunications development, Qwest Communications
International's $57 billion takeover of U S West received final
federal regulatory approval.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOW CLIMBS ON PHILIP MORRIS DEAL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris drove the Dow Jones industrial average higher as
investors applauded its plan to acquire the snack-food business of
Nabisco Holdings. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 138.24
points, or 1.3 percent, to 10,542.99. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index was up 13.83 points, or nearly 1 percent, to
1,455.31, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 66.78 points, or
1.7 percent, to 3,912.12.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WARNACO COUNTERSUES CALVIN KLEIN  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warnaco Group, which makes underwear and jeanswear under the
Calvin Klein label, answered a lawsuit by Calvin Klein by filing a
countersuit seeking nearly $1 billion in damages from Calvin Klein
Inc. and the designer. The complaints against the company include
defamation, breach of good faith and interference with its business
practices.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR VIVENDI, A QUESTION OF SYNERGIES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the announcement of Vivendi's $41 billion deal to acquire
Seagram last week, analysts have been squinting to see the
synergies between Vivendi _ which owns environmental, waste and
communications businesses _ and Seagram, which owns a major record
company, film studio, theme park business and liquor operation.
Still, Vivendi's chairman, Jean-Marie Messier, plans to sell the
concept of a wireless Internet world where Vivendi's acquisition
would reap a windfall.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XEROX TURNS TO BLUE DOGS FOR ADS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, a name synonymous with pricey corporate copiers, is about
to begin an advertising campaign for low-priced ink-jet printers
for the home. The centerpiece of the campaign will be the cult-like
Blue Dogs of the painter George Rodrigue.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXISTING HOME SALES UP 4.3% IN MAY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sales of existing homes increased by a strong 4.3 percent in May
and prices crept higher, as pent-up demand caused by a slim choice
of homes for sale kept activity buoyant despite higher mortgage
rates. The National Association of Realtors said that sales in May
rose to an annual pace of 5.09 million units from 4.88 million in
April. This surpassed expectations of Wall Street economists, who
had predicted no change  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT TO ANNOUNCE NEW BRAND  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies will announce a new brand Tuesday for its
unit that sells communications products to business customers. The
unit is in the process of being spun out of Lucent as an
independent company. Lucent plans no initial public offering of
stock in the new company, and intends to distribute all the shares
directly to its own shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
