<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-HATE-REACT-NYT     06-26 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HATE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING ON N.J. HATE CRIME LAW `SLAP IN FACE,' RESIDENT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With SCOTUS-HATE-CRIME)  By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mattie Harrell pointed to the second story of her gray stucco
house to a handful of pockmarks gouged out by bullets in 1994 _
indelible evidence that when she and her family moved that year to
the outskirts of Vineland, N.J., they were not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   After five incidents of gunfire in five months, Harrell said she
and and her family _ the first African-Americans in the
neighborhood _ felt some sense of justice later that year when the
police arrested Charles Apprendi Jr., a pharmacist who lived about
a mile away on the same street.
</P>
<P>
   A judge, invoking New Jersey's hate crimes law, determined that
Apprendi had been motivated by racial bias and sentenced him to 12
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court, after hearing an appeal of
Apprendi's case, struck down a part of that law, saying that only a
jury can decide whether a crime is motivated by bias.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell, who continues to live with her three children in the
house on Chestnut Street, said the gunfire had caused her family
tremendous pain _ pain that was renewed by the high court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tore the whole family up,'' she said after learning the
court decision Monday. ``We will never be the same. Today is a slap
in the face as far as being a minority goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi pleaded guilty to possessing a firearm with an unlawful
purpose and unlawful possession of a bomb, which would have brought
him a sentence of 5-10 years. But prosecutors asked for a harsher
penalty under the state hate crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in a 5-4 vote, the Supreme Court said it was
unconstitutional for the judge to have ruled that the offense was a
hate crime. New Jersey officials, however, said that with
legislative fine-tuning, the 10-year-old law could be modified to
pass constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christine Todd Whitman and legislative leaders said they
would change the law to reflect the decision, which struck down
only part of the state's Ethnic Intimidation Act.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi's lawyer, Joseph O'Neill, said, ``The bias crime law
carries a social stigma, a stigma that you're a racist. I think
that deserves a decision by someone's peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi has served five and a half years of his sentence and is
now in a halfway house, his lawyer said. He was not available for
comment. O'Neill said his client would go before a jury for a new
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Gochman, a deputy state attorney general who represented
New Jersey before the Supreme Court, said she believed that there
were two other New Jersey cases in which defendants had received
longer sentences because a judge had found them guilty of bias
crimes. They will also have to return to the trial court for new
sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
