<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MIRANDA-NYT &LR;      06-26 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIRANDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE COURT REAFFIRMS MIRANDA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court on Monday reaffirmed one of the finest
legacies of Chief Justice Earl Warren's era _ the court's Miranda
ruling of 1966, which requires police to advise suspects of their
rights before beginning an interrogation. Seven members of the
court chose to uphold Miranda's constitutional vitality, and the
majority decision was written by one of the court's more
conservative members, Chief Justice William Rehnquist. That should
help discourage future efforts to portray Miranda's sensible
safeguards against coercion as an extreme and extraconstitutional
``milestone of judicial overreaching,'' which is how Justice
Antonin Scalia sought to depict them in a dissent joined by Justice
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The case arose from an appellate court ruling in Virginia last
year. That court said that courts were no longer obliged to exclude
evidence in federal cases when the police neglect to remind
suspects that they have a right to have a lawyer present and to
remain silent, and that any statement they make can be used against
them _ a legal incantation that most viewers of television crime
shows can recite by heart. The appellate decision rested on an
obscure 1968 law providing that a confession is admissible as long
as it is ``voluntarily given'' in light of ``all the
circumstances'' _ regardless of whether the suspect was read his
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But as the court has now ruled, the core principles of Miranda
are grounded in the Fifth Amendment's privilege against
self-incrimination and the 14th Amendment's promise of due process.
Thus Congress cannot undo it. As the chief justice noted,
``Miranda, being a constitutional decision of this court, may not
be in effect overruled by an act of Congress.'' In declining the
invitation to overrule Miranda, the court also said that a
departure from precedent required extraordinary circumstances not
present in the case at hand. The court confessed that it might not
have imposed the Miranda rule were it addressing the issue for the
first time. Nevertheless, it wisely decided against tampering with
a rule that has added an important measure of consistency and
fairness to police work, and has ``become part of our national
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   In another important ruling on Monday, the court invalidated
California's ``blanket'' primary. Under this system, Californians
were given a single ballot from which they could choose a candidate
from any party, regardless of their own party affiliation. The
court found this system to be a violation of the parties' rights of
association _ that is, each party's right to control its nominating
process. The question of whether the associational rights of
political parties should take precedence over the state's
countervailing First Amendment interest in encouraging broad voter
participation is a closer call than the court's 7-to-2 split
suggests. The political parties have a strong interest in defining
their identity. But the nomination process is not a private matter,
but an integral part of the system for choosing government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The court studiously avoided applying its ruling to the 20
states that use a less drastic form of open primary to choose
candidates, so the new ruling is unlikely to be the last word on
the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
