<DOCNO> NYT20000626.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECT-1STLD-     06-26 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE IN ZIMBABWE SHOWS OPPOSITION MAKING BIG GAINS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs for writethru.)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Supporters of the opposition party cheered
and danced on Monday as election results from the weekend's
parliamentary elections showed their fledgling party making
unprecedented gains on the governing party that has dominated
Zimbabwe for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The final result was unclear, but with more than three quarters
of the vote in Tuesday from counting stations across the country,
tallies quickly established that the nine-month-old party had
become a powerful opposition force in Zimbabwe _ a feat considered
unimaginable just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For years, President Robert Mugabe's governing party has
controlled all but three seats in Parliament. But the new
opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change, easily
surpassed that figure, winning 48 seats and claiming lopsided
victories in urban districts, where voters have been squeezed by
skyrocketing inflation and deepening unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the early returns, it appeared that the governing party
would likely maintain its majority as it carried 51 mostly rural
districts, where the party's support has traditionally been
strongest. Mugabe was also guaranteed 20 appointed seats, giving
him at least 71 seats in the 150-member Parliament. The local
chiefs elect 10 members.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the results reflected nothing short of seismic
realignment in the political landscape here, laying bare the
weaknesses of the governing party and of its chief, Mugabe, 76, an
aging leader who has been widely viewed as unassailable for nearly
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   And the vote also demonstrated the unexpected power of an
energized, urban electorate that shook off the political apathy of
recent years and carried its frustrations directly to the ballot
box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have wanted the landslide in the urban areas to have
extended to the rural areas, but no matter what the climate will
never be the same here again,'' Ian Makone, an official in the
MDC's election directorate, said in an interview early this
morning. ``It's never going to be the one party system that it was.
That's a thing of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts predicted the votes would continue to split
along urban and rural lines for the 120 parliamentary seats that
were up for election as the counting continued through the early
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials had contended all along that they would
maintain their majority, but they publicly acknowledged that for
the first time they had misjudged the mood and needs of people in
the cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not being swept away by these elections, but we're
getting a kind of wake-up call,'' said Jonathan Moyo, the spokesman
for the governing party, the Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front, known as ZANU-PF. ``They're doing better
than I expected them to. It's a reality check for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe and party officials had campaigned heavily on the pledge
that they would make good on their promise to redistribute fertile
land, which is still mostly owned by a tiny white minority here.
They supported the invasions of hundreds of white-owned farms by
black squatters and were widely blamed for condoning a campaign of
intimidation and violence that left at least 26 people dead, most
of them opposition supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But the message clearly had little appeal for urban voters, who
had grown weary of fuel shortages, corruption and unfulfilled
promises. And here in the capital and in the second-largest city,
Bulawayo, people flocked in droves to the new party that promised
an improved economy and clean government.
</P>
<P>
   There were casualties on both sides. The losers included Morgan
Tsvangirai, the leader of the MDC; Dumiso Dabengwa, Mugabe's
minister of home affairs; and Emmerson Mnangagwa, the justice
minister. All three lost their seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The first results, which had been expected on Monday afternoon,
trickled in slowly in the evening. In a nation where elections have
been characterized by voter apathy in recent years, about 60
percent of the more than 5.8 million registered voters cast ballots
during the polls on Saturday and Sunday, and election officials
were quickly overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnout was just too large, overwhelming,'' Tobaiwa
Mudede, the Registrar General, said this afternoon. ``They have not
started counting.''
</P>
<P>
   As the nation waited anxiously, the officials spent hours
checking ballot boxes and ballot slips for any evidence of
tampering or election rigging. Angry young supporters of the
opposition grumbled suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, observers from the European Union had condemned
Mugabe's party, accusing it of supporting the violence and
intimidation that marred the run-up to the vote last weekend. And
on Monday, the government quickly deployed police officers around
the country to prevent any outbreaks of violence and urged the
public to remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   The observers made it clear that the two days of peaceful voting
had done little to allay the concerns spawned by months of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calls for peaceful campaigning and efforts to restrain party
supporters, including war veterans, were often ambiguous,'' said
Pierre Schori, the head of the European Union observer mission.
``Overall, the conduct of the government has failed to uphold the
rule of law and compromised law enforcement agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the night reportedly passed peacefully, with most
people glued to televisions and radios, waiting nervously for
results to come in. It was the first time since blacks won majority
rule in 1980 that an opposition party had challenged the governing
party in every district.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the first time in nearly two decades that many voters
had gone to sleep without knowing for sure what the morning's
election result would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long night, a long wait,'' Makone said
yesterday. ``We're going to be very strong in the urban areas. But
it's going to be a nail-biting experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
