<HEADLINE>
ANGELS EXPECT GLAUS TO GET BACK AT IT TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Troy Glaus, after starting the first 73 games, missed
his second consecutive game Sunday with back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia again said he held out the third baseman
as a precautionary measure and expects him to play tonight when the
Anaheim Angels open a critical three-game series in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who leads the Angels with 24 homers and 57 runs scored,
had a light workout before Sunday's game with hitting coach Mickey
Hatcher, but Scioscia said he didn't consider letting Glaus pinch
hit to test it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have (batting practice),'' Scioscia said. ``I didn't
think it was wise to throw him out there after he sat for a few
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Downplaying it: Darin Erstad, with 16 homers, is just three
shy of his career high, but he doesn't get too excited about his
first-half power surge. And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, I had 18 at the All-Star break _ check the
numbers,'' said Erstad, who extended his hitting streak to 11 games
Sunday with two singles. ``I ended up with 19. Yeah, the home runs
are up, but I'm not going to concern myself with that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Getting a chance: Two seldom-used pitchers performed well in
mop-up duty Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Pote, making his first appearance in 16 days, allowed two
hits, an unearned run and struck out three in 1 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Turnbow, the right-hander the Angels acquired through
the Rule V draft _ which requires them to keep him on the
big-league roster all season _ allowed a homer to Jay Canizaro, the
first batter he faced, and then allowed just one more hit and no
runs in three innings. Turnbow walked four and struck out three.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fyhrie, who pitched a scoreless ninth inning, has allowed
one earned run in his last 13 innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
